description: This route begins climbing up a right angling seam. Before getting into the overhang, you encounter a low crux on thin holds. After battling the overhang, you gain the face to encounter an even more challenging finish on more thin holds till the top. It's not over till it's over!
location: The first route to the left of Zen Arcade/Manufacturing Consent.

description: Roughly 60' left of Tear Stained Eye.  Bulgy route.
Dirty bottom, fun top.
location: 10ft left of prominent alcove, just left of "Pita" 5.10a

description: Tricky Techy at the bottom
location: Left of Train in Vain

description: This route is located just to the left of Express Checkout Line and use the same entrance.  Has a low and balancy crux.

location: 15 feet left of Tear Stained Eye

description: GREAT arete route, very technical.
location: Obvious arete in the center of the wall.

description: Currently there are no anchors equipped on this project. Have fun figuring out the sequence.
location: 10ish feet left of the Blazed of Glory Project.

first_ascent: Ray Whaley Jeff Frizzell Matt Queen
description: Meander up the beautiful face left of No Paynes in Heaven.
location: Left of No Paynes

description: Climb the dihedral crack until it ends. Stem your way to the anchor after that.
location: The dihedral crack directly right of PITA

description: Climb up and through the weirdly shaped hueco in the center of the face. A few cruxes on this one, its not over till its over.
location: 30ish feet to the right of Raging Intensity

description: It's the next route on the rounded corner, 30' left of Ladybug Lynn.  Veer right at the 2nd clip.
Hard crimpy holds and a few pockets. Stay strong on this one.
location: To the right of the dihedral and Blazed Of Glory Project

description: Climb up the overhanging flake and finish on the headway all. Watch out for the pump!
location: First route to the left of Working Class.

description: There is no anchor equipped on this project. Climb the red face through blank sections.
location: 30ish feet left of Jones'n In Jacksonville

description: Begin in a broken, right-facing dihedral system. Climb 20 feet up, 20 feet to the left, and 20 more feet up. Mantle on to the upper ramp and belay on small gear. The second pitch consists of a scramble up the ramp, past a bolt to the anchors.
location: A few hundred feet left of the main Raging Intensity wall, look for an unappealing, broken, right facing dihedral with a ledge at 20 feet, a roof at 40 feet, and a ramp above that.
protection: standard rack, small to medium gear primarily. bolted anchor at the top of the second pitch.

description: More fun, steep 5.9 climbing, starts of with some steep jug hauling then pull over some more bulges.
location: Just to the right of the first unknown 5.9. This is the second route around right from "Spits or Swallows" on the main Beaver Wall. It is the second route from the left on Beaver Wall Right.

description: Climb the overhanging prow of the tower, big dyno.

An odd route that definitely "strays" from the bolt line. The beginning is intentionally bolted to force a face move that is probably the crux of the climb but then the climb moves into the chimney for 2 bolts. Up higher there is a great looking, thin section of wall that is appealing but the path of least resistance climbs the dirty rock to the left.
location: left side of gully (nice cool breeze) 30 feet left of Group Therapy. Last route on Applejack Wall in Yusuf's guide.

This route starts like 50 feet left of Touch My Shelf and goes up and right after the steep overhang. We started under the first bolt and slightly to the right so we could utilize the cool roof feature, which is absolutely worth the effort.

description: A short route on the west side.
location: West side of the boulder furthest right.

description: More steep goodness.
location: First route encountered approaching from The Gallery.  On the right side of the overhanging wall.

description: The left of three 10's on the west side of the boulder.
location: It's to the right of Energizer on the west side of the boulder.

description: Interesting climbing, different than most of the routes at the Gallery. The anchor is set unnecessarily far back up a lichen covered slab, but one could easily use "The Walrus" anchor just to the left before the low-angle slab.
location: Located on the right side of the gallery, this is the first bolted route to the left (about 15') of the obvious "Cringe Chimney." It is just to the right of "The Walrus."

description: Sustained high quality route, makes a great warm-up.  Crux is somewhat height-dependent and involves surmounting the first bulge about half way up. Slab top out.
location: Located on Gallery wall, third sport climb from the right.

description: Overhung crack to the left of Group Therapy.  When crack ends, climb to the left or right (your choice) and top out on either Group Therapy or King's Jester.
location: Located between Group Therapy and King's Jester.

description: Another classic line at the Gallery, start on easy terrain and move through several cruxes up higher.
location: From Group Therapy, this is the fourth bolted route to the right. From the obvious 15 ft tall flake feature at the start of Deep throat/King's Jester, it is the next bolted line to the left.

description: Low crux. One move wonder. Fun first clip.
location: 5 feet left of the large crack near Group Therapy.

description: Somewhat sustained difficulty. Hard stuff seemed to be in the middle.
location: Its the overhanging jug haul just around the 90 degree corner.
protection: 6QD + anchor. one bolt is very hard to see from the ground.

description: Climb the face near the hanging pine
location: 30ish feet to the right of Crybaby Club

description: Start to the right of chemney about 6ft, after the last bolt there is a gear placement in a pocket, a #3 tri-cam , if you need it, may have been retro bolted,
location: about 100ft to right of Group Therapy,

description: Short but good, beginner-friendly for sure. Start at the bottom, climb to the top. Use the holds.
location: Furtherest left route at the gallery. It's the one with 3 bolts.

first_ascent: Alan Carrier + Co. 1989, FFA Eric Ulner 1989
description: Overhanging jug haul. A hold broke off the original line, increasing the difficulty. Keep an eye out for the no hands rest ~2/3 of the way up!
location: After you reach the Gallery, walk right around the corner and you will find this glorious overhanging jug haul. You'll know the line when you see it, if its a weekend you'll know it by the line on the ground. First bolted route right of the obvious "Squirrel House Crack."

first_ascent: Lawrence Stuemke 1988 First Free Lead Chris Schmick 1999
description: Easy pocket climbing, leads to a crux pulling the bulge, and ends on a stint of slab.
location: Leftmost route in the Gallery before the corner.(Not the arete)

description: Pulling the overhang is entertaining.
location: Starts to the right of Sore Throat in the scoop and goes up through the overhang.
protection: 4 bolts + anchors. Easier bottom climbing is protectable.

description: Pocket climbing, to a bulge crux. Slabish ending.
location: Immediately to the right of Earthbound Misfit.

description: First route right of the Minstrel
Set up a top rope and stem your way up the chimney
location: The wide chimney feature to the left of The Minstrel

description: Climb just left of the arete on steepness.
location: Furthest left route on the west side.

description: Middle of the 10's on the west side.
location: It's the second route on the west side of the boulder.

description: Similar to Corporal Punishment, this too you will need to rappel in from the top.
location: This is the first bolted route you will find left of Applejack Crack

description: A thought provoking and challenging climb for the grade on sculpted holds.  Don't let the top fool you!
location: to the right of extinguisher, just in front of elm tree

description: Technical powerful climb.
location: Found in between ‚ÄúAreteouffee‚Äù on the left, and ‚Äú Manhattan Project‚Äù on the right.

description: Beginning off the small boulder, pull through some tricky moves and the climbing get easier the higher you climb.
location: To the right of Ridin' Cowgirls.

description: A great looking almost blank face that have never been sent. Good Luck
location: First sport route left of The Shootist

description: Begins with a difficult boulder problem, which leads to hard sustained climbing and a blockbuster finish to the chains. To get full points for this route, avoid using the wall on the right. Contrived, I know.
location: This route is found between ‚ÄúRajun‚Äô Cajun‚Äù on the left, and ‚ÄúBuckets of Jam‚Äù on the right.

description: Climb using small crips to reach the top.
location: The short face just right of the small boulder

description: 100 feet left of Ragin' Cajun, stay inside broken block hallway. Starts in a roof with a large, flat flake. 5 QD to the first fixed anchor. Variation 5.13a. Two more QD left to the other fixed anchor. F/A Chris Schmick 2001 From "Vertical Heartland" 3rd edition by Eric Ulner
location: Dirt trail leading up to the wall takes you directly to the start of the climb.

description: Please note, this is a mixed line that you must rappell into from the top.
location: Right and around the arete from Bill & Tee's Excellent Adventure
Large dihedral crack on the big ledge.
protection: Standard rack, big stuff is probably a good idea.

description: Climb up the arete to the right.
location: Found in between ‚ÄúBuckets of Jam‚Äù on the left and ‚ÄúCorporal Punishment‚Äù on the right.
protection: 5 bolts. It‚Äôs advised to stick clip the first bolt:

description: Climb up to the depression near bolt 3. Be ready for hard moves
location: First spot route to the right of Applejack Crack

description: More challenging than it looks!
location: Found in between ‚ÄúAin‚Äôt No Sunshine‚Äù on the left, and ‚ÄúRajun‚Äô Cajun‚Äù on the right.

description: From behind the large tree, follow the thin crack upward until it widens into a large water groove off width/chimney at about 15 feet. Follow to the top.
location: Just to the left of the end of The Gallery, just past the large chimney/gully.
protection: Trad gear - large sizes and thin stuff for the beginning (I used micro-wires)

description: Difficult moves off of thin holds, monos, and bad slopers on great stone = one difficult route!
location: Found in between ‚ÄúIce Harvest‚Äù on the left, and ‚ÄúAreteouffee‚Äù on the right.

description: Start on the boulder and climb over the right of the low roof.
Start 12 feet right of the arete and go straight up the face.

location: Far right of the east wall, between If I Could Fly on left and Wrecking Ball on north wall.

description: Start in a smooth, tiny right-facing corner then go up and left.  About 25 feet right of "Wrecking Ball", and just at the hallway entrance, its the leftward angling sport route.

In the middle of the east wall, 15 feet right of Void Warrior. Initially, at rainy day 2002, Me and my friend from Poland, Tomasz Samitowski start bolting from the ground. We put 2 bolts. I equiped entire route 5 years later, after successful top rope attempt by my son Maciek. At this time I was not able even repeat first crux move.
location: Middle of east wall
protection: 2 old 3/8 bolts + 3 new 1/2x3.5 Hilti + new anchor (+chain)

description: Start over the low roof and climb the face to anchors under the right of the high roof.

location: On the Battle Axe Tower, sandwiched between Viking Blood on the left and The Flail on the right.

description: About 30 feet right of "The Reckoning", easy moves up to a high block/ledge then climb the arete by its right side.
protection: Use tree as anchors.  3 QD and a slider nut.

description: This is a former trad route that has since been bolted. It's a slab climb typical of jackson Falls, although with more features than you might expect. A little sketchy for the new leader, stick clip recommended in this case. Once established on the route, the first three bolts are pretty easy to clip. Keep moving right and you might need your belayer to describe the feet. Once you establish moving upward, it only gets easier to the top.
location: On the right just to the left of the arete on the obvious slab of the actual Battle Axe Tower
protection: 6 bolts (?) and shuts. Well protected, to the point of some rope drag.

description: Climb up to a right-facing flake then the face and the left side of the bulge.  Lives up to it's namesake....
protection: Chains are difficult to reach at top!

description: The crux on this one is low to the ground. Don‚Äôt get too comfortable after the crux though, lack of feet makes it easy to punt before making it to the chains!
location: The route directly to the left of ‚ÄúTons of Fun‚Äù. The first route you encounter on the exam wall coming from the Dynasty wall.

description: Before entering the hallway, climb up and right on the left side of the steep face.
Start 15 feet left of the small corner and climb up to the right of the high bulge.
A project given 5 stars in the guidebook, this has been sent since then. "Beautiful pockets leading to a steep slab top out.
location: 15ft left of "The Bolted One"

description: Old JF project. Rebolted. Technical start up a sloping seam followed by a good rest. Culminates in a hard boulder problem that revolves around a bad pinch and an iron jib.
location: Right of "Splinter Faction."

description: Climb in the middle of the face.  Vertical, then steep.

Start 6 feet right of the alcove/chimney. Climb through the beginning bulged to gain the face, which is one of the most technical at Jackson. Pull onto the roof and get ready to crank. This climb is a great mix of balance and power, thin crimps and slopers, with a little spice to top things off.
Gear climb the right-facing flake/crack in the corner.
Gear climb the left-facing dihedral.

location: The obvious bolted chimney to the right of two steep 5.9s. The third route to the right of "Spits or Swallows" 12a (The last route on the right side of the main Beaver Wall)
protection: 6 bolts to a 2 bolt anchor. Or gear if you want an extra challenge.

description: Fun and steep 5.9 climbing pulling over multiple bulges. Very similar in character to the next 5.9 to the right, and that route could easily be toproped from the same anchor as this one.
location: The first route to the right of "Spits of Swallows" on the main Beaver Wall. Leftmost route of Beaver Wall right.

description: A good introductory 5.10, with a single move that might be 10a mixed in with a lot of fun, juggy 5.8/5.9 climbing.
location: Rightmost route on Beaver wall Right. First route to the left of Chimichonga. Immediately right of Cats in the Cradle.

description: Climb bulge and pockets to a bulge with great pocket with a shallow crack above,(crux) a very tricky¬† crux,
location: Between Beaver Wall and Mr Jimmy Boulder,¬† Just to the right of Beaver Wall, on the next buttress, 1st bolted line to the right of dirty chimney,

description: Start with some fun pocket pulling, reach a burly, reachy stand-up single move crux, that seemed to me to be somewhat improbable for 5.11, and continue romping up to the anchors.
location: The second route to the right of the obvious bolted chimney. The third route to the left of Chimichonga 5.8. Start by a 2 foot tall tree stump.
protection: 5 bolts to 2 bolt anchor. Easy to set on toprope from either of the 5.10s to the right, if one were so inclined.

description: Pull down on the holds, and go up. Another classic pocket-pulling adventure.
location: Second route around to the left from Chimichonga, route to the right of Cougar Love 11b.
protection: 5 bolts, 2 bolt anchor. Anchor is very easy to reach from the 10a to the right, if one were so inclined.

description: Climb the face. Traverse right around the roof. Follow easy ground to anchors.
location: Directly right of Flying Pig

description: Beginning  on Draft Root Beer, climb the opening moves. Clip the first bolt and work up and left to an in-cut shelf. Clip the bolt and continue up and straight from here until you reach the anchor.
location: Begin at the same spot as Draft Root Beer

description: Narrow chimney. Requires a top rope set by someone who has considerable experience building anchors.
location: As you enter Carol Lamb‚Äôs Bedroom from the right passageway (walking between between Sprecher Brew Co and Sir Mix-a-Lot), look for the first overhead boulder that joins the two walls. This route is on the side of the boulder closest to the trail (farthest from Carol Lamb‚Äôs Bedroom).
protection: As of this posting, there are no fixed anchors. Requires a top rope set by someone who has experience building anchors.

description: Climb just left of the corner, work your way up to the seam and continue to the top
location: To the right of Know Your Grammar
protection: 3 bolts to the anchor (shares anchor with the route to the right of it)

location: Directly left of Phillip's route
Tell 'em you're with Mac is a section of wall (within the Pacific Union Traverse crag) that runs along Kinzie Avenue between cross streets Hart Ave. and Wolcott Ave.

description: Begin pulling on good flakes and climb into the scoop. Work to get high feet and pull the small bulge using a good left hold and a pocket. Continue through good holds to the top.
location: first route to the right of ticket to ride

description: Climb through good holds through a leftward leaning fin. Pull over the top of the feature and clip the anchor
location: Refer to photo when posted. Left side of hallway, on the right

description: Mixed, climb the protectable crack to a single bolt. Anchors are over the second ledge.
location: Directly left of Dr. Feel Good

description: Begin on Dr. Feel Good, but immediately move right after clipping the first bolt. Climb to cool iron blobs.
location: First route to the right of Dr. Feel Good

description: Start on good holds traversing up and left. Use the obvious but not so positive slot for the left hand and rock up to a slopeyish crimp. Make the clip and utilize the rest, the hard part is over. Locate the secret jug for clipping the 3rd. Once you hit the lip it's positive holds to the chains. Quite possibly the best route at the Pass.
location: Refer to photo when posted

description: Climb the face using big holds and easy moves
location: First route you come to on the trail. On the left side of the first tall wall

description: Begin by climbing left of the arete. Use good holds on the arete to access a blocky rail on the left. Continue through tricky moves to the top.
location: To the right of

description: Start up the easy face to a hard sequence using poor feet.
location: Directly right of Sir Mix-a-Lot

description: Climb through the steep face on good holds
location: Directly right of the Unnamed 5.12

description: Climb the featured face. Follow the bolt line and pull through good holds to reach the top
location: First route to the right of Geometrics

description: Climb the right crack, protecting when necessary. When the main crack system ends, pull over a small roof and climb the last crack section and top out the route.
location: The right crack in the bedroom
protection: Standard rack to No. 3. Currently a top out climb. No anchor

description: Begin in the left crack. Work your way up to a small roof, cut left with the crack, and continue up.
location: Left corner crack when you enter the bedroom

description: Narrow chimney. Requires a top rope set by someone who has experience building anchors.
location: As you enter Carol Lamb‚Äôs Bedroom from the right passageway (walking between between Sprecher Brew Co and Sir Mix-a-Lot), look for the first overhead boulder that joins the two walls. This route is on the side of the boulder farthest from the trail (closest to Carol Lamb‚Äôs Bedroom).
protection: As of this posting, there are no fixed anchors. Requires a top rope set by someone who has experience building anchors.

location: Begin on Draft Root Beer
protection: 6 bolts to the anchor. Extend the last 3 bolts for better rope management

description: Start on the arete, and begin pulling through good holds. Angle up and right moving through a good side pull and edges to reach the anchor
location: To the right of Unnamed 5.10. Refer to photo when posted

description: Starting at the low point of a jug rail matched(butt should be on ground) work your way right working the feet to a fairly easy cross. Work feet again an set for a throw then to another. Then traverse right an work your way up the easy face. The finish has good holds but there is some that could be questionable(Use your best judgment). Top out is a right hand up to a horn feature then slide left onto the ledge. Also in the traverse you will encounter two sharp crimps an a crummy slopey pocket. Not sure on the grade. Hopefully others will get on it. If I am not the FA please let me know and we can change it.
location: To the left of flying pig. You will see a sign at this area. When facing it look left and down to the obvious starting jug.

description: Climb the featured face to a hard roof sequence. Make sure you have an attentive belay
location: Left route on the overhand about 50ish yards down trail from Draft Root Beet

description: Make thin moves to easy ground. Climb the steep, juggy roof to high anchors.
location: On the overhang located about 100 yards down trail in the tree line
Unknown
protection: Hang 3 webs from the trees above and rope up for safety.

description: This is a 160', 8" band of white chert running 6'- 10' above the ground, on a sunny south-facing cliff of chossy limestone. This is mostly a traverse. Handholds are on the shelf the chert lies on. Footholds are wherever one finds them. Bouldering and climbing may become safer as the wall looses it's chossiness. Chalk is NOT required for this route.
location: Disc golf basket #23

description: Route straight up from small cave before curve. Top out on top ledge.
location: refer to description.

description: Ring of Fire starts on a large pedestal, climb up it and through the roof using large pockets and crimps to the crux finish at the lip.
location: Start in the middle of the Spirit Cave on the pedestal.
protection: Bring a lot of pads and spotters for this problem!

description: First boulder problem right of small roof.
location: refer to description.

description: Around corner & 10 feet right of a small cave
location: refer to description.

description: Start standing on two side pulls. Do a couple wide compression moves on sloper sidepulls then top out. A harder sit start could be possible.
location: to the left of the Oriole

description: Takes its name from the bright orange coloring of the sandstone. High start on underclings, throw to jug. Classic.
location: Middle of boulder facing the lake

description: Pretty fun little traverse, albeit a little sandy. Decent warm up for the area. Start standing on the right side of the Oriole Boulder traverse to the end of the Oriole and topout.
location: to the right to the Oriole

description: Bypass the first move, starting on the two thin crimps. Make a small move and set up for the world class huck.
location: See Life on Mars

description: sit start. move through a few sharp crimps to a jug then bust a big move to a ledge.
location: To the right of the Oriole boulder on the cliff-line.

description: Sit start on rail a few feet right of the arete & head up left. Follow good holds to fun topout. Defintely a Roost classic.
location: South side of Lake Boulders

description: Start same as Screaming Eagle but climb out right. Long move to sharp hold & top out.
location: same start as Screaming Eagle

description: Perhaps THE classic hard problem of The Roost. Sit down start The Oriole. Left in pocket, right low undercling for full value.
location: sit down start to the Oriole

description: On the back of the Oriole boulder, start on left side of Southern Illinois's biggest sloper. Climb out to arete, follow it up staying on the right side.
location: back side of the Oriole Boulder

description: In the cave, jump start to obvious horn like feature. Climb out right to pockets on the roof.
location: middle of the cave

description: Stand start in the obvious seam & top out. A VERY hard project exists starting this much lower on the seam deep in the cave.
location: obvious seam in cave

description: Sit start on big layback, move to slopey shelf. Head right on big pinches & top out on shelf.
location: Located about 50 yds around corner from Cooker's Cave.

description: Right of metal staircase, up distinctive water drainage (dry unless it just rained). Start as Booze and Burritos and traverse over.
location: Shares the same start as Booze and Burritos

description: Right above staircase, right of a small water drainage, in bend. Tops out on rock before it turns to top soil above.
location: Above staircase.

route_name: Two in the Crimp One in the Brimp
description: Mostly crimpy vertical face. Safest as a top rope, but if you want to send it as a boulder, be sure to clean the holds up top well. There's no clear crux on this route other than avoiding getting sand in your eyes up top.
location: A few feet to the right of Breast Melk. Start matched on the low, right rail.

description: This route is top-ropeable from a tree but it should be done as a boulder if you have the means/ambition. Climb on mostly manufactured holds to a tricky crux on a slippery "S carving." A little extra effort cleaning the holds on rappel would be worth your time. Use the tree as your last hold for the airy mantle, and drink some breast melk for muscle recovery.
location: Climb the leftmost route on the vertical wall at the back of the glen.
protection: A couple pads would be neat

description: Several feet left of Creal Billies, sit start on pinch pocket & go straight up.
location: Left of Creal Billies

description: Climb the proud arete.
location: High start with left hand jug and right hand diagonal slot.

description: Fun warm up. Begin on good holds. Work up to big jug ledge and top out straight up.
location: The line just to the right of Foot Thief.

description: Another good one for a young climber
location: To the left of Training Wheels

description: Ascend the small but deep right facing crack. Down climb to the right.
location: To the right of Lily wall right before the trail stops.

description: Start on two hand rail jug and work up right on crack.
location: This boulder problem starts directly right of the obvious crack.

description: Climb the arete while starting low
location: Directly right of Open Arete Project

description: Begin low on undercling feature and climb straight up the arete
location: The arete feature 5ish feet right of the obvious crack feature

description: This is an open project that someone should go claim. ¬†Sit start and follow the technical line straight up the face.
location: Climb the face starting 4ish feet left of the obvious crack.

description: Start up the ramp and climb through the blocky section to reach the anchor
location: Left of N.L.C.

first_ascent: Bill Weishaar, Dan Rapp, Doug Rothe
description: Climb the dihedral and use the same chains at N.L.C.
location: Directly left of N.L.C.

first_ascent: Ryan Richardson, Bill Weishaar, Dan Rapp, Doug Rothe,
description: Climb the crack
location: The first crack to the left of N.A.R.B.

first_ascent: Robin Marquand, Trey Weishaar, Bill Weishaar, Doug Rothe, Dan Rapp
description: Climb the face using small edges and a thin crack to reach the top
location: Directly left of Cody's First Lead

first_ascent: Bill Weishaar Jr., Bill Weishaar, Doug Rothe
description: Climb the slab using edges to reach the chains at the top
location: Directly to the left of Anchors Away!

description: Climb the featured slab to reach the chains
location: Left of Scout's Dihedral

description: Climb the obvious water groove located right in front of the tree.
location: From the gap cut out pathway, head right. There are multiple problems on the boulder to the right that comprises the rock out crop. You will soon come to a perfect water groove. Climb it.

description: High start in weird looking large jug. Head right.
location: From the gap cut out pathway, head right. This problem is just before Groovy Mike.

description: Start in pockets and work up the water groove to bad slopers.
location: Left of Groovy Mike.

description: Climb the arete across from Nimbus boulder.
location: If looking at Nimbus, this boulder is just to the right and also faces the River to River trail.

description: Climb the arete and be ready for the last move being the crux
location: The tall prow of the main boulder

description: Start on the large jug at the bottom and climb up the beautiful arete.
location: On the opposite side of the Cookie Monster boulder.
See map.

description: beta pending
location: See picture

description: Climb up the blocky cleft to the find hand crack that starts 30 feet off the ground. Follow the crack for 15 feet and finish beneath the cedar branch.
location: 10 feet right of Shady Lane.

first_ascent: Tom Patterson and Jim and Clif Lingenfelter (TR, 1989)
description: Generous pockets and a few strategic face holds are spaced just right to stay on the "fun" side of the line.
location: This climb stays on the left face of Diabolical Dihedral all the way to the top.

description: The route on the Practice Wall. Lots of pockets!
protection: Looks like most people sling the big tree stump top and center. Approach on the right.

description: This route starts at the west-northwest edge of the Indian Head Buttress and wraps around the south edge.
location: This is the west facing front edge of Indian Head Bluff, one of the most notable images of the Mississippi Palisade Park.  You will be climbing right up the nose!
protection: Trad protection can be used. However lower in the route, the rock is more flaky.  This does not have fixed top anchors and will tyoically be anchored off the tree line across a 12' chasm.  Bring static rope for TR anchor for 30-35' span.

description: North face climb up the Indian Head tower.  Starts in the center of the north side and follows straight up the center crack the angles right.  Leads to a grassy ledge before finishing the remaining 15' to top out.
location: Location is at the Indian Head Buttress area.  Top Rope anchoring is accessable from side access approach from the northside.
protection: TP Anchors to the main buttress area across a 12' chasm which makes this route a PG for TR anchoring.  There are no bolts in route or on top.  There is a few large rock notches to redirect anchors.

description: Short route on the south corner of the Indian Head main face.  Nice holds and simple to belay from top or bottom.
location: This route is on the main face behind the tower. It faces South West on the corner.
protection: No bolts.  Plenty of trees on top.

description: This is a short route from the access area between the tower and main face of Indian Head climbing area.
location: Center access from the top of the Indian Head face.  there is an access route from the center face area wrapping around from the north side down into the chasm between the face and tower of Indian Head.

description: This could possibly be classified as a moderate fourth class scamper.  Starts at the northeast corner and follows narrow ledges to the top of Indian Head Tower.
location: Access to this area is from the top of Indian Head Buttress.  YOu can get to it from a moderate hike up the north side of hill.
protection: Could use some traditional pro.  Has 2 anchors with chains at the top of this climb on the ledge just above access climb

description: In the center of the wall is a yellow nose pointing Southwest. Climb the face just below this nose, and then tackle the nose itself.
location: the left climb on the small wall just south and uphill from the main wall.

description: Follow the dihedral to the top. Surprisingly solid rock. The route passes behind a cedar tree halfway up.
location: The blocky dihedral just right of Buzz Off

description: A slightly overhanging face with several fine, roomy pockets. The only problem is that the pockets are just far enough apart to be brutal.
location: 30 feet north of diabolical dihedral, and a few feet left of the gravel-filled off-width.

description: Another hard face climb. The face overhangs, the pockets are small, and the footwork is dubious at best.
location: 8 Feet left of Diabolical Dihedral.

description: Climb up and left on a ramp. When you reach the dead end in the yellow, overhanging dihedral, traverse right on a small horizontal ledge to the center of a smooth face. Using and undercling and a very long reach, continue up the face to ledge holds and pockets with a mantel to the top.
location: See picture. 5 feet left of Decapitator.

description: Follow a small double-crack dihedral for 25 feet to an overhang. Dodge around the bulge on the left, and climb up 10 feet to a ledge. From the ledge, follow a seam directly above the lower crack to the top.
location: See picture. Roughly in the center of the face.

description: It starts with pockets and works left slightly up into the overhang. The overhang about halfway up requires interesting maneuvers and a little bit of power. great face climbing on good pockets and crimps. Quite a bit of pump near the top as you traverse to the same end as Nutcracker.
location: Just to the left of Buzz Off and right of Nutcracker on the mostly blank face.

description: Climb straight up the center of the face.
location: See pic. Center of the south face.

description: Climb 15 feet to the crumbly ledge. Follow the dihedral to the top.
location: See picture. The large, blocky dihedral.

description: Stay out of the depths of the chimney by stemming across the opening. Avoid the huge hanging blade that gives the climb its name.
location: The large, block-filled chimney near the right edge of the wall.

description: Climb 10 feet into a seam, that opens up into a dihedral. When that gets too tough, step right around the corner.
location: See Picture. The whitest nose on the buttress, at the right edge of Bee Wall.

description: Double-shallow-roof route at the north end of the wall.
location: See picture. Just along the rail from Indian Head is a tall, crumbly monolith. Directly behind this outcrop is Bee Wall, and the Bee Line is the prominent double roof on the upper wall. The lower roof iw about 2 feet deep, and the upper roof is about a foot deep. There's a cedar at the top.

description: Climb up to the lone bush on this ramp, and then take the hand crack up to the cedar.
location: In between the prominent roofs of Six Hairy Legs and Four Wings and Fly, is a rubble-covered, low-angle nose.

description: Begin in Bruce's Jam, then move left end of the ledge. Straight up from there, then rejoin Bruce's Jam to finish.
location: Starts at Bruce's Jam

description: This route used to be used to train for mountaineering objectives. Start at the lowest point of the wall, and scramble up ramps, ledges, and blocks.
location: See picture
protection: Rope? This was generally used as a practice for moving with a rope on uncertain terrain.

description: beta pending
location: See picture

description: beta pending
location: See picture

description: Regarded by the guidebook authors as one of the finest in the park. Can be done in 2 pitches. Start at the extreme right of the yellow quarried rock. Up a sharp crack to a slanting roof.
location: See picture

description: Starts our as a thin seam, but opens up to hands and then fists.
location: 35 feet to the right of Fear of Flying.

description: Face holds to a ledge 15 feet up, then up to the left and over a bulge, to more face climbing right of a small dihedral.
location: Halfway between Fear of Flying and Bruce's Jam

first_ascent: Bill Collett, Stewart Anderson, and Gary Taylor (1982, TR)
description: Layback the dihedral. Very few face holds.
location: Left-facing dihedral left of the overhanging wall

description: Climb over a bulge to the crack. Crux consists of finger jams.
location: Far North end of North Butter Wall.

description: Climb up pockets to the edge of the arch. Once above the roof, move left up the face.
location: 20 feet to the right of Way-Back Layback.

description: Follow a faint diagonal seam up and left, then move up and right to a small ledge. Continue straight up from the ledge.
location: 10-feet to the left of the butter knife crack.

description: Climb the crack. Well-protected lead.
location: Prominent knife-edge crack near the right side of the wall.

description: Face holds up to a ledge. Angle up the seam system, then go for the top.
location: Just to the left of the Butter Knife crack.

description: This is a long, arching, overhanging crack in the dihedral. The crack starts in solid rock as thin fingers, then at 10 feet opens up into a nice hand crack. About 30 feet up, things get a bit dicey when the crack arches left into an area of looser rock.
location: See map. Second dihedral south of the waterfall access.

description: This route lies in the first dihedral north of Wide Glide. Climb through 3 small roofs 25 feet up, and continue to the top.
location: See map. The first dihedral north of Wide Glide.

description: This climb follows the rotten 6th dihedral to the right from waterfall access. (Second dihedral North of Wide Glide.) Thrash your way up the dirty, loose, gnarly crack and claim the ascent!
location: See map. The 6th dihedral south of the waterfall access.
Crack in the fifth dihedral to the right (S) of the waterfall access.

description: Climb directly up the south-facing rippled face, just left of LM Crack. The route actually ends on the ledge 30 feet up, but a slight move to the right will allow one to pick up the upper jam crack of LM Crack.
location: See map. Just to the right of LM Crack.
The corner to the left of Ode to Allen.

location: beta pending

description: beta pending
location: beta pending

location: beta pending

description: beta pending
location: See picture.

description: Fun slopey moves, sustained and with nice exposure and river views.
location: Climbs the bulge at the south edge of the stone platform.
protection: toprope anchors in the trees.  A 50' piece of webbing can be slung around at least 2 trees.

description: Start on Gumby's Pizza, move into large circle pocket and then fire straight up to good hold on lip.
location: Small boulder across from Dropzone and up the hill.

description: Short and sweet. Sit start on small pockets. Traverse right through large circle pocket to the arete.
location: From Dropzone, walk east up the trail and you will see a small boulder on your right with chalked pockets, this is Gumby's Pizza.

description: Start low on underclings and begin working up opposing side-pulls. Work through pockets and transition left into sloped horizontals. Top-out will likely be dirty, bring a brush and chalk bag up with you.
location: South-facing "Domes" area with a 45 degree wall.

description: beta pending
location: See picture.

description: beta pending
location: beta pending

description: This has a face start to a dihedral crack to a medium chimney towards the top. the crux is about 15 feet up when moving from the face to the dihedral.
location: In the northeast corner of the quadrangle. This is the prominent dihedral.

description: beta pending
location: beta pending

description: beta pending
location: beta pending

description: Sustained 5.8 face climbing.  A fun route, definitely worth doing.
location: First face on the approach to the cove, on the right after the boulder scramble.  Longer than most routes here.
protection: Solo the east face of Sentinel to set up anchor on the bolts/chain.

description: The easy laidback east face of Sentinel Tower.  Massive jugs and ladder-like climbing.  Crux is probably the top-out move.
location: The large laid back face to the right of the big chimney crack.  For a good alternate, scramble through the chimney to the ledge facing the river.
protection: Chicken necks can be slung in a couple spots, or use large active pro in the pockets.  Bolts on top for anchor.

description: Climb the chimney from the Cove (East) side of the Sentinel. Escape right to the north face near top and avoid the block on the South tower of the sentinel.
location: Separating the two towers of the Sentinel.
protection: TR from bolts on the Sentinel North tower, or solo. There may be placements for Big Bros in the chimney or smaller side gear on the East face.

description: Climb the wide crack and face on the left.

Nose/ar√™te around the corner from Double Overhang.  Follow the nose all the way up, but watch the spiders.  Crux is about a quarter of the way up, where handholds get marginal so you have to just hug the ar√™te and high-step it.  The exposure and views are pretty amazing, and it's also a wonderful photo opportunity...
location: Sentinel area.  Obvious nose around the corner from double overhang.  Start in the corridor access area.
protection: Bolted anchors and lots of solid trees at the top for TR.

description: Two bulges after the midway point mark the crux - the second harder only because you'll be more pumped when you get to it.
location: Off the edge of the cove to the far right.  Down climb to the belay or employ Aaron Stover's super swing method, which may well put a nearby tree branch up your heinny if you don't dial it just right.
protection: Anchor the cedars at the top.  Bring at least 50' of webbing.  The climbers approach to the top of the cliff is found down near the regular people's trail, before you do the class 4 moves into the cove.

location: The boulder in located at the bottom of the Sentinel area on the right side.
protection: Pads because the boulder is close to 12ft tall. There is also a bunch of trees close to the bottom that if you were to fall wrong you could easily fall onto.

description: beta pending
location: beta pending

description: Sustained climb, starts same as Pretzel and angles left at the split in the crack (where Pretzel angles right).
location: In the middle of the face between Third Crack and Nosey (at the Cove/Sentinel area).

description: The crux is the namesake of this route.  A hard reach right to an undercling and slick foot smearing.
location: Second wall on left (after the cave), follows obvious central line.

description: beta pending
location: beta pending

description: A moderately laid back arete and face route.  Crux is early.
location: Around the corner to the right of Pretzel.  Climbs the face and arete.
protection: Anchors the same trees as Pretzel.

description: Climb starts just left of Blank Wall,climb up small pockets with out holds from Second Crack and Blank Wall.Work up to thin crack (dont barn door)Pull small roof at top .

description: the route takes a little balance,and the crux is just under the the small nose overhang
location: The climb is in the Sentinal Area the climb starts just around the corner of Up n Off
protection: takes about 15 feet of webbing,same tie up as Up n Off

description: Crack and dihedral system to the right of Blank Wall.
location: First crack is in the southeast corner of the Quadrangle.
protection: Toprope or scant pro. Has dedicated anchor chain which can be reached by traversing right from the Nosey anchor ledge. There are a few bolts available to protect the traverse.

description: starts just left of third crack under an over hang- ends up and to the left by 4th crack
location: Sentinel area between 4th and 3rd crack

description: Bouldery overhang start to easier moves.
location: First route on left face as you enter the cove.
protection: Two or three larger cams should do it if you feel good running out, or hike to/approach from the top and drop a toprope from the three bolts surrounding the tree. Plenty of webbing needed for the anchor.

description: Large Chimney all the way up.  Classic ROute in MP.
location: Last large crack before the southern access point to the top.
protection: No Bolts, Top Rope from natural anchors.

description: Little pockets are the trick on this one.  Big first move with smears up to mono and 2-finger pockets. Sustained for the first two thirds, then it mellows out a little.
location: Up the middle of the face between the cracks at the east end of the cove.  Starts on a juggy 2-hand pocket about seven feet up.

description: Climb the southwest corner of the Open Bible to a large slanting ledge. Move left down the ledge to climb the short dihedral with and awkward but exhilarating layback finish.
location: See map.

description: Start on the overhanging face left of North Crack. Muscle straight up the face without using either corner, or the large tree to the left of the route.
location: See map. Left of North Crack.
See map. Starts just left of the center of the south face.

description: Climb 10 feet up the overhanging crack and continue up the easier blocky crack above it.
location: See map. Middle of Open Bible's north side.
Starts in the middle of the overhanging west face.

description: Just left of the Access Route is a nasty little overhang. This line is just like Hellish Move, but on a smaller scale. Warning: the crux is probably dealing with the face just below the roof.
location: See map. On the east side of Open Bible, left of the Access Route.

description: Start in the center of the face, directly below the offwidth crack with the tree at its base, in the upper level. Climb straight up and finish in the upper crack.
location: Center of the south face.

description: It's not as straightforward as it seems to be! Climb straight up the ridge.
location: See map. SE ridge of Open Bible.

description: Climb the east face on easy ledges just left of the large tree.
location: East face of Open Bible.

description: A short exposed offwidth chimney climb. Start in Chimney top out on face.   Best used as access to north facing climbs such as Northeast (5.8).
location: on south side of Twin Sisters, starts from a scramble up to ledge over face climbs
protection: set a bomber fist placement while on ledge, then a second can be placed before top out.

route_name: North Chimney (Flat on Your Back Crack)
description: Crack / chimney in the middle of the north side of Twin Sisters tower formation. Belayer is best at the very bottom near the trail - the climbing is 4th class / 5.easy at the beginning as you work your way up the ledges. Starts getting dicier as you approach the crack / chimney. Crux is when you first pull up into the chimney area and you're left to decide whether to try and wedge your way up the chimney or climb out onto the face. The hand holds are decent - the feet are a little trickier. Once you get over the chimney area its nice holds to pull yourself on top with some feet in the chimney to step up on.
beta pending
location: beta pending

description: Short but fun climb
location: just right of pedestal on at the base of Twin Sisters
protection: TR- cracks on top good for pro.

description: Another short, but easier climb. Climb the hand crack all the way to the top.
location: See topo. Start at the base of the tree (stump) above the cave entrance.
In Twin Sisters Area

description: Climb the face around the corner from Dihedral Crack.
location: See topo. Near the cave entrance just around the corner (to the left) from Difficult Crack.

description: Struggle up and through the triangular niche set in the wall about ten feet up.
location: See topo. Overhanging finger crack 6 feet west of Airhead.

description: Climb the chimney. The chockstone jammed in there will provide a bit of a challenge - it is easiest passed with a long stem across the chimney.
location: Chimney on the left side of the north face.

description: start at center of face, easy classic climb
location: Twin Sisters area located on south face of Brother Buttress
protection: TR pro or webbing at top. Available casual scramble to the top to build the anchor.

description: Begin on the block and follow a tiny seam up and to the right.
location: See topo. Begin on the block at the level of the horizontal crack 6 feet off the ground.
protection: Thin pro, if at all. Available casual scramble to the top to build a TR anchor.

description: Follow a series of ledges on the corner of the buttress.
location: See topo. Southwest corner of the buttress.

description: This route is a challenge right from the start.  The crux is at the bottom where a short 7ft crack turns horizontal to meet up with the rest of the crack just to the right of it.  Using a nice jug that's deep in the crack and some clever smearing you can set yourself up nicely to make the transition between the two cracks.  After the crux is below you a series of well placed hand jams will give you success.
location: The route is in the brother's buttress and twin sisters area and is just to the right at you pass the lower wall of the twin sisters on the trail that comes up from the road, parking lot, and outhouses below.
protection: There is one large boulder and one 3ft round boulder on top of the bluff that make for great top rope anchors but if your short on gear there are some good living trees that will do the trick if set up properly. Available casual scramble to the top.

description: Crack to the right of Java on the south face of Brother Buttress
location: Twin Sisters area Brother Buttress south face
protection: Top rope slings around boulders or a couple of cams and nuts. Available casual scramble to the top to build the anchor.

description: This short but challenging climb follows the crack that starts at finger size and opens up to off-width hands, on the corner of the North face. Climb the crack using a layback with your feet inside the chimney.
location: See topo. a Crack on the corner of the north face.

first_ascent: Dan Rapp, Dave Hug, Bill Weisharr, Rich
description: Layback the thin seam and eventually use face holds to reach the anchor
location: First sport route to the right of the crack

first_ascent: Dave Hug, Dan Rapp Bill Weishaar
location: Farthest left sport route on the wall

description: Navigate your way through the start to the small roof bulge. Take a deep breath and punch your way through the solid limestone crux sequences. This one will keep you on your toes until you clip the chains.
location: First sport route to the left of Apex Predator

first_ascent: Molly Gabel, Dave Hug, Eric Ulner, Doug Rothe

location: Begins at the same spot as The Luna Moth

description: Climb your way between the two walls, stemming, and eventually reach the anchor
location: Right side of the wall

description: Climb the thin crack in the center of the wall
location: Center crack of Ryan's Balcony

description: Climb the arete using both the arete and face holds to reach the anchor
location: Right most route of Ryan's Balcony

first_ascent: Chance Weith, Ryan Richardson, Dave Hug
location: Left most side of the wall

description: Not yet bolted. From the ledge its the left most bolted short route
location: Leftmost route perched on top of the ledge

description: Pull on edges and face holds moving up and right to reach the anchor
location: First route left of Spicy Guacamole

first_ascent: FA: Ryan Richardson, FFA: Dave Hug & Robert McKenny
description: Begin up the left side of the aerie using good holds, eventually work you way to the aerie and use both sides to reach the top
location: Directly right of Cricket Crack. Its the left arete of the Tombstone Wall

first_ascent: FA: Ryan Richardson, FFA: Dave Hug & Robert McKenny
description: The beginning is a worker. Especially in warm conditions. Once standing on the ledge prepare yourself for sharp yet very positive holds to a jug. Shake it out and work those feet through a mini crux to the chains. Fine line indeed. :-)
location: Center climb of the Tombstone face

first_ascent: Molly Gabel, Robert McKenny, Dave Hug
description: Another great climb found by Ryan Richardson. Begin in the crack and work your way up to the first bolt. From here work you way to the right and side pull against a crack to eventually an undercling to stand up and work you way towards the top.
location: Right around the corner (to the left of) from the other routes

location: First crack to the left of Sleeping Indian

description: Climb the crack jamming and laying back when you can. Bolted anchor at the top

description: Start up the face and work your way into the crack system. Layback and stem to the anchor
location: 15 feet left of the Eagle Wall
protection: Cams of varied sizes and an anchor

description: Climb through easy terrain to the ledge.  Move right to small face holds and finish to the left of the arete.

description: Sit start with a right hand on a sloper, and a left on an undercling. Bring a brush. This rig has cool moves, but is probably dirty.
location: East side of the Greenie Boulder

description: Climb the boulder problem left of the Cheek Project. If you climb straight up it is harder then if you angle up and left.

description: Climb up and right clipping two bolts, then mantle over a small ledge. Clip the small bolt on the ledge (as a directional) and continue to the anchor from here.
location: First sport route to the left of Planned Parenthood
5 feet to the right of the crack in the center of the wall

description: Start out on very moderate moves. After utilizing the jug to clip the 2nd bolt fire out to a right hand crimp. Left foot placement is crucial here. Do a mini gaston to a positive yet painful finger lock. Do a left hand foot match to stand up then clip. Take a good couple breaths and finish it out on slabby 10+ terrain to a fun mantle. The locks and holds can be sharp so if you have delicate fingers stay off.
location: First sport route to the left of the crack

first_ascent: Molly Gabel, Dave Hug, Dan Rapp, Jim Thurmond, Eric Ulner, Alan
description: Climb the the short hanging bloc section to reach the dihedral face. Begin up, and eventually reach and pull around the right. Climb the last section and reach the anchor
location: Directly right of Numero Uno

first_ascent: Molly Gabel,  Dave Hug, Bryan Haberberger
description: Pull through the hanging bloc and gain better stone. Ease your way through tricky moves and eventually mantle over the top to reach the anchor.
location: Directly right of Dead Mouse

first_ascent: Dan Rapp, Eric Ulner, Jim Thurmond, Dave Hug
description: climb the rightward crack to the anchor
location: Crack on the right

first_ascent: Dan Rapp, Eric Ulner, Jim Thurmond, Dave Hug
description: Climb the crack to the anchor
location: The crack on the right

first_ascent: Matt D., Dave Hug, Bryan Haberberger
description: Pull through the hanging bloc and begin up the face. Lay it back and hike though the arching flake to eventually mantle over the top and reach the anchor
location: Directly right of The Ring Neck

first_ascent: Thaddeus & Ashley Portz & Dave Hug September 2017
location: Begin on The Tallest Man and refer to photos for directions
protection: Standard rack of cams, quickdraws, and runners to extend/protect corners.

description: Climb through large block jugs into a vertical flake system. Lay it back and work up and right into block jugs on the face. Mantle over the top and reach the anchor.
location: First sport route to the left of Dietsche Legacy Ladder. Refer to photo

first_ascent: Dan Rapp, Eric Ulner, Jim Thurmond, Dave Hug
location: Left crack

description: Begin climbing on the right side of the wall. Climb up and mantle on the ledge, clip in and traverse left. Follow the seam and mantle the top to reach the anchor.
location: Middle of the Lily Wall
First route to the right of State Sponsored

first_ascent: Dan Rapp, Eric Ulner, Jim Thurmond, Dave Hug
description: Climb either crack or both using a variety of moves to reach the anchor
location: Left side of the wall

description: Climb the crack using lybacks and jams to reach the anchor
location: Refer to photo

description: Send the arching flake protecting when needed. Plug gear into the horizontal before the anchor
location: First crack to the left of Oyster Bar
protection: Standard rack mainly bigger sizes. Use passive pro when possible

first_ascent: FA: Hornbein & Dietsche, FFA: Ryan Richardson
description: Fight your way through the wide crack and protect when you can. The higher you climb the more it relaxes. Upon reaching the top tread your rope into the ram horns.
location: The wide crack directly left of Fin Inn
protection: Bigger cams, there is a hand crack in the back of it that protects well. Bring runners. Ram Horn's on the anchor for easy lower off

first_ascent: Ryan Richardson, Dave Hug, Dan Rapp, Jim Thurmond, Eric Ulner
description: Pull a few moves and press out the crux early on. Enjoyable climbing leads to the anchor
location: Middle line of the pillar

description: Climb the  large arching flake utilizing stemming and jams. Pull the fin at the top and reach the anchor
location: First crack to the left of The Loading Dock
protection: Standard rack .3 - 3 use passive pro when possible

description: Sit Start on a jug, reach up to some slopey jugs. Then, fire up to a large sloper. One of the best problems at Pounds Lake according to Matt Bliss.
location: Start on jug to the right of Zebra's in America
Once you meet the cliff line above Shadow of a Man, walk to the right past the roof. The wide crack is in a left-facing dihedral

description: Start on low edges. Left and right variations.
location: Left side of wall

description: Sit start with a long move to the horn.
location: locate big horn in small cave to the right of Formaldehyde

description: Climb the dihedral crack, crux is midway up.
location: First dihedral crack left of the blunt corner inside the woods.

description: Face climb with large pockets
location: Go around the corner left of Ditch Pitch and climb the face. Start about 10 feet right of Open Book crack.

description: Straightforward climb straight up the center of the gully
location: Its the second gully from the right side of the start of the cliff.

first_ascent: Gary Schaecher, Craig Barnes, Gary Frazier, Bruce Cyganowski, Bob Bennecke. FFA Adam Growowsky 1970's
description: Climb up the wandering crack. For a better challenge, start in the hand crack and work your way through the roof.
location: Climb the meandering crack 30 feet to the left of Goreville Eating Society

description: Another straightforward climb straight up the center of the crack
location: About 20 feet left of First Climb.
protection: TR from sturdy trees on top of cliff

description: Supposed to go up and left. Hard line. Follow the path of least resistance
location: Starts six feet left of Jennifer Goes To Hollywood

description: Climb the well protectable dihedral.
location: 90 degree dihedral to the right of Hawks Beak
protection: Standard traditional rack, larger sized pieces

description: Begin up the crack until it ends halfway up the wall. Traverse left along a rounded shelf. Pull through an overhang and climb up through a "V" shaped groove.
location: The crack 35 feet left of Rusty Pin

description: This is a tricky, balance dependent route. Climb no handed through the farthest gully /crack
location: Farthest gully/crack on the right side of the wall where the cliff basically ends

description: It starts on the right side of the Short Wall. Go straight up the face towards a cedar tree. The route is named for Ferne Clyffe's Ranger Sam.
location: On the Short Wall. The Short Wall is located 20 feet left of Cracked Heart. The wall is not very featured and is a high angle slab about 25 feet tall.

description: Begin by climbing through a small overhang on good holds. Continue through the continuous crack that angles to the right.
location: About 30 feet left of Hawks Beak.
protection: Standard traditional rack, takes small gear well.

description: Clim up the dihedral crack
location: 6 feet left of First Born. The dihedral crack

description: Climb the face and avoid using the crack
location: Starts three feet left of I Don't Care

the approach trail ends at the cliffline.Cross stream to the right and approach the base of cliff which is a overhang/cave. the route starts at right dihedral in overhang. Fashion anchor with slings to trees.
protection: The finger crack in back of water groove protects well with varied sizes and it has good stances to clip from.

location: On the Short Wall. The Short Wall is located 20 feet left of Cracked Heart. The wall is not very featured and is a high angle slab about 25 feet tall.

first_ascent: Jim Schneider, Jeff Allison, & Dan See 1994
description: Work your way up and through big pockets while angling leftward as you ascend
location: 20 feet left of Missouri Breaks. Go up through big pockets
On the Short Wall. The Short Wall is located 20 feet left of Cracked Heart. The wall is not very featured and is a high angle slab about 25 feet tall.

first_ascent: Scott Mueller, Dan Caldwell, & Pat Flynn 1995
description: Climb the face on the inside of the dihedral. Continue up, angling to the right, and move towards an overhanging point. Pull over the point, and follow the aerie to the top.
location: 40 feet left of Gangster. Its an overhung dihedral with an aerie on the right

description: Climb up the face
location: Climb the face a few feet to the right of Under The Influence
3rd gully from the right end of the crag.
protection: Traditional route which might take gear in the first third is all.  Usually TR'd or soloed.

location: About 80 feet left of Under The Influence.

description: Climb the thin flake until you top out onto a shelf. Top out straight above
location: 40 feet left of Miles From Nowhere. Walk through a corridor formed by boulders on your left. After you pass the first boulder look to your right and spot a thin flake. The route begins here

description: Climb the chimney left of Quasimodo
location: Its the chimney left of Quasimodo.
protection: TR from trees on top of cliff, might be possible to lead with standard trad rack

description: Climb the hand crack. Takes gear well for the leader
location: 18ish feet left of Divine Intervention
On the Short Wall. The Short Wall is located 20 feet left of Cracked Heart. The wall is not very featured and is a high angle slab about 25 feet tall.

description: Starts on the same flat jug as Grey Matter. Traverse pocketed feature up and right.
location: center of the wall

description: Begin on awkward underclings and climb the crack
location: left of Formaldehyde

description: Sit start in pockets, climb left and top out in Formaldehyde.
location: Locate pockets in cave to the right of Formaldehyde and begin from there

description: Start on flat jugs. Climb up and left.
location: same start as Formaldehyde

description: Awkward moves in a short fist crack lead to a ledge underneath a roof. Once you figure out how to stand up underneath the roof, one kind-of-airy move will get you above it, then a short army crawl will put you in reach of the anchors.
location: Right facing crack to your left when you meet the cliff line on the trail from Shadow of a Man

description: A nice(although short) line that starts as fingers and gets gradually wider after a small ledge. There are a few face holds to pull on when the crack turns to wide hands near the top.
location: This crack is located near the point where the main trail meets the cliff line by shadow of a man. When you meet the cliff line, there will be a wide crack slightly to your left. Turn right and follow the cliff for a few yards.Look for the obvious crack next to a small tree.
protection: Standard Rack. Bolted anchors have recently been installed at the top.

location: begin on pockets down low and right of Formaldehyde.

description: Traverse into The Zebra
location: Starts directly right of Flatty

description: Sit start on The Zebra, then traverse up and right.
location: Shares a start with The Zebra

description: Climb the prow feature
location: Begins on the right side of the arete, to the right of A Dedication to Andy Boone

description: Open project located on the short cliffline
location: Directly across the hillside from the Zebra boulder

description: Climb the thin crack with the natural pin scar
location: Thin crack to the right of the Arete Project

description: Climb up and right
location: Begin on the right side of the arete from Patty Cakes Left

description: Climb up and left
location: Problem begins on the arete to the right of the arete finish for Green Flies

description: Start low and climb up the face
location: begin in the shallow corner right of Patty Cakes Right

description: Project that climbs through the cave.
location: Uphill from the Zebra Boulder

description: Jump start to a huge pinch. Climb up the blunt arete. According the the guide book, the was the first boulder problem climbed at Pounds Lake
location: The arete to the right of Pin Scar Race

description: Start to the right of the Highball Project, traverse to the right and then go up.
location: Start near the Highball Project

description: Low start on a flat jug and work your way to the top from here.
location: Far left problem on the Zebra Boulder

description: Climb the arete
location: Next arete to the right from the Prow Project

description: Start low in the back of the cave, pull perfect hand jams out the cave.
location: Begin in the back of the cave to the right of Ivy

description: Climb over the small hump using a few ticks moves. Work up the apex of that feature and continue to the top.
location: To the right of the Makanda Layback and left of The Gully.

description: Start on Duraflame. Once you reach the obvious "positive/pinch/edge hold", move left into Sizzler
location: Starts on Duraflame

description: Form the block jug on Makanda Layback traverse left about 6 feet,keeping your feet inches from the ground, then go straight up ending in Open Book Direct's bowling ball pocket.
location: Begin on the large block jug at the base of Makanda Layback, traverse left, end in Open Book's bowling ball pocket

description: This is the infamous bouldering traverse problem that lines the lower edge of Shelter 1. This traverse holds three different crux sections. If you can find them, there are no hand rests along the way. This is truly a world class climb.
location: This classic variation is located between the Jill's and Camel's Hump. Start on the rock protruding out of the ground  at the base of Jill's, proceed by following path of lease resistance, and end by standing up at the base of Camel's Hump.

description: Climb up and pull the steeper side of the roof. Throw up and catch yourself on the lower edge of the table. Let your feet cut loose and pull the moves to the top. It is recommended that you belay the route from the top.
location: The exact opposite side of the tower from Chris's Climb. Start in the narrow hallway
protection: Standard traditional rack, tri-cams, nuts, slings

location: Climbs directly to the right of the Northwestward facing arete
protection: Standard traditional rack, tri-cams, nuts, slings

description: Begin on the lowest jug. Classic Southern Illinois sloppy topout.
location: Refer to Sandstone Warrior

description: Start on feature. Climb out on small holds. Finish by climbing rail system out and left.
location: Start on feature just below roof and to the right of the V12 project

description: Climb out roof on super small holds
location: To the right of Appleknocker

description: Fun.  Begin matched on Shelf at back of cave.  Work out cave roof on decent edges to jug on lip, avoiding flaking rock to the right(a hold was recently broken).  Exciting and tricky mantle top out up and to left.  Don't be afraid to get your heel over your head!
location: 10 ft left of Appleknocker. Starts on shelf at back of cave just to left of flaky feature on roof.

description: Adds a few really fun moves before linking up with Peach Valley. Start on Duraflame and traverse right into Peach Valley.
location: Begin on Duraflame and work right.
Starts on rail a few feet to the right of Duraflame
Start on light colored, chest level jug to the right of Sizzler

description: Start on the back obvious feature. Climb out and left to long move.
location: Located on the left side of the cave

description: Begin on Walk Up and make your way to the iron band jug at the first bolt. From here work right an up through a huge hueco to eventually reach the fourth bolt on Shotgun. Climb up to Shotgun's anchor to finish
location: Begin on Walk Up and end on Shotgun

description: Start by laying back the flake. Continue up and pull through the weakness in the overhang and continue to a narrow "S" shaped stripe. Continue laying back and move up and right to top out.
location: 18ish feet to the left of Shotgun

description: While performing a ballet of sorts, use some creative footwork to stem and smear your way up the wide gulley. Pull on good face holds to crank through the bulge and reach the top.
location: First sport route to the the Barne's Overhang
Begin on the Makanda Layback, traverse all the way to George's

description: This is the grand traverse that lets one venture across the Shelter 1 Bluff line. This route allows you to climb high above the grassy field below and avoids the harder sections underneath the overhang. A must for anyone desiring to explore the vertical sphere of the bluff. Absolute Classic!
protection: Standard traditional rack, tri-cams, stoppers, slings.

description: Another high angle staircase of a climb. Easy goes it. Good first lead.
location: First route to the right of Right Side Route

description: This is a short but sweet route. Standing On Air truly begins when the featured slab of Drunkard's Crack meets the wall just left of the small wash. Climb up the face using small nubblets.
location: From the base of Drunkard's Crack, locate a small wash. Climb up and left of it.

description: Staying to the right of Camel's Hump, climb the smooth face and skip the larger holds on the left.
location: Refer to photo. First route to the left of Standing On Air.

description: Climb up the slab to reach the wide gully at the base of the crack. Pull the tricky move and enjoy casual climbing to the anchor.
location: Directly right of Easy Crack
protection: Cams .3-3 and a set of small stoppers to help protect the face.

location: In between Walk Up and Double Barrel. Locate the short crack that goes through an overhang to the left of Shotgun. Follow a straight path up from the crack.

description: Begin up the ramp that leads to the Chimney. Refer to photo for specifics. Climb up the face, trick side pulls, work into the large undercling feature, then out through pockets and face holds. Stay left of the Shake N Back crack system, and right of Geroges Nose.
location: Refer to photo.

description: Climb the leftward angling crack system that juts off of the Chimney. Place cams until the angling flake feature meets the bolt line. Clip bolts from here to safely protect.
location: Directly left of the Chimney. Refer to photo
protection: Lead the first half with gear, as the rock quality decreases above the half way point, begin clipping bolts on the left of the crack. Follow the three bolts to an anchor.

description: Clip the bolt before pulling pulling the first bulge. Tricky is putting it mildly. Get your feet set, use the left hand side pull at the top of the seam almost directly below the first bolt. Reach up, grab the crimp with your right hand, and slap your way up the big sloper feature on the left. Climb the face and reach the bulge. Use a right handed, 2 finger pocket and perform a hard sidepull while getting your feet high to reach a decent left handed edge. Crank through and climb a short face to reach an anchor.
location: First sport route to the right of Tiny Dancer/first route to the left of Nowhere

description: High angle step climbing. Follow the water groove
location: First sport route to the right of Diagonal Direct

description: From the two stacked pockets climb through the upside down V formation and stay to the right of crackpot cave.
location: Starts on the two baseball sized stacked pockets about 15 feet left of Makanda Layback. Go up through the upside down V formation to the left of Open Book's bowling ball pocket.
protection: 6 bolts + an anchor whichever way you chose to finish.

description: Climb through the dihedral layback leftward to the base of the gully crack.
location: Obvious gully to the middle left of the Shelter 1 bluff.
protection: Standard traditional rack plus some nut placements.

description: Pull through the short moderate boulder problem to the base of the gully crack, mantle into the gully and enjoy.
location: Directly under the gully crack.
protection: Standard trad rack plus nut placements

location: Base of the Makanda Layback

description: Begin with the short, overhung start. Pull up and stand on iron-band ledge. Pull up and to the "pentagonal" hand pocket. Continue up the slab to a 3-finger pocket. Pull the move and follow good holds to the finish.
location: First sport route to the left of Joe's Variation

description: Beginning on Double Barrel, climb up and only use the left of the large hueco's that make the "double barrel". Basically continue to the top from here. This is an eliminate version of Double Barrel.
location: Shares the same start as Double Barrel

first_ascent: Doug Drewes & Joe Healy circa 1970's. Leo Kottke fans
location: Shares the same start as Graves.

description: Pull on small jugs to enter the gully crack, layback to the right and pull moves to eventually reach up left to nice horizontal edges, from there proceed to climb to the safety bolt "place a nut in the crack to the right to beef up the anchor point", then continue to the top through a rather blank section eventually meeting the last face, angle up and left eventually toping out and reaching the anchor. Fairly Committing Lead...
location: gully crack to the left of the camels hump
protection: Smaller trad gear down low then work into 5 bolts + anchor

description: Originally, you were to ascend the left facing crack system continuing straight above. Now, you begin just right of the original crack and climb the face.
location: A few feet left of The Bulge, refer to photo for specifics.
It's the obvious leftward leaning zig-zagging crack to the right of Poison Ivy.
Begin on Graves, refer to photo

description: This climb is similar to Drunkards in the way of how it angles to the right and is well protected. This is a great climb for those learning trad. Crux is either the crux of Makanda Layback or getting off the ground for The Gully
location: Begin at the base of Makanda Layback, climb up to the bolt, clip in and follow the crack at your feet as it angles to the right, top out on  Camel's Hump and use the anchors to belay partners up. (Easier Variation: climb up The Gully, go to the bolt, and then traverse right)

description: Starting just to the right of the tree, climb up for about 20 feet. Then continue up and right for 30 more feet, crossing back onto Dead Dog.  Continue by climbing through iron bands and finish by Cedar tree.
location: Start about 8 feet left of Dead Dog. Refer to photo.

description: Beginning with a unique high stepping mantle, balance over on your feet using shallow divots. Layback, high step, and slab climb your way to the anchor.
location: About 10 feet to the right of Standing On Air

description: Beginning a few feet left of Joe's. Locate the large pinch hold and crank up the face. Use a series of side pulls, edges, and underclings to reach the bulge. Reach out right, stick the pocket and work your way over the bulge using pockets and a life saving edge. Easier moves to the anchor from here.
location: Begins a few feet left of Joe's Variation, refer to photo for specifics.

description: Either choose to move a picnic table to the juggy ledge to aid in starting the route, or begin directly under the Camel's Hump and traverse left into the gully. Either way, stay left of Camel's Hump and work up through the slab towards jugs.
location: Its the wash left of Camel's Hump

first_ascent: Joe Healy, Doug Drewes, Adam Grosowsky
location: Locate the small cave in-between Jill's and Crackpot, climb through holds directly below it, and top out above Jill's
Refer to photo. Begins to the right of George's

description: Start directly below on the right side and make you way towards the chimney, plug your way through the gully crack.
location: The next large gully crack to the left of Chimney.
protection: You can clip three bolts as you climb up the face, then use catalogs 1-3 to protect crack, and now has a bolted anchor at the top.

description: This is the no-hands version of Drunkards Crack.
protection: If I recall correctly the last high step off the top is R/Xish as you really have to lean forward and commit or you'll for sure launch off and go flying backwards off the damn thing.

description: Begin at the base of Makanda Layback and climb up and left of M.L. setting yourself to climb up through the blank face
location: Start on Makanda Layback, angle leftward and ascend the blank face. Stay left of the crack on Makanda Layback and right of Open Book's bowling ball pocket.
This is the obvious crack up the hill and left of George's. Refer to photo.

description: Climb Dim View on trad gear. Boulder through crux sequence about 20 ft to good stance and some good but small gear( .75 and blue or purple Metolius TCU). Pull through the next pumpy sequence to reach another break which will take a #1 or #2 BD Cam.¬† ¬†Climb through the upper crux, sling the horn if you'd like then on to the anchors.
protection: C4's- .75, 1, 2.   Metolius TCU- Blue or Purple   Slings

description: Its the obvious wide crack that leads to the top. Commonly soloed to set more difficult routes. Great route for teaching traditional placements.
location: Located on the far right of shelter 1 bluff. It is the obvious rightward leaning crack. Two smaller trees are rooted in the crack in the lower section. Refer to photo.
protection: Single rack and an anchor at the top.

location: Begin on Poison Ivy Left and continue straight up through two large pockets while avoiding the gully.
protection: Standard traditional rack, tri-cams, nuts, alpine draws

first_ascent: Doug Drews, Joe Healy, Jim Foster 1970's
location: Locate the small boulder in the ground that is used to start Return To Forever, from there climb up and left while paralleling Jill's

description: Climb the sloping face and work your way to the anchor of Drunkard's Crack.
location: Face directly right of Drunkard's Crack

description: Climb to the small cave feature then work through the overhung crack feature until it ends. Step up on a slabby face and work through face holds and pockets and eventually reach the anchor.
location: A few feet left of Walk Up. Refer to Photo.
The route begins on the small crack on the leftside of the small cave to the left of Shotgun.

first_ascent: Jim Foster (during snowfall) 1970's, first free lead Chris Ecklund with worthless gear 1988
description: Climb the overhanging crack system into the little cave straight above, continue above it and top out.
location: Locate the cave about midway up and left of the Open Book Gully, follow the crack system leading up to it and top out.
