Nestled between Jill's and Poison Ivy Right, climb through the pocketed face while avoiding both crack systems.

description: Start at the bottom left, follow the crack up to the chimney, pull through the chimney.
location: First large chimney in the woods left of Poison Ivy.
protection: Standard traditional rack primarily on the larger side. There is now a bolted anchor at the top.

description: Start up Crackpot until you get to third bolt then cut left all the way to City Limits. You will pass through the cave on Graves on the way. Keep traversing until you reach the rest after City Limits crux. Finish the upper wall on City Limits. Long draw on the third bolt of crackpot eliminates any rope drag.
location: Start on Crackpot

description: This popular TR goes up the huge hump in the wall. By placing a picnic table at the base of the climb, you can make the start easier. Begin at the bottom-right of the hump and climb up toward the center. Top out through vertical bucket climbing. According to the 1972 guide Sandstone Climber, "every inch of the Camels Hump has been climbed."
location: Goes up the huge hump in the wall to the left of Drunkard's Crack.

description: Start on the short rightward tieback. Pull the mantel shelf about 10 feet up. Then go straight up to the top while staying 6 feet left of George's chimney.
location: Starts a few feet left of George's direct, refer to the photo for specifics.

description: Work your way up the slab and through pocketed holds in the overhang.
location: First route to the right of Easy Crack. Refer to photo

first_ascent: May 9, 2020. Andrew Staff and Dave Hug
description: This route traverses almost the entire length of the cliff. From the anchors of "Drunkards Crack" all the way across the bluff to the anchors of "Easy Crack". The climbing isn't that difficult, there are some tricky down climbing sections as well as a couple of run out spots. It's a fun way to get some easy mileage in and to touch some holds you probably haven't touched before. I belayed the second at the anchors for Gr√°ves and the anchors for The Chimney.
Climb the bulging arete feature 6 feet left of 1,2,3.
location: 6 feet left of 1,2,3

description: Climb the featured face up the angling wall.
location: First route to the right of Bittersweet

description: Located in a pile of boulders before the 45 degree wall, and behind two trees. Sit start with left hand on crimp, and right in pocket. Send from there.
location: Refer to Sandstone Warrior

description: Start below and climb through big hueco feature.
location: Far right side of the wall, climb through the big pocketed feature

description: Climb the right side of the wall
location: To the right of Slab of Meat

description: Low start on flake and reach right to slopey pocket. Move up right.
location: Right of Leather Face, begin on nice edges.

description: Direct start to Night Shift. Starts right of Thurmond Problem.
location: Right of Thurmond problem

description: Start in Thurmond Problem. Cut right at topout.
location: Starts on Thurmond problem

description: Start with right in low pockets. Climb right to small edges.
location: Obvious pocketed line on the rightish side of the wall

description: Climb straight up on big holds. Head left for the topout.
location: leftmost side of wall

description: Start sitting and move up to a pair of close holds at around face height. Then, move through a few slopey holds to a mono before making a big move up and left. Top out above along path of least resistance.
location: Between Gravedigger and Leatherface. Either starts sitting/crouched on a RH vertical sloper rail and LH pocket or standing at a closely-spaced LH pocket and RH incut near face level.

description: Climb on line of least resistance
location: left side of wall

description: Sit start on a jug rail and go straight up
location: 10 feet to the right of R.I.P.

description: Climb the left side of the wall. Easy slab as far as Southern Illinois goes.
location: 25 feet to the right of The Tomb

description: Climb the crack by starting in limestone-like pockets.
location: Climb the obvious crack in the middle of the wall
Leftmost problem on the wall

description: Stand Start on flat slopers and dyno to a flat flake. Then pull on good holds to the top.
location: Locate good holds on the right side of roof and dyno from there.

description: Start with a thin pinch on left and undercling pockets on right.
location: First problem to the right of Skeleton

description: From crimps at face level, move out to the cool slopey pinch feature, then continue out right on seam crimps to the obvious incut pocket, then up to the finish rail. Hang & drop.
location: To the right of bass assassin on the face described as the "hang and drop" project wall in the guidebook. The start crimps are directly below the right side of the pinch feature.

description: Begin with your hands matched on small edges. Once set, throw out big to the right for a blocky pinch. Top out from there.
location: To the right of Desperado in near the center of the boulder.

description: Sit start with matched hands on a big sloppy pinch pocket. Throw out to a pinch on the arete. Pull yourself around the arete. The problem ends when you stand up on the face to the left of the arete. Good problem.
location: Follow the directions posted on the mountain project page and they will lead you directly to this problem.

description: Start with left hand on side pull, right on slopy edge. fire to the crimp, then shoot for the jug.
location: Right of Smitty's House

description: From the foot trail, eye up the path of least resistance and go from there. The crux is in the lower section.
location: From the parking area hike up to the bluff line. As you approach you will notice a gradual sloping face almost directly in front of you.  The route climbs on the face.

description: Climb the clean extremely features slab.
location: About 100 feet to the right of Slip

description: Climb the face left of Unknown
location: 7 feet left of Unknown

description: Climb the crack left of Slip. Crux is low
location: The crack that starts 15 feet to the left of Slip
protection: Standard traditional rack, tri-cams, nuts, alpine draws

description: Climb the featured slab, using an assortment of holds to reach the top
location: Begins a couple feet to the right of Scout

description: Climb the crack on the left edge of the Gill Roof.
location: The crack on the left side of the gill roof that extends to the top.

description: Follow the broken crack system to the top, place gear when necessary
location: 6 feet left of 1,2,3

description: Beginning a few feet left of Scales of Iron, climb up using slopey edges eventually gaining access to unique iron banded holds. Follow the path of lease resistance to reach the top.
location: A few feet to the left of Scales Of Iron

description: Climb the angling, featured ramping face until you reach a steep wall at the top. Find the key holds to make the clip. Call it good from there, or very burly moves lead you to the top out. (top out variation 5.12-?)
location: First route to the right of 1,2,3.

description: Climb through the triple overhanging system. Protects well on lead
location: Located about 60 feet to the left of Jack's Crack.
protection: Rack of cams .3-4, Long Runners, +Bolted Anchor

location: Refer to photos

first_ascent: Dave Hug, Bailey Bunyan, Max Walsh, Molly Gabel, Chris Nevell
location: Refer to photos

description: Make you way up some low angle boulders, and climb on top of a ledge. Pull on good holds that aren't easy to find and make your way to the top. A fun addition to the Amphitheater
location: Directly below the Devils Standtable

first_ascent: Max Walsh, Molly Gabel, and Dave Hug
location: Refer to description.

first_ascent: Bailey Bunyan, Molly Gabel, Dave Hug, Max Walsh April 2nd 2019
description: Begin up a featured slabby face utilizing creative moves. When it becomes more difficult, turn off your tunnel vision, and let yourself lean back
location: Directly left of A Fissure of Green

first_ascent: Dave Hug, Molly Gabel, Bailey Bunyan
description: Climb the Canyoneering Route or Fissure Of Green and upon reaching the anchors, continue climbing through two more bolts to an even higher 1/2 inch eyebolt anchor setup. A fun continuance of an already creative route.
location: Begin on the Canyoneering Route or Fissure of Green

description: Climb up the crack system that divides the slabby face. Follow the crack, protecting as needed, until the crack ends. At the end of the crack, work up and left to a bolt, then stem your way out the top. Refer to photo for anchor location.
location: Far left side of the Amphitheater.

description: Start on jug rail to the right of embryo stasis. Traverse right to the arete, climb up and top out.
location: The climb to the right of embryo stasis.

description: Begin on good holds low and to the right of the arete feature. Climb through the arete to a hold in the seam. Top out to the left from there.
location: 20 feet to the right of the main Vultures Nest problems. Locate the obvious arete feature.

description: Starts 8 ft right of Higher Education, sit start on low slopers.
location: refer to photo

description: This problem follows a brown streak up the shorter, far-right portion of the wall.
location: Far right portion of the wall, right of Giraffe's Hat

description: Sit start. Intermediate jugs exist.
location: Left of the waterfall

description: Sit start in obvious pockets work up to crack feature, heel hook the overhung roof and top out.
location: A few feet to the left of Medicine Man.

description: Start low, slap to lip, move out right.
location: This is on the short boulder in front of The Center Line.

description: Sit start with left hand on arete and right hand in first pocket. Compress your way up using the arete and the two big pockets for your right hand.
location: Left most problem on Gill Wall.

description: This is the highball problem just left of The Streak. Starts in sidepull crimps and climbs through the biggest feature on the wall, a large hueco.
location: This is the highball problem just left¬†of The Streak.

description: Starts in buckets at eye level, continues through a softball-sized pocket to a highball top-out.
location: Middle of the wall

description: On the left side of the Gill wall, starts in high crimps. Thin face climbing to the top. A rap from the top to clean/inspect holds is probably necessary.
location: First problem on the left side of wall

description: Begin on the slab and climb out the roof using cool pocketed formations and a sloppy pinch. Topout on ledge around 20ish feet.
location: Start on slab 8 feet left of Teeter Totter.
protection: Crash pads and spotters are a must

description: Sit start on the side pull, and throw for the Hueco. Work through the Hueco and climb up and left to top out
location: refer to photo

description: Unnamed problem from the comp.¬†Sit start with hands on a slanted crimpy flake. Smear right foot in the dish and choose 1 of the 2 foot nubs for your left foot. Traverse right along the lower ledge using crimps, a sloper, and a heel hook or two. Lip/top of the boulder is off until the topout at the first crack on the lip. Casual topout on jugs after that.
location: On the second boulder next to the path in the Tyler Durden area when approaching from the Mollusk. Traverse left to right towards the unnamed V2 arete.

description: Unnamed V2 from the comp. Sit start on the obvious jug/flake. Climb up pinches¬†on the arete to a juggy topout.
location: The right arete on the second boulder in the Tyler Durden area when approaching from the Mollusk.

description: Start standing on an undercling and reach back to one of a couple good sloping holds near the back of the boulder. You may have to hop a bit to reach the hold. Top out. Small, short and sweet.
location: On a very small sloping ramp to the right of Tyler Durden. Walk off the boulder to get off.

description: Start on two underclings under the bulge. Work your way up to the next slopers and guck for a slopey edge up high. The boulder to the right is off.
location: Odd Job is located to the right of Tyler Durden and to the left of Robert Paulson and the tree.

description: Starting sitting the same as Tyler Durden, cut left and move to a good pocket and do a large move to a jug. From here, go straight up and somehow execute a tricky, dirty and scary mantel off not good holds. Be mindful of the slightly sketchy flake out left. AKA "Marla and the Tree," for reasons that may be obvious when you arrive at the problem.
location: Starts at the same place as Tyler Durden and cuts up and left. Walk off same as Durden. The tree behind the problem will make it easy to recognize.
protection: Pads and a good spotter to help you avoid the tree

description: Start on 2 big undercling jugs at the start of the horizontal crack. Cruise over on juicy underclings and follow the left leaning crack up. At the top, grab a slopey hueco in the big cut out, get a high foot, and reach up to nice jugs above the bulge to an nice top out
location: Opposite face of Tyler Durden. Tall, vertical, heavily-featured face.

description: From a sit start on two juggy holds, work upwards utilizing either a long pull off a small gaston or a big throw to a sloping jug off a crimp near the gaston. Grab a near the top of the boulder before slapping back to another sloper. From here, move right to a good sloping feature and top out. There is a variation that begins on Tyler Durden that cuts left and moves back right to join the top of Durden, and it is around the same difficulty.
location: Obvious line up the center of the Tyler Durden boulder. Walk over to a smaller, slabby boulder to get off.
protection: Because of the traversing and slightly insecure nature of the top out, 2 or more pads would be preferred.

description: Climb the arete to the left of grade school starting on a jug at head height.
location: Arete left of Grade School

description: Start on flakey jug, then work your way up using slopers.
location: Directly to the left of Cracked Shell.

description: Start low on pointed jug, climb up through the "embryo" and topout through the thin seam.
location: Vultures Nest Boulders (center).

description: Start as per Embryostasis, but continue left out of the embryo feature into the slopey topout of Cracked Shell.
location: Look for the embryo-like hueco. Begins on jugs below at the same spot where Embryostasis starts.

description: Start low on jug and throw to crimp ledge. Match and fight through slopers to finish.
location: First route to the left of embryo stasis.

description: Beginning low in the seam, utilize crimps and slopers and side pulls to eventually top out. The struggle is real.
location: 4 feet right of Sloper Slaper

description: Use the high start and climb up the right side of the arete
location: The tall arete 8 feet to the right of Seldom Chance

description: The obvious jug line on the roof. Start on the jugs at the bottom and work your way from monster jug to monster jug. Top out is crux. Either pull hard up to the horn or move out to the left to pull over the top.
location: The right most of the three really classic lines on this roof
protection: Pads. Good to have spotters for top out

description: Start on big holds around chest height, use good feet and good holds to get up.
location: Starts to the right of Texas Revolution.

description: Texas Revolution starts near the middle of the boulder, on the monster jug. Walk your feet up to get hold of the small left hand crimp, get your feet up, and do a dead point to the high right hand crimp. Get hold of a left hand, get your feet up, and launch for a hold near the top. This is a tall man problem unfortunately.
location: Center of the boulder.

description: Sit start and climb the arete using gastons and pockets, feet like to cut...
location: Left leaning boulder on top of the slab about mid way up the wall.

description: Get to the holds up above your head using the large steps on the left side of the boulder. Establish yourself, get a high heel, and go for the big slot up high.
location: Directly to the left of Texas Revolution.

description: Begin with a sit start, throw left hand to obvious fat sloppy pinch, stick the match and climb out the roof
location: First problem to the right of The Standard
protection: Crash pads and spotters for topout

description: Follow long moves on small holds out the roof
location: First boulder problem to the left of Devil on a Leash

description: Distinct & awkward lowball on the short boulder next to the Gill wall. Hands follow the lip from left to right on good slopers.
location: Begin on good holds in the middle of the small boulder to the left of the Gill Roof

description: Start in corner on left of Leashless Angel. Go right and traverse around roof till you are past the corner then topout. Save some strength, top out is probably the crux.
location: Sit start on low ledge left of Leashless Angel
protection: Crash pads and spotter for top out

description: Sit start right facing crack to the right of Pinch Me. Move out to the obvious shelf then traverse left. Same top out at Pinch Me.
location: Begins at the crack to the right of Pinch Me
protection: Crash pads and spotters for topout

description: Start with a huge move to small holds, continue out through jug eventually to right hand side pull, stick the swing at the end and top out.
location: This is the boulder line that goes out the middle of the Gill Roof.

description: First and second move
Start with left hand in crack and right hand on Jah Arete, figure it out from here
location: left of Jah Arete, refer to photo for specifics

description: Start low on the arete. Use the side pull on the right to top out this super tricky problem.
location: refer to photo

description: Sit start and layback the arete, climb through apex and top out. Super slopey and cool. People call this problem V3 but is more likely V4.
location: Down past the little stream and up by the actual standtable. Before the sign turn left and follow a noticable path down by the bluff. On the backside of a boulder facing the bluff is a left leaning arete, this is Buzz Arete. Its directly across from Jah Arete

description: Match hands on good edge with bad feet, make big moves and go up and left.
location: 8 ish feet to the right of Brimstone, refer to photo.

description: Begin by using the high edge feature, throw to the lip of the boulder.
location: In the narrow hallway a few feet to the right of Jah Arete

description: This is a cool warm up for the area. Begin low and in pockets. Use the seam and Sloper hold to climb up and left
location: 6 feet left of Goldfish

description: Begin very low in the good undercling hueco. Throw up to some crimpy holds and work through slopers and edges to finish. A burly move awaits
location: 5 feet right of Cluck Catcher

description: Begin with right hand on side pull in the seam, and left hand in shallow pocket. Throw to the fish head ‚Äúopen mouth‚Äù hold and work up and left, then top out.
location: 6 feet right of Splitting The Difference

description: Beginning with a left hand on a crimp, and your right hand with fingers stacked in a flaring¬†groove, plant your feet and fire up to the chicken heads. Pull through good holds and exit left or right.
location: 3 feet right of Goldfish

description: Start on good horizontal seams, get your feet set and make a long reach to a good hold. Continue using horizontal seams to reach the top.
location: First problem to the right of Battle For Endor. Refer to photo

description: Climb using thin horizontal seams to reach the top
location: To the right of Boba Fett.

description: Start at the beginning of the arching rail feature and climb up the "worm" through jugs and slopers with helpful heel hooks to keep you from cutting feet. Finish on the large jug at the end of the rail.
location: In between the KFC boulder and the Public Enemy boulder. Climbs Worm's Way without the hard, V9/10 start.

description: Climb up the last seam to the right of Big Meech to the positive ledges and the classic slopey topout.
location: Last line to the right of Big Meech.
protection: A single crash pad should be fine.

description: Same start as Red Sea, but go directly up the arete.
location: Same start as Red Sea. Climbs the face directly to the right of Armageddon 5000.

description: Between Inspector Gadget and Darkside is this tricky one mover. Start standing with your left hand in a small undercling pocket and right on an awful crimp. Pull onto the wall and smack the lip of the boulder. Move left a bit onto some more positive slopers to top out.

Start deep in the cave with both hands in the hand jam section. Work out the cave using fingerlocks, smears, and brute strength. Pull the bulge and finish in the massive hueco for a nice sit down finish (or top out the tall fist crack).
location: On the main cliffline in between public enemy and undercling king. Look for the massive hueco (15 ft     high) above the cave.

description: Variations exist for the Start. Either very low on juggy pinches and huecos, or slightly higher on slopey-er pinches. Either go straight up or up and left. Grade depends on these factors, but basically falls withing the V1-V2 range.
location: Directly to the left of Inspector Gadget. One of the leftmost lines on the Public Enemy Boulder.

description: The Square arete on the far right side of the Public Enemy Boulder. Starts on two slopers and does a big move up and left, then another bump with the left hand. A strange three finger undercling/sidepull pinch at the lip leads to a jump to a 45 sloper. Unique top out.
location: The Farthest right side of the Public Enemy Boulder.  Its the Arete.

description: Start on a big jug, then cross with your left to a interesting pinch and find a way to reach the top of the boulder.
location: Narwhal starts immediately to the left of Platypus.

description: Far left, low sit start on short problem

Starting seated, reach to a friendly crimp with your left hand and leap to a very positive edge above the lip of the boulder with your right hand. Mantle it out. A fun jump, albeit not the biggest dyno in the world.
location: It is about in the center of the trailside face. Once you've topped out, jump off the boulder onto a pad to get off.
protection: The boulder is not very high and one pad should be fine

description: The usually dirty face to the left of Platypus
location: Between Dark Side and Platypus

description: Starting standing on a left hand undercling and a right hand crimp, do two hard bump moves to reach your right hand to the lip of the boulder. Fun and tricky mantle to put you on top. Cool holds and movement, but a bit too lowball to be a classic.
location: About five feet right of Inspector Gadget, right before the ground starts to go downhill

description: Start on a low undercling with your left hand and a side pull with your right hand. Pull two moves to the jug on Narwhal.
location: Between Narwhal and Platypus.

description: A beautiful tall, slabby ar√™te.
location: Anthrax Ar√™te is on the boulder next to the Public Enemy boulder. If you're facing Platypus, it's the boulder to the right, on the opposite side.
protection: Pads + Spotters. Be careful, to the left of the ar√™te is a drop off!

description: start low and left. make a few moves on whatever holds feel best to a hard move to gain a good hold in the middle of the face.  keep moving right then up the heady, somewhat slopey topout
location: backside of boulder. start on good holds down and to the left. the problem starts heading straight up to top out right above the detached boulder on the ground.

description: Moses starts on a horizontal edge/pinch to the right of Red Sea. Move left to a crimp and then pull a large lock off move to intersect with Red Sea. Finish up on Red Sea.
location: Moses starts directly to the right of Red Sea.

description: Based on "Secrets of So iLL" video: Start in middle of the wall and dyno to gaston-jug (crux). Lower start on crimps may exist.
location: Red Sea boulder, the wall to the left of the slopey rail for Cain and Ankle.

description: Sit start and climb up slopey rail using some crimps out left.
location: Left side of scooped face on back of Red Sea Boulder.
Sit Start the same as Moses, then after the 1st half of Moses, continue over into Big Mitch and finish on Big Mitch.

description: Start matched on a pedestal ledge, climb right on good edges, finish it off with a large throw to a good sloper.
location: Between Red Sea and King Solomon.

description: Start on horiztanal holds with hands crossed, then reach up to the seem to the left, paste your foot and fight your way up using nasty slopers.
location: Starts the right Cain an Ankle. Obvious bulge looking problem.
Sit Start the same as Red Sea, then do the first half of Red Sea, then continue over into Big Mitch and finish on Big Mitch.

description: Start low on two jugs, throw a heel toe cam in, match the left and work your way through a series of pinches and slopers. This problem isn't over till you've topped it out.
location: Armageddon 5000 starts to the left of Red Sea.

description: From a sit start, traverse right on a series of poor pinches to a really large move to gain the huge swooping jug feature. Using the jug swoop, do a sequence that clocks in around v3 and hang and drop at the large circular jug.
location: Facing the Shadow of a Man boulder, turn around and walk to the cliffline. You will see an obvious, swooping jug feature. The problem begins seated underneath and to the left of that feature.
protection: 2-3 pads and a spotter. All the difficulty is 3 feet off the ground but falling off the v3 section with no pad would just be adding injury to insult.

description: Climb Worm's Way to the jug, but rather than hanging and dropping, follow a line of crimps to the top of the wall and top out. Might be nice to have these moves dialed in just in case you send Worms Way and have a bit more juice left at the jug. Would be easy to climb up the jug feature to work the crimp moves.
protection: 2-3 pads and spotters. Falling off the top of this will probably be safe, but scary nonetheless.

description: Start on two matched pockets and move up the slab on sparse holds and kind of bad feet. The topout is a little tough.
location: On the Shadow of a Man boulder, on the slab face that is between the Shadow of a Man arete and Seafoam Arete. It's near the middle of the face and starts on two matched pockets, to the right of Seams Easy V5.

description: Start on edges on the arete do a long reach, followed by another long reach up and left. Easy top out, but not a great fall if you blow it.
location: The arete left of KFC. On the boulder behind Shadow of a Man and Secret of Davenport.
Shadow of a Man.

description: For the sit start, begin several feet to the right of the normal start for Shadow. Pull a large first move to some crimps, then traverse left into the start for Shadow of a Man.
location: A few feet to the right of the normal start of Shadow.

description: Work your way up a tall slab that leads to a commuting mantle up high.
location: Located to the right around the corner from Shadow of a Man. Start down low and to the left of the tree.

description: One of the best of the grade the Holies has to offer. Starting on a low jug, move up to a slopey sidepull, do some magic with your feet and reach your left hand up to a bad crimp. Get your feet up, and do a tricky move to a blocky jug in the middle of the face.
location: On the face of the Shadow of a Man boulder directly left of the right arete.

description: Start sitting quite low on the center of the Shadow of a Man face. Follow small crimps left and up slightly. Slap the lip and do a weird mantle about five feet above the ground. Not the best problem at the Holies, but cool holds. I climbed this thinking it was an FA and gave it this name. Dave Chancellor has since told me it has been done, but he says he cannot recall the name, so we will just go with this.
location: Shadow of a Man boulder, same face as the namesake problem

description: Follow the thin seam to the top-out. Crux is about mid-way up.
location: This route is located on the same boulder as shadow of a man (around the corner to the right of it). Its on the South West facing side of the boulder approximately in the middle.
protection: A few well placed pads and active spotters should keep you safe.

description: Follow the slopey arete to the top of the boulder.
location: Walk around to the face opposite of Shadow of a Man on the Shadow of a Man boulder. It will be the arete on your left.
The face opposite Shadow of a Man.

description: An interesting slab problem revolving around one difficult move. Start standing on a thin left hand iron crimp and right hand broken sidepull. Work upwards on small holds to a very long lock-off. Continue towards the jugs near the top of the wall. Hang and drop from the jugs at around 15 feet. The rock is pretty but a bit brittle. Be careful!
location: From KFC/Worm's Way, walk uphill to the back of the huge boulder that Worm's Way is located on. There should be a large, orange amphitheater across from the slab on the back of the Worm's Way boulder. The Other Axis is located about 10 feet left from the rightmost arete of this wall.

description: Move through good holds until you can get your right hand on the faint, slopey arete. Work your way through this cool feature to the easy top out. Short but sweet.
location: Walking down the trail to Shadow of a Man, this relatively small boulder will be on your right. Worms Way will be to your left, Shadow of a Man just ahead. KFC climbs the trailside face.
protection: 1 pad, spotter if you want it

description: This may have been an FA as I've never heard any talk about this climb, but it seems too obvious to not have ever been done. Name is what my buddies and I have always called it. Climbs the obvious arete to the right of The Other Axis on sharp holds. Hang and drop when the holds get really juggy. Dirtyish...
location: Uphill from KFC and Worm's Way in the huge orange amphitheater-type wall. The rightmost arete on this wall.

description: A compression problem that goes up between Tennis Shoe Arete and KFC. Go to the pocket with your right, then climb up the two arete features.
location: Between Tennis Shoe Arete and KFC.

description: A tall proud line. Begin on the middle of the face and work your way up the wall using positive crimps. You may want to try the moves on a rope first, the crux is at the top.
location: Located to the right, around the ar√™te of Worms Way. The start is on the middle of the face.
protection: Lots and lots of pads and spotters! Also the landing is very slanted.

description: Starting on a very awful looking hold, follow nearly non-existing holds slightly left and upwards. I do not know very much info about this route, and as far as I know it is unrepeated. Another twisted boulder problem from the mind of Kehl...
location: Located between Worms Way and Baby Killers. A trifecta of crazy, double-digit problems... Begins quite high on an improbable looking hold that may or may not be chalked.

description: Start standing on slopers, follow the slopey lip about halfway across the entire face and then mantle. Poor feet.
location: Facing Seafoam Arete and Comfortably Numb, it traverses the swooping lip of the boulder starting on the right side.

description: Follow a line of small, sharp crimps up the slabby face. Could have more stars if the holds felt a bit better to hold...
location: Facing Seafoam Arete, it is the problem that ascends straight up the face.

description: Starting on two strange slopey holds, pull onto the wall and lock a heel-toe cam. Work upwards on crimpers to a slightly high top out.
location: Two lines left of Worms Way
protection: 3 pads or so would be good for the top out

description: Start low on a flat shelf and climb up through a flake and some positive slopers to an even more slopey top-out slab. Finesse your body over the bulge and finish your way up the delicate top section.
location: Trend right on the trail through a few large, tall boulders with a very low angle slab to the right. This boulder is located directly through this corridor, the problem is located in the middle of the face.

description: Start matched on two crimps down low. Pull some moves to get out to the arete out left. Same finish as Stilleto.
location: Same boulder as Stiletto. The start is down and right of the bulge.

description: Climb the offwidth chimney on the warm-up boulder. Shimmy your way up to the lip without using the arete.
location: On the warm-up boulder near Fire Up the Barbie and Hot Rats.

description: Start matched on a large flake and cross into an interesting plated-mushroom hold on the roof then move out the the large, positive sloper to the right. Establish on the sloper and move up through your choice of pockets and other holds to a jug and following top out.
location: This problem is directly right of Sweet As, Man. Look for the big sloper.

description: The start to this problem is down low, on a right hand pinch and a left hand crimp. The first move is the crux, and you need to be careful to not dab on the boulder behind you. Fun arete climb.
location: To the left of Sweet As.

description: Start on head-high jugs, heel and cross up and right to some smaller holds. Then toss to the lip, mantle, and scramble to the top.
location: Take the trail right between two tall boulders. Walk past a slab on the right towards Sweet As, Man, then turn right.
protection: One or two crash pads should do it.

description: Climb using good hold to the top
location: Left most problem on the boulder. Refer to photo.

description: Use good holds to reach the top
location: To the right of That's No Moon.

description: Pull using good holds to reach the Death Star. Continue up and through the middle of the Death Star
location: First problem to the right of No Disintegrations. Refer to photo

description: Start on the right side of the boulder pulling on crimps. Make a long reach to good holds and continue to the top.
location: Refer to photo

description: Climb using thin horizontal seam to reach the right side of the Death Star. Climb to the top from here.
location: First problem to the right of Death Star Center. Refer to photo

description: The back of the Mollusk boulder is littered with a large amount of holds, most being very positive. There are many variations that exist. Traversing from left to right (and back again as much as you please) is a great way to get warm on some great feeling holds.
location: On the back of the Mollusk boulder
protection: Pads and a spotter if you're going to top it out

description: Follow the very obvious line that goes along the slopey scoop on the right side of the boulder. The classic warm-up of the Holies.
location: Right side of the Mollusk boulder

description: Start on two wide sidepull crimps, and drop into a right hand crimp. Then climb straight up the technical face... (look for that undercling!) a committing last throw to a jug in order to avoid dabbing/crashing through the  tree. Crux is making the stab into the slot at mid height. Some use the thin undercling, others go big...  Absolutely classic.. Enjoy.
location: To the right of Enlightenment around the arete. obvious face climb on crimps and slots.
This is ten feet or so to the Right of Flugelhorn, below a large groove in the rock, just before the boulder gets very low and mossy. Ill add a picture sometime soon.

description: Sit start on the far left side of the overhang. Crux is a fun dyno off a left-hand pinch.
Start matched in crimpy hueco, post your feet, then go for the lip. The topout is the hardest part!
location: Wall facing the path.

description: Kung Fury has the same start as Flugelhorn, but instead of topping out directly up, you move left behind the tree on small sharp crimps.
location: Same start as Flugelhorn.
Hueco start under roof. Sit Start

description: Short, steep, pinches & compression on the far right side of the boulder.
Start low on pockets, traverse up right and top out behind the tree.
location: To the left around the ar√™te from Open Gates.

description: Adds two moves. Low start with right hand slopey hueco sidepull, and left hand hueco sidepull. Left foot either toe hook or heel-toe cam. Climb up the slightly overhung wall utilizing slopers, pockets, crimps and a second heel-toe cam. Cruxy top-out. Sometimes also known as "Crimson Flower"
location: The Sit Start to Trillium

description: Starts on a left hand 3 finger pocket (four for some) and a right hand slopey slot. Utilize either a hard to place heel-toe cam or a bad smear to get to an iron crimp feature. Slopers, sidepulls, and crimps lead you to a hard topout.
location: To the right of Michael Jordan, the leftmost line on the first boulder.

description: Dont know who put it up, and fairly certain it has never been repeated. Climb the water groove directly left of the tree, and to the right of trillium.
location: directly to the left of the tree.
To the right of Undercling King

description: Same start as Running with Scissors, but cut right when you reach the seam heading to the right side of the boulder.
location: To the right of Undercling King.

description: Begin on a sloper, pull a couple lock off moves, then cruzer at the top.
location: Left side of the face that Jungle Book is on.

description: Start directly to the left of Enlightenment. Stand Start on two holds at chest height. A right hand sidepull, pockety fingerlock thing, and a left hand pinch. Hard move going left to a pinch, go right to a sloper, then duckbill crimp, then top out. Two topouts are often done. If you traverse right into enlightenment, it feels morelike v6, but the original way stays straight, and avoids all the holds on enlightenment. This way probably clocks in around v7.
location: start to the right of a tree and left of Enlightenment

description: THE testipece of the Holy Boulders. Jason was shown this line when it was dubbed "fatty sloper action" and devoted his time to be rewarded the FA of the best line at the Holies. Start down and right on the arete jug and move up and left through horrible slopers to a hard heel hook or hop move at the lip. absolutely gorgeous climb on sticky holds with perfect Fontainebleau friction, and features.
location: to the left of Michael Jordan. the first, and rightmost line on this boulder.

description: The amazing looking sloper problem to the left of Crimson Flower. Sit Start down and right in the "Air Jordan" feature. Make a big move up and left and then work through the slopey feature to reach a bad right hand crimp. Make a huge dyno move off of this crimp to a hold over the lip. Hard, scary mantle.
location: to the left of Trillium/Crimson Flower.

description: Tall but doable. Start on a large undercling sidepull jug feature and work up and slightly right. Crux is a long move to a gaston from a small 2-3 finger right hand gaston. high as hell, proud.
location: when facing the jungle book arete, this climb will be up and right of you. You will see a large hueco on a face up the hill. This is the boulder you want. Head through the corridor to a a tall face, with a large jug undercling/sidepull feature at about 6 feet. This is kings high

description: Classic overhung arete madness on the leftside of the New Zero Boulder. start on the left of the arete on jugs climb up aways till the holds disappear then do a large, but static move to a sloper on the arete. Slot a toe-hook then match the sloper. Cut your feet and enjoy the ride. Stick the crazy swing and then campus the final moves to a hard but manageable topout. Absolutely hyper-classic
location: the arete to the left of the new zero
protection: many pads and spotters for crazy swing.

description: This is the first boulder you will come upon in the Illuminati sector. Climb the rounded ar√™te utilizing slopers jugs as pinches. Sit start low and slightly right on ar√™te with big feet. The crux is the topout. Enjoy
location: First obvious ar√™te with slopey huecos and jugs. Down climb is on back of boulder

description: Start on high ledge, pull move into large flake and climb up.
location: Directly to the right of Bubbles.

description: Climb the finger crack that splits the face like an exponential decay function through a graph. Sit start low on the crack and finesse your way up with toe jams, gastons, and laybacks.
location: Just downhill from the Full Grain slab, but before Jump for Jesus. The crack can be seen by looking through the corridor between Jump for Jesus and the abutting boulder to the right.

description: A slab problem using the right ar√™te of the Full Grain boulder.
location: Swade is located on the right side of the same boulder as Full Grain. Start and finish using the right ar√™te.

description: Start on a side pull around head height, get a smear and pull up to a bad right hand side pull. Hand-foot match, and stand up.
location: The right side of the same slab the Stand Up to the Left is located. Also directly behind Have It.

description: For this problem you're going to start on the left bigger hueco on the big slab face. Once you have your hands in it, start traversing left and up to a committing last move.
location: This problem is directly up the hill to the left from the Full Grain boulder, and slightly to the right of the tree next to the boulder.

description: Start low, with right hand on the ar√™te, left hand on anything you can grab. Stand up to a small left hand crimp, get a higher right foot and shoot for the lip.
location: Shoot from the Hip is located a couple boulders to the right of the problem Jump for Jesus. When heading that the direction, you'll come face to face with the slaby problem.

description: Same start as B-Cup, but go up to the pinch with your right hand instead. Use a toe hook to pull a rose move to the top.
location: Same start as B-Cup.

description: Start low and to the right of the start for B-Cup. Pull the first move to the start of B-Cup, then throw for the ar√™te to finish.
location: Starts down and to the right of B-Cup.

description: Start sitting down, climb up on good holds.
location: To the right of Jump for Jesus

description: Begin a few feet to the right of the arete. Climb up the slab face using good feet and a crimp near the top. Arete is off.
location: Behind Have It and around the corner of Stand Up to the Right.

description: Start in the middle left of the face, then work your way up and to the left to the ar√™te using crimps.
location: Located on the opposite side of the Boulder as Stand up with the Left, in the corridor. The start is a little bit to the right of the ar√™te.

description: A tall slab with a little dyno with decent holds.
location: To the right of Avant Gardener.

description: Start on two opposing crimpy side pulls, dyno to the lip and top out.
location: Downhill from Full Grain, right from Bill Cosby. On the far right side of the boulder's face.

description: You better keep your core tight if you want to finish this one. Have It starts with your left hand in a pocket and right on the ar√™te. Work your way up the ar√™te using smears and balance. The finish move is the crux.
location: Have It is located on the ar√™te of the cliff cline up the hill from the Full Grain boulder.

description: Start towards the bottom left of the slab, hand(s) in a slopey dish. Continue straight up the slab until the crux at the lip, don't slip!
location: Downhill from the cliffline and trail between the Illuminati boulders and Vulture's nest area. Just uphill from Jump for Jesus.
protection: A few pads and a spotter.

description: Start low, with right hand at the end of the pockety feature, and left hand on pinch. Huck for the lip, then mantle.
location: A few feet directly to the right of Bourban Shooter.

description: Work your way up the face using pockets.
location: Bubbles is located on the cliff line, a little bit to the right of where Have It is located. Unfortunately there isn't a direct path to the problem.

description: Start low with left hand in a two finger pocket and right hand on a pinch. Huck to the lip and mantle.
location: The problem immiedtly to the right, around the ar√™te, from Shoot at the Hip.

description: Start matched on the large hole, move out left to the arete, and top out.
location: Left side of the boulder that Jump for Jesus is on.

description: Same start as Bangin Blood, but go directly up instead of using the crimps out right.
location: Same as Bangin Blood.

description: Start on flake, pull over arete to crimps and top out.
location: To the right, down the cliff line from B-Cup.

description: Start low on sloper, throw for the boob, then pull to the lip.
location: B-Cup is located on the cliff line. To get there start at Have It, and move left along the cliff line for about a hundred yards till you hit an ar√™te. You'll know you've found it when you see a iron boob-like hold.

description: Climb up tall featured slab. The crux is at the beggening.
location: Avant Gardenor is on the right side of the same wall that Presto is on, but to the left of Lemon of Pink.

description: Start on two good side pulls to the left of Bangin Blood. Climb up using some nasty slopers.
location: To the left of Bangin Blood.

description: The slab along the arete to the left of Presto. This is also the (scary)¬†downclimb for Presto.
You'll have lots of options to go up and down the rails that run this side of the boulder, but a lot of the holds are junk. Give it a feel before jumping on. Good warm-up.
location: Start on Lowrider and traverse right. Topout up the crack at the end. Have a spotter to drag your pad, and to keep you from hitting the tree if you fall off the topout.

description: Sit start on great jug and okay feet. Follow obvious jugs. Great sloper to left of the small crack and a good lefthand sidepole on the left edge make for a clean topout.
location: SW corner of boulder. Sit start hand-matched on great jug.

description: start on horizontal finger cracks at chest high to the left of con artist, work straight up crimps on short problem

Start on your choice of very poor slopey slot crimps and head straight up the short slabby face. Hard move off bad left hand crimp. Deceivingly hard. Selected quotes: "Oh, that'll go next go for sure." "That was so close!" "Maybe next trip..."
location: Center of the Mollusk boulder
protection: 1-2 pads, a spotter isn't really necessary but may help

description: Start in the cut out part of the boulder, then figure some way to get your feet up onto the slab part.
location: This problem is around the right ar√™te of Bubble Wrap. It's the obvious slab problem.

description: Start low and work your way up using slopey pinches. The topout is probably the hardest part.
location: Hourglass is located the right side of the largest boulder in the second cluster of boulders, next to the small bridge.

description: Fun little problem on the left side of the Brown Cow Boulder. Jugs to a fun topout.
location: Two problems left of Brown Cow. RIght in front of a small tree.

description: Start as low as you can on the slopey ar√™te. Traverse right on good holds, then top out.
location: Left side of the boulder.

description: Left most (of the good climbs) on the first boulder. Goes up the center of the wall utilizing two big sloping square pinch features. Tops out up and left.
location: Center of the Wall, starts on obvious Jug feature. Down climb is back and left of the boulder.

description: sit start and go up along arete
Same start as Bio-Terrorism, but when you reach the lip, start moving left, then top out.
location: Same start as Bio-Terrorism

description: Sit start with your hands on the lowest slopers possible. Climb up using more slopers to a crux, slopey topout!
location: On the right side of the Bio-Terrorism boulder.

description: Good but short. Sit Start on the farthest right side of the first boulder in the Brown Cow Area, on small edges. Climb up the seams and edges to juggy top out.
location: On the farthest right side of the boulder.

description: Short and Dirty Crack on the right side of the first boulder you come to at the Brown Cow Area
location: Obvious crack on the right side of the first boulder in the Brown Cow Area

description: Dig hard on that heel and follow the bad slopers up and right to the start of Sukha stand. Start hold tends to be wet for a while after a good rain.
location: Sit start low and left of the start for Sukha, and follow the bad slopers.
Rightmost line on the same face as Brown Cow. Big Slopers and Jugs. This also serves as the downclimb. .. stack pads and jump off.

description: Tall face to the right of Brown Cow. Start on high start holds and climb up the featured wall.
location: on the rightside of the Brown Cow face, seven feet left of the arete.

description: Start on low jug undercling and do a big move up and right, out of the overhang to a good edge. Match the edge and finish on jugs. Crux is not draggin yo azz on da ground.
location: directly down and right from Brown Cow. Starts on jug undercling in the chossy mini roof low to ground.

description: Sit Start on two 1 pad crimp/seam/edges and either go out left to a pinch on the arete and then head up, or do a big left hand move straight up to a good rail. Juggy topout.
location: The leftmost line on the back face of the Brown Cow Boulder. Right around the arete from Sukha.

description: The starting section has a fun sequence moving through big holds. Easy topout.
location: Start the same as Fisherman direct, but move farther up the rail until in the groove, and then move up to the topout from there.

description: The first route on the next boulder if heading right up the trail from Sukha. The sloper up and right of the first crimp on the face looks good, but is practically useless; bumping your left hand up the rail is the better option.
location: Start low on the big holds immediately right of the tree, move up the rail until beneath the slopey crimp. Then move up directly to the slopey rail and top out.  Going out right into the groove puts you on the V2 variation.

description: Start in slopers at chest height and traverse right through more slopers to a somewhat dirty topout. Fun, just needs more traffic. Walk right to get off the boulder.
location: To the Right of Cross and Toss.

description: Fun little warmup on good slopey edges. Farthest right line on the backside of the Brown Cow boulder. Short but sweet.
location: Just to the left of the arete on the backside of the Brown Cow Boulder. Farthest right line.

description: On the first boulder at the Brown Cow Boulder. Traverse left from the farthest right sit start holds to the V2 (I) and top out as such. A good warm up.
location: Runs the length of the first boulder

description: Fun climbing on cool edge features to a high right hand gaston finger bucket and a fun topout. Starts on the ledge features which is used as a heelhook on Brown Cow.
location: Start directly left of Brown Cow.

description: Start in good edges with a big ass right foot down low. Climb left and then up. Heed the name. Do a righthand cross move to a good slot, and then jump out left to a comfortable slopey jug. Big jugs all the way to the top! instant classic. Thanks to Phillip and the ICA for cleaning off all of these old classics!!!
location: The line directly right of Helios.

description: To the Right of "V2 (I)." Starts on a Jug and climbs up and right through crimpy flakes and sidepulls, and eventually a righthand seam. Tops out using a juggy "spearhead" looking hold.
location: To the left of the obvious jug crack on the first boulder in the Brown Cow Area.
protection: pads and spotters... Be careful of the flexing edges down low. Dont step on them too much!

description: Community Service stars on a left hand pinch and a slopey crimp for the right. Work your way up the boulder using slopers and pinches.
location: This problem is located on the right side of the same boulder as The Fisherman.

description: Fun but contrived. Climbs the obvious brown streak of wall with black speckles. Start on your choice of low start holds (a left hand edge, and a right hand crimp or right hand slopy pinch) with a massive left heel hook. The heel hook ledge is "off" for a hand. Figure out some beta and work your way up powerful sidepull pockets and features to some sharp jugs and a thoughtful topout. Holies V6.
location: The obvious brown speckled streak of wall with lots of chalk.

description: Sit Start on obvious crimper plate/flake feature. Do a big lockoff up and right to some good slopers, fun and casual topout. Wish it were longer!!
location: Second rightmost climb on the backside of the Brown Cow Boulder. Starts low on obvious crimp plate feature.

description: A short, ugly boulder problem (similar to the first ascentionist), which consists of two moves. Starting on a jug with a right heel hook reach to a bad sloping edge and then do either a big bump to a jug up and right or match, then do the big bump.
location: The farthest left line on the first boulder in the Brown Cow Area. Starts right of a tree, on a good jug very low to the ground.

description: Climb up the large water groove, using slopers and pockets. Crux is near the top.
location: Twin Eagles is to the right and around the corner from Brown Recluse.
protection: Pads + Spotter. You'll probably want to get on a rope and clean off all the holds as well, due to the problem not getting much traffic.

description: This thing is absolutely crazy! You begin under a short roof, get set up on a couple crimps and do a huge dyno to a sloper. Then work up using the slopers, a mono, and a heel-toe cam. The second crux is throwing to the lip. After this you top out on about 10 feet of slab, 20 feet off the ground.
location: Cripps is located up the hill from Brown Recluse on the cliff line.

description: From a sit-start just left of the middle of the face on a right hand sloper hueco, and a left hand juggy hueco, climb left and then upwards on cool sloping jugs. Move out right for first crux move before finally heading straight up and left on fingery holds to the scary and difficult topout.
protection: Many pads, as the landing isn't perfect and a fall near the top of this big boulder is possible!

description: Start low on a thin rail and a right undercling, bust through the opening move and continue up the face to the easier top-out.
location: First problem on the far right of the Bubble Wrap boulder. This will be the initial problem you encounter coming down the trail.

description: Start on One Bourbon and move right across the face. The crux comes at the One Scotch starting holds. Finish as for One Beer.

first_ascent: Unknown, cleaned up and named by Jesse Sell in 2017
description: Fun body positioning with a throw to the top and a classic Holies mantle to finish.
location: Start around the corner from Half-Wheel, just right of the tree. Sit start on slopers with left foot on nub. Move up and left, with a good throw just left of the tree. Mantle or top out at Half-Wheel.

description: Weight of the World
A lowball traverse problem on perfect stone. From a sit-start on the lowest left side of the boulder, follow the lip of the bloc from left to right. When the holds end, mantle it out.
location: It is the small, UFO-like piece of stone jutting out of the ground that you will see when approaching the 911 Aretes from the back of the Shadow of a Man boulder.

description: Another fun arete climb! Ascend the small boulder using the arete on the left side. Make sure to not mantle it out too early.
location: On the trail near the cliffline, walk a bit further than you would for Your Body is a Wonderland and the 911 Arete boulder. There will be a small boulder facing the trail.

description: V0 sit start.
location: Right of Far Nearer. Sit start of the right arete.

description: A surprisingly fun one-mover. Sit-start low on the very obvious smiley crimp and get to the jugs at the lip.
location: On the trail near the cliffline, walk a bit further than you would for Your Body is a Wonderland and the 911 Arete boulder. There will be a small boulder facing the trail. Climb the trail-side face.

description: Climb the sloping arete on the leftside of the boulder. Sustained climbing to a relatively easy topout. Climbs harder than it looks.
location: When facing Your Body is a Wonderland, this obvious boulder will be to your right. Start low on the left arete and follow this to the apex.

description: overhanging face nearest to the trail with fun topout
location: to the right of V1 arete problem

description: climb arete nearest to the path on Atlas
Starts as a sit start and works right.
location: On Atlas boulder to the left of Calypso.

description: Start low on the big ledge and move up the overhanging arete through good slopers and pinches. Top out over the corner where the arete meets the top slab.
location: On the boulder opposing the face of Atlas.
protection: 2-3 pads to protect the rock below the entire problem.

description: Sit start and slap your way up. Top out seems like the crux.
location: The trail side of Atlas Boulder

description: start with good, chest height hands. work straight up sidepulls. big jug on left is optional, but not necessary.  small detached boulder on ground is off.
location: cliff side of boulder. first problem you see when walking the trail.

description: to the right of Calypso
Starts on positive holds, go up using compression moves to a cruxy top out.
location: Directly to the right of Davey Crockett.

description: A sweet compression problem with a knee bar and a crux top out.
location: The problem to the left of Davey Crokett.

description: A low ball that's pretty much just a topout.
location: To the right of Windfall.

description: Start matched on a jug about chest height, climb up the center of the boulder. Sharp pockets at the end, with s slopey topout.
location: The center line of the Alamo boulder. Goes up the tallest part of the boulder.

description: Grab holds at head height in the middle of the face and make a move to the top of the boulder.
Sit start on the left hand side of the boulder. Move up to a good sloping ledge and through sloper pockets to the top out.
Start on a good hold at chest height on the left side of the boulder. Move up and left to a large jug and make one more move to the top.

location: On the Bar Stool boulder. Start with the good side-pull of One Beer left hand and right hand around the corner, then head straight up. Toping out is easier if you traverse left a couple feet first on the lip.
protection: Good landing, crash pad should suffice.

description: 5.8 climbing that is separated by a crux off of two somewhat thin crimps through a slight bulge (this can be dynoed through though if you wish for a more fun variation)
location: The left side of the cliff, maybe four minutes down the trail.

protection: P1:  Trad medium cams and stoppers.  P2: 1 large cam and 3 QD  Has 2-bolt anchor

description: Take a right when main trail runs into wall,about 75 feet up small hill right before left facing dihedral.
protection: 4 bolts, anchor little runout on easy climbing after 3rd bolt

description: Climb the prominent arete, which is sandy and tricky, up to a sandy ledge below a roof.  Do some big moves to gain jugs at the lip and make the clip.  A difficult boulder problem on tiny crimps and pockets gets you to the anchors.
location: The obvious arete right of Phillip's Overhang.
protection: Five bolts to a bolted anchor.  Be sure to use a long draw on the fifth bolt, which is just over the lip.  Falling at the crux with a short draw will shred your rope.

description: After a few bolts of surprisingly tricky climbing on big holds, head right out the overhang and up into the large water groove.
protection: Five bolts to a two bolt anchor with rap rings.

description: Information on this route was from Jim, who has not climbed the route in a long time.  It follows a short roof crack on the prominent arete of Moon Rock.
protection: There is at least one bolt on the route, which should be considered suspect.  There is also some natural pro.  Not sure about anchors.

description: This line is deceptively slopey and difficult.  The crux in the middle of the route is very cool but hard to read.  Pumpy.
location: This is the right-most route on Moon rock.
protection: Five bolts to bolted anchors with rap rings.  Be sure to clip the low bolt on the ledge, which makes the falls a little cleaner. Clipping the second isn't too hard, but a fall would be bad.  A stick clip is recommended.

description: The easier variation of Ralphie's Ruse. Fun pocket pulling ties your back into the main route.
location: 3ish feet right of Ralphie's Ruse
This is the left of the newly bolted lines on Moon Rock.  It begins about 15 feet right of the prominent arete.
protection: Five bolts to a two bolt anchor with rap rings

description: Follows the arete right of the roof crack.  Any additional info on the route would be appreciated.

location: Just right of Dust Doctors.
protection: mainly bolts.  But you will need some stoppers and small to mid cams for the 1st pitch.  The 2nd pitch is bolted however, you can place a green alien in a pod b/t clips 3 and 4.

description: Fingery route down low with a triangular roof (that one can cop a nice sit down rest on) halfway up.  Difficulties ease once you surmount the roof.
location: 30 feet to the left of Geppetto, around the corner

description: Start as C-Crack, the at the traverse rip up the overhanging hand crack.
location: just as C-crack, but to come down you must downclimb the dead tree to the right to get to the lower anchors. Yikes!
protection: Small to Medium cams and nuts

description: Go up the easy crack system until you hit a roof.  Either continue up the roof for the direct variation, or as I recomend, head right on the horizontal, near footless, hand crack traverse.  Finish on the antkiller belay ledge.
location: Just around the bulge to the left of Ant Killer.
protection: small to medium cams and nuts.
Trad:  Small to mid-sized cams and some stoppers

description: Fantastic 5.9 Dihedral Crack.  P2 not as classic.
protection: Trad: Stoppers will do you fine and a few small to medium cams.

description: Sit start on right hand crimp rail and left hand sloper. Climb up and right using various slopers and crimps and make a committing move to a final jug. Watch out for dabs on this lowball!
location: On the north facing side of the boulder.

description: It starts at the base of the tree and ends where the trunk splits into shoots. Yes, it is a tree. Be careful because while most of the bark is secure, footholds especially may break. The bark is rough so take care of your skin. And be careful, it is near the sidewalk, but in all the times I fell on it I never had a crash pad and never fell on the concrete.
location: It is located in the northwest corner of Lauth park in Skokie, Illinois.

description: Start on a left hand crimp and a right hand sloper with a heel down and to the left. right hand throw to a slopey crimp rock up on your left heel and throw left hand to a small sloper rail. Then right hand bump to a sharp crimp. stand on your left foot and move your left hand to the final sloper. Easy top out.

Sit start with hands on the bottom two blue marks and feet on the green marks. Press up to grab the small crack circled blue. Your feet can only touch the two original footholds and the two starting handholds. Dyno to the top, directly in the middle, grabbing hold of a small slab that sits about 8 inches in from the edge. Do not grab the edge of the top rock! After grabbing, your feet can go anywhere to top out.
location: South face of the large boulder

description: Heel hook around the boulder then rock up on your heel to top out. Hands start on SW face of the boulder. Do NOT use any section of the boulder below the hand start.

location: Follow the area page directions to the wall. This will be in the middle of the wall.
protection: pad(s) or the trash cushion underneath the route

description: Sit start at the obvious left crimp and right sidepull crimp as seen on the photo's. Follow the line directly up and through the face. Throw a high right heel to make your way up, but no standing on that same right ledge to help you top out. You gotta climb that slab!

This is the large arching crack on the left side of the main amphitheater wall.  Large to medium sized gear will protect most of the route.  You can lower off of the sport route that meets the crack to avoid the somewhat chossy finish.  To get your money's worth, you can lower off of the anchors for Inception.

Begin low and left in the amphitheater, work up and right through the first two bolts. Above the third bolt is the first bolt of legacy. From here follow the bolts through a series of side pulls, slopers, and edges to reach the final section. A technical slab wait for you at the top. Get psyched!
location: Begins in the left corner of the Amphitheater and work the route that goes up the middle. Refer to photo

protection: nine bolts to a two bolt anchor with rap rings.  Due to how far the route traverses, the bottom four or five bolts are best cleaned on top rope to prevent a dangerous swing.
Some gear and several bolts.  Rap from Tree.

location: Left most route leaving the shared first bolt on the left side of the main wall.
protection: Seven bolts to bolted anchors with rap rings.

location: Rightmost of the routes sharing the common start.
protection: Eleven bolts to a 2 bolt anchor with rap rings.

description: Start the same as The Dark Side but then go to the left while staying on the good foot. Make some crossing slaps then pull yourself around the bulge. Climb the slab to top out.
location: Same as Dark Side

description: Start on a tiny right hand crimp and a sharp and small crystal for the left. Put your foot in any of the pockets below. Establish off of the ground then fire to the lip.
location: Left of Meditation

description: Start on the sloping ledge with your body as low as possible. Use the pocket feet and throw to the top sloper, then work your way to the top out. The holds the the left are off, and the sign is off. Only use the sloping ledge, the top, and the pocket feet.

Hands start on the West face, toe hook the ledge on the East face. Work your way underneath the arch to the East side of the boulder. Do NOT use any section of the boulder below the circled areas in the photos.
Start on the opposite side of Ring Around the Toesies and top out at the start of Ring Around the Toesies.
West face of "Big boulder." Sit start, climb pockets only, all other holds are barred!
Dyno to the top from the start holds
use only the left arete/crack and right crack (blue line crack) to compress and hug your way up this boulder! feet - whatever you can use!
Follow the obvious line to the top

This is a "Figure 8" traverse. Start off matching both hands on the north west point of the rock at the blue mark with feet on the green marks. Traverse right using the crack at the red line mark and various holds below it. Do not use a hold above the red line. Work your way under the middle cave and out to the south east face of the rock, avoiding any hold above the red line. Work around the south face and traverse left along the south west face to the cave again, following the same guidelines. Route is complete when hands and feet make it to the north starting point.
protection: Traverse stays low. No additional protection needed.

description: Pockets only

5.9 climbing to crux move at the roof when traversing right to the anchors on Middle Face. Very exposed move, and has potential for pendulum swing into opposite wall. Not sure if anyone has climbed this route before. When traversing I knocked off a large rock that almost hit my belayer.
location: The crack between Middle Face and Left Face. Lower on bolts on Middle Face.
protection: Set of Cams #.5 - 3, set of nuts. Save #3 for the traverse.

description: This is an enjoyable climb that ascends the right side of the dugout.  It is comparable in difficulty to the Middle Face.  However, the anchors are inexplicably located about ten feet past the logical end of the route, requiring the use of a rusty upward driven bolt to aid to the anchors.  The sandy boulder problem this bolt protects is probably possible (grade is an estimate), but not nearly as quality as the rest of the route.  A lower set of anchors would decrease the grade to about 11D and increase the overall quality.
location: Rightmost route in the dugout
protection: Five bolts to a 2 bolt anchor with quick links.

description: Use the words on the school sign to get to the top.
location: Bateman Elementary School Sign

description: See picture for what's on. For the starred holds, try to avoid using the tops. Crux is at the end. Can also be done in reverse.

Work your way out through the entrance of the cave, mantle and finish on top of the rock. There are at least three jugs, and a majority of the route is a large rail. Any and all rock inside the cave is on. Don't use the rail marked in the main page's photo, it's chossy and let's not break it. There is a pretty solid heel hook near the end of the route, kind of fun.
location: Enter the cave through the wider opening, the start of the route is immediately to the left on the pillar.
Once you enter the cave, there are two small holes/paths towards the back. The route starts on the right of the hole that is on the left.

description: See picture for what's on. Do whatever to get to the start.
See picture for what's on. Along the bottom of the wall, the concavity and the rail just below it (a few mm wide) are also on for different beta.
See picture for what's on. Small hands match more easily.
See picture for what's on. Along the bottom of the wall, the concavity and the rail just below it (a few mm wide) are also on. Crux is the start.
See picture for what's on. End is anticlimactic.
Several bolts of pumpy pocket climbing leads to a mediocre rest.  The crux is moving past the final bolt to the anchors and is difficult to read.
location: Starts about ten feet right of the large dihedral.
protection: Four bolts and a two bolt anchor with quick links.

description: Climb the tricky water runnel up to a roof.  Do some creative stemming to pull the roof and reach the anchors.
location: Just left of the prominent dihedral.
protection: Four bolts to a two bolt anchor with quick links.

description: Top out on the piller then there‚Äôs and easy down climb to the top of the wall then down climb the wall.

location: On the west side of Carlson Tower balcony, along Kedzie. Look for the small pockets right off of East the side of the street. Just North of the river.

description: The middle has some sharp crimpy holds. Some of the holds nearby are loose so double check what you are grabbing.
location: Under the fallen tree

description: Start on the right side of the boulder, without using the lip traverse left around the arete and top out on the overhanging far side
location: The shorter of the two climbable boulders
protection: No pads, you'll never be more than 5 feet off the ground.

description: Crouch start on the two deep crimps with a right flag. The first move is the crux: left hand to another deep crimp above. Then, right foot step right arm up, and catch the top with your left hand.
location: Near the California Blue Line stop, in the courtyard between the apartment highrise and Colectivo Coffee. There are two climbable boulders; this is on the West side of the taller of the two.

description: Sit start with the first move as the crux. Make an awkward throw to a ledge and work your way up from there.
reference pictures for route. A fall could be bad since the ground is slanted and goes into the water. The wall takes over a week to dry after a rain and even then its still fairly wet.
location: Middle section of the wall that is to the left of the waterfall

description: Work your way up about two moves before mantling on the flat part of the boulder
location: The shallow dihedral right under the flat part of the tall boulder

description: Sit start on the vertical arete of the tall boulder and make literally one move before mantling
The pictures show where the hands are. The feet are open, but that being said the rock is so crumbly that solid foot holds are spread out a little bit.
location: Refer to the pictures for the start and end of the route.

protection: ! pad or 2, depending on how high you get.

description: An old chimney on the side of a school, built out of stone rough enough to climb.
location: Pull into the school lot, you'll see the route. The only way down is to downclimb.

Landmarks are your friend here. ¬†Honestly, finding this thing was half the fun, so enjoy the hike. ¬†This is located between the two points of the Wolfden loop trail. Around 1.5 miles in, just after passing beneath a large overhanging Chossy wall, focus on the cliffline. ¬†Look¬†for a natural arch key hole at the top of a boulder, followed by a very clean, recessed area of vertical wall. Just past this, keep looking at the base of the cliff for a small cave opening directly behind a large Ash tree. ¬†If you see a large, egg shaped boulder then you have just passed it! ¬†Turn around and look closer. ¬†The cave drops down below eye level looking from the trail, so keep your eyes peeled!
protection: 2-3 pads or you could genuinely just have an active spotter. ¬† Anti-spider spells are key here

description: Not quite as high as the West Side Bridges but more technical.
protection: 1 pad for up to 12 brick layers. Anything higher double stack pads.

description: This is a seldom done trad line at Draper's, but it is fantastic.  The crux short 15'..but burly.  The top is a little scary and one move is protected by a manky rusted piton.
location: Right of Shame.  Look for a left facing dihedral with a roof.  Often wet ground at the base.  The route still has the remains of a large honey bee hive.

description: The Crux is between 2nd - 3rd bolt and another b/t 4 and 5.  The route is very sustained so pace yourself.  The second pitch is a bit scary getting to the first bolt.  You will hit a ledge if you blow the move.
location: Look for eye bolts right of Sidewinder, the popular 3 bolt 5.6.
protection: Bring a small cam to supplement b/t the 1st and 2nd bolt on the 1st pitch and small - mid cams to protect from the ledge to the first bolt on the second.  Some like a mid sized cam to protect the final moves...but it is much easier climbing high on the pitch.

description: This climbs the V chimney/dihedral to a roof.  The roof is a hand/fist crack that is set deep in a flared chimney of sorts; but, the jams are solid.  Pull through on jams into an easy 5.7ish chimney that leads to a two bolt chain anchor.
location: Farthest side of Draper's near the fence.
protection: Stoppers and a single rack to 3".  Some might like an extra 3" and a 3.5" for the top.

description: This climbs the left of the twin cracks under a roof with a perfect handsized slot.  Pull the roof using the slot and pull into a left facing dihedral.  At the top traverse right and take the path of least resistance.  Use caution on the traverse (5.9) as a fall here could get ugly quick.  This is probably why it is named Genuine Risk.  The 11 crux is very well protected by mid-sized cams
location: past the 3rd class gully found past The Bloody Nose.  This is on State Land and climbing is not legal here.
protection: Doubles in the 0.5 - 1 BD single #2 BD and one #3 BD some small stoppers.

location: Left of the dental bill and right of the the Blue Roof.
protection: 14 draws and two cams (#1, #2, or #3 BD) if you do it as one pitch.  Otherwise the 1st pitch is 7 QD + anchor.

description: Sustained first pitch followed by a spectacular traverse into an alcove up through a roof.
protection: Standard free rack w/ small to medium cams.

description: You can choose to boulder to the top or top rope.
location: Once at the top you can walk down a steep hill, or repel.
protection: Pads, anchors are at the top but they look pretty old and rusty.
1 pad, double stack pads if your passing the arc.
1 pad will do if your climbing to the arc. If your going past the arc you will need to double stack your mats.

description: Begin on the undercling and have fun figuring out how to top out!
location: Locate the undercling near the Arete

description: Start a low as you can with your left hand on the arete and your right hand on a undercling
location: To the left of classic face
locate the overhangs

description: This problem is on the front left corner of the boulder if you are facing the creek, sit start off a sloper to a small crimp, then move the left hand to another crimp then the right hand to the top, short problem, but fun to work out.
location: Read the previous description

description: Climb the face while following the bolt line.
location: First bolted route to the right of April Fool

description: Short, fun and slightly fingery route near the end of the bluff
location: Third sport route from the far right side of Cedar Bluff

description: Climb the chimney crack to the left of Schoolyard Blues
location: Chimney crack to the left of Schoolyard Blues

description: Fun face climb with a wild roof!

Ascend the right leaning seam that goes up a slab and continue with it as it becomes vertical, followed by going through a small open book gully. Continue until you reach a small ledge before you reach the top.
location: Starts 10ish feet to the right of Big Sting
protection: Trad gear of varied sizes + bolted anchor

description: Follow the bolts to reach the anchor
location: First route to the right of St. Louis Graffiti

description: Route on bulge just left of Dos Equis.  A bouldery start leads to relaxed climbing with not exactly ideal gear placements; get creative with mid size cams and nuts.  Joins with Dos Equis last two bolts to the anchors.
protection: Doubles of Small to mid size cams and nuts. 2 QD plus anchors

location: About 50 feet right of Hypothermia. The route ascends the gully.

description: Ascend the slab/face next to a tree 12ish feet left of the actual bolt line. Traverse into the route and make careful moves until you traverse under an overhung arete. Ascend the upper arete and eventually reach the anchor.
location: The sport route to the right of Those Bear Memorial
Begins at the base of the gully to the right of Jack In The Green
protection: Set of cams and nuts + 1 QD

description: Climb the large rounded arete with a psychological crux at 2/3 height
location: around the corner from the fully bolted "Schoolyard Blues" (about 70 feet)
protection: 3 quickdraws plus some medium sized gear

description: Head right look for the two X-like features in the rock about 15 feet up. A waist-high roof is underneath. Goes straight up.

first_ascent: John Payne, according to Vertical Heartland guidebook
description: Enjoyable slab route. Starts with a crack in the middle. When that ends, you work your way left a tiny bit to a crack on that side.
location: A short ways to the east of "St Louis Graffiti." A short ways west of the 2nd class walk-up.
