description: Climb the crack system "gully" protecting when necessary and eventually top the bluff out.
location: the crack just right of Ghosts and Goblins
protection: Trad gear of varied sizes + bolted anchor

first_ascent: Jeff Scheff, John Payne, Brian Vana 1985
location: 30ish feet to the right of Ghosts and Goblins
protection: Trad gear of varied sizes + bolted anchor

first_ascent: John Payne Greg Simons, Frank Borzager
description: Climb the leftward angling dihedral feature
location: The dihedral feature to the left of Oily Easter Beaver
protection: Trad gear of varied sizes to the anchor

description: In the middle of the wall you will see a V-shaped notch beneath an overhang resting on a smooth undercut bed of rock. this is the Persian Wall. Climb, if you can, straight up the wall, through the notch, and over the overhang at it's widest part 45' to the top.
location: Read the directions already listed

description: Slabby start, to good pockets towards the top of the boulder. Find feet and stand up reaching for pockets and top out.
location: Free standing boulder across from Gill Traverse. This problem runs up the middle of the boulder facing the creek.

description: Climb up the boulder to a great pinch
location: To the right of Pocket Slab

description: Climb the different options
location: To the right of the V3 Arete

description: great warm up one hard gastone move
location: By the frist pinic area foot bridge

description: starts under small roof with right hand on big sloper, left on edge under roof. move up, over roof, and towards arete/top
location: from trail leading from parking lot, first group of boulders on left. located on left side of main part of matrix boulder

description: start standing on awkward chest-height holds. throw for top.
location: to the right of storm and rain. obvious line up center of matrix boulder

description: Begin from the belay ledge, and go straight up. Move through the center of a gully and clip the bolt near the ledge. A long, easy slab tops it out.
location: Begin at the belay ledge

description: Begin on High Flying Bird and pull over the first bulge. From here work up and right, skipping the open book feature of H.F.B. and a word towards a bolt in a "honey comb" featured spot. Clip this bolt and pull the last strenuous bulge to reach the anchor.
location: Start on High Flying Bird and after pulling the first budge, climb up and right.
protection: Mixed gear with 3 bolts to an anchor

description: Start matched low on the right side of the arete, throw around and out left to the bumpy rail, out high right to crimp seam and match, then shoot for the flat jug at the top, mantel.
location: Head up the trail from the church and hang right at the bluff line, they are about 20 ft before you hit the cave, in an overhang.

description: 1st problem on overhung face. Jugs to start, left hand to fat slopey pinch, and top out the bulge.
location: This boulder defines the right side of a dihedral which starts about 30 paces west of the bouldering cave. There are 2 cool v4ish problems on the side which is (at first) hidden from view.

description: Sart on same jugs as the v4. Go left & reach around to the other face to match on sloping but positive edge. Top out Left.
location: This boulder defines the right side of a dihedral which starts about 30 paces west of the bouldering cave. There are 2 cool v4ish problems on the side which is (at first) hidden from view.

description: From a sit at the starting edge, move through slopers, pinches, and an undercling to reach a pair of incut edges above. From there, move out left to a similar, smaller, pair of edges. Figure out the moves straight up to the big mouth-shaped ledge above, then top out through easier roof climbing above.
location: To the right of the compression problem. Start sitting on the obvious edge low with an incut LH and flat RH. Moves through an obvious undercling and two incut edges above to thin crimps out left, eventually hitting the giant ledge above them.

description: Name totally made up (certainly not a FA but not in the guidebook, though I thought it worthy of description). Grade is a tired 4th-day-on estimate, so probably soft. From good ledges at the back of the cave, move straight out the cave to a close pair of positive ledges. From here, go to a slopey 2 finger LH pocket/pinch, then make a big RH move to a solid 4-finger pocketed ledge, probably cutting feet. Make another big move with the LH to a similarly positive pocket and begin the romp to the top on giant incut pockets.
location: LH side of cave, probably the first chalked line on the left. The left hand pocket should be obvious (there's a little 1 finger divot just left of it).

description: Name totally made up (certainly not a FA but not in the guidebook, though I thought it worthy of description). Grade is a tired 4th-day-on estimate, so probably soft. From ledge at back of cave, slap to pinch on lip of the low roof tier. Use foot trickery of choice to bring LH to flat sidepull. Slap RH to another pinch, then move up on good ledges.
location: Right of the pocket problem in the shallow cave. Comes out of the low roof near the dihedral where the shallow cave meets the tall cave, then moves out and left to top out by whichever way is easiest.

description: Sidepulls galore. Beta I attempted: start sitting on sidepull edges/pinches, throwing high to more sidepull edges (good LH, semi-slopey RH) before moving to better holds above. Name totally made up (not in the guidebook, though I thought it worthy of description).
location: Just right of the dihedral on the left end of the tall cave portion. Middle sidepulls at face level should be obvious. Start sitting with opposing sidepulls (there's another sidpull left of the LH start hold).

description: This is a nice little cave with the roof ranging in height from 4-12 feet.  Always stays dry and there are a handful of eliminates/problems possible - enough for a session or two.
location: Walk to the far right hand side of Cedar Bluff and this is what you will find.

description: SDS just right of unnamed v3. Pinch, move to sidepull in big hueco and top out left in slopers or right in small, left-facing pockets.
location: This boulder defines the right side of a dihedral which starts about 30 paces west of the bouldering cave. There are 2 cool v4ish problems on the side which is (at first) hidden from view.

description: Start on the two jugs next to "The Son" start, throw up to the pinch then to the jug on the lip, hit the high sloper and reach for the slopy rail with the seam in it, fire for the side pull Jug and finish the mantel.
location: Head up the trail from the church and hang right at the bluff line, they are about 20 ft before you hit the cave, in an overhang.

description: Facing "the son" directly to your left against the corner are the under cling starting holds. hit the huge block jug and up and right to the pad and a half flake, big stretch right again to a good hold then mantle the son.
location: Head up the trail from the church and hang right at the bluff line, they are about 20 ft before you hit the cave, in an overhang.

first_ascent: (5.8/A.4)Steve Nelson/Adam Ggrowsky/Mike Azrin mid 70s.1st Free Lead Sean Sucras,Clay Erickson(installed bolt on 2nd pitch) 1984
description: Pitch 1-5.8 Starts about 30 feet left of the big off width. Start in the left facing dihedral with a thin crack. Follow crack system up and to the right. Go around corner and rig a hanging belay here. Pitch 2-5.10a ascend the ramp dihedral to a safety bolt and top out above.
location: Follow cliff line left ward till you see the off-width. Past here about 30 feet. Easy walk off or rap from chains on the sport route to you right.
protection: Mixed gear of varied sizes. Cams for first pitch. Not a bad idea to have a couple tri cams forr belay. Sling the horn and 1 quick draw for pitch 2.

description: Its the sport route that climbs a thin seam
location: Begins 5 feet left of Fear of Flying

description: A nice first trad climb. good stances for placing gear and good gear.
location: obvious crack that runs up the middle of the face at the end of the trail. it's to the right of the Africa.
protection: small to medium cams and nuts. a good horn to sling around 2/3 the way up the route. there is an anchor the the left on the ledge at the top but NOT one directly above the climb.

description: Thin and strenuous, bouldery start. Fun
location: Moving left, it's the 1st sport route.  Look for the high 1st clip.  Stay right of the 2nd and 3rd clips.

description: Climb the face, clipping the two bolts as you move working into the crack. Work you way through the crack as it widens and becomes slightly overhung. Climb over the ledge and reach the bolted anchor.
location: This mixed route is the first one you come to as you approach from the church. Locate the route that has one climb the face and transition into a narrow, then widening crack.
protection: Two bolts and mid sized cams to the anchor.

description: big long offwidth crack, that gets bulgy and dirty near the top. some real nice sit down rests near the top. finishes out with some face climbing. took me a while to figure out offwidth moves, but it was fun figuring it out. might want to wear pants and tape ankles or wear high top shoes (i've lost some skin to this one). i've only top roped this route using several trees at the top for anchors.
location: on the left wall of the dihedral, to the left of "Cave City"
protection: I top roped it using long pieces of webbing to anchor to the trees at the top. to lead a person would need several large cams for the offwidth.

first_ascent: Jim Thurmond, Alan Carrier, Eric Ulner 1987
protection: natural small to medium gear with bolts.

description: A few starting moves will get you to a large ledge, where you can place gear in the crack. Edges and jugs through bolts. Clipping stances are usually pretty good. Finish straight to the final horns; the chains are on the wall above the finish.
location: Right of Africa, left of the large chimney/crack, start up on moderate edges and flakes.

description: Deep dihedral crack. fairly straightforward climbing. a fall while leading could be bad. several spots you'll have to squeeze through.
location: the dihedral crack to the right of Fear of Flying.
protection: i used the trees at the top of the cliff for a top rope anchor. you need two long (60') pieces of webbing. to lead you would need a varied rack.

description: A fun toprope.
location: a little to the left on the wall that is directly in front of the trail. Identified by the big plate that looks somewhat like Africa or South America (i could see both).
protection: bolt anchors at the top for toprope. could be lead but the trad lead rating i think is an R or X.

route_name: 2 Six-Packs, 1/5 of Scotch & A Full Moon
description: Begin with some high bouldering up a 5.5ish looking slab. Reach a 6ish foot protruding boulder with a flat top. Climb on top of that, Climb through 4 bolts to reach the top.
location: Sport route to the right of Cave City

description: This is hardly climbed so bring a brush to clean it up. Climb the short face.
location: Starts 2 feet right of Number 35

description: Begin by climbing up the short face, clipping two bolts as you go, and eventually reach the top
location: It starts on the ledge about 10ish feet right of the 4th class scramble
protection: 2 quick draws and top out the route

location: While looking up at the upper wall, look up at the lower left part of the wall and locate a grassy ledge. This serves as the fixed belay station.
Begin at the belay ledge

description: Climb the vertical crack on the left side of the steep overhang.
location: Starts 10 feet to the right of Short Stuff

description: The problem starts at the bottom right of the cave climbs to meet the other wall, then goes up to a slab top out filled with lots of moss and moisture.
location: Read previous description on how to get there

description: Start with some small crimps, small feet and a tiny sidepull/pocket thing and go up to bigger, better holds and an easy topout.
location: A short ways down the trail from Auld Lang Syne, there is a large boulder on your right near the creek. Walk around the backside of the boulder past a few easy problems, and This problem is on the right side of the face closest to the creek.
protection: Crash pads, there are a few rocks at the base

description: Begin in the crack,traverse to the right and then head up. Fun problem
location: around the alcove area that has the dihedral

description: Climb up and down the obvious Iron flakes. Top out is doable, but needs to be cleaned up.
location: Stand alone boulder near in the main boulder field, facing towards the pool. Its hard to miss.

description: Begin as low as you can. Pul through good holds to some large throws out right, pull the slopey top out.
location: Refer to photo

description: Many fun variations on this wall leading up to the top out of "Miller High Life"
location: Roadside wall, start low to the left of the "Miller".

description: Sit start low on the left corner and finish and top out on Roadside Wall
location: Starts on the left corner of the roadside wall just to the right of the tree.

description: Harder then the problem to the left, great slopey top out
location: A few feet to the right of Sit Start V1

description: Sit start and pull through good holds to a slopey topout
location: Leftmost boulder problem

description: Start right around the ar√™te when coming into the cave, then climbing directly up, using pockets and slopey edges.
location: Located around the ar√™te when walking in around the ar√™te.

description: Climb through the vaguely featured face to nice holds on top. Classic V3
location: The classic line that goes up the rather blank face.

description: Climb up the face to the left of King of Smears.
location: Directly to the left of King of Smears.
protection: Pads and spotters. You may have to build up a landing as well.

description: Start on decent edges, climb up and out through a slopey top out
location: A few feet left of Rebuttal

description: According to Sandstone Warrior, "rumored to be John Gill's hardest problem".
location: Gill area

description: Begin in cave feature. pull hard and reach to a lip, top out from there.
location: Left of dwarf, refer to map.
Start right on the ‚ÄúMiller‚Äù painting

description: Sit start from a jug and move up and right. Push hard through a mantle and finish. Short and sweet.
location: Gill area

description: Start low on an pocket you can undercling. Pull the difficult mantel
location: Share the same start as Road Worthy

description: Start on low slopers and traverse right towards Dream Weaver. Driftwood has the same topout as Dream Weaver.
location: Start on low slopers to the left of the cave where Dream Weaver starts.

description: This is a very strange/unique problem. Dream Weaver starts inside the cave, with left hand on a positive crimp undercling under the bulge, right on on a small edge side pull. Start the problem off with a tough first move, then find some way to work your way out the cave.
location: Located inside the cave on the bulge.

description: The top out of Dream Weaver/Driftwood. Start on good holds and top out.
location: Starts on good holds at the edge of the cave.

description: Start on horizontal slopey crimps, pull the first move to a good side pull. The first move is the crux, and the problem is pretty much done after that. Holds will probably be sandy, so be careful!
location: Wash Out starts to the right of Proud Mary.

description: Starting on the good start holds of Jimbo's, head right on good crimps and jugs. Hit a huge jug in the middle of the face and go straight up to two incut crimpers. From here, move your left hand once more into a good, slightly slopey jug, hike your feet up and do a hard move to the final hold. Ultra classic. One of the only problems in the v6 range in So iLL on jugs!
location: The big overhanging face of the Sex on the Beach boulder, the huge block you encounter when you arrive at the Beach. The obvious line of good holds. Walk down off the boulder to get off.
protection: Pads and spotters optional. I have fallen topping this out and completely missed the pad and fell into the sand and I didn't think it hurt at all.

description: This extremely overhung line follows incut crimpers to the top of the boulder. Starting on two small jugs, either explode up and right to a small but positive crimp or reach your left hand to a bad slopey edge and lock off to the incut crimp. From here, get your left foot very high, and get left hand to a small gaston far away, using the incut intermediate next to it or just going straight to it. Grab a couple good holds and do a simple top out. As far as I know, this is the second hardest problem at the Beach. A lower start on two bad crimps may be possible when the sand is low... So iLL strong men, get out there!
location: Right side of the overhung Sex on the Beach face. Walk off boulder to get off.

description: Proud Mary/Sex on the Beach link-up. Start on Mary, do some moves to gain the jug of Sex, finish on that. Found this on a local guy's 8a.nu page while I was looking around for obscure boulder problems...clever name...sounds fun man!
protection: Whatever you used for Sex on the Beach, plus a pad near Proud Mary

description: There are a lot of holds on the arete, so the beta can be hard to read. There are a couple variations on the problem, but I began the problem starting on two holds on opposite sides of the arete, doing a big move up and left. A couple more weird slopey moves will put you on top. Not the best problem at the Beach, but not bad either.
location: Faint arete to the left of Jimbo's

description: Starting standing on good holds, move upwards to a big cruxy huck to a nice sandstone sloper. Top out the boulder. The classic warm up of the Beach. Awesome, overhanging sandstone action.
location: Facing the main overhanging face of the Sex on the Beach boulder, it is just right of the slight arete on the left side of the face.
protection: A pad or two, if you want

description: Start on high edges and pull a difficult move to shelf above.
location: Starts on the opposite side of Sex on the Beach problem.

description: Sketchy traverse by the creek. After some cleaning, it'll be way better. Lots of ledges and some big pockets. Bring multiple pads.
location: Start above the slopey, bad side pull on the left. It moves up and to the right all the way to where the dirt trail meets the cliff.
protection: At least one crash pad, preferably more.

location: South side of Eigenmann hall, located on the east side of IU's campus.

description: There are some semi-highball easy warm up boulders with many variations in this spot.  There are also some anchors located on the top of this climbs if you want to set up a top rope
location: To the left of the bolted routes. This is first area where the cliff is low enough for bouldering.
protection: Pad if you want, or set up a top rope on the anchors located on the top of the cliff

description: Two hand pinch sit start with a high right toe hook for tension, fallow the deep crack moving left¬†all the way to the top with good feet once your past the start move.
location: West side of the rock,¬†best climbed in the morning.

description: Arete on the River. Seasonal, because the landing and beginning may be under water. Very cool problem when dry.
location: Northwest Arete of Zeppelin Boulder

description: Traverse west face of the boulder North. Step off.
location: West face of Zeppelin Boulder

description: Small fat unattractive looking boulder.  Start on the right side of the boulder traverse left onto small chossy looking holds and work your way to the top. Easily the worst problem in the area.
location: Right of the Warm Up Area

route_name: Thinking is the Best Way to Travel
description: Juggy bottom, at the top there is nice compression and stemming moves on tubes.
location: Fourth from the left end.

description: Start in the seam and move straight up.

Start with your left hand in the dynamite rail and your right on a small crimp at about chest height, from there move up to a good right hand crimp.  Be VERY CAREFUL when topping out, the rock about is very chossy.  It's best to traverse to the right after gaining the initial lip on this problem.
Start low somewhere in the plethora of pockets and find the pockets that work for you to gain the top. Around the Corner from Meaty Beaty Big and Bouncy
protection: Pad and a Spotter the landing is a little awkward

description: This is a boulder with a good amount of holds it is great to warm up. One would call this the variation station..
location: Approach from Hoosier daddy: go left for a while directly before Golden Shower (V2+).
Follow the crag all the way to the end, this is the last big face and overlooks the highway. This is the middle route of the three bolted routes on this face.

description: Start low on the jug rail, traverse right for a few moves before going up to a couple of small crimps then make a desperate throw for the good horn jug.
location: 30 feet to the left of Ball Buster

description: Start matched on the good left facing side pull.  Move up on underclings and small crimps with bad feet. This problem stays left of the faint dynamite rail on the wall. A V4 variation has the same start then moves to the right side of the dynamite rail.

Climb up to the choss to the overhanging section, use the amazing jugs and side pulls to do whatever variation you want. This boulder offers many opportunities to put up very hard problems. This one route deserves multiple pads, a spotter, and is a definite no fall problem.
location: One of the tallest boulders in the area, about 20 feet left of The Dirty Bird.
protection: Atleast 3 pads, a spotter, and a will to go HIGH

description: Climb along the left side of the black colored highball boulder.
location: To the left of Pocket Pinball

description: This is a classic route at Unlikely, it has history and many strong people have crushed this fun problem. This has many variation starts, one being a very low start on a good jug, cranking up to some small crimps. Work your way up the wall using an amazing iron deposits.
location: Directly left of My hero the ZERO.
protection: One pad with a good spotter

description: Work up this technical arete to a big finish on a jug that is a huge hole.
location: Directly to the left of The Golden Shower

description: Start with your right hand around the arete and a left hand in the dynamite rail.  Work your way up rail to gain the lip.
location: To the left of the Warm Up Area

description: This is a rather beta intensive route with constant tracking. The arete is off for this problem. From the juggy undercling make your move to the two small crimps, choose wisely. From there make a slight angle left working your way up the wall then a strong finish.
location: This route is to the right of the highball problem.
protection: need one pad great landing area.

description: Slopey sidepulls and technical feet create a route that requires exacting beta.
location: Directly across from the crooked tree! The left of two bolt lines.
protection: 3 bolts, 2 bolt anchor over the lip with chains.

location: Follow the crag all the way to the end, this is the last big face and overlooks the highway. This is the last route (to the right) of the three bolted routes on this face.

description: This is the classic route of the area, the base was dug out by some strong climbers. This is a low starting route off some amazing pockets either use the chaosy feet below or a harder version heel hook around the lip and make some technical moves and cut feet. ENJOY
location: Left of Glory Hole
protection: two pads the landing is not flat so be cat like

description: Climb the "arete" on the northeast corner of the Kirkwood Observatory. Start matched on crimp rail indicated in red circle, finish with both hands matched on crimps indicated in green circle
location: Northeast corner of Kirkwood Observatory

description: The OG Union Street Center buildering problem. This traverse combines a gnarly sidepull match crux with a fun dynamic start. Not climable when wet, make sure that inhabitants aren't home
location: Route is located on the Hickory building of Union Street facing the courtyard. It is on the long building and located to the right of the second window from the tunnel. Look for the words "Phish" written in chalk
protection: Bouldering pad at most, this route was projected with no pro

description: Super fun problem. Start on a jug rail, dynamic move to the next rail. High foot, some compression and a reach to a decent pinch. From here match the pinch and get you feet up and you‚Äôre at the railing. Mantle over the railing and enjoy the view :) crux is reaching up for the pinch
location: The front face of Wells Quad Foodcourt. Beautiful and simple line!

description: The route starts with a match on the first section of limestone brick that has fallen out which creates a jug like hold with both feet smeared. Then traverse across the rest of the wall using the other sections that have fallen out. Once you have traversed all the way across the final section is the ascent to the top.
protection: No protection needed other than maybe a spotter on the final portion.

description: A surprisingly fun problem. Starts on the positive rail and ends with a big(ish) move to the top. Various beta depending on height. Taller climbers generally trend left, while shorter trend right. Do your best to avoid the arete.
location: East side of the Eigenmann wall adjacent to the power generators and across from the parking lot.
protection: A pad would be nice, not necessary. Flat landing.

description: there are 4 climbable limestone pillars that support the bridge over to Switchyard Park. Each one of these pillars likely have many good eliminates. The shorter 2 pillars are the perfect bouldering height, but the taller 2 are highballs. No problems have been established yet, but there will be some soon.
location: Drive to Switchyard park and park in the lot. Walk over the bridge, and then walk around the side of the bridge. The pillars will be obvious.
protection: If you are climbing on the lower two pillars, I would bring general bouldering gear. One or more crash pads and a spotter is recommended. If you are on the higher two, I would either bring three+ pads and a couple of friends, set up a rappel at night, or solo it. (Climb at your own risk! It is very likely that rappelling is illegal but I'm not one to tell you what you should and shouldn't do.)

description: Start on north arete of the west side pillar, traverse across and into a limestone bar the spans the gap between the two pillars under the bridge. Traverse across to the other pillar, finish on the north arete.
location: Located underneath the b-line bridge to Switchyard park.
protection: A few crash pads and a spotter.

location: Starts sitting below the Spider on a left triangular undercling and right crimp pinch, as for Ivy League.

description: Starts on two undercling side-pulls, then left hand to crimp and right hand throw to pinch. Finishes on jug further up the wall.
Sit start under roof, below the obvious arete. Crank roof and climb arete to top out.
location: Beneath obvious arete.

description: Squat start at the lip of the boulder, work¬†your hands and feet up and mantel to top it.
location: It‚Äôs on the opposite side of Thighmaster

description: Climb the southwest side of the head. Start by standing on the pedestal. Move hands around the top of the head until you find two good jugs, then mantle onto the head using the ear for feet. Top out on top of the head.
location: Look for two giant, stone heads on the south side of Pao Hall. They're hard to miss. Tweedledum is the east head.

description: Climb up the northeast side of the head. Start by standing on the pedestal, and move hands around on the stone until you find two pockets near the top of the head. Use the ear for feet. Top out on top of the head
location: Look for the two giant, stone heads on the south side of Pao Hall, they're hard to miss. Tweedledee is the western head.

description: Climb the west I-beam of the Slater Hill amphitheatre. Reach around the back portion and step up the front. In 20 foot increment, there are cross-sections stable enough to pull up onto and sit in. If you are confident, top out on the hanging structure up top, but not recommended.
location: Head to West support beam. All are sendable, west is most covert
protection: None. Falling is not an option here.

location: It‚Äôs on the opposite side of Thighmaster

description: Right side of roof with Hoosier Daddy. Sit start on positive hold and crank the roof to sloper pockets. Top out.
location: Right side of roof with Hoosier Daddy.

description: Don't know anybody who has sent this. Only heard it referred to as Project Choss. A few hard moves getting out from under the cave then easy top out.
location: Just left of Osiris, starts on underclings on underside of cave with feet on left heel of Osiris and goes straight up the right side of the corner.

description: Sit start using a big slopey block sidepull to the right and a big undercling to the left. You can opt to use a slopey crimp on top of the undercling if you want. Go up to a sharp crimp edge and work up out left using sharp crimps and pinches to a great jug in the middle of the wall. From the jug go up to a slopey lip and find the slopey jug. You should be able to find a top out from there. There is also potential for a lower sit start on another undercling that adds in one or two hard moves into the start of this problem.
location: Past The Contortionist and just before the Osiris roof. There's another boulder called Unknown to the left of Osiris and this is to the left of that problem.

description: Start low under left side of roof on undercling crimps. Climb out through hard moves using spike tooth-like hold. This is a lower start to "Commencement".
Butt start matched on heavily chalked jug, deep under the roof.  Climb out the roof and up the face using pockets, jugs, etc.
location: Walk a ways past the Hoosier Daddy area, passing under 2 large roofs.  Osiris is on a roof very low to the ground.  The right side of the roof has a chalked up jug near the back, and the pockets normally retain chalk through decent rains.  Left side of the roof is a different problem that moves left into the dihedral.

description: Reach as high as you can to start.  Harder in the beginning, easier topout.
location: This is the feature right before reaching the hoosier daddy/yertle roof.

description: Waist start. Crank left side of roof to topout.
location: Continue down Strawberry Fields until you come across a roof that is about 4 or five feet tall. Hoosier Daddy ascends the left side of this roof.

description: Skip the beginning of daddy by starting on left crimp and right lower shallow 2 finger pocket.  Make long move to slopey pockets, hold swing, continue to topout.
location: same as hoosier daddy

description: Start on two pockets on the roof, with an obvious heel out left. Pull up, go for the overhead jug with left hand, match, keep the heel and follow hands up the flake. Crawl feet over to the right, right hand bump out, switch heel to a toe, stand up and grab pocket with right hand. Finish both hands on jug rail.
location: Directly to the right of Osiris, starting on roof. Muddy topout, just finish on jug rail and jump down.

description: Start with one hand on each of two slopey crimps on either side of a head-height bulge. Fight through one or two desperate hard moves up and left into the dihedral and follow it to the lip and an easy mantle. Expect weirdness.
location: Locate the slopey start crimps on either side of a head-height bulge dotted with shallow pockets just right of an obvious dihedral about twenty feet left of Osiris.

description: On the left side of the first of two large roofs after the Hoosier Daddy feature, locate a slopey pinch for the left and three-finger sidepull crimp for the right. Pull on and climb straight out along the left arete of the roof through foot trickery and tensiony moves until a small two-finger pocket is gained with the right hand. Move left hand to an edge up and left on the vertical wall, with intermediates available (mostly blind). Move up and right to top out via the tall arete. Watch for sandy holds- water runs down this arete in the rain and deposits some dirt on the wall. This finish is tall, though it eases up after an insecure move to a pockety jug on the upper arete. Rapping over the line to brush it up and make a plan for the top is recommended.
location: The left arete of the first of two large, blank-ish roofs in the Roof Sector, beyond the roof with Hoosier Daddy. Starts from a low stand with a slopey left pinch and flat sidepull crimp for the right hand.
protection: Several pads. The crux is low, but the arete is insecure until midway and the holds are often sandy before a good brushing.

location: Sit start to The Contortionist, which starts just right of and climbs the nose of a small bulge and an obvious right-facing dihedral about 20 feet left of Osiris.
In the same roof as Hoosier daddy (uses the same start hold).
protection: 2 or more pads. Make sure you have good spotters for the top out and when you're standing up in the big lip.

location: Just left of Ivy league and just right of Wild Flower
One of the first problems on the wall in the grey dihedral.
Starts on a very good left jug in the roof and right juggy edge at the transition from roof to skirt at the bottom of the roof, left and below the opposing sidepulls start of Rogue Dentistry.

description: Jump Start to a decent hold, crimp out left and up. Jump Down.
location: Follow tangerine wall until you pass the Cult Boulder. This route is on the right side of an arete immediately past the Cult Boulder.
Left of the Chili Pepper, the next roof section. Scramble up the hill above the problem to the trail and walk off.
Starts sitting as for Red Hot Chili Pepper

description: One of the best boulder problems in Muscatatuck. Sit start on a decent undercling and make a move to a sloper. Slap to another sloper, throw a heel and make a hard move to a slopey edge. Continue to the top of the bulge to an obvious knob above the sloping rail. Jump Down.
location: A ways down tangerine wall, underneath an obvious bulge. Next to the Pink Boulder.

description: Many ways to do it, all of similiar difficulty.  Start by underclinging below a bulge then move right into dihedral.  Problem ends at obvious jug rail.  There is a pointed block right below it that you use.
location: Just left of hicks on skoal and before the spider.

description: Direct Start to the Spider. Sit Start on roof below the Spider on a pinch and undercling. Deadpoint to a small crimp, move to an undercling, pull a hard move to a positive sidepull at the lip of the roof. Campus to good edges and finish on the spider. V10 approximate difficulty, using The Red Hot Chili Pepper as a guideline. May be harder or easier. Tendency to seep during heavy rain. Rad sequence.
location: Begins under small roof below The Spider.

description: Stand start on big undercling jug, plaster feet and negotiate the 'incisor' hold to establish on the hold options above it. Then, make a long move to the pocket jug on Rogue Dentistry. To top, continue through the line of pockets straight up and right to the top of the cliff.
location: Left of the Chili Pepper, the next roof section. Just right of Rogue Dentistry, start in the obvious undercling jug.

description: Use sidepulls in the dihedral to layback.  I used these to get high right foot on the arete.  Easy ground after that.  End on jug rail.
location: Arete and dihedral directly in front of a tree, just right of paisley dragon.

description: Climb the windows on Forney Chemical Engineering building directly across from the steel Civil Engineering statue. Pull into the window frame, make a large move directly up to the next, and repeat. A bit sketch due to landing zone
location: Walk to the Civil Engineering statue. Turn towards the Chemical Engineering building and walk down the little aisle. Half the aisle is filled by a large vent at the end

description: Climb the red steel Civil Engineering statue between the buildings. Easy but fun warmup for fountain projects. Wobbly, be careful
Climb the south face of the east wing. Use the squares incur to the wall, go till they become shallow, and if you're ballsy, top out.
location: South face of east wing (Face towards ME building, wing points to MSEE)

description: Begin on the same start as Go Fish, and then traverse the lip left. Mantle and top out at the end of the lip to exit.
Climb the obvious arete by the river, mantle the lip and top out.
location: Obvious arete by the river.

description: Juggy Pockets.Decent Warmup.
location: Immediately to the right of the stone steps.

description: Follow the fun and easy flake to the top.  Jump down, climb down, or topout and walk through the parking lot.
location: The large flake just right of kundilini/religion.

description: Uncertain if existing - PM me if I am wrong. Links the start of "The Politician" into "The Racist". Starting holds for The Politician, climb up to the left sloping edge and make a far move left out to the series of side pulls that comprise The Racist. Finish and top out are the same as The Racist.
location: On the Heinousness Wall, linking The Racist and The Politician.

description: Crimp up the vertical face to a mono-crimp and crank to the top. Topout.
location: Just to the right of Kundilini

description: Uncertain - PM me if I am wrong.  Side pulls and good feet.
location: Right after Mark's lunge.

description: After initial moves to left handed slopey layback maneuver to more slopey right hand. Press and squeeze to good foot. Don't miss the gaston before the lip.
location: Just past the racist.  Last problem before wall becomes heavily featured.

description: Clean line up good crimps that are well spaced.  Lunge/dyno to the lip for a nice topout.  The high foot variation to not lunge is called static cling.
location: Just right of catcher in the Rye.
Towards the beginning of Heinousness Wall. Same start as Kundilini immediately to the right of the rock shelf.
Climbs just left of the arete feature on Kundilini from a sit start.
protection: Two+ pads. Landing is flat and grassy, but the problem is moderately tall.

description: Begin on positive hold, move up to sloper and then to the left side of arete to good crimp. Match and make big move to good slot. Continue to topout.
location: Begins just to the right of an obvious arete on heinousness wall.

description: Climb the politician but eliminate the gaston before the lip.

Two hand start using the undercling and the crimp to the left of the undercling near the bottom of the boulder. Nice move with the right hand to a slopey edge. Cam your heel into the bottom of the dihedral to make a move into the left crimp. Use your body tension, possibly with a toe hook, to land the pocket.  After the pocket it's smooth sailing. Move to a gross pinch for an easy top out sequence.
location: On the very end of Heinousness Wall on the overhanging section. Has a large shelf a few feet above the start.

description: I remember 1 great crimp, 1 2-finger crimp, and several side pulls.  You might find something else. Jump down, climb down, or top out into the parking lot.
location: Just to the right of RUsirius. Look for big sloper sidepulls.

description: Uncertain - PM me if I am wrong.  Very easy beginning leads to good vertical slot, good horizontal crimp, and bad sloper.  Moving up to bad feet will get you to the jug.
location: Right before Mark's Lunge
To the left of Peachstress.

description: Big holds & bad/high feet at the start, then easier.  You cant miss the big holds when you reach the wall.  It finishes at a roof that you can apparrantly traverse, campusing, at around 10a.
Two hand crimp start on left side of dihedral,¬†right foot stem, use undercling to move up to finishing left hand holds

location: Right near the start of Peach Wall, look in between the dihedral and the flake Skin Massacre starts on for a jug and sloper. (Jug should be on left side and the sloper is to the right of jug)

description: Squeeze the pillar like a vice. Throw a heel and grab the sloping top.
location: Light pillars found south of Hovde hall, north of belltower. Also present between MSEE and EE, as well as MSEE and PHYS

description: Climb the left or right side of the "Hail Purdue" monument located between Elliot hall and the Belltower. Mantle up, top out. Good warm up for Engineering Fountain Boulder.
location: Between the south side of Elliot Hall and the Belltower, locate the "Hail Purdue" monument

description: Climb the base of the belltower. A bit slopey, pinch hard. Don't walk under
location: Look for the belltower and walk to it. Watch for people who may not approve of your actions

description: Sit start on the arete. Begin on the crimps and throw for the point of the boulder. Top out.
location: Arete on Cult Boulder.

description: Start on the right side and basically dyno to the top.
location: It's the smaller mushroom shaped rock across from the bathrooms.

description: Located near the back of Mushroom State park opposite of restrooms.
location: see description

description: start on the lower ledge then move out the left side of the roof

route_name: when i put my climbing shoes on i become like super man
description: start matches on an under cling¬† compression use slopy crimps and pockets to top out

description: Start low on a left side pull and work right through a right-handed¬†gaston towards the top
start on lower ledge move up under the roof compressing the sides to pull straight out the middle
location: refer to picture

description: start on the lower left corner use moderate holds with big moves to top out
location: refer to photo

description: start on a slot crimp move up and to the left for a spicy top out
location: refer to photo

description: start low left then more right and up easy holds up the left side

description: Start on a matched chest high crimp and follow pockets and crimps toward the top out
Start matched on the right side on a low jug rail. Hit a right handed crimp on the right side of the block and work around for the top out
start on the lower ledge use the under cling¬†in the roof to pull the lip
start on the Southside pillar climb up and slightly to the left grabbing a small left edge on the cap and going straight up.

description: Start on a side pull low and to the right in the left cave move through moderate holds and pull the blocks to top out

location: Starts on right side of slab. Labeled 1.

description: Starts the same as ready set brush, Accra the rail above the overhang, ¬†then traverse left until the rail disappears into a finger crack, follow finger crack until it turns into a rail then finish up the arete at the end. ¬†It has been done with feet up high and below overhang, rating feels the same both ways. ¬†Very enjoyable, and a endurance run for sure...
location: Labeled 1.

description: Climb the middle line up the boulder. ¬†My dad and I‚Äôs First boulder problem...
location: Labeled 5.

description: On the face of the house, start on the left corner pillar, traverse across some crimps and tough balance parts. Finish is a pin in the doorframe with both hands on the large white headstone above the door.
location: On the left face of the house

description: Star your feet on a small crack beneath the mouth bring your left leg up try and get your foot into the eye on the right and step up and top out
May have been done before. Let me know, and I will change what is needed.
location: At the highest concentrated problems. Directly to the right of close contact. Start on the two slopers where your right hand is to the left of the Wahquahboshkuk name. From there, work your way up the crimps, and top out. If you like crimps, you will find this the best boulder in the field.

description: starts on right side of face. perfectly vertical. Side pull and crimp up to some tiny pockets.
location: battle canyon
protection: Crash pad and spotter if you want to do the real top out.

location: Left face of Golden Belt. Its the prominent feature there.
protection: Maybe a pad? The sand is almost soft enough.

description: Far right on boulder. Go straight up slopers and ledges to top.
location: Far right on Golden Belt Boulder

description: Fun low ball crack traverse. Start matched as low as possible in the crack and then work your way up and right.
location: Right side of main boulder field. One of the first boulders you encounter on the way in.

description: Steepest climb at Rock City? Start sitting under the short over hang, left hand on a small crimp and right hand on a sloper. Throw a right heel and make a hard move to a jug. Top out. Very low ball, but a fun, challenging move.
location: On the far left side of the main boulder field is a short boulder sticking out of the dirt. It is very close to the shed.

description: Start on the boulder called "the Lips" in the yellow pamphlet given by the gift shop. Hands start on the bottom lips, and go up and slightly left.
so named for "Owen" scrawled into the boulder near the start.

To the L of 'Unknown' route on same boulder. Starting low, smear and match on large jug, then jump to large pocket on top with RH; left heel hook on a ledge, then use the first jug to top out. Get down from the R side of the boulder or jump off

Probably done before, but a fun little problem I put up while passing through Kansas. Start left of Eye sockets with your right hand in the left socket and a heel hook. Move up to a horizontal slot and then up through underclings to top out. Crux is not dabbing since you start real low.
location: Just left of eye sockets

description: One move wonder. Start matched on the flat ledge and use the good foot to dyno up to the sloper. Match and go to the top. A bit contrived due to the crack out to the left being off, but a fun climb regardless.
location: On the back left side of the main boulder field, on one of the last big boulders. It is on left side of the corridor as you face the road.

description: Start low at the base, LH jug in large crack, match, RH sidepull in same crack, RH sloper at the intersection of the three cracks, LH crimp on a very small knob above, then use obvious jugs and ledges and top out; come down from the other side of the boulder (in part using the adjacent one).
protection: I didn't use a pad as I was traveling through, but given the height (10 ft, maybe more) it's a good idea. This is one of 3-4 taller boulders in the park

description: Start left hand side pull under finger pocket, right hand in right eye of ‚Äúfrowny face‚Äù. Can use mono but it‚Äôs rough pull. Left foot in bottom crack under side pull. Bump right to three finger pocket, right foot crack under. Semi dyno to good crimp near top, stand into worse crimp above mono. Reach over and top out!
location: Rear big boulder, back of field, shed to right.

description: Two hand start with the two pockets
location: This route almost faces the parking lot and is closer to the parking lot than other routes listed on this page. The "eye sockets" look out SSW.

description: Foot edges on the light colored rock beneath, RH sloper, LH square sloper above, match, twist to adjacent boulder to the L around using obvious ledges there, use pinches and jugs to get to the top of that boulder; come back down across the back of the first boulder
protection: A pad would be good but IMO the whole park is pretty safe to use without it

location: This route is on the same boulder as "Get the hang of it". It is directly across from a park bench.

description: Just left of prior
location: Labeled 6.

description: Sit start straight up
location: Labeled 1.

route_name: The final line of this chapter...
description: traverse rail just left of dead tree, around corner and top the same as 2... my final project at the part, and projected for 2 years before completing...
location: Labeled 3.

description: Up the left side of boulder.
location: Labeled 7.

description: Funny sit start in corner
location: Labeled 4.

description: Sit start bottom right, then up and left on diagonal rail.
location: Labeled 2.

description: start left hand on a small jug and right on under cling pinch go up to the obvious sloper and crimp bump left then go big right to a jug then top out
location: the first overhang section look for the sloper and crimp your start holds are under that

description: Start on a big jug undercling and throw up to a beautifully sculpted sharp pocket. From there work your way up and to the right on a spicy topout. Be sure to bring some grit to this one.
location: Walk down the cliffside until you see a big jutting out overhanging lip, the start is directly below that.
protection: Lots and lots of pads. But if you‚Äôre ballsy 1 or 2 should do.

location: On the main boulder of the area, to the left of taming wolves, watch video to be exact

first_ascent: I climbed it in 1979, others might have climbed it earlier.
description: An overhang near the top provides the crux.
location: The tallest part of the cliff, with the overhang.  It's towards the center of the cliff.
protection: Tree anchor at the top for TR.

description: An easy move to an unnecessary fist jam
location: The west side start in-between the turntables

description: a short problem that goes through a hole in the top
location: Southwest corner

description: A large traverse with plenty of heel hooks
location: Start at northeast corner working towards the south east corner
In Indian Rock park, not on the side close to the river, there is a dry pond next to the problem. Impossible to miss from the trail leading to it.
This is on the smaller boulder near the parking lot, very hard to miss.
On the small boulder near the parking lot

description: Start on the far right of the rock there will be good deep jugs as you make your way right. Good luck finding good foot holds, you have to grab a crimp to the left and then top out.
location: Indian Rock

description: Start on a crappy left hand pinch and a good right hand crimp. From there work your way to the right up to some powerful moves near the top. Finish on the lip near the top. Haven‚Äôt cleaned the topout yet.
location: Further down the cliff to the right from Wheaties in the Wheat Field. Again this area should appear a lot cleaner than the rest of the cliff.
Starts low on the left side of the entrance boulder near parking lot

description: starts on the right side of the piano boulder. Don't dab on the pole just dance around it
location: On the right side of the pole work up to top out

description: Starts at the vertical crack

10 ft traverse from right to left (though left to right is nearly identical). The hand holds are very solid and are mostly in the horizontal cracks that run the length of the route, but feet can be crumbly. The route was originally done on only the gray rock for extra challenge and to avoid the crumbly yellow stuff at the very bottom. No real crux, fairly solid moves and holds throughout the WHOLE 10ft! We have to work with what we got here in kansas, so no using the top or pulling off choss.
location: Past the "main" area. Start / finish are fairly obvious.
protection: the crash zone has been nicely cleared of rocks, sticks, and bushes. You're never more than maybe a foot of the ground, but crash pads and spotters are always a good idea.

description: Starts at the soutwest arete on a bridging of 2 layers of rock. SDS that follows the left side of the arete and exits near the piece of driftwood. This route shares the same start as Got Driftwood and Fracker's Traverse
Shares the same start as Back Burner and move up and to the right where is shares the same finish as What the Elk and Got Driftwood.
Shares the same starting hold and finish as What the Elk. Quickly moves out left and up to the piece of driftwood.

This route starts on the southwest arete and shares the same start as What the Elk and Got Driftwood. It follows a leftward traverse low then over the middle bulge (starts for Popped my Cherry and Backburner) then gradually trends upward to the very top left corner.
Cool, but sadly very short problem. Start low with a big heel hook to a tiny crack. Match, then move to next tiny crack and finish with an easy mantle.
location: Up the arete at the "main" cliff / outcropping/ crappy road cut out thing. Starts on really low, big holds. Down climb is very easy and obvious.
protection: Crash pad! You're low to the ground but could easily hit your head on the heel hook.

description: Starts on medium sized rock in the center of the west side of boulder. This route head straight upward and then deviates to the left with an obvious top out.

location: On the left if walking down the old road from the parking area. The longest, best looking section and the only one with a real trail.
protection: The crash zone area has been nicely cleared of bushes, rocks, and sticks. Bringing a crash pad would be a good idea, though you're never more than 2 ft off the ground.

description: Starts far left of boulder and then straight up for finish
Starts right of the vertical crack and traverses the seam above the horizontal crack and finishes out on the top left
Starts on far left side and goes straight up the arete.
Starting on the far left corner traverse right across the horizontal to meet up with Up the Crack
Starts in the crack just beneath the downward pointing "beak". Traverses right and finishes out the same as The Cracken
Starts to the left of the "beak" on the horizontal crack and exits straight up the top
Climbs the north end of the Piano
location: start at the northeast side working west

description: This starts on the flake to the far left and traverses via heel hooks to the right and finishing on the start of Hookers to the Left
Far left sds with a hand jam and and toe jam if you so chose
Starts in the middle of the lower two rocks. A deep hand jam may be helpful. Goes straight up for the challenging top out

This is a fun and exposed route. Start on a couple of short boulders on the hiking trail. The beginning has a little bit of chossy rock but is mostly clear. Follow a crack up and right to a north facing wall and cruse to the top. This route could eventually be a trad route if somebody doesn't get sketched out by the runout at the beginning.
location: The base of the route is just outside of the massive roof to the north. Another way to find the line is to look for the crack that starts 15 feet up and separates the west wall from the north wall of the roof.
protection: Tree anchors. If wanting to attempt trad: Cams #0.5 -- #2 should give you multiple placement options.

description: a dangerous route with compression moves near the top
location: see picture

description: start on the sloper rail move up and a hair to your right
location: look at picture

description: start on the sloper rail pull the under cling then use pockets and tec¬†to top out
location: see picture

description: start on the sloper rail pull the undercling and climb the crack
location: see picture

description: start on the lower sloper rail move up and to the right using the pockets on the top to top out
location: look at picture

description: Start low on the far right and quickly get to the top and traverse left using a series of heel hooks. Use the slightly unstable ledge on the far left to plant a foot for a unique top out.
Climb up slab doing reachy moves past 4 bolts. You can top this climb out, but there is loose rock above the last bolt, so be cautious.
location: In the middle of the Memorial Wall. It is currently the only bolted line.
protection: 4 bolts, no anchors. I left a quick link on the last bolt to lower off. An anchor could be built using trees at the top of the climb.

description: Boulder up on to a ledge to gain a crack system. Follow the narrowing crack to the top.
location: About 20' left of the wide corner and just to the right of the blue "Kelsey" graffiti.
protection: Singles .75-#3. The crack is very irregular inside, so be prepared to fiddle with the gear to get it set well. Currently no anchors, but solid trees on top for a TR anchor.

description: Follow rail to the right into the crack. from the top of the crack work to the right through obvious jugs
start on the large jug rail pull 2 finger pockets to a high step committing¬†move then use larger holds to top out
location: see picture

description: a stunning roof problem where your feet are the most important thing! start on the rail at the back of the cave move up and to the right then moving into the crack to pull the crux moves to top out.
location: refer to picture

description: Start just right of the easy corner, using small edges to move up to some horizontals. After placing some gear, move up past the huge creaky flake. I yarded on this flake quite a bit before leading the route and it didn't fall off. However, it flexes quite a bit and is huge, so I didn't pull on it while climbing. It is easy to avoid, so you might just want to do that. The upper part of the route is fairly juggy, but it is quite a ways down to your last piece, so keep it together. There is a flake you can place a questionable C4 #.75 behind, as well as a pass-thru that can be threaded.
location: Just right of the prominent wide corner.
protection: I gave this route a PG-13 due to the flexy flake and for decking potential due to the questionable gear higher up on the route. This is not a lead for beginners. I placed a #4, #1, and #.75 C4. There may be more opportunities for gear, but I felt safe with those pieces. No anchors at the top at this time, but with a good amount of webbing (20'+) you can set up a solid tree TR anchor.

description: Slopey crimps lead up to a good horizontals. Once past the horizontals, climb pockety jugs to the top.
location: Left of the prominent wide corner, and immediately left of the blue "Kelsey" graffiti.
protection: #1 C4, a medium nut, and a sling for a pass-thru at the top. No anchors, but trees can be used for a TR anchor.

description: Starting the route can be a bit more difficult for people shorter than 5'10". The first few holds are fairly small but you'll get a nice rest on several jug options about ten feet up the route. The crux is a five foot section in the middle of the route and starts with a sharp but good left hand two finger pocket (or a mono depending on how fat your fingers are) and a small right hand gaston. Then deep pockets to the top.
location: On the east wall there is a small tree that is directly in front of the start of the route. Another way to identify the route is by finding the very slight overhanging bulge in the middle of the wall.
protection: There are several nice sized trees to set up a top rope anchor on.

location: On a set of boulders broken off the main face, appears as if people have camped in the cave created

description: Sit start at the base of the overhanging arete with a good right hand and a sharp left hand crimp. The route goes straight up the arete to a nice jug for the topout.
location: On the east side of the boulder there is an overhanging arete.

description: Start no hands use pockets to top out
location: See picture

description: Far left side of the wall facing away from the water another staircase like structure. Easiest to down climb the far right side of the wall (Andre's Dong V1)

Climb up around the back side of the wall starting down by the water and climb up until you can reach the metal bar and then just shimmy across to the other side where there is some other weird stuff to mess around on. Go for foot work practice or you can let go of the metal and try and find actual holds on the way but if you fall the water is only about a foot deep and their is some metal and rock at the bottom so I don't recommend falling on this side of the wall!

On the side of the wall facing away from the water on the far right side their are blocks sticking out forming a kind of staircase arrangement. This route is also the easiest to down climb which will be required once you top out.

Massive pockets lend themselves to uninspiring climbing. Good for warming up or for a confidence booster if the other problems are shutting you down. There could possibly be a line on the south face of this rock, avoiding the ar√™tes, which would definitely not be a v0.
location: The Southernmost rock.

description: Balance is key. Sit start on the right side and work up through a couple v3 moves to a decent stance under the small overhang, then its small edges, and tiny slopers to the top. The ar√™tes are there but it is a better climb if you don't use them.
location: The South face of the middle rock.

description: Compression holds on good ar√™tes with an decent smears and heel hooks. Somewhat continuous which earns a v2 grade. Avoiding the obvious chipped crimps around the right ar√™te (mural side of the rock) is the best way and makes for a much more rewarding climb.
location: The South side of the Northernmost rock. It is aptly named for the skinny shaft and slightly bulging cap.
protection: Not much room to top out. It would be wise to bring along a spotter.

description: Sit start to some decent jugs before working the ar√™tes to the top. Avoiding the chipped crimpers around to the far right keeps the climbing more consistent and engaging.
location: East face of the middle boulder.

route_name: All Quiet on the Western Front
description: A powerful route with a solid ar√™te on the right with slopers and a sharp pocket on the left.
location: West face of the Northernmost boulder.

description: Start left and right paw on crimps. Right hand up to a pinch or sloppy side-pull, left will go find a nubbin. Catch the lip. Considerably better rock quality than the other face. Will clean up over time. ¬†Stay on the line, arete is off, the face has a nice flow to it, enjoy.
location: Breakfast Boulder, face to the right of the arete problem.
protection: Pad to protect rock in fall zone.

description: Climb the arete, moving into the slab face of the wall.
location: Start on the undercling on the corner of the arete and move into balance driven slab

description: lets pull on some crimps
location: see picture

description: start on a left side pull crimp and a 2 finger pocket follow the arete¬†to the top
location: see picture

description: bad landing, but solid hang problem
Starts on right side of the bottom following the lip to the top.
protection: Rocky fall so pads are a good idea

description: Best boulder in the overlook area and the biggest. Has potential for multiple lines.
location: west of the fossil boulder
protection: pads and we're working on building a better landing

description: The rating varies from 5.4 to 5.9 (left to right) on this face of cracks. Left of J.C. Superstar. Great setting for Cliff Dr. Lower from the belay tree and make the climb two pitches.
location: J.C. Area - 1.5 miles south from the north entrance to Cliff Dr. Hike toward the cliffs. Steep hiking. Killer Bees block is located just before the hilltop. Continue past Killer Bees on the right. Gain the hilltop and break left. The top of J.C. and Tobacco Road and is a nice block perch looking out over Cliff Dr.
protection: Trad. Bolts possibly up top for TR and/or rappel. Check condition if bolts exist.

first_ascent: Not yet... Jonah almost sent it...
location: Just down stream from the first and seemingly biggest falls.
protection: This is a pretty low boulder route.

description: This is the west facing #4 sized crack on the upper two levels of the parking garage, butterfly stacks for the whole way.
location: just get to the top of the garage and choose either the right or left crack

description: Just South of fire pit. Build anchor off trees at the top and rapel dow to knock loose rock away before climbing

ascend the north portion of the wall and gain the top. There- you have two options...progress on your butt...straddling the wall for the distance or stand up and majestically stride along this wall...er....ridge.   Slack liners - a challenge to you...who can walk this first and post a pic?
location: the walmart at the corner of 9th ave and 43. Large walmart..look to the back see the long ridge- max height 25 feet- long long traverse.
protection: depending on the time of day this location is very low bust.  Bring your wits and maybe a driver.

location: The steam tower south of the library.

north side of "steam tower"- which is a square concrete building near waldo library and knauss hall. Look for the obvious campus board like feature. Look for the small sculpture of a person balancing (slack lining?) at the top of this building.
protection: super nice landing, no pads needed

location: south west corner of the shakespeare building. down town kalamazoo.
protection: at least one pint of beer from the pub might give you the courage to go for it. A soberish spotter is a good idea.
easy landings on grass. A good spotter is all you need.

description: east side of Markin Glen County park. Over looking the ox bow lake off the Kalamazoo River. This long, concrete hand traverse concentrates on foot smears and slabby hands. While not very varied, it is good practice for the pitch directly after passing through the "darth vader head" on the Wolf's Head in the Wind Rivers- Wolfs head Traverse.
location: Markin Glen  County Park. Kalamazoo, Michigan
protection: guts, and a willingness to take a 15 food ground fall on concrete.

route_name: Kalamazoo Communities  In Schools Wall ( KCISW)
location: The KCIS building in the alley way near Climb Kalamazoo. Downtown.
protection: your wits. a pad will only slow you down.

location: East side of East Hall. Hard to miss.
protection: your wits. Bringing pads would only slow you down.

description: river rock cemented in the wall in front of bernhard center has various routes up - the longest is about 20 ft straight up, some good holds and some are trash. bad fall onto concrete, but easy to mantle once you're up
location: @ bernhard center, corner of building in between main entrance and the "bronco mall" stylized entrance on the side of the building

route_name: The Secret Is In The Choss
description: Just South of fire pit. Build anchor off trees at the top and rapel dow to knock loose rock away before climbing

route_name: On the 8th Day He Created Choss
description: Very chossy LH side of small open book just north of fire pit. Build anchor off trees at the top and rapel dow to knock loose rock away before climbing

route_name: I'm Not good At Juggy Stuff
description: Lots of crimpers and some side pulls. Nice vertical face. very little choss. Lots of fossils in the rock. Crux is the mantle.
location: Southern area. South of the pond

description: Left corner arete
location: In southern area. South of the pond (which may be seasonal). Next to I'm Not good At Juggy Stuff
protection: TR. Anchor to the trees up top

description: Very chossy RH side of small open book just north of fire pit. Build anchor off trees at the top and rapel dow to knock loose rock away before climbing

route_name: Big Holds, Huh? Alright, Welp, See Ya Later
description: A small roof to get around
location: Just south of On the 8th Day He Created Choss, near the fire pit
This is the obvious hand crack on the east side of the garage
protection: I put this up as a free solo... you'd probably get arrested if doing it any other way.

description: This climb is around the overlook area and starts to the right under the roof.
Just to the left of the finger crack taking good holds to a hand jam
The name says it all
location: Down and right from the overlook

description: Slabby face. Decent tilt.
location: Top of the Ice Fall area - next to Rated P.G. This is a great rappel to get into the area at the bottom of Rated P.G. and the top of Lie Detector, Ice Fall, and Stoned Cold Liar.
protection: Top Rope. Do not remember any bolts as the guide book describes. Thin pro maybe?

description: Straight up the dirty slab to the first roof, pull to the easy slab above. ¬†Angle left up this slab to the left corner under the orange second roof. ¬†Reach out and ascend the bomber flake up to the mantle. ¬†A "thank god" ledge gives you time to sort out the small nuts needed to protect the crux (with bomber placements at your heals) which is the move out right around the 3rd roof. ¬†Get established on the slab above and cruise to the treeded ledge. ¬†At this point you need to choose where to stop. ¬†This is the natural end to the climb and a bomber white pine anchor, but one rope will not get you down, and the pull from the tree is really tough and barely doable ¬†(will be replacing webbing and rap rings.) ¬†Or, you can continue up ¬†the buttress on an easy featured slab and anchor on the white pine about 40' higher. ¬†The rope will pull much easier from this tree. ¬†There is no 4th class approach from either side of the buttress to toprope this route or walk down. ¬†Sometimes has Perrigrine falcons nearby, so avoid if nesting perigrines are giving you the flyby.
location: This route is visible from the road, you can see the orange second roof directly up from the curvey road sign. ¬†You can park there and walk straight up to the climb, navigating a small swamp. ¬†Head up through the boulder field. ¬†This climb is located between Overkill Roof area and JC superstar area.
protection: standard rack, need small nuts/ large micros.

description: This route starts straight up from below the headwall of Exotermic through the triangular roof.  It is the farthest to the left on this face.  The next route to the left is around the corner on Obsession face and that route name is Clavin's project.
protection: Little ability to protect until triangular roof.

route_name: Stoned Cold Liar (AKA Old Dirty Bastard)
description: Up and slanting right then straight and then left to the anchors. Crux is 15-20 ft. before the anchors, the holds thin somewhat and you make a right to left move upward. Look for a block with a neutral grip.
location: Just around the corner to the right from Lie Detector. Might need cleaning.
protection: Protection could be sketchy on this face with the freeze/thaw from the winter snow. Build an anchor in the same area as for Lie Detector and Ice Fall.

description: Off-width to the right of Obsession. Head through the roof.
location: Just left of Obsession Direct.
Just uphill of the mossy boulder in the Ice Fall Area. Ice Fall and Lie Detector are 400-500 ft. to the right (north-eastish) from Rope-burn.
protection: Top rope by gaining the top of the RB block via a ledge system up and right from the base area of the climb. Lead would be exciting for sure. Thin pro, at best? This short route lends itself to more TR than lead. Be safe, don't deck. Climb on Garth.

location: Top of the Ice Fall area. Above Ice Fall (5.7), Lie Detector (5.8), and Stoned Cold Lier (5.8). Rappel down the slab to the east of the Rated P.G. block/arete to begin Rated P.G. or scramble down to the tops of the above three routes.

description: This one is fun, but the ending is kind of lame because you can exit on the slab. There is a potential dyno just left of this Arete. The top would need some scrubbing. Given a generic name beause im sure it has been climbed before.
location: South of Mossy Boulder, downhill.

description: Start right hand on patina crimp pinch. Left hand on slopey horizontal or in crack. Move left through good edges. Has potential for a lower start, but is scrunchy. Given a generic name because I'm sure it has been done before.
location: South of Mossy Boulder, uphill. Faces the road.

description: Tough overhanging face. Watch the pendulum and lead fall potential.
Head left from the lower ledge and up the arret and over the headwall. One bolt after the headwall?
location: bsession Area. 1/2 mile south of the north junction of Cliff Dr. and U.S. 41. The Obsession Block is obvious from the road. See pictures. Hike up and left of the tailings piles. Hike up and left to the top  of the hill and find the top of Obsession. Or hike lower and access the bottoms of many climbs on the area.

description: Start from the ledge (15' above the ground) at the bottom of the lower slab. Head up right or left. Head past the small overhang and then the big one. Piton (if still remaining) was placed in 1981.
location: Obsession Area. 1/2 mile south of the north junction of Cliff Dr. and U.S. 41. The Obsession Block is obvious from the road. See pictures. Hike up and left of the tailings piles. Hike up and left to the top  of the hill and find the top of Obsession. Or hike lower and access the bottoms of many climbs on the area.
protection: Trad. Natural anchors and pro placement.

description: Squat start on sloping crimp rail with terrible feet. Pull through to holds trending toward prow. Top out on moss covered holds (needs a good scrub). Given a generic problem name because I'm sure it has been climbed before. Obvious line with hard opening moves. It's even hard to establish on the start hold. Stand start is about V4.
location: Mossy Boulder.
protection: Two pads and a spotter would be nice. Sharp blocks in the landing.

description: Sit start and traverse the lip. Lowball.
location: South of Mossy Boulder.

description: Start up a flat featureless slab for the first 20 ft.  Hug the right side arete, as that's where most of your initial protection can be found.  Pull over a small roof/shelf and work your way left to two obvious large crescent shaped cracks.  Balancy to the top.
protection: Cams of just about any size will work on the crack, but it seems like having a fistful of BD #1's it the way to go.  Set up on belay ledge same as Dandruff.

description: Nice face climb perched above the forests of da U.P. eh! Cracks and ledges help your way. Variations on this one.
location: J.C. Area - 1.5 miles south from the north entrance to Cliff Dr. Hike toward the cliffs. Steep hiking. Killer Bees block is located in the trees just before the hill kicks up steeply. Continue past Killer Bees on the right. Gain the hilltop and break left. The top of J.C. and Tobacco Road and is a nice block perch looking out over Cliff Dr.
protection: Top-rope. Maybe thin pro? Scope it out on rappel.

location: Ice Fall Area - 2 miles south of the northern Cliff Dr. junction with US 26/41 just before Phoenix. Locate large mossy boulder in the lower flats in the woods just prior to the hillside rising. There are many boulders, but this one stands out a bit. Hike uphill a few hundred feet. Approach from either above or below. From below cross a talus field and broken cliff edges, watch for poison ivy. Or continue to the top of the cliffs and hike east then rappel in on the right (east) side of Rated P.G. which is Tip Toes. Walk down the trail to the tops of Ice Fall and Lie Detector from here.
protection: Thin pro on lead. No bolts. Natural anchor. The top puts you at to the path/rock ledges in between the top of Ice Fall and Rated P.G.

description: Climb up the left side of the block and gain the horizontal right-left tending crack. Move right all the way to the end and exit onto the face above.
location: The Diamond Block - 1.85 miles south of the north junction of Cliff Dr. and U.S. 41. Scout out a path through the talus field.

description: Begin on the leaning slab and in the crack. Crux is pulling the roof. Finish 10-15 ft. after the roof.
location: Ice Fall Area - 2 miles south of the northern Cliff Dr. junction with US 26/41 just before Phoenix. Locate large mossy boulder in the lower flats in the woods just prior to the hillside rising. There are many boulders, but this one stands out a bit. Hike uphill a few hundred feet. Approach from either above or below. Continue to the top of the cliffs and hike east then rappel in on the right (east) side of Rated P.G. and walk down the trail to the tops of Ice Fall and Lie Detector. Or find the talus field at the bottom and hike east skirting the cliff outcroppings. Beware of poison ivy!
protection: Traditional protection. Standard rack. Or top rope from above.

description: A large tower/buttress coming out of the wall just to the northeast of the ice falls area.  Good protection every 10-15 feet, variety of gear sizes needed.  Top rope access extremely difficult/impossible.  Excellent learner piece for first time leaders.  Can top out by traversing the top of the tower back to the wall and climbing the sides of a very steep, scree filled gully.  Climb the gully walls, not the gully itself, as it is NOT STABLE and has FATAL FALL potential.
location: Spot the tower from the base of the road.  You'll have to fight through thick tag alder and pick your way up the boulder field.  Directly left of Overkill roofs.  Tower to the left of Free to Roam that looks like it has excellent route potential.
protection: Climbed with rack of Trango Flex #1-4, Metolius Masters #1,2,4, BD #2, omega nuts 1-13 and metolius hex 1-10.  (obviously) did not use them all, but didn't record what was placed.  2 large white pines on route facilitate 2 stage, single rope rappels.

description: The most northerly climb in the Obsession area, just north of Catholic girls.  A face with deceptively small holds.  Stick to the right side.  All balance.
Starts on the left face in the chimney.  Move left at the horizontal groove to gain the headwall above a desperate precipice.
protection: No ability to protect on lead.

description: On the face directly below the large, woodpecker ridden red pine.  Large flakes and a good crack.  Very juggy, good for beginners.
protection: Nuts hold extremely well in the crack, and you can safely protect the thing in about three pieces.

description: Second slab as you hike in on the trail. Dished face climb.
location: Obsession Area. 1/2 mile south of the north junction of Cliff Dr. and U.S. 41. The Obsession Block is obvious from the road. See pictures. Hike up and left of the tailings piles. Hike up and left to the top  of the hill and find the top of Obsession. Or hike lower and access the bottoms of many climbs on the area.

description: Sit start on two crimps and work the compression feature on bubble wrap holds. Top out, and then top out again. Great rock quality and clean. Given a generic name because I'm sure it has been climbed before.
location: Just south of Mossy Boulder.

description: An easy out for Killer Bees up a small crack on the left side of the face.  Good first lead.
protection: Small cams, two rappel anchors at the top if you want to top rope it.

description: Lowball boulder. Start on the crack and crimp to the left. Move up through the crack and top out.
Two pitch route, or make it one. Fun little cruiser climb.
location: Approx. 150 yards to the right (northeast) of Stoned Cold Liar.
protection: Bolts for most of the route. Check the bolt conditions due to freeze/thaw exposure and/or lack of use. Might be spots for some traditional protection.

description: Good crack up to small roof.  Deceptively few holds coming over.  Cracks can be difficult to protect due to flare.
location: When the JC trail begins to head up the gully, break off to the left until you hit the first roof.
