protection: bring a large nut of BD2 cam to sink into the roof.

description: Go right just before the first set of stairs. Stay low, after about 100 yards you'll see it on the left with a small tree (5 inch in diameter) about a foot and a half away from the cliff. BETA SPRAY ALERT: Sit start matched on a right slanting rail and a left foot backstep. Left hand up to a jug, throw a right heel up, make a bump to an undercling, switch to a toe, then fling yourself up to a left hand slightly sloping rail while making sure you sneak past the guard of the small tree behind you. Finish out left. It would be better if the tree wasn't there but I didn't want to tick anyone off by cutting it down. All in all its a pretty dang good Boulder problem.
location: Go right just before the first steps. 100 yards through the woods gets you there

description: Based on the amount of lichen and moss I scrubbed off this thing I'm guessing no one has climbed it. Please let me know if I am wrong about this. Start left hand low on arete, right on an undercling grip around right ar√™te, and a right heel. Slap your way to the top. There exists a low start the would be proper burly.
location: Right off the trail on your way up to the main cliff

description: Ariel map of route locations

route_name: Hope You Got Insurance And Shit

description: Grab a pint or two at The Well and hop on this Greektown classic.
location: This is located in an alley just around the corner from The Well.

description: Start on slim holds and work your way up towards the crack in the brick wall.
location: From I75, take the Mack Exit and head west. Turn left on Brush and then left on Division. The building is located on the left side of the road. Twinkle Toes is located in the center of the west face.

description: Slim start moving to deep pockets.
location: From I75, take the Mack Exit and head west.  Turn left on Brush and then left on Division.  The building is located on the left side of the road.  Red Meat is located on the far left side of the west face.

description: A selection of brick stacks run along South McKinstry street. Each one poses a slightly different challenge. Most float around a V1, but some can be a bit more challenging. Check brick quality due to an areas that may have been damaged by fire.
location: An old manufacturing building across from the old Boblo Island ferry terminal (Reddish Brown in color). Routes run along South McKinstry Street.
protection: Boulder Pad or 2 should be used, just in case. Some glass and other city trash along base of building

description: Not really a particular route here as it is a big old brick wall with a bazillion holds sticking out of it.  The wall was painted white when this picture was taken, but it has since been painted blue.  Most of the holds are pretty bomber, but it is old brick, so be careful.
location: This wall is located on the West side of the Canfield substation which is just East of Woodward on the North side of Canfield.  There may be access issues today as it appears from Google Maps that there is now a barbed wire fence around the property.
protection: Bouldering pads are always nice to protect from falling on a needle in Detroit.  That being said, this is in Midtown, so your biggest threat is probably getting a ticket from Wayne State Police.  Have an escape route.

description: There are a number of arches and other features down here that are climbable.
location: B3 is located in teh basement of the Book Cadillac at the corner of Michigan and Washington.  Access is difficult as this area is usually locked.  If you can find a nefarious dish washer at one of the hotels fine dining establishments and slip him a twenty or a bag of oregano, he may be able to get you down there.

description: Start matched on slopey jug. Make move up and left to a solid jug. Then throw a heel on the slopey jug and make some bumps up good holds and topout. Crux is topping out. Fun little problem with some pumpy/powerful moves. (Low juggy foot at the start is off, as it is pretty loose)
location: Behind the corner of Alley Slab. From the trailhead, walk down the hill and turn right. Walk until seeing Meteoright/Meteor-left along the trail on the right. Walk up the hill on the trail along Meteoright/Meteor-left, and take a left. Problem will be on your left.

description: Stand start matched on a large jug. Climb up and topout using good holds.
location: Directly below Warm Up 1. From the trailhead, travel down the hill and take a right once at the bottom of the hill. Route will be down from Warm Up 1, which is less than a 1 minute walk from the bottom of the hill.

description: SDS on two low jugs. Pull to standing and reach for good central jug before moving feet up and topping out. Like climbing a ladder.
location: From the trailhead, travel down the hill and take a right once at the bottom of the hill. After about 1 minute, look left. This boulder will be at the top of a slight incline towards the river. The problem can be found directly above White belt.

description: Stand start matching on prominent jug. Traverse left using good holds and topout using solid rails. Fun movement to warm up on.
location: From the trailhead, travel down the hill and take a left. Walk the trail for a couple minutes, and the boulder will appear along the trail on your left.

description: Start with right hand on large jug, left hand on side crimp. Climb up using jugs on arete and left hand crimps before gaining feet on large ledge. Easy top out
location: From trailhead, travel down the hill and take a right once at the bottom of the hill. After a couple of minutes there will be an opening to the left. Walk left through open corridor and look left to find this problem. It will be in a clearing between Warm Up 1 and the Neighborhood area.

description: Start on low, large rightmost jug. Traverse left using solid rails and side pulls. Climb up Rhino Horn to finish. Crux is at the beginning.
location: From trailhead, travel down the hill, and take first available left. Follow this trail until reaching this boulder, which will be to the right of the inland trail. This problem is directly right of Rhino Horn.

description: SDS on detached block using high jug with right hand and low side pull jug with left. Climb up along the crack using an obvious Rhino horn looking jug. Tricky top out for the grade.
location: From the trailhead, travel down the hill, and take first available left. Follow this trail until reaching this boulder, which will be along the trail on the right.

description: Start low with left hand on a slanted rail and right hand on a lower rail. Climb up using the arete and good holds.
location: In cul de sac area. From the trailhead, walk down the hill, and take the first right. Follow the trail for 1 minute, then take a left at a small clearing and walk towards the river. Enter the cul de sac close to the river.

description: Stand start on good crimps and heel. Make a few bumps up into prominent jugs, then traverse left along a juggy crack/rail. Match on jug on far left of the overhanging boulder.
location: Overhanging boulder just past Meteoright/Meteor-left. From the trailhead, follow the trail down and then take a right at the bottom of the hill. Follow the trail parallel to the river until you reach the boulder, which will be along the right side of the trail.

description: Stand start on two side pulls. Climb up using slippery feet a prominent side pull/rail. Crux is reaching the jug just above the prominent side pull.
location: Closet problem to the river in the cul de sac area. ¬†From the trailhead, walk down the hill, and take the first right. Follow the trail for 1 minute, then take a left at a small clearing and walk towards the river. Enter the cul de sac close to the river.

description: Stand start with compression using ¬†left hand on a solid sidepull jug and right hand high on a crimp. Gain high feet and throw for a small crimp. Then climb up into a quartzite band to solid jugs. From here, traverse left and climb into the crater feature. Top out as if on Meteor-left. Crux is the beginning move throwing from compression to the high crimp.
location: From the trailhead, follow the trail down and then take a right at the bottom of the hill. Follow the trail parallel to the river until you reach the boulder, which will be along the right side of the trail. 5 minutes from the parking area.

description: Start standing with left hand on small crimp and right hand in small mouth features (may only fit a few fingers). Bump hands to good rail before shifting weight and reaching left to flat knob feature (use intermediates as needed). Transition right to the quarzite strip of jugs halfway up the boulder before moving up into the crater feature and follow the easy top out on the left side of the crater. This 20+ foot climb is a lot of fun with good movement and neat features.
location: From the trailhead, follow the trail down and then take a right at the bottom of the hill. Follow the trail parallel to the river until you reach the boulder, which will be along the right side of the trail. 5 minutes from the parking area.

description: Stand start matched on low block. Make a lieback transition into the higher blocks and climb up the arete to better holds up top. Crux is transitioning from low block.
location: From the trailhead, travel down the hill, and take first available left. Follow this trail past Rhino Horn/Traverse until the trail opens up along the right side. Look down towards the river within this clearing.

description: Compression start with left hand on large sloper, right hand on low sidepull. Move up to rail before bumping onto higher holds and moving for a heel hook. From here work left to sideways crimp before finding better footing and bumping up to good rail and mantling for the top out.
location: On the opposite side of Alley Slab. From trailhead, walk down the hill and turn right. Once you walk past Meteoright/Meteor-left, this problem will be your next right. Or, if coming from the top of Working the Corner/Alley Slab there will be a steep path leading down to this problem to the left.

description: Sit start using right hand crimp and left hand on arete. Match on right start hold, and then bump right hand further right to another crimp. Dyno to the lip. Could be different beta using the arete.
location: From the trailhead, follow the trail to the bottom of the hill. Take a right and follow the trail along the river past Meteoright/Meteor-left. Walk past Painted Black and take a right. Boulder is up and right of Painted Black.

description: Crouch start with left hand on arete and right hand on low rail. Climb up using the arete, then transition into Backyard BBQ to top out. Crux is transitioning from arete to holds on Backyard BBQ.
location: First climb on the left when entering the Neighborhood area. From the trailhead, walk down the hill, and take the first right. Follow the trail for 1 minute, then take a left at a small clearing and walk towards the river. Enter the cul de sac close to the river.

description: SDS with left hand side pull and right hand low rail. Pull up to side rail before reaching large jugs and an easy top out. Crux is the first move.
location: In the cul de sac area. From the trailhead, walk down the hill and take a right. Follow the trial for 1 minute, then take a left up a short hill with a clearing. From here you will be above the cul de sac area. Look down and you will see an circular piece of ground surrounded by a small boulder section. Downclimb into area or go further down the trail and climb up near the river. This problem is directly right of Cul de sac kid.

description: Sit start with right hand jug and left hand crimp. Climb up using good crimps and topout.
location: From the trailhead, walk down the hill and turn right. Walk until seeing Meteoright/Meteor-left along the trail on the right. Walk up the hill on the trail along Meteoright/Meteor-left, and take a left. Problem will be on your left.

description: A little bit of everything on this one! Slab to a large ledge at 15 feet. Grapple with an interesting Texas-shaped block, move left onto wavy overhangs and a thin headwall, then pull onto a good ledge, then a slab finish.
Climb slab to a roof 30 feet up with a splitter crack in it. Pull the heinous roof crux, and trust those feet to surmount and clip the next bolt. ¬†Finish on vert/slab.

Technical and thuggy crux off the deck; stick clip first bolt. Unlock the wicked roof, then trend up and right on consistant crimps staying on the face right of the ar√™te, don't reach around the arete till your under the last bolt on the slab. ¬†Shares last bolt and anchors with #4.

first_ascent: Unknown, Equipped by P.P. and E.L.
location: From the parking lot by the stairs walk towards the trail with white blazes. From the entrance of this trail, look uphill past the first roll and the crack should be visible through the trees. Get creative through the boulders to reach the base.
protection: Eye it up from the bottom. Two bolts above to establish TR anchor. Can also walk off the top.

description: Start from a small ledge under the right side of Desolation Roof. Begin climbing up and right, following a diagonal crack. Step over a notch and make your way to a rightward-leaning slab. Finish left at top of slab. Shares last bolt and anchors with #5. Clip the perma draw on the third bolt to clean as you descend.
Start at the base of a ledge system which leads to a face split by a crack system. ¬†Climbs just right of white, orange, and black streaked section.

The farthest route climbers right on the main wall, just before you enter the *** POISON IVY*** patch. ¬†Start in front of the tree that's branches touch the wall. ¬†The Line begins with a short finger crack climbing off a small ledge at one meter. ¬†Climb up the seams, and out from under the tree to the sunshine above. ¬†Continue up the broken cracks up and right to a tree anchor high above.

location: Underneath the right end of Desolation Roof. Starts with a short right-angling dihedral/face (crux) leading to a nice ledge. ¬†Traverse right and up to gain the slab. ¬†Bob and weave your way up while trustin dem feet. ¬†Anchors way up by ceder tree which can also be accessed from the top.
protection: A set of stoppers, and cams to #3. Bring small cams. It is safest to clip the first bolt of Yo Momma to protect the crux start.

route_name: 37. Don't Panic, and Bring Your Towel
first_ascent: Cleaned B.M. August 2019. Equipped by P.P and L.P.
location: Starts in a triangular cutout below an OW at the far right side of the lower wall. Right near the two maple trees growing very close together. ~20 ft right of where Love Street, Matrix and Resurrection are clumped together, anchors are immediately below a white pine on a ledge near the top of the wall and are visible from the bottom.

first_ascent: Bolts had been chopped in the late 90's, originally equipped by A.L. & S.E..  Re-cleaned by L.P., N.P., P.P., J.J., J.K.; anchors installed by L.P.  .
location: The route lies close to the far right side of the cliff, 15' left of Wine Line and 10' right of Resurrection
protection: Rack consists of small to fist sized cams, double up on #1 Camelot size and below

location: This route is located slightly downhill from the two currently (6/2015) bolted routes right of the 5.8 curving trad line called "The large crack".  The lower trail from the climbers' parking lot leads directly to the route "The large crack".

description: Only for desperate and deprived tradsters. ¬†Usually wet and dirty. ¬†Climb the obvious left-leaning, greenish crack 10 feet right of Queen Bee (#30). Use Queen Bee's anchors.

This is the full Queen Bee route. Ascend a heavily featured face to a crack, then continue up and right through a chill slab to a nice ledge. Clip one of the bolts of the anchor and battle through an awkward diagonal crack to better holds on a headwall. Anchors below a small roof.
location: Second bolted route to the right of the obvious diagonal crack 5.9 ¬†trad route Sexus (aka The Diagonal Crack).

protection: Trad, chain anchors on Pine tree.

first_ascent: Equipped by M.G., J.L., E.L, J.H..
description: An easy slab leads to an awkward dihedral. Huff and grunt to surmount a small roof, then find some hidden holds to unlock the short headwall to the anchors.

First pitch, Traverse Variation (5.10b): Starts immediately right of Beyond Hell/Above Heaven (#25) and traverses right, following a nearly horizontal hand crack for first 10 feet. Then climb up and continue traversing right using the same crack for your feet. After the fourth bolt, follow the bolts up and diagonally right to anchors on a small ledge. 60 feet, 6 + anchors.

protection: Completely bolted, but the top pitch can be a fun trad lead.

description: First pitch, Direct Variation (5.11b): Starts just left of an obvious diagonal crack system. Climb a sheer face on thin crimps and sidepulls to the same set of anchors as the Traverse Variation. Sustained climbing. 50 feet, 5 + anchors.

Right-most climb under the Rainbow Roof. ¬†Crux is getting to and from a large flake 10 feet up (consider stick-clipping). ¬†Head up and right to beginning of orange and white streaked blocky overhanging terrain. Anchors are in a small roof; can be hard to spot from the ground.
Left bolted line from the Golden Heart anchors. ¬†Use the right set of anchors to belay. ¬†Head up and left from anchors. Liebacks and crimps are the name of the game of this one. ¬†Continuous.

Sickest route at Silver! This is the right bolt line from the top of Golden Heart. Belay from right set of anchors and incorporate a bolt about 5 feet to the right to get the belayer out of the fall zone. Head up and right to blank headwall. Huge moves between nothing holds. Get ready to log some flight time on this one. Does not let up until just below the anchors.

Classic. Marked by the yellow, moss-covered, somewhat heart-shaped block at ¬æ height. ¬†Try not to get wedged into the alcoves...they feel safe to get into, but good luck getting out of them! Use the left set of anchors to top rope this pitch (to avoid a sharp edge). ¬†Both Golden Heart/Bypass and Golden Heart/Direct can be linked, but watch for rope drag.
Starts on a short right-facing arete. Crux off the deck, then a chill 5.8 through incut ledges and a couple of cool geode pockets. Pull out your mantle moves to reach the anchor!
From the main approach trail, this is the first climb you come to under the Rainbow Roof. A fun and safe introduction to Silver Mountain and an excellent first lead.
location: The obvious staircase route.

description: Marked by a crisp vertical section of crack near the first bolt. A low crux leads to smooth sailing all the way to the roof.
Very fun route. Climb a slab to an eye-catching pink/orange headwall right of an arete. Consistent fun climbing on interesting holds. Anchors in roof.
Climb 6 feet up to a rightward diagonal crack that leads up to the anchors of route #21. ¬†Can be dirty?
protection: small to medium nuts and cams

description: Start on a large boulder at the base and pull out your mantle moves right away! Climb ledges to face, and one more mantle to reach the anchors in the roof.

Extension of Silver Gold. From the chains, climb slightly right and strike out through the roof. Monkey your way through spread-out jugs to gain the ar√™te and notch. A large ape index helps tremendously.
Leftmost route under Rainbow Roof. Climb ledges to face, anchors just under roof. ¬†All 3 "Silver" routes (Gold, Sickness, and Sweetness) can be linked, but expect some rope drag.
Currently the leftmost bolted route. Starts just inside a hemlock corridor. A shorty but a goody with a stout, height dependent little roof.
First route left of Rainbow Roof. Tough for first 20 feet; find underclings. Interesting climbing through varied terrain. A 60M rope with stretch just gets you down.

Maybe the best line in the U.P.! ¬†This one is on you right from the ground; recommended stick clipping the first bolt. Rest on a small ledge before tip-toeing your way up a sheer face. ¬†Using your pocket microscope to look for foot holds, trust what little you can find. Technical, thin, and continuous.

route_name: 11.  Between A Block And A Hard Place
description: Super classic! ¬†There is a huge tree next to a nearly flat belay block at the base of this route. Start just right of first bolt and wander your way through the first three bolts to gain a series of large semi detached blocks. Bear hug, lieback, and tip-toe your way to a rest before the crux. After the crux section, a much more chill yet still on ya finish awaits. ¬†Finish in vertical crack right of anchors.

Begin on rightward-angling ramp and climb onto the huge ledge, then continue right to the left-facing dihedral. From there, meander up and left, using blocks and dihedrals. Top out left of cedar tree or use anchors for toprope. This route eats gear!
A shitty, mossy, dirty crack, that with some cleaning actually is fun. Balancing and flaring cracks make this a challenging trad climb.
location: Follow the cliff left past the major roofs, all the way up to the hemlock gully. The route is about 30 feet left of the leftmost bolted line (#2).
protection: Small Cams and one huge hex! ¬†Currently no anchors.

description: Start left of Enigma on 2 not so good edges. ¬†Climb straight up into a worse set of crimps and finally into the crux set of crimps. ¬†Exiting left to the good pocket is V5 but this is the old/original problem that's been around for a long time.
location: Between the two Orange streaks on the face on the Eastern most side of the cliff.

description: Ignore the starting hold for Blind Faith and make difficult campus moves on hard to reach carbonate start holds. ¬†After a few moves the climbing eases and continues up using the same holds as Blind Faith.
location: Climbs face just left of Blind Faith ar√™te.

description: Start on the obvious shelf under the roof at the left side of the great roof. ¬†Climb staight out and then left gaining a stance on the face. ¬†Call it good or TR to the top with 5.9 climbing, much better broulder problem than TR.
location: Across from the Tooth under the left side of the roof on obvious shelf.

description: Move along pockets and decent feet until you're under the V and can reach up to top out (see picture). I call this a V1 compared to other problems around here but if you don't have the reach for the first big move or don't have nice edges on your shoes for the very last move then this will be more tough. If there is a previously established name for this, please leave a comment and I'll edit the name.
location: The first problem you'll find after walking down the stairs at grand ledge (stairs that are left if you're facing the river).
protection: 1 crash pad for the last move

description: Climb the arete and exit stage left.
location: On the west side of the crag about 50 yards from the west stairs.

description: Start left of Doug's Roof on low jug and left sidepull. ¬†Climb straight up heading for the slot at the top of the face, up and left of the "Up Yours" mono and end there.¬† Kind of a high fall from the top but the landing is good.
location: Left most climb of the "overhang".

description: Starts at the base of Doug's roof. Instead of making the move to the jug, move left and traverse under the large ledge using the namesake mono. Continue traversing left and eventually mantle on top of the ledge.
location: Same start as Doug's roof.

description: Sit start on low holds under the black overlap. Stay right of the rounded ar√™te, climb to the jugs or contend with the filthy top out for bonus points.
location: On the "Bouldering Wall" climber's left of the "Slag Traverse"

description: Sit start on the rock in front of the sun and up through the the large crack
location: Look for the sun on the wall. Mid way through the crag.

description: This fun little climb contains lots of large ledges; making it a great beginner climb. Start under a tree growing out of the rock, head left out from under a boulder, then move right and up to the top.
location: This route is located right of the large platform on top of the cliff.  The climb starts just below a tree growing out of the rock. Please be aware of Grand Ledge climbing regulations.
protection: Top-rope - Slings from large trees near the edge of the ledge.

location: Walk West past most of the top roping, the trick is located just left of poison ivy jam and just to the right of a two foot tall "9" or backward "P" etched in the wall. You should see the chalk.

description: Get into the a set of holds around 6' up and launch for the top.
location: The Trick area
The Trick area

description: Sit start with both hands as low as you can go with your left heel hooked and placed in a slight depression. Continue up the arete and top out at the end. A great little warm up.
location: Locate the large pile of rocks that have obviously fallen of the cliff. The largest boulder is the tooth boulder.  It is opposite Ludwig's dude and Resistance.
protection: one pad, there is a boulder right off the start that could really hurt your tail bone.

description: Follow a diagonal rail up and left until it is possible to climb directly to the top of the crag.  Beware the potential for a swinging fall early in the climb.
location: Located on the rightmost end of the crag, begin about 20' uphill from the Enigma corner.
protection: Two large steel eyebolts can be used for TR setup.

description: Stand up on large but slopey (probably sandy) holds and slabby feet. Step up and reach for another set of large holds above. Make a harder move off a sidepull to make it onto less vertical terrain.
location: Right of the obvious protrusion of The Nose. Try to avoid the holds for No Soap on the right.
protection: Long lengths of webbing or static rope to sling trees.

description: Start with Astral projection then connect with stepping out to finish
location: Same start holds as rocket man

description: Climb Rocket Man in the corner then 'step out' to the blank face to the left. Continue upwards through a couple move crux and finish with some easy climbing.
location: Just to the left of Rocket Man (to the right around the corner of Doug's Roof)

description: Long black streak of rock, climber's left of "Saving Grace." Standard traverse is left to right.
location: Climbers left of "Saving Grace"

description: Climb the hand crack to the left of Beginner's Corner.
location: Between Despondency and Beginner's Corner. Right of Doug's section and left of the Big "e" section.
protection: TR can be set by slinging trees. Can also be climbed using the bolt anchors for Beginner's Corner if you're not afraid of a little swing.

location: Start left of the ‚ÄúSAVING GRACE 8/5/27‚Äù engraving.
Astral and Despondency Walls

description: Rocket Man is the right facing hanging dihedral immediately to the right of Ragged Edges.  It is one of the better 5.10 routes at The Ledges.  Start on a sidepull and make a couple of long moves up into the dihedral.  Pop over the lip and work your way up on face holds to the right of the corner.
location: Just right of Ragged Edges and around the corner that is to the left of Despondency.
protection: Easy toprope setup from large trees above the route with webbing or static line.  Tread lightly and use carpet to pad the lip to prevent erosion.  See the Grand Ledge overview page for more information.

description: Start low and to the right of Cowabunga sit start. Traverse left staying low till you end on the start hold of Intimidator
location: Right beneath Cowabunga

protection: Top rope from Doug's roof is fine.

description: The striking and unavoidable overhanging arete to the left of "rocket man". Easy climbing leads to a long reach and a several move crux sequence that would make a burly onsite but is pretty tame when the beta is deciphered.
location: The right arete of the main overhang area. Left of "rocket man" and right of "cowabunga"

description: Start left of the arete and just left of the "9" carved into the rock above. ¬†Climb up through crimps into seem and up into the "9" finishing on the ledge or topping out rather high off the deck.
Same start as Rage except more left into the good pocket on the orange streak and then up. ¬†Solid problem, super bad angled landing makes it rarely cliombed.
location: Mermaid Wall

description: Start on a decent left facing side-pull and crank with the right to a hold just over the mini roof. Find a foot and launch to the jug up and left. Top out.
location: Number 47 "Unknown F" in the Fixed Pin guidebook. 5 feet left of Ballerina

description: Make a long move from a slightly awkard undercling to a pocket then continue up on crimps to the top.  The starting feet are often greasy, but this little route has some interesting movement.
location: On the rightmost end of the cliff about 10' right of the Enigma arete.
protection: Two large eyebolts for top rope setup.

description: Lots of local climbers do laps on this and neighboring routes as a warm up. Down climbing is a good way to practice feet on overhung routes. The crux is working around the two overhangs that are in the first 10 feet of the climb. Follow the crack after the crux to the top.
location: In the Mossy Gully dihedral on the right-hand wall. Start is on a wooden plank. Starts in a inset on the wall, then follows a long crack to the top.

description: Large crack in picture. Climb up crack and onto face to top out.
location: Take the western path down. Poison Ivy Jam is just to the right of The Trick (which is just to the right of a two foot tall "9" or backward "P" etched in the wall).
protection: Toprope setup from trees above the route with webbing. Tread lightly and use carpet to pad the lip to prevent erosion. By standers below should be alert for small falling rocks during setup.

location: Resistance Wall

description: start on the small ledge and move right onto the wall and follow the pigeon poo to the top.
location: about 10 feet left of the small natural spring
protection: A large tree, but better to use chains.

location: Start on Ballerina to the left of Doug‚Äôs Roof

description: Start in the open book and traverse left onto the orange face and climb to the top.
location: Orange face left of the old mine.

route_name: One For the Road AKA One Last Time
description: Follow the best holds to low roof. Crux comes pulling it and the next few moves after that. Maintain through the pumpy upper section on small sandstone jugs. Fun holds abound. Benefits from less traffic than its five neighbors.
location: Line to the left of Brachiator, right of the obvious Mossy Gully corner.
protection: TR with Standard GL rack - Long slings, webbing, cordelette

description: Climb the obvious left-facing protrusion which splits the Nose Buttress. Some people think it looks like a nose?
location: Right of Extension, left of Technical Difficulties and other climbs by Alice's Corner. Right of the massive overhang.

description: Great little slab to practice balance on. The intended way to climb it is without using elbows, arms, or knees to aid you in climbing this slabby rock. Great fun to try out just for kicks. It unfortunately doesn't help warm up your hands for other climbing.
location: Far left side of the crag, on the side of the path opposite of the wall.
protection: Keep your hands ready to stabilize if you do slip. A crash pad and spotter highly recommended so that you do not slide and roll right down the hill and into the river.

description: Climb up the rather blank face, making thoughtful moves on good holds until it levels out higher up. Would be good if it weren't so short.
location: To the right of The Nose and Technical Difficulties, ascending the blankest part of the face left of Alice's Corner.
protection: Toproping from trees, bring lots of webbing or static line.

description: Start at corner of Poison Ivy Jam pillar. Work up corner topping out atop pillar. Do not use crack, only corner and slab holds
location: Next to Poison Ivy Jam. start is on corner of pillar, holds are obvious.
protection: Top rope anchors. Belay should be setup down hill, clearing edge of pillar. Be aware of rope abrasion on top of pillar.

description: Essentially a lieback with some extra holds thrown in, Mossy Gully provides easy cranking up a clean looking corner until it widens into a dirty v-slot. "Clean" meaning the line the crack cuts, not necessarily the grunge covered bottom of the climb, or the muddy base you may encounter.
location: Several climbs left of Potato Chip in the dihedral
protection: Trees, webbing. I recommend slinging it from the side to serve as a dual anchor for Black Buttress and Mossy Gully since a) Mossy Gully protects well with that anchor anyway, and b) you'll avoid the hellacious, Salvador Dali-esque rope grooving that happens lower down on Mossy Gully due to its lower angle.

description: Short for My Little Flakes. Climb the first bit of Chips then move right onto a ledge. Continue from here up to the top on small, friable flakes.
location: Begins as for Chips and moves right.
protection: Sling some trees or climb it using the anchors for Chips.

description: Ascend the face just right of the corner/roof system of Building Blocks, a few feet left of Root Route. Hardest moves could be pulling yourself onto the rock using sloping, sandy holds (and feet which are perennially wet and slimy). Slab your way to the top and the fun moves of the final mantle.
location: Right of Building Blocks Corner, left of Root Route on the big slabby face.
Starts 10 feet right of Comedy of Terrors/Ballerina
protection: 3-4 pads, spotter; perhaps a spotter for your spotter

description: Sit start and climb up and put the left side of the small rof.¬† Top out and walk around on the stairs.
location: 50' right of the Buns Bulge near the west stairs.

description: start on the same ledge as Pigeon Shit and follow the small cracks to the top.
location: 10 feet left of the small natural spring.
protection: A large tree, or chains at the top of the route.

description: Start on the two obvious crimps and smear up the slab. Nice topout and an easy exit on the backside.
location: Around the left of the overhanging roof. About 30 yards from the west stairs.

description: Hand to foot and up the slab. Requires adult assist or the pre-pubescent amygdala of Alex Honnold.
location: Slab directly facing Machine Buns.

description: Start under the huge roof... climbing past very old bolts, pull the roof to the top.
location: Left of the old mine under the largest roof.
protection: Very... very large tree and some webbing!

description: Start is far left, underneath the observation deck, work your way up and traverse right to some smaller holds to your anchor/tree. Use the large tree just to the right of the observation deck.
location: Beneath the observation deck on the left side of the crag, just left of the cave and severe overhang.

description: Same as Karen's Overhang, but this route runs directly upward. Start with a few crimps off of the rocks and work your way upward through a semi-sustained route. This route can become sandy.
location: Just left of the severe overhang, directly in line with large anchor tree (just to the right of the observation deck).

description: Start approx. 10ft right of Doug's roof, on blocky holds.  The crux is moving through these holds and into the easier roof section.  A fall on this lower section will send a top-roper swinging out into space and has the potential for collision with rocks on the ground, hence the name!  Finish on 20ft of ledgy, featured sandstone, angling gently left toward the Doug's Roof anchors.
protection: Two pieces of webbing.  Create anchor at the Doug's Roof chains.

description: Typical Grand Ledge 10b
location: Start 8 feet left of Three Mules on high holds and slopey feet and head straight up. Mantel the ledge and join Three Mules on top.

description: Start on the slab and reach your way up through some easy technical climbing until you get to the arete where the 5.12 crux is to some small edges after a high step. ¬†There is two ways to pull the crux, without the arete ¬†make a reachy move to an edge using a toe hook.
location: In the large open book with carved lower case "e", on the east facing wall, left of "Despondency" on the arete

description: Climbs the blocky arete to the left of Black Buttress.
location: The arete left of Black Buttress, to the right of the trees on Ultimate Bushwhack and the Building Blocks slab.
protection: Typical GL toprope. Can be done with a rope set up for Black Buttress.

description: Same start as Walk on By but instead of going straight up when you get your feet on the face, traverse 4 feet right with a big move. After hitting the move, continue straight up easier rock to the finish.

location: Resistance Wall

description: Large pockets, easy boulder. Great warm up.
location: Far right side of the crag, easy to spot big holds on a blank face.

description: Best Dyno at the park. ¬†Left hand on a decent sidepull and right on an edge, paste your feet and go out right to a big slash. ¬†Match and call it good, gain the face or top out into dirt.

Getting off the ground is the crux on this one.  Contemplate how much soil has washed away here as you either dyno to the first good hold, Batman the rope, or finagle a traverse in from the left.  Thin and sandy holds lead to the top.
location: On the right end of the Ledges, about 15' left of Enigma
protection: Arrange a TR from trees above.  Not the easiest setup.

description: Sit start on the right side of the bulge about 15‚Äô left of the diving board/mantle problem. There is a fist sized crack about 3‚Äô in length below chest level that serves as the start. Eliminate the large diagonal crack near the start and everything above the obvious ledge system traversing it across to the left and topping it out when it peters out.
location: On the Buns Bulge just a few feet down from the western staircase.

description: Just left of "reflections" climb tiny crimps to the top just right of the seam. First ascent put a #4 camalot in under the overhang to limit the swing out with a fall. careful because it can blow easily if not placed perfectly
protection: TR. FA used boulder pads at base and head pointed it.

description: A direct route through the horizontal rail of Three Mules and heading straight to the top.
location: Located on the rightmost end of the crag, begin about 15' uphill from the Enigma corner.
protection: Two large eyebolts used to be present, but now you must use trees or fence posts.

location: Between Conscientious Objection and The Nose on The Nose buttress, right of the massive overhang.

description: Start with a right hand side-pull on the right side of the arete at chest height and your left on a side-pull in some carbonate deposit hold. Step your left foot anywhere you can get a clean foot and match your right heel to your right hand and go.  The problem ends at the very large side-pull.
location: As you walk down the East path to the river and bottom of the cliff, it is the first arete you come to. You can't miss it.

description: Start by doing the low boulder start of Cowabunga then traverse at flake left till you meet Doug‚Äôs then finish it on Doug‚Äôs roof
location: Left of Rocket, to right of Intimidator

description: A bouldery start in a shallow open book... climb to the flaky roof then heel hook to pull out and follow the jugs all the way to the top..... Classic!!
protection: one of the few routes that have (very)old chain anchors....

description: Directly below overlook porch. Work your way up wall, just left of Karen's. Route is from guide book and its name does it justice. The second half of route is fragile sandstone, so watch your holds.
location: Directly below porch. setting anchor too far right will cause a hard swing into poison ivy crack upon fall.
protection: Trees at top above Karen's (2 45-60 foot loops of webbing). Porch does have cement foundation with what appears to be anchor mounts, but requires longer webbing or static line.

location: Just to the right of "Beginner's Climb" aka "Beginner's Corner".
protection: Build an anchor at the top.

location: To the left of the staircase blocks leading up an open book corner. This is The Tooth V1 area.

description: Difficult beginning with a few condensed moves. Get ready for either a dyno or a lengthly lock off to a decent hold in the middle of the route. Find hands on a small crimp, get high feet and pull hard on a crimpy sidepull to finish the rest of the route. Last ten feet are 5.easy
location: The route can be found on the flat wall to the right (and around the corner) from the Doug's Roof overhang section
protection: Trees and roots with webbing for top rope set up.

description: Begin to the right of Doug's Roof on a small arete. Begin by bouldering up to the roof and work crimps slightly to the left.
location: Arete between Doug's Roof and Rocket Man

description: Same start as Despondency Direct, but traverse right and up a series of right-facing sidepulls to bypass the big move to the jug. Once you get to jug, the finish is the same as DD.

Same start as Brakiator. When you get to the ledge traverse right to go up between small Brakiator Crack and larger Potato Chips Crack. Climb to the top avoiding holds on each of the other two climbs.

location: Left of Extension and The Nose on The Nose Buttress. Right of a huge roof which contains Midget's Delight underneath. Pigeon Shit is around the corner to your left.
protection: Typical GL TR set up (trees + webbing)

location: Starts as for Ballerina Direct.
protection: 3-4 pads and a really good spotter, and maybe a spotter for your spotter.

description: Start at the side pull and crimp just below Ballerina (green tick marks shows start) Use slippery feet under you and crank up and right (red ticks shows holds). Crux is just over the lip, holding on to a sloper and throwing for a small crimp.
location: Route is between Doug's roof and potato chips. After topping down climb potato chips to get down.
protection: A pad or two, spotter is always nice.

description: Follow the flakes to the right of potato chips.
Start as for Building Blocks and transition out of the quickly onto the left (orange) face and through the small roof.
location: Located left of building blocks and right of Peek-A-Boo. This is the farthest left area of climbing within the terraced belaying area.
protection: Top Rope setup with webbing off trees (same as for Peek-A-Boo).

description: Start at the left of the large crack in the Buns Bulge.¬† Climb right and when the crack ends top it out.
location: Buns Bulge

description: Eliminate - Start on the left of the Buns Bulge low below the obvious ledge bisecting the bulge. ¬†ELiminate the lede climbing low into a deep/good pocket then top out.
location: Buns Bulge

description: On the left side of the Buns Bulge on the huge ledgeis the obvious start. ¬†Paste the feet somewhere underneath and jump for the top. ¬†Going out left to the lowere ledge or using any other starting holds other than the ledge itself is not part of the problem, although they're still fun.
location: Buns Bulge

description: start in the open book and follow the thin crack to the blocky finish.
location: right of Peek-a-boo

description: The next top rope groove left of Potato Chip, Brachiator starts blocky before blanking out. After facing this holdless horror, there are some pumpy jugs leading to the top.
location: Left of Potato Chip

description: Same start as Walk on By. ¬†After the first couple of moves, go up into a crimp and out onto the arete finishing in the crescent moon. ¬†The Walk on By jug is off as the problem climbs the arete straight up.
location: Left side if teh Great Roof

protection: Webbing, trees. I recommend using the anchor setup on Black Buttress for it and Mossy Gully as less wear results on Black Buttress.

location: Between intimidator and cowabunga. If you‚Äôre under the red spot, too far left.
Start on top of the pedestal in the corner
protection: New, safe bolts at the top of the route.  Be sure to lay carpet over the cliff where your ropes are going to rub the rock...

location: Ballerina Bulge
Ballerina Bulge

description: Stack pads, use stump, or jump start to a two hand rail, pull through the open book, walk over to chips and climb down. Could be a bad fall on the retaining wall be careful. A dirty and wet direct start begins awkwardly a bit lower on a two handed undercling/sidepull, and goes at V5
location: Between the main overhang area and "chips", at the retaining wall
Start Just to the right of Rocket man with the arete on your right.

description: A short and fairly easy climb in a sandy dihedral with a few chopped holds.  Makes a good kids climb.  If I remember correctly, the name "Alice Andruson" is carved into the rock near the base of this route.
location: At the top of the pedestal just left of the mermaid carving.
protection: Sling trees at top with long webbing for top rope.

description: There is a sloper rail that is in between two entrances that goes about v3. There is a Dyno from the slopper rail that goes straight up to a good ledge, then goes left toward the roof. One of the entrances has features all around it for endless variations.
location: This is an old school building on the block. E Seminary St and Horatio. The North side, or Seminary St side of it offers some interesting buildering problems. Watch out for the locals across the street and befriend them with rap music if you have a boom box
protection: Bouldering pad and police look outs.

description: There are three autobelays on this climbing wall and a padded mat surrounding the floor of it. The vertical fiberglass wall sports many rock-like features and is updated four times a year. The grades range from 5.4 to 5.11
location: 800 W Lawrence Ave, Charlotte, MI 48813
Literally the only crack on the east face of the Argo Bridge. It's a slightly left-leaning finger crack on the left side of the mural. A few feet left of the mysterious bolt...
protection: A single bolt at eye level and small cams (

location: Follow area directions; West-most cliff band with a cave-like opening. Follows the line through the cave and up the flat rectangular face.
protection: Sand; a crash pad may help protect from tree stumps at the cave/face transition.

description: SDS on two small crimps. Some powerful slaps will take you into the middle of Swiss Rolls
location: Right of Swiss Rolls

description: Stand start matched on an undercling crimp rail. A few tenuous moves lead to an improbable lock-off crux guarding a mellow top out.
location: Center of the east face on Bouldre #1

description: SDS on a sharp flake. Climb left through a few sloper rails before entering an exciting crux sequence with two sweet pockets. Top out. A quality, sustained line.
location: Right side of the east face on Boulder #1

description: SDS matched on a rail low on the left ar√™te. Ride sweet edges on the epic refrigerator feature to the top out.
location: Left side of the east face on Boulder #1

description: SDS with two crimps. Climb up and left through sloping rails and a few pockets, topping out as for Mouse Trap
location: Between Red Velvet and Plush

description: SDS matched on the prominent rail. Climb the face and top out.
location: South face of Boulder #1. Left of The Golden Fleece

description: Start as for Leather face, but head left through some slopers before topping out.
location: South face on Boulder #1. Left of Leather Face.

description: SDS matched on a flake. Climb edges to what might be the best jug in all of Michigan. Top out.
location: South face on Boulder #1. Left of Blue Suede.

description: SDS with right hand in the four-finger pocket and left on a side-pull. Trend right on the sloping lip before topping out in the dirty dihedral.
location: Left of Ball Dragon Extension

description: Start as for Marshmellow, but head left up the face with neat edges to a top out.
location: Right side of the south face on Boulder #1

description: Start with left hand in a four-finger pocket and right on a nearby edge. Trend left on sloping edges into the start of Ball Dragon.
location: Left of Ball Dragon
protection: A thin pad would be nice

description: SDS matched on a sloper rail. Weave under the tree with similar features to a funky crux before the top out. Dabby.
location: Southwest corner of Boulder #1
protection: A thin pad might be nice

description: Same start holds as Ribeye (sandstone crimps). Traverse left through fun and interesting moves before topping out. Same exit as Fudge Rounds (V3-4).
SDS on your favorite edge of the incredible rib feature. A few powerful moves link into the top section of Ribeye.
location: South face on Boulder #2. Left of Ribeye

description: SDS on two triangular crimps. Climb over the bulge and left through the sweet rib features to a mellow top out.
location: Right side of the south face on Boulder #2

description: SDS with hands on the prominent shelves. Climb left on the sloping lip before topping out at the apex. Very flowy and surprisingly pumpy.
location: Left end of the southwest face on Boulder #2.

description: Start as for Fudge Round, but climb right into the rib feature before surmounting the bulge and topping out.
location: Right of Fudge Round

description: SDS matched on an edge near the left ar√™te. Climb up and left through side pulls to a powerful top out sequence. Detached blocks are off.
location: Southwest corner of Boulder #2

description: Start as for short rib, but climb left through some sharp crimps before riding big ledges to the top out.
location: Left of Ribeye

description: SDS with left hand on a low slot and right on the ledge around the right ar√™te. A few moves of powerful compression lead to a crux dead-point just before the top out. Detached blocks are off.
location: Right side of the overhanging face next to Fudge Round

description: Stand start with a left hand undercling and right in a pocket. Follow the line of pockets left and up the slab.
location: Right side of the east face of Boulder #2

description: Start as for Cosmic Brownie, but head left up the overhanging face on small, sharp edges. Hard crimping on a 35 degree overhang, classic. Detached blocks are off.
location: Left of Cosmic Brownie

first_ascent: Bush wached by MG, JL, EL, and PP
description: Basically a 5th class gully. ¬†At the pod head left up along a never ending shitty very chossy 4th class ramp/catwalk, solid pro is hard to find.¬† A direct line out the top of the pod is possible when dry, might redeem the route a bit, maybe? ¬†Climbing above the pod is

protection: One set of wires and single set of cams to #4.

first_ascent: Carter Stritch, Kendra Stritch, Samantha Glowacki
description: An adventure route that starts in a crack on a steep slab and then does an airy traverse left to a large ledge with little for pro.  continue past the ledge up to a belay in the shrubs.  from this belay, find your way up to the top on vegetated slabs.
location: A couple hundred feet to the right of The Stritch Route. The start of the route is located at 46.654136, -89.51511

description: The route accends a long slab starting in a left facing corner for about 30 feet into a leftward horizontal traverse putting you at the base of a 100ft crack system. The crux comes right after the traverse. Well protected and loaded with holds this route has a little of everything!! There is a 4th class pitch if your starting from the bottom to get to the starting ledge. I would recomend rapping in and leading back out to avoid the loose scree at the base of the cliff.
location: Climb is located lookers left on the cliff. Long clean slab split by a long moderate crack.
protection: No fixed anchors, Takes standard rack of cams and stoppers

description: Start at the small rock pedestal/platform and climb  up between a tree and a bush, with athe tree on your right.  Angle up and left through a slab section with good feet to a groove and then skirt left around the small roof. You will find a small belay ledge at 45m on climbers left.  A #3 and #4 can be used at the belay. From the belay, go up some slightly vegetated slab to the top passing over a long ledge with some small bushes to sling, 30m. Belay from trees in the woods.
location: Far west end of the cliff.  Scramble up 30 feet to a small platform great for flaking out the rope. Start of route is located at 46.65404, 89.51511 As of September 2017 there were small rock cairns at the top and bottom of the route.
protection: standard double rack. A #3 and #4 Camalot can be used at the belay ledge.

description: Shares 2 pitches with "Book of Saturdays", but removes the first pitch and the long traverse.    Pitch 1- Starts on a large slab with thin cracks for protection, then traverses over to large grass filled crack.  Pulling grass can reveal the pro.  Large cams or large hexes are a must.  Wild country #6? .  Pitch 2- Belay stance is to the left of the major grassy chimney of the second pitch; Use small nuts to protect belay.  Look for stuck Omega Pacific nut to find out where to set up belay.  Follow the large chimney up to the roof.  Some protection can be found by venturing out onto the slab, but stay mostly to the chimney.  Crux can be found right before the cave area.  Pull a couple of exposed moves, and Metoliuschimney up a large overhanging crack. Traverse into the cave area.  Watch the loose rock, and maintain your footing.  Pitch 3-Belay from the cave area; protecting this can be tricky, but there should be a protectable crack out and around the corner of the cave.  Look for a stuck nut to give you and idea where to place.  Head out the cave and around the arete.  Easy pulls up to the top of the climb.  Top out and enjoy the view!
location: See description
protection: Bring a lot of gear.  A few large cams would not hurt as "O Sh*t pieces".  Metolius flaring nuts are extremely helpful.  They hold perfectly int he smaller cracks.

description: Two anchors to start, higher middle of bald spot . ¬†One ring anchor at the back of the major horizontal break, just after a 12' free air rappel. ¬†One ring anchor when it really starts slabbing off till the next drop onto the final slab. ¬†Watch for poison ivy at the bottom of this whole sector. ¬†Two anchors will be place 2020 to make each station a set.
location: Anchors from the top start on the lowest bald spot of rock on the far east side, but not at the end of the bluff.

first_ascent: Cleaned by AL, NL, GP, and PP
description: Starts on a very distinct cleanish crisp 10' wide 60' long chunk of slab, optional belay over the top.¬† Continue on more slab into a wedge area where a right facing dihedral starts, belay here. ¬†Climb dihedral for 30 and head up and left on face and ledge to a clump of junipers, belay.
location: About 75' right of center rap route.

description: This route is in the vein of adventure climbing the rock is dirty and some people might not think the rock to be to quality but I enjoyed the route. it stars on a long slab to a long 3rd class ledge were we belayed for a small part. you then climb through a chiminey to a corner that leads to a cave the rock here is sketch and is also the crux of the route. try and arange a belay in the cave then exit out onto the face and finish with a 100 foot pitch . walk off along ways either way.
location: the central largest section of cliff
protection: standard trad rack to a #1 camolot lots of small pro

description: Located on the west (left) side of the cliff band. The route tops out to climber's left of a large juniper bush right at the top of the cliff, where the terrain starts going steadily downward. Starts on a small shelf just left of a tree and ascends through a short sheer slab with shallow vertical grooves, into a crack system 10 feet left of an orange, left-facing dihedral. Crux is just right of a permanently wet spot halfway up. Scramble up vegetated ledges at the top to anchor on a tree. Fun route with good pro. Still some loose rock.
protection: Mostly small cams and stoppers with a nice #3 cam placement at the crux.

description: This route assend's the mid crag access rap stations. ¬†Overgrown. ¬†Not far climbers left of .....¬† slab start.
Follow the Berke's Kitchen, but branch off to the left on the third bolt.
This climb follows the arete just left of Leaving Tracks. ¬†It has not yet been redpointed.
This climb has not yet been redpointed.

Climb the 5.7 hand crack until you each a horizontal break about 10-15 up.  Travers right about 8 feet until your under a small bulge, mantel up to access the small finger crack.  Climb to ledge.  Continue up though a small dihedral to the top.

This route is on the far right of the wall.  Climb up the small right facing corner to gain a ledge.  Climb up and right under the roof. Undercling and lie back to gain the top.  To continue walk left and climb the wide flake to the tree
location: Far right of the wall.  uneven belay

description: This is the most distinct line on the wall. Climb up on a solid flake to gain the hand crack.  Use face holds and crack to gain a ledge. Then continue up on easy 5th class to the top.  Large trees for TR or belay
location: The most distinct crack on the left side of the wall.  walk or rapp of.

description: This is a great beginning leader route. ¬†Climb the obvious corner/crack system. ¬†Place gear in the crack at the top then stem (crux) to the top out.

This is a great wandering climb over a scantily stting block. ¬†Follow the crack along the right side of the block then pull up to mantle the block. ¬†From here, follow the crack to the top. ¬†Some micro cams to protect the thin crack at the top would be a good idea.
This Route also require's some bigger cams. ¬†Follow the jagged crack as it goes from an undercling to a big pull (crux move) to top out.
This climb follows a series of ramps and medium cracks.
This is an excellent crack climb complete with liebacks and jams. ¬†You'll nee a few bigger pieces to lead this one.
An excellent beginning leader route. ¬†Begin at the crack to the right of the last climb.
A wonderful sport route. ¬†Stay to the left of the crack system (Jack 2001).
Start in the corner directly above the pile of porcupine crap. ¬†Use the crack in the corner, then work over the right onto the face. ¬†Bring small to medium nuts and cams.
This face just left of the prominent crack (March Madness) has not yet been redpointed.
Great warm up route. Left is easiest, right is hardest.
The defenite crux is just after clipping 3rd bolt. Work through a technical sequence on small crimps with almost no where to put feet. Watch out for loose rock in the first 10'.
Stay out of the Stairway To Heaven crack!!! ¬†Climb heavily featured face/slab, wandering slightly, through a sea of crisp edges and sidepulls. ¬†Sometime's the top seeps. ¬†Can be lead trad.
Follow a broken, zig-zag crack up as it widens to the anchors. ¬†A smorgasbord of different techniques and movements on this one!

This climb follows a nice thin slab to a crux dead point to a sloppy ledge with a jug on the far right (direct route and hardest). You may also follow the route left towards a piton and a awkward body jam to gain the fourth bolt.
Start just left of crag practice anchors. ¬†Angle up and right making bigger moves off pretty good holds. ¬†Crux at top, but holds where they need to be.

A zig zag route for sure. ¬†Angle up and right till you get to the 2nd bolt then up and left then back right. ¬†Holds right where you want them. Very continuous route. ¬†Seeps between 2nd and 3rd bolts.
This climb goes up a sustained overhanging wall to crux move on a pinch and small finger crack to pull the roof. Move to jugs to gain the anchors.
Left most route at Suicide. Large flaring crack with decent protection. Watch for loose rock.
Mostly continuous crack on right side
location: Right side of crag

description: Three cruxes of 5.10 for a 80 foot pitch. sustained with one good rest at the bottom. the route follows the rappel line in the picture
location: Pinacle area
protection: a boulder at the top can be slung and there is two stopper slots #10-12.

description: A nice traverse with a bad landing
location: at the base of the pinacle

description: Start as for Disco Lemonade, but instead of following the ar√™te, climb straight up and into the slab.
location: Left ar√™te of the 45 degree boulder directly downhill of Pump'n the Gardner.

description: Right route on the wall.
Middle route on the wall

Mystery Jam is the obvious line at Isabella.  Start on the face to a cruxy throw.  Work your way up to the beautiful crack.  Continue up past a few committing jug moves to easier ground.  The top is marked by a fixed nut and pin.
location: This route is at Issabella, not Palmer.  Continue driving down Isabella (past the turn to Slugg's Bluff) for 3 more minutes.  Take your first left on a dirt road, then your next right.  Drive though a field to the cliff.  First major route you will encounter

description: Kinda of obscure but once you are on it an awesome adventure! Trverse the lip of the roof with sidepulls, heel and toe hooks to a hold on the slab alowing passage to the top of the pinicale.
location: Just downhill from pumping the gardner on a tall boulder with a pinicale top.
Left side of the 45 degree boulder directly downhill of Pump'n the Gardner

description: Start crouched with an undercling for the left hand and large edge for the right. Climb the ar√™te, topping out just shy of the apex.
location: Left ar√™te of the 45 degree boulder directly downhill of Pump'n the Gardner
protection: Flat but rocky landing. At minimum, 2 pads and a spotter

description: 10 feet right of #8. ¬†Head up and right only to traverse hard left just under a small roof. ¬†Exit on the left side of the roof and punch it straight to the top.

This route climbs a flake on the left side of a dihedral for twenty feet. Then the route climbs a few small ledges heading into two small roofs. Climb around the left of the first roof and then to the right of the second roof ending at the rap rings.
location: The route is the second route from the left of Open Book. Between Lucky Corner and Open Book there is a 7 shaped crack. It should be in a corner with a small roof. From the ground you can see rap rings on this route.
protection: .3-3 cams and a set of nuts.

description: Left leaning fingers to hand crack that zig back right a bit then straight to the top.
The slabby east side of the spire.
Start on the left/south side of the spire and head for the arete.
Starts 5' right of route #2 and ends up merging with route #2 at 2/3 height.

route_name: 7.  That was Zen, This is Tao
description: Classic. ¬†Consistently hard.
Just the the left of unknown crack, where the crack splits tend left.  Climb up to 3rd class and to a roof.  Go right, left, or straight...the choice is yours
location: just left of 1st crack
protection: a set up nuts, up to a #3/4

description: Start up a left leaning ramp into sustained, technical climbing through a couple bulges to a crux near the top.
location: Furthest right route at Slugg's.

description: One of the furthest climbs to the right, this is a popular crack.  Mainly top roped, is a great trad lead as well. Start up the easy 5th class ramp to an off width. The crack spits, climb right.  There are crux sections, have fun! Then climb up to easyer ground.
location: Follow the cliffs edge from left to right.  One of the last climbs found on the wall.

description: Same start as #17 except when the crack Y's take the left crack around the arete. ¬†Trends up and left most of the way until the last bit when you head straight up for the topout.
Wall just right of Big Chimney. ¬†Multiple ways to weave up through the face. ¬†Long and scenic.
Start 5' left of Big Chimney. ¬†Climb straight up till you hit the roof. ¬†Exit a little left of center through roof and weave through another more manageable roof to anchors just over the top.
Starts 15' left of the Big Chimney. ¬†Head straight up to an overhanging alcove. ¬†Continue straight up out of the alcove to the top.
Right side of slab.
Left side of slab.
The route is the off width crack in a dihedral. It starts with wide fists and eventually widens in to a chimney.
location: This route is towards the end of the crag just before the bolted sport route and chimney. It is after the only route with rappel rings.
protection: A .75, 1, 3, 4, 5 (or another 4). Bring small nuts for an anchor.

description: This route is a fun short crack that goes from fingers to fists that has a decent number of face holds. The crack starts out on a large block and then gradually gets wider at the top.
location: This is the very first route at the crag on the far left side. It is just before a route with a slightly overhanging hand crack for the start.
protection: A single rack from .3-3 and a set of nuts.

description: Sit start low on the left-center side to the right on the crack.
location: Above the traverse to the right when facing the traverse.

description: There are a couple good lines (with some cross still) on this boulder. It is located above the traverse.
location: Above the traverse.

description: Upper body dependent problem with some heel hooking. Sit start on northwest side of boulder (lake on climbers left and parking lot on right side over hill) and traverse to left 6-7 moves then top out. Legs are under overhung boulder when not heel hooking.
location: Park in black rocks parking lot. Go around hill to left in back of parking lot and come out on black rocks until you come to the middle. This boulder is lakeside behind a large boulder in the middle of black rocks.
protection: Crash pad optional (this problem is a lowball traverse)

description: The test piece boulder problem for the Marquette area. It was done in the early 90's by Mike Moss at maybe V4, but a key hold had broken and it took another 4 years for Josh to piece it together. Start far right on your bum. With your hands on the lip of the overhang, drop below the lip and traverse 20 ft to your left till the overhang comes to an end and top out. Good luck.
location: Before reaching the black rocks jumping area, there will be a big dirt parking are on your right. Park here and take the trail over or around the mound at the back of the parking area and down to the lake. Walk straight out on the rocks till you'd have to jump in, then turn to your left to find a nice secluded overhanging area.

description: SDS on good ledge. Move up on fun slopes and crimps. Top out. Good landing, but sometimes wet at base.
location: If looking at the traverse, it is down and to the right.

description: Rock quality is not the best, but it isn‚Äôt bad. Start in the water and climb up pretty good holds to top out. Jump in and repeat.
location: In the cove between before the normal Black Rocks Cliff jumping spot. Easiest to get to by walking from the traverse towards the black rocks (cliff jumping area).

description: The route goes straight up the middle of the back face of the Pinnacle. Start below the right hand side of the big ledge, mantel up and move slightly right to climb for two moves up a column like feature. Using the undercling, move out left onto the face and climb straight up. the last move is the crux
protection: sling the small block to the climbers right, and place a yellow alien (or something similar) in a finger crack directly at the top of the main route on the other side.

description: Fairly continuous crack on left side
location: Left side of crag
drive 1-2 minutes down the dirt road, park in a pullout on the right.  Should be visiable from the road in winter/early spring/late fall
protection: pad, be careful of the loose block that will totally crush you if it finally goes when your on it.

description: Begin by the small old tree stump (disappearing with the years) and work straight up to a faint left-diagonal crack then straight up to the top.  The big holds you reach from the ground are about all you get once you step on the rock.
location: Look for the short old tree stump at the base.  It is not very big.

description: Begin directly below a small triangular niche (bomber) about 15 ft up.  Crank up to the niche then rightward & up to the top on thin sharp edges.  Variation (5.10a) ¬ñ same start, but avoid the triangular bomber by moving straight past it on the left.
location: See Topo sketch

description: Up the thin crack and series of small ledges then right along upper flake to top.  The crux involves moves getting to the big diagonal crack that splits most of the face.  Left is the standard warm-up at the crag.
Begin beneath the large triangular niche and work up and to the right of it to pick up a small corner to the top. (Variation - harder - go directly up through the large triangular niche).
location: See Topo Sketch

description: Start on the bump below and a step right of the small triangular pocket about 12 ft up.  Go relatively direct up the face to the right of the triangle pocket.  (Did you really try to use that Triangle?!)
location: See Topo sketch

description: Contrived route between "Left" and "Center".  Holds on "Left" are OFF for right hand and foot while holds on "Center" are OFF for left hand and foot.  If you use a couple of sharp crimpers with the right hand, you are probably ON the route.
location: See Topo sketch

description: Slither the green stuff four feet up to the small ledge by the pine tree then walk the line directly up to the group of three pines at the top of the crag.
protection: Top rope off trees. Protection unknown.

description: Begin at the boulder that is splotched with white quartz. Climb up to the crimpy slab and finish at the ‚Äúsmiling‚Äù Pine tree.
protection: Top rope off trees. Protection unknown.

description: Start in an alcove on the short vertical face. Climb up slabby section, past a blueberry patch on climber‚Äôs right, and finish in the large trough.
protection: Top rope off trees. Protection unknown.

description: Start in front of the large pine tree, climb the short green slab then pass the small tree three quarters of the way up on the left hand side. ¬†Stay left of the inverted V notch apex of the route Doin‚Äô Time.
location: Start in front of large pine tree near the left side of the crag.

route_name: Get Busy Livin' or Get Busy Dyin'
description: Start in the same alcove as the beginning of Guilty as Charged on the short vertical face. Climb up several small overhangs, past a blueberry patch on climbers left, and finish just right of the trough.
protection: Top rope off trees. Protection unknown.

description: Same start as Walk the Line then move left and up toward the upper overhang that forms the right side of the inverted V notch. Take the overhang directly to tenuous friction on the final slab.
location: Same as Walk The Line.

description: Climb the short vertical face of broken boulders to gain the easy slab to the top. ¬†Finishes at the large pine tree to climbers right of the ‚Äúsmiling‚Äù pine tree.
protection: Top rope off trees. Protection unknown.
Top rope off one medium and one small tree above.

description: One of the best routes at Marquette Mountain. Can be easily top roped but also makes a nice trad lead. The crux is pulling the first lip and the gear is tricky. Be careful and have fun.
location: this climb is on the right wall with 5 angular cut overhangs
protection: toprope off trees or nuts and small cams.

description: You'll have to clean this one again befoe you can even find the holds. Shorty but a goody.
Starts just right of leftward leaning ledge system. ¬†Climb straight up.¬† Dirty!

location: This is one of the more intimidating (i use this word loosely) faces on the wall. ¬†This is on the upper section, just left of the Jolly dihedral.

route_name: 8. Clip It, Mix It, Or Kiss My @#!
description: A cruxy start up past the 2nd bolt. Pull a bouldery 5.10 start with no feet and clip the bolt (or stick clip). Keep climbing up though the obvious crack, up and right to the chains.
location: This is just right of the unknown 11 on the upper section of Glenda's Pile.  A obvious cave makes the start of this route
protection: 5b's + anchors. ¬†Trad, fingers to hands, big set of balls to first placement.

description: More straight forward. ¬†Big incuts, funky slab walk, and chill ending make for a fun adventure.
Another Chutes And Ladders style route. ¬†Stick clip first bolt.
The name says it all. ¬†Hope your climbing and mantling on sloping glass holds skills are up to speed. ¬†Gotta nut up a bit on this one! ¬†Still a good route.
~10ft giant steps in the wall to the left of whirly dirly area.
First line on your left when you come out of the assess gully. ¬†Dihedral/face with a small crack section before ledge. ¬†Staircase to the anchors.
By far the best route of the crag! ¬†Super delicate slab, consistent all the way to the anchors! ¬†Anchors can be accessed by scrambling carefully up right side of slab.

Starts inside of the left facing dihedral/chimney. Climb to a good ledge then utilize both cracks to a somewhat ackward top out. You can TR this climb by climbing Dirty Girl and moving up left to it's anchors. ¬†She's called Green for a reason, do the crag a favor and take a spin on it, it does clean up!
Starts where base of trail meets cliff. ¬†Climb through left leaning diaganal break, ending over bulge to slab.
There are a couple of variations that go relatively straight up the lower face, initially on small holds, to ledge hopping higher.
Begin to the right and follow an easy ramp up to the "Notch" then straight up.
location: Far right end of the Blade Runner overhang section.

description: Variation start to Overhang Notch.
protection: TR off trees. ¬†Has been led Trad. Lower slab not protected.

description: Climb up to and through the overhang‚Äôs right side staying left of the notch.
Tricky moves under the overhang to a jug over the lip.
Climb right of Blade Runner up to and over the overhang.

Begin under low notch, make a few moves rightward then back left on the slab up to the "Blade". Watch your fingers on the "Blade" as you move into the V-notch. There is a "rattler" rock in the crux section that appears to be securely wedged, but exercise caution.

route_name: 23  Far Right area and Walter's Route
description: Unrecorded Variations have been done on the Far Right end (mostly mid-5th class and harder). Also, after a gap and access gulley, there are a few boulder problems on a short steep red wall and one short difficult route ‚Äì Walter‚Äôs Route (5.Hard) ‚Ä¶ further right.
location: Far Right area.

description: Go up the slab to the roof. Pull the roof directly. A small hold on the left edge of the Roof is useful.
location: Right Side Roof area.
protection: TR off trees.  Possibly a couple of sketchy Trad gear spots.

description: Slither up the slab crack then either jam the crack under the overhang (Spider) or reach far right across the gap to a good edge (Fly).
location: Spider and the Fly area.

description: Right of Four (Five) Overhangs. Follow a line of least resistance fairly straight up. Rating is not confirmed. Gear placements unknown.
location: Right of Four (Five) Overhangs

description: Begin directly under low notch below Blade Runner and climb straight up to the "Blade". Crux is moving from the notch onto the slab below the Blade. The angled ramp on the right at the start is "off".
Meander up the slab to the short hand crack in an upper block.
location: Right of Four (Five) Overhangs area.
protection: Some trad gear possibilities in spaced places.

description: Up the right edge of the slab and direct to the top.
location: Randy's Quivering Sphincter Area.

description: Up the slab then through the difficult notch. Alternatively, one can begin on Route 17 and traverse left to the notch to finish on Route 16.
location: Randy's Quivering Sphincter Area.

description: Begin between trees to the right of Classic Crack area. There are multiple variations up to a slab then a short upper face.
location: Easy Slab variations area.

description: Start on Classic Crack. Above the bulge, move left on the ledge and climb the thin face. All of the crack is ‚Äúoff‚Äù. It is difficult to top out without moving into Classic Crack.

Begin in a shallow corner, negotiate a bulge to a ledge then finish up a thin crack. The bulge is the crux, but topping out can be sketchy. The route is leadable on Trad gear. Variations exist on the left and right sides of the upper crack.
location: On the left side of the crag, right of Midway Direct. See diagram photo.
protection: Toprope off trees. The route can be led with Trad gear.

description: Begin by the tree and follow the diagonal ledge up to the big hanging flake. Continue up the right side of the flake. Watch for swings on top rope.
Go straight up moderate rock to the upper steep slab. Crimp up the middle of the slab.
Start under the bulges. Balance up to a good ledge then go over the bulges directly.
location: Approx. 20 ft right of Overhang Notch.

description: Climb over angled bulges and diagonal cracks.
location: left of Blade Runner.

description: Obvious crack witih large open space. Tons of loose rock here. Dangerous. Avoid.
protection: top rope or could possibly trad

description: Shares holds with broken glass, but shifted just to the right. Crimps and small feet to start, then gain a right hand up to a finger hold sloping left sort of a gaston, and then right hand again, with or without inching feet up, on the top out. Be careful if topping out as some rocks may be loose.
location: Just to the right of broken glass

first_ascent: I'm guessing this has been climbed before- anybody know? Name of line?
location: Roughly the center of the face.

description: Stand start right crimp and left flat faced hold. Right hand up to sloper. Left hand upside down to finger crack, up to larger holds for top out.
location: Obvious crack on the right side of the wall

description: large obvious flake that could likely be climbed 5.12? Sounds like a drum- I'd avoid this as the whole flake could pop off. Also looks of loose rock I cleaned on rappel.
protection: Top rope or could possibly trad. Danger of entire large flake coming off. Avoid.

description: Starts in the middle of the formation. ¬†Once of the ground it's hard to even let go. ¬†Compact and stout.
Starts at the lowest point of the crag and follows the ridge/slab to anchors up past Zebras anchors.
The shorter right side of the main Bud's Wall.
Face between Carbo and Protein. Get your micro crimp on. Hasn't scene a first assent as far as I know. ¬†Hasn't been climbed in forever. Any taker's?

This is the classic local test piece. ¬†The route is slightly overhanging with positive holds but a sustained cryptic longish crux. This climb can be real pumpy due to its overhanging nature and is a great workout. ¬†An area must do!
This crack climb is well protected. Starting thin and flaring to larger size by the top it provides a fun little lead with varied gear.
location: Approach via the Wolfs Den area. Climb is on the far left of main cliff
protection: Large tree for toprope anchor. Likely good pro for trad if desired.
