description: Follow the low angle slab with a large broken crack on the right. The crux of this climb is at the start. This climb really is nice and easy like cheese and crackers. Goes trad as well. Equipped by P.P.
location: This climb is just in front of the large boulder at the bottom of the crag and the third bolted route over from the last bolted climb on the right side of the crag.

description: First route right of talus. This is a great climb with an arsenal of fun moves and interesting holds. This climb really goes well after some "Cheese and Crackers".
location: This route is located just to the left of "Cheese and Crackers" and just in front of the large boulder at the base of the crag.

description: Bottom right of talus. The prominent buttress with a few bulges/roofs. Starts from boulders and traverses right and up through notch in roof/dihedral. Slab to another roof just below junipers.
Delicate slab. ¬†Trust your feet, cuz your hands ain't great. ¬†Equipped by L.P. and P.P.
Start at the base of Greg's Sonic Boom but head immediately right and up. ¬†Stay mostly straight up line, wandering just a little. ¬†Equipped by L.P. and P.P.
Furthest left bolted line. ¬†Great textured slab. ¬†Thank god ledge just below anchors.
location: Left side of talus field.

description: Right most route at AAA. Trail to top is just right of start. Short start leads to a diagonal sloped ledge. Though provoking slab leads to fun top.
Great beginner/little person route. ¬†Left side of slab. Many variation's and lots of room to wander.
Rarely climbed blocky corner to slab. Worth setting up with the other TR's nearby.
Short tecnical face to powerful mantel move. Fun slab to top
Left seam route on mini flat iron formation. ¬†Face to Slab. ¬†Great textures.

Start on land ledge between swamp and short vertical face. ¬†Mantel onto ledge above face then ascend another short face to a slab. ¬†Bring a couple hundred feet of webbing to set this one. Old school.
Follow a nice juggy start on a slightly overhanging wall to the small roof crux at the top of the route. Two ways to finish. Watch out your rope dosen't end up in the pond when you pull the rope.
location: This climb is the farthest right bolted route at AAA.

description: Thin steeper start leads to thinner crimps with some technical balance higher up.
Thin positive incut crimps down low lead to jug haul higher up. Good varied climbing. May be challenging onsight without the chalk highway to lead the way.

Dirty, body width, flaring crack immediately left of left most bolted line(Greg's Sonic Boom). ¬†Doesn't see much traffic. ¬†Takes good gear, but did I mention dirty. ¬†Do the crag a favor and get on it to keep it clean.
Left side of the small Bud's Wall face.
location: Basically you can wander whereever on the short Bud's Wall face. This route would keep mainly on the left side.

description: The middle and tallest section of the main Bud's Wall face.
Start right of arete and continue following it while using the face to the right. ¬†Watch out for pendulum.
** STAY OFF *** ¬†Bolts are suspect!!! ¬†So many holds have broke off it might not be a viable route anymore anyway. ¬†Historic route.
Farthest route right on main wall. ¬†Multiple boulder problems. ¬†Time to get creative with this one.
Start on rock platform. ¬†Consistently hard and a bit awkward. ¬†Clipping the chains can be exciting.

I have been informed that the leftmost bolted line goes at around 5.11, although I can not confirm this. I have named it Sugga sugga and listed the route at 5.11 until someone can confirm or suggest a name, grade, bolter, etc.
location: Located on the main face.

description: SDS with slots under the mini roof. Using the unique fin feature, some fancy footwork, and a little burl will get you over the bulge to the mellow top out.
location: The small cave on the lower outcrop of Man in the Chair

description: SDS with underclings in the roof. Surmount the bulge and layback the in-cut crack. Top out.
location: Crack on the left side of the roof in the lower outcrop.

description: Stand start matched on the undercling flake, climb nice ledges to the top. Neat holds.
location: Lower outcrop. The flakes left of Ladyfingers
protection: A small pad if you can squeeze it.

description: SDS with left hand on a side-pull around the ar√™te and right on a low pinch. Compress the blank feature before making a powerful throw at the lip.
location: The beautiful prow feature left of Galactose

description: SDS with left hand on the ar√™te and right on a low side-pull. A powerful move lies between you and the mantel.
location: Left of Fructose.

description: SDS matched on the ar√™te. Climb up, getting into a bit of compression before topping out.
location: Left of Sucrose

description: SDS matched on the right end of the lip. Utilize some body tension and traverse left until reaching a sizable in-cut near and mantling it out.
location: Right of Galactose.

description: SDS low on the left side of the boulder. Ride the sloping lip, topping out as for Maltose.
location: Left of Maltose

description: Start crouched, compressing the overhanging refrigerator feature. A powerful deadpoint leads to the mantel. The ramp below is off.
location: The center of the main pile.

description: SDS matched low on the ar√™te. Ride it to the top out.
location: South face of the freestanding boulder north of the main pile.

description: Tuck Orginal Route is the fist and as of this posting only route in the area. It follows the overhang on small holds into the backbend tuck move out the roof then cut loose and hold on!! This route then traverses right out of the roof around the corner and vertical for another 15ft.
location: The obvious roof in the hillside

description: Stand start with a low side-pull edge and a shallow mono-pocket at head height. A nice sequence with sweet grips leads up the face to a mellow top out.
location: On the lower outcrop, left of the ladylike ar√™te.
On the lower outcrop, left of Widow's Crack

description: This is the rightmost bolted route on the main face. No known FA has been made on this route, nor has any grade been proposed. For the time being I have listed it as 5.11+
location: First bolted route on the face.

description: Begin on the two lowest obvious crimps, and climb straight up the face. Fun powerful moves lead into a barn-door finish on the "love handle."
location: This is the southernmost boulder found along the face.

description: This project is a low start to Love Handle (V5) which begins on jugs down and right (around the corner) from Love Handle's start holds. Powerful, pumpy, and techy.
SDS with right hand on an incut side pull and left on a triangle edge. Move left to the undercling rail before muscling your way to a decent edge above and topping out. Unsuspectingly burly!
location: Just right of Tamaracked.

description: Stand start, with right hand on a side pull and left on a low small crimp. Fight the barn door and throw for a jug. The grade is height dependent (V1 for tall folks, V2 for short folks)!
location: Center line on the outcrop. Just right of Spruced Up.

description: Left hand on three finger (one pad) sidepull and right hand on 2-3 finger (one pad) sidepull. Move out to arete and up. Good movement.
location: Left of Lawyer
on the point, to get to the two climbs with bad falls climb down to the water between two walls
protection: Crash pad. a cam at the top and a harness could be helpful for the route over the water

description: sit start, head straight up the nice ledges
location: behind jam boulder route, go around the right side

description: Start as for Stage Right and traverse left topping out on Latter or start as for Latter, traverse right and top out on (aka exit) Stage Right.
location: The Warm-up center boulder.
protection: A pad for the top out

description: Start with double gastons at head height. Move left to a flake before topping out. Fun sequence.
location: A few feet right of Trail Booger.

description: Sit start with a side-pull and ledge, climb right, to the key undercling. Toss for the sloper and top out.
location: Between Former and Trail Spice at the Warm-up Center.

description: SDS matched on a positive block, gain the big slot and climb excellent edges to the top. Great sequence!
location: Center route on the Warm-up Center, just right of Former

description: Two ways to climb the crack, the easier starts off the block, the other traverses in from the right
location: off the left side of the trail before the point

description: SDS with a side pull for the left and the large sloping ledge in the right. Climb the arete. Very technical. Body positions are kind of scrunched, may be easier if you‚Äôre short.
location: This dome-like boulder sits just to the left of the trail and is the first you encounter as you walk to the point.

route_name: That Chossy Good for Nothing Traverse
description: SDS all the way left on a big ledge and sidepull. Traverse left, topping out just before the outcrop ends. Questionable rock quality.
location: The long rock band left of the Trail Roof and above the Trail Booger Boulder.

description: Start matched on a rail, climb up the slab using sloping edges.
location: Right of The Crawl

description: SDS with the two mini triangle pockets. A nasty lock-off leads into Stepwise. Open Project.
location: Left of Trail Booger

description: Stand start with right hand on the ar√™te at waist heigth and left on a slopey triangular cutout. Techy and progressively easier slab climbing leads to the top out.
location: Left of Trail Booger

description: Right under the down tree that leans on the boulder. Start with a right handed under cling/crimp and a left hand on a full pad crimp. Not quite a sit start. Reach up with the right to a V shaped crimp. Bring your right foot up and drop the left. Grab a slope-y pinch with the left at hip level to stabilize and then bump it up to a crimp matching the right. Lock off to bring your feet up. Stand up reaching for sloped crimp (crux move). Then either lock off if you are stable enough or a dyno to a sloper top to the right of the crack. Finish with a top out or call it good. I won‚Äôt judge.
location: Follow the path down to the beach and follow it north along the beach to a patch of boulders along the shore. Looking for the boulder that has a dead tree leaning against it. It‚Äôs about half way to the point of the cove.
protection: Can be done with 1 pad but I suggest having a spotter

description: SDS low on the big flake. Ride tasty side pulls to the top!
location: Left of Deliverance

description: SDS with a right hand edge and whatever you can find for the left. Slab it out. Questionable rock quality.
location: Left of the Altruist

description: SDS on a nice in-cut before climbing through more positive ledges to the top. Nice grips, short but sweet.
location: Vertical face left of the Trail Booger Boulder

description: SDS with a side pull for the right and left wherever is comfortable, climb positive edges to the top. Detached blocks are off.
location: Far right line on the Warm-up center

description: SDS on the largest in-cut in the center of the face. Climb edges and slots to the top. Watch out for loose blocks as you near the top out.
location: The high-angle slab right of the Trail Roof

description: SDS matched on a slanting in-cut, climb the arete-like feature of the ramp till you reach the top.
location: Beneath the ramp feature, just right of Trail Spice.

description: Start with right hand on the ar√™te and left on a small edge. A few delicate moves lead to the top.
location: South ar√™te of the freestanding, pyramid shaped block beneath the Trail Roof

description: Stand start, layback the ar√™te and top out. All detached blocks and adjacent walls are off.
location: South ar√™te of the freestanding, pyramid shaped block beneath the Trail Roof.
protection: A pad if you can squeeze it

description: Start low on the ar√™te. Some laybacking on poor feet leads to a slopey top out.
location: West ar√™te of the freestanding, pyramid shaped block beneath the Trail Roof

description: Start Crouched with right hand low on the ar√™te ¬†and left on a small edge. Climb the ar√™te before sneaking left under the roof and topping out. Fun movement with an awkward landing and poor position. All detached blocks and adjacent walls are off.
location: East ar√™te of the freestanding, pyramid shaped block beneath the Trail Roof.
protection: Maybe a pad if you can squeeze it in there

description: SDS on a triangle feature, climb positive in-cuts before reaching the top out.
location: Far left line on the Warm-up Center Boulder

description: SDS on two side pulls compress positive edges to the top. Rock quality is questionable, landing is sketchy.
location: Triangle shaped face left and just uphill of the main face of the Warm-up Center

description: An awkward start with two sidepulls leads to mellower climbing and a top out. Adjacent left wall is off
location: Left of Serendipitously

description: SDS matched on an in-cut flake, climb positive ledges before mantling on to the ramp and topping out.
location: Beneath and right of the ramp feature. Just right of Ramparts.

description: SDS on a matched on a protruding block. Climb similar positive features to the top.
location: Just left of Latter.

description: Start crouched with opposed slopers and poor feet. A few heady moves lead to a milder top out.
location: Left of Self Service

description: Stand start in on the face just left of the roof. Climb the dihedral till you reach the prominent crack. Layback and follow the crack up and around a bulge before topping out. Excellent climb, bad landing. The freestanding block behind you is off!
location: Dihedral on the left side of the Trail Roof boulder.
protection: No good place for pads or spotters

description: Stand start with a left hand pocket and small right hand tooth. Climb the up the slab using sloping ledges and cool pockets.
location: Left side of the slabby face just right of the Stage Right.

description: SDS with right hand pinch and left hand gaston. Slopey edges and some high stepping defends the top out.
location: Left of Stepwise

description: Sit start from the big ledge. Gain and climb the tapered crack.
location: Obvious crack on the west face of the Overhang Boulder

description: Start matched on the big undercling. Work through crimps before taking on the bulge and topping out.
location: Center of the south face of the Overhang Boulder

description: Sit start on the big ledge. Gain the crack, then head left before surmounting the bulge and topping out.
location: Right side of the Overhang Boulder

description: Start on two side-pulls, gain a sharp slot then head for the lip and top out.
location: South face of the Overhang Boulder

description: Sit start with a slopey pinch for the right and a nearby crimp for the left. Climb the ar√™te.
location: Left of Da Slab

description: When the water is low, the left overhang can be climbed
location: first boulder on the point

description: on the ledge block there is four routes, the finest of these starts off small sidepulls center face and moves up and right. traverse boulder has one route and moves from a sit right to left follow the obvious line and top out along the way
location: on the point (see photo)

description: SDS with a big incut in the right hand and left wherever is comfortable. Climb the arete. Detached blocks are off!
location: Right arete on the north face of the Jam Boulder

description: SDS. Stand up into some interesting thumberclings befor heading for the lip.
location: Far left side of the north face of the Jam Boulder

description: Start crouched on the obvious ramp. Stand up and use a dirty crack and good feet to walk up the slab.
location: Center line on the slabby north face of the Jam Boulder

description: The route climbs center face on good holds to a hand jam at the top
location: on the point

description: SDS on an undercling flake. Gain the arete and ride it to the top
location: Left side of the Jam Boulder.

description: SDS. Climb the arete. All detached blocks are off.
location: The arete right of the center line on the Jam Boulder

description: Sit start with a left hand side pull and right hand pinch. Climb the slab
location: West face of the Overhang Boulder

description: SDS on a large ledge, climb the slab. Nice holds with good movement!
location: South face of the Crack Block

description: SDS with a side pull crimp for the left and sloping vertical rail in the right. Climb up and right through blocky features before riding the arete to the top. No detached blocks for feet.
location: North face of the Crack Block Boulder.

description: SDS at the left arete with no detached blocks for feet. Climb the arete to the top
location: Left arete on the main face of the Crack Block.

description: Sit start directly below the crack on slopey crimps. Gain the crack and top out.
location: Main face of the Crack Block

description: SDS as you would to climb the crack, but head straight up, using holds on the arete and face.
location: Base of the prominent crack on the Crack Block

description: The direct line going up the crack is solid, one more line follows the arete to the right on face holds
location: one of the first two boulders on the beach

description: Start crouched, climb the left side of the slabby face to a top out.
location: Slab directly on the trail between The Burbot Bloc and Sugar Bowl.

description: Start as for Mizayikaa (right hand side-pull, left hand undercling) and climb left, executing a crux throw to gain the start of Lush. Top out as for lush. Pleasing and sustained movement, but slightly dabby.
location: Back-center of the Burbot Bloc, down and right of Lush.

description: SDS on the lowest jug, make big moves on more positive edges before topping out
location: Just south of Rum Runner's Cove

description: One of the best traverse routes on the lakeshore. The scoup traverse sit starts far right and takes the lip of the cave into the original scoup route on the left
location: scoup boulder

description: SDS in the back of the cave matched on an undercling. Using small crimps work through the steep bulge to into the start of The Scoup. Nice movement, but a bit dabby. Detached blocks are off.
location: In the back of the overhang beneath The Scoup

description: SDS matched low on the ar√™te. Follow the lip of the boulder, utilizing some poor footholds, before topping out on the far left end.
location: The short wall to the right of Mud Shark.

description: The low start to Poor Man's Lobster. Start sitting in the hole on two edges. 5 moves, just enough to zap some power, stand between you and the start of Poor Man's Lobster. A sequential, power endurance block that would surely be classic if it weren't so awkwardly dabby. All detached blocks are off!
location: In the hole directly beneath Poor Man's Lobster on the Burbot Bloc.
protection: Something super thin like an Organic Blubber Pad would be nice for the start. Otherwise, a pad or two should protect the top.

description: Start as for Pork Eater but top out early and right using a large ledge.
location: A few hundred feet south of The Scoup.

description: SDS with right hand on a sloping crimp and left on a three-finger edge. Traverse left into The Butcher using positive edges and nonexistent feet. Rather dabby...
location: A few hundred feed south of The Scoup.

description: Start sitting partly in the hole matched on an undercling. Gain the large ledge before trending right and making the powerful crux move to a far away edge and topping out.
location: Leftmost route on the freestanding boulder facing The Lakeshore Overhang
protection: Excellent Landing, A pad or two

description: Sit start matched on the prominent rail. Balance up the high-angle face to a mantel top out.
location: Left end of the west-facing wall 100 yards past the Burbot Bloc

description: SDS with right hand on a side-pull deep in the cave and right compressing a large in-cut side-pull. Tension your way to the wave-polished sloper before pulling the bulge and topping out.
location: Cave-like feature on the far right end of the backside on the Burbot Bloc
protection: A pad or two, something thin would be nice.

description: SDS with left hand on an undercling and right on a side-pull edge. Work up the steep face with some fancy foot work before executing the crux throw and topping out on the slab above.
location: Center of the backside of the Burbot Bloc (down and right of Lush).

description: Start as for Eelpout Low, but cross into an undercling crimp and head left through a few edges before manteling at the lip and topping out.
location: Right end of the east face (lakeside) on the Burbot Bloc.

description: Stand start with a left hand on a sloper and right hand a horizontal pinch above head height. Gain a couple in-cuts and power over the bulging lip to a mellow top out slab.
location: Center of the north face of the Burbot Bloc

description: Lay-down Start with left hand on the ar√™te and right on a slopey, side-pull crimp. Muster up some body tension as you work through a series of crimps to gain the start of the dead-point. Top out as for Loche.
location: Left end of the east (lake side) face of the Burbot Bloc.

description: Stand-start with left hand on the ar√™te and right on a small crimp. Establish and toss for the lip. There is potential for a lower start, but it would be much more difficult.
location: West face of the boulder adjacent to the Lakeshore Overhang.

description: SDS with a small pocket in the left and a slopey pinch for the right. Climb the ar√™te using small edges and blocky pinches. Top out straight over the lip.
location: Right ar√™te on the freestanding boulder opposite the Lakeshore Overhang.

description: SDS with a left hand side-pull and right hand gaston. Make a powerful move to a stellar quartz pocket before gaining the lip and topping out as for Lota Lota.
location: Center face of the Burbot Bloc

description: Stand/jump start on the lip at the far right end of the boulder. Traverse left on positive edges and pockets topping out at the other end of the boulder. Excellent holds with thoughtful movement.
location: The lip of the freestanding boulder opposite The Lakeshore Overhang
protection: Two-tiered landing. Two pads and an attentive spotter should feel comfy.

description: SDS with a side pull in the left and a slopey ledge for the right. Compression on blocky holds leads to an awkward top out.
location: This feature lies a hundred yards or so south of The Scoup.

description: Climb the center of the tall slab, don't fall
location: Obvious slab southeast of the Lakeshore Overhang

description: Laydown Start with left hand on an edge and right on a low side-pull. Use some core strength to keep your but off the pads as you gain the start crimper of Eelpout and ride its nice crimps to the top.
location: Right end of the east (lake side) face of the Burbot Block.
protection: Two pads or so and a spetter

description: SDS with a low ledge for the left and an incut edge for the right. Climb Diagonal crimps to the top.
location: Lakeside face of the freestanding boulder opposite Lakeshore Overhang.
protection: A bad barndoor could leave you wet, but there's really only room for a pad

description: Start squating on a low block. Work up big ledges before moving left to a large side-pull feature after which delicate movement on sloping crimps leads to a thoughtful top-out
location: The face right of The Scoup, landing may be wet depending on how windy it is.

description: SDS with left hand on a small incut and right on a tiny three-finger crimp. Make a powerful move to gain the big holds of Lota Lota and top out.
location: In-between Lawyer and Ling Cod.

description: SDS with left hand in the seam and right on a side-pull/undercling feature. Head up and slightly left through a series of stellar grips to a thought provoking top out. It's not possible to protect this climb with the current water levels, exercise caution.
location: Where the water meets the shore on the west facing outcrop 100 yards past the Burbot Bloc.

description: Start as for butcher but climb straight up through huge in-cuts.
location: A few hundred feet south of The Scoup

description: Start matched in the giant flake/crack as far down at left in the slot cave as you can manage. Traverse left following the crack until it goes vertical. Head up with it and top out. Sustained and sharp.
location: Slot Cave in the gully between the Instant Oats slab and Burbot Bloc.

description: SDS with right hand on a positive side-pull and left on the sloping ledge. Move left along the ledge before rocking over to grab a very sharp but positive rail and topping out.
location: A few hundred feet south of The Scoup

description: Link Ling Cod into Lota Lota. The length and movement of this climb are make it very enjoyable!
location: Right ar√™te of the freestanding boulder opposite Lakeshore Overhang
protection: Two-tiered landing, 2 pads and a spotter

description: Starts off at a crack near the bottom of boulder, follow this crack up until you make a big move with left hand to a triangular slope, then move right hand to grab vertically flat crack. The left hand then moves left to a large crimp and the right hand moves up to a crimp. Big Left hand move up to a jug and match this hold. From here traverse left grabbing a sloper with the left hand then a crimp with right so you can move the left hand to a pinch and then bump it to a jug. Match this jug and finally there are two more jug holds to top out.
protection: 3-4 Pads will cover the whole route with protection.

description: Start standing with an undercling in the left and a small crimper in the right. Climb the slab. There is potential for a sit start.
location: Ar√™te on the main outcrop.

description: Start low, climb the dirty hand-sized crack.
location: Prominent crack on the island outcrop.

description: Dynamically step into a press with both hands, dyno to a side-pull ledge. A rare comp-style problem.
location: Center of the lake-side face of the outcrop.

description: Start crouched with big feet. Climb the slab and top out
location: Right of Island Crack

description: SDS with right hand on side pull and left on a small crimp. Gain a slopey edge and march your feet upward as you enter the slabby dihedral.
location: Just right of Anaerobic Arete.

description: SDS with left hand on a side pull and right on a slopey edge. Stand up and climb through positive ledges to a thought provoking top out.
location: Just right of Tamarjacked.

description: Stand start, with left hand on the arete and right wherever is most comfortable. Climb slopers and small edges keeping the areate on your left.
location: Arete on the far left side of the outcrop

description: Start standing, with left hand on the arete and right wherever is most comfortable. Climb the arete, but transition from the right side to the left side about halfway up. Easier and less committing than the right exit.
location: Arete on the far left side of the boulder

description: Start sitting with hands low on the sharp ar√™te of the large detached block. Head towards the small overhang surmounting it using slopers on the ar√™te.
location: From Infamous, walk 30' or so along the shore.

description: Start crouched with underclings, head left though more underclings to the top. Fun sequence!
location: Short slab with two cracks approximately 100' downshore of Swamp Donkey.

description: SDS matched on a side-pull. Climb up and right through some one-pad crimps to the top out.
location: Left side of the rock face visible from the dock.

description: SDS match on a side-pull. Climb up and left through big ledges to a top out.
location: Furthest left route on the wall visible from the dock.

description: SDS with right hand on a big flake and left on a sloping edge. Climb slopey crimps on the face to a top out. Nice movement!
location: Right of Noise Pollution.

description: SDS with both hands on the big ledge. Make a powerful move to gain the ar√™te. Climb slopers to the top.
location: The ar√™te right of Intrinsic

description: Stand start withan undercling for the left and the lowest sloper on the ar√™te for the right. Climb more slopers to the top out.
location: The ar√™te rigth of Intrinsic.

description: Follow the obvious rail hold on the backside of the boulder to a slopey top out
location: South side of boulder

description: Beautiful project that will go with some work. Lots of pads could help the commitment level. Start on the indented hold and move up on small crimps to a over the head lieback.
location: Striking clean overhang just before the large white pine

description: It seems tall and unlikley but "hang in there" for the thank god hold at the top passing the overhang
location: just past the downclimb route on one of the taller sections where a crack splits an overhang

description: Used as a downclimb for the main part of the cut but a fun route on the way up as well. Climb up on a easy lieback crack and step left to the top
location: Center of the main cut

description: SDS on a slightly incut edge in the center of the overhang. Move left to a side pull and then bump to a large ledge. Climb positive holds to the top.
location: Backside of the Lean-to boulder

description: Laydown start with both hands on the ledge in the back-center of the roof. Climb out through the overhang on powerful under-clings and slopers before topping out. Bring your biceps for this classic.
location: Center of the roof

description: SDS with a right hand finger lock and rattly left jam. Climb the overhanging finger crack. Painful and burly, bring some tape for this one.
location: Crack in the far right side of the Roof

description: Stand start at far left of ledge, climb left and into the flake, top out.
location: The prominent ledge in the center of the left face of the outcrop.

description: SDS with left hand on side pull, and right on a sloper. Climb flakes and crimps to top.
location: Left side of the face on the hillside the roof juts out of.

description: Start on the blocky feature in the front-center of the roof. Head left through a sloper and pinch, topping out as for The Shindex.
location: Front-Center of the roof.

description: SDS on with both hands on the blocky feature in the center of roof. Head right, into a prow feature, before making a huge dead-point beneath the lip and topping out.
location: Front-center of the roof

description: SDS with a sloping dish on the left ar√™te and a low opposing side-pull edge in the right hand. Bump into the rail utilized by the Shindex and execute some burly compression before trending left at the lip and topping out. Powerful, strenuous, and dynamic.
location: Left side of the roof

description: Stand start matched on flake a few powerful moves to gain ledges, top out. This one's got a spooky landing situation.
location: The flake on the left face of the outcrop.

description: Stand start at far right of the ledge, climb similar features to a top out.
location: Right of Pig Headed.

description: Start as for Shindex, but climb right at the lip linking into The Other Side of Paradise. A sequential, power endurance block with a heart breaking last move.
location: Back-center of the Roof

description: This highball climb has some fun overhanging moves low and nice slab moves up high. Start low and head for the jug at the lip. Gain the jug and climb the upper slab to the top.
location: Left side of the Cougar Bear Area

description: Lay-down start. Left hand on a large ledge and right in an incut triangle-jug. Move left to an incut ledge before highstepping with small edges in hand. Would be considerably less awkward without the birch tree right behind you, nice movement though. Detached blocks are off!
location: Backside of the boulder located on the south end of the 2nd cobble beach
protection: A pad and maybe someone to pull the tree out of your way!

description: SDS with right hand on an undercling edge and left on a positive ledge. Climb large edges to the top.
location: On the trail side of the boulder on the far right on the 2nd cobble beach.

description: SDS with both hands on a the large undercling. Muscle up to a decent edge before heading right to similar edges and topping out. A bit dabby in some parts, but an excellent climb nonetheless!
location: On the right face of the cave feature of the Lean-to Boulder (actually on the adjacent boulder).

description: SDS with right hand on an edge and left on a small side pull/pinch. Come in to a left hand pinch and blast to a jug. Top out.
location: Far left line on the backside of the Lean-to boulder.

description: SDS with left hand side pull and right hand on another side pull. Climb right, into the middle section of pan and top out.
location: Leftmost route on the trail side of the boulder on the far right of the 2nd cobble beach

description: SDS matched on the prominent rail in the center of the overhang. Head out right to a side-pull crimp before gaining the prow. Employ some exciting footwork to surmount the lip and top out. A short climb with powerful, gymnastic movement. Classic!
location: The prow on the right side of the Lean-to Boulder.

description: SDS on blocky jug and climb the ar√™te, topping out at the apex.
location: Prominent ar√™te on the rigth end of the outcrop

description: Stand start with left hand crimp, right hand sloper, dynamic to edge, flake features to top. Potential for hard but awkward sit start.
location: Right of Meeting of the Minds

description: SDS on undercling flake, move left set up deadpoint to best sloper in Michigan. Continue left and top out above.
location: Far right sector of Rocklandia, landing is level with the swamp.

description: SDS and climb the splitter hand crack to top out.
location: Splitter crack in the center of the corridor.

description: SDS matched on the sketchy loose jug that refuses to come out (trust me, I've tried!). Head left then up, through a couple ledges, before topping out. Nice movement.
location: Right of Big League Chew

description: SDS with both hands in the finger crack. Jam and stem your way through the overhanging dihedral to gain the lip. Head left and top out.
location: Overhanging dihedral in the center of the outcrop

description: SDS with two triangle crimps. A few powerful moves on small holds leads to a top out. It may be short, but it sure packs a punch!
location: Far left end of the outcrop

description: SDS compressing the overhanging fridge feature, squeeze your way up before trending left and topping out. A powerful and sequential moderate. Classic.
location: Center face of the east half of the dream.

description: SDS matched in a horizontal crack in back of the roof. Follow the crack up and left through the overhang. Top out above.
location: Right side on the swamp facing section of the dream.

description: SDS matched on an in-cut block feature. Climb up and into Ar√™tection.
location: Center face of the outcrop.

description: On the west side of the island, next to an easy access ramp into the lake, there is an aesthetic cliff that is slightly overhanging. Grades are hard when you are wet and holds are wet. Water is deep enough to take a fall (5 feet and deeper). The right line starts with right hand on a good pinch and left hand on a crimp. Move out right to a sidepull and up. The left line starts anywhere on a long crimp rail. Climb up small crimps, or make a big, and very fun, move to the lip. For summer days, lots of variations here. This is near the Pinnacle Boulder.
As of this posting still a project. Should go in the low 12's high 11's. Toprope curently off of gear and trees
location: Above the boulder field left of the break after Bonasi Pipeline
protection: Toprope off gear and a tree

description: Fun little romp up a pronounced corner that splits two sides of the cliff. I'm sure it's possible to lead but have no info on gear.
location: Right of Bonsai Pipeline starting around the corner and topping out left.

description: Good crack climb just a little to high for most to boulder. Start by scrambling to a small ledge where the crack starts and fire up to the top!!
location: Far left of the Northwest Gully just past a small chute

description: Little slab and corner with fun easy moves. I've included this because it was my personal first outdoor climb in 2004 -Brandon Snyder-
location: Directly left of the "Tilt Project"

description: Sit start under the overhang and reach for a nice hold, undercling the mini roof and go for the knife!! Folow the blade to the top.
location: Right side of the boulder field

description: One of the tallest climbs on sugarloaf! Gear is good but a bit runout! Avoid the block pulling into the crux by traversing low and looking for a horiziontal placment that is really solid. From there climb stright up left of the bonsai pine!!
location: Tallest climb in the gully
protection: Standard rack up to #1 Camalot extra gear for anchor

description: Easy way to get to the top of the climbs from the boulder field. Easy 3rd class climbing but listed as 4th class because of fall expousre
location: Obvious ledge heading let from the start of First Day Out

route_name: West Side Deep Water - Roof Route
description: Fun line up a cool overhang feature. This one is borderline deep enough. Shallowest spot is about 40 inches. Need to have good awareness how you fall, or don't fall.
Start on head height edge, get a high foot, and make a few easy but fun moves to top.
location: This boulder is wedged between Joe‚Äôs Roof and the highball slab boulder.

description: Nice finger crack
protection: no protection for this one because it is over a bad water landing

description: To the left of the Pinnacle Boulder is a clean granite face. There are 2-3 unique lines on the face. On the left, is the hardest line. Start on a good ledge and make big move to jug. Move up and top out from there. In the middle, with a stand start, climb up staying left of flake. Good holds to the top. To the right of the flake is the easiest line. These are approximately V2-, V0, and Veasy.
protection: Flat but sloping landing. It is high, so 1-2 pads.

description: There are alot of routes on this rock. one up the pinacle two cracks behind the pinacle and two faces
Start low and left utilizing only this boulder. climb up crimps and slopers to top out.
location: This is on the middle to east side of island. You can see Hidden Beach in the background of the below beta picture.

description: Depending on season, might have water under it. Start on two small holds with a high foot, and make big move to an awesome two finger pocket. Move up and top out.
location: Looking at Joe‚Äôs, it is to the right.

route_name: Joe‚Äôs Roof Area - lowball Boulder to SE
description: Short but fun moves. Start low on blocky sidepull feature. Move out to arete and up.
location: If looking at Joe‚Äôs Roof, it is directly behind you.

route_name: Joe‚Äôs Roof Area - Boulder to SW - Right face
description: SDS with left hand on crimp and right hand on small side pull. Work your way up on crimps and side pulls. Top out and walk down slab.
location: Right next to Joe‚Äôs Roof.

route_name: Joe‚Äôs Roof Area - Boulder to SW
description: SDS with left hand low in side pull and right hand on side pull. Move up crimps and sidepulls to¬†top out.
location: If looking at Joe‚Äôs Roof, at climbers left.

description: Local test piece. Stout overhanging granite. Start on obvious crimp. Move out to lip and top out.
location: This is at far NW side of island.

description: SDS. Start with right hand low on blocky side pull and left had on small side pull. Move up arete using corner and face holds. Finish at ledge and traverse right to escape.
location: On the Highball slab. Side facing lake.

description: One of the most aesthetic problems in MQT. It is slightly less than vert. Start on obvious crimp edge. Move up thin crimps to top. LZ is complex and needs 3-4 pads to make for a good landing zone.
location: Right next to Joe‚Äôs Roof on NW side of island.

description: On the east side, there are several good lines for deep water boulder problems. There are at least 5-6 distinct lines in this area. Depending on how wet hands, shoes, and holds are, most are in the V0-V3 range.
location: On the North East end of island. Look for area in below pictures.
protection: Water landing. Plenty deep enough. Be aware of cold water and the risks it creates. There is an easy swim out climb out 10 feet away.

description: This is the old rock the climbs are on the 3rd stair from the top and start in horizontal holds
High ball finger to hands crack
Start low on left side. Work way up thing crimps and arete to top out of view of Wetmore/Hidden Beach areas.
location: In the center of the north end. Should be able to locate by the below picture.

description: Start on low ledge and work your way up good face holds and sidepulls. Tall and heady but not very difficult.
location: On North end of island. Pretty obvious boulder.
protection: More pads the better give the height.

route_name: The Birthplace of Fred and George
description: Easy slab. There are two possible routes on this boulder, one that follows a slight bump up to the right, and one that goes to the left. The one on the left starts with two underclings on two ridges, about arms length apart.
location: Wade out to Little Presque Isle, and take the trail that heads along the east shoreline. Descend down the first rocky section you come to that is made of granite, and the boulder will be on the left, across a small gap from the bay boulder.

description: This boulder is the first encounted when walking east around the point
Start on far right side on a crack/edge. Move up arete and top out.
location: NW side of island.
protection: Need a couple pads to cover a big crevasse.

description: SDS low on the ar√™te. A fun sequence climbs through nice slopers with a thought-provoking mantle at the apex.
location: Right ar√™te of the outcrop.

description: Start crouched with hands on the big flake-undercling and feet on the detached block below. Climb out the mini roof on nice ledges and top out.
location: The mini roof on the left side of the Death Star outcrop.

description: Start matched on the bulging flake with feet on the block below. Climb up and through a few sloping ledges to the top out.
location: Left of Death Star.

description: The sit start to Death Star. SDS with left hand on a blocky undercling and right on an in-cut side-pull. Make an powerful move right to a blocky ledge before heading into the regular sequence of Death Star. Burly and sequential compression. All detached blocks are off for feet (even the very tempting belay ledge right where you want your feet to go).
location: Right side of the Death Star outcrop.
Right side of the Death Star outcrop.

description: Start crouched on edges, climb the slab and top out. An aesthetic line.
location: Left side on the east face of The Dream

description: SDS, climb the thin crack and top out.
location: Crack left of Mondo

description: SDS back in the overhang matched on a horizontal crack. Climb out right through crimps before making a crux move to a ledge before climbing the face and topping out.
location: Right side on swamp-side face of the dream.

description: This is the most striking line on hogback! Starting up a a steep wall with a series of nice holds launch into an overhaning stem using the tips crack to pull into the fantastically unlikley stem. Lieback into a kneelock rest at the top of the overhang then either crimp stright up, or launch backwards to a deadpoint cross and mantle onto the "jug" rail. Both varaitions are similar in difficulty and provind a rest stance at the top of the overhang. The funs not over yet!!! finish on a slightly overhanging seam and pull right over the lip.
location: Second butress left middle of the long wall. Obvious overhanging corner with red and black streaks
protection: this route had top ancors but they have been removed at request. bring a pad to protect sharp edges and try to get the ancor over the edge to reduce rope drag.  a few trees can be used as well as a nut or two.

description: Obvious crack that leads to a small ledge with a block on it. Bottom is wet a lot of times but easy going moves that lead to good gear. Crux is where the finger crack starts to lead to hands.
location: Located on the first wall as you come down the gully betwen first and second buttres.

description: The route starts in an diagonal seam that works up and right to vertical cracks the top is face climbing on jugs.
location: top of the world crag far right
protection: there are small trees that can be used for anchors, small stoperrs and finger sized cams for the lead

description: Follow the corner from it's lowest point and turn the lip at the top. Slightly highball with not the best landing use caution .
location: Just off the road visible from the highway

description: Super fun route with a nice balance start on small footholds up a steep slab then into some easy terrian that joins the finish of "turning a corner"
location: Left of "turning a corner"

description: Sit start and climb the crack into the top section of Tarzan
location: East side of the lower outcrop.

description: Begin matched on low crimp rail with heel hook. Pull up right to slopey side pull and throw for the lip.
location: On the face to the right of crack traverse

description: SDS low and left. Ride the sweet rail feature to more big ledges and a mantle top out. If only it were taller...
location: East side of the lower outcrop.

description: Start matched on a low edge. Climb left finishing on the end of the crack traverse
location: Right of the overhung feature of the higher outcrop.

description: Technical climbing on ledges with varying levels of positivity leads to a thoughtful top out.
location: East face of the lower outcrop.

description: Start matched on the massive slot. An epic gymnastic sequence with two huge moves and arguably the best hold in the UP lies beneath a huge and heady top out with sparse holds. Still has yet to see an ascent. Another slightly harder version traverses in from the left on small edges.
location: Left corner of the overhang on the higher outcrop.

description: Stand start on two side pulls. Moderate techy climbing leads to a powerful and scary sequence to the lip. Highball.
location: 30 feet left of the overhung section of the higher outcrop.

description: SDS matched in the slot with feet under the bulge. Climb horizontal edges to the top.
location: A little ways uphill of Tarzan.

description: SDS with double underclings. Move up and compress the ar√™te to gain the jug. Match and drop. Full top out is slabby, blank and still a project.
location: 15 feet left of Pull Out or Bleed.

description: Starting in the far left of the overhang, traverse left across large ledges to the right angling crack. Ride the crack to a large ledge. Top out or drop. Often wet.
location: Far left of the overhang on the higher of the two outcrops

description: Stand start and climb the ar√™te to a slopey top out.
location: East face of the lower outcrop

description: Horiziontal holds center line lead to the top of this face.
location: Right off the road down hill from the big leaning corner. There is an obviously moved boulder near the base now.

description: Climb the right side of the fin
location: left of the roped climb obvious diamond shaped boulder.

description: Face left of the crack. Crack is "OFF".
location: Begin at the base of the diagonal crack. Stay left of the crack up the slab the a crux move to get over the small overhang. The top-out moves are also difficult.

description: This is a must do for anyone wanting to push into some reasonable highball moves. The crux comes low and with a sloping landing the comitment level is just right.
location: Direct line up the "Shark Fin" boulder

description: Climb the two flared seams
location: the northwestern summit

description: hand crack boulder climb
location: kinda hard to find, on one of the ridges between the road and the mountian

description: SDS with right hand on a low side pull and left on an undercling. Climb up, compressing neat in-cuts before toping out. Cool grips!
location: Right side of the Jam Room

description: short hands crack
location: next to fingering the hog

route_name: I Turned in my Hammer Drill
description: this route can be as hard as 11b if you direct start. climb up and left of the roof and take the arete to the ancors.
location: second butress two the right of the chimney with a large tree at it's top
protection: two bolts at the top with chains have been removed toprope off trees and nuts

description: There are four ways to this climb this route. The crux on all is the virticle step and evey varaition goes at the same grade
location: Far west end of second butress left of Hanging With Hornets

description: Many variations possible on thin slabs leading to a pull through an overhang. The lead is slightly run out at the bottom but has a solid stance to place the first pice of gear
location: on second buttress just left of Two Many Ladybugs
protection: this climb had top ancors they have been removed please don't plug or use the holes. the crack can be led with 00,0, and 1 metolius cams and a #4 stopper the top rope is off trees and nuts.

description: Stand start matched on the big ledge. Climb up through similar features and top out. A sit start is possible, but wouldn't contribute much.
location: Left of Pulled Pork in the Jam Room

description: purest finger crack in the UP
location: hogs hoof

description: Fun low angle crack
location: Hang a left up either gully left of the slab wall and the crack will be at the top on your left

description: This route takes the super thin seam right of the Bomb-Garden crack.
This route takes the crack in the corner through overhangs and finishes on the finger crack at the top
location: On the left going up the advanced trail on sugarloaf
protection: The toprope for this route either takes lots and lots of webbing or a #8,#10,and #11 hexcentric.

description: This route is short and sweet and has some fantastic moves on it. For the lead bring several crash pads and spotters to protect the first section to the stopper placement. It's a good idea to toprope the route first and work out the sequence as it's very specific thru the roof. An onsight would be super impressive on this one!! The entire route is left of Rays Bomb-Garden Crack but shares the same last move and protection.
location: Left of RBG
protection: for the lead #3 stopper .5 camalot and a #2 tcu for the top crack and crash pad or two

description: This is a fairly stright forward climb. Obvious left facing corner that starts about 10ft up the wall. Takes good small cams for the lead
location: Hiking uphill on the NCT from the north side, the route is on the left just off the trail.
protection: Small cams and trees for the anchor

description: Just like the aproach trail this one is usually pretty dirty! With more traffic this could become a great beginer lead.
location: Just left of the trail same approach as "North Counrty Corner"
protection: Trees for top rope anchor, Standard rack for lead

description: Starting with right hand in an undercling, climb comfy edges and ledges to the top.
location: Just right of the One Move Wonder

description: Start matched on the thin crimp rail. Head right to a big sidepull/pinch before searching for the key hold above the lip that guards the top out.
location: Right Face of the Top Boulder

description: SDS with left hand on an edge and right on an obvious flake. Compress slopers and slots to the top.
location: Center face of the Top Boulder

description: Start matched on the thin crimp rail. Head left into a small pinch. Tenuous foot moves and a small dish lie beneath a heady top out.
location: Right face of the Top Boulder

description: Start matched on the prominent ledge, bust out to slopers on the lip and top out.
location: Right of Topsy Turvy

description: Stand start matched on the large edge. Head left, surfing flat ledges with poor feet before topping out at the apex of the boulder.
location: Left face of the Top Boulder

description: SDS with hands in the crack. Strenuous laybacking leads to the top out.
location: Left of the Smalls ar√™te at the west end of the Sand Lot Slab

description: Stand start with a crimp on the right ar√™te and a side pull near the adjacent face. Ride the slopey lip into the dihedral and top out.
location: 30 feet west of the Sand Lot Slab

description: Starting with the prominent undercling, climb the face. Attempted but not completed. Poor landing.
location: Right of the Classic Crack

description: Stand start, climb the broken crack. Questionable rock quality.
location: Furthest left crack on the Sand Lot Slab

description: SDS with a crimp on the ar√™te for the right and the crack for the left. Climb the ar√™te to a slopey top out.
location: The ar√™te feature at the west end of the Sand Lot Slab

description: SDS compressing the ar√™te on the left and a sloper on the right. More technical compression leads to a slopey top out.
location: The ar√™te feature at the western side of the Sandlot Slab rock cut.

description: SDS with underclings beneath the prominent bulge. A pleasing sequence through neat features leads to the top out. Would surely achieve classic status if the rock quality wasn't so questionable.
location: The face left of the furthest left crack (Squints) on the Sand Lot Slab.

description: Eliminate. Climb The Xanax without using the adjacent wall on the left.
location: 30 feet west of the Sand Lot Slab

description: Stem up a small recess and moss jam it up to the top
A short section of hand-sized crack leads to ledgy climbing and a top out. Sketchy landing.
location: First crack on the east side of the slab.

description: Start crouched with a sloper in the left and crimpy undercling in the right. Climb the sparsely featured face. Big moves, scary and sequential. This climb has been attempted but not completed.
location: The face left of the Moss Crack.

description: Start with side pulls above head height. Delicately climb the face and top out.
location: Just left of the first crack (L7 Weenie)

description: Nice high ball crack, jugs at the top
Stand start both hands on a small ledge, climb the face and top out.
location: The face left of the Classic Crack

description: SDS with a side-pull rail for the right and a sloper for the left. 2 powerful moves lead into the regular start.
location: The face right of the Moss Crack

description: SDS compressing a ledge on the left and slot rail on the right. Climb the short, gently overhung face and top out. If only it were twice the size...
location: 50 feet northwest of the Sandlot slab

description: Start matched on the large ledge, climb the dihedral.
location: Left face of the Top Boulder

description: Start crouched with right hand on a good sidepull crimp and left on a micro crimp. Climb the slab. Surprisingly fun and engaging with a gorgeous top out view.
location: The slab opposite the Top Boulder

description: Stand start with two tiny crimps and even smaller feet. Use two perfect pockets to float through the high-angle section and up to 15 feet of well-earned, low-angle victory slab. An absolute must do for the Marquette climber.
location: Center of the near-blank slab.

description: Start matched on the ledge, climb the crack (tight fists/wide hands).
location: 30 feet left of the One Move Wonder

description: Alternate start to Layback Snack. SDS beneath the small overhang with a key undercling pocket. Gun for the crack and ride it to the top
location: Left side of the small overhang on the left wall of the Dinning Hall.

description: Climb the second, right angling crack.
location: Second, right angling crack on the left side of the corridor.

description: Start matched in a huge undercling. Ride small edges beneath the bulge before gaining the big ledge and executing a thoughtful top out.
location: Far right side of the left wall of the Dining Hall.

description: Start low and climb the right angling splitter crack.
location: First crack on the left side of the Dinning Hall.

description: Stand start from two small side pulls, use two small dishes and tiny footholds to make it to the lip. Be sure to stay in the center of the face, don‚Äôt wander to the ar√™te!
location: The triangle shaped slab.

description: Short crack on the Hogwart with two varaiotions. Not very tall but a good beginer route to teach how to lead short routes safely.
Start matched on a side pull, climb the face to a techy mantle.
location: Left of Fumbling

description: Start as low as possible compressing the pillar. Climb big ledges to the top.
location: Just left of the Crack Roof

description: the route consists of four mini pitches. the first is a slab followed by a overhang with a good crack try to avoid the loose flake when the crack goes to fingers, the 3rd section is a stem up a corner, this corner is visible from the trail and is helpful in finding the route. the 4th section follows cracks directly to the summit
location: hike the hogs back trail till just before the final uphill stretch and cut of the trail to the left
protection: no protection but could be led

description: Starting with a side pull and poor feet, climb the face.
location: Left of Beginner's Luck

description: Steep to slightly overhanging climbing up the tallest part of the cliff.
Climb the obvious crack in the back of the left leaning corner
location: Just uphill from the wall

description: Start as for Crack Roof Left but traverse right, staying under the roof, and topping out.
location: Crack Roof

description: Start on side pulls with good feet, stand into the roof and climb the shallow crack.
location: Right crack in the Crack Roof

description: Start low in the dihedral and climb the crack.
location: Left crack in the Crack Roof

description: Start with two side pulls, climb the high-angle slab and top out. Detached blocks are off.
location: Left of Killer Piller

description: Stand start matched on the prominent ledge. Mantle and top out.
location: Just left of the A-shaped slab

description: Stand start matched on the undercling, gain the big side pull before executing a fun top out.
location: Left of Sensei's Slab

description: SDS with right hand on the prominent sloper rail and left on a sloping edge under the roof. Climb straight out and over the bulge, top out.
location: The small roof of the freestanding boulder in the Gateway Outcrops

description: SDS with right hand on the lowest sloper rail and left on a poor side pull. A powerful yet tenuous sequence on improbable holds leads to an unfortunately dabby section just before the top out.
location: The small roof of the freestanding boulder next to Sensei's Slab

description: Stand start, climb the ar√™te.
location: Right ar√™te of the A-shaped slab.

description: Start on two slopey edges. Make powerful moves to on slopey ledges before topping out.
location: Right side of the Moss Pit outcrop

description: This route starts in the crack formed by the boulder laying aginst the base of the cliff then traverses along the lip of the boulder as far as you can go then tops out
location: Base of the wall

description: This route is the most right of the dihedral systems.  Climb up a chimney like feature to a flake and continue to a nice ledge
Easy slab-like boulder problem in a fun setting. ¬†Lots of good holds, but some are sharp. ¬†Great view from the top. ¬†(Other climbs possible on this big boulder)
location: Follow the main paved trail/bike path through town to the east. ¬†Boulder is right near the 1 mile mark, and is located near the Arch Rock stop.

description: Arguably one of the most aesthetic lines in Marquette has to offer. SDS with a left hand finger lock and right in a big slot/ledge. Compress the gorgeous prow before trending left through big ledges and scrambling to the top. Great movement on an epic feature. Classic.
location: The obvious prow on the right side of the Saloon outcrop

description: SDS with a sloping edge for the left and in-cut side pull for the right. Climb left through the ar√™te feature, compressing cool edges before topping out as for Jukebox Hero.
location: Left of Jukebox Hero

description: Follow a left facing corner with two cracks on the left face
protection: As of now has not been freed

description: On the southeast side of island. ¬†Chossy.
Start in the cave beneath the chockstone and work our way out to an arete. Pass the overhang into a shallow right faceing corner and finish in the crack
location: left of Sliced Bread

description: Start crouched with a left hand sidepull and right on the ar√™te. Neat grips and a fun compression sequence takes you to the top out.
location: Right ar√™te on the outcrop with double cracks

description: SDS matched on a left facing ar√™te feature. Climb up (don't go left to the ramp) to a one move crux just beneath the top out. A bit contrived.
location: Leftmost route on the outcrop with double cracks.

description: Start as for Lost in the Choss. Traverse left into Dark Necessities. Cool rock, nice holds, but a less than inspiring sequence.
location: Center of the outcrop with double cracks.

description: Start crouched beneath the lower of the two cracks. Climb up to a crux double finger lock beneath the lip. Heady with excellent movement.
location: Left of Pale Blue on the outcrop with double cracks
The prominent double ar√™te/prow feature in the center of the outcrop.

description: SDS from the rock matched on a side pull. Fun climbing on nice ledges leads to a thoughtful top out.
location: Slab on the far left of the Washroom outcrop

description: A fun crack climb located in the large chimney.  It is possible use the crack and the chimney at the same time. It's quite easy to get nice rests by putting your back against the other chimney wall while climbing the crack.
location: The route is located in the chimney to the right of O'C Electric. It can be difficult to get back into the chimney to start the climb as there is some vegetation blocking the chimney at the bottom.  It can be easier to climb the short block to the left of the chimney as opposed to going through the vegetation on the left.
protection: Single rack with optional #4 and #5. Plenty of cracks on top to make an anchor

description: Fun straight forward climb,lots of fun hand jamming the crack. Loose rocks removed on 1st assent, seems pretty clean. New at rating climbs so let me know what you think!
location: Line is 3 foot to the left of the corner up to the inviting crack. Route is located between Double Crack and Rain Maker. Access top on a scrabble left of the stonehead.
protection: Long static line or webbing needed for solid top roping.

description: This route is the squeeze chimney/ off width on the west side of the O'C Electric block.
location: The route is located on the West side of th OC Electric Block.
protection: The route requires Big Bros or Valley Giants to lead it as a chimney.  It is easiest to solo the route or top rope it.

description: This is a great and steep route that climbs throughout the steepest part of the cliff.  Positive holds and a surprising amount of feet make the climb enjoyable!
location: The route is located at the tall section of cliff with a roof just a minute or two from the road. Climb the corner and up to the left of the old nest.  Traversing in from the left on a ramp system can be fun.  When your feet are level with the nest, traverse a little right on hand holds and then up.  Be careful of the large block left of the nest.  It is a little loose and may need to be removed.
protection: Top rope off of trees.  Lots of webbing or cord needed.

description: Starts of the short section of vertical rock and then goes into the left facing corner on the right.
location: Located to the right of the roofs and to the right of Ixodes.  Shares the same start as Ixodes.
protection: Lots of webbing or cord for a TR anchor off of trees.

description: This route starts up  some vertical rock to the low angle rock and traverses left to the right facing corner.  If rock climbing on top rope , continue up a little to the right of the crack in the corner.  If drytooling, the first half of the climb is a little strange for tools and goes at maybe D4.  The upper section is much more interesting as you can get great torques in the corner and goes at D7.
location: Located to the right of the roofs and to the left of Scapularis that shares the same start.
protection: Lots of webbing or cord to make a TR off of trees.

description: Follow Large crack from arrow to star on picture. Access top from the left
location: Ist 40+ ft route on left of cliff face ,approach base from far left and follow shelf.
protection: 20 foot distances from boulders and large White Pine top rope anchors. Trad possibilities present

description: A fun face climb that skirts left of all the roofs.
location: Located to the left of the roofs.
protection: Lots of webbing or cord for an anchor on top.

description: A crack climb that follows two parallel vertical cracks.  The difficulty increases near the top.
location: The route is located on the West side of the OC Electric Block.
protection: A single to double rack.  Two #4 Camalots can be useful.

description: SDS with left hand on a side pull in the dihedral and right far out on an edge. A perplexing move gains you the crack which leads to the top out.
location: Right of Bath Bomb

description: SDS with left hand on a sharp crimp and right in a tips slot. An improbable mantel and a few tenuous slab moves lead to the top out. A very satisfying climb.
location: Center of the slab feature in the Washroom cut.

description: Start as for Loofah Roofah Right, but head straight up through the bulging ar√™te and top out.
location: Right side of the Loofah Roof

description: Start crouched with left hand in a slot and right on a side-pull around the ar√™te. A few awkward moves lead to a mellow top out.
location: Furthest right line on the Washroom outcrop.

description: SDS with left hand in the slot and right on a nearby sloper. Head right towards a micro crimper before powering through the overhanging bulge. Brutal.
location: 40 degree overhanging prow on the far left side of the Washroom cut.

description: SDS with right hand on a low side-pull and left on an edge. Traverse left to the big flake before working into the cool roof feature. Skirt left to top out. Fun moves on cool holds.
location: Just right side of the roof section of the Washroom
The prominent roof right of Power Shower

description: SDS matched on a crimp seam. Awkward climbing in the dihedral leads to a sweet crack and mellow top out.
location: Left side of the dihedral on the far right of the Washroom outcrop.

description: SDS matched on the seam low on the ar√™te. A techy mantle leads to a few small holds beneath a mellow top out.
location: Right side of the slab feature in the center of the Washroom Cut

description: SDS with right hand in a left facing slot and left hand on a small crimp. Climb the left face of the dihedral. Topping out straight up (without traversing left into the crack) sustains the route's difficulty and provides for a more full-value climb.
location: Dihedral on the far right side of the Washroom cut.

description: SDS with a left hand crimp at the lip of the bulge and right hand on the blocky fin feature. Surmount the bulge and head through nice edges on the slab before topping out.
location: Left side of the A-shaped prow in the center of the Washroom cut.

description: SDS with both hands on the blocky rail feature. Make a powerful move to the right ar√™te and compress it to the top. Harder for short folks.
location: Right of Bathtub

description: On the Seattle Wall (previously the Upper Wall) At the ground, start to the left of the boulder, looking up at a little roof. Shift to the right just under the roof, and follow a small crack up to a ledge you can rest on. Move back to the left and continue just until the base of the big boulder, then shift right once again to finish at the top of the boulder.
location: Seen as the highest route in Picnic Area, on the Seattle Wall. Take note of the large boulder at the top (snowflake when climbed in December)
protection: Webbing or static ~50 ft. needed to reach a few trees.

first_ascent: Equipped by Paul DeMay & John Winkler
description: Furthest right, bolted route on the large slab, follow a crack that cuts to the left for the first 3 bolts, then some near vertical climbing for the finish. Crux is near the last bolt.

Start to the right of the overhang, follow the fracture up to a rest ledge with wavy rock. Move left and up through the overhang. Definitive crux moving through the overhang before getting to a small in-cut crimp, heel hook and jug haul to the finish.
location: Starts to the right of the over hang. The rock is wavy from ancient water.

description: SDS with left hand low crimp and right hand jug. Climb up the low overhang and top out. Crux is getting over the lip when topping out.
location: Top of the talus field towards the middle. To the right of One Trick Pony.

description: SDS with a sloper on the left ar√™te and a low in-cut. Pull off the ground and make a few powerful bumps before compressing the prow and getting your hands on those glorious horns at the top.
location: Directly beneath the overhanging wall at the top of the talus field (up and left of the crazy fin feature)

description: Follow face hold and a lieback
The name says it all
Deadpoint off jugs and mantle the top
Crouch start matched on low juggy hold. Climb up using the arete and good holds along the face. Fun movement with crux at the top.
location: Up and to the right of the shark fin feature. Near the start of the bluffs and to the right of the overhanging bluffs above the shark fin feature.

description: Start on two sloping edges in the back of the roof. Work some foot magic to gain the lip before taking the brutal release and riding slick quartzite slopers to the mantle. All detached blocks are off!
location: Roof at the bottom left of the talus.

description: Climb from two central jugs up to top of boulder. Arete is off til top out.
location: Center of the tali‚Äôs field, directly below shark fin feature.

description: SDS with right hand on arete and left hand on prominent jug. Climb up the arete through good holds and top out. Crux is getting over the lip on the top out, as it is slightly overhanging.
location: Middle of the talus field, right below shark fin feature

description: Stop and have a picnic is the obvious trad line that is on the far right side of Picnic Area Left. Follow a great selection of hand jams, stems and laybacks up a great line.
Poly-Ticks is a great sporty line that starts about 6ft to the left of Stop and have a picnic and goes up the white rock through a small roof then up the headwall to the top.

Blood Diamond is about 6ft to the left of Poly-Ticks and about 8ft to the left of Abba. About 10ft up you should see an obvious diamond shaped rock jutting about 4 inches out from the wall around it. Climb up to it, move very slightly to the left past a small roof through good holds to a small dyno and finish on decent holds.

protection: Currently TR only. Bolts will be added soon.

description: This route is in the middle of Picnic Area Right. It follows a left facing corner about 15ft then switches to a right facing corner and eases up to the top of the cliff.

route_name: I Lost My Sole in the UP
first_ascent: Eric Landmann, Kamila Fassbender, Burt Lindquist, March 2019
description: On the right part of the wall, start left of a rock rib. Go up 2 moves to a short leftward traverse to a convenient tree stance. Next up to the ledge, move left to a shallow blocky groove. Top out on a large ledge. You can rappel from a huge pine tree 30 feet to the left. Gear is there but not very obvious. This is a pure gear route. FA was done in proper style, ground-up, on-site.
location: Far right side of Picnic Wall, to the left of a blocky area near the right end of the wall.
protection: Mostly small to medium cams, a couple of medium nuts, there are no bolts on this route.

description: This is a diagonal crack leaning to the right.  The climb is broken mid way by a ledge and has a large pin tree to climbers right on the top.
Middle route on the large slab, similar start as the route to the left, the ‚Äòroof‚Äô may be tricky for new climbers!
location: Middle bolted line on the large open slab area

description: Furthest left on the large slab wall, start on a scramble/slab and clip the first bolt. The second bolt protects a small ‚Äòroof‚Äô cruise to the top keeping just right of the arete/crack.

Slabby climb with some good opportunity for underclings. More difficult variations depending on which side of bolt line you climb. Finish at anchors just higher than The Bearded Lady (the route to climbers' left). Crux at the start and roughly 3/4 of the way up.

Slabby climb with some good opportunity for underclings and hand jambs. More difficult variations depending on which side of bolt line you climb. Finish just higher than the peak to your left at anchors. Crux at the start and roughly 3/4 of the way up.

Oh yes I DID! ¬†Welcome to the wide world of offwidth/squeeze chimney climbing, except its protected by a few bolt's. Route starts out at 12" and maintains that for the first half then flares to 18". ¬†There‚Äôs a thin seam running straight up one wall just inside this beast. ¬†Quintessential chock stone rest mid route.

Super short crack, can set up top ropes on either side of it for some short beginner routes, mind the trail and potential fall off the trail to below. Possible to link the ~50 feet below for a long and easy distance climb.
protection: Setup Top rope on trees above

description: Climb up the ‚Äòstaircase‚Äô to get to the start. Similar style to the route on its left, but smaller holds all around and no crack to help. Smear, smear, smear, good luck if it‚Äôs wet.
protection: Setup top rope from trees above

description: Climb up the ‚Äòstaircase‚Äô to get to the start, first 2 bolts are a gimme, crux is at the 4th bolt during a series of crack moves. One more big move to stick the 5th bolt and a little bit of runout to the anchors.

Climb up the ‚Äòstaircase‚Äô to get to the start, climb up the slab on the right and stem for a fun 5.8 and vary with a little bit of crack climbing with your left side, stick close to the arete for a more challenging 5.9.
protection: Setup Top rope anchors on tree directly above route.

description: Just on top of the staircase, route starts with big holds which continue most of the way up. Veer left or right slightly for some variation in difficulty and end at the placed anchors basically standing at the edge of the camping platform. Walk left to top out if desired (this can save you from using the walking path to get to the top).

The start can be difficult if you want it to be by starting in the corner underneath the large shelf. There is a staircase used to access the right most routes that you could use to start if avoiding the crux is desired. Otherwise, a very fun full body mantle onto a shelf is the crux before the first bolt. Climb left of anchors for easier terrain, in line for moderate, and a bit to the right for some harder to reach crimps/pockets. Anchors are placed for an easy top rope setup.
Similar start to route #9 but follows the crack. Finish at the anchors of route #9 by moving around the boulder at the top, can be a tricky last move!
A proud sun-soaked route with quality stone and quality pro.
Started right in the center of the face, plenty of starting footholds/handholds
location: Theres a rocky outcrop in the center of The Pit that has a large burn mark on the north facing side of the rock. This route was directly East of the burn mark, still on the rocky outcrop.

description: Either nobody climbs here or there‚Äôs a reason nobody climbs here. Rock is very loose or crumbly all across the bluff. All potential routes are unclean and potentially dangerous of rock fall. DO NOT belay from below. Not a place for unseasoned climbers.
location: HoneyMoon Bluff at the east end of Hungry Jack Lake off the Gunflint Trail. Easy to find, google it. Short approach from parking lot. At the lookout on the other side of the railing. Left of center look out point. Short and sweet little sustained leaning ledge climb.

description: Start in obvious hole under the roof. left hand gaston jug. right hand undercling pinch/crimp. climb the path of least resistance.
location: teachers overlook roof
At the top of The Upper Boat Dock Area you will see a down sloping slab with a splitter 2" crack that overhangs the river, this is the top of the climb.
protection: .75"-2" cams, For TR it doesn't hurt to extend a 1" cam underneath the mini roof, so you don't swing out too far in the event of a fall.

location: From the parking lot/visitor's center, this route lies about 100 yards down the road to the river boat dock on the right.   There is a gravel area with several large rock.  Sonny and Jaunita is the first dihedral on the right.
protection: Nuts, Hexes, Cams.  Mostly nut sized.  Hexes and nuts for the TR setup.

description: NIce beginner trad lead - good stances, adequate pro, convenient anchor set up, and some fun movement. There's a rattly block near the top
protection: Nuts and cams, mostly small to #.75. Gear anchor in a vertical crack
Nuts, Hexes, Cams. Mostly nut sized. Hexes and nuts for the TR setup

location: About 25 yards from the parking lot at the visitor's center on the road to the boat dock.
protection: Nuts, cams, hexes.  For the TR setup add some webbing.

location: Directly left of Noah's Ark
protection: Same TR setup as Noah's Ark (nuts and pods for a black and blue totem). I forgot to pay attention if there was adequate pro to lead it

description: Overhang-capped arete right of Daphnis & Chloe.
protection: standard rack.  long webbing to setup top rope
Nuts, Hexes and Cams.  Mostly smaller stuff.  Hexes and Nuts for TR setup, easy to TR as variation of Sonny and Juanita.
Nuts, Hexes, and Cams.  Mostly small stuff.  Hexes and nuts for the TR setup.
Nuts, Hexes, Cams. Mostly nut sized. Hexes and nuts for the TR setup.

location: Below the stairs that lead to the river and skiers left by about 50-100 feet, in a corner.

description: This problem will get better with more traffic. Start on a somewhat vegetated slab and use edges and in-cut horizontals. Follow the path of least resistance until reaching broken features above the slab, then trend slightly right. Aim for the outcropping fifteen or twenty feet above the ground, bypassing two small trees on the left near the top. Use care at the top; there still might be a bit of looseness up there. Promises to develop into a classic warm-up and beginner problem.
location: This is one of the first problems you encounter if you follow the trail down from the Teacher's Overlook picnic area. Follow directions for Slab Center and Left of Center. Begin on the other side of the pit/corridor opposite Slab Center.  Walk off a few feet to the left on the trail by which you descend from the Teachers Overlook picnic area.

first_ascent: Probably Old School. First known ascent-Jacob Gerber.
