description: Sit start using obvious hold in the center of the slab. Climb straight up. Once you reach the huge ledge a foot below the topout, it might be best to traverse left to topout as the stone at the topout directly above the start feels loose and quite sketchy.
location: Directly below the teachers overlook parking lot. You can see the top out from the informational signs at the overlook, but you might not realize that it is a pit with slab walls in it.
protection: One pad and extreme caution grabbing the topmost rocks. They are large and loose.

description: Sit start to Scareface.  Start on obvious shelf below stand start of Scareface.  Use feet, crimp, shelf, and whatnot to gain ledge and continue on.
location: Climber's right of the large cave.
Climber's right of the large cave.
protection: Multiple pads & spotters or a TR anchor.

first_ascent: A. Dale, A. Tagge, A. Wright
description: Stand start, both hands on generous hold about chest-height, feet on narrow ledges below (a more generous angled foothold can be found a little bit up and to the left). Traverse right, some smearing required; very small toe-holds along the horizontal crack here. Straight up to topout, watch out for the slender branch overhanging, or go right a bit to avoid it.
location: Right of Slab Center, traversing farther right and up

description: Sit start on a slot and a small crimp deep under the roof. First move crux pop up to a crimp. From here follow the rail to the easiest exit over the lip. Traverse back left once on the face and follow it to the top, just right of the scoopy-dihedral. There might be a line that doesn't wander out right...
location: Smack dab in the middle of the roof.

description: Same start as One Two Ar√™te Direct, move up holds and top out to the right. Not flat, but a much safer landing than the direct variation and the trees don't get in the way of toping out. Slightly easier than the direct variation.
location: Straight down from the picnic area parking lot and upstream about 20 yards or so along the upper cliff line.

description: Sit start way low (is there such a thing as a "lay start") with both hands on obvious hold on the point of the ar√™te. There is a good heal to start to the right. Climb and top out straight up the ar√™te. Top out has a tree in the way but can be done without it. Landing is sketch for both the climber and spotter. If you fall past the small flat area you might continue down a steep rocky hill. Crux is the start or the top out. Probably a 3 star if not for the landing and tree at the top out.
location: Straight down from the picnic area parking lot and upstream about 20 yards or so along the upper cliff line.
protection: Two or more pads would be preferable.

description: Stand start, right hand should look for the two-finger hole about chest/neck height, left hand can go up a bit to a vertically-oriented hold (both are chalked up a bit from previous use and should be easy to see). Feet in obvious footholds below. Good warm-up for other climbs on this slab.
location: Left of Slab Center on the end of the boulder.

description: Start with hands on shelf and feet on free standing block.  Reach back for angled crimp and work up to nice holds on left and right side of roof.  Work right and exit up through second roof.
location: Obvious overhang climber's right of Booster Shot.
protection: Pads to cover rock left of start and below roof.  Spotter encouraged.

description: Sit start to Mentor Overhang.  Start as Booster Shot, trend right on small crimps, gain start shelf for Mentor Overhang, but, keep feet off of free standing block as you progress towards roof.  Finish around roof as Mentor Overhang.
Stand high on crimps between the first and second roof. Huck to the lip.

protection: One or two pads at the perpendicular wall.

location: Climber's left of large cave

description: Sit start and climb straight up through delicate moves until reaching small crimps a bit short of the lip. Crux is figuring out how to get to the lip.
location: 2 or 3 feet left of Slab Center, just below the Teacher's Overlook. This problem is very close to Slab Center but climbs distinctly.
protection: At least one pad. Two would be better.

description: You can get a good campus move in then a dead point to some awesome delicate balancey moves high ball moves to a throw for a jug just below the top
location: The start to this route is on a chalked up jug just under the roof with no/bad feet. to the right of pop quiz and the left of scarface/schoolwork.

description: Start on obvious cluster under the roof. A tricky and powerful sequence gains the start holds of The Freshman. Follow right from here.
Sit start below the left edge of the roof, traverse on the ledge to the far right - then top out using only the holds on or below the roof.

Sit start with hands on the left side of the fin. Work your way up the right side of the sloped fin without using the loose rocks and boulder near the base. A little finesse and a bit of delicate footwork will see you through to the finish.
location: Down the hill from the primary wall, just off the main trail.

description: Start in the slot on a ledge. Small crimps and perm-moist holds gain the lip.
Sit start the same start as Clouds. Veer right under the overhang and onto the face. Top out without using the huge detached block on top.
location: Directly down hill from the picnic parking area and 50-100 yards up stream along the top cliff line. Just upstream from Banning Genesis and uses the same start as Clouds.

description: Big moves from the ledge to the sleepy slot.
location: Start on the big ledge, climb through the roof, finish direct on the face.

first_ascent: Silvio Pardron (or OG bout that is doubtful)
description: This route climbs better than it looks. Sit start low on the left side of the cave-ish area, Climb out left and top out straight up. The somewhat detached blocks above are on, but the detached blocks at the base of the vertical face and the completely separate boulder to the right are off.
location: Directly down hill from the picnic parking area and 75-100 yards up stream along the top cliff line. Just upstream from Banning Genesis.
protection: a couple of pads would be nice as the landing is uneven and rocky.

location: On the right face of a dihedral under a large roof, directly across from "One and Two Arete" and "Space Heater".
protection: One crash pad, second pad is suggested to cover the large boulder/drop off to the right of the problem.

description: A great warm up or first outside bolder for beginners. Stand start on the ground and use the detached rock at the bottom to climb straight up the line where the rock color changes. Top out is probably the crux but not out of line for the rest of the climb. Landing is pretty flat but there is a detached rock/boulder at the bottom that could come into play but probably wont. A couple pads are a good idea.
location: Directly down hill from the picnic parking area and 50-100 yards up stream along the top cliff line.
protection: At least one pad. More would be better.

description: Start on good side pull jug. Use decent feet to struggle up a straight crimp rail. Find feet and dyno to a very bad sloping dish right under the top. Find feet again and do a big move to the top out or go for decent edges and add a few extra moves. Very easy mantle top out
location: Around the corner that magnetic arete is on. Only one way to climb this section of the boulder. Very aesthetic route

description: Crux is definitely the opening moves. Start on single pad crimps. Gain a good foot under bulge with left and heel hook arete with right. Throw for knobs with right and match with left. Pull yourself over the bulge and walk easy slab up. Was V4 until new easy beta was found. Fun problem! Good warm up
location: Same boulder as "in the time of chimpanzees"  obvious bulging arete that you can see from the approach
protection: 2 pads. Has a good landing. Watch for crumbly rock at the top

description: Getting to the sloping rail is crux on this one. Start left hand on crimp right hand on good flat ledge. Jump from top to other boulder just below top out
location: Magnetic lake, superior national forest. Up the Gunflint trail. Go to Gunflint lodge, paddle to magnetic or rent a motor boat from Gunflint. Through narrows across lake then to west bay on magnetic. Obvious boulder 20 yards inland from lake. Project on back side. Easy access to boulder from lake. 25 minute approach in motor boat. 1 hour in canoe. Start on obvious feature with left and good ledge on right. Starts on west side face of boulder
protection: 2 large pads or 3+ small ones. One on ground and 1 on large boulder below top out. Confident spotters

location: HoneyMoon Bluff at the east end of Hungry Jack Lake off the Gunflint Trail. Easy to find, google it. Short approach from parking lot. At the lookout on the other side of the railing. ‚ÄúCenter-ish-right‚Äù
protection: Cams, nuts, cord, all the essentials for a solid top rope set up

description: This is a placeholder for Magnetic Rock.  A large exposed glacial rock formation 1.5 miles from the Gunflint Trail on "Magetic Lake" hiking trail.  I was unable to complete this send as I did not hike this trail with the proper gear.  The photo is of me just playing around.  The rating is a complete guess for the face in the photo.  There are lots of possibilities here.  If anyone has any information regarding this rock or climbing it please let me know.
location: Take the Gunflint Trail North to the "Magnetic Lake" trailhead on the Right side of road.  Hike the trail 1.5 miles through some rocky, but well established terrain.  Very fun approach!
protection: Lots of cracks.  Stoppers and Hexes smaller than fist size should work.  Or some good crash pads.

description: Either nobody climbs¬†here or there‚Äôs a reason nobody climbs here. Rock is very loose or crumbly all across the bluff. All potential routes are unclean and potentially dangerous of rock fall. DO NOT belay from below. Not a place for unseasoned climbers.
location: HoneyMoon Bluff at the east end of Hungry Jack Lake off the Gunflint Trail. Easy to find, google it. Short approach from parking lot. At the lookout on the other side of the railing. ‚ÄúCenter-ish‚Äù

route_name: Crimpin aint easy (but it sho is fun)
description: Start on under cling side pull jug. Good feet directly under start. Shoot up with left hand to crimp then gain right hand crimp. Adjust feet and Gaston to decent crimp with left. Do a funky mantle move to gain good right foot. Slowly reach for another right handed crimp. Move left hand up crimping rail and smear with left foot. Big move to decent slopes. Gain wide feet and do another big move to 2 pad crease on top out. Easy mantle top out
location: Same boulder as magnetic arete and in the time of chimpanzees. Directly to the left of magnetic arete
protection: 2 pads over rocks at base of problem

description: Start same as crimpin ain't easy. Grain decent crimp in left and match. High feet lead you to a big left hand throw to bad sloping crimp thing. For balance Gaston on poor sloper under your left hand. Bring left foot up to good edge and the Gaston with right hand again to decent crimp. Throw your right foot over the bulge and try to find good feet. Drop left foot and bump left hand up above your right hand to another poor crimp. Reach way out to poor sloping seem with right and compress your way up to a scary stand. At this point you have to smear with hands and feet and find your way up the tall slab. Best problem in the area so far!
location: Variation to crimpin ain't easy. Same corner to the left of magnetic arete.
protection: 4+ pads. I did it with 2 trifold metolious pads but some of the dead logs that make the fall dangerous weren't covered. Suck it up and go for it!

route_name: Batchelor Party at The Bowling Ally
location: HoneyMoon Bluff at the east end of Hungry Jack Lake off the Gunflint Trail. Easy to find, google it. Short approach from parking lot. At the lookout on the other side of the railing to the far left (south).

description: I started in the center of the rock pictured, I ended up going slightly to the left as I got up higher and ran into a tree root. The root was loose and not good to put weight on so I would recommend not using it. Decent hand holds, and not many loose stones. Very easy to get back to the bottom of The Pit when you top out.
location: If you enter The Pit from the west and are walking east, there will be a large area when you first enter that has a rocky outcrop in the center, surrounded by various levels of rock walls. Route 1 is on the north side of the outer rock walls, slightly opposite of the large burn mark on the rocky outcrop in the center.
The obvious corner over the east side of the overlook. Set anchors and rap down.
protection: Anchors at top off east side of platform. Sketchy setup left and well below the overlook. Use lots of webbing to set low enough. Do not anchor to the overlook platform.

description: A finger crack in a dihedral leads up to a small roof.  Pull this then head right to a crack and an A shaped alcove.  Above this are a pair of cedar trees growing out of a crack (be nice to them).  Climb the crack to the top.  Pretty sustained and great exposure for the region.
location: Just right of Fractured Fairy Tale.

protection: bouldering pads, standard rack for tr.

description: Dyno directly to the 2 hand pocket rather than traversing to it
location: Same as Slicksides
protection: boulder, top-rope, trad is possible, but why?

description: Angel Food is a distinct line that runs under and up to a very large roof. To get the most out of this route follow the diagonal crack system to under the roof, avoid the easy terrain to your right that is very tempting for your feet, place your pro and fire over the roof using the splitter crack and undercling. If you avoid the slanting ledges to your right this climb climbs consistently 5.8+ to a 5.10b crux. This route is #38 in Rock Climbing Minnesota and Wisconsin at the Minnesota Strip.
location: Far right side of Minnesota strip area. Once you're in the climbing area look up and find the large, protruding roof.
protection: Standard Rack. Small cams at crux.

location: Rose bush is one of the first routes you see on the Minnesota strip.  As the trail comes around to reveal the cliff it is the inside corner immediated in front of you.
protection: Nuts, Cams, and Hexes, nothing bigger than hand sized is needed.  Standard top rope setup, extra webbing (60 ft should be more than sufficient) for trees and spread out placements.

location: just right of Rosebush is a smooth face with some great movements

protection: Standard rack emphasis on smaller gear.  Standard top rope set up with a little extra webbing for the spread out placements (I used about all 60 ft I had anyway).

location: Piece of Cake is the prominent crack on the right side of the large rectangular block first visible upon entering the Minnesota strip.
protection: Nuts, Cams, Hexes.  The bottom takes medium sized stuff (large nuts to small hexes).  The top takes larger stuff.  Standard top rope setup with extra webbing (60 ft should more than cover it.)  The rock is somewhat broken toward the edge of the cliff and the best placements are a ways back from the top of the cliff.

location: Left of Fallen Knight on the MN strip.  I didn't use the large ledge a couple feet left of the route about halfway up.

description: In my humble opinion one of the best routes at Taylor's.  The combination of vertical and horizontal cracks makes for both jams and face holds.  This route protects very well throughout its course, taking stoppers especially well.  Start in the middle of the rock and follow the line to the top.  The moves switch from fingers to hands towards the top.  Also a fun aid route if you can hit it on an off day.
protection: Nuts, cams, hexes, nothing bigger than handsized.  Emphasis on smaller stuff.  Standard top rope setup.

location: It is just right of Columeister.
protection: A standard rack, save hand sized cams for the hand crack at the top.
Small gear for lead.  Standard TR setup.
Standard rack emphasis on smaller gear.  Standard top rope set up.
Nuts, hexes, smaller cams.   Standard top rope set up.
Nuts, cams, hexes.  Standard top rope setup.

description: Solid rock, fun move over roof, if feet come off, the roof pull can be campused
location: Directly in-between Good Knight & Fallen Knight, go straight over the roof rather than left or right.
protection: Solid top-rope set up or medium sized nuts/cams
Small nuts and cams, maybe a larger piece for the beginning.  Standard top rope setup.

location: This route lies in the middle of the prominent column on the left, further side of the Minnesota strip.
protection: Nuts, and small cams should do it.  Standard top rope setup.

route_name: One Thin Fish AKA "One Slim Fish"

location: In the Armpit Area, to the right of the crack

description: Start to the right on good holds and move left into the obvious crack.  Great jams and slick feet bring you into the crux up higher.  A couple dicey moves up and left bring you to the topout.  Many people climb this route as a boulder problem.  In that fashion it's a great highball but can easily be TR'd or led on gear.  A classic for the whole state.  Because of the high crux and a non-movable rock in the middle of the landing (when bouldering) many ankles have met their demise on this route.  Vertical crack in the middle of the large pot hole.
protection: bouldering pads, standard rack for tr.
bouldering pads, standard rack for tr.

description: Enjoy high steps and solid crimps on this face route just left of of the obvious corner.  Avoid the bigger holds left and right for a fun 5.8+ route.
protection: top rope. can be looked at as a highball boulder problem with interesting topout move.

location: From Slicksides walk 30 feet toward cliff overlooking River.  On your right is an attractive weatherbeaten face.  The route finishes in the center of this face about chest high of where you are standing.  You can access the base by climbing down rocks on your left.  May want to harness in for safety.  There's an old metal bar embedded here that makes a handy hold.

description: Start out on angular, large, blocky holds and get established into underclings/sidepulls up higher.  At the top, there's a full on feet cutting dyno to a thank god jug.  Top out after the jug is reached.  A great route with a somewhat sketchy landing.  Bring a couple pads and good spotters for this one.  Can also be TR'd or led on gear...  When looking at "Slicksides" this is the route/problem is just left of a diagonal crack.
protection: bouldering pads, standard rack for tr.

For TR, you just need some cord and carabiners. For trad, you'll want micro-nuts, a blue alien, and a willingness to break an ankle. For boulder, make sure there is a big pile of snow, and maybe 4-5 pads.
bouldering pad, standard rack for tr.

location: To the far right of slick up the incline. Just to the right of the 4 tree cluster.

description: Fun route, crux being either the leg stretch to the right or getting there with no foot holds, smearing the wall. Find the hole at ‚ÄúWhat is Sunshine?‚Äù, then move right along a crack and top out on ‚ÄúBad Habits‚Äù.
location: On the Sizzlefoot Wall, you can start on ‚ÄúWhat is Sunshine?‚Äù ¬†Looks like a sun (hole in wall) with rays (cracks) around it.
protection: Use at least one crash pad, two preferred as some sharp rocks are below

description: Crack to the right of Cirith Ungol.  Start this from the ledge or the ground and stick to the left hand crack.  Great lead that eats gear!  Solid fingers to hands.
location: Just right of Cirith Ungol near a dead tree

description: A hard start for the grade. Can cheat start to the right a few feet and cut back left on a ledge a few feet up. The direct start is the route, however. About 30 feet up, cut left on a fortuitous hand traverse, bushwack around some bushes, and follow a nice corner up and to the top.
location: Start about 20 feet left of Old Number Nine by two small trees with a discontinuous crack above leading to a small roof. Cut left at the roof and traverse below and around bushes. Easier to the top.
protection: Adequate gear for leading to 3 ". Placing pro at the start will likely fill the best jams. Extra small gear. Extra slings.

description: All the business on this climb comes in the first 15 feet then it's easy sailing!  Tricky finger and jam crack leads to a somewhat discontinuous crack system that seems to just go on forever!  As you get up near the top, look behind you for a surprise view of Lake Superior.  Eats gear the whole way!
location: About midway between Old Number Nine and Swords of Zanzibar.
protection: Cams and nuts from fingers to #2.

description: Follow a low angle crack/ledge system that diagnals up left from a leaning block to a more vertical fist crack.  Easy lead...
location: Almost to the far right end of the crag.

description: This is the face just left of Old Number Nine.  Pretty straight forward climbing up well featured rock.  A fun romp on toprope after you've led Old Number Nine.
location: Immediately left of Old Number Nine.
Just to the left of the main access gully that splits the cliff.
protection: Best toproped as the gear on the variation is sparse to non-existeent.

description: This route has a little bit of everything; chimney, lie back crack, face, and slab.  There is no defined crux of the route; it's all 5.5.  This would be a good 2nd route for a new leader but there is some slab climbing without much pro.
location: 20' right of Oz Before the Wizard (across from the large birch).  Look for the chimney.
protection: Everything to an optional #5 BD.  Bring long draws and watch out for rope drag!

description: A tricky climb!  Fist crack in a dihedral leads to a wide roof crack.  Pull this to mellow climbing above and finish out on a perfect hand crack.
location: Between Gollums Stairwell and Fractured Fairy Tale.

description: This route is a good warmup lead. The crux is at the small roof that marks the start of the dihedral.
location: Just to the left of the main access gully. Look for a crack that starts maybe 10 feet up or so and curves right and then back left. Shortly after that is a small roof followed by a dihedral.
protection: Standard rack to 3". Protection is adequate but you have to work for it. Good luck protecting the crux without filling up the best jam. Bring extra slings for the trees at the top.

description: The first route on the left hand side of the crag...this is pure squeeze chimney offwidth and is a bitch to protect.  Slither up the chimney to easier climbing above.
location: Left most climb on Mystical Mountain Zone

description: The obvious broken jagged chimney/off-width just right of Jack Be Nimble.  Worm your way up this and either finish on the hand crack or Jack Be Nimble or munge straight up.
location: Towards the far left of the left hand face.
protection: Standard rack of nuts and cams to #3

description: A thin continuous crack starting from a ledge behind a dead tree.  Strenuous!
location: Right of the approach gully and just left of Swords of Zanzibar
Left of the Cithril Ungol... just left of the the gully up to top of "Jack Be Nimble", etc...
protection: Smaller pro... small nuts, cams no bigger than a #1 camalot (if that), as I recall. BD C3's/ Aliens would be very handy. I believe it would be a challenging lead, but I'm more than certain that it has been done.

location: Tis route is 20-25 feet to the right of Old Number Nine at the far right end of the cliff. Look for the large tree fallen over at the base that is very near the cliff.
protection: Toprope recommended. Sparse gear prior to the finger crack.

location: Farthest right route facing the wall. Set anchors and rap down.
protection: Anchors at top off east side of platform. Sketchy setup left and well below the overlook. Use lots of webbing to set low enough. Do not anchor to the overlook platform.

location: The face climb that starts under the low roof beside the corner. Set anchors and rap down.
protection: Anchors at top off east side of platform. Sketchy setup left and well below the overlook. Use lots of webbing to set low enough. Do not anchor to the overlook platform.

location: The only climb off the west (right) side of the overlook. Anchors are easy to set here, but don't use the platform itself. There is a good tree to use, but be careful of its branches.
protection: Anchors at top. Set and rap down.

location: This route is directly behind the pillar of double crack.

description: Up the corner to a void slab then traverse across it and up.
location: Just right of a cedar tree 30' south of Double Cracks.
protection: Thin passive, or top rope anchor

description: Follow the red line straight up the boulder.  Get creative.
protection: Single cam higher up (.75ish) or just highball boulder.

location: 50 ft downstream from Devil's Chair
protection: Standard Rack. Trad only, no TR

description: Move up and left using the horizontal cracks till you reach a sloppy dish.  Match on this and throw fo the lip.
protection: 1-2 pads and a spotter is pleanty

location: The obvious buttress Just down river from the Keyhole Area
protection: Surprisingly, there are two bolts at the top of this buttress.

location: The obvious buttress Just down river from the Keyhole Area
protection: Surprisingly, there are two bolts at the top of this buttress.

location: The obvious buttress Just down river from the Keyhole Area
protection: Surprisingly, there are two bolts at the top of this buttress.

description: Face climbing with a handful of options that climbs up through a crack that splits an overhang.
location: Just upstream from the base of Delicate Dihedral.
The obvious buttress Just down river from the Keyhole Area
protection: Surprisingly, there are two bolts at the top of this buttress.

description: The top of this route features some small overhangs to climb over using big holds while the bottom offers some face climbing.
protection: There are lots of cracks on top of this route to set up top rope or else sling a couple of big features in the rock.
A few hand fist and finger sized cams will do the job.

description: Follow the yellow line, reach out right for a side pull just left of a hand crack lower down.
protection: Single cam (? .75 Black Diamond) up higher or just highball boulder it

description: A decent thin hands and finger jam crack.
location: The shorter crack about 2 or 3 feet to the right of "Just Driving By Direct". The blue line from the Highway 8 Boulder page pictures.

protection: No fixed gear. Trees and gear for toprope anchor

description: Up the left side of the keyhole face staying to the left as you climb.
protection: Set your top-rope to the left of the small summit prow.

The pro dissapears after deviating from the standard route so I would not recommend leading, unless you can find something I didn't see.  Same top rope setup as keyhole.  Nuts, and webbing for the large boulders.

location: Keyhole is the main route in the area, the top is located slightly north of the overlook.  To reach the top walk around the overlook from the right and continue under the base of the overlook around some large boulders to a ledge.  The ledge is the top of the keyhole face.
protection: Nuts and cams.  Mostly small stuff, nothing bigger than small hands is needed.  For the top rope setup, webbing for slinging boulders and a small nut placement is all I could come up with.

description: Slabby, requires good footwork.  It does have a good variety of body movements.
location: Up and right of the Keyhole, stay in the small seam
protection: Solid top-rope set up, small to medium pro on lead
Top rope from the top of the block.  Slings/webbing and carabiners are all that is needed.
Protects well, crack is wide up top. Std rack.
Nuts, and cams, nothing bigger than thin hands is needed.  For the top rope setup slings or webbing and carabiners are all that is needed.

first_ascent: Jim Slichter and Tom Anderson, circa 1980
description: [Falcon Guide] The name comes from the consequences of blowing the first move, boys.
location: Up the very crest of the arete right of Stretcher.
protection: Thin passive or top rope anchor

description: [Falcon Guide] Difficulty is inversely proportional to the climber's height. Don't bother if you are less than 6' tall.
location: Drop your rope from the triangular ledge left of the top of Iron Ring a.k.a. Witches Tit. Extend yourself desperately up the crack left of the Vasectomy arete.
protection: thin passive, top rope is best

description: The cave boulder on the approach to sugarloaf begging to be climbed. Start all the way in, finding hands. Lift off. Pull the lip and fire the roof.
location: This route is easily located on the approach trail to Sugarloaf. Look for the enticing roof. No pad needed. Plenty of sand!

description: Stand start from tiny roof, and work right
Stand start under the roof.

Climb the clean face with great rock to the right of Franklins Tower. After surmounting the initial block the crux is the first two bolts. Using cool pockets and edges climb pretty much straight up passing an old bolt placed by the Winona Alpine club in the 60s. Finish on the pillar type formation to the right of Franklins Tower.
location: This route is located directly to the right from Franklins Tower on the far right side of the west face.
protection: Fixe Glue In bolts to cable draws with fixed SS wiregate biner anchor.

description: Climb up initial steep corner to lower angle terrain and through the obvious overhang with closely spaced bolts  to protect the slab below. Fun moves through the overhang lead to easier terrain to a two bolt anchor with fixed SS wiregates.
location: This route is located in between Six Pack(to the left) and Franklins tower(to the right)

description: Start on a slab just to the right of the large inside corner on the SE side of the Sugarloaf. Follow good holds to the final bolt where a mantel is needed to pass the last steep section.
location: To the left of the Exterminator and to the right of E Walks.
protection: 4 Glue in bolts to cable anchor with SS biners

description: Time bandits climbs the inside corner just left of The Ramp route. Start up a vertical section which leads to fun easy climbing up the corner system to a two bolt anchor.
location: Just to the left of the ramp route.
protection: 5 glue in bolts to to bolt anchor with chain and ss wiregates.

description: Fun route with varied climbing including some tenuous  slab to steeper finish. See if you use the sweet "six pack" hold while clipping the last bolt.
location: Center route on right side of West face. Two routes left from Franklins Tower and just right from leftover salmon.
protection: 6 bolts to chain anchor with SS wiregates at the anchor.

description: The Sheriff was the first route bolted on the North Face and is one of the best routes on the Sugarloaf. The climb follows nice edges and flakes to a concave steep section that is passed by fun bear hug style sidepulling or you can bail left to make it easier.
location: It is the third route (L to R) on the North face. The ledge is very narrow so there are two glue-in bolts for the belay as well.
protection: 5 glue in bolts to chain anchors with permanent stainless steel wire gate carabiners

description: Shakedown street is a fun addition to the north face of the sugarloaf. Use the belay anchors for Lonely Arete and climb the pillar on the right side to the top of the pillar. From there a crux high step with cool pockets gets you to the chains. There is a runout between the 3rd and 4th bolts but the climbing is easy and holds are positive.
location: Located on the NW corner of the North face. This route is the furthest to the right when looking at the North face from town.
protection: 5 bomber glue in bolts to two bolt anchor.

description: Super fun climb that is steeper than it looks. Start with a crack over a bulge which leads to fun moves in an open dihedral through another bulge finished with a steep flake to the chains.
location: Second route from the left on the SE face; right of teh exterminator.
protection: 7 bolts to chain anchors with fixed SS wiregates

description: Running Scared Direct follows to the right of the bolt line directly. Begin with delicate yet powerful moves which are harder than they look to reach the jug above the small overhang. From the jug launch for the big holds approx 3.5/4ft above. Finish the same as Running Scared.
location: Located on the North Face in Between Rope Thief and Lonely Arete.
protection: 5 bolts to GI bolt anchor with cables and SS wiregates

description: Running Scared is the 6th bolted route (L to R) on the North Face of the Sugarloaf. Climb to the left of the bolts using flakes and side pulls to gain a jug at the 4th bolt. Use the left corner to gain another jug ¬†3-4 feet above. Clip the last bolt and make a reachy clip to a two bolt anchor with cable draws and SS wiregate biners. There is a single belay bolt at the base.
protection: 5 glue-in bolts(one being a fixe, others being wave bolts). Cable  perma draw anchors with SS wiregates at the anchors

description: Climb the short steep face while trying to avoid the large ledge to the right for full fun. Thin moves lead to a pair of huge pockets which leads to easier terrain to the anchors. If interested, you can add another pitch or continue on(watch ropedrag) to the summit making a two to 3 pitch practice climb.
location: Runnin' Late is the first route to the left of the large inside corner next to The Exterminator.
protection: 4 Glue in bolts to a town boot anchor with SS wiregate biners.

description: Rope Thief is the 3rd  bolted route from the left side of the North Face. Start by climbing easy big ledges leading to steeper edges and eventually using sidepulls and lay backs off the large flake feature that runs the majority of the climb. The pump builds to a crux right at the chains(were its supposed to be!).
location: 3rd route from the left on the North Face
protection: Glue In bolts with a little run out between bolts 2-3

description: Begin just right of the obvious corner climbing  through a couple large ledges and continue up the ramp/low angle climbing to the chains. The most difficult section is the first 10 ft. I t can be made easier by starting to the left. Good first lead.
location: Ramp Route is the bolted route that climbs to the 4th set of chain anchors on the west face(L to R).
protection: 6 glue in bolts to chain anchors.

description: Climb the pillar/trunk feature on the SE face with a crux at the halfway point. At the ledge 10ft from the top either finish using the bolt to the right(PG) or use the last two bolts of The Saga for a tame finish.
location: 3rd route from the left on the SE face; right of The Saga. Start down low for added value. Afternoon shade/ morning sun.
protection: 6 Fixe GI bolts; shares the same top anchor with The Saga

description: One Eyed Lady gets its name from the cool crystal filled pocket near the start of the route. The route climbs just to the right of the Sheriffs bolts and ends at chains down and to the right of that routes anchor. After the pocket climb past a couple big ledges to the crux steep section leading to the last bolt and chains
location: Second route from the left.

description: Follow two expansion bolts to an old bolted anchor and continue to the two glue-in bolt anchor above. Very easy climbing with a great view. Can be made harder or easier by climbing further left or right.
location: Northwest Corner of the tower

description: Matador is a super fun route which climbs through a concave feature located on the NE face of the Sugarloaf. Begin by climbing up a blocky, sort of hollow pillar past a bolt to a good stance on top of the pillar. From there super fun and steep stemming leads you to big holds and a final mantle which holds your attention.
location: NE corner(left most route on the north face).
protection: 5 bolts to a two bolt anchor( same as for Air Pig).

description: Vertical climbing up the left side of the obvious pillar to its top and climb the steep bulging wall above to the anchors. Bouldery climbing from the top of the pillar using the arete to the chains is the crux. Small feet leads to a sustained finish. Fun with awesome position.
location: Furthest right to the right(west) on the North face.
protection: 7 Fixe bolts to chain anchors with fixed SS wire gates. Bolts are close together to protect from top of pillar half way up.

description: An eliminate face climb  on great rock with a few variations. basically climb straight up the bolt line without using the crack to the right or ledges to the left for max difficulty.
location: This route is in between Ramp route to the left and the Green Room to the right.

description: The Lampshade route climbs the unassuming section of the east face right of the East Face route. The climb is defined by two different sections; the first is a fun steep face followed by the second section which is fun steep climbing over the small lip to clip the top anchor.
location: 10 feet right of the East Face route.
protection: 4 bolts to a two bolt permadraw anchor.

description: Keystone light begins on the subtle corner right of the start of Six Pack. It then climbs through the fun bouldery section between Six Pack and West face overhang where you use the Keystone for the crux section, then passes the overhanging section on the right following bolts to top anchors nearly on the top of the sugarloaf.
location: The route starts on the subtle corner to the right of the start of the Six pack route.
protection: 8 bolts to a two perma draw anchor with an extra bolt for clipping if you do this in two pitches to the top or want to practice building 3 point anchors.

description: Fun route which gets easier as you climb. The first 20ft are the most difficult while the top section offers fun easy vertical climbing. One of the longer routes on the Sugarloaf.
location: This route is the 3rd route(L to R) on the main west face. Look for a short crack in the beginning with  bolts to the left.

description: There are a lot of good holds for hands and really good feet for most of the route.
location: The route starts on the right hand side of the back of Sugar Loaf (facing away from the river)with a low bolt. Climb to the top and clip the chains, rappel down.
protection: There are 5 bolts, 4 are new. 4-5 quickdraws are recommended depending on skill level.

description: Franklin's Direct is the straight up version of Franklin's Tower. In stead of stemming and using the corner and arete feature to the left, climb straight up using one newly added bolt to complete the line. Better climbing than F.T. but a grade harder.
location: Clip the first bolt of Franklin's Tower and after the initial mantel climb straight up.

description: This route was bolted as a beginner lead. Closley bolted with easy clipping stances makes this a nice stress free first lead.
location: Third bolted route on the west face; approx 40 ft right from the NW corner.
protection: 4 bolts to chain anchors with SS wiregates

description: This fun route begins by climbing a small over hang above the last pair of belay bolts in the center of the North Face. Continue through a cool black streak to a small corner system and finishing on the big corner/flake feature. Clip the last bolt and follow the corner using laybacks and side pulls to a good edge above the anchor bolts. 6 GI bolts to a two bolt anchor with SS wiregate biners.
location: Fear and Loafing climbs up one of the most obvious features on the N. Face, the large weakness/corner system. Look for the last pair of belay bolts if coming in from the left(east) side. this climb is in between One Eyed Lady and Rope Thief.
protection: 6 bolts to two bolt anchor with SS wire gate biners.

description: Fun, bouldery climbing leads to easy steep climbing finished by a small runout to the chains.
location: Second bolted line to the right of the Practice anchors on the SE face.
protection: 5 Glue in bolts to chain anchors

description: Fun route on the east face that serves as a good 2nd or 3rd lead. Well protected and fun opening moves.
location: This route is, you guessed it) on the east face. Located to the right from The Pillar. Look for two Fixe GI bolts at the start of the route.
protection: 3 GI bolts followed by one expansion with GI anchors and SS biners on the anchor

description: E-Walks climbs the fun prominent inside corner on the SE side of the Sugarloaf. Start with a stemming corner and following increasingly larger ledges to a short run out to the anchor.
location: Located in between Running late and Tiny Hammer. The route climbs the obvious inside corner.
protection: 4 bolts to two bolt anchor with SS biners.

description: Start with some fun bouldery moves leading to a hanging inside corner. Climb to top using the same anchors at the Sheriff. One of the best routes on the loaf!
location: 3rd route on the North Face in between Air Pig and The Sheriff.

description: Start on the arete/layback in between The Exterminator and the Saga. A few bouldery moves past two bolts leads to steeper climbing using the remaining bolts of The Saga. Stay left of The Saga bolts for full value.
location: SE face in between The exterminator and The Saga
protection: 7 SS wave bolts to chain achors with fixed SS wiregates.

description: Beginners Delight is located just to the right of the NW corner route and is a great first lead for the budding sport climber. Bolted ¬†with new climbers in mind, all of the bolts are located at great stances with a small runout to the chains to get the feeling of being above gear.
location: To the right of NW Corner route
protection: 5 glue in bolts to 2 bolt anchor

description: Climb the overhanging face to the right of Running Scared. Begin with big holds climbing towards the overhanging notch. Climb through the notch using good horizontal ledges to a steep finish. Chains need to be moved a little to the climber right to make it better(soon). You can set a TR by climbing Running Scared and clipping the anchors out right around the arete.
location: Located to the right of Running Scared.

description: This is a great beginner lead with well spaced bolts and short crux section. Crux is located at the white Amoeba shaped section of rock. Stay on the bolt line for the best route even though it looks less obvious than to the right.
location: Second route on the west face approx 2o ft from the NW corner.
protection: Wave bolts to to fixe GI with cables and SS wiregate biners.

description: Climb off the belay anchor through a small overhang climbing on a subtle arete then trending to the left through a bulge which leads to the chains. Fun climbing; try to avoid the large ledge to the left while climbing the first half to add to the grade.
location: This route is the leftmost route(east) on the North face directly above the first belay anchors.
protection: Mix of wave and fixe GI bolts to GI anchors with fixed SS wiregate biners

description: Thought originally to be Witches Tit, but more commonly known as Iron Ring because of ... the Iron Ring.
location: Climb just right of the iron ring to a ledge two/thirds of the way up. Now try to do the crux corner above.
protection: thin passive or top rope anchor

description: Back in the Saddle is a fun west face route and great lead for those starting to climb the grades. Climb up as if you were starting the First Lead and follow the steep corner system exiting out and to the right to the same anchors as Time bandits.
location: Located to the right of First Lead.
protection: 4 wave bolts to two bolt anchor with SS wiregate biners.

description: Just to the right of "Thin Ice" is a crimpy face route that heads straight up the face and finishes over a small bulge at the top.
location: Just to the right of "Thin Ice",  downclimb off the ledge on the left (with the iron ring) to water level and head up the face.

description: Start a few feet above the water and 2-4 feet from the aerate and head up. As you climb you will gravitate to your left; avoid going too far left or you will be on a different, easier, route. The top requires a reach and good route finding.
protection: Use a small piece as a directional to position the end of the anchor above the route.

description: This is a great beginner route (or warmup if you do a few laps). From the downriver face ledge this is the obvious flake/crack leading up. Beginners like this route a lot, while experienced climbers will find it too simple but that's what a 5.7 is.
Nice solid climb. When you are near the top right under the big overhang ledge, go to the right for an easier climb
location: in the left corner on the wall
protection: Bring some small and medium sized nuts and cams

description: Near the middle there is a sandy bit with very crummy rocks! Avoid this by going on the face to the left.
location: The right corner in the area. it has a short overhanging bit in the middle and it is covered overhead by trees

description: An easy endurance route. Start on the horn at the left side of the pit and traverse on positive features into a technical corner. Reach an enormous rounded jug and then follow the vertical crack.
location: Start on the Slicksides Pit Traverse and join the Slicksides crack at the enormous rounded jug.
protection: A crashpad on the rock bellow the Slicksides crack.

description: Move up the less steep face to the left of Lunge or Plunge through blocky, uninspiring holds.
location: Slicksides Pit, left of Lunge or Plunge at the far left of the climbable rock.

description: Sit start with left hand on obvious crimp and right hand on less obvious crimp.  Work straight up avoiding the right side features/edge.

A classic boulder problem requiring balance, body tension, and tenacity. Start on the jug immediately to the right of The Crack. There is a foothold "on" about 3/4 feet to the right. Climb straight up on right-facing seams and slopers and make a muscley move to the lip. No part of the crack at left is "on."
location: In the Pit.

description: Pending. Move left through good vertical slots/crimps and up to the top off a poor, slopey foot. See picture.
location: The corner to the right of Twinkletoes.

description: Sit start on two crimps with a high foot.  Use right arete to work up to left crimp and good holds to sloping finish.

A fun technical problem with poor handholds. Move from the right end of this short face, and move up and left on slopers to top out. The face and crack itself at left are OFF, but there are some foot holds immediately right of the crack are "on." If it feels like a good foothold, then it's probably off. Remember, you're only cheating yourself.
location: Right of Spread Eagle is a slab problem. The face to the right of this slab is the Slopey Traverse Problem. Start at the far right.

description: Start in the crack at left of One Slim Fish. Bear down on some SMALL crimps with poor feet, and make some hard moves up and right, into the second half of One Slim Fish. One of the hardest lines in Taylors Falls.
location: Start in the crack left of "The Crack" and Twinkletoes.
protection: The first move appears worse than it is. A few pads at the base can make this fairly safe.

description: The very tall face left of The Crack. Stand start on the jug immediately left of the crack. The exact nature of this line is not entirely clear. Move either straight up, past a good match crimp to a pair of two-finger sharp crimps and lock-off to the top (straight up). OR, move left from the two two-finger sharp crimp over a no-fall zone of busted rocks to another crimp, and then up from there.
location: In the Pit, left of The Crack.
protection: The line straight up the face is high, but adequately protected with 3-4 pads. The line moving up and left is definitely R/X, and you may be hurt if you fall from the top of left as you would land in the gully. This line is traditionally top-roped.

description: From the jug start of One Slim Fish (to the left of The Crack), dyno to the lip. I don't know the actual grade of this.
location: The Pit, left of The Crack.

description: Easy, yet surprisingly fun slab climbing. A nice warmup.
location: The slab, immediately right of Spread Eagle and the Twinkletoes face.

description: Jam your hand in and go. Use only the crack after the first move
location: The straight crack just to the left of the "Easy Slab"

description: The obvious crack is surprisingly difficult, with hands, ringlocks, fingers all available options. Do not use holds outside the crack!
location: In the Pit.

description: Left of The Pit, climb the left arete/face to the overhang, pull over that, to the top and then exhale...
location: Left end of the pit. See photo.
protection: Two or three pads. Better not to fall.

description: It's dark in there.
location: Start at bottom of Sizzlefoot wall, standing two hand start. Follow through small cave, come out next to the No Hands Face.
At the left side of the Sizzlefoot face. This thin crack/face climb is directly opposite a small culvert under the walkway. The culvert points at the climb.
protection: 3-4 pads, a couple feet of snow helps cover the pointed rock at the base.

description: A toprope/highball straight up through the roof/fist crack in the middle of the face. Right of Genetic Control. Akward. I'm not aware of anyone who has bouldered this line. For the Taylors connesouer/hardman.
location: Middle of the Sizzlefoot wall. See the photo.
protection: Lots of pads and friends to catch you.

description: The face to the right of Bad Habit; this is the downclimb, and an easy upclimb on nice edges. The No Hands is a twist on the game, and a challenge. No using hands, elbows, wrists until you can grab the lip. You have to commit for it!
location: Right side of the Fat Man Boulder.
Just left of Miasma, on the fat man boulder

As one walks down from the parking lot with the Pit on the left and Tourist Rocks at right, turn left to see the Sizzlefoot Wall. The first boulder you see on the trail is the Fat Man boulder. Miasma is on the face to the left of Bad Habit (V0-1), and in front of a small tree. See photo.
protection: Crash pad to keep your tailbone from getting bruised.

description: At the far left of the wall. Climb the end of the wall, using "both" corners at the end of the wall.
location: The end of the Sizzlefoot Wall, use opposing edges/corners.
protection: Many pads, a cool head, and spotters.

description: A short, short problem that packs a punch. Start seated with a right-hand crimp in a sloping slot and your left-hand just below gastoning a good crack.  The start is a but odd, but it is the logical, lowest starting position.  Your feet are on the large base of the boulder; the base of the boulder is not off!  Thin crimping, hard compression, and brute strength get you to the top.  The problem is called Humpy Hump for a reason.
location: About 15ft to the right of Fat Man boulder.  Located on a short boulder (10ft) with an obvious blunt prow that faces the main trail.
In the crack/corridor (the left entrance), left of Miasma and "behind" the Fat Man Boulder.
The left-angling crack immediately left from the "cove" in the middle of the wall.
protection: 9 1/2 pads were used on the first boulder ascent. Top-rope  rehearsed.

description: Right of Bad Habit and the pillar, start with the jug on the right of the face. Make a big throw into the large scoop. Make a difficult match and mantle into the scoop. Challenging.
location: Right of the free column/pattern to the right of the Bad Habit/Miasma boulder, the Fat Man Boulder.

description: Traverse the Fat Man Boulder (contains Miasma, Bad Habit), however you like.
location: Fat Man Boulder, at the base of Sizzlefoot Boulder.
protection: Low-ball, pad to protect your tailbone.

description: Direct line to the Flusher. Start on the thin face, pull straight up. Start on one pad, any more than that more is cheating!
location: Face to the right of Meaty Staff of Righteousness and No Hands Face.

description: Classic sit problem, right on the walking trail. Sit and squeeze both corners, stand/stab into a good right hand, and then to the top. Two variations-- the easier variation uses a low right/good foot, and a left bump for a foot. The more fun/"tough" variation uses only the left foot/arete-- the low right foot is off. Have fun!
location: Right on the walking trail, after passing Tourist Rocks/The Pit and heading left to the Sizzlefoot Wall, it's the short face right on the trail.
protection: One pad to keep you off the tourists.

description: Again, another very hard line that I don't know the grade of. I'm making up grades to encourage people to try these lines and add some thoughts. Harder than Genetic Control. This is a top-rope, and I have not heard that it has been done without a rope. Start on the sloping triangular rock/ledge (it's 3-4 feet high) about 6 feet to the right of The Real Thing (the roof/crack just right of Genetic Control). Climb a few moves up the face to the lip, reach left over the roof and make some hard pulls up and left towards the bush/brush at the top.
location: Between The Real Thing, and the warm-ups on the right of the Sizzlefoot face (at the left of Miasma).
protection: Many crash pads, spotters, courage, and power.

description: That's right, traverse the whole pit. Left to right, or right to left.
location: Slicksides Pit. Traverse just above the ground, or as you like.
protection: Use your skillz. Or a pad.

description: (soon)
location: The right angling crack to the left of Slicksides crack.

description: On the right side of the "cove" (the back/right side of the Slicksides pit) is this slippery, technical testpiece. Slick feet and edges lead to a slopey slap and a tough topout. Very fun!
location: To the right of Digitalis and right of Fun Unnamed Problem.
protection: One pad, it's a nice flat landing.

description: (soon)
location: Slidesides pit, left side. (See photo.)
protection: At least two pads and a good spot.

description: (soon)
location: The obvious vertical crack in the Slicksides pit.
protection: Two pads, cover up and ankle-breaker rock right at the base.

location: Between Slicksides and "Unknown Prow"
protection: Couple of pads and a spotter.

description: To the right of Digitalis on the left of a short face, scramble up blocky large holds easily.
location: Back in the "cove," the right side of the Slicksides pit.

description: this is a route called Digitalis Prow a V5 it starts under the overhang moves out onto the tip of the nose with a right heel hook you throw for the dishy jug.
location: The face, to the right of the overhanging prow, about 12 feet to the right of the Slicksides start.
protection: Two pads and a good spotter.

description: Sit Start with Right hand on the sloper side pull and left hand on the crimp. Go up using anything between the two vertical cracks that run from the ground to the top. Both vertical cracks are off.
location: On the right side of the Slicklides Pit. Right of Digitalis Pit Left (Fun Unnamed Problem)

description: This problem is cryptic and technical. It's not easy to read or figure out. Expect some effort and time involvement on this one.
location: Sit start between the two boulders, straddling the arete.

description: Start on obvious chalked jug on the small overhang. thug your way under and up to the right using good feet and slopey hands. top out! Very dabby! core tension and thuggery are a must.
location: on the "egg boulder" line skirts the overhanging section. Look for the obvious chalked jug.
protection: pads. a slider pad is perfect for the low, dabby start

description: Classic taylors eliminate! Start on big "Horn" front and center. Use smear feet and a high step/hand foot to gain the lip. all face holds are off, except the HORN!!
location: trailside on the path down to the tour boat. past the REI toprope spot, on the right.

description: tba
location: Left crack, immediately right of Crash Landing on the right side of the B2 Pit.
parent_sector: Boonyards aka The B2 Pit, The

description: Tba
location: Immediately adjacent to the entrance boulder, on the right side of the wall.
protection: Two pads to cover the boulder at your back.
parent_sector: Boonyards aka The B2 Pit, The

route_name: This Sporting Life (aka, Left of Lloyd's Sit)
description: A few difficult and powerful moves with bad feet leads into Left of Lloyd's Stand. Start sitting and move up and left to a decent crimp match before moving into Left of Lloyd's Stand.
location: Sit at Left of Lloyd's, on the face to the right of the pine tree. In front of the large rock in the ground.

description: Great beginner problem. bad feet with ok hands. 1 move wonder to a big slopey horn.
location: Just right of the obvious overhang.

description: Start on good edges and move up and left into a right-facing undercling-sidepull with bad feet. Make a big reach left into a pocket. Some powerful moves on opposing slopers lead to the topout, through the groove.
location: From the Boneyards entrance, Primordial Soup is the pothole at right. Directly across from this is the right-leaning Lloyd's Crack. Spider Tracks starts between Lloyd's Crack and The Slab and moves left.
protection: A couple of pads are useful to cover the rocks, especially at left.

description: Stand start on big sloppers and shity feet.  Repeat untill you move up into a match on big slopper.  From there move up into a crappy right hand seam.  The crux is pulling off of this and topping out.  Crack to the right (B2 bomber) is not on.
location: Just left of B2 bomber.

description: Follow the angled finger crack, and then commit to smearing on the face to reach up to a nice jug. The crux is in trusting your feet to stick when you reach up to the next hold after the finger crack
location: When you enter the Boneyards it is on your left, between Spider Tracks, and The overhang

description: The Minnesota State Parks Service requests that climbers do not climb inside of potholes, which would include this route. This climb additionally has the potential of you slipping into an unpleasent algae-laden pool. This climb is included for historical purposes. Traverse out a good jug rail without feet, and make a hard reach up into the crack. Top out.
location: In the Boneyards, immediately at right, in the pothole.
protection: Water. Don't fall. Pads if it's winter.

description: Start underneath the overhanging rock, work your way up to the over hang, and then reach for the "secret" pocket to carry you out of the roof
location: Between Slab, and Nanhole

description: Move up the face on small crimps with or without the mono pocket, through some slopey holds to good holds at the top.
location: From the left side of the Sizzlefoot wall, walk straight ahead, up the stairs into the Boneyards. Nanhole is just before the bridge, on the left. Look for the Hole that is 6-7 feet off the ground. Start here.
protection: Flat landing; one pad is sufficient

description: Sit Start.  Feet to the left, double up hands. Reach back and traverse underneath. Hook Heel, and Reach up to Jug. Top Out.
location: Actually Just outside the boneyards, Go under the Bridge and you're staring right at it.

description: This classic route requires awkard and powerful underclinging/sidepulling straight up the wide crack flake, into some deadpoints between good holds. For many folks, the first move can be the crux, and a pad or three is often required to help get off the ground. The true finish goes to the left of the "bowl"/scoop, which is the finish of Spider Tracks.
location: To the right of the pine tree, stand start with both hands in the undercling flake/crack, and head straight up.

description: This short power problem is THE classic hard route at Taylors Falls, along with the Cave Traverse. Stand start at a good left hand gaston edge, and a right undercling, with glassy feet. A thin undercling leads to a difficult deadpoint into a three finger pod, and a big move up right to a sloper. A good, thin foothold recently broke on this climb, making the deadpoint move more difficult, but appears still do-able. The old grade was V11, the new grade is yet to be determined. Expect it to be V11-V12. Few repeats to date.
location: In the Boneyards, start to the right of the pine tree; left hand gaston crimp, right hand undercling crimp.

description: At the far left of the Lloyd's/Left of Lloyd's face (immediately at the left of entering into the Boneyards) is an easy face/good warm-up.
location: Next to the Pine Tree. To the left of Left of Lloyds. In the Boneyards.

description: Bad feet and powerfully awkward moves add significant difficulty to the classic Lloyd's crack, without necessarily adding classic movement. For the local climber, "it's H and H... Hard, and here."
location: Sit start directly below Lloyd's Crack.
protection: A couple/few pads are useful to pad the rocks at the base.

description: Fun big throw to the sloping lip.
location: Walk into the Boneyards; Boneyards dyno is on the right side, past Primordial Soup, before the bridge. Grab the to jugs and jump for the slopers at top.

route_name: Shot Down in Flames Right Exit
description: Climb Shot Down in Flames but instead of exiting left to jugs, add a few moves by working through crimps up and right. Heady finish over the pit with no feet makes this thing spicy.
location: Left side of the B2 pit.
parent_sector: Boonyards aka The B2 Pit, The

description: Start by placing your finger in the hole (usually wet) and your left hand on the corner jug, proceed straight up to a thin crimp, and then slopers
location: To right of Nanhole, Just before the bridge

description: This route is most easily recognized by it's pair of double D slopers, at the far left of the "left" wall (the B2 Bomber wall). The entrance rock and the "crack" are off. Sit start with good holds and big feet, and move up to the slopers. Paw at these for awhile, and then move left to a non-obvious but not-bad crimp. Either move left and up (for the left variation, less fun), or move back to the right to a thrilling finish. More or less the same grade, both variations, maybe slightly easier moving left. Surprisingly fun climbing.
location: Immediately left upon entering the B2 pit, or the most left climbable face, on the B2 Bomber/A Wing and a Prayer side of the pit.
protection: Two pads is probably best, a spotter can be useful too.
parent_sector: Boonyards aka The B2 Pit, The

description: tba
location: tba
parent_sector: Boonyards aka The B2 Pit, The

description: Tba
location: The right crack, immediately after entering, on the right side of the B2 Pit.
parent_sector: Boonyards aka The B2 Pit, The

description: This is a V6. sit start on a low crimp rail to a hard campus move keep your feet off the ground. gain a high left foot then a through for the jug. from here you get to decide to go left or right. left is harder a V7 and right keeps you at V6.
location: tba
parent_sector: Boonyards aka The B2 Pit, The

description: Undone, traverse the right side of the B2 Pit, from SOS to Crash Landing (gully and "top" are off).
location: tba
parent_sector: Boonyards aka The B2 Pit, The

description: Start at Shot Down in Flames, traverse right and into B2 Bomber, finishing on this route.
location: As described. B2 Pit.
parent_sector: Boonyards aka The B2 Pit, The

description: tba
location: tba
parent_sector: Boonyards aka The B2 Pit, The

route_name: A Wing and a Prayer (formerly known as "Social Candy")
description: Left of B2 Bomber.
location: tba
parent_sector: Boonyards aka The B2 Pit, The

description: Classic eliminate! start with left hand on small crimp side-pull, right hand on good ¬†side-pull jug. Compress and stand your way up on crimps and edges. Big jug ledge on the left is off, as well as big holds around the Arete to the left.
location: On the unknown boulder slab side! just to the right of the big face holds.

description: Sit start. Basically Straight up, one of the most obvious routes.
location: On the main face
lower left side of the egg boulder overhang.
protection: 1-2 pads. there is a rock in the landing zone

location: This route is located about 15 yards past the wooden lookout where Palisade Head should be visible.
protection: Park service installed enormous bolts, please use these to save the trees whenever possible. You can also fit a brown tri-cam in the drilled test holes. As with all Shovel Point routes bring a lot of webbing.

description: Climb the center of the face,
location: The east face of the Sheep Bones boulder.

description: Start on the left arete and finish up the crack to the right.
location: The east face of the Sheep Bones boulder.

description: Climb the right arete. This is not V-easy, the grade is simply a place holder.
location: The north face of the Lake Boulder.

description: Stand start, left hand on the arete and right on crimps.
location: The north face of the Lake Boulder.

description: Find a dark recess with and odd shaped stone about 8 feet off the ground.  Climb up to block and to a tree.
This is a curving flake found just to the left of #8.  Not too challenging and somewhat dirty.
Find some blobby rocks at the base and head up to overhang.  Just to the right of #4.
Up a thinner crack past a tree or two.  Up and over a little overhang.
About 30 feet left of #2 is a thin crack that leads to the right of an overhang.  You can go left for a little easier variation.
protection: Top rope with smaller cams and nuts.

description: A corner heads up to the right edge of a ledge.  A good warmup route.
location: Same anchor setup as #1

description: Follow two crack systems up to a ledge.
location: Just right of #5.

description: This is an inobvious crack left of a scoop and up to a small ledge.
location: To set this one up, climb the bushy gully about 20ft left of #1.  There are lots of choices for easy scrambling up to set up climbs #1-8.
protection: You'd need some cams and small nuts to build a top rope setup.

description: Climb a number of very easy, low angle, slab problems on the southern side of this boulder.
location: The south side of the Lake Boulder.

description: This is a beautiful overhanging granite face. Sit start on a good crimp. Work your way up on progressively worse crimps until your reach the lip, a spectacular jug rail.
location: Have at least two pads and a spotter
protection: On the right side of the main wall. Start on the block a few feet right of the small arete.

description: This is a beautiful overhanging granite face. Stand start on a good crimp. Work your way up on progressively worse crimps until your reach the lip, a spectacular jug rail.
location: On the right side of the main wall. Start on the block a few feet right of the small arete.
protection: Have at least two pads and a spotter

description: Start with your hands on the enormous horizontal granite flake. Then make a burly deadpoint for a shallow dish on the lip. Work your feet up and top out with whatever you've got.
location: Left side of the main wall

description: Climb the right arete.
location: The east face of the Sheep Bones boulder.

route_name: Wake Up and Smell the Coffee
location: Climber's right of Narcoleptic Epic.

description: A reasonably good, long route.  The line is probably not too important - just about anywhere you climb in  between here and "Straight, No Chaser" is about 5.10.
This route is short but technical. Layback the finger crack working your feet up until you can reach positive holds over the lip. Then mantle your way over the top.
location: The obvious finger crack in the corner

Look for Narcoleptic Epic, which finishes in a little gravel shoot at the east side of the main climbing area (about thirty feet east of the Sugar Plum Slab).  Straw House climbs the arete to the west of the horror that is the Narcoleptic Epic corner.
Just right of The Tree Route.

description: A good introductory route. Very short and fun. Lower to the ledge about 30 ft down.
location: Climber left of the Great Yawn. Photo soon!
protection: Anchor off trees. Be careful with them, Shovel Point's trees are very fragile.

description: A fun climb with a very very technical crux on a slab/crack with little friction.  Go left of the first roof, and right of the second to find the aesthetic crux crack.  A proud route to on-sight, this thing is no gimme.
location: Climber's right (east) of the Sugar Plum slab, look for two roofs as you head down to plot out your climb.

description: I have only ever top roped this route from above, but it is also possible to lead it in 2 pitches.  The first pitch is reported to be 5.8 and mediocre.  For top roping lower about 60 feet to a tree and climb the dihedral stemming your way to the top.  There are several old pins within the thin crack, that are about the only protection I remember towards the top if you were leading it.
protection: Standard rack for lead. Long (50'?) webbing for top roping off trees.

description: A fun moderate climb. From the ledge climb face holds up the corner. This climb is a little less traveled than the other moderates and has a bit of moss.
location: Climbers left of Wake Up and Smell the Coffee. Please access this climb by going back to the main trail and taking your first right past the restoration area. HELP RESTORE SHOVEL POINT!
protection: Anchor off trees. Not sure if this route has been lead, it would be thin and a belay anchor might be difficult.

location: East end of the cliff.  It's the first route in the last area of the cliff that is not roped off for re-forestation/regrowth.  Big hangers above, a bolt on the face a little ways down, and a big dead-looking tree arching out of the rock at the base.

description: A little more technical than Rise over Run or Out on a Limb - be ready to jam your foot into a smooth flared crack and stand up. ¬†Crux is about 2/3 up, where you need to make a big move up to an almost-deadpoint (depending on your height) jug.
location: A pretty obvious notch about 20 feet down from the huge bolts for Out on a Limb. ¬†The top has an eroded beginning, somewhat like ¬†Limb.
protection: Lots of trees, although you'll need a lot of webbing.  I wouldn't use the bolts, it would create an odd angle.

Standard Rack with a few large pieces, I racked to a #4 camalot and felt pro was adequate.  Webbing off trees for the TR setup.  There maybe be large bolts installed by the forest service atop this route.

location: The right side of the big roof that also holds Ego-itis.  Close to below the new wooden observation platform, maybe a little to the west.

description: Lower down to a small ledge just before you are completely surrounded by the namesake bright yellow lichen.  Climb up somewhat broken and dirty overhung rock to the top, climbing two roofs in route.  A fun route well worth doing but the dirtiness and slightly chossy nature of the rock detracts from the climb a bit in my opinion.

first_ascent: FTR: Dave Pagel, Rick Kollath, FL: Dave Rone
description: No single crux, just continuous highly-technical stemming in a smooth dihedral.  On the lead the pro is solid but sometimes requires patience to find and get in. (and you won't likely be feeling real patient!)  Nice spot for a belayer at the bottom of the route.  Otherwise, toprope it and just enjoy the moves.
location: About 60' east of the Sugarplump Faeries slab.  A good size tree right at the edge of the cliff lies directly above the dihedral.
protection: Mainly RP's to finger size stoppers, a couple larger sizes for the finish.  Some very small cams might be helpful.

description: Three pitches. Pitch 1: Start at the end of the talus and climb up to the base of the Ross's Crack dihedral and belay. Pitch 2: Traverse up and right, then down and right, and belay below the "Faeries" slab. Pitch 3: Finish up left of the slab.
Begin route moving up and right to the edge of the arete. Work past two small overhangs up to the top. Crux is balancing up on a small knob and using tiny edges.
location: Start from the tree on "Ross's Crack"
Climber's right (east) of The Sacred Biscuit, this line starts in the same place, and heads right.

protection: Webbing off trees.  Newly installed forest service bolts??

description: crappy bouldering located at the stillwater Boomsite (not at the ice climbing area, its across the river)(in MN). The best and one of the only bouldering problems in stillwater, very cool technical V3 , top out on a big jug about 8 feet off the gound
location: about 20 feet left of the waterfall and right by all the semilarge rocks on the ground(see photo). sit start with each hand in little jugs with good feet. top out on perfect jug about 8 feet off the ground

description: A scrambly ascent to the far right of the South Face before the rock becomes scrubby and unclimbable. A very short slabby section at the end that can be walked around. Used this area to rappel down after setting up our top rope.
location: Farthest right on the South Face, about the last climbable section of rock before the bushes. Right of #27.
protection: TR setup from plentiful trees at top. Easy rappel location. Could be a potential intro/practice trad lead if cleaned some.

description: Start low, on the Southeast corner of the boulder on the crimp rail. Work your way straight up through interesting slopers.
location: The East face of Monkey Wrench

description: The West face is both a great place to warm up, and to down climb from some of the more difficult routes. Just note that many of the perfect plates that make this face interesting are hollow and may break off.
location: The West face of Skink's Palace

description: A short crack route.  Climb a narrow crack up to a birch tree.
location: Find a small overhang about ten feet off the ground.      Follow the crack up and slightly left.
protection: Toprope with small cams and nuts.

description: A major crack on the inside of the chimney on the right wall.
location: Inside the chimney.

description: Start High in small crimps (may be a stacked pad start). Pull on and with terrible feet make a static move to a cool 2+ finger pinch. After gaining the pinch continue to the top of boulder.
location: A round the corner from Dead leaves on the dirty ground.

description: This is the perfect arete problem. The feet tend to be good; however, the poor crimps and sloping arete demand balance, precision, and core strength. Sit start low and work your way up the left trending arete!
location: The West arete of the Dead Leaves Boulder

description: This is the easy slab to the right of the Craft Arete.
location: The West fave of the Dead Leaves Boulder

route_name: Dead Leaves and the Dirty Ground
location: On the far left side of the dead leaves boulder.

description: Venture into the omnious cave to the West of the Dead Leaves Boulder and you may find a dead animal, because Crack Kills. The ceiling of the cave has an perfect hand crack. Follow this crack out and over the bulge!
location: The cave to the West of Dead Leaves Boulder

description: Powerful reachy moves gain an easy slab finish.
location: Sit start matched on the left facing side pull rail on the main face of the boulder. Make moves right until the arete. Rock over onto arete and finish on the slab.
Sit start matched on the left facing side pull rail on the main face of the boulder. Make moves right until the arete. Then follow Relationship Of Command to the top.

description: Climb up the talus block staying right of trees, move up and left to a small seam.
location: Find a chimney formed by a large block.  Just left of that is a pointed talus stone.
protection: Nuts, cams and webbing for the toprope.

description: Climbs a shallow crack up to a ramp.
location: About twenty feet to the right of the major corner.    Find the shallow crack.
protection: Cams and webbing for the toprope.

description: From ledge on 16 step right and straight up the over hang. Stick the sloper and top out. Crux is finding the sloper and pulling up.
location: Climber right of 16
protection: TR can be done from the setup of 16 but best set up climber right of 16 Trad up 16 and one place ment in the overhang. Watch for loose rock.

description: Climbs the major right facing corner, lots of fun.  A few tough moves at the end.
location: The face on the right facing corner.
protection: Webbing for trees and boulders, cams.

description: A fun route, follows a thin crack system on the face just before the corner.  Moves up past a small roof at the top.
location: Just left of the major right facing corner.  There is prominent boulder on the edge of the buttress, the climb is just below that boulder.
protection: Webbing and cams for the toprope setup.

description: This is more of a variation to #15 than a route.  Find a junky crack system about ten feet off the ground and head up and then join #15.
location: About ten feet left of #15.
protection: Top rope with nuts, cams and webbing.

description: Another good route.  Up a left leaning crack, traverse right into a v-groove and then up
location: Find a small left facing corner with a left leaning crack.  Setup is about right of #16.

description: A fun route, start at a left-leaning crack and head up through a pocketed face.  Continue up a roof using a hand crack.
location: The Center of the buttress.
protection: cams and nuts.  Setup is at the right end of a line of junipers.

description: A dirty/mossy route, not really worth the time.  A crack heads up the right side of the alcove, at the overhang you can go left or right.
location: Find a dirty alcove with some downed trees to the right of #10.
protection: Cams and nuts to set up the toprope.

description: A good route following a thin seam up and left.
location: About six feet to the left of #9.

description: Start in the center of the east face near the left side of the crack. Make a through for a small dish just above the lip, and continue up and over.
location: The East face of Skink's Palace

description: Find the good hold in the center of the face. From here make a through, and then finish the problem.
location: The South face of Skink's Palace

description: The namesake for the boulder, and with good reason. This route traverses the unique crack that defines the Skink's Palace Boulder. Start on the farthest left side of the East face and work your way right, finishing up the North face. You will need endurance, jamming skills, and good eyes to spot the thin feet. Good luck.
location: The East face of Skink's Palace.

description: Work left to right on crimps.
location: The South face of Skink's Palace.

description: Start on the lower right of the crack and make a big move.
location: The North face of Skink's Palace

description: Same start as See No Evil, the good hold in the center of the face, but move to the crack rather than moving left.
location: The South face of Skink's Palace

description: Start left of the crack, move up onto the slab and continue rightwards.
location: The East face of Skink's Palace

description: Near the Southeast corner, find the distinct crimp rail. Sit start matched on this feature, and move up through small crimps.
location: The East face of Monkey Wrench
