Climb the corner up to the first roof, go right, then up the east-facing crack to the upper roof (which can easily be made harder, but hardly made easier).
location: Start on the south face near the corner, its pretty hard to miss.
protection: I would have a lot of large pro. Up around the second roof there is a beautiful pothole you can thread with a sling. There is another large pothole that can be slung for an anchor.  Better yet, just walk around back, climb the fairly easy Class 3 chimney to set up a top-rope.

description: Immediately right of The Layback is a wide chimney.  K-1 ascends a flake on the right side of the chimney. When the flake ends, improvise straight up.  It's possible but easier and less aesthetic to stem the chimney behind you.
protection: Long (20+ feet) slings are recommended to sling the large boulder above this route.  Setting up the anchor involves some exposed class 3 scrambling across the chimney.

description: Start 4 feet left of The Layback. Surmount the roof and follow the arete above.

The Gambler is a slightly squeezed but independent line that slices up the left side of the face between Triple Chockstone and On A Roll.  Begin up easy climbing to a ledge.  Fire straight up through some sequential edges and sidepulls on the face left of the black streak.
location: The face right of Triple Chockstone.

description: Primitive Man is a fun climb on the far right side of primitive buttress starts about 5 feet right of Failing Fingers and goes straight up the ar√™te the crux is just past the middle where a couple strenuous moves come into play
location: far right ar√™te of primitive buttress
protection: Can be a lead with small gear or can share set up with failing fingers and get both done.

description: Five feet right of Death Scream, go straight up. Once you get to the roofs go right rather than left as for Death Scream. The crux is here and the holds can be hard to find. Make some big moves here and then higher onto lichen.
location: Just right of Death Scream
protection: Standard TR set up, same anchors as Death Scream.

description: Just to the right of the arete, begin with a fun little double dyno to get off the ground (very easy but fun.)  From there make some face moves on small holds and work your way up to some cool underclings and blocky features (unfortunately, a few of these features wobble a bit).  Continue on thin face moves to the top.  Needs more traffic or a brush to clean up all the lichen and spiderwebs.
location: Four feet right of Evolution

description: Fun climb follow a crack up and left of the roof then move straight up. Around the corner from death scream
location: Climb around the corner from death scream

description: A really fun but short face climb on a slightly overhanging face.  Limit yourself to the face left of the big crack in the corner.  The holds and crimps are fairly large, but don't hang around too long due to the somewhat steep/pumpy climbing.
location: The face to the climber's right of the triangular roof (left of the triangular roof is Cam Shaft.)

description: A fun stemming corner with small holds and a slight overhang that still remains at the guidebook rating of 5.5.  The face on the right side is unfortunately home to quite a bit of lichen.  Looks harder than 5.5 at first glance.
Start in the dihedral under a few mini overhangs is consistent 5.9 climbing on good holds
location: Failing Fingers is on the right side of primitive buttress very fun climb
protection: nuts and small cams could lead c3s or aliens or easy top rope set up set of nuts for a vertical crack at top

description: Evolution goes directly up the ar√™te through small roof the crux is going past the roof
location: evolution is the route next to old world monkey goes directly up ar√™te
protection: standard blue mounds top rope set up good crack to plug gear

description: Straight up the center of the face until reaching the huge roof. Enter the roof using decent holds and surmount it with a mantle-y thing. Feet are mostly minimal and poor through the crux. I have not seen it climbed gracefully.
location: Right up the center of the face, then up and left through the roof.

description: Follow the crack through the roof and find some solid jams and some stemming.  Hit a jug after making a few awkward moves and you'll soon find yourself at the top.  If it was longer it might get more stars.
location: Up the crack with the triangular roof on the right side of it.  Roughly ten meters north of Death Scream.

description: Begin making face moves on thin but somewhat positive crimps up the improbable-looking face. Find some cool underclings somewhere around half way up and rest there. Use a thin shallow seam and possibly a couple layback moves to the top.  Needs traffic or brushing to clear out all the lichen.
location: A few feet right of Missing Link

description: Climb up to a crack in the roof (hands/fists)and work left around the roof.  Continue to the top using the crack and face holds.
location: Locate a roof with a diagonal roof branching to the left.  The route starts below the roof and traverses around it.

description: Starts on the far right side of Everyday Buttress.  Step up onto the wall, face climb up and left of the small roofs into a left facing corner.  Continue straight up the bulging face.
protection: Standard Blue Mounds toprope (long slings helpful)

description: Begin about 8 feet right of Jammer.  Work straight up into the right facing corner below an overhang.  From the corner move a few feet right and follow the crack over the roof and straight to the top.
protection: Standard BM toprope.  Long slings are helpful.

description: Midnight Chimney separates Midnight Buttress from Sunday Buttress.  Prow-ess starts on dark rock immediately left of Midnight Chimney going straight up over the bulging upper half (crux).  Straying right to the chimney eases the difficulty considerably.
A fairly standard route. Leadable for trad'ers, and a good warm up before moving onto Prowess or Mean Streak.
location: To summarize "Prairie Walls: A Climber's Guide to Minnesota's Blue Mounds State Park" by Hynek and Landmann, this is a hand crack set at the back of a small dihedral, six feet left of Midnight Chimney
protection: A standard rack, including a big sling or two and a large hex or cam is useful.

description: Face climb between Alexandra David Neal and the arete on the right.  The route is fairly straight.  If you set your top rope right you can do both this and Alexandra David Neal on the same rope.  Even slide over a bit to do Old Stump if you didn't want to Lead it.
location: A few feet right of Alexandra David Neal and just left of the arete.
protection: Anchors further back with cams/hexes/nuts.  Easy to top belay.
Standard rack.  Standard top rope set up.
Nuts, Hexes, Cams including a larger piece such as #11 BD hexentric, #4 Camalot or equivalent Big Bro.  Standard top rope setup.
Nuts and hexes.  Bring cams if you trust them in quartzite.  Standard top rope setup.

description: The face between Ivy Right and Old Stump.
location: The face between Ivy Right and Old Stump.  Access via the class 3 gully on back of the buttress.
The first top rope problem on the buttress.  This route starts about 5 feet right of the corner of the buttress, and about 5 feet to the left of Black Wall, starting to the left of a thin seam.

description: This is an excellent climb that is completely independent of Jasper's Dihedral, but can be done off the same rope.  The climbing is great and offers some of the best exposure at Blue Mounds - an excellent line.  Enjoy!!
location: This is the arete just to the right of Jasper's Dihedral.  You sort of bounce around on either side of the arete following the holds.

description: Face climbing with a fairly definitive crux half way up.
location: 6 feet to the right of Old Stump.
protection: Easy toprope setup - same as per usual.

description: A decent beginner climb or to teach someone stemming.  The first half of the climb is really easy followed by the 5.4 moves up high in the chimney.
location: Just around the corner from Prow-ess on the north side of the formation.
protection: Standard TR set up including cracks for small to medium cams located very close to the edge (horizontals)
Nuts, Cams, Hexes, nothing bigger than hand sized.  Standard top rope setup.

description: left of prowess

Seldom climbed.  Starts on the face left of the chimney separating Sunday and Everyday buttresses. Balancy climbing on thin edges and sidepulls straight up leads to a tricky short crack (crux)above the roof. Avoid the temptation to wander right and use the left edge of the chimney.
protection: Standard Blue Mounds toprope (long slings helpful)

description: Climbs the flaring short crack above the lower overhang.  Start a few feet left of Balcony Center going up the black face.  Engage the crack and sloping edges (crux) up to the balcony.  Finish up the left side of the balcony.
protection: Standard Blue Mounds toprope, long slings may be helpful.

description: Starts about 15 feet right of Balcony Right directly under a large protruding block on top of the cliff.  Face climb up to a break in the roof which initially includes a right-facing corner.  Crank over the roof (crux) head towards the right side of the overhanging block on top.
protection: Standard Blue Mounds toprope or lead with small to medium nuts/cams.

description: Very popular.  Begins underneath the right edge of the balcony going straight up the crack and shallow corner (crux).  Continue over the right edge of the balcony's roof.
protection: Standard Blue Mounds toprope (long slings helpful) or leadable with nuts, hexes, and small to midsized cams.

description: A must do at Blue Mounds.  As the name implies start up the crack and edges below the middle of the "balcony", muscle up on big flat edges.  Finish up the tricky center of the balcony roof (crux).
protection: Standard Blue Mounds setup, long slings may be helpful but not necessary for this one.

description: Up the obvious jamcrack which breaks slightly left.
location: On the left side of the Everyday buttress, before the everyday chimney, there is an obvious jamcrack up the face.
protection: Take big stuff if you intend to lead.

description: This route begins in the corner on the north face of the buttress.  Climb up through puzzling corners either straight up (harder) or slightly right (easier).
A fun although not entirely obvious route.  Locate a small crack in the top of the buttress between X and Z.  Find holds on the face working your way to this crack and the top.

X is the crack route at the right edge of Chimney Buttress's large roof.  Start up the left side of the crack eventually moving to its right side.  Continue over the small roof (crux) and up on easier terrain.
protection: Very protectable with nuts, medium to small cams, and hexes for the old schoolers or use a standard Blue Mounds toprope (long slings helpful).

description: middle crack
Roofs goes up a broken crack system to an overhang (crux) and left facing corner.  The crack stays wet longer than almost any other route at Blue Mounds.  This route is a testy lead for the grade.
location: Starts in the crack about 15 feet right of Chimney Buttress's left edge.
protection: Protectable (when dry) with nuts, small to medium cams, and probably hexes; otherwise use a standard Blue Mounds toprope (long slings helpful).

description: A face climb going straight up the center of Chimney Buttress's large roof.  Subdue the roof with a tricky sequence, continue up on slightly easier terrain.
location: Begins about 15 feet right of the route Roofs.

description: climb arete, bottom is crux.
location: Left (South) end of buttress.

description: Crummy climbing up the dihedral and into the off width above.  It was a long time ago that I did this one so maybe it isn't as bad as I remember it being.
location: Locate it using the huge off width looking crack half way up.
protection: Standard TR set up.  Long webbing helpful.

description: The Horizontal Tango starts up the dihedral in between Seduction and Rejection and In and Out.  Follow this dihedral up to the roof and continue straight up or stay in the crack that works to the right a bit for a harder version.
location: Up the dihedral in between "Seduction and Rejection" and "In and Out."
protection: Standard TR set up.  Long slings are helpful as usual.

description: good sequential climb
location: Located on chimney buttress in between jugs of whine and roofs

description: Follow the crack straight up the big roof.  There are a lot of jugs throughout this section that make the roof very manageable.  Watch out for cactus at the ledge half way up.  Finish by working right after gaining the big ledge, ending on the face of the giant block at the top.
location: Just north and around the corner from X, Y, Z, it's the thin crack that goes straight up the roof.

description: A short little route that might feel slightly hard for its grade.  Begin climbing the scattered features directly below the corner overhead.  Get your hands in the crack above the roof and transition to a pumpy layback (if that's how you choose to do it) with small slick foot holds.
location: The northern-most route on Chimney Buttress, Boy Howdy follows the corner with a layback crack.
protection: Standard TR set up.  A few long slings may be helpful.

description: This wide crack is on your right when you enter the cave just north of Z.  It sees little traffic and is usually dirty.  Follow this crack straight up and emerge out of the chimney above.  Practice your stemming by using the opposing wall on your way up.
location: Inside the cave to the right (north) of Z.
This route follows the prominent crack on the right end of this buttress.
protection: Large hexes and cams from #1-#4 or #5 (camalot), preferably with doubles of #4.

description: Slightly overhanging flakes and jugs, Left of Oath
climb face to ledge, up crack/dihedral/chimney.
location: Left side of large ledge, left of Oath of Fealty and Destination Unknown
protection: TR, or standard rack to lead.

description: Climb straight up the right side of the shallow pillar.  Pull on rocks that look loose to get up on to the Buffalo's Buldge. Pull on flakes and pockets to the top. Don't stray over to the left or right climbs...aka...the climb is a little contrived, butt fun.
location: Look for the buldge/face between Oath and Destination.
protection: standard anchor - can use the same one from Destination

description: Gain a ledge about eight or ten feet up.  A left facing dihedral with an obvious handcrack leads up from there.  Negotiate straight over a small bulge and youre done.
location: To the left and around the courner from Celtis Crack. Left facing dihedral.

first_ascent: Sam Smolnisky and Nora Olson Maybe?
description: Start in the chimney left of Destination Unknown.  Gain a ledge and work your way up the dihedral using the crack.  Crack is short but sweet.
location: Located about 10ft left of Desination Unknown.

description: Start in some foliage under a tree and break through the small canopy and onto the rock face about ten feet up.  From here go up the pedestal and then the crack/dihedral above which includes the crux.
location: Leftmost crack.

description: Follow the crack up on the right side of Bottom Boulders.  The cruxes involve cranking on loose rocks, diminishing the quality of an otherwise nice climb.
location: North-most route on Bottom Boulders.  Follow the crack system straight up.

description: The route is a little thin in places but all there. Best advise is to take your time and think before you move, don't just throw for holds.
location: Right of Piernas Borraches and left of Save Me Tree.

description: Climbs up one of the prettiest walls in blue mounds with purple rock and bright yellow lichen. The crux is low.  It's a shame this climb isn't longer or it would be an area classic.
location: On the south side of the buttress (walk partway up the gully to access).  Climbs the obvious crack with yellow lichen all over the wall.
protection: Standard blue mounds, long webbing for TR.  As for the lead I didn't really pay attention (was on TR), there are definitely placements low but I don't remember up high.

description: Go up on the pedestal. Hug the pedestal with some compression-style climbing including heel hooks and slaps.
protection: Probably best as a TR route but feel free to look for placements. There is an assortment of cracks at the top for a top-rope anchor.

description: obvious crack through roof follow big flake

Start on the arete just left of the yellow lichen, possibly standing on a rock to get started, then follow edges and side-pulls straight up. Hard climbing right off the ground gets easier as you get higher.
protection: Long slings are helpful for TR set up.

description: Begin easy climbing straight up the middle of the face to the big ledge half way up, then climb the right-facing corner to the top. There is a large loose chockstone in this corner system a few moves into it. The crux is surpassing the first couple moves in the dihedral. There are adequate protection opportunities for lead climbing.

Pedestal Left follows the crack up the dihedral on the left side of the pedestal as the name implies. It's a good choice for beginners or for getting comfortable with leading on quartzite. The crux lies about halfway up after which the rock becomes more featured. Protection is adequate for lead climbers.

This is an interesting variation on Pedestal Left.  Use the same stat as P.L, go up a few feet and look left.  You'll see a small bulge/roof.  Head left (towards the arete) moving underneath the roof.  Climb up the left side of the bulge and continue at a diagonal up and to the right near where P.L tops out.
protection: Std rack - cams/nuts up to 4.  Nothing unusual.  Use Bigger cam to protect crux.

description: A short but fun route on the climber's right side of the south face.  Follow edges up the thin crack.  Some good holds can be found in the crack in addition to small but ample footholds.  It's a bit dirty as you get higher.

Begin five feet right of Pedestal Right going straight up easy climbing to a ledge halfway up.  From here go up and slightly right to interesting face climbing (crux). Can feel much harder when the sun is baking this climb and you forgot your chalk bag.
protection: Standard TR set up. Long slings helpful. Not a good lead probably.

description: Northern-most route on Yellow Lichen. Mostly easier climbing leads to the crux up high (last ten feet to the top-out). The tree is gone.
location: The farthest north (climber's right) route on Yellow Lichen.

description: A face climb 4 feet to the right of last grasp
location: second route on Boke's buttress

description: Climb up to the third ledge on the left side of the buttress, then step right to the nose.
location: left side of boke's buttress

description: Up the middle of the face toward a small depression at the top.
location: right side of Boke's buttress

description: Tree ledge, berry brothers... have fun on this botanical adventure. Start below a tilted , flat top boulder just right of the hikers trail leading to the top.
location: first good route to the right of hikers trail.

description: Shorter climb up the crack with no real layback moves to speak of - but maybe I did it wrong?  Still fun.
location: The furthest left route on this buttress... the obvious large crack right of the break in the buttresses.
protection: Definitely not a lead for the 5.7 leader.  Pro is very bad.

description: Start on the left side of the buttress as you would for Layback Crack and then follow the obvious line of holds about a quarter of the way up that start moving right out onto the face.  Keep going right and follow the holds to the top.

A fun but contrived little route to try if you happened to be climbing on the adjacent cracks.  Ascend the face between Cussin' Crack and Noseprick while staying away from the cracks.  Fun and balancy face climbing on crimpers the whole way.
location: In between Cussin' Crack and Noseprick.

description: Noseprick is the second crack counting from the climber's right.  Polished footholds make up the crux a little over half way up the crack.
protection: Standard TR set up, long slings helpful.

description: The Klinger is the line which goes up the face between Noseprick and Incapacitation until reaching the small crack halfway up. It is the fourth crack from the left.
Fun, easy climbing on a short face. The crack is a bit vegetated in places. This is the right-most crack on the many cracks buttress.
protection: TR or a couple hand sized pieces for leading.

description: Very similar in style and appearance to Stinger. This is a stout top-rope problem up the steepest part of the bulge on the many cracks buttress. The route starts on the easy ledges in the access gully, then at 10 feet the route starts on painfully small edges then moves into powerful side-pulling then a crux high-step and deadpoint to the one good jug. Several more 5.10+ moves on dirty rock will take you to the top.
Climb blocky stuff with ease for five to ten feet then follow the crack and find the crux about 3/4 of the way up.  My vote is 5.8, but I've entered the guidebook rating of 5.8+.
location: The fourth crack counting from the climber's right (not counting The Klinger.)
protection: Standard TR set up.  There are solid cracks for your anchor on this one (big 3"-4" cams helpful.)

description: A short Top-rope problem on the bulging face 5-10 feet right of Incapacitation. Long powerful reaches to huge jugs on a steep face.

Go up the crack to the overhang on the left side of the east face. As you near the top look out for birds and thorny plants.  I found numerous skeletons of dead animals so depending on the time of year you might have to contend with wild creatures for a good spot to belay from.
location: We lowered off the south face, where Couch Potato should be, and the last guy down climbed the 5.4 (Couch Potato). If you arn't too excited about that down climb, you could probabily find a better way around to the west or find a way to rap off.
protection: There are plenty of places to use smaller nuts and cams.

description: Climb directly up past the right edge of the long overhang. A little over half way up a nice dihedral will lead you the rest of the way to the top.
protection: You may have to start out going toward the right corner to find a place for gear if you are leading this. Around back of the buttress is a Class 3 chimney you can boulder on up if you don't want to mess with leading.

description: easy climbing low then muscle your way through the two roofs with little feet and finish the thin crack to top
On the south face, start up a dirty leaning corner just right of the large tree.  Follow the crack and edges up to easier climbing.
location: Start just right of the large tree on the south face.
protection: Standard BM toprope.  Long webbing can be useful.  Gear placements may be tricky.

description: The west face of the tower hosts a crimpy little affair.  Tough moves right off the ground give way to easier terrain up high.
location: West face (faces the main cliffline) of Sun Drop II Tower.  Lead or solo Burnt-Out Candle around the corner to set up a TR.
protection: Toprope setup with nuts and hexes.

description: Climb the podium several feet right of Into The Sun and continue to the roof. Move left around the corner (crux) and finish on the easy climbing of Into The Sun.
protection: TR as for Into The Sun

description: Excellent route up the Arete (to the far right of Into the Sun).  Fun and pumpy! :)
location: Straight up the well defined Southeast Arete
protection: Small gear TR Setup on top of the tower

description: This climb isn't on sun drop tower. It's 30 steps to the north on the west wall. Not sure what that piece of rock is called?
protection: Cams for leading, nuts for a anchor up top.

description: A short route that starts on the northwest arete.
protection: Toprope with nuts and hexes.  Long slings not necessary.

description: The South face of Sun Drop II Tower.  Starts on obvious edges moving straight up the face on edges, sidepulls, gastons, a full hand pinch, and one good rest.  The route eases considerably after the first two-thirds.
location: About 30 yards before the Quarry break left on a steep trail up to the cliff line, go west for about 10 yards...can't miss it.
protection: Toprope with nuts and small hexes.  Long slings not necessary

description: The easiest way to the top of this feature.  Start in the dihedral and gain the big ledge.  Here you can plug in some gear to protect the 5.5 face move if you aren't soloing.  Be cautious of cranking hard on the holds near the crux since they are part of a detached block (can be seen at the bottom of the main photo.)  Easy climbing to the top.
location: Start in the dihedral with the chock stone, go up.

description: Easy climbing on the left side of the tower is the way to set up a top rope.  Not really worth doing except to TR other routes.  No anchor at the top of the tower so you may want to downclimb this to get off.
right corner of buttress
Crux is first couple moves
location: On the left edge of the south face
protection: Toprope, could be lead would probably need a pad to protect the first couple moves and plug gear in the horizontal seam half way up.

description: Listed in Farris Falcon guide book. Climb up left side of pillar. Finish to the top after manteling pillar¬†to find the crux. Remember to check the view.
location: Right of Inca Roads- on the left as you enter into the quarry.
protection: Tree and cams to a power point.

description: Start on SE corner and continue directly upwards on far left side of east face.
Straight up over the initials "W.S." a bit right of the arete.
location: on the east face of the WS buttress

description: face climb right up the middle of a large boulder.
location: follow the Bur Oak trail from climbers parking lot  furthest left route on rock tall enough to justify a top rope.

description: Through the weakness in the overhang a few feet right of "Short Hop"
location: located on the east face of WS buttress

description: climb is located five feet right of Brianna
location: located on the mirage boulder

description: This beautiful corner starts with series of juggy power pulls into a nice stance before entering the Crux. The feet go away - some jamming and stemming bring you up to a 5.9 move above gear. Mantle out the top, place a small piece, and head straight up on easy ground.
location: Follow the bar trail south to the last section of rock tall enough to deserve a rope. The corner faces SE.

description: Fifteen feet left of "Short Hop" Up a left facing dihedral, then move right around the overhang.
location: on the south facing side of the buttress.

description: Climb the south face of the buttress, left of a large inset.
location: this climb is topped by a large rounded rock

description: on the east face just right of the southeast arete.
location: located on the mirage boulder
on the right side of the south face

description: Face and chimney on the left side of south face.

route_name: It Ain't Over til It's Over
description: Move up and a bit left on nice edges between the two overhangs that guard the ends of this block.
location: Climbs the obvious east face about 40 feet left (south) of Elm Tree Pinch.
protection: Standard Blue Mounds set-up.  Long slings are useful.  Access via the gully to the left of this route.

description: Up the center of the east face to a difficult roof with a thin crack.

location: This route is on Hidden buttress about 8 ft right of the hidden direct. Bushwack your way uphill from the acute corner. This climb has several trees at the base which must be climbed through.
protection: TR, might want a helmet if you plan on falling into the wall behind you.

description: face and OW on right side of south face.
Climb the south facing panel immediately left of Elm Tree Pinch on nicely spaced edges and horizontal breaks.
location: Start immediately left of the crack system on Elm Tree Pinch.
protection: Standard Blue Mounds toprope set-up.  Long slings helpful.  This route can be led with small to medium cams in the horizontal breaks.  Small to medium nuts could also be used.

description: Is a few feet to the right of Acute Corner and will be a black streak just above. Just like Acute Corner the crux is down low.
location: can easily get to the top by going by sundrop tower and up
protection: standard bm top rope set up I like to set a nut with a leash to down climb to ledge

description: Stay on right side of pillar- stay off side wall for true 9.
location: Can‚Äôt miss it walking into the quarry

description: Climb the face left of the Headbanger Crack. First half is mild, second half is a contender for hardest 5.9 in the park...the final kneebar move is key to sending this route.
location: Left of Headbanger crack on Quarry buttress.

description: Climb up center of pillar using thin crack to reach the roof. Go directly over. Don‚Äôt forget to heal.
location: Right of Thriller Pillar, just before entering the open quarry.
protection: Tree and cams to power point or quad

description: Sharing this¬†route is listed in the MN/WI Mike Farris Falcon guide book.
location: Just right of Static Cling

description: A spooky, wide crack/chimney with lots of loose junk.  If you insist on climbing it, keep your belayer and others well uphill out of the fall line. - M. Farris
location: The first large crack and chimney to the left of the corner.

description: Chimney up a few feet to a corner on the arete.  Follow corners to the top. - M. Farris
Sustained climbing that actually looks harder than it is - start in the Dihederal 6 feet to the left (South) of the Acute Corner.  Tackle the bouldery dihederal and then don't pump out up the face.
location: Dihederal to the left (South) of the Acute Corner and to the right of the large Headbanger crack.

description: A great line.  Start on the prow under the roof.  Fight through the low bouldery start, then onto easier climbing up the arete.  The holds are all great!  M. Farris put it best - "A gym climber's delight."
location: On the very corner.

description: large crack

Start just left of the Offwidth crack and move up to gain the small pedestal.  Negotiate the slightly overhanging face to the top.  Watch out for the hollow flake eventhough it seems to be the only hold.
location: Between Coyote Blues and Off Width

description: start on obvious crack to ledge then protect the thin seem with micro nut find poor feet and move up crux.
location: thin crack in between offwidth and deceptive ledge

description: to the ledge, and up
left corner of buttress
Begin standing on small flat stone, move up the easy arete slab to the top of the boulder.
location: left side of the north face of the summer boulder

description: Begin standing, use jugs in the roof and the flake/arete to surmount the roof. Easy problem, beautiful vantage.
location: center of the east face of the summer boulder, start on obvious jug under roof.

description: Climb the far left side of the Summer wall face using the large ledges for the right hand and the corners for the left. Stand start, avoiding the roof.
protection: Route is over very bad landing so not falling is advisable, otherwise a couple pads.

description: Some of the best finger crack in Duluth, this climb eats gear up and is a great lead!  If it were longer it could hold it's own anywhere!  The crack proper starts about 15 feet up the face but the bottom is fun as well...
location: The obvious finger crack (it is blacker than the rest of the face...)

description: The slab!  Thin climbing on dime edges...good TR but no way to protect it for leading.  Maybe a highball boulder problem?
location: The slab on the First Street side.

description: This covers all of the current "routes" in this area.  All follow crimpy lake stones with not much variation.  A dihedral route is possible, as is mantling on a small ledge and pulling some sick roof moves in the tunnel.  All are pretty fun...all can be slimey...but nonetheless, get out there and get on it...someone put a lot of work into this!
Slightly less chossy than the others. Gets worse at the top in terms of loose rock.
location: Above the large rock at the base, follows the flatter face to the left of California Roll.

protection: Three bolts at the top from which to set up a top-rope.  Bring webbing or long slings as quickdraws will not clear the edge of the cliff.

description: Crack problem.  THe start is the most difficult part.  I have cleaned this a lot but it is still a bit dirty.  Good warm up for working projects.
location: only crack on the boulder

description: start on the right side of the arete left of tiger blood the first two holds are good and then it goes almost blank untill the top.  possiblibty for a huge dyno?
location: left of tiger blood
protection: a few pads and a spotter as the landing is not flat

description: start the same as tiger blood but move right out of the crack into terrible rails.  Not sure if this can even be done but just putting it out there.  Would be super hard
location: start the same as tiger blood but move right around half way up

description: Difficult start on a rail and crimp your way through 3 small holds.  Crux is making a huge throw off of the tiny crimps to a decent jug.  sure to be a tough send.  I am only guessing at the grade but i know it's harder then V7 and probably V8.  Have worked this for over a year and gotten no where close to getting it.
location: starts on the left side of the north arete

description: Crumbly like fried rice, would need some major cleaning but could be fun if done.
location: 10 feet to the right of the boulder at the base of the wall. Goes up and to the right of the bush halfway up the wall.

description: The middle route of the sushi routes. Named California roll because it is simple and most people like it. Watch where you grab as there is a decent amount of loose rock. Would need to be cleaned to be more than one star rated.
location: Right of the large boulder at the base of the face, goes straight up, to the left of the shrub halfway up the wall.

description: The right side of the slab...lots of big holds on this one!  Not a bad way to retreat if you opt to boulder the slab.
Impress your friends by free soloing this ~5.3.
location: on the west/1st side, far to the left. A bit left of "Unknown 1"

description: Free soloing this will make you feel almost as hardcore as Alex Honnold.
location: on the west/1st side, far to the left

description: Thin face and horizontal crack climbing up frictionless rock...fun climb!
location: Just to the right of The Alcove

description: The start is about 4 feet east of the crack on the 1st St side, start on the featureless bulge, scramble up the midsection and then pull through the overhang. The crux is definitely the first few moves
location: 1st St Side of the wall, Just left of route 14 in the Duluth Urban Cragger book.

description: Thin face climbing on hard to find edges.  It really is a question of balance (and reach!)
location: Piedmont side of the rock!

description: Face climbing just to the right of The Lord is Coming Wall.  Pretty straight forward up rock with poor friction.  Can be Top Roped from the same anchor as Stove, The Alcove and Lord is Coming.
location: Right side of the face that makes up the Alcove, Stove and Lord is Coming.

description: Fun romp up the face to the right of Stove...used to bear spraypaint that warned the lord is coming (apparently) but this gone now.
location: Right of Stove
protection: A few nuts or better yet, just TR this...

description: Starts near drill hole to right of 3rd class gully. Gets a little slabby at the end.
location: Left side of Woopee Wall's main face.

description: Climb the corner between "The Iron Bar" and "Contrived". Moves up and left near the top out of "The Iron Bar". Beware of the rusty metal at the top. Set up your toprope on trees above, be sure to protect the edge well.
location: Walk down piedmont past the area with "Stove" and "The Lord is coming" until you can see the far-right area shown in pictures. Walk up a small overgrown hill and some steep rock to get to this area. This one starts on the inside corner between "The Iron Bar" and "Contrived"

description: Climb the arete avoiding the namesake of the route (a rusty iron bar and wires stuck in the rock). Falling could be dangerous because of the bar. Set up your toprope on trees above, be sure to protect the edge well.
location: Walk down piedmont past the area with "Stove" and "The Lord is coming" until you can see the far-right area shown in pictures. Walk up a small overgrown hill and some steep rock to get to this area.

description: easy 5.6 climbing broken up by three ledges, maybe a 5.8 move or two if you shy away from the cracks
location: on piedmont side

route_name: I Need To Know Where This Relationship is Going
description: Starts to the right of "Contrived". Face climb, crimp anything you can find, and work your way straight up. Walk down piedmont past the area with "Stove" and "The Lord is coming" until you can see the far-right area shown in pictures. Walk up a small overgrown hill and some steep rock to get to this area.
location: Walk down piedmont past the area with "Stove" and "The Lord is coming" until you can see the far-right area shown in pictures. Walk up a small overgrown hill and some steep rock to get to this area. It starts on the face to the right of "Contrived".

description: Short face with some horizontal cracks. Fun boulder problem although a little tall for some.  Watch for glass at the bottom.
location: To the left of "The Alcove" on the east face of Whopee Wall off Piedmont Ave.
protection: A few nuts, or a pad to boulder it.

description: Fun, crimpy and balancy.  The bottom has lots of roots and a big tree near so it is most often TRed, but has been bouldered by some
location: Off of Piedmont Ave, the farthest route to the left before you get to the approach to "Question of Balance".  Easy downclimb exists just to the left of this route.

description: A pumpy flake/face climb with terrible feet to the right of "Knife Edge". Pull hard and walk yourself up to the positive part of the edge, work your way left along the roof and top out in the obvious corner. Set up your toprope on trees above, be sure to protect the edge well.
location: Walk down piedmont past the area with "Stove" and "The Lord is coming" until you can see the far-right area shown in pictures. Walk up a small overgrown hill and some steep rock to get to this area. This one starts at the obvious "D" shaped block of rock to the right of "Knife Edge".

description: Route #8 in the Urban Cragger.
location: Between routes "If at First - 5.6" and "The Alcove - 5.6"

description: A dark and sometimes wet crack...not a bad lead but not much to it...
location: Piedmont side...it's obvious

description: Short, bouldery line approximately 10 feet left of George of the Jungle. Crux is shoulder wrenching on very small edges.
location: just left of George of the Jungle on the Buttress behind Square Block buttress. Both routes are only 20 ft tall or so.

route_name: The Tree Made Me Do It
description: Sit start on the right side of the tree. Work left on undercling rail being careful not to dab on the tree. After you're on the left side of the tree the problem turns into a rad compression boulder with heel and toehooks.
location: Start on the lowest part of the arete to the right side of the tree.

description: This route follows up the arete, stand start on flat ledge and small crimp above your head. slap up to higher ledges and hit a crimp on the face. continue up the arete and top out with spotters ready.
location: This is the Right most line on the cliff band.
protection: A few pads are nice, the landing is half on a boulder, coming out from the rock.

description: Obvious line strait up cliff band, great problem with and easy start, crux is getting your self established on sloping side pull rail and throwing for jug rail.
location: when you walk up the trail to the boulder this it the first route you come to. Route made obvious by sloping rail 15 feet up.
protection: a few pads and a spotter, the more pads the better. It is a flat landing but a fall from the top would still hurt.

description: One hard move to the lip joins with a few more moves into Gaia. Instead of heading around the boulder, head directly up and the point, and ascend into the heavens and join Uranus.
location: Start on face, two gastons.
This is on the backside of the Quarry Boulder. To get to the slab, climb to the top and walk down to the end of the slab and start there.
protection: If you do happen to fall, which you shouldn't, your gonna go over the edge and onto some rocks. So be sure to have a spotter with a pad or two. This is why I gave it a PG-13, although it doesn't deserve that safety rating, I just didn't want anyone to get mad at me if they fell and busted themselves up if only gave it a G.

route_name: Rain With a Chance of Boulders
description: This is the clean line up the northeast face of the quarry boulder (the backside). It features pristine holds and fun exposure. Enjoy your first jug because all you have left is a crimp and then slopers!
location: Located on the northeaster side of the large boulder in the center of the abandoned quarry.

description: Begin on low edges and work your way up to the high right hand edge (v4). Match hands on the edge and move through difficult pinching and a powerful gaston finishing with a long reach around the roof to a mono slot (v6). Set up on the pair of sloping edges just right of the slot and make a committing dead-point to a good three finger edge one more committing reach right and a high step take you to the top out jugs (v3). CLASSIC!
protection: Pads and a spotter to protect you from a large rock behind the landing if you plan on doing the final moves.

description: Begin on low edges and work your way up to the high right hand edge (v4). Heel-hook and make a powerful reach to a left hand sloper, the crux is a difficult compression move while traversing left. Finish on the easy south face.

Want to do the committing final moves of Pieta without having to climb all those darn roofs? This route is a bit contrived but sure is a ton of fun. Stand start as for David, once on the large holds traverse about seven feet right (v1). Once established on the pair of sloping edges on Pieta make the final dead-point move and reach for the top!

Start bottom left with everything else. Continue right, past Pieta and wrap around the other side of the boulder. Climb the obvious line that follows all the way around this gigantic goddess of a boulder!
location: Start on low left holds.

description: SDS on nice big crimps on both side of arete. Pull up and onto feet near the bottom of arete. Work a bouldery sequence to either deadpoint or just got for it hold on the outter rim. Hold is good and can match both hands. Work final movement to the tip of point and up.
location: Backside. Obvious overhung arete

description: Sit start with both hands on an under cling start. Working your way up to finish with a heel hook.
location: If you take the main hiking trail south past the Farmhouse Boulders, you should come to the Sixth Sign Boulder on the west side of the path. There are two boulders on the west side of the path and one on the east. The one on the east side of the path is the boulder with the Route F.W.S.
protection: Bring a crash pad or two.

description: Crack left of ATV
location: crack 5 feet left of ATV

description: SDS on two pockets and move up using side pulls and pockets till you make a dynamic move to a large jug half way p the wall(crux).  Hike your feet up and make a big move out left to a good hold and head for the top avoiding the crack
location: middle of the wall
protection: as many pads as you can get and a spotter

description: A fun climb to do if you want something easier and are already in the area.  A helmet isn't a bad idea on this awkward climb since people seemed to be bumping their heads a lot.  Go straight up the wide crack in the corner to the left of Poison Vines.
Start standing on a small boulder, climb directly up on big holds.
location: South face of quarry boulder.
protection: The starting boulder presents a problem but if you move a little to the right after getting established you can be protected well by a pad.

description: Up the crack on the south side of L-Buttress.  Solid pro for leading.  The crux is the last ten feet to the top out.  Another fun Blue Mounds crack that sees little traffic.
location: The south side of L-Buttress.

description: Began very near the left side of the large roof below the outside corner.  Once on top of the roof, stay between the outside corner and the Poison Vines crack.
location: South face of L-Buttress underneath the left side of the roof. Starts lower about 7 feet lower than the rest of the south-face climbs.
Ten feet right of Hammer, straight up the face.
protection: Standard TR set up - small/medium nuts and cams.  Long slings are helpful.

description: First crack around the corner right of Loose Rock.
location: See Above.

description: The first crux is getting to the second crux without falling. Maybe start middle, working up left then straight right back to middle. From there head up middle on small or sloping holds. Stay out of cracks on either side.
location: Face climb in between Power Booster and Poison Vines. Don't use crack on either side

description: One arms length left of Power Booster.
location: One arms length left of Power Booster.

description: Climb through the wide bottom section until you reach a smaller crack off right.  Move up the crack and for an aesthetic finish and slightly exposed sensation, work slightly left at the top and finish on the face instead of the notch off right.  Great on lead, watch out for hollow and loose rock about halfway up.
location: Climber's left around the corner from Pojama People.
protection: Standard rack.  Eventhough it looks wide, you can manage without wide gear.

description: crux is a pinch.
location: East face of square block, up darker colored rock.

description: just left of the ar√™te on the south face
On the east face, begin on the corner just below the enormous roof.  From here go more or less straight up, wandering a bit at times to find holds.  The crux is the last 15' or so.
location: Up the corner under the roof and straight up from there.

description: Just left of Pojama People using same anchor.
finger crack behind the boulder between blockhead and glacier calf moo, crack to grassy mantle on ledge then finish crack up
Follow crack up short face.
location: This route is the obvious crack on the buttress just left and behind the Square Block Buttress.

description: Line follows the arete on the right side of square block buttress up to and over the roof. Crux is pulling the roof.
location: Right arete on square block buttress.

description: 5 feet left of seasons opener hard start leads to easier climbing

Start at the far left end of the crack and traverse horizontally up to your right negotiating the crack and feet on obvious foot holds. Traverse fully to the right hand corner and top out on corner. Great climb lots of fun.
location: Main horizontal crack on West face.

description: This climb follows up the obvious arete on the Road Weary wall. Sit start on crimp and or undercling with feet at or below "ground" level. climb up to crux using a hold just to your right and up to jugs at top. The very top is blank but is easy with large jugs to stand on.
protection: A few pads will be fine, and maybe a friend to pluck you out of the air would be nice.

description: Start with hands on ledge above the "W". Wing your way over to the arete, then up the east face. Crux is a set of sharp crimps on arete.
location: right side of east face, Craig's Cave.

description: Sit start on the south face, up on large holds that all slope the same way. Top out at the apex.
location: South face with black coloration in the center.

description: Sick route with a scary top out that will make you almost wet your pants. Easy start that transitions into a more powerful and technical set of beta to get yourself secure on the thin vertical crack. The crux is getting to the top out because you're high off the ground and your feet feel insecure. There are good enough hand holds and you just have to trust your feet to get over the top!
location: Start at the same starting holds as Bulbasaur. I start with a nice underling, a high left foot, and a smear with my right foot. Work your way left on the easy horizontal crack and then go straight up following a gnarly thin vertical crack. work your way all the way to the top while squeezing your butt cheeks because of how scary and and how insecure your feet feel going over the top for the finish. Bonus points if you yell "help!" towards the top because you know you'll fall haha.
protection: We used at least 3 pads and always had at least 1 spotter

description: The movement on this plus the super fun topout make it a must. I cleaned off a serious amount of crap to get to this boulder, so you should humor me by climbing it. Pull right from the sit start and work up the horizontal cracks to a beautiful right hand crimp above a mossy platform (avoid the platform).  Straight up to an apparent slope and top out using the deepest diagonal crack ever.
location: The rightmost of two obvious routes on the wall that share a central sit start (sit start is bottom right of main picture). It is excellent for the grade and has some of the most improbably nice crimpers you'll find around. You will recognize it by several horizontal cracks that are too sweet for Duluth.
protection: A pad for sure and possibly an extra to cover the rock ledge in case of a slip. Spotter is helpful.

location: just right of S.P. or left around the corner from the Blank, finish on the blank slab.
protection: spotter to protect head and neck from the boulder behind the start.

description: Start low (sit) on the East Corner and climb the slab. Cruxes are the start and transitioning onto the slab.
Start near C.V. up arete
start at H.M. strait up.

Sit start with left hand on the corner and right hand on right corner, feet smeering. Work left hand up left corner and right hand up right corner. Top out straight up the face, friction and good smeering is a must. Strong but classic line!
location: The Northwest end/face of the Northwest boulder. Route is between the left corner and the right hand sloping corner.

description: SDS in the triangle hold and a two-finger pocket just beneath it. Pull straight up and work up the large crack with your left hand and hit the beautiful rail. Finish off with style.
location: Farthest right route before corner. Corner is off. There is also a low rail left of the large crack that is not on. See beta pic.

description: This route is a hard slab and contains not many good hands. Thought the hardest part may be the feet when moving from the first few holds to above the green house. You can use the crack right by the 3rd to the right paw finger. Also to top out use the horizontal crack.
location: Slab Dive is to the left of the middle crack on the slab face of WSB.

description: This route is a good warm up that only uses 4 holds. Start on the obvious lower drill hole, and continue from a silver ledges to the second drill hole, top out from there. This route requires balance and may be hard for kids due to the long reaches. Be careful to not crimp to hard on the drill holes because they can be sharp. Avoid using the crack in the middle of the face as well.
location: This route lies to the right of the crack going through the middle of the slab face. It is the middle route on the slab face. It also tops out in the middle of the slab face.

description: SDS same as for Huckleberry Hooch move out left and straight up using the crack left Huckleberry Hooch and the left corner. Move up on good but committing holds.
location: south face

description: This route requires good body tension. A lot of this route also need opposition. The start is the obvious first drill hole on the slab face move up the left side of a silver dihedral using arete holds. This whole line follows a curve that the arete creates.
location: This route is located on the slab face of WSB. It is to the right of drill hole direct, and to the left of the silver dihedral arete, that separates the south face of the boulder and the slab face.

description: Same start as Unknown (2), but instead of topping out on the jug, move left to side pull then top out.
Crux is moving up the small crimpers.
location: The problem starts just to the right of North Arete. Start by matching on a jug and working right and up.

description: Start on right side of the roof. Worth through the roof using good edges. Make a long reach back, place a heel and match hands. Cut feet and make a long campus to a blocky ledge. Top out.
location: Only problem in the roof right now.

description: Short and dirty. Sit start on the down hill side of the north face and ride the lip until you hit the arete. Head straight up from there. The crux is not dabbing on a small rock that follows the line.
location: North side of the Red Green Show boulder.

description: Sit start on good edges with a right heel. Work through a couple of amazing crimps and compression moves. Head straight up to a tricky top out.
location: This problem is located on the South side of the boulder underneath an obvious overhang.

description: Stand start on good juggy ledges. Work straight up to the lip. The crux of the boulder is topping out. Easiest way is to traverse left on the lip before pressing it out.
location: On the South, overhanging side of the boulder.

description: Variation of Red Green Show that works out left using small crimps under the roof to a credit card crimp on the left face. Use the arete and a few holds on either side to work your way up to a potentially¬†comical finish on the left face.
location: Same as for Red Green Show.
protection: Two pads, a spotter would be nice.

description: This is the down climb for Red Green Show but hosts some amazing crimps and edges on a slight slab. Worth playing around on.
location: This problem is found on the West face (cliff side) of the boulder.

description: Sit start low on left hand pinch and right hand sidepull. Make a small move to an incut half pad crimp. Throw for a good ledge out right. Finish straight up.
location: Backside of the larger boulder.

description: Powerful and hard tension moves throughout. Cool toehook off the start. Make a huge move to either the slot or to the lip. Match hands on the lip, work the feet through and hit the slopey edge. From there, go straight up to top it out.
location: Sit start underneath Bernie's Last Stand to the right of the supporting block. Do not use the supporting blocks for feet. Left hand starts on a sidepull pinch and right is on a small crimp on the rail. Head out and left of the overhanging and finish on Bernie's Last Stand.

description: Establish on the arete and make a big move to a good edge. Match and finish straight up.
location: Below and slightly north of the Trump Boulders.

description: Start with left hand on edge on the arete and right hand on a small sidepull. Optional dyno to the lip or use some micro crimps to work through it. Short but fun.
location: On the smaller boulder holding up the larger one.

description: Sit start and work the lip with heel hooks. Finish through Bernie's Last Stand.
location: Left side of the main boulder as you approach the Trump Boulders.

description: Stand start at the lip. Make a few moves through some crimps and slopers.
location: Middle of the face as you approach the Trump Boulders.

description: Crux is getting in position to top out.
location: The problem is on the northwest arete. The problem starts below the tree. You have to go around the tree and you can't use it either...no kidding right?

description: There are 2 cruxes, the first is the transition from heel hook to bicycle hook. The second is the mantle to the top. I don't believe that this traverse has ever been sent. If any FA information is available please notify me. Until then the FA will remain as it is.
location: The route starts on the far left on two jugs.

description: Crux thus far is finding a start and getting off the ground. Then after you figure that out, you have to somehow throw into this tiny/painful finger lock. Then work your way all the way to the apex and top out.
location: The sit start is on the southeast arete. Trying to find a start is a problem in itself.

description: Crux is the move to the top.
location: West face. Start on the right side of the boulder. Match on the jug to start and finish with dynamic move to jug at the top. Fun problem as well as a great warm up.

description: Easy dirty slab on the northeast corner. Go Straight up to the left of the small rib like bulge.
location: north east face

description: Wild problem with an audacious landing. Sit start with hands high on the two good jugs, throw for the sloping side-pull over the lip and hang on for the swing. Crux is holding the swing and not dabbing. Top out is still a bit dirty.
location: The severely overhanging east face of the NQB
protection: Awful landing, stacked pads and spotters are a must.

description: Stand start with your hands stacked on left hand crimp and right hand on good edge about a foot and a half underneath the lip. Bump right hand to hold just below the lip and traverse left around the bulge. Reach far back to good rail on top. Throw a right heel and top out. The landing is in a pit and is hard to protect. Bring spotters and pads to keep it safe.
location: This problem is on the northeast corner of the boulder in the obvious overhang.

description: Excellent roof problem with fun moves. Start low on the rail with a heel-hook, make some moves out right under the ceiling, reach a sloping hold on the left lip then throw right to the large jug. Make the big reach over the roof and establish on the south slab using small sloping crimps. Would be an area classic were it not for the rib-cracking, dab inducing boulders under the roof.
location: SW corner
protection: Pads, preferably one thin pad to protect the lip of the boulder without further exacerbating the dab factor.

description: On the backside of the boulder there is a bulging, cooler size block sticking out. Sit start with hands on a pinch on the corner and a good crimp. Make a decent reach to an incut rail on the lip. Easy topout.
location: South side of the Neverland Boulder.

description: Sit Start. Climb the wide crack with some face-holds over large boulders and a large pit.
protection: Very uneven landing even with ample padding a fall could be nasty.

description: Stand start. Climb the south facing wall of the chamber just left of the trees. Easy 5th class climbing after reaching the ledge at 15 feet.

The Prow is a must-do classic problem for Blue Mounds! Wonderful big moves on perfect quality pink quartzite, slightly overhanging the whole way. Begin on the brick pinch. The crux is the long move to a sloping block, tiny feet for the crux section. Airy finish, Superb!
location: The obvious prow when approaching via the ORC wall.
protection: Several pads. This rock is tall.

description: Stand start in the pit. Using the large flat edges on the main cliff climb up and finish by moving slightly left to large top-out jugs.
location: On the cliff-line wall over a pit in the NW corner of the Chamber.
protection: The top of this climb is very exposed over a bad landing. (5.7)

description: Stand start with right hand on horizontal flat edge and left on gaston flat edge with one good foot. A consistent boulder problem with big moves to decent holds and a huge slap to a sloper high up off the deck.
location: The giving tree project on the face to the right of "The Prow".

description: Very nice looking slab. Down-climbing the Chamber Maid is the best way down from all the climbs which top out on the cliff-line.
location: North East corner of the Chamber

description: Sit start with right hand on excellent edge and left hand on the low side-pull. One big reach to good jugs.
location: The right side of the overhanging east face.

description: Stand start on the sloping hold and a pinch in the middle of the east face. Climb directly up while avoiding vines.
Sit start. Climb angular holds using toe hooks after the first few moves the climbing backs off for an easier top-out. Dab!
location: Left side of east face. Try not to dab on adjacent boulders.

route_name: Crocodile Who Swallowed an Alarm Clock
description: Start on low left hand undercling jug and a right hand down pulling edge. Make a long reach to a bad three finger one pad edge. Move your feet higher and make a huge deadpoint to start holds of The Project of Yesteryear. ¬†Finish on The Project of Yesteryear. Might be impossible or substantially harder if you're shorter than 6 feet tall.
location: Low start to The Project of Yesteryear on the north east corner of the boulder.

description: Starts low on crimps and moves up onto better crimps and a nice deep small crimp on the bulge. Go straight up to the point from here on a 2 finger crimp that you crank up onto. Kind of a scary committing top out.
location: North face of this block

description: Begin by sitting on one of the talus boulders with hands on the sloping ledge on the right side of the South face. Crux section is the first section of lie-backs. Do not fall off to the right!
location: Right side of the South face on lie-back features.
protection: Gnarly talus and a big drop off make this problem a bit hard to protect. Best to have several pads and spotters; regardless, avoid falling to the right.

description: Same start as the Psychologist V3 only once you hit the crimp on the bulge keep traversing right and throw up for a beautiful jug hold right before the lip. Both variations have been done straight up is slightly easier. The scary part of this climb is mantling the angled slab on the side if you dare.
location: north face

description: Short climb with big holds which still need some cleaning. Be careful not to hurt yourself getting off this boulder, downclimb the lichen covered slab and jump to the adjacent boulder to get off.
location: This is on the far left side of the South face of the NQB. Start sitting on one of the big talus boulders.
protection: Pads. Best not to fall off in the first place due to butt busting boulders.

description: Start matched on the block feature and make a huge throw to lip on the right. Pull yourself over and top out the boulder.
protection: Pads and spotters. Despite the jagged back-breaking talus. The fall is actually not too bad with properly placed pads.

description: Sit start on the big flake in the tunnel, then move left and top out on the north side. Unique movement. Easiest way off is by climbing to the top of the quarry then down-climbing by a tree.
location: Finishes on the North West Corner of the boulder.
protection: A couple pads to protect from jagged talus yet this is a short boulder.

description: High stand start several feet left of Blue Sunset. Possibly much harder moves with a lower start.
protection: Awful landing crash pads are mostly useless.

description: Face to the left of 4th Dimension fun smearfest and easy warmup to the area.
location: on the cube. To the left of the 4th Dimension.

description: Sit start sideways underneath the overhang. Feet paste on up high. Left hand starts on good rail and right on a small pinch. Huck for the jug about 4 feet off the ground. Swing out and grab some small crimps to hidden pocket in a sloping rail. Match and top out. If you start from the jug it goes at V4. Fun tricky line.
location: Right most line on the boulder. Starts in overhang underneath the boulder and supporting boulder.

description: Sit start underneath the overhang. Left hand on a long, horizontal crimp rail and right hand pinch on low arete. Kneebar on the supporting boulder and work right to the arete. The crux is finding a way to release from a wide wingspan. Top out is fairly easy. Landing is kind of sketchy but the hardest part of the problem is over by the time you get to that point.
location: This is the only problem on the boulder but a direct line could still be done without the use of the supporting boulder. Would go quite a bit harder.

description: This is a super unique line. Sure it's a lowball, but it is one of the best lines in the park. Sit start on a low rail. Find a heel and a toe, bump right hand to a slightly worse crimp, and toss for the lip. Topout is tricky but not bad.
location: This problem is on the South side of the boulder with a slight overhang. You'll see a clean face with a rail and a single crimp.

description: Start with one hand in the obvious, large hole and the other on a good crimp. Make a few moves up the slight slab and top out. Fun beginner line.
location: Find the dynamite hole on the main face of the boulder.

description: follow the obvious line that leads up the left corner on the face that faces West. Sit start.
location: The route starts on the west face of the cube or the face that the boulder gets its name from because it looks like a square or tipped cube. Sit start under the tiny overhang to the left and follow up the crack line that leans towards the left. The LEFT CORNER IS OFF.
protection: Crash pad(s) kind of rocky below a spotter?

location: The shallow crack in the middle of the boulder's east-facing side. About 4 feet to the right of the left-most (south-most) arete, and just a couple feet to the left of the More Momos.
protection: A spotter is highly recommended for the south and north face.

description: Prepare a few curse words for this one-trick-pony of a climb. Start on the ground and find the correct heel-hook / sloper / crimp combination that allows you to liftoff to a few wonderful edges just out of reach from the ground. Once you have the edges, follow them for more straight-forward V1 - 2ish action to the top.
location: This problem is about in the center of the boulder. Find the obvious crack with many blocky pieces and scoot about 3 feet to the right (north) of it. You'll find a couple of crimps at your disposal with all the real good stuff just out of reach. When you start complaining to your friend that you wish your arms were just a little longer, you're in the right spot.
While facing the east-facing side of the boulder, this problem starts on the north-most arete (the right side.) It is the furthest north start possible on the east face.
protection: One bouldering pad to protect the mantle. A second pad (or a spotter moving a pad) is nice to protect the start.

location: On the east-facing side of the boulder, find the south-side arete (the left arete, if facing the boulder face) and take a seat.

description: Could have been named "Momo's Mirror". Start sitting at the shallow crack in the middle of the boulder and use a heel hook to give you the chance to get off the ground. There are many options for starting handholds- use what works for you (so long as your butt is on the ground when you start!) Work straight up the shallow crack and finish with a mantle over the top.
location: The shallow crack in the middle of the boulder's east-facing side. About 4 feet to the right of the left-most (south-most) arete, and just a couple feet to the left of the (slightly easier) More Momos.

description: Sometimes too many trees is a bad thing. Start on the ground with your back near a young tree. Avoiding grabbing the loose rock (cleverly disguised as one of the few phenomenal hand holds on this boulder) makes this climb marginally harder. Scramble your way up, then duck right at the last move to avoid the overhanding branches of another tree hanging over the top of the boulder.
location: This problem is on the north-facing wall of the boulder. It start about in the center of boulder.
protection: Single bouldering pad and a spotter

description: SDS. Rather short climb on the blue colored south face of the Alpine Block. Lots of exposure!
location: South Face of the Alpine Block.
protection: Spotters and pads, do not fall off to the right!

description: Tackle a strenuous boulder problem (V4?) right off the ground that leads to an undercling at the roof, then do some stemming up the corner followed by 5.7 climbing to the top.
location: This is the next corner and roof system north of Fancy Feet.  An improbable start leads to a clean corner.

description: follow crack up the blackened wall, crux is the optional (and more aesthetic) finish up smooth overhanging face at the top of the route.
location: several feet left of large inset with roof. This route follows the blackish line with a crack until moving left onto smooth face at the top.

description: Easy crack/scramble between Fingers Games and Fortress Chimney.

Follow the main crack up the nose and the face to its left.  Easy climbing/good pro until the crack ends and you find the surprise ending.  Head into the crux with gear just below foot level in a nice horizontal crack.  Watch out for the rocks behind you if you fall.
Same start as Beetlewood (V1). Climb straight up the corner. Crux is the left hand sloper pull to the top out.
location: Same spot as Beetlewood (V1)

While walking along the Burr Oak trail, you'll eventually come to a spot where the trail has to squeeze between two large boulders. Beetlewood's boulder is behind the boulder on the left of the trail. There's a small gap (alley) behind the left boulder and the Beetlewood boulder with enough space to set up a couple pads.

description: Sit start on two wider areas in the crack that runs along the boulder and two bad feet, gain a heel/toe hook and slap up left to a crimpy sloper then work up to the right. short boulder, pretty physical.
location: West side of the boulder 10-15 feet north of the Bur Oak Trail.

description: Crux is body position and footing after first crossover. The route itself is fun!
location: Route is on the furthest boulder to the east. It starts on a juggy bulge on the southern arete. Work your way up and to the left along the arete which leads you to a fun top out!

description: Crux is first couple moves. Good short climb
location: Furthest south rock face on the first fortress butress

description: Right up the wide crack north of Finger Games.  Take a big piece or two for the bottom section if you lead it.  Very short.

Start to the left of the corner with a tree to the climber's right (edit: said tree has been cut down).  Find some interesting finger jams in the dihedral, where the crux comes early.  Then look for holds out right on the ar√™te and go straight up on slightly easier face climbing with the tree behind you.
Start up the crack with a big roof overhead.  Good holds will keep the grade in check but it is roofy for a 5.6.  Finish as desired, but whatever you choose expect to find plenty of lichen and dust.
Five feet left of finger games work the red dihedral through a series of crimps to glory holds to the top. Easier variation to the right once above the dihedral.
protection: Nuts couple cams for Toprope setup

route_name: A Fool and Their Beer Are Soon Parted
description: A series of roofs and overhangs for a pump-tastic climb. Start directly beneath the first roof and follow the dihedral up to the roof. Circumvent the first roof with the help of a ledge and chalk up for a second roof. Another small ledge and some fancy footwork bring you to the crux halfway up the climb. Figure out the beta to circumvent the final small overhang and celebrate with an easy final 10 feet!
protection: Top rope with long slings. If the slings are too short, the rope will drag harshly over a rough edge.

description: Low sit start under the north east corner. Sharp holds, fight the barn-door in the crux, move left, and up to the top.
location: North side of the Kanaranzi Boulder on the steep face with small, sharp, block features.

description: Same sit start as "Slap Happy" pull up on tiny crimps that are actually really good. Work some good angle work matching feet in the seams as you move along this traverse and up at the other end of the boulder. You could be a lazy climber like "Matt" :) and just smear feet but that looks silly and defeats this beautiful line. Traverse it matching hands to feet. V3. If you feel the need to monkey Traverse it, it clocks in round V0-V1.
location: Metamorphic rock

description: Sit start on the west corner of the boulder. Work up and to about the 2nd crack in the seam from here slap the top for non existent holds if you can stretch far enough you'll hit a nice knob to grab. Fun moderate problem hardest part is trying to pull up on nothing since you can't see the knob. Short fun and bouldery movement make this a great problem.
location: Metamorphic rock
protection: crash pads Great landing below, its really cleared out and just dirt and leaves below.

description: Middle of kanzanri boulder
Right crack of the inset.  Work your way up the crack until you can transition to the right face.  Use your fancy feet to dance up over the roof and continue up the dihedral to the summit
location: Right wide crack of the obvious inset.
protection: Bust out the big bros for this one.

description: This is the left side of the obvious inset.  Work your way up until you are under the roof.  Find some pro and jam your way through the roof.  Once you are above the roof, find some holds and struggle to the summit.  Crux is jamming through the roof and moving up the slightly offwidth crack to the obvious flake.  Protects well.
location: Right of Glacier Calf Moo.  Left crack or the obvious inset.
protection: WIDE WIDE WIDE.  Leave your nuts in your ruck sack and cast a large hex or two at this crack.

description: Follows the crack up the boulder on the west face. Starts on two side pulls and uses pretty obvious holds.
location: On the west face of the boulder that has Flamingo and Back to Redemption.

description: What a fun line. Despite being only 3 moves it packs a punch with an exciting finish. Stand start with relatively good holds. Right hand to a sidepull, left hand to a crimp, establish high feet (crux) and throw for the top. Mantle and top-out. The general idea is to ascend directly up the face between A-cup and deadpoint dihedral.
location: This line is located on the West Side of the Power Puff boulder. It is sandwiched between "A-cup (aka Burlfest in the guidebook)" and Deadpoint Dihedral.
protection: Slightly slanted landing but overall free of obstruction. Pad(s) + spotter.

description: Sit start just left of Bessie the Cow. Move up to the edges over the lip and climb the left side of the face.
Begin on the good pinch as for Cow Pie. Traverse low across the boulder, finish in the shallow grove on the right side of the face.
Start sitting with hands on large nose feature...may need to stack pads if you are short. Set up and lob to the hold up and right.
location: nose in the middle of the east face.

description: Crux is the press with your right hand.
location: The route starts on the arete that is in the middle of the face. It is a heel hook sit start. Make a static move to your right to a ball looking feature and pinch-press it. After you get around the bulge in the face top out.

description: Just a fun little traverse.
location: It begins as a sit start on a matching jug. Then from there traverse right as far as you can on the whole face and top out.

description: Crux is defintely topping out. An overall fun problem.
location: Problem starts with left hand in crack and right hand on small crimper. Move right and straight up.

description: An easy, stretchy problem.
location: Same start as Left to Right Traverse but this time go straight up and top out.

description: The crux is the start.
location: There is an obvious single crack towards the bottom of the face. Both hands begin in this crack. Reach up to your right to grab bulge and work straight up.

description: Crux is the mantle. One hold may be wet so be sure to check all holds after rain. Be careful of tree directly behind you. It'd be better to have 2 pads or more. Don't move around the overhang, go right up it baby!!
location: The route is beneath an overhang on the south facing arete. Start with your left hand on a tiny crimp and your right hand on an undercling.

description: Start with a match on a jug and move up and right or straight up...either way same grade.
Crux is reaching last jug. Good overall problem, look for the heel hook.
location: Start on jug and go to your left on solid a pinch. Go around nose and top out.

description: Starts on the sit-start of Cow Pie move up and right, reach for the good holds over the lip and climb the left side of the big face.
location: Link the start Cow Pie to the finish on Urban Sasquatch.

description: Sit start on the far left side of the boulder and head straight up.
location: the farthest left route on Bessie

description: The center route on this rock. stand start from the crimps and finish at the slabs high point.
location: In the middle of Bessie.

description: In the trees you come out of the trees and top out on nice crimpy holds that are really good. Sit start with a pinch to your left. Crux is second move after getting off the deck.
location: Right below the parking lot.

description: You start out on two small side pulls and start moving up using a good rail and then a pinch for your left hand. There is a dead point towards the end which is hard giving how slick this rock is.
location: On the west facing face of the A Cup boulder

description: Sit start on the steep arete 5 feet left of the Muffintop Dihedral. Work up the arete utilizing holds on both sides.
location: on the SE corner of the Muffintop Boulder. 10 feet from the trail at the #2 sign.

description: Sit-start left hand crimp right hand side-pull, continue on difficult side-pulls until reaching easier climbing. The parks dept. has removed all the branches from the Sphincter Poker, it is now a much more enjoyable problem.
location: Several feet left of Sweat and Slide and immediately right of Deadpoint Dihedral.

description: Stand start 5 feet right of Sweat and Slide heading up the seam (fingerlock) and topping out, crux is overcoming extremely slick feet (V1+). Or alternatively, sit-start as for Sweat & Slide and traverse right, the crux is traversing on dismal feet that face the wrong way (V3+)
location: On the south face of the Sweat and Slide boulder, 5 feet right of S&S.

description: Sit start near or left of the start for Sweat and Slide. Use the good foot to propel the right hand into the sidepull. Adjust and make the solid reach-thru with the left hand up to the ledge. Top out in the trees (Yuck)
location: between Sweat & Slide and Sphinkter Poker

description: Start in dirty dihedral with a small crack up to a roof which should be surmounted. Style dictates mantling from as far right as possible.
location: This route is on the backside (east face) of the boulder closest to the number 2 sign.
