description: Sit-start obvious block up to crimpers on good feet, crux is pulling on the "sharp as a knife" sidepull-undercling. Good jug makes the top-out not too scary for v1 boulderers.
location: This boulder is the big guy right on the trail between the 1 and 2 signs. The route is on the south face, coming from the interpretive center this route is hard to miss and begins on the block. Great warm-up for the problems just downhill.

description: Sit-start on two good crimper jugs then make the crux deadpoint move to a sloping crimp, footwork will bring you to better holds and an easy top-out.
location: This route is located 5 feet right of A cup on the steep corner dihedral.

description: Sit start under the roof and head up.
location: On the uphill (west) side of the boulder next to the block containing sweat and slide and a cup.

description: A rock start is up from A-cup and is a fun sit start its the only small tower by itself we cleaned the route it used to be really dirty. Crux is coming out of the sit start.
location: Up from where "A-cup" is small tower by itself.

description: There is a lower crux and upper crux. The lower crux is finding proper foot position to reach around nose to hold. The upper crux is the top out. Becareful...there is loose rock at the top and tree to hit if you fall as well as a rock right below you that would cause some damage if you fell.
location: It is the southern most boulder. You will see a roof that is on the ground, the start is underneath the roof, and the start holds are the crack in the back of the roof. Go off the southwest face after send.

description: Starts on the large block looking hold and then moves up using a really nice heel hook and some big holds.
location: On the boulder with Flamingo and Back for Redemption on the east facing wall.

description: Start on the right side of the face couple tricky moves lead to the top out
Stand start on the left side of the north face

The start is on the south facing wall. It's a huge pinch with your right hand and a decent crimp for your left hand. You then make a huge move to a jug like feature with you right hand. From there move your left hand to the undercling and top out. Crux is the start.
location: Head south from the trail about 70 yards and you'll see the big boulder.

description: Sit start climb the nose feature and top out
The route starts on two crimps right at the arret. You make two big bumps with your left hand using an amazing heel hook. From there move your right hand up and top out. The crux is the top out.
location: Head south from the trail about 70 yards. The route is just left of Flamingo and uses one of the same start holds.

description: Sit start on the arete. Crux is a long move to a good jug

Start sitting on the trail to the left of the boulder as you look at it from the trail.  Move up easy hand holds and obvious footholds.  Move up to the lowest part of the boulder.   Builds confidence especially for those tag-alongs who you want to get into the sport!
location: The smallish Farmhouse boulder which is a really unique landmark feature right on the trail (but it is pretty short as Jon Marek states).

description: Start sitting on the boulder protruding beneath the overhang. Move up the overhang and face. Crux is a set of two finger crimps.
location: Left side of overhanging arete which sits on the trail about 25 yds downhill from the large slab.
protection: pads, the boulder beneath this climb is a butt-buster.

description: Start sitting on the trail to the right of the boulder as you look from the trail.. but sit -left- of the rock holding the boulder on its south west side slightly beneath the rock.  Stay exclusively on the boulder (especially your right foothold as you start).  Move up to the highest part of the boulder.   Crux is getting to your 1st or 2nd hand holds.
location: -The- smallish Farmhouse boulder which is a really unique landmark feature right on the trail (but it is pretty short as Jon Marek states).
protection: pad but have someone spot you behind the rock and next to the tree in case you peel to your right

description: Start left of Hanging Dihedral and strait up the face using the good holds on the arete.
location: NW of the Farmhouse boulder, 20ft from the trail.

description: Sit start in dirty finger crack and up the dihedral.
location: 20 feet uphill from the trail NW of the Farmhouse Boulder.

route_name: Bullwinkle aka God Created Gene Hackman
description: Sit start on the trail, up and left on good holds.
location: Obvious overhanging line on the trail.

description: Sit start in crack, continue up crack until you reach the face which should take you to the top.
location: 8ft right of Rocky and Bullwinkle, on the same mini-buttress.

description: Climb straight up the arete between Lucy's Ladder and Gitchigumi Groupie
location: between Lucy's Ladder and Gitchigumi Groupie

description: Standing start in the center of the face, chuck to the horizontal from the arete, and try to smile while negotiating the thin slab above.
location: Located in the center of the cliff face.  Climb down either side of the cliff.

description: Standing start just left of the telephone pole on small holds, climb up and past the middle seam.
location: Located just left of the telephone pole.  Climb down either side of the cliff.

description: Right side of the arete, sit start on crimps. Head up then straight over the overhang
Pretty similar to "Awesome," but a little bit taller. Slabby topout with good holds and some fun moves. 2 variations on this one; you can go left or right.
location: 2nd from the right on the Upper Wall, to the left of "Awesome."

description: Start on the most left problem and traverse right through some good crimps and nice holds to the most right problem. The transition to follow the thin crack is the best part of this climb. Great counter pressure move with a crimp in left hand and right hand in crack. Go up from there.

Traverse the same as solo mission till you begin to go up Made in Switzerland.  Instead of finnishing on made in switzerland, match in the thin crack then move right to two small crimps and a big sloppy gaston for your right hand.  Good footwork allows you to move to up to some better holds and on to an easy top out.  Crux is getting established on the crimps and sloppy gaston.
location: start the same as solo mission and end 3 feet right of Made in Switzerland

description: SDS on the same holds as Rock biter and climb straight up.  Good warm up for Rock Biter
protection: One pad will do the trick

description: Sds on a crimp and a sidepull. Move right to an intermediate, or go straight to a poor side pull. Fire for the top. Don't get bit.
location: Furthest problem to the left at the Upper Area, past the 3 on the main wall a little off to the side.

description: Climb the right side of the upper wall. Named for the ancient Swiss Army sunglasses we found hanging on a tree at the base, which we left and are probably still there.
location: Right side of Upper Wall.

description: Climbs the middle of the Upper Wall. Crimpy fun moves to a good and somewhat hidden jug to the right.
This climbs the left side of the Upper Wall. Good crimps and a few moves about the same difficulty as the other problems to the right, but shorter with better jugs at the top.
location: The left of the 3 climbs.

description: The further one gets towards the lower wall, the higher the band gets, the more climbing is available. Hence the bump in quality for this one. Fun slabby moves pretty much the whole way.
location: Third from the right, to the left of the "Slab Happy" variations, to the right of "Lonely Lover's Chimney."

description: This is the obvious chimney that is on the upper wall to the left of the first four problems. Home Water Birth is the the left of this. Squeeze up it if you're bored, or use it for the downclimb.
location: Upper Wall.

description: I was tempted to give this four stars since there are very cool holds on this at just the right spot, but it just doesn't flow as well as a four star should imo. Get on it and tell me what you think. Climb the arete and hold it together at the top. Exit rightish. A cool looking variation has yet to be done (that I know of) using both aretes.
location: The first route around the corner to the right from the lower wall.

description: Good holds lead shortly to a slabby topout.
location: Furthest problem on the right of the Upper Wall.

description: Sit start on a big lieback and head straight up.
location: Almost to the arete on the bigger face.

description: Stand Start on ledge. Head up and left on slopers.
Stand start on ledge. Head skyward using slopers.
Squat start on ledge on the arete. Follow arete to the top.
A sit start that climbs up a series of crimps...pretty mellow
location: Left most climb on the bigger face

description: Sit start using finger crack. Head up using finger crack and poor face holds. Avoid dihedral and arete.
Start low on the face. Head up to slopey rail then left to crimps. Finish straight up.
Sit start below the big roof - climb straight up and through.
location: Beneath the obvious roof at the far climber's right.

description: Sit start with both hands on the horn and climb through small crimps to the top
location: Just right of Oh Goddamn

description: From Peter's Guide "Sit start left hand on a high pinch and a right hand on the rounded arete. Work straight up through powerful moves without using the far side of the dihedral."
Sit start on jugs. Work through ledges to committed top out.
Start on crimp rail then head straight up the slopey arete.
The arete on the right of the bigger face...
location: The right-most climb on the bigger face

description: Starting near the graffiti, climb through the crimps, then up and around the overhang.
location: This route starts near the graffiti ten feet left of the telephone pole. Climb down either side of the cliff.

description: Good warm up and place to run laps.
location: Little traverse wall on top off all the other boulders. Top out easy climb by lucy's ladder and you will see it. It starts all the way right and goes left and up.

description: Pretty fun little climb and I am no crack climber! I ended up doing a fun little bump/toss for the lip and that was the crux I thought.
location: Red line on photos, next to Oblivious.

description: THe crux is right at the start where the crack is more of a seam more up into easier teritory and get some pro in.  Then move on to easier climbing to the top.  Can be bouldered at V0 R/X
location: To the right of the bouldering.  Climb the most obvious crack on the slab.
protection: small cams or quite a few pads if you are stupid enough to boulder this.

description: Left hand on good hold with right hand on big hold/sidepull. Trend up and left and top out straight up. When you get to the top you can just top out to the right but going straight up gives a nice little mantel which is fun. If cleaned and a base is built above the water this line could start lower by the water level. We're working on it...
location: This line is to the left of Oblivious about 20 feet if you're looking at the rock. Walk the rocks and hop up on the little ledge of a rock to the start of this one.

route_name: Over the River and Through the Woods
description: SDS on broken sloped rail with feet on small rails. Due to the unique nature or this rock I did not use the rock protrusion just to the left for feet, it is more like the ground than part of the wall and much more fun without it. Move up through big holds and top out on sloped ledge. Cool movement and really awesome features and rock.
location: Just downstream from the other routes. Look for the makeshift bridge and platform. The wall is literally right above the stream, and makes for a pretty sweet setting.
protection: Pad. Don't fall off or you may be getting wet!

description: Super fun climb with the crux on the second half of the climb after you get the gaston pinch hold. Pretty tall and pretty scary, but a great landing is built. I did it solo since there really isn't room for a spotter anyways.
location: SDS left of Gitch. Groupie. To the left of the crack with the crack not on. Using the crack is Rotten Carcass. Sit start on two big good holds with awkward feet and move up to crimp with right hand and then to sweet gaston pinch. Then figure out feet to move up and left to pinch and then some sidepulls. Top out has huge holds but still freaky.

description: SDS made a bit awkward by the platform and vicinity of the stream. As long as you have a pad it is not as awkward. Use side pull and strange jug for start holds and move up through awesome features and finish on sloped ledge. Avoid mossy dihedral feature
location: Just downstream from the other problems. Look for the makeshift bridge and platform. Bare rock surrounded by a sea of moss.

description: The crux is probably the start? The sloppy edge/lip hold is super cool.
location: Located on sloppy boulder to the left. Sit start on obvious sidepulls and move straight up to sloppy edge hold and up from there.

description: Around the corner to the left of Lucy's Ladder. Start on obvious ledge, to side pull, to double side pulls, and up to crimps to top.
location: Around the corner to the left of Lucy's Ladder.

description: Start of the right side of the sloppy boulder with left hand on decent hold and right hand on sidepull and trend left to the super cool little seam and then straight up. This boulder has some of the coolest features and texture I have seen, but it's sadly to featured to put out anything super awesome.
location: Sloppy boulder is in between the Zach attack wall and the main boulder you come to from the trail. If you get over the creek past PB & J you'll see it.

description: Traverse left starting on the far right side of the cliff on a ledge just above your head.  move through a tricky sequence to get around the arete and into the crux.  the begining is tough until you figure out the right sequence.
location: start to the right of reveling the beauty and traverse left around the arete and twords the dihedral.  top out just before the dihedral.  easy to figure out once you see it.

description: Stand start with hands on obvious holds, smear on slab and follow semi-jug holds to the top.
location: On the far right face, around the corner from Gitchigumi Groupie .

description: I know, I know. 4 stars Chris? Seriously? Yes dudes. I'm telling you, this is a classic climb. Here's my reasons: 1. It has a great sit start (a lot of sds in Duluth lack the quality of actually being cool) 2. The movement flows well and is consistent throughout the climb 3. The holds are cool 4. There is an amazing pinch that I had to use (and you will likely not find a hold like this anywhere else in Duluth or Northern MN for that matter!) 5. It's a good enough length to have a little risk involved. Named XMen for the X's that criss-cross the face, the new evolving climbing scene in Duluth, and the mutants that are starting to appear.
location: To the right of Top Out Problem on the lower wall.

description: Sit start on the left side of the boulder with feet on the small left wall (It is really hard without it). Work up following the rightward slant of the boulder to an intense top out. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)
location: The down stream side of the boulder. On the left looking back upstream.

first_ascent: Joe -dont know his last name- my room mate
description: sit start way scrunched. make a hard move or two and your home free. more information to come
location: left

description: The main line, start in the back of the roof with hands on the triangular block. Go strait back using the only hold on the underside of the roof and gain the lip. From here 2 big moves get you comfortably standing above the crux. 5.8 climbing to the top, don‚Äôt fall.
location: Canter

description: Start on a good side pull and bad right hand. Go up using an even worse hold, big move to a left (crux). From here use some jugs to get above the lip and climb the same 5.8 of putins palace to the top.
location: left hand side

description: Start with your hands in the horizontal crack at the back of the roof. Through a toe hook and go up the right side on the bolder. keep your feet off of the lower wall to the right of the inflection, it makes the climb more fun and keeps you out of the dirt. After the crux it‚Äôs smooth sailing of the friction-slab
location: Right hand side of the don wall
protection: This is the safest of the three routes 1 pad

description: sit start in dihedral, hands in vertical crack. Feet off the the right help. Make your way up and left on the blocky features.
location: in the dihedral
on the egg like protrusion
protection: 2 pads to protect the rock in the landing. Some what reminiscent of top out problem but not nearly as bad.

location: far right side of the wall.
to the left of the egg protrusion, on the detached block

description: strait up the more chossey wall, ends in toilet bowl
location: far left hand side

description: Start in the middle of the wall grabbing low and lay backing on the crack. Mantle onto the jug rail above you and move to the left to finish out on obvious large holds. If you stay right and go straight up from the jug rail it is hard and has yet to be done. Don't Grab the detached block as it sounds very hollow.
location: Middle of the wall next to the compression problem. Look for the obvious crack, jug rail, and detached block.

description: sit start matched on the obvious rail. move up and right to gain the underclings then top out out right.
location: the overhung face just to the right of "a romance with the woman of your dreams"
The down stream side of the boulder. Starts slightly under the boulder on the left.

description: Start same as Snowball Effect. Do the first few moves, than work right. ¬†Use a kneebar to transition into Eli.
location: Same start as Snowball Effect
The start hold is the same large triangle sloper-jug you use on Asian Porn before you cut right.
protection: Pads. Be careful of the wall behind you.  Maybe hang a pad if you dont feel solid on the last few moves.

description: Sit start on a jug at the bottom of the fissure crack. Follow the crack into Snowball Effect. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)
location: The down stream side of the boulder.
Start 2ish ft. to the right of Snowball Effect, underneath the boulder.
protection: A lot of pads 5+?  Attentive spotters/pad movers.

route_name: A Romance With the Woman of Your Dreams
location: On the upstream side of the boulders. Starts on the underside of the smaller, higher boulder.

description: Harkness cleaned up this route (by pulling off all kinds of loose choss). This is a sit-down start on good underclings (that may soon break off) and moves through huge holds with big easy moves and then gets serious real quick with the slabby top-out. The giant loose jug in the middle of the route could probably be crow-barred off to make the route a little better.
location: This is first problem on the left side of the lower wall, next to, yet again, another ambling tree that is growing up the side of the rock.
protection: Ankle-breaker with a small boulder at the base. Several pads are recommended.

description: Very difficult start although you have good hand holds leads to a couple sloppers and then a difficult topout that may bump up the grade if you are shorter then 5'9".  both sides of the boulder are "NOT ON" when toping out.
location: First boulder to the left of the lower wall
protection: 1 pad and a good spotter.  I had my pad offset when I fell the first time and landed on a stump, hence the name of the problem.

description: SDS on the far right side of the wall as your looking at it.  Traverse left a few feet off the ground on good holds but poor feet.  Traverse to the left side of the wall until you meet up with Top Out Problem and finish on that.  This is hard to grade as none of the moves are that hard till you top out but it is pumpy.  I will go with V5 but could be anywhere from V4+ to V6 but defiantly harder then Top Out Problem.
location: traverses from right to left on the lower wall

description: A terrific V1 sds warmup. Climbs more like a route than a boulder problem, and is almost a little pumpy towards the end. I'm claiming the FA since I spent an hour one day hanging from webbing cleaning this up and making it solid and climbable.
location: Furthest right climb on the lower wall. Too bad there isn't more in this area.

description: Starts on the underclings of Top Out Problem and traverses into XMen.

location: Between the Gorilla Warfare arete and Universal Truth.
protection: ?? Depending on where the water is flowing through the stream bed, this climb may be above the shallow Merritt Creek. As of 2015 there is no solid ground below this route.

description: From the sit start explode with power to hit the jug. Either finish directly or work slightly left in order to make the problem contrived and more powerful (v5)
location: This is located just climbers right and lower of Slight Dab. Sit start on side of steep hill (awkward)
protection: 1 pad. This is a great low ball, but the landings on the hill give opportunity for pads to be kicked out and three stooges type of action to follow.

location: Right side of the confederate wall. Obvious shear wall in a shallow alcove.

description: Start left up jugs and good crimp. Move right at 2nd horizontal crack and using crimp work over to the vertical crack and follow it up to decent top out. The way the slab bulbs outward makes it a bit awkward but fun.
location: Far right of Lisa's Slabs. Look for the Porcelain representation of Baby Jesus at start.
protection: Pad and spotters would be nice

description: Sit starts all along bottom of rock along shelf then follow multiple holds to the top.
location: All over the rock!

description: Project line that I haven't messed with a whole lot yet, so the grade is a total guess. Sit start (?) moving up to the horn corner of the lip and traverse to the jug holds near the middle of the lip and top out same as "perspective."
location: Starts on the far right side of the boulder. Stand start is pretty mellow, but a sit looks doable.
protection: Several pads, or a spotter moving a pad as you traverse.

description: Super fun lip traverse line! Amazing texture and neat holds make this heel hook heavy line a must check out kinda line. Crux is toping out from the jug hold to the uber blank slab top. Good luck!
location: This problem starts on the left side of the face with 2 textured slope holds and traverses roughly 12 feet to the right and then tops out. Super easy walk off to the climbers left onto the SHT.
protection: Several pads is ideal, but not necessary if your spotter can keep moving the pad as you traverse.

description: This is a short crack that gets a little creepy at the top because it starts at about 8 feet up.  Sit start the crack and work into a trusty layback with foot jams to top out.
location: This is only about 15ft right of Squat Thrust. The climb starts on the "next level up".
protection: Padding and spotting are difficult. If it goes wrong at the top, there is potential for much calamity/hilarity.
pads and good spotters are recommended. Though the heights are low, the landing has a cliff behind it.

description: Easy route for warming up or for youth climbers. Can be made easier or harder depending on use of the main wall.
location: At the boulder along the creek. Climbs the short, blocky side wall to the right-hand side of the main wall. Faint graffiti as of the first ascent reports that "Frederick was here"
First route to the left of Bubba.¬† The start is 8ish feet right of a small cave thing.

description: Fun route with a big move at the top. Taller climbers will have an easier time.
location: At the boulder along the creek. Starts on crimps near a small notch in the rock on the right side of the wall. As of the first ascent in 8/15, starts in the middle of the graffiti reporting that "BUBBA was here".

description: Stand start on high jug. Pull the roof then head up and left to the giant ledge. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)
location: Left side of Confederate Wall. On the face right of the obvious Gorilla Warfare arete.

description: Squat start in horizontal slot jug below roof. Move up to slopey ledge, then crip your way straight up to the slopey top out. Arete is off. Don't cheat the topout by going around the arete. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)
location: Left side of Confederate Wall. Slightly overhanging face left of the Gorilla Warefare arete.

description: Squat start low on the arete. Follow arete with awesome jugs. At the upper ledge, don't wimp out and traverse right, be bold and dyno to the top of the corner on How Dirty Boys Get Clean. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)
location: Left side of the Confederate Wall. The obvious arete near the end of the approach trail.

description: Squat start low on Arete. Follow arete with awesome jugs. At the upper ledge, follow it right to an easy top out. (From Peter's Guide to Duluth Bouldering)
location: Left side of the Confederate Wall. The obvious arete near the end of the approach trail.
Right of the Gorilla Warfare arete. Also right of the small shelf that allows access to Orange Against the Sky and Gorilla Warfare.
protection: ??  Depending on where the water is flowing through the streambed, this climb may be above water. As of 2015 there is no solid ground below this route.

location: Right of the Gorilla Warfare arete. Also right of the small shelf that allows access to Orange Against the Sky and Gorilla Warfare.
protection: ??  Depending on where the water is flowing through the stream bed, this climb may be above the shallow Merritt Creek. As of 2015 there is no solid ground below this route.

description: start in the obvious dihedral at the right end of the confederate wall. follow this dihedral up then shoot left for the giant horizontal flake and finish straight up.
location: furthest climb on the right end of the confederate wall.

route_name: Better Than a Stick in the Eye
location: Right side of Confederate Wall. The left side of the shallow alcove containing Universal Truth.

description: Start above the miniature choss cave with a very cool left hold and move on up. A sds to this would be very cool. There's also a possible variation just the left of this that could go up the mungy crack (read: needs to be cleaned) and would be a bit more difficult, but somewhat contrived. Come on out and climb it dudes!
location: To the right of Pitocin on the lower wall. Roughly in the middle.

description: Pretty mellow warmup. A lot taller than the picture shows. This follows good holds on a crack that comes to a stance. Continue up the crack on an angled slab or exit right. Left looks kinda sketch and somewhat dirty.
location: First of the easier climbs from the left, next to Bananimals.

description: Possum starts off the climbing on the lower wall. Kind of a one move wonder, and like so many climbs in Duluth, ends in a slopey topout.
location: Furthest left problem on the lower wall.

description: A good V1 to induce your climbing experience at the PPW. Follow the dirty crack to the right of St. Luke's.
location: In between St. Luke's and St. Mary's on the lower wall.

description: This fun climb looks harder than it is. The wall blanks out for a bried moment here and "Midwives" is the result. Slabby face climbing.
location: Just to the right of the easier climbs, next to St. Mary's.
The furthest downstream route, also the farthest left rock on the Confederate Wall. If you follow the approach trail past the rock bridge, this is the first wall you come to.

description: A neat little crack that requires some finger-lockage and few reachy moves. I thought stand start was V3. The sit start variation begins on a good undercling and requires a little more desperation, so V4
location: Next climb to the right of Possum, up the good crack, left side of the lower wall. (2nd problem from the left).

description: I gave this a climbing rating because of it's length and grade. Super mellow, but pretty high. Still nothing to worry about.
location: Next available climb to the right of Midwives.

description: Bananimals is a terric crimpfest with a deadpoint balance crux. I would give it 4 stars if it was a bit longer. Awesome jug for the last move. The sds has yet to be done and might add a number to the grade.
location: 3rd route in from the left on the lower wall, next to "Get the Epidural." Blank looking face.

description: Sit start on a bomber undercling and poor feet.  Move up and left the arete using slopers and crimps.  When your over the center of the boulder top out.  Don't wuss out and move out to the right.
location: on the right arete of the 45 degree boulder to the left of Friction Fighter slab

description: Start on Start stemming facing Warm up crack without using the crack (yeah I know).  Move onto the right using the diagonal crack then move back to the left using the crack and top out the same as warm up crack.  The crux is establishing yourself onto the face.
location: I think you can find it

description: Use mainly face holds to start and finish using arete on both sides at the top. Stay in the middle of the face and climb obvious features, easy climb with fun moves mixed in.
location: Highest line of East river side. Obvious block sticking out on the left side of the wall.

description: Slabby climbing the center of the cliff. Use decent sloppy holds till you hit the thanks god jugs at the top.
location: As you are looking at Doughnuts for James, head left 30 yards.  This heads up the center of the cliff
protection: Very poor landing.  At least 3 pads and two spotters.  With out them a fall will leave you tumbling 50 feet down the hill and probably earn you an expensive trip to the hospital.

description: Start under the roof and use the finger crack to find the enormous undercling.  Once you've found this bomber hold, head straight up.  Find the little crimp ledge on the edge of the roof and the mediocre crimp/sloper a foot higher and use these to get yourself to the top!
location: Under the mini-roof of the Whatever Wall.
protection: One crash pad will get the job done.

description: Sit start using a good ledge for your left hand and a undercling for the right.  Move up to the horizontal crack using decent crimps.  Move your feet up and throw for the last jug of Mr. Muscles.
location: Just to the climber's right of MR. Muscles

description: Start with both hands squeezing the double arete. Then move into crimp rail and up into the jug like Killer Bees. But instead of going up, traverse out onto the lip of the roof and top out to the right.
location: Whatever wall

description: This problem is just to the left of the mini-roof.  Choose from the many mediocre start holds, taking advantage of the great feet.  Then throw to a bomber ledge approximately two feet above the start holds.  Use the flake to top out, being careful not to bare down too hard (feels solid, but who knows?).  Fun move, but unfortunately a one move wonder!
location: Just left of the mini-roof.

description: Stay within the black streak.  If you step outside of it, you arent doing this route.  Start on the large hold, reach for the right hand pinch and high step.  Next, head towards the pocket with a left hand and figure the rest out from there.
location: Uphill from "Doughnuts for James"
To the right of Grandma Bubbles - kind of the arete on the main face but follows a thin crack system
protection: The lower crack will take C3s or nuts.  Higher up you can plug a #1 Camalot.  Walk off or rap from the anchors on PB or GB.

description: This route begins to the left of the obvious black streak.  Work upwards.
location: From "Doughnuts for James" (#6 on the hand drawn map) hike up the hill to the left.  Passing the large boulder with a crappy landing on the right, you will arrive at the "flat landing boulder".  There are three routes on it.

description: SDS on sharp crimps on the arete to the right of Foxy Lady.  Follow the arete to the top out.  All face holds are off.
location: To the right of Foxy Lady
In a dihedral to the right of Grandma Bubbles.

description: Start the same as Pandora's Box but hang a right at the crux.  The name says it all!  Not a hard climb but the protection sucks!
protection: Not much until you are near the top!

description: A few ledges then up to a large bulge 10 feet off the deck with poor holds.  Get out there and send this.  Crux is pulling the bulge and toping out. Grade is approximate, you send it and let me know.
location: Just to the right of Foxxy Lady and Quick Fix Crack as you come up the trail.
protection: At least 3 pads and a couple spotters.

description: Sweet slab climb on dime edges with a sloper mantle on top...There are a few horizontal cracks to make it easier if need be...but you should avoid them for style points!
location: Upper Fox Rock

description: What could be an amazing climb fizzles after 8 feet!  Splitter crack in a dihedral and then pretty boring 5.1 climbing.  Could be a good first lead for someone who is really new!  Not a bad solo...
location: Between Golgatha's Chimney and Pandora's Box on Fox Face.

protection: 2 bolts plus a few cams or nuts from #00 to #.75

location: Fox Face

description: Standing start on invisible crimps to a side pull.  Bump your feet up and gun for the topout.
location: Foxx Face just below Quick Fix Crack on the obvious 15 degree face.

description: The route is chossy and may be easier using roots shrubs as aid.  The crux is mental as you hope not to fall back upon the steep approach.
location: An alternate access chimney to the top of the Foxx Rocks climbs.  It is located climbers right of the crag, past Quick Fix Crack.
protection: Pro is not necessary but a spotter would be helpful if attempting any stylish moves up the route other than just getting up it as quickly and safely as possible.

description: This line follows the crack the whole way, anything outside the crack is off. Sit start to obvious crimp and crack next to it,up to the small crimp up and right off of the crack then to top.
location: To the far left of the black streak, follow Y crack on the right to the top.

description: Start on the left side of the boulder on a crimp.  Figure out the feet (be creative) and reach up for a left handed undercling.  Get here and you're as good as done with it.
location: "Flat landing boulder"  uphill from "Doughnuts for James".

description: SDS for donuts for James on decent holds and poor feet.  Pull your butt off the ground and bump your right hadn straight up to the slopper.  Move into the double underclings and finish the same as Donuts for James.  Adds a lot of difficulty
Up the center of this boulder/cliff band. Undercling, step up and dyno for the rail.
location: East Walls. This is the furthest East cliff band on the North side of Haines Rd.

description: Finger crack below Quick fix crack and to the left of Foxxy Lady.  Probably 5.9 and could be combined with quick fix crack if you are really desperate in get new climbing in.
location: See description

description: Pinch, pull and crimp your way up the face
location: Lower Fox Rock, to the left of the obvious dihedral with a finger crack.

description: Corner system to the right of Remember The Fallen...kind of gross and scary do to the loose nature of the corner.  Start from the upper ledge.
location: To the right of RTF
About 40 feet left of Skittle Phlegm is an obvious cave and off width roof crack.  Do'nt destroy it!
protection: A 2x4 slung and drapped over the top might work.  But do you really want to kill yourself?

route_name: Smack My Ass And Call Me Sally
description: Harness up, and grab those draws boys and girls, Little Fox has its first sport route!!  The beta...work your way up to the third bolt using some solid crimps.  The crux is definitely the last few moves, suck it up, and throw for the top.
location: Follow the orange tape to the roped climbs and the route is in between Skittle Phlegm and Remember the Fallen.

description: This hidden gem of Duluth is one of the most asthetic climbs in town.  Starting with off-width and ending with hands, this crack should be 200 feet long!  But it's not.  The crack is 20 to 25 feet.  The finish is a mantle to a small ledge and a couple easy moves to top out.  Don't let the 5.6 rating fool you...this is a sweet route and may be a touch sandbagged if your crack technique is iffy.  Go climb it now...
protection: Cams from .75 to 3.  Ring anchors at top - If you use them to TR please your own draws...

location: Little Foxx - to the left of the graphitti

description: Just to the left of Skittle Phlegm...work up the big crack and ledge system.
location: Left of Skittle Phlegm

description: Sit start on large rail work up to left onto smaller features, feat smearing and edging. Make a large move to a left hand dish. Situate your feet continuing on big features to the left on the slab. Top out between the grass mound and the huge white tube with a technical shamoo.
location: Climb farthest right on the tunnel wall. First climb you see on your right as you come down the hill. Large rail and features on the diagonal.

description: Consider top roping before going for the send. Start up the corner in the middle/rightish side of the super slab. From the top of the corner climb straight up through the crux on the blank slab with a few bad holds. Very balancey, static is key to survival!
location: From the Friction Fighter area of North Little Foxx head left (toward Lake Superior) for about 75 yards at about the same elevation. Look for the huge Super Slab. There's a little bit of a trail angling toward it from the freestanding boulder (Shikidang). What's Your Reynolds Number? is in the middle/rightish side of the Super Slab. Left of Probability Density, Right of Time Dilation.
protection: 2 pads, spotters, rope to bail on...

description: Great fun warm up for the other bouldering. I have bouldered this but would take gear if you wanted to lead. Some great hand jams and stemming. Very wet the majority of the time. Give it atleast 3 days after a rain to dry out.
location: Superior Hiking Trail pull off. Follow bright orange flagging to crag. Crack between the two right most slabs.
protection: Pads and spotter or a couple medium cams

description: Named appropriately for the uninspiring line it takes but a good warm up none the less.  start in the finger crack just left of the arete combine the ledges on the arete and the finger crack to top out.
location: The right arete of the right slab

description: SDS on a great left hand side pull in the crack and tiny half pad crimp for the left.  Move up to a sweet pocket then move left into PH balance using the sloppy rail.  Top out the same as PH Balance.  Feels much hard until the right beta is found.
location: starts about 10 feet left of PH balance and moves over into PH balance and tops out the same.

description: Sit start on bottom left of arete on big side pulls.  Move up into the first crimp rail on the face.  Then the second rail on the face, then use three slopers that follow arete out right to the top.
location: From the small overhanging bloc to the left of Friction Fighter, go up the hill and to the left prob. 50-yards.  Its the only rock up there.

description: Really fun route if you can keep your nerves at bay. Starts on the big under cling directly below a distinct long vertical crack. Heads straight up a short slabby crux to the long crack with good holds. To top out follow the small seam that angles up and left (it may be tempting to bail up the large ledge to the right, fight the urge!). Keep your head on for a second crux at the top out. Super high top out so be careful! Not a route you want to fall on.
location: From the Friction Fighter area of North Little Foxx head left (toward Lake Superior) for about 75 yards at about the same elevation. Look for the huge Super Slab. There's a little bit of a trail angling toward it from the freestanding boulder (Shikidang). Time Dilation is on the middle/left side of the Super Slab. Left of What's Your Reynolds Number? Right of Decayed Strange Quark.

description: start on good holds at eye level. go up with face holds, arete and cool slopers at top.
location: the slightly steep face to the right of "Step it Up".  on the upper of the two cliff bands to the right of the main trail before you reach the main area or the freestanding bloc

description: Climb up the blank face starting on small crimps, left one on the face, and the right on the arete.  Use arete to make  you way to the top, then traverse left on the super sweet lip.
location: On the blank face to the right of PH balance.  "on the upper of the two cliff bands on the right on the trail before you get to the main area."

description: Sit start on the arete with your left hand low on a terrible crimp and right on an ok side pull. Slap left hand to sloper. Two more easy moves and your done. The crux is the first two moves.  Must start very low for full value
location: Take 40th Ave west to Skyline and continue up Haines Road for a few hundred yards. Park in the Superior Hiking Trail pull off. Follow bright orange flagging. Slightly overhanging boulder right of the three slabs. goes up the arete on the same boulder as moonlight delight and fight the phunk

description: Sit start just to the right of the small ledge.use the large side pull for your left and a tiny crimp for your right.  Move your left hand up on the verticle rail and right up on sloppers.  good technique allows you to stand up to a tiny slopper and dyno for the lip which is the crux.
location: On the free standing boulder around the corner from Shikidang.  This is in the middle of the tallest face just to the right of the small ledge.
protection: Probably two pads and a spotter as the landing is poor.

description: On free standing boulder. Sit start with nice arete.  Use slopy arete to the left and crimps to work up main arete.
location: While looking down hill from the main area, the arete is on the down hill right corner of the freestanding boulder.

description: Sds. Try not to get wet in the little river that sometimes runs directly around and under the steep face of this problem. Throw to the jug, get your right hand up, resituate, and throw again around the lip to the next jug way up right on the sloping face. Or crimp yourself up. Either way, a good one of a kind problem in Duluth. Much thanks to BIATHLON! for cleaning this boulder up. I didn't want to take the time because it didn't look that great, but these 2 problems are actually well worth the time! Thanks Adam.
location: This is on the little free standing boulder off to the left 20 ft of Friction Fighter.

description: On the right side of the Super Slab you'll see a 10 foot vertical finger crack about 8 feet off the ground. Start directly below it and head straight up. Using the arete on the left and crimps on the face work through the low crux to get to the crack. At the top of the crack angle up and left on the easy but exposed slab to the top out by the birch trees.
location: From the Friction Fighter area of North Little Foxx head left (toward Lake Superior) for about 75 yards at about the same elevation. Look for the huge Super Slab. There's a little bit of a trail angling toward it from the freestanding boulder (Shikidang). Probability Density is on the right side of the Super Slab.

description: Sloper route!  sit start on two side pulls in midle/right side of face.  bump longer sidepull up from start then move into the slopy top out.  For duluth, I think this is really fun.
location: on the upper of the two cliff bands to the right of the main trail before you reach the main area or the freestanding bloc.  This is the obvious short climb with the sweet water groove/hp like topout.

description: Start on the same holds as Friction Fighter but move right after the first move of friction fighter.  Follow the thin crack around the right side of the arete to the top.  The top out is surprisingly good in comparison to many of the other routes in this area (it has holds).
location: Start the same as friction fighter

description: Just to the right of fight the phunk. Fun little problem

Named for the pile of fish bones found at the top on the FA.  Good friction rails lead you most of the way and then holds and feet stop.  Use the friction to topout as the angle decreases.  Do not wuss out and move twords Foxxy arete at the top.
location: Just left of the seam crack to the left of Friction Fighter

description: Start on a terrible round rail and move up through two more crimpy rounded rails with poor feet.  Once the crack is reached climbing gets much easier, follow the crack up and right and top out.  Let me know if you send and take pics.
location: Starts in the middle of the face between Warm Up Crack and Uninspired Arete

description: This short problem starts matched on a low rail on the right corner of the boulder.  Feet stay out left while not using the obvious side of the dihedral. Then make a move out left to a descent crimp. From there, either slap to sloper out right or all the way to top.  Mantle out as far left as possible.  This is a great problem for really short people being that the first long move actually feels long. Difficulty changes with height for sure
location: This is on the first boulder that you pass on your way to Friction Fighter.  The problem is on the far right "westish" side of the boulder as your walking on the marked trail.
protection: one pad covering the disappointing boulder which forms the sit start.

description: Sit start on whatever.  Use crimp to work into a really good right leaning side pull.  then work up and ALL the way to the right on really fun slopers.  I have to jump to first sloper, but longer reaches can prob. just grab it.  Super fun warm up.
location: to the right of uninspired arete.  Tops out all the way to the right on top sloper.

description: Sit start under slight overhang on good holds and traverse left till you reach the finger crack (which is not on) then back right and up. The top out is sketchy on thin holds. This skips the crux moves of friction fighter.
location: pad and spotter
protection: Take 40th Ave west to Skyline and continue up Haines Road for a few hundred yards. Park in the Superior Hiking Trail pull off. Follow bright orange flagging to crag. Left most slab of the three.

description: A Little Fox classic and a must do for any Minnesota Hardman!  The most obvious line on the three slabs.  Sit start under bulge on two bomber side pulls.  Pull up over the bulge to a sloppy/frictiony rail and then move your left hand to a small rail where you can fit 2-3 fingers. Find a small nub for your left foot on the slab and pull up into a right hand foot match.  10 feet of mellow climbing brings you to a good rest.  Here you can contemplate either down climbing or committing to the top out.  Climb up a couple more feet then reach way up to two small crimps.  Use these to get your feet high enough to mantle and it's all over.
location: Multiple pads and a spotter or two.
protection: Take 40th Ave west to Skyline and continue up Haines Road for a few hundred yards. Park in the Superior Hiking Trail pull off. Follow bright orange flagging to crag.

description: Great holds and feet make a great warm up.  Be sure not to wuss out 2/3 of the ways up by moving out onto the ledge.
location: Left arete on the farthest to the left slab.

description: Just right of Slap Happy. Sit start on with your hands matched on the obvious ledge. climb straight up on big holds.
location: Take 40th Ave west to Skyline and continue up Haines Road for a few hundred yards. Park in the Superior Hiking Trail pull off. Follow bright orange flagging to crag. .

description: Sit start on sharp tiny crimp in a horizontal crack.  Move up to a second horizontal crack with two more sharp crimps.  Step up and then dyno for the sloppy lip, then top it out.  The arete is off.
location: On the other side of the arete(right) from tip-top.

From the Friction Fighter area of North Little Foxx head left (toward Lake Superior) for about 75 yards at about the same elevation. Look for the huge Super Slab. There's a little bit of a trail angling toward it from the freestanding boulder (Shikidang). Decayed Strange Quark is on the left side of the Super Slab.

description: sit/stand start on the right corner arete of the down hill face of the free standing boulder.  follow slopy curving arete to the middle of boulder.  then top out.
location: as you look down hill at the free standing boulder from the main area. this is on the back left corner.

description: Start on the uninspired arete, half way up the move left onto the face using a good crimp and poor feet.  Crank off of this and make the very long reach to the diagonal crack to your left.  Follow this crack to top out.  Really a one or two move wonder.
location: On the right most of the three highball slabs.  Start the same as the uninspired arete.
the middle of the face between Warm Up Crack and the Blue Jaguar

description: This route climbs the slab right below the top of what i think is called fox nob. Right variation is v0- Small Yacht, middle goes at v2- Clean Water Slab and the left area has yet to be climbed although it looks promising
location: From the SHT parking lot follow the COGS trail to the top of the stone outcropping, the slab will be below the top towards the road. Alternatively approach as if heading towards Pandora's Box and head uphill from the top of Pandora's box.

description: Start left hand on a high gaston and right low on a bad crimp.  Move up on good crimps untill, suprise suprise, the holds get bad 15 feet off the deck.  Keep it together and top it out.
location: just around the arete to the right of Friction Fighter

description: climb arete next to tree, then mantle
location: to the left of PHbalance.  on the upper of the two cliff bands to the right of the main trail before you reach the main area or the freestanding bloc.

description: Furthest right problem worth doing. Kind of. If you like short but dangerous awkward V0s. Or if you're just really bored or you climbed out South Little Foxx. Start around to the right of and on the bulging prow and move up on bad slopers to the top.
location: Furthest right problem on the Ultimate block.
protection: Pad, and spotter who gives a damn.

location: Front and center of The Short Block. Climbs up the obvious groove angling right. Walk off top out to the right of the boulder.

description: Start low on crimps that start the rail in the center of the Tree Boulder. Move up and right until a good crimp can be had above the useless mono-pocket, then head straight up without going onto Tree Hugger. That's the idea anyway. A variation could continue up the crack through the end of Tree Hugger as well.
location: Essentially the first problem one comes to when entering South Little Foxx. Inspiring but tough as hell! Perfect for a fall ascent.
protection: A single pad would work as this has a great landing.

description: Sit start on obvious holds on the arete and move up to a good right lippy pocket, then to the angled crack with thin crimps. Very high feet place one in a slightly crunched position, but ready for an exit, either straight up or out to the right.
location: An ambling crack starts at the base of the tree and works its way up around the bulge. Tree hugger starts about 5 feet to the right of the tree on low holds and meets up with this crack.
protection: 1 pad is enough with a good landing.

description: Start the slab fest on some pretty positive crimps to a solid jug.  Now to the business.  Get your feet set for a few committing moves on some tiny crimps to a ledge.  Pull past the ledge (don't look down) to a thin diagonal crack.  Use it to top out!
location: This is just around the corner of the Depression Wall, which is to the right and part of the same formation of the Ultimate Block.  Slabadabadoo is straight up the middle of the slab.
protection: A pad or two.  Use a spotter!  Landing is not great!

description: A nice little 5.9ish jam crack on the left side of the Depression Wall (wall that is just right of the Ultimate Wall).

Sit start using left face hold and right arete.  With the right wall off limits, work your way up into the double arete through the overhang.  Top out before your depression causes you to make a poor decision.
location: The Loathing Arete is located on the far right end of The Depression Wall, just past Arete's Syndrome.  Look for the obvious double arete where this rock is separated from the right wall.

description: Jump start (unless you're Justin or Soren) to the extremely sharp starting holds on the rail. Dyno up to the right to the jug.
location: Near the Center of the Depression Wall.
protection: Pad, watch out for the slope.

description: Start on Prozac Crack till you hit the horizontal crack.  Move right on slopers and ok feet, the pump builds just as you hit the crux.  Finish on Loathing Arete.  The crux of this is really establishing yourself on coner and then moving around onto loathing arete.  Sending this is an immediate cure for your depression.
location: Traverses the depression wall
protection: one pad with a spotter to drag it under you or about six the length of the crack if your alone

description: Start with a hold on the face and a fish hook on the arete. With high feet on the face, throw out left to a poor sloper. Work the arete and feet to a desperate crimp that really can only be used for balance. Fire for the jugs and the top out is yours.
location: This is on the Depression Wall, which is to the right and part of the same formation of the Ultimate Block. Arete's Syndrome is on the far right end of the wall, with a giant flake suspending a small boulder in the air to the right.
protection: Pads and friends; good flat landing.

description: Stand start move up on slopey holds till you reach the positive horizontal crack (beware of the loose death block wedged in the crack).  top out up and to the right.  As this cleans up it may get better but mossy for now
location: about 15 feet to the left of off route

description: Same start as Cool 2, but continue right into small gully.  Then find your way up using good holds.
location: continues to the right of Cool 2
protection: pads... please protect punji pit from possible piercing and potential painful penetrating puncturing power.

description: SDS on decent holds low and to the left off the start holds for off route.  Make a big right hand move to the start of off route and continue from there
location: pad
protection: on front face of the Next Block while walking from the Whatever Wall

description: This takes the obviouse line up the front side of the boulder as you walk at it from the Whatever Wall.  Start on crimps at eye level then move up to awesome vertical crack that continues to top.
location: on front face of the Next Block while walking from the Whatever Wall

description: Stand start on crimps and climbs straight up on, suprise, more crimps plus a horizontal crack
location: couple feet to the left of off route
just to the right of "cool 1"
Once you past the boulders coming from the the ultimate area, the climbs are around to the left.
protection: a pad/ a filler pad for weird landing

description: Start to the right of Tree Hugger on good underclings. Move up to the crack on the right and keep going till the jug on the upper left is accessable. Top it out.
location: Furthest right problem on the Tree Boulder.
protection: Pad the rock in front. Slightly on a slope. Use a spotter.

description: Make the first move on Tree Hugger to the lippy pocket.  Then move far left to a hidden crimpy flake, adjust your feet, and bring your right hand to a small frictiony bulb.  This gets you onto the Welcome to Duluth project.  Finish straight up the slab using the seam.

Stand start with hands on the flat shelf above your head (or at your head if you're taller). Do not be tempted to lay-back the giant solid obvious flake inches from your right hand like a little girl. Be a man and dyno this thing like you know it wants to be.
location: The U.D.O.U.D. is the left most problem on the Ultimate Block. If starting from the Tree Boulder (the closest boulder to the parking), just follow the orange flagging for about 400 meters until you come to the Alien Wall. The Ultimate block is immediately to the right about 20 feet.
protection: A pad that you might think about tying to the tree behind you to keep it from sliding downhill. A spotter is recommended

description: This is the obvious overhanging crack in the middle of the picture. Crux move is right off the ground pulling on a very insecure handjam. You'll definitely need a good spot for the upper moves.
Climb the prow dudes. Jugs to the left are off. I started with a high left hand and my right in the cool little pocket. A lower start has yet to be done.
location: Arete of the Ultimate Block.
protection: Pads and a spotter who can dig their heels in.

description: Start beneath the bulging prow on the razor sharp undercling.  Move up and over the bulge to top out on Ultimately Pointless.
location: Near the far right side of the Ultimate Block under the obvious small roof.
protection: 1-2 crash pads and a spotter so you don't fall down the hole or off the edge.

description: Start with high hands on one of the holds that start the Ultimate Arete (but just to the left of it. Climb up the slopy curve to jugs and top out. The grade on this can go up or down depending on the beta/holds used. V4 is a general middle of the road grade for many variations that can occur on this side.
location: Between the dyno and the arete on the Ultimate Block.

description: Start the same The High road but move right only a couple feet off the ground.  The hand holds are decent but there is some hard heel hooking.  Tranverse into and finish the same as Ghetto Coolade.
location: Starts the same as the High Road and finishes on Ghetto Coolade.

description: Sit start on a small ledge using good side pulls.  Trend right till our about ten feet up and then reach way out left for a small side pull.  Fancy footwork allows you to reach ever father left to a better side pull.  Match on this then throw up to the sloppy rail and then straight up using what ever you can to top out.
location: up the center of the first cliff band between dirty harry and deer run
protection: Bring lots of pads and a few spotters.  A good one to work on TR first as a fall from the crux (top)would have bad consequences.

description: Stand start with small hands up to a slopey hold. Super slabby and really fun!
location: Number 12 in Peter Dodge's Guide to Bouldering.

description: Fun little line that has an obvious start with the slots in the horizontal crack that is maybe hip high or so. Move up to the rail and then start navigating squeezing both aretes. The rock is gritty, so that's awesome, but getting the feet up is the main challenge.
location: Lower band, further up stream from "morning slug" and other lines. If you hit the bigger wall that looks a bit chossy, you're barely too far and will see it you turn around.
protection: Couple of pads. Landing is so-so and a spotter would be handy.

description: Very thin line that has been sitting there just waiting to be seen. You will start with a left hand sidepull near (but not in) the large crack and right hand on an arrowhead looking hold. Move slightly right and straight up. You will not use the main large crack at all as you move far enough right that it wouldn't be close enough to be helpful. Look for a small crimp and a really cool press/mantle move.
location: This is between the large crack line and ASP3.

description: "Stand start on slopers. The slopey bottom ledge is on. Follow the large water runnel to the top." Description from Pete's Digital Duluth Bouldering Guide. It's all about shoe friction and body positioning on the slab/slopers.
location: At the Lower Wall at West Enger Park, the boulder in front of/nearer to the road than the wall with all the cracks

description: Standing start on the little seam...climb up using the seam and face.
location: The first crack (tiny seam) on the upper face

description: Standing start at an arete and throw for the horizontal.  Gain that then stick to the thin slab and don't think about falling!
location: Around the corner (left) of the easy cracks.
protection: Pads (more than one will save your ankles)

description: Finger crack / Face climb between Pounder's Crack and the hand crack...pretty straight forward but fun.
location: Between Pounder's Crack and the hand crack

description: Standing start on a straight forward crack and face climb.
location: Obvious finger crack on the upper face.

description: Climb the crack with use of the arete across the archway. ¬†Easy climb with the opportunity to practice different techniques.
Start out on the left corner of the large wall and crimp up to a ledge followed by a second ledge. Top out farther right, may require the use of a tree to top out.
location: Far-left side of the highball wall.

description: Highball boulder. Start on the right side of the large wall, move straight up above the large loose-looking rock. Mantle on top, then move left to the top. May require the use of a tree to top out.
location: At the base of the large rock wall by the street, below other Enger boulders. Far-right side almost in a corner.

description: Climb the hand crack...pretty simple, huh?
location: Upper face.

description: The slab just right of the hand crack - this is pretty fun and worth while.  Thin climbing up crimps to a mildly dicey top out.
location: Blank slab just right of the hand crack
Head down towards the lower cliff band and then turn around to walk to the creek. You'll see it on your right side once at the creek. Start and finish of the line is very easy to see.

description: Located on the upper band, you will see this one right away. There's a tree right at it, but is easy to avoid the dab. Sit start with left hand on longish rail and right hand on large pinch thing coming out of the wall. High right foot will let you rock up and get into the crack that will lead up and to the left. An easier start is right hand on the longish rail and left hand on super nice sidepull in other crack.
location: Look for the tree on the upper wall, very easy to find.

description: Sit start with left hand on undercling and right on crimp. Move up to another crimp or straight into big hold in dihedral. Climb up and out the mini roof. Several ways to finish it, but the direct up the face without using the huge crack off to the right is the most fun.
location: Lower cliff band, pretty much the first boulder you'll run into once you go down there. Hard to miss the unique roof feature.

description: Start on the corner, move right and up into the shallow dihedral.
location: Route #8 in Urban Cragger.

description: Route #7 in the Urban Cragger. Just to the right of The dihedral warm up problem. Stand start using slot and sloped rail. High feet and use diagonal seam to the top.
location: Obvious triangular pocket and sloped rail. Just to the right of the classical dihedral warm up.

description: Same start as Unknown 3, but move towards the arete and then to top.
location: Route #4 in Urban Cragger.

description: Starting at the horizontal  above a cresent dish, climb up  using the diagonal seam.  Seam can also be aided at C2.
location: Just left of Rocket's Revenge

description: Standing start low on two flakes, dynamic moves take you to the top.
location: Route #2 in Urban Cragger.

description: Sit start on the obvious arete and climb up left of the arete.
Just left of Stump Chump...Start on the holds on and left of the horizontal and climb the crimps to the top.
Feels more like a scramble than a climb. Straight up the slab face to the top.
location: Number 13 in Peter Dodge's Guide to Bouldering.
Side of boulder facing the road. Sit start on the rightmost jug near the ground.

description: Same Start as delight. Move right to decent sloper. Stand up and finish
location: Front of First Street Boulder

description: Sit start on obvious jug ledge. Make a left hand move to the rail and match. Big move to small crimp, shuffle feet, and proceed to send.
location: Front of First Street Boulder. Right of the chump routes.

description: Start the same as Chump Unknown but instead of finishing in the shallow dihedral continue into the starting crimps on unknown #3 problem finishing with the fun dyno.   Adds a more difficult finish to Chump Unknown making it a solid V5 in my opinion.
location: start the same as Chump Unknown and finish on Unknown #3

description: Start on Stump Chump (or just stand using the bomber undercling and huge left sidepull). Work up a move or two, then use that core strength to press into a wicked double gaston. Fancy footwork bring one into the shallow wanna-be dihedral to the right of the arete, and perhaps another gaston. Either stay in the shallow area, or utilize the arete on the left. Both exits make this semi-traverse the most classic line on the First Street Boulder (in my silly opinion).
location: This is the proudest line on the steepest arete with the huge chalked starting holds, where the boulders meet the dirt, road facing.
protection: The landing can actually be kinda sketch, as small boulders start to line the base on this side, so several crash pads a couple spotters are recommended, but not necessary if you're as awesome (stupid?) as Egg and me.

first_ascent: Adam Van Straten and Kraig Decker
description: Follows the arete.  SDS A few big moves to start until a ledge is reached half way up.  from there its cake
location: follow the right of The Sound of the Life of the Mind
protection: a few pads and a spotter.  there is a pit right where you whould fall.

first_ascent: Adam Van Straten and Kraig Decker
description: follow the left crack.  pretty mellow till the top where the crack flares a bit and you must smear with you feet.
location: just left of skeeter snack

route_name: The Sound Of The Life Of The Mind (direct)
description: SDS Head straight up the bulge.  Good start holds turn to poor crimps quickly.  Very technical. Took months for me to figure out the Beta.
location: first problem you come to

first_ascent: Adam Van Straten and Kraig Decker
description: the right of the two cracks on the boulder.  Lie back the rail till it ends.  use a poor slopper and high feet to get to the horizontal crack then top out.  Easier for taller folks.
location: The right most problem

route_name: (project) The Sound Of The Life Of The Mind
description: start on the right arete on traverse the horizontal crack into the direct version of this problem.
location: Staarts on the right arete

description: SDS under the small overhang with your feet on the low angle slab.  use a big sloppy pinch in the mini cave and a small crimp above it and move up and to the left for couple move on nice big holds.  Then traverse right making a big lunge to a big ledge on Aiden's great escape and top out the same as that problem.  A nice warm up with fun moves.
location: starts right below the tall overhanging hace and then move right into Aiden's great escape about 5 feet 5-6 feet off the ground.
protection: a pad or two and a spotter is recommended

description: Start with a pinch on the start hold of Aiden's great escape and a crimp on your right. Bump to triangle on right up to the rail. Over to the bomber lip on left corner up to the sidepull, sloper and top out....It's less confusing when you see the face of the climb, mainly a sart to straight up..
location: to the right of Aiden's great Escape

description: This takes the line straight up the steepest part of the wall.  The crux half way up way you must match on a sloppy rail and move off of it.
protection: This is only PG13 if it is bouldered.  Top rope by slinging two trees with lots of webbing or many pads and spotters if you are brave enought to boulder this.

description: Start: match on credit card crimp up to intermediate sloper/crimp, up to large shelf hold to top out horn area.
location: To the right of Aidens great escape on the slab around the corner.

description: The crux is starting this.  sit sart matched on slopper and lousy feet and bump up and left.  match stem left and hit the next good hold out left and its over just top out.  The crack is not on
location: left side of cliff band

description: Great holds but a bit of a sketchy top out with the trees behind you.
location: right side of first cliff band

description: Match crimp to upper crimp to finsh on crack , completely linear route, topout horn by Dudeus maximus.
location: So the right of Aidens Great escape on the corner seam.

description: Sit start under small bulge and climb up slightly overhanging rock on good holds and lousy feet.  Then move out left and top out.
location: Walk 300 yards down deer trail to the second band of rock

description: Work around the giant flake below the start of the crack (either left or right, though left seems to put one in a harder position). Lay back or finger lock if you can get them in; rattly at places as well. Hold it together with some good footwork and you're free into the trees that gaze over the top of this wall. Exit to the right down a shallow gully.
location: The right and thinner of the two parallel cracks one sees upon arriving at the base of the Alien Wall.
protection: Couple pads and spotters with long arms. I don't recommend doing this one alone.

description: This is a lesson in thin techniqual climbing, which is much different then its neighbors. Stand start on crimps on the seam that moves up and to the right.  Move up and right to a horizontal seam.  Some techniqual foot work allows you to make a big move to another horizontal seam.  More good foot work allows you to go for a crimp out left, fall here and you'll land on the small tree.  Make one more big move up and right back into the seam to a decent hold and then top out the slab.
location: Ten feet left of Flight of the Navigator
protection: one or two pads; 1-2 spotters is a must, if you come off up high you are going to tumble down the hill

description: Start on the left side of the giant flake, move up through the little roof and out onto the bomber hands crack. Breathe it out to the top and you're good to go.
location: The left of the 2 center cracks on the Alien Wall.

description: Start at the giant flake and climb out the hands crack to the right and around the corner.
location: The right crack on the Alien Wall.

route_name: Close Encounters of the Trad Kind
description: Start with an impossibly small crimp and a dish for your thumb, with feet on the huge ledge. A couple desperate moves deposit one into the amazing hand crack that finishes Flight of the Navigator. Time for the crimping men and women to pull out some traditional skills and jam to the top! Fun through and through!
location: Face climb just to the left of the two parallel cracks upon arriving. There is a low mono pocket to the right of the start that could help this go as a very difficult sit start.

description: Sit start on the farthest right side of the alian wall.  Either matched or with left had out in side pull slot. then move out to horizontal crack on face, or stay on faint arete. go up to large crack using cool sloping holds.  you could continue on the arete line for a harder scarier top out. maybe contrived but fun
location: faint arete on furthest right side of alian wall.
protection: 1 pad.  more if you go straight out on the arete line.

description: An array of sharp crimps up the face with good sit start variations.
location: Route #7 in Urban Cragger.
Left boulder, stand start on right angled rail directly behind tree.
protection: pads, spotters. pad the tree directly under the problem, and maybe some more all down the hill to the sidewalk. a little exciting

description: climb the obvious slab
location: to the right of gumby and Snooky Loves Curly

description: SDS in the small dihedral/corner.  Lie back for the first half, couple of large ledges for the second.  Watch out for loose holds and moss
SDS match on crimps.  Move up using a flake and the crack.  High step then use the sweet pinch hold and go for the top out.
SDS match on the ledge, move up up to a crimp half way up in the middle of the face.  Hike your feet up and gun for the top.  Only two hands move but fun.

Start hugging the arete with your left hand and your right in the finger crack.  Slap up the arete with your left then bump your right hand up to a good crimp.  Make a dynamic move to a good crimp then top out.
protection: One pad and a spotter (potential to roll down the slope)

description: Was much harder for me until I found the right beta.  SDS on crimps  and feet in the mini cave.  move up using both aretes.

SDS on the face just right of Volume 1.  Start with your left hand on a poor crimpy sidepull and right on a good crimp.  Make a big desperate move to a good sharp incut crimp (crux).  Then move your right up to a hidden pocket.  Gain the ledge and it's all over.
location: to the right of volume 1 on the face

description: SDS left hand on the corner right in the crack, feet smeering. Bump right up corner, left up to the sloper crimp. Right into upper horizontal crack and throw up to the top nose. Not too difficult but fun for a short problem.
location: To the climbers left about 50 yards on the same cliff band as the main set of routes.

description: SDS start on the large ledge and use crimps till you reach another ledge about ten feet up.  There layback the large flake for the last 5-6 feet the top out.  This climbs a lot like a trad route but still fun
location: center of the south cliff band

description: Climb the rail up and the right, don't fall off into the tree.  This would be really sweet if you didn't have a ledge for your feet
location: up the hill from the other problems

description: This is the thin left facing crack to the right of Gumby.  Very little to use outside of the crack.  Has not been free'ed from what I know but aided at A2.  Get one it.  I'm not sure what the grade is but it requires you to enter one
location: to the right of Gumby

description: Climbs the right side of the arete.  Start with a crimp for your right and slap your left up the arete till you find a decent spot.  Dyno for the sloper then top out
location: The arete to the left of Gumby

description: Start on Gumby and traverse left half way crimping the horizontal seam t the lft arete then top out.
Follow the crack up and right.  The first couple moves are on bomber holds the you are required to use a decent sloper and make a big move out right to a good hold (the crux), then its all over
location: The left of the two cracks

description: Continue up the arete to the undercling. After the undercling, the height becomes heady, but keep going!
location: Sit start on the tree located almost right between the 2 boulders. This is the most obvious line starting on the left arete of the right boulder. There is a stand start option, standing on the tree to get the undercling as a starting hold.
protection: 2 pads recommended and a good spotter. I have never fallen on the tree, but it is a possibility.

description: Sitting or standing start the climbs up and left.
location: Route #14 in Urban Cragger.

description: Standing start that climbs through loose holds up the face.
location: Route #15 in Urban Cragger.

description: This kickin' little line is more or less a standing start up the dihedral, with a fun throw to the last jug.
location: Route #3 in Urban Cragger.

description: Standing start on the crimps mid face, climb up and through without either arete.
location: Route #9 in Urban Cragger.

description: Standing start, climb up the arete.
location: Route #8 in Urban Cragger.

description: Sit start with hands on flake, follow cracks up and right.
location: Route #16 in Urban Cragger.

description: Standing start with sit start variations.  Start left of rock, traverse right and climb up face.  Stay left of arete.
location: Route #2 in Urban Cragger.

description: Start sittin with face holds in hand and climb up. (Starting lower under the boulder adds a lot.)
location: Route #5 in Urban Cragger.

description: Sit start on the face holds left of the arete, then climb straight up the arete.
location: Route #4 in Urban Cragger.

description: Start head first, descending into the hole climb towards road and finish with mangle back to where you started.
location: Route #10 in Urban Cragger.

description: Sit start, climb face without the aretes.
location: Route #1 in Urban Cragger.

description: This can be done as a sit start, or standing for the unambitious. Pretty straighforward; climb the bulge to a cool undercling, then to the somewhat creepy mantle without getting too much lichen on yourself. A key hold for me resides out left.
location: This tiny wall lies about 20 feet uphill from the Hobo Boulder. An open project is several feet to the right in a shallow dihedral. V10+ maybe?
protection: Couple pads and a sober spotter, without whom a fall would result in rolling down the hill.

description: Sit start on a low rail, climb out and up a face following the right arete.
location: Route #13 in Urban Cragger.

description: This is an open project.  It has two polar opposite cruxes one right at the start and one near the end.  Start on crimps head height on the face.  Make a big dyno to a ledge, match and then gaston up and to the left, bump up your feet and dyno to the left arete.  Move up to a horizontal crack up and right then up to a crimpy flake.  Here rest the best you can before the second crux.  It involves using tiny crimps and slapping up the featureless smooth arete.  This leads to a couple of better crimps on the face before the top.
location: On the face between Brewer's Arete and Brewer's Crack
protection: TR for now, hopefully to be bolted soon.  A pad over the boulder to the left to protect any falls in the first crux, without it you might have a really sore butt!

location: The face above the boulders at Brewer's Park
protection: Cams from finger to hand...4 pieces max and maybe a big hex to protect the belayer.  Sling boulders at top for anchor or build from gear.

location: The prominent arete at Brewer's Park that can be seen from the road.

description: Start with left hand in seam, right on the lower crimp.  Move up right while climbing through shitty crimps.
location: Route #12 in Urban Cragger.

route_name: All Brewed Up And No Where To Go
description: SDS on the right side of the blunt arete. Using hold on both sides of the arete work your way to a difficult top out.  Crux is the first and last moves.   Walk off/ climb off to the right (you may want a pad for this,you are basically down-climbing a chossy V1)
location: 75-100 yards east from Brewer's arete along the cliff line.

description: Start in the two drilled out shallow pockets (I did not do this) and make one move to the lip and top out.  Beware of loose holds, I pulled off a bunch but there is still some choss.
location: center of the west face

description: Climb the obvious line up the center of the east face of the boulder
location: east side of the boulder
