location: Near the middle of the Pontoon Wall, this route starts under the small cave and left of the large cave/roof system on the right end of the wall.

description: Climb the face near the corner for some interesting moves.  At the top, pull into and through the dihedral with the block in it, using the cracks or holds.  Mostly good rock.
location: On the right corner of the Pontoon Wall.
protection: 4 bolts, 2-bolt anchor.  May take a #3.5 Camalot.  Rap or lower.

description: Quite a mix of climbing styles.  First, climb up and left through the steep pocketed roof.  From there, head up to the base of the right-arching crack.  Follow it up and right, around a bulge.  From there, finish by heading straight up to the anchors.  Mostly great rock, with a few hollow or fractured sections.
location: Near the right end of the Pontoon Wall, this route exits out of the middle of the cave/roof system on the right end of the wall.  Start a few feet right of the first bolt.
protection: Bolts, gear to #3.5 Camalot, slings.  2-bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Climb up under the small roof on decent rock, coming kind-of close to Inner Pigeon.  Then, head up and right into the good stuff.  This route is more of the great face climbing and good rock that the Pontoon Wall is known for.  Finish at the anchors of Inner Pigeon.
location: Near the middle of the Pontoon Wall, this route exits out the left side of the large cave/roof system on the right end of the wall.
protection: Bolts, 2-bolt anchor, shared with Inner Pigeon.  Rap or lower.

description: Nice moves up vertical face.  Good rock on the route, choss above it.
location: Near the right end of the Slabtown area, this is the bolted line between the crack that is Mental Hygiene and the small cave near ground level.

description: Climb the slab beneath the left angling dihedral that becomes an undercling roof. Take advantage of pro before getting to the crack. Start working a hand traverse under the roof and navigate through loose, dirty rock eventually joining the anchors for Logan.
location: Slabtown between Logan and Lo and Behold.
protection: SR. Lots of micro cams helped feel safe on this route but I used a lot of gear in general as some pro is questionable.

description: Climb the face to the crack.  Climb the crack to its end, then traverse right ot the anchors on Rattler.  Pretty good rock.
location: Near the right end of the Slabtown area, this is the subtle, often-vegetated crack.  Start below it.
protection: 3 bolts, 1 pin, gear to 2".  2-bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

first_ascent: Jer Collins, Ben Williams, bolts by JP Sankpill
description: Starting in Foxjaw Cave, climb out its right side on fractured rock, then head up.  The rest of the climb consists of fun face climbing on good rock.
location: Near the left end of the Pontoon Wall.  Start in Foxjaw Cave and exit out the right side on bolts.

description: Steep slab climbing on good rock.
location: Near the left of the Slabtown area, this route is right of both Centipede and Soup.  Begin under the left end of the roof up high.

description: Great face climbing through bulges on good holds.
location: Near the middle of the Slabtown area, this route begins just right of the left-arching roof crack that is Raiders of the Chossed Arc.  This line splits the two small bulges.

description: More steep slab/face climbing on pretty good rock.
location: On the right end of the Slabtown area, just left of the broken vegetated crack that is Mental Hygiene.

description: Good steep slab/face climbing on mostly good rock.  The sling before the first bolt may be old, so bring your own.
location: Near the middle of the Slabtown area, this route is the steep slab/face right of Lo and Behold.  It usually has a sling through a hole before the first bolt.
protection: 4 bolts, a sling, 2-bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Exit the small cave on the left and follow the thin crack up and left on bad rock to its end.  Then head left to New Directions' anchor on bad runout slabbiness.
location: Left end of Stealth wall.  Broken left arching crack coming out of a small cave.
protection: Pro to 2".  2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Climb the slab to the roof, past 2 large huecos and more steep slab to the anchors.  Good rock.
location: Towards the right end of the Stealth Wall, this line climbs the slab to the right of Crisis of Belief and pulls a small roof in the middle of the route.

description: Start on the slab, clipping one bolt on the way to the crack.  Climb the crack to the left, around the bulge, past the tree and to the anchor.  Good rock, excellent climb.  This has been the first trad climb for many MO climbers.
location: In the middle of the Stealth Wall, this is the left-arching crack line with a tree in it near the top.
protection: 1 bolt, gear to 3", 2-bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Follow the bolts up the steep crimpy slab and face.  Good rock.
location: The farthest route right on the Stealth Wall, 30 feet right of a tree on the face.

description: Generic slab climbing through the horizontal line of pockets halfway up.  Good rock.
location: At Slabtown, this is the leftmost route, the first one after coming down the main walkdown.  Start under the first bolt.
protection: 3 bolts, maybe a larger cam, 2-bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Climb through choss down low to 2 pods side by side. Face/slab on good rock, angling left, to the anchors. Be careful coming down as you will lower through a very loose section.
location: Left end of the Stealth Wall. Right of long thin roof and left of thin crack coming out of a small cave. Start beneath two pods side by side.
protection: Bolts, 3.5 camalot, 2 bolt anchor. Rap or lower.

description: Climb slab to the right arching flake with the wide crack behind it.  Layback the flake (careful, it's brittle limestone) and finish by angling right on a slab.  Ok rock.
location: This is the right arching flake on the left end of the Stealth Wall.
protection: Gear to 4", bolt, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Climb the steep slab in a direct line to the anchor.  Good rock, classic route.
location: In the middle of the Stealth Wall, this is the bolted slab framed by an arching crack on each side.

description: Climb the slab to the roof.  Pull the roof and gain a small ledge.  From there, follow the crack to where it peters out, then head left and up for more slab climbing.  Good rock.
location: Towards the right end of the Stealth Wall, this line is directly right of the Saint.  Start under the roof that leads into a right-facing crack.
protection: 3 bolts, gear to 3", 2-bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Face climb past the bolt and make a 'walrus move' on to the ledge.  From there, continue up and left in the thin hand crack dihedral to the anchor.  Good rock.
location: Just left of the main Washboard Area.  Start beneath a bulge and a left facing/left arching crack.
protection: Bolt, gear to 2", 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Follow the dihedral to a traverse left on pockets.  Some face moves then lead you to the right angling roof crack.  Follow it up and right to the anchor, never really pulling the roof, though.  Good rock.
location: In the middle of the Washboard Area.  The line follows the dihedral, then the right angling roof crack.  Start on ledge above the belay ledge.
protection: Bolts.  2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Climb the dihedral hand crack until you can step right onto the face about 1/3 of the way up.  Face climb the rest of the way, folowing the bolts.  Good rock.
location: Starts on the right crack in the back of the alcove, left of Dogfish.
protection: Pro to 3", 5 bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Steep prow at far left side of Funhouse alcove. Mostly casual climbing to a short V6 crux. Sends have generally skipped the mid crux bolt as it interrupts the climbing but makes for a good means to hangdog/work it.
protection: 11 Draws. Anchors below lip and above lip.

description: To the right of AtmosFear and left of Pressing Shish. Start in vertical scoop, and escape out the right side. Follow bolts and a pin through upper bulge, which leads into a layback crack.
protection: draws- optional #4 camalot at pin. Stickclip start

description: Pull the dihedral roof on a finger crack.  Then continue up following the crack as it arches to the right near the top.  Pretty good rock.
location: Starts below a right facing dihedral roof crack, just left of a steep bolted roof and face.  Belay on upper ledge to spot the climber.
protection: Gear to 3".  Walk off or rap on trees.  Better to walk over to the top of Droopy Corndo and rap.

description: Long bolted face to the right of Black Snake Crack.
protection: 9 draws (some may want a finger sized cam for runout between 3rd and 4th bolt) Stick-clip start. Bolted anchors on top-out.

description: After climbing Yahoo Crack, angle up and right on face holds, pulling a small roof 10 feet past the first anchor.  After that, more slab/face climbing takes you to the second anchor.  Ok rock.
location: The extension to the Yahoo Crack can be found on the right side of the Far Side buttress.  Start under the right facing dihedral crack.
protection: Pro to 3" for the crack, 2-3 bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Lower or rap.

description: Climb through the chimney like crack in the roof, clipping a bolt above and gaining the ledge.  Continue in the dihedral crack to the anchors halfway up the cliff.  OK rock.
location: Start below the dihedral crack on the right side of the Far Side buttress, under a wide crack through a low roof.
protection: Bolt, Pro to 3".  2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

location: On the prow of the Far Side buttress, start on the highest ledge you can walk on.  A very low bolt clippable from here is the start of the route.

description: Climb up the slab to the base of a vertical section containing a finger crack.  Climb it, then head up and left in the hand crack.  After pulling around the corner, head up on bad rock to the top.  Belay on trees.
location: Left of the Far Side buttress is a slab.  Go to the thin tree on the slab and above should be a left arching roof crack.  That's the climb.
protection: Gear to 3.5", slings for tree anchors.  Walkoff in drainage area between the slab and the Far Side buttress.

description: Climb the slabby section down low and a vertical section containing the double undercling.  Head up and right through the big roof, then up through a smaller bulge and to the anchors.  Mostly good rock, though a little broken near the roofs.
location: Face right of the Far Side buttress.  Start below the sole bolt line and a roofy area up top.
protection: 6 bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Start on Tigerbill on the far left ledge of the funhouse alcove. Follow to it's fourth bolt, then merg right onto steep white blocks over a cave. Numerous technical moves lead to an exciting finish.
Climb the right of the dihedral a few feet to gain the finger crack to the left.  Follow this up to the first bolt.  Then climb the face and slab to the anchors.  Good rock.
location: Right in the middle/back of Funhouse Alcove.  Start on the right side of the dihedral, then left to the finger crack.
protection: 4 bolts, medium to large nuts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Climb hand crack low for 30 feet, stay left at the tree into the crux offwidth to slab finish.
location: Same start as Tomiko right of Gomerwood.

description: I start on Tigerbill, heading right when it gets slabby.  Whatever way you choose, you need to end up at the base of the steep left-angling hand crack.  Some nice steep crack moves take you to a small tree.  Sling it and head right to the bolts.  Good rock, if you go this way.
location: This line climbs the left arching crack up high.  Start either on Funhouse to the right, in the vegetated broken chossy finger crack (the original line), or on Tigerbill to the left (the best way)
protection: Pro to 3", 2 bolt anchor.  Bolts, too, if starting on either bolted line.

description: Start on thin vertical/slabby face climbing, heading left near the top of the first section.  Head back right as you scramble up to the base of the headwall.  Then, head up on excellent moves and good rock past 3 or 4 bolts.
location: In the middle of the right facing wall, just left of Gomerwood.
protection: Bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Maybe take a .75 camalot for between the first two bolts of the headwall near the top.

description: Clip the first bolt and work around the left side of the very chossy section to gain the ledge.  Here, the climb may be considered a little runout because if you fail to clip the second bolt, you will deck.  From the ledge, head up on pretty good rock and enjoyable face climbing, pulling a small roof along the way.
location: On the right side of the alcove, this route starts on a bolt below a ledge.
protection: 6 bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: This is a choss pile and should only be used to access Pocket Rocket above.  Just follow the bolts.
location: Starting on the left side of the biggest prow at Warsaw, around the left side of Funhouse Alcove, by the walkdown gully.  The first bolt is about 15 or 20 feet up.
protection: 2 or 3 bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap, lower, or go up on Pocket Rocket.

description: To the right of Tomiko on a nice gray face, start with a bolt right off the ground then trend up and right, following 7 bolts.

Start left of the first bolt, maybe clipping it with a single locker, then angle up right through the roof.  After gaining the ledge, head up left, following bolts.  After pulling the small roof, follow a neat finger crack and face ot the anchors.  Mostly good rock, maybe a section of barely questionable holds.
location: On the left side of Walrus Ledge.  This is the bolt line left of the dihedral crack system, Pressing Shish.  Start under a roof 10-15 feet off the ground.
protection: 7 bolts, 1 pin, 2 bolt anchor.  Also take a #4 Camalot or tech Friend to back up the pin.  Rap or lower.

description: Pull through the wide roof crack at the bottom, gaining a ledge.  The PG rating is for here because of the poor quality of rock.  After the ledge, follow the enjoyable hand/finger crack up to the anchor.  There is good rock on all but the starting roof.
location: This is the dihedral crack on the left side of Walrus Ledge.  The start is under a wide roof crack.
protection: Gear to 2 or 3".  A wide cam for the start may be useful.  2 bolt anchor on the left or top out.

description: Pull the very low roof to gain a ledge.  Some consider this part runout, because if you fall off the ledge or the first move without clipping, you will deck.  Continue up on vertical face climbing, joining Droopy Corndog up high.  Anchors are on a nice comfy ledge at the top, so you can walk off or rap in from here.  Good rock.
location: On the left side of Walrus Ledge, this is the second bolt line right of the corner system on the left.  Starts at a very low roof with a bolt clippable from the ground.
protection: Bolts, two bolt anchor over the top.  Rap, lower, or walk off.

description: Start in kind of a shallow corner, heading up and right.  Gains a small ledge, then up on face climbing and through a small roof, ending on a slab.  Anchors are on a ledge at the very top, allowing one to walk off or rap in.
location: On the left side of Walrus Ledge.  This is the first bolt line right of the dihedral crack system.
protection: Bolts, two bolt anchor on a ledge at the top.  Lower, rap, or walk off.

location: Near the right end of Walrus Ledge, this is the first bolt line left of the large dihedral crack.

description: Climb the face to the base of the roof.  Pull into the chimney, then right around the corner to the face.  Climb up to a ledge hight on the route.  Pull the final moves on a face to clip the anchors.  Good rock.
location: Near the left end of the Washboard Area.  Starts beneath the low roof with a wide crack/chimney running through it.  A dihedral crack system runs above this.
protection: Bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Start on a ledge above the belay, clipping a bolt from it.  Then head straight up on slopers, going left after 3 or 4 bolts.  This joins Gary's Route after 4 bolts.  Good rock.
location: In the middle of the Washboard Area, just left of the large dihedral system that is Gary's Route.
protection: 6 bolts, 2 bolt anchor on the flat top.  Rap, lower, or walkoff.

description: Climb the face of Brooks and Spiders From Mars.  Then "either squirm through the chimney, or heel hook and stem out left on good holds to the first independent bolt."  From there, continue up the face to a beautiful short vertical face at the top.  Good rock.  The middle section isn't awesome quality, but not too bad.
location: At the left end of the Washboard Area.  Start beneath the low roof crack/chimney that is Brooks and Spiders From Mars.
protection: 9 bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Face climb on mostly good rock, weaving close to and farther away from the dihedral.  Pull into and around the right side of another small dihedral at the very top.  Good rock.
location: In the middle of the Washboard Area, just right of the large dihedral.
protection: 6 bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap, lower, or walk off.

description: This is a 2 bolt variation for the start of Freefall Cafe.  Thin face climbing for 10 feet or so.  Good rock, though those crimps seem like they may peel off someday.
location: Starts on the small ledge just left of Freefall Cafe, at a bolt clippable from the ledge.
protection: Bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Face/slab climbing, pulling left over a small bulge near the top.  Pretty good rock.
location: On the right end of the Washboard Area.  Start in a dihedral/chimney thing.
protection: 5 bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Face climb to a ledge with a tree.  OK rock.
location: 10 feet right of Freefall Cafe.  Starts right behind a tree.
protection: #3 or 3.5 camalot.  Rap off a tree.

description: Start in a left facing dihedral, pulling the roof and heading up and right.  Follow the slab to the left arching hand crack roof.  Follow this up and left to the anchors.  Good rock.
location: On the right end of the Washboard Area.  This line pulls the right side of the low roof, then aiming for the right arching hand crack at the top.
protection: Bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Start either left of the bolt or on Disco Inferno, then hand traverse under the line.  Crunch up under the roof and explode over it on slopers (you heard me).  After that is a bit of easy slab.  At the headwall, head left, then back right to the anchors.  Good rock.
location: This route is just left of Disco Inferno and pulls the middle of the low roof.
protection: 6 bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

location: Near the middle of the Washboard Area.  Start beneath the two bulges at the very top of the route that look like the route's namesake.
protection: Bolts.  2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Climb the bolted face to the roof crack.  Pull into it and continue up the crack system to the anchors.  Mostly good rock.
location: Near the left end of the Washboard Area.  The same start as Spiders From Mars.  Start beneath the wide crack/chimney runing through a low roof.
protection: Bolts and gear to 3".  2 bolt anchor, if I remember right.  Rap or lower if there are.

location: Between Cleavage and Warrior Poet, starting in a left facing white dihedral.

description: Climb up into the overhanging flake, then head up and right.  After 3 or 4 bolts, head left to a cool finger crack.  Climb up right beneath the large dihedral roof crack with a dead tree in it.  Here, traverse right to another dihedral crack.  Climb it up to the anchors on the left.  Good rock up high.  Pretty good rock in the overhanging flake.
location: At the left end of the Crescent Wall, this route starts below a right-arching overhanging layback flake.
protection: Bolts, slings, gear to 2".  2-bolt anchor.  Rap.

description: TR might be the best option since the bolts and gear placement can be a bit sketchy in spots

5 bolts lead you out the ceiling of the cave via the obviously line of pockets to the crux just below the craziest mantel at Trappers. ¬† Has fixed draws minus the fifth bolt, anchors have rap rings. ¬†Great place to escape the heat...
location: Up the gully north of ‚ÄúMorning Wood‚Äù
protection: 4 fixed draws, 1 draw needed for the fifth bolt

description: Follow Ultra Pimp all the way up to the traverse under the large dihedral roof crack with the dead tree in it.  Instead of traversing, climb this crack.  Be careful not to pull on the tree or it may come out.
location: Starts on Ultra Pimp.
protection: Bolts, gear to 2.5 inches.  2-bolt anchor.  Rap.

description: Climb the slabby crack to the vertical dihedral halfway up, the highlight of the climb.  Continue around the right side of the chossy buttress on the left.  Decent rock.
location: In the middle of the Crescent Wall area, just right of Fish and Bits.  Aim for the dihedral up higher.
protection: Pro to 2".  Rap off of tree.

description: Climb up and left, following bolts and pulling some bulges along the way.  Near the top, head into the right dihedral crack or traverse left into Ultra Pimp for a less 'heady' finish.  Decent rock.
location: On the Crescent Wall, 20-30 feet right of Ultra Pimp.
protection: Bolts, gear to 2".  2-bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Climb the featured slab, maybe getting in occasional pro.  Decent rock.
location: On the right end of the Crescent Wall area, between Fish and Bits and the walkdown.  Begin under the low-angled slab with many scoops and pockets.
protection: Sparse gear to 1".  Bolted anchors, though they may be suspect.  Rap.

description: Climb the slab to the first anchor.  To there, it's 5.7.  After that, continue on more slab to the base of the roof finger crack.  Place gear and pull the crack to gain the second anchor for a nice 5.9.  Good rock.
location: In the Crescent Wall area, this climb starts on the slab to the right of the large cave halfway up.
protection: 4-5 bolts, gear to #1 camalot, 2-bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Be careful not to fall on the ledge. Pull through some hard moves, following beautiful colored streaks in the rock to reach the anchor.
location: First route to the left of Screamin' Eagle

description: Climb up through a corner system. Fun moves
location: First route to the right of Dandelion

description: Climb straight up through an orange streak. Hard and weird move towards the top. Go straight
location: First route to the right of Wicked Googily

Look for the black vertical streaks on the wall, then in this area find the notch in the top of the bluff line, that's the topout. Starting jug is slightly to the right, assuming the water hasn't covered it.

description: Powerful moves off a sharp pocket
location: Left of Streaks in the steepest part of the wall, go straight up and look for obvious pocket.
protection: Make sure the water is deep

description: Climb the face just right of the small cave, ending on the right side of the bulge at the top.  Pretty good rock.
location: Near the right end of the Paddlefish Wall, this is the second route from the right.  Start just right of the small cave and end on the right side of the bulge up top.
protection: Bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Low, tricky crux on face climbing, then sustained at a slightly moderate level.
location: Just right of Godspeed

description: Climb past the first few bolts on Jeronimo and step left into the right facing dihedral crack.  Make sure to place long slings before and after going into the corner, as it is sharp.  Follow the dihedral crack up and right.  Where it ends, traverse right to bolted anchors on another route.  Pretty good rock.
location: Start on the first bolted line on the left of the Paddlefish Wall, Jeronimo.
protection: Bolts, gear to 2", slings.  2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Climb the face starting on the left side of the cave and ending on the left side of the bulge at the top.  Pretty good rock.
location: Near the right end of the Paddlefish Wall, this route starts on the left side of the small cave.  3rd line from the right.
protection: Bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Climb the technical vertical face and steep slab above on pretty good rock.
location: Near the middle of the Paddlefish Wall, this is the 4th bolted line from the right.
protection: Bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Vertical face and steep slab climbing on pretty good rock.  If I remember right, there are both a mono and a cool fingerlock on this route.
location: Near the middle of the Paddlefish Wall, this is the second line left of the small cave.
protection: Bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: Face climbing on decent quality vertical rock.
location: Near the middle of the Paddlefish Wall, this is the first bolt line left of the small cave.
protection: Bolts, 2 bolt anchor.  Rap or lower.

description: First route right of the cave/alcove. Climb to a roof, then follow the ar√™te/face to anchors.
location: Far left end of Paddlefish wall before hiking towards Little Long Dog Wall

description: Blank face with many unique mini-cruxes right of the Shadow Puppet dihedral.
Climb the low-angled slab to a chossy ledge.  Then continue on better rock through the blocky bulge up high to the anchors.  Half the route is pretty good rock, the other half is pretty chossy.
location: The farthest bolted route to the right on the Long Dog Wall.  This route starts left of the small cave and under the large block up high.

description: Pull hard moves on the highest quality limestone. Sustained climbing leads to an anchor
location: First route to the left of Wicked Googily

description: Climb through the face of hanging bloc, pulling down, not out, and follow the bolt line to the top.
location: The wall past the main climbing area. This route is the only developed route in the lose-er rock
protection: Several bolts to a 1 bolt anchor

description: This is a project. Supposed to be around the 13+ range
location: First route to the right of Tangerine

description: Pull burly moves through the small overhang, stick clip the first bolt.
location: First route on the right side of the wall.

description: The pocket route just to the right of Gonna Leave You. Great lead for new climbers.
location: Starts just to the right of Gonna leave you.

description: Starts on Hand in My Pocket then instead of fallowing the pocket line continue straight up pulling in small crimps. Things let up and get easy for the last 8'.
location: Start on hand in my pocket.
protection: Set a top rope off of Gonna Leave You or Hand in My Pocket

description: This is easy pocket route with a small Traverse at the top. The grade is pretty steady throughout.
location: Just around the corner from the last set of routes you'll find a slab with two lines Pockets up the left side.
protection: 6 bolts including the anchors. Burning a zinc-coated quick link or two to rap off.

description: Climb just right of the pocketed face using good holds to reach the top
location: First route to the left of Wasbenator

description: Another Project
location: First route to the right of Wasbenator

description: Abandoned project. Needs more bolts
location: First route to the right of Another Project

description: Beta on photo. Fun outside problem
location: Refer to the map. It is the one on the right label with the red "X".

description: Beta is on the photo

first_ascent: Dakota Walz, Jer Collins, and Billy Claycomb
description: Climb the center face aiming towards two separate, left leaning crack features. This was the first route put up at Raven Rocks and was done ground up with traditional pro.
location: North side of the Lighthouse just left of Arrowhead

description: High ball problem. Flat landing, but you'll want spotters to stop you if you roll or the tress can do the job. I did it today just fine and love the view from the top. At least 18ft.
A nice sit-start, with aheel hook to pull yourself up to a crack, where you can then top out.
A sit start with a low crux. You  follow the vertical crack up to a horizontal ledge, where the problem is finished. It is impossible to top out, due to brush.

first_ascent: Jer Collins, Zion Collins, Billy Claycomb, Spanky
description: Connect cool pinches and features to a flared hand crack then angle right to the anchors of Turtles.
location: Between Birds and Turtles

first_ascent: Dakota Walz, Jer Collins, and Billy Claycomb
description: One of the two ¬ìmust do¬î traverses over the water. Climb sustained 5.8 with occasional great rests from one shore line to the next.

first_ascent: Billy Claycomb, Dakota Walz, and Jer Collins
description: Start at little pocket and trend left to the flake and shattered rock. Finish with some slopers and a series of mantels to the big ledge.
location: South side of the Lighthouse, left most route.
protection: 4 bolts, shares anchors with Deli Faction

first_ascent: Dakota Walz, Jer Collins, and Billy Claycomb
description: Starts under the big red mega jug, climbs right across a ledge, and climbs the left side of an ar√™te with sweet features.
location: South side of the Lighthouse, right route.
protection: 5 bolts, shares anchors with Iron Bro-ccoli

first_ascent: Billy Claycomb, Jer Collins, Dakota Walz
description: This is THE line. Ascending the beautiful east edge of the picturesque standalone tower, this route has the best positioning and top-out of any climb at Raven Rocks and arguably the whole state.
protection: 6 expansion bolts, steel lower off anchors

first_ascent: Jer Collins, Dakota Walz, and Billy Claycomb
description: Climb through the super cool huecos and pockets up wonderful sustained moderate climbing. If the start is flooded, traverse in from Turtles of a Shell. First done ground up with traditional pro.
location: North side of the Lighthouse and farthest right.

description: Classic problem here. Hard and skin-taxing.
location: South end of Blue River rd. Drive along until you see the second pull-off o nthe right side after Minor Park. Park on the right side. You will see an opening in the trees. Follow bush-wacking trail until it meets the mountain biking trail. Turn right onto the trail. Follow it until you can see the cliffs on your right. Look for area to step down along the cliffs. Once down turn left until you find it.

description: Start on the far right side at a corner where the boulder is just a few feet high. Start traversing left with a good undercling into a smaller crimp. Easy moves over a wide crack lead to a few sloopy holds. A wide move around the corner leads with a reachy move to the top.
location: From the parking lot, head the trail up to the obvious boulders. Continue parallel to the street (boulders left, street right) until height of boulders gets lower.

description: Beta on the photo.
location: Refer to map it is the one of the left side.
protection: You will want a pad since rocks cover the landing. Watch out for bikers also.

description: For beta refer to photo. Starts back in the crack and don't use the left wall. Plus feet must stay off bottom rocks
location: Refer to Map, it is the red "X" on the right.

description: Use the arete to climb up, easy climb and could be done in your street shoes. Great view of the woods from the top.
location: down the trail left of the low-ball problem

description: Brittle and flaky face, left of Zig Zag

10 feet east of "Jesse James".  Climb through overhang 10 ft east of Jesse James,  tcu and nuts are handy, then run it out to the obvious finger crack above the horizontal band of jugs, potential ground fall) after the short finger crack traverse to the anchors of Jesse James.  Very run out!
location: 10' east of Jesse James

description: 15 feet west of "Jesse James".  Pull through the overhang to access the vertical crack.
protection: Pro to 4", top out to tree, anchors coming September 17

description: On the corridor side of the boulder, this is the face left of the thin crack.
Follow trail. Trails maps are offered in the nature center. Great roof problem with rock that is actually solid
location: Midpoint of trail. Refer to GPS.

description: Sit-down-start. Climb up the side side of the roof using prominent holds.
Giant slab problem right as you enter on the trail to your right. Work it right to left with hard mantle for a finish.
location: left side of start near the beginning.

description: Climb the right side of the arete where the corridor and the wall that faces the road come together.
Climb the face just right of the tree.  Sit start.
Climb the dihedral using the thin seam and crimps.  Sit start.
Start on crimp in the middle of the wall with both hands, do a hard pull-up to establish your feet on the wall. Dyno to the top.
location: Middle of the wall, right of the dihedral and left of the wide crack.

route_name: Peter Pan in a Porn Star
description: Climbs the obvious wide crack.
Climb the right arete, just right of the wide crack.  Sit start.
Climbs the face between Seam As It Ever Was and Peter Pan on extremely sharp crimps and an undercling.  Sit start.
On the corridor side of the boulder, this is the face right of the thin crack.
On the corridor side of the boulder, this is the thin crack.  Without the face holds, it is V1.
Sit down, then compression moves to the top.
location: up the trail on the hill located on the right.
protection: pads for sure because of rocks

description: refer to photo
location: Up left side of the hill on the right side of the trail.

description: Sit start to small flake, match there and then dyno to top or pull on small crimp.
location: Right of "Jerk Chicken"
protection: Pads and spotter. Watch out for the ledge to the right.

description: On the left side of the boulder, around the corner from the main face.  Climb the face left of the corner.
Start on the right end of the boulder.  Head left and then up and left on the rail to the top left corner of the boulder.
Start 4 feet right of the left corner.  Climb straight up using crimps on the left and the rail on the right.
On the slab side of the boulder, climb the right side of the face using no hands.  Don't forget to top out.
On the slab side of the boulder, climb the left side of the face using no hands.
From a sit, tic-tac to the top on shrinking holds and worsening feet. Stout.
location: On the south face of the No Hands boulder, identify this by a left-angling system of crimps that are not as nice as they look. Start matched and seated in the horizontal. This face tends to seep.

description: Climb the arete where the slab side and the corridor side come together.
Sit start on jugs, do a couple moves on small crimps and dyno to the lip.
location: Located on the south face of the No Hands boulder. Climbs up the middle of the steep blank face.

description: On the left side of the main face.  The face right of the water streak.  Sit start.
Climb the leftmost water stain on crimps and underclings. Good jug and an optional to topout. Arete is off(?)
Sit start with hands in the horizontal crack.  Bust up on polished slopers and a sidepull.
location: On the right side of the main face.

description: This is the low angled arete on the right end of the boulder.  Sit start.
Closer to the right corner of the boulder.  You only get the horizonal crack start and the small 4 inch wide pocket most of the way up.  Sit start.
Best V2 on the boulder. A little contrived due to its proximity to Pooh's corner. Climb the  incut crimps on the right side with awesome feet.
This is the left corner of the Pocket Boulder.
Fun boulder problem with sharp holds and scary top-out. Also one of the highest boulders in Swope.
location: Down the trail after "Chicken Patty". Right before overhang area.

description: Little crack in the Creek side area to practice laybacks and even a foot jam or two.
location: About 20 ft left of Jerk Chicken

description: Low start. Start holds.
location: First noticeable climb on the trail while hiking NE.

description: All the way at the end of the trail. Huge area with a lot for potential for harder problems.
location: end of trail.
protection: Rocks scattered throughout the floor, loose rocks, and fear of rolling on down the hill. Pads, lots of them and a spotter

description: Sit-start; climb the obvious zig-zig crack.
Refer to photo
location: Left on the hillside. Follow trail.

description: A fun eliminate. Start in a low bucket and reach out to a good pocket. Traverse the lip out to top out on the point of the prow, avoiding the jug rail a foot or so above the lip in favor of crimps and slopers
location: Look for the obvious chalked jug under the roof, and bust out the lip climber's left.

description: Start left and then move right using heel-hooks and move around the boulder for top-out.
location: left side of the prow boulder

description: A nice, gently overhanging face with many jugs and slopers. Use whatever holds you want to create warmups for yourself.
location: Anywhere on the face right of the dihedral that marks the area, climb the juggy/slopey slightly overhanging face. Not really a problem, just a way to warm up.
protection: Pads if you feel like it.

description: Traverse with your heel and pull your way up to the first ledge. Possibilities to continue to the top of Choss after a rest but glory is already yours.

Hard problem sharing a start with The Bulge. Start matched on the undercling tufa and work right on small underclings and huge feet. Head straight up just left of the (dead) tree on poor holds. Stay out of the big holds on the arete.
location: From the same start hold as The Bulge, access the right side of the face via some small underclings. If you don't see the sculpted tufa start hold, you're definitely lost.

description: Sit-down-start; begin on the horizontal crack on the far right side of the boulder. Bump to the jagged finger crack and then a series of good crimps before topping out.
A very fun problem. Sit start matched on an obvious undercling tufa and huge feet. Work up through a jug rail, a crimp, and huck for the top. Fun and brief.
location: Left side of the boulder, before the arete. Obvious line
This boulder sits close to Lake of the Woods behind the back entrance to the Zoo. This is a left-to-right traverse across the front of the entire boulder.

description: A fun problem, one of the best in Swope. Start on an obvious, chalked jug under the roof. Reach over the roof using an awesome sloper and a few crimps/sidepulls. Figure out where your feet belong and stick the "dope for swope" crux move. Top out on easy jugs. Low in the grade.
location: Clean problem to the right of a small tree and left of a small dihedral and rock shelf. Stays mostly shaded!

description: Crimps on decent rock just right of the middle of the face facing the rail problem on No Hands Boulder.

location: Looking at the boulder from the road, this problem starts on the left face. The underclings seemed to be the easiest way to stand start.
protection: Pretty good landing. 1 pad is okay, 2 if you are concerned about the top out.

description: Start right of the small undercut on an obvious larger hold. Angle up and left to the hueco shared with Arborist right using underclings and crimps on the slab. Requires a good cleaning most of the time.
location: This problem is located along with both Arborist problems on a small undercut left of a long section of mossy low angle slab, well past all the roped climbing. This problem begins on the right side of the undercut.

description: Great line on ridge of roof.
location: refer to GPS of the area and photo.

description: Long crack slopers into overhang.
location: Refer to photo ad GPS.

description: Sustained, short hand traverse between bolts midway, cool pocket-undercling-pinch finish
location: 2nd route on traverse

description: Fun route sharing a start with Love Letter. Stick clip and boink past the choss. Traverse right and up, unclipping and re-racking the first two draws behind you to save on rope drag and ease cleaning. Bust up through the roof on jugs, clip the last permadraw, and collect yourself for a dynamic crux at the lip. Two bolts of easier climbing take you to the chains.
location: Starts the same as Love Letter, heading up and right.
protection: 2 bolts (unclip these behind you if possible) to permadraws to 2 bolts. Two bolt lower-off anchor.

description: Unfortunately, this climb requires a "trolly start" due to the unclimbable sugar-choss at the base of the route.  Stick clip the first bolt and haul to the near-by jugs.  Past the second bolt,  the climbing is fantastic.  Climb through the crux at the first roof and then rest up before being briefly transported to Sam's Throne on the short, but tricky, headwall.
location: The furthest left route of the Refuge area.

description: The little, but worthy, brother to "The Grand Finale" Start as for "The Grand Finale", when you pull the first roof trend right towards the bolts without permadraws, continue upward for a nice vertical outing.
location: Starts the same as "The Grand Finale"

description: A Missouri masterpiece, start in a Dihedral leading to an overhanging roof, pull the roof to a standing rest and continue for more overhanging jugs leading to a thin redpoint crux.

As you enter the crux of Modern Petroglyph, instead of going up, follow fixed draws across the lip of the roof to the right, pull over onto a face, then up the steep headwall continually angling to the right. A bit of rope drag due to length and changing angles, but back-cleaning a few clips helps.
protection: Mostly fixed draws to lower off chains

first_ascent: FA: Kelly Mallicaot, Clint Carikker FFA: Ryan Surface

description: Identified by right facing lieback
location: First bolted line on the traverse just right of two trees

description: Tough overhanging no feet start to crimpy sustained sequences
Left of the two trees, starts on a bucket jug that leads to sustained excellent vertical climbing.
Dirty low but good clean 10a climbing on upper portion over green lichen to pocket finish
location: 3rd route on traverse, shares anchors with One Shot

description: Start on an obvious jug on the far right of the Osage Chiefs undercut. Head left under a hanging orange blocks using small small crimps and cool footwork. Stick a big move to the finishing jug on Osage Chiefs Center and top out.
location: The Osage Chiefs are located in a small undercut on the right side of the trail. Look for a grey shield of perfect rock leading to a ledge at around 8 or 10 feet. Orange rock underneath the shield yields a number of small crimp rails. These rails should generally be chalked up, making the area relatively easy to identify. OC right takes the rightmost obvious start.

description: The easiest line out of the cave. Start low and follow obvious chalked jugs to an exciting topout.
location: The Osage Chiefs are located in a small undercut on the right side of the trail. Look for a grey shield of perfect rock leading to a ledge at around 8 or 10 feet. Orange rock underneath the shield yields a number of small crimp rails. These rails should generally be chalked up, making the area relatively easy to identify. OC Left is the leftmost line.

description: Start as for Osage Chiefs Left on an obvious jug, instead heading right out the sick thin crimp rail, eventually making a big move to a flat, orange jug. Top out the shield as usual. Engaging movement makes up for a relative lack of height.
location: The Osage Chiefs are located in a small undercut on the right side of the trail. Look for a grey shield of perfect rock leading to a ledge at around 8 or 10 feet. Orange rock underneath the shield yields a number of small crimp rails. These rails should generally be chalked up, making the area relatively easy to identify. OC Left is the leftmost line.
Right exit of the cave.

description: Start on the left side of the undercut on a left angling flake(Arborist Left), heading straight up though amazing slopey grips and eventually grabbing the obvious hueco above the undercut. An exceptionally powerful problem with some really poor holds.
location: Located on the left side of an undercut left of a section of mossy slab. Look for the obvious hueco in the slab above the undercut. Starts on the left angling rail and heads straight up.

description: Follow a left angling slopey rail to a big sidepull jug and top out the easy slab. Quite a good lowball problem.
location: Located on the left side of an undercut left of a section of mossy slab. Look for the obvious hueco in the slab above the undercut. Starts on the left angling rail and follows the feature to its end.

description: Starts in an obvious left-facing chalked flake. Follow a proud line of perfect incut crimps to a huge jump move to the jug pocket. Probably possible to top out but this one is generally done as a drop off.
location: Walking down toward the west end look for a perfect white and gray face with some obvious chalked crimps- three small holds and a juggy starting flake. The start flake is easily identified as the largest hold on the problem and has a small triangular protrusion. The climb is maybe 30 feet right of 1976.
protection: The landing kind of drops away on this one. Bring pads and a spotter or two.

first_ascent: Kevin jarvis, Carl Carter, Zach Wilhoit
description: Just right of Thistle, work up blank slab face towards curved cut in roof. Muscle over roof to the chains.
Float up the low-angle face on comfy crimps and awesome ledges, finishing below the roof.
location: Right of Moon Compass

route_name: Thats not how you eat a banana
first_ascent: Kevin jarvis, Carl Carter, Zach Wilhoit
description: Just left of tree, stretchy first move to easier climbing to chains.
location: left of big tree

description: Fun low crux with several solutions leads to easier terrain working towards an attention-getting finish to the lip.
location: Just left of 1976, and 20ish feet right of Thistle Do.

first_ascent: Carl Carter, Kevin jarvis, Zach Wilhoit
location: Right side of big tree.

description: A plethora of jugs, edges, and pockets leads to a thin 2-move crux. Bash enormous jugs to the anchors.
Start on the rising, under-cling rail. A handful of strenuous moves to the second bolt comprise the crux.
location: Travelling west, this is the first bolted line past the Zig-Zag area.
protection: 5 bolts, lower off anchor, stickclip recommended.

description: A V6 boulder problem leads to nice ledgey steep terrain, pull through the boulder problem and climb at mid 5.11
Climb neat jugs and ledges to a break in the rock. A hard, fngery move gets you through the blank section. Top out on the dirty ledge to clip the anchors.
location: At the far West (clibmer's left) end; just right of Forgot My Crashpad.

description: Far left route. Blunted arete with 3 bolts up to anchors on a ledge (anchor carabiners hanging over lip on slings).
location: Far left route (as of 03/2017), just left of Ibexercise.

description: A powerful V4 boulder problem leads to a pair of pockets on the face. Super ultra thin and sloping crimps take you to a rad, incut pocket and a big dyno to the anchor. This route cuts off before the choss band above it, which would likely decrease the quality of the route. It is possible the extension may be bolted in the future. The grade is a guess, it could be a bit easier or way harder. ¬†The route has not been sent, please do not climb on it for the time being.
location: Continuing past Moon Compass and the other shorties, walk past the green arete and a tall undercut. The left side of the undercut has a big jug. Start here, heading slightly right then straight up.

description: Starting off a rockstack, head up on a couple of jugs and then left on pockets to a huge move. Could be 5.11, could be a bit harder. If you're feeling really saucy, a direct start would certainly up the difficulty.
location: Continuing past Moon Compass, this is the 1-bolt route just before the gorgeous green arete. I haven't been back to try it since it was bolted, so please don't climb on it just yet.

description: Climbs above spray paint name sake. Well featured face follows bolts right of the roof. Make a big move just above the roof up to nice rail. A small hand traverse and crimps lead to chains.
location: Left of North of North 40
The first bolt is just above the middle of the entrance to the cave

description: Start on sharp holds and power through a short series of fun sustained moves. The difficulty eases up only slightly after you pass the steep face and near the anchors.
location: On the right side of the alcove.
protection: Stickclip, 6 bolts, steel lower off anchors

description: Fun ar√™te with a good rest below an exciting over vertical crux finish to the anchors.
location: On the southeast corner of the Fortress.

description: Climbs a seam to face above. Brutal small holds.
location: Just to the right of Inertia

description: Climb the vertical face above the large flake.  Pretty good rock.
location: This is the second route from the left on the Long Dog Wall, starting at the massive flake leaning against the rock.

description: Bolted line through roof right of bushy crack. Somewhat contrived at crux.
location: Left most of a series of routes to the right of a bushy crack

description: This is the left-most bolted line on Long Dog Wall. Starts off a flake left of the ramp.  Stay left to avoid harder climbing.
location: Just to the (climbers) right of a brushy slab gully leading to the home above.

description: Sweet line up center scoop on wall.  Crux fourth bolt may seem a bit high and can benefit from a pre-hung draw.
location: 2nd to the right form bushy crack

description: Climb the face to the left of the cave, heading a little right near the top of the cave to the anchors.  Mostly decent rock.
location: This is the farthest route right in the Long Dog area.  It starts immediately to the left of the large cave and hugs the cave most of the way up.

description: One-move-wonder to great climbing above. This would be 3 stars if not for the start.
location: right most on the central long dog wall

description: Starts on deep left angling flake to a series of fun moves on jugs. Exciting photogenic finish on the ¬ìtongue¬î feature.
location: Above the large boulder.

description: Slightly harder start to Native Tongue.
location: Just right of Native Tongue. Shares start with Nevermore

description: Steeper alternate start to Rockabilly on the left.
Shares start with EAB then angles sharp right under a small roof. Getting passed the small roof section is the short exciting crux of this great route.
location: Same start as Edgar Allen Bro. Just right of the big boulder.

description: One of the more sustained routes at the Fortress. For full value, start low inside cave on a huge jug flake.
location: Goes through center of the alcove on the left side of the Fortress
protection: Stickclip, 6 bolts, steel lower off anchors

description: This route climbs up broken ledges with awesome solid conglomerate rock.
location: SW corner of Goose Island, gray open dihedral

first_ascent: Dakota Walz, Jeremy Collins, and Blake Bennett
description: Start right of the little cave on a spine feature. Climb the spine to a ledge and climb straight up the technical face and through a large smooth shoot feature.
location: North side of Goose Island, starts right of little cave.

description: Righteous climbing up an ar√™te with a no hands rest before the first crux. Pull sequential moves high up at the second crux to reach the anchor.
location: North side of Goose Island, farthest route to the left.

first_ascent: Jer Collins, Zion Collins, Bryan Schillig, Billy Claycomb
description: Start at the SW corner of Goose Island. Traverse out left to a single bolt belay, then angle up the face and top out.

One of the two ¬ìmust do¬î traverses over the water. Climb sustained 5.8 starting on the south side. Work your way over the water to a crux at the overhang just before reaching the shore again. The overhang is about 5.9 if you go high or 5.10 if you climb low at the water.
White ar√™te on the southwest corner of Goose Island
protection: Bolts, shares lower offs with Climbing for Two

first_ascent: Jer Collins, Dakota Walz, and Billy Claycomb
description: Short route with soft rock on an ar√™te.
location: East face of Goose Island.

protection: Small rack of cams, shares lower offs with Firestar

first_ascent: Jeremy Collins, Dakota Walz, Blake Bennett
description: Start near the water on a small boulder. When flooded start as of Snake & Eggs and traverse in. Climb the beautiful far right ar√™te nearly right over the water.
location: North side of Goose Island, farthest to the right near the water.

description: Climb up above the left side of the little cave, into a technical vertical face and straight up to the anchors.
location: This line goes straight up the center of the North side wall. Starts left of the little cave

description: Right of the cave. There is a particular clip that must be approached with caution above the midway ledge.
location: Right of the cave

description: Campus start from a jug pocket, and work your way through the bulge on good holds. Two mantels and the beautiful arete finish make it worth your while.
location: Farthest left route on the wall.

description: Left of Wayne Burnside, climb to roof and make a couple powerful overhung moves to surmount the tiered roof, cruise to top
location: Route starts just left of the "Wayne Burnside" spray painted on the wall and is directly under the right side of the big roof.

description: Easy climbing left of the cave leads to a standing rest. Bust a bouldery move and hang on until the chains.
location: The first route on the left side of the cave,

description: North 40-esque 10a
location: Left of cave

description: Stick clip, then execute a strange technical sequence on sugary rock to jugs and a second bolt. A powerful jug-to-jug deadpoint gains the third bolt and a good rest. Execute a V4 boulder problem or dyno through, and mantle over a ledge into a no-hands rest. Solve two more short problems separated by a ledge. Were this route not interrupted by two no-hands rests, it would be 4 stars and one of the best routes in the state.
location: Between Chief Monegaw (roof route without the chain) and resistance (leftmost route with ar√™te finish).

description: Start at the base of the zig zagging flake. A few big moves gets you to the massive roof. Pull over the roof with a few powerful moves. Mantle up the tiered ledges for a thin finish.
location: Left of Planet Sound

description: ledge sit start to sharp crimps.
location: Refer to map.

description: This boulder may not look like much, but it a great boulder. Awesome hard sloper topout and will make you press your stomach as hard as you can into the rock.
location: After you have reached the Headache boulder keep on the trail until it comes to a giant bend. This is where Back Band is located.
protection: Pads and keep an eye out as always for bikers.

description: For historical completeness, this was the first route done without bolts or top rope on the overhang. It goes directly through the stacked blocks in the center of the overhang. The crux is being able to stand on the blocks then moving up to the left side of the small cave above. A knee bar in the cave gives a great rest before the final moves. On the topo it is between routes 5 and 6. ¬† I understand this route has now been bolted so I changed it to a sport route ¬†(I haven't personally been back to see). ¬† ¬†When I soloed it, there were no bolts anywhere on cliff drive. ¬† Times have changed as has the slickness of the rock I hear.
protection: You may be able to get gear behind the blocks but I didn't.

description: Found to the left of Strong Man. Starts on jugs, traverses left and top out. Nice jugs but is a challenge.

A large boulder that locals use to jump into the water, towards the right hand side of the boulder facing the water there is an amazing over hanging edge. Start low near the water and climb your way up under the ledge and navigate over the lip (v1-v2). From here it is a very easy (v-easy) climb up the remaining of the problem.
location: Start at the Wildcat glades conservation area and head towards the shoal creek access. From here head towards the over pass, you cannot miss the boulder from there.
protection: Spotter so you don't fall in the water, and 1-3 crash pads.

description: Sit start low and pull a few crimps to the ‚Äúslam dunk‚Äù then top out.
location: If you turn left at the softball area and go a few hundred feet there is a detached boulder with a pretty large hole in it. problem starts on the side facing down the hill.

description: Sit start in small cave, work out on rail to big slopers finish with a mantle
location: To come

description: Mid way up the route there is an interesting under-cling match to navigate against the face to the top out.
location: Across the river from mothers nature crack, follow the path that lies perpendicular to the small bridge near the pavilion.

description: I am relatively new to climbing so this is my first time doing this- this is an easy ascent, with two ledges. the rock is sharp, not really worth climbing unless you want a warm up or are teaching new climbers.
location: follow the bluff trail, after crossing by Mother Natures crack, there will be an outcropping to the left as the trail goes slightly to the right, this is your spot.
protection: this is a top rope only climb, there are multiple trees for anchors, bring an ample amount of webbing, rope protection is highly recommended.

description: Found to the left of the overhang. Boulder looks like an upsidedown plate and the problem is in between 2 boulders. SDS-top out.
Starts at the outside of the overhang to the right of Fumunda. Starts on jugs and traverses right as far as you want.
Found to the right of the cave. SDS on the flat rock found in the overhang towards the back. Traverse out of the overhang and climb the cliff about 10 ft up.
location: Right side of the largest overhanging cave.

description: Meanders a little.  Sustained climbing through roof midway up, then up and left to share anchors with the Bolt Route.  Big moves.
location: Just right of the Bolt Route.
Just above Chomping the Bit
protection: Bring four quickdraws. Anchors of chomping the bit serve as fixed draw.

description: Easier face climbing takes you up to the sequential and interesting crux section.  The anchors are under the large roof.
location: This is the first route right of Chomping the Bit and starts left of the leaning tree.

description: Climb the short 5.7 crack 10 feet to the ledge. Follow the 5.6 dihedral all the way until the crack ends. Don't climb on the dangerous loose choss to the right of the dihedral. Fun route, just a little dirty.
location: Obvious crack right of the overhang.
protection: Mostly nuts and some hexes or cams. Nothing bigger than 4". No anchors.

description: Fun overhanging face climb with a very high first bolt.  It's easy to the bolt, though.  After clipping the third draw, begin heading up and right to turn the roof for the finish.  The clipping holds can be muddy if it has been raining recently.  If not, they are typically covered in a slick film of dirt.
location: This is the climb near the middle of the wall that has the highest bolt.  It angles right and turns the roof to the anchors.
protection: 4 bolts, 1 permadraw, clip anchors. Anchors tend to have stuck gates from runoff.

location: This is the leftmost bolted line under the Overhang.  It ends only partway up the wall.

description: Easier face climbing leads to small crimp undercling to pull the roof.  Then angle up and left to the anchors on easier holds.
location: The farthest route right on the wall.
protection: 4 fixed draws and a 2 bolt anchor with fixed biners for lowering.

description: Climb the first 3 bolts of Bovine Direct, the farthest route right on the Overhang.  Then continue up and left past another bolt.  Either clip the last bolt on Sea of Cheez and continue to its anchors or head back right to the anchors on Bovine Direct.
protection: 2 draws, 2-3 fixed draws (variations), 2 bolt anchor with fixed biners.

location: This is the 3rd bolt line from the left, just right of Malaria.
protection: 3 bolts, 1 permadraw, 2 bolt anchor with fixed biners. Some may find it helpful to extend the permadraw, eliminating a strenuous clip.

description: Pull the hanging start, work up to a defined razor crimp crux

Bouldery start that leads to crazy melting limestone and a few Tuffas, slightly contrived because of the proximity to "Bannister Federal", stay to the left of the bolt line. Some call it the Oliana of Kansas City.
Tough hanging start with a fingerlock to crimps. After the jug rail midway try not to stray to the left onto "John Brown".
Tough start leads to several right facing sidepulls/pinches mid route.
Start on low jug and two big pump moves to the top. Top isn't shown.
location: Near the biggest cave, which is on the right side of the trail. Once in front of the biggest cave walk across the wooden bridge to the right and you'll see it.

description: This is a super reachy route a few decent holds, but mainly crimps.
location: Cave hallow in warrensburg MO. First Parking lot on the right. Follow the paved trail to the end and find the main bouldering area. It will be on the left hand side of the area. Look for te big head made into the stone and the name Munson and you should be right by the start. It starts there and ends up at the head with giant lips on too of the boulders
protection: Bring a couple crash pads with you when you go.

description: look at photo
protection: pads because it is a high topout

description: Start on the lowest two finger pockets
location: main climbing area at end of trail

description: Fun sit start to a nice ledge. Work through holds with good feet. The Crux is working up the feet to make a reachy move off the side pull. Top out to the right. Might need cleaning at the top, but worth the effort.
location: Just to the right of "Pockets".
protection: Just a pad. Two and a spotter is nice.

description: start on left rail and work way across then up.
location: Near the biggest cave, which is on the right side of the trail. Once in front of the biggest cave walk across the wooden bridge to the right and you'll see it.
protection: the fall is a little bad. Need spotters so you don't roll down hill.

description: Start tucked under the roof on a shoulder press with good feet. Traverse left and then up through the overhanging dihedral to the sloper. Crux is the move to the lip. Fun, easy top out. Best problem at the hollow.
location: On the right side, at the mouth of the main hollow.

description: sit start on right facing crimp rail under the lip work up the arete trending left for top out.
location: tall arete' right of turtle head.

description: To the right of turn of the screw. squat start on bad crimps...move out left to shelf, work your way up the slopey topout.

location: 20ft left of the Detonate Flake. Start right beneath  the pocket/slit.

description: SDS on shelf to right, work your way left to pinch and crimps. Follow slopey rails to topout. Reach for the softball!
Starts on the pinch under the roof, work your way out right using the arete, cave crimps, etc.
Left of softball. SDS, work your way up the bulge or head and topout.
Same sit start as Softball. Work right on slopers to lip. Top out right of the tree.

location: Far right end of the wall just left of that flake.

description: Start standing four feet left of Hawt Pockets. Go up and a little left to that thin pocket then continue up and right. Top out using tree to the left or down climb once you reach the top.
location: Four feet left of Hawt Pockets

description: Sit start on the two pockets 3 feet off the ground. Go straight up.

Desiccation is the face climb just right of the dihedral. Left wall is considered off. Don't plan to fall off this problem, its a bit high. Presently dirty finger/hand cracks lead to a side pull to the top. Your already pretty high by the time you get up there so top out.
location: First climb right of the dihedral.

description: Layback the flake until you come to the block with a hole you can sling go left and up to the tree. Rock seems solid but decide that for yourself.
protection: Gear to 3", sling, risk assessment as this is a new climb, helmet.

description: To the right of Grounds Off, Lance. Stand start on sidepull jug. Work your way up to swiss cheese holds up in the roof. Hold the swing and topout on this heady classic!
To the right of Mind Games!!! Found on obvious overhanging bulge. Start low and work through slopey rails, crimps and a high foot for the topout
Start on chalked shelf and trend right onto positive edges and jugs of left side of roof. Top out.
location: Left side of "Big Toe" roof.

description: Left of Jabba the Hut. Starts on tooth, climb in roof and work your way out to good holds. Topout to left. Classic.

Walk to the right of Bliss Jump. Starts on shelf on the roof, work your way on shelf to slopers and top out. The tree makes for a good spot. **There is another jump start in between the two climbs as well as a hard dyno project.
To the left of Turn of the Screw. Stand start on crimps. Move into pockets, lunge for gaston, go to jug and top out left. v8/9 AKA The Beast

To the right of Perfect Spotter. Huge arete. Start on the left side and work your way through slopey crimps to the jug horn on the arete. After that is some heady but easy arete climbing. *** You can also climb the face to the left of the arete for a "Wild Ride". Pretty heady & good!!

To the right of Muggy Situation. Start up under roof on tooth. Work your way on the roof through crimps and finger jams in crack. Leap for jug, hold the scary swing as you are already 10ft off the ground! Move to obvious slopers, arete and nipple at top. You got balls.....we will see.
Start on a jug under the large roof.  Follow the sloping shelves slightly right out to the lip and top out
location: The large rounded roof in the middle of the Mind Games area

description: Same start as Turn of the Screw instead work left into pockets once in the roof and topout of My Mistress / Grounds Off, Lance.
To the right of Flying Dude Man. Starts up in the roof on an undercling, make a big move out to jug and work your way right to topout.
Start on Swinging Machete & end to the right of Flying Man Dude. The stand start v6, starts on Dry Dreams & ends out right of Flying....
Start on obvious holds and work up in the roof on pockets, top out on slopers. For the v4 grade, stay right of the crack.
location: Right of Jabba the Hut when facing the cliff.
protection: Its been done without pads but 2 is nice.

description: Starts on obvious jugs in roof, right of Flying Man Dude. Same start as "Grounds Off, Lance". Undercling to a jug and work left once at the lip. after traversing left topout on the far arete.
To the right of Jabba. Stand start and work your way left on arete. Get to slopers and follow the water drainage up.
Right of Chicken Sandwich. Start on jug, work up and left to slopers, fire to crimp, topout. Sweet climb!
On the same overhanging bulge as Trees Off, Dan but starts and stays on the right side of the tree. Start low and work up overhang. Cool pinch and crimps lead to a slopey topout
To the right of Walking on Thin Ice. Starts on a hold on the lip of the roof. jump and work your way on slopers straight up. There is a climb going left from the start hold as well.
Starts under the roof and works the right arete to the face, hold the compression moves and topout on slopers

The white arete/face directly right of Muggy Situation. Start under roof on holds, work out to shelf, to several moves on slopey crimps to the horn and crimps for topout. Scary beginning moves. The fall from the crux (crimps) is a flat landing.
SDS on shelf below Turtle Head...work your way to pinch, pocket and out to shelf. Go straight up and top out on the turtle head...
same start as turtle head. After the move to the lip traverse right across the seam into woodland prostitute(V5).
location: on the turtle head face

description: Start far left on good jug and trend right on arete and underclings to top out on highest point of boulder.
location: just 20~ yds SE downhill from Turtlehead boulder

description: Super fun, powerful climbing on ergonomic pockets with many options for beta.
location: On the far left side of the cave, look for an obvious chalked and ticked undercling jug. Look for a flake and a line of pockets out the cave. There is a left exit for the problem but the straight up variation seems more popular. If you can't find the start, work your way back from a chalked sculpted pocket with an obvious thumb catch. There exists a low start that is said to go at the same grade.

description: Climb the manmade ledge system at the far right end of the crag, two gullies right of the Book.  At the top, a trail leads all the way to the left end of teh crag.  Be careful.
Climb the broken finger crack in the dihedral.
location: This is the dihedral at the right end of the area.
protection: TR recommended, but I suppose it could be led on gear.  Use trees at the top for anchors.  See Walk Up in the Book area for top access info.

description: Start with a high hand match on the ledge a few feet below the first bolt. Stay on or slightly right of the bolt line before the big ledge. Avoid using the crack to the left of the route. The fifth bolt is a glue-in just above the big ledge and is optional. Be careful when clipping the anchors as a fall could land on the big ledge.
location: Just right of the big crack.
Left of the dirty corner. Start on the big flake

description: Fun moderate climb. Bouldery start with some more difficult moves 10 feet from the top.
location: Just left of The Big Crack
protection: There are four bolts. With two permadraws as anchors

description: Climb the left facing flake, left of the dihedral crack.  Join the dihedral near the top.
location: On the right end of the crag, just left of the dihedral.
protection: TR.  Anchor on trees above, reached by hiking over from the top of the right end of the crag.  See the Book area.

description: Start at a broken ledge and work straight up a few crimps and solid jugs to a sweet mega jug at the 3rd bolt. Move through cool side-pulls, under clings, and more jugs to the anchors.
location: Right of El Sasa Beach and left of Campbell

description: Either stick clip or scramble up the small ledge to reach for the first bolt. Then move left and up with the flake for two more. After clipping the third bolt traverse through a short crux right and up to the anchors.
Climb the twin crack system.  Fun.
location: At the left end of the area, this is the double crack system.
protection: TR recommended, but it could be led.  Use trees at the top for anchors.  See Walk Up in the Book area for top access info.

description: Easy climbing to a ledge and high first bolt leads to sequential moves and technical climbing up a slightly overhanging face.
location: Between The Blimp and Fun Wall
Starts just left of "The Book" dihedral / crack.

description: Start on top of the detached flake on the bottom for a 5.6 climb or start left of the flake for a more difficult slick, dusty climb. Climbing over the detached flake could result in a bad fall onto the flake.
location: Look for the detached flake just around the corner right of the book.

description: Climb only the right hand wall of the book.  Sounds contrived but is actually a good route considering how few routes are available in the area.
protection: Good gear is available in the crack at the back of the roof.  Actually a hex drops perfectly in a slot there.

description: Blimp is the arete right of The Book. The start of this route is kind of a pain with slippery foot holds and some loose rock. Don't blow it clipping the second bolt. If you do fall while clipping the second bolt it could very well be a ground fall and a twisted ankle due to the not-so-flat-landing, plan accordingly. The second half of the route is still challenging but offers some more solid rock and foot placements with some interesting moves and some exciting exposure.
protection: The route has four bolts plus a two bolt anchor. If you're worried about falling at the second bolt  then bring a stick clip or crash pad.

description: Interesting leftward linkup going past two or three bolts of Fun Wall, through a big flake, connecting a single bolt to Under Fire's anchors and onward over run-out chose to The Blimp's anchors.
location: Gradual leftward traverse across Funny Wall area

description: A long, obvious endurance line out the cave. A couple of hard moves lead to a core-intensive rest and another hard sequence on a big undercling and crimp rail. Top out via V2-ish climbing. An epic journey of a boulder problem, certain to cater to route climbers. To my understanding, V7 is the grade the FA proposed. 5.12b or 5.12c seem just as appropriate
location: At the back of the cave, toward the left side, look for a well-chalked tufa/udder-like hold with an obvious undercling on the back. Make a hard move to a deep pocket, then follow the chalked line out to a large, heavily chalked jug ledge, and continue along a crimp rail, out to an obvious flake. Follow the natural weakness out the prow on the cave. The original line, Triple D's, cuts left at some point and is the less popular option. Due to the horizontal-ness of the roof and the relative popularity of the line, all the holds should be chalked up and easy to find. If you have trouble finding it, start by looking for the chalked pockets of Pistol Grip Pump, look right to find the crimp rail, and follow it back to the start holds.

description: This is the polished left-facing dihedral crack.

You'll never believe it, but this is another long endurance line in the cave. Shares the same start as Triple/Natural D's, Training Wheels, and Finders & Repeaters, then branches right and takes on the right side of the central prow. This is the longest and most enduro line that starts on the common start. Excellent rock quality and movement, various rests, and the sky is the limit on how creative you can get with your beta.
location: At the back of the cave, toward the left side, look for a well-chalked tufa/udder-like hold with an obvious undercling on the back. Make a hard move to a deep pocket, then follow the chalked line out to a large, heavily chalked jug ledge, angle right from here into a long rail that leads to the right side of the big prow. Work your way out the last section of the roof, and ride the right side of the prow to the relatively easy, and usually dry top out.

description: Start in the hueco on the left wall of the cave,¬†pull your feet on, then bump out to the lip. 1st crux is moving from this position into a spot where you can continue up and right along the rim. Same top-out as ‚ÄúAtaraxia‚Äù.
location: Two hand start in hueco on the caves left wall.

description: Climb the east-facing section of the rock that makes up the initial set of jumps. Crux is the last two moves.
location: If you went down the stairs and swam straight down and then turned left after the little cave you'd be at the face.

description: Good foot work to move you out in order to walk your hands up the rail is the only trick!
location: Lowest ribbon of rock is not on route (still mostly covered in dirt). Start in a compression with the right hand on the base of the right facing rail - left hand on the only optional hold feet left and deep to the rail. Feet out right on middle ribbon of rock (see pic). Move out to the rail, then climb up, pulling the lip for a top!

description: Climb the perfect hand crack placing gear when necessary
location: Refer to page 109 in the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Follow the overhung corner and pull the moves through the face
location: Refer to page 42 of the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Follow the diagonal crack. Pulling the roof is the crux
location: Refer to page 42 of the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Another great sustained splitter crack
location: Refer to page 42 in the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Great sustained splitter crack
location: Refer to page 42 of the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Great sustained splitter crack
location: Refer to page 42 of the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Friendly crack
location: Refer to page 42 of the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Traverse the rightward leaning crack to finish on Rock Candy. Build and anchor on Rock Candy.
location: Refer to page 109 in the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Climb the perfect hand crack placing gear when necessary. Build and anchor at the top.
location: Refer to page 109 in the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Climb the big crack formed between the huge stone slab and the massive boulder. Follow the crack up underneath the roof, and exit to the right.
location: Refer to page 108 in the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Sit start, and climb the rightmost ramp of the cave. No defining crux. Broken into 3 main portions: bumping to a crimp so you can drop your body down, climbing your hands up the sloppy ramp toward the finish, and keeping your feet on the wall to before pulling the lip. Fun movement with fun holds the whole way.
location: Sit start in the rightmost portion of the cave. Both hands in the big dish formation, right heel can be up, on the lip, left toe on a ledge under the overhang (pic uploaded that shoes start position). Drop into the edge, bump hand out to a crispy edge gouged out of the rich, and begin the traverse. The top two ribbons of rock are on, but not the lowest ribbon which is mainly in the dirt. Pull the lip for the finish when you reach the right facing rail (same finish site as ‚ÄúSlippery When Wet‚Äù)

description: Pretty well-sustained on slopers. Choreographing the correct hand/heel¬†placement may take a few attempts, but it‚Äôs a fairly straightforward climb up to the final holds.

Crux: the last few moves - finding how to move over into the drainage section to pull the lip. Movement is great - forcing good utilization of heals and toes. Holds can be dirty and hard to see, so brush and mark to optimize the send.
location: Start in a huge undercling (just down and right from a right-facing rail toward the right end of the cave). Use lower foot block and rail to move onto the lip of the cave. Work left to the center (drainage area) of the cave and pull the lip.
Currently the left most route at The Landing

description: Coming soon, please be patient
location: Close to the big oak tree

description: Starting moves are difficult, then easier climbing to middle of climb were the two small Crux sections are . Finishing going right to anchors. ¬†Good hands most of the climb.
location: Starts on the outside left of the Dark Hollow wall.

description: Belay from first tier, route is furthest right on South facing wall. ¬†1st bolt is eight ft from the ground. Climb past easy ledge to the main wall. ¬†The Crux is at the top of the climb.
