location: Right side of Dark Hollow wall. 15 ft left of Ichabod
Ichabod is the slab climb located on the right outside edge of the Dark Hollow wall alcove.

description: Belay from top tier with belayer bolt. Climb past ledge with roots, to first bolt. Longer draw will reduce rope drag on first bolt. Crux is in the middle of the climb going over the bulge. Fairly easy route staying left of the bolt line all the way to the anchors.
location: Left route on West facing wall. 8 ft left of Asylum.

description: Left side of the Wave Wall is the easy down climb and an easy boulder problem for those looking to scuff up those new shoes!
location: Left side of the main Wave Wall overhang. Just to the left of the down climb tree you will find easy holds to stand on and manage your way up a slab.

description: This is the standing start option for one of the center roof lines. Reach high and grab a good left hand and reach far right to get a lower right hand. Use a high right foot, at the lip of the roof to then bump your right hand up to a high right hold. After reaching the top of the slab, avoid the dirt walk around by traversing left on good feet to reach the down climb tree slab.
location: Center of the Wave Wall roof

On the left side of the Wave Roof, just right of the big tree, start from a sit start, under the roof, and reach out to holds along the lip. Finish at ¬†the top of the slab and down climb by moving left to easier down climbing near the tree.

description: Start with hands on the lip of the roof and use a right heel hook to gain higher hands. Transition from right heel to right toe smear to bump your right hand to high hold. Difficulty is now over. Stand up and finish the short slab and traverse left to the tree slab down climb.
location: Center of the Wave Wall roof

description: Beautiful red/orange rock just right of the dihedral. Lots of fun, plenty of holds. ¬†Try to stay balanced at the anchors. ¬†Belay from top tier, with bolt for belayer or next to wall with another bolt for belayer. 1st bolt is ten foot up from ledge.
location: Left route on South facing wall. 8 ft left of Blitzkrieg

description: Belay from second tier or next to Wall. ¬†1st bolt is on the main wall 10ft up from the ledge. ¬†A little more shelf climbing than the typical Robinson pocket climbing makes it fun and interesting. The Crux is in the middle. Then easier climbing to the anchors.
location: Middle route on South facing wall. 8 ft left of Kamakazi.

description: Belay from top tier, with belayer protection bolt. Climb past ledge to get to left part of roof. Crux is the first few moves through the left side of the roof. Stretch for the nice shelves to get past the bulge. ¬†Small hands at top but still good holds and a god send left hand 2 finger pocket if you find it. ¬†Really fun route.
location: Right route on West facing wall.

description: Coming soon, please be patient
The title refers to Robinson Crusoe's companion, Friday. The route goes up the arete and, at times, seems somewhat squeezed between Crusoe and Mrs. Robinson.
location: Between Robinson Crusoe and Mrs. Robinson
6 feet right of C is For Crumpecker.

description: This route is named after an early pioneer in social distancing. His story was published 300 years ago! ¬†The route starts on the left side of an arete. Mrs Robinson is around the corner on the right. ¬†As usual, the hardest part is near the bottom
location: Just 15 feet around the arete from Mrs Robinson you run into Robinson Crusoe

description: This route maintains a safe social distance from Mrs. Robinson on the left and Crumpecker on the right. Climb straight up to the massive orange hooks. The hardest moves occur in two places - near the start and later in the steep area above the first ledge.
The route is quite varied and sustained. The crux is getting to the second bolt. There is a long horizontal ledge, about 20 feet up.
location: It is right by the big White Oak tree on the John Prine wall. The big white oak tree has numerous scars from all the rocks that have recently bounced off it on their way to the river.

description: This route begins in a right facing dihedral and a high first clip. With the movie in mind, you just may feel like shouting "ELAINE!" when you reach the clip-in anchors.
Need a bail bond or some used auto parts? See Mr. C in nearby Tiff, Missouri! ¬†Otherwise, try this route. It starts by the beautiful left leaning crack that ends much too soon....

location: Route is found in the center of the City Limit Wall and starts below a small roof.
Center of the City Limit Wall, find the slightly overhanging start that follows the bolt line over a small roof and converts to a steep slab with minimal holds.

description: On the far left hand side of the City Limit Wall, start below the C-shaped, shallow dihedral, then follow it up to a small roof to find the crux. Once you have clipped the rap anchors, you have passed the hard part so enjoy the view of the river and remember to thank your belayer.
location: Far south end of the bluff line, on the left side of the City Limit Wall. Route is left of the large scoop in the wall.

description: Crux is just a few moves in then easier climbing to top it out.
location: Start just 5 feet left of the arete. See photos for specifics!

description: The line gets increasingly more difficult the higher you climb. Jugs take you past the big flakes at the bottom and the first 4 bolts. Then the face turns a bit more vertical and balance is more important. holds decrease in size and the small pockets become important. It was a bit muddy during my last climb which made the climb feel harder like a 5.9 or so. (Still a new climb as of Jan 2020) The crux moves are just below the anchors. The last clip is fairly close to rap anchors so you are well protected for the move. The climb would be rated a bit harder if it was extended another 10 or 15 ft towards the upper lip.
location: Right of Tomahawk
protection: 7 draws to the hooks at the top.

description: A good route with good movement. There is a short reachy crux section about halfway up just before you pull over a small lip to the "Thank God no hands rest ledge". First bolt is pretty high so if you're not solid in the grade bring a stick clip. Good exposure and a great view at the top.
location: About 20' left of Show Boat "Horseshoe 8" on legacy wall start is on a small mini arete.
protection: 18 draws as the chains don't have hooks yet. Bring a helmet there's still some cleaning needed.

location: This is the first route on the Legacy Wall when approached from the stairs. Start on the Party Boat crack to reach the first belay anchors, 50 ft up. Then climb another 50 ft to the second set of rap anchors. Consider rope length and rap position when coming down. Rapping off the top anchors straight down puts you coming down from above Show Boat crack.

description: Head up left side of large stack of boulders to reach first anchor. Reach high to gain second anchor for the top of the rock stack. Small lower roof is below steep slab. Hueco holes start below the upper roof and angling crack, then continue in a sequential fashion, leading into the crux. Traverse a couple steps left to utilize the upper arete. Balance is key. Keep from becoming pumped by resting when possible. Quite a fun line!
location: Route is a line of bolts that continue straight up from the top of the large stack of boulders. Stick clip could be handy for clipping past the lower small roof. Guess it depends on your person ethics.
protection: Quickdraws, some perma-draws provided through upper crux

route_name: Magic Carpet Ride aka One for Bill
location: Right side of the Cryptic Wall.
Look for the obvious red section of rock and follow the bolt line that is on the right side, near the lighter white rock. 2 O'Clock Shadow starts just left in a dihedral.
protection: 14 Bolts plus Top and Mid-route Rap Anchors

location: 10 ft. right of Sawasdee
protection: 14 bolts and hooks at the anchors

description: Starts just left of the first bolt climb 5.9 for the first four bolts then the business starts. Then 10 ft 5.10a to a good no hands rest to clip from. This is where the first Crux starts. Use a rail out left to get a high reach for a jug and then come back right to a good two hand pocket to clip from. Things let up after the next bolt until you reach the cave and get another great rest. (You could sit up there all day if so inclined.) Once you've rested enough start the second crux
location: At the vine wall locate the obvious roof/cave feature about 75' up above the large scooped it section of the wall with a tree stump in the bottom middle of the feature. The start is almost directly below the right of the roof

description: Bluff Banter moves a bit back and forth, from side to side, as the line works a path to the anchors below a large cedar tree. The climb starts easy and turns a bit more technical with the more vertical face above. Feel free to stay just right of the bolts or left for a different crux feel 3/4 of the way up the line. Climb past the last bolt for an easier, juggy finish. Rap chains provide an easy rappel.
protection: Quick Draws and anchor cleaning protection

description: Flat gray slab to a bulge. Hanging slab to the flower petals on the overhanging orchid.
A nice challenge for 11 climbers. Tends to stay wet for a while after a rain.
location: Around the corner about 100 ft past Acres Of 9.
Walk south past Bee Hive when approaching from the stairs. You can find this line on the right hand side of the Cryptic Wall following up an obvious, left-facing, dihedral corner.

description: Climb to the left of the bolts on small positive holds and enjoy the crux near the finish.
location: Just a little past Magic Carpet Ride

description: This is going to be a really nice route once it cleans up. It needs some traffic. You have a fairly high first bolt but an easy stairway on the right to get up to it. ¬†After the 2nd bolt and then again at the top you need to pick left or right which will either make it easier or harder. Nice little hueco to stand in while you clip the anchors or clean. Make sure your belayer has a helmet.
location: 20 ft past Fragile Flake.

description: Some continued cleaning needed below the second or third bolt and just below the rap anchors, otherwise this line is quite fun. Pockets and exciting movement makes for another good line at Robinson!
location: Start just left of Party Boat, on the lower slab, then stay on the left edge of the steep section of rock.

description: This dihedral is the first pitch of a two pitch route. ¬†Easy 4th class climbing gets you up to the 1st bolt then jugs to the second. Now standing, in the base of the dihedral, easy 5th class (5.3 - 5.4) stemming gets you up to the two bolt anchor.
location: Two routes left of Party Boat, identity the dihedral and how the start is the same for two different lines. The dihedral is Show Boat and the arete line is called Contrived. Contrived has a separate set of rap anchors.

The first route to the right of "Vandal" on legacy wall. When you come to Legacy wall find the tall dihedral that is "Horseshoe 8". Left of it you'll find Vandal and Saturday detention. Vandal is the line that finishes to the left of the large cedar tree at the top of the bluff and Saturday Detention finishes on the right of the tree.
protection: 13 bolts mussy hooks at the chains

description: Start on the fun lower slab then head up and into the left facing dihedral crack. This section can get pumpy depending on if you like crack climbing. The right hand side pulls on the other side of the column are fantastic. You'll also encounter an undercling that's a lifesaver.¬† The crux is moving through the crack and back onto the face. Rap anchors allow for easy quick draw retrieval.
location: Right hand side the Legacy Wall, so the first line you come to when approaching, walking south from the steps. You will drop down along the trail, from the Cryptic Choss Wall, coming around the base of the Three Hour Tour ridge buttress. Party boat starts at the base of the slab.
protection: 6 quick draws plus anchors, and an "optional pink 0.5 tricam".

description: Description on its way soon
location: Left of Beer Ledge and Beer Ledge Boulders.

See the photos provided for orientation. This line heads up the right side of the steep, slightly overhanging, scooped face. The bolts are in the red stained rock, to the right of the lighter white portion of the overhang. The bolts continue up above the obvious furthest right small cave alcove.

description: Start on steep face below large pockets. Crux is above pocket, moving through a thin face sequence. Mid-route rap anchors are convenient to lower off after the crux or reduce rope drag if climbing as a two pitch climb to the second set of rap anchors above the next ledge.
location: Just left of Mr Turtle, look for the large pocket that sit just below a small roof bulge. Bolts follow a line up then angle slightly up left towards first ledge anchors.

description: Exit Stage Left is a steep slab line with a short section of creative side stepping to gain the upper section. Step up, smearing on the lower slab, then continue through a steeper section, moving left to exit the crux of the route. Continue up the rest of the steep slab to the top anchors.
location: Start just right of the large stack of boulders, located below the routes Tennessee Whisky and Beer Ledge. Step up, smearing on the lower slab that is roughly 30 feet left of Legacy Falls.

description: Description coming soon, some cleaning required.
location: 10ft Right of Norm's route

description: Left of the Party Boat crack, this line starts sharing holds with Show Boat then follows the slight arete straight up. Separate bolts protect this line. Separate rap anchors provided also. You can continue on the second pitch but I do not give it many stars until more cleaning has happened.
location: Left (south) of the Party Boat crack, this line starts sharing holds with Show Boat, then follow the slight arete straight up.
This tall face is to the face right of the Legacy Wall area. Roughly 15 meters south (left) of the Beer Ledge boulders.
protection: Quickdraws and a 60 meter rope to rap from the top anchors

description: Similar start to Tennessee Whisky, but head up and left from the first bolt, on the left side of the large stack of boulders. Crux is mid way up the route and greatly depends on if you are left or right of the bolt path. Finish on slightly easier climbing.
location: Start this line on the left side of the Beer Ledge stack of large boulders. Line follows a dark streak of rock, left of Tennessee Whisky.
Head 2/3 of the way down the Vineyard Wall area to find the obvious right facing dihedral and great belay staging patio area positioned below a cedar tree above.
protection: 9 bolts plus rap anchor cleaning gear

description: Use your stick clip since the start is tricky with limited feet. A series of good small ledges will take you to the 6th bolt, this is were the next crux is, after that ¬†nice holds to the anchors located under small cedar tree.
location: 10 ft left of Tomahawk
protection: 10 Quick draws with hooks at anchors.

location: Right of War Hammer on the Vineyard Wall Area.

description: First bolt is 15 ft off the ground, with easy climbing. ¬†The Crux is around the middle of the climb over the buldge. Then to easier climbing to the top. A couple Alpine draws will cut down on rope drag.
location: 12ft left of The Watch Tower. At the end of the Apache Wall.

description: Start with easy climbing to the first bolt. Stick clip recommended if not comfortable climbing 14 ft to first bolt.¬† Lots of good holds and stances to the top.

Start with a couple moderate moves through the 4th bolt. You'll end up going right for a while, then coming back left, then right again. ¬†Keep looking for the good holds, they may not always be straight up. Use a couple longer draws on bolts 5 and 6 to reduce rope drag through the ledge. ¬† Then a good section of rock to the crux between the last bolt and the anchors.
protection: 9 bolts and hooks at the anchors.

location: This line comes out of the obvious small cave opening, at the far north end of the bluff line. Climb starts as a sit start, just inside the cave opening, then the line moves out and left then straight up to the top, following a line of jugs.

description: Climb the front section of taller, clean rock and step off of the short backside of the Mini Spire.
location: Left side of The Den area, which is the furthest most north section of the Robinson Bluff exposure.
protection: Pad, Spotter, large pile of stuffed animals!

description: Lower crux leads to jugs for a finish top-out.
location: Start just left of Seam of Dreams, continuing straight up. Better to climb during drier season months. See photos

This line comes out of the obvious small cave opening, at the far north end of the bluff line. To get there, follow the Boulder Ridge Trail down from the campground. Small cave is on the north end of the Den area, where the ridge trail meets the base trail turn. Climb starts as a sit start, as far back in the cave as possible, moving towards the opening. Then the line moves out and straight up to the top, following a line of jugs.

description: Pocket jugs in the corner of The Den still needs some cleaning but has the potential for being another great warm-up.
location: Corner of The Den area, left of Juggernaut.

description: This sit start follows a sequence of pockets vertically along The Den's rounded arete. Sequence is important for following the easiest path to the top. If it feels harder, try to rework the handhold sequence. The holds get bigger the higher you climb. Jug finished allows you to stand on the top.
location: Take a trail to The Den Area and find the small cave opening. Roughly 12 feet left of the small cave, a rounded, pocket riddled arete can not be missed. Start sitting below, using small pockets and edges.

description: Easy climbing will take you through to the second bolt. ¬†Take advantage of a good, quick rest (if you desire) while you prepare to take on the crux through bolts three and four. ¬†Underclings exist for clipping both. ¬† Get through some technical climbing through the crux to find another good undercling rest on bolt four. ¬†Shake out and continue onto much easier terrain to the anchor.
Stem up the dihedral to the chains. Another nice short warm up route.
Easy climb with one balance move when you're clipping. ¬†A couple great rests as you go and a nice stance for clipping/cleaning the anchors.
Nice technical arete climbing gets you up to a ledge, then a bit less difficult arete/face climbing takes you to the anchors. Shares anchors with Ain't No Thing But A Chicken Wing.
location: Far left end of Picasso Wall, right-side arete of the column separating Picasso Wall and Red Dihedral Wall

description: Two routes left of Sweet Crack, follow vertical edges past a steep crux section between bolts 2 and 3, below the small ledge. Then the middle is a fun little ride. ¬†The second crux is near the top on the vertical face with horizontal holds. S & M stands for Steve and Marcus. Steve Martin cleaned the line, which was no small order, then placed the rap anchors so the route could be easily top roped. Thanks for your hard work Steve!
Well the bottom is easy and the middle is fun. Then you get to the top.
Stem and jam up the finger crack and corner to a ledge, then pull an airy move over the bulge and make your way up to the anchor.
location: Dihedral at the far right end of Red Dihedral Wall

description: One of the first "great" routes at RB. The crux is getting to the 2nd bolt. From there it's just a fun ride to the top. Stick clipping the 2nd bolt is a good idea.
Another route where the challenge is getting started.
location: This is the 2nd route past the classic Red Dihedral route.

description: A steep slab crux leads to a small ledge rest then up a short dihedral at the top. Two permadraws allows you to work the tricky upper section without the fear of needing to leave your gear. Climb with confidence. Use the big pocket underclings (horse like mouth) to ¬†work your feet up. Reach out left to use laybacks to gain the raps anchors above. Route feed back has included the feeling that the line feels a bit more like a 10 b/c.
location: Just left of Sweet Crack.
protection: 6 bolts plus perma draw rap anchors

description: Sweet route directly to the right of the Red Dihedral. Standing at the bottom you can see what looks to be holes 3/4s the way up. The Crux is moving through those holes and making a throw off the last one.

A bouldery crux is below the first bolt. Feel free to use a stick clip then follow the line of tan bolts through the line of pockets, up an open dihedral, just left of Red Dihedral. The second crux is near the top. Keep a wide stance and climb with confidence. Route gets its name from when I was bolting the line. Midway up, while drilling an anchor hole, the drill bit penetrated a pocket of rock that was holding about five gallons of water. Immediately, water squirted from around the drill bit and started gushing out of the hole in the rock, like an oil well. Hence the name. A different hole was then drilled for the bolt.
location: Find the line of tan bolts between Unclung Hero and the Red Dihedral. These three routes fit snug into this section of the Red Dihedral Wall.
protection: Line of bolts to rap anchor chains

description: A little trickier than it looks, but still a fun little route. Start below the first bolt, right of the route Alpine, and continue straight up to avoid skirting left. Shares anchors with Alpine.
Get yourself started and then remember the name of the route for beta.

This route is a bit of a conundrum. You might think you're at HCR. ¬†It's a pretty difficult V4 boulder move to get off the ground, but once you're at the 2nd bolt turns into a nice 5.9 with sidepulls, some stemming and nice ledge for a rest before going for the last 15 feet. If you're tall the start might be considerably easier.¬† Shares anchors with Funky Side Pulls.
location: 3 routes before you get to the obvious "Sweet Crack" route.

description: If you're short might be a good idea to stick clip the 2nd bolt. ¬†The bottom is all pretty easy. ¬†Getting to the anchors after clipping the last bolt might be the crux.
location: On the obvious face between Sweet Crack and Tito's Arete.

description: Well what can you say. It's short, easy, and a good warm up if you need one, and shares anchors with Golden Ticket #1, just to the right. Head past the the first few bolts by angling up and right, then clip a bolt to your right before finishing at the rap anchors.
location: Just past the practice anchors. You have practiced your route cleaning right?

first_ascent: FFA Marcus Floyd &Lauren Dunning, FA Dave Hug
description: Steep face to the right of Duel Administration leads up to a roof bulge and a left hand under cling. ¬†From the under cling it's a long right hand reach to a crimp which is the start of the crux.¬† Once you are over the roof bulge a couple of balancing moves takes you to the anchors.

Redtail starts as a 5.2 - 5.3 slab that gets serious when it turns vertical below the obvious Picasso roof. At the alcove, stay right and use small edges to gain the pockets. Climb very intentionally, for the pockets are positive but some are positively sharp! Once you reach the large pocket at the roof, the crux subsides if you keep working the feet gracefully.
Technical work early on leads to a cushy life up top.

A route that looks a little easier than it is. As you traverse right in the middle you find your self looking for holds. The last bolt is left of the anchors, clip it and then traverse right. ¬†If you go straight up you make it a more difficult finish.

protection: 2 bolts and fixed draws. Bring an extra draw for a total of three if you plan to set a top-rope.

description: This route is mostly a jug haul over a series of small ledges, with the crux about half way up. Check out some of the cool (geodes?) shining inside many of the pockets.

location: Located on the left side of the beautiful, steep Picasso Wall. This starts just left of the 5.12 and is two climbs right of Number One.

description: We're updating route info as quickly as possible, please be patient.
A steep start leads into easy climbing straight up the bolt line. ¬†Obvious crux at the permadraws. ¬†Find the good holds for a short boulder sequence to finish at the anchors.
protection: 6 draws + 2 perma draws + anchors. ¬†Chains and quick links at the anchors, no biners.

location: The second route once the wall gets more vertical and the holds get more sparse.

description: This really fun climb goes up juggy pockets until around the fourth bolt. The crux section goes from bolts 5-7. Move up and a little right from the fifth bolt and either clip #6 high off some crimps or go up higher to a fairly good two-hand rail and clip from there. Going from 6 to 7 is a bit easier using some good but very rough and painful pockets and up to some jugs by the 7th bolt. Smooth sailing once you've got that one locked down.
protection: Perma-draws provide permanent sport clips for the upper portion of the climb. 7 bolts + anchors

description: A route that looks easier than it is. The bottom is delicate, it's easier if you go right, but then if you're leading it's hard to reach your clips. ¬†The middle is fun but then the top is the 10a/b portion with the baby roof and limited good holds.
Climb through technical crimps and pockets up to a committing crux. ¬†High feet, a good plan, and a jug make a tough move to a sharp easy finish. The crux might be height dependent.

route_name: Ain't No Thing But A Chicken Wing
description: Gain the small shelf about 3-4 ft up and navigate through the rather thin but fun lower 1/3 of the route. The rest is quite easy as you get to the top and share the last bolt and anchors with Tito's Arete.
location: Go past Titos Arete and this is your next route right around the corner and in the dihedral.

description: A really enjoyable climb, that's pretty much a cruise. Stay right of the bolt line the whole way, particularly after the 3rd bolt where looking left will show you nothing but a blank wall. A nice shelf for a rest before you take care of the last 2 bolts.
Another of the long routes at Robinson. ¬†Pretty easy as you go with what challenge there is coming in the last 10-15 feet.

The bottom is super easy 5.4, but once you get up to the upper face, you'll need to clip a bolt, with a chain that extends the clipping range over the edge. ¬†Clipping this bolt was part of the crux. Climbing up over the bulge can be elusively frustrating if you do not find the right hold. Grab a good right hand layback and mantle with the left. Avoid using the tree if it still remains.
A tricky little route that requires some thought for a 5.9. ¬†Take it slowly, decide whether to follow the bolt line (harder) or stay to the side and enjoy the trip to the top.

location: This line starts on a vertical face right of Ray's Cow Bell.
protection: Anticipate seven to eight bolts plus anchors

description: A straight up route that doesn't wander on you. If the bottom is wet you can still make the start by staying left. ¬†Great hands and feet for the first 3/4 of the route. ¬†You'll be thinking it's an 8. Then the top is the 9+ part as it gets just a touch negative and you wish for more feet. Super nice, great re-climb value.

route_name: How I Sent My Summer Vacation
description: Start under a baby roof and either go straight up where your feet are the challenge but your hands are good, or stay a little bit right with better feet but less great hands. ¬†There is a gorgeous side pull down low if you find it. ¬†Once you're at the 2nd bolt the route just becomes a cruise.

If you have a long enough stick clip you can literally clip the 3rd bolt before you jump on. Once you've pulled the baby roof and you're past the 2nd bolt, and have your feet up you're through the crux. Great shelf for practicing your cleaning skills. Your main challenge is finding the right pockets while going through the crux before the pump sets in.
Climb nice pockets to the crimpy bulge, pull over and finish with slightly easier climbing.
Climb up to the overhang, enjoy some laybacks and small finger pockets to the chains.

location: Far right side of Juarez Wall

description: Climb flat face to overhang for difficult finish.
Good beginner route. Climb up the 2 platforms to a bowling ball hold move at the chains.

location: Start in the obvious dihedral feature just right of Bee Hive. Follow the steep slab to the steeper face above.
On the far left side of the cave, start by following the steep face to a ledge above the cave.
Start on the left side of the cave roof and follow a line of pockets and bolts.
This is the first route you come to, just south of the bottom of the stairs.

description: Has yet to see a first ascent. Start in the cave and give it a go.
location: Just to the left of Pillow Fort at the bottom of the stairs.
You can't miss it!
protection: Hand railing provided along with rest areas.

description: Nice long moderate climb. Mostly less than vertical, with a few steeper sections mixed in for some fun. At points you can choose left or right for a short section and depending which way you go it will vary the difficulty.
location: Right route on the obvious tall wall climber's left of the staircase and cave.
protection: 15 bolts plus anchors with chains and mussy hooks.

location: Start below the small lower roof, left of Bee Hive, and follow the slab to gain the first set of anchors.

protection: 17 bolts, bolted anchors with chains, hooks, and a quicklink.

description: Start in the dihedral and stem through the 5.8 moves to get past the first two bolts then to the ledge. Clip the ledge bolt then above the ledge go up staying right of the next two bolts and baby dihedral to make it a little easier (5.7), or go straight up the bolt line if you'd like to experience the 5.9 moves. From there it's a cruise to the top. ¬†A 60 meter rope will barely get you down if you include rope stretch. Better to use a 70, but either way tie safety knots and wear a helmet.
location: Starts in the dihedral just past the Goblin Grotto.

description: Start on the same start as Road to Mordor. This start sequence is the crux of the climb. Instead of traversing left under the roof, continue straight up and right on the face above. ¬†You might think your next crux would be at the baby roof, mid way up the climb, where you go straight instead of left following RTM, but that move isn't too bad. ¬†Up a little higher, you have to look around more for feet, but they're there. This line is well protected!

Arching crack that traverses left below the obvious roof above. Start right with a short, standing start, V1- boulder problem then it lets up to some easy 5.7 climbing once you're over the lip. Then head up to the roof and follow it left. You can finish by lowering off on the fixed gear or get a workout on the top half of Blue Tail Rising. A really fun route with movement you don't see everyday.¬† If you go for the link up make sure to bring a 70m rope.
location: Start right of Fight or Flight.
protection: 10 bolts plus anchors, Stick-clip recommended due to the landing area.

description: Diagonal crack in the middle of the wall.  Use face holds to the right and crack.
protection: Not much protection.  Set up a top rope or boulder.

description: Hand crack
location: Cracks starts half-way up, a small pine grows at the bottom of the crack

description: Hand crack
location: First crack on the wall, in front of a block boulder

description: Start in the horizontal crack high up, then use the two parallel hand cracks.
location: Right of No. 10, near the end of the dike

description: Crack. Starts narrow and widens towards the top
location: The second crack that goes all the way way to the ground

description: Right arete. Sit start
Straight up through the vertical seam. Sit start
Crack on the left side. Sit start

location: 10 ft. right of Blue Tail Rising
protection: Quick Draws, perma-draw rap anchors provided

description: A funky challenge with a tough belay area.
location: First route you come to after taking a left at the bottom of the stairs.
Just right of Begin Again.
protection: 14 bolts + anchors. Perma-draws at the crux and perma-biners on the anchors.

location: Just past Corey's Kazoo on the arete.

description: Climb the face to finally place a good cam in a horizontal crack. Climb the crack to the top and build an anchor
location: Refer to page 75 of the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Starting from the right edge of the Eagle's head roof, follow the finger crack
location: Refer to pg. 89

description: Great crack climb with a nice finish
location: Refer to page 75 of the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Same sit start as aint no lie but move up and left into two good holds. keep left to a slopey shallow hold. use the side pull out left if needed and go to the top.
location: left of aint no lie

description: Sit start with your hands in the horizontal crack. Then lay back the crack (or not) until you reach good holds to a nice top out.
location: Roughly the middle of the left twin.

description: Sit start on Swamp Pull Make the crux move low and left through a crimp. Continue left avoiding the holds at the top of the boulder. Fight the pump and finish about 4 feet left of Tree frog on obvious lay back feature with jugs.
Sit start with hands in the horizontal crack. Pull on good holds for an easy top out.
location: Just right of Chief Slap-a-hold on the right twin.

description: Sit Start on two big side pulls work up to the top arete feature. Eliminate all the stuff to the right for a slightly harder climb.
location: almost at the end of the boulder to the right.

description: Sit Start low on jugs. Move to Underclings on arete Work your way up arete better holds on left side to jugs at the top. Good movement One of the best lines on the boulder.
location: middle of the two boulders just left of slap a hold.

description: Start Low on two small pockets with good feet underneath the overhang. Use some crimps and a slopy ledge to set up for a dynamic move to a jug on the next ledge.
location: To the left of hot for teacher, on a protruding face.
Far left on the School of Rock boulder chain just left of Short Bus.
School of Rock boulders, right off Skoolyard Bully.

description: Sit start on small crimpy pockets right in the middle of the wall, big move to the break, another big move to the lip and a good incut up and right, balancey top out watch out for trees
Sit start on a good flake, move left into a good slot, keep working left through big sharp jugs, big slap moves up top on slopers, and finish it out
location: Keep following the broken cliff line to find this boulder

description: Sit start with right hand in the undercling and left on the pad only pocket. Pull up hard and throw for the ledge under the overhang. Get high feet and gain a jug. Then you're home free.
location: Head around the corner right of Short Bus there's a mini dihedral with a cedar growing out of it. Hot for Teacher starts to the right

description: Sometimes you just gotta slap-a-hold. Sit start with your hands on the good holds and pull up to slap the arete. Then bump your hand up until you can get the side cling with your right hand.
location: Second problem on the left of the right twin.

description: Follow the crack up to the roof, pull the short move, follow the arch up and left to top out.
location: Refer to page 111 of the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri
Refer to page 79 of the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Sit start with paired underclings. Move up and out from under the roof with beta trickery and some big moves. The rock is a little prickly.
location: The overhang to the right of Mud Crack. The first corner of the outcrop past the one that holds All That Glitters.

description: Start with a low sit using your right hand to grab a lip at head level and the left with a jam in the crack. Traverse up the crack and throw for the pocket halfway past the horizontal crack.
Sit to start with hands on the side cling and small pocket. Top out center of the Boulder.
Sit start, use the angled flake, top out left side of boulder
location: Left side of warm up boulder

description: R.O.U.Ss is easy dispatched with a little fire and perseverance. Standing start on small side clings so you can gain the ledge. Then throw big to the top of the overhang. Then with a little high foot action pull over the top.
location: If you follow the boulders to the right of the top access Trail in the small Alcove you should run into ROUSs. It's one of the most recognizable boulders in the area.
protection: Bring a couple crash pads so you have a good landing area.
pad and maybe a spotter for new climbers

description: Sit start with matched hands on the slightly mossy jug. Then lay back the arete until you can get the good holds up top.
location: You'll find this on the protruding ledge about a quarter mile down the trail on the right about halfway up the hill. GPS 37.973741, -90.531991 Second to last problem on the right.

description: awesome problem. techy moves down low, come around the roof big move up, and commiting moves at the top.

This is the direct line climbing out from the from the cave. Start with your left hand in the hueco pocket as your right on the crimp. Climb out using the pockets and underclings until you can pull the roof. ¬†It's currently an open project so make sure to let me know if you get it.

Variation of Song Bird. Sit start to the right of Song Bird about 5 feet. Starts with left hand in sharp 3 finger pocket, right hand pinch the small arete, and right leg knee-skums around the corner. Avoid using the shelves underneath for your left foot (sort of an eliminate). A hard opening sequence links you into the second half of Song Bird.
location: At the Song Bird Roof.

description: Sit start with your hands under the cows head feature.¬† Then pull hard and throw for the top.
location: Right of the Song Bird Roof about 30'.

description: A nice problem with great movement. ¬†Sit start with your right hand hueco pocket and your left on the thin hold in the corner. The move up to the good holds on the outside of the roof. ¬†Hey high feet and go for three spicy top-out.
location: Start is just left of Song Bird.
protection: Crash pad.  If you don't have a spotter bring at least two.

description: Start right hand on a undercling pocket left hand on arete. Work your way left up the arete. and the end of the short arete follow jugs to the top. Super low ball ridiculous start. Careful not to blow the first move and throw yourself of the ledge.
location: Just to the right of Just a Little Lie.

description: Sit start, move up and right through big dumb moves on big dumb-ish holds (and one or two small ones). Could be a bit harder for shorter climbers.
location: Well past the first set of boulders on the loop, just a little ways before a creek crossing. The boulder is up and to the right of the trail on an overhanging block with a big roof.
protection: Pad and maybe a spotter for the topout

description: Sit start in the low slot move up the face using low side pulls and slopey pinches to a dynamic move to a crimp and slot before the jugs at the top.
location: just to the left of all that glitters

description: Start on the low obvious jug. Big move to a side pull match on top up to a slopey ledge. Holds at the lip and finish. Cool movement on solid rock.
location: Just to the left of Just a Little Lie

description: Thin, spectacular crack system
location: Refer to pg. 82

description: Thin crack
location: Refer to pg. 82

description: Slab overlooking the river. Start low off the triangular rock in front of the face, move up and right on interesting holds and balancey compression. Spooky top out.
location: A bit tough to find, but not so hard to spot once you see it. Downriver from the Lounge area. Look for the knee-height slanted boulder on a ledge in front of the black face.
protection: Pad, two to be careful and probably a spotter

description: Mantle up and gain a crack in a chimney/dihedreal. Stem and chimney your way up and pull through a small roof to top out.
location: Right of arrete, noticeable crack in a chimney/dihedral.
protection: Gear to 2, you can rig an anchor off trees above to allow for rap/topropping.

description: Direct start with face holds or mantle up on left. Gain entry into the crack placing a piece low to prevent falling into the stream. Fingers to jams up at the top. This route was extremely dirty. Be sure to bring a nut tool or brush to clean out the crack.
location: Thin crack just right of chimney/dihedral.

description: Climb southfacing arete of Spire.
location: southfacing arete
protection: None, hope you fall in the water

description: Follow the bolts using side pulls as you pull your way up the ramp.
location: To the right of Thin Cut

description: The classic traditional route of the park. Excellent route with high quality rock.  Layback the thin dihedral to a huge chockstone-like double-dihedral. From here, the choice is yours!  Use 'em both or pick a side.
location: This is the obvious dihedral to the right of the three listed sport routes.  It really is EXCELLENT.  It's short, but classy.
protection: Good nut placements and cams under 3.

description: Begin on a small hollowish flake launching up to a positive left hand crimp. From here utilize sidepulls and small crimps with a dash of some fancy footwork. Gain a great rest around the 4th bolt then bring it home. Wonderful route in a pretty cool setting.
location: Center of the first wall you walk to

description: Jam and ly-back your way to the top while placing gear as necessary. 2 safety anchors at the top.
location: The crack to the left of Onlooker
protection: Standard rack to No. 2 camalot, safety anchor at the top.

description: Use small holds and get to a great pocket. Throw left and catch a good hold. Cross over right and work into good jug. Pull through one more tricky section and use good holds to reach the anchor.
location: to the right of La Tre France'

description: Beginning on Rendezvous, climb through the first two bolts, then angle up and left, through the dihedral, to a pair of safety anchors
location: refer to description

description: Moderate for St. Francious. Climb the mixed line top out straight and right. Strong contender for best route at the site.
location: First route to the left of Tre France'

first_ascent: FFA Dave Hug 2015, FA Thurmond, circa 1990's
description: Climb the crack using the chockstone until you reach a ledge. Clip the bolt and angle rightward to the top.
location: To the left of Little Trad

description: Pull some hard moves and work towards laying back the crack. Follow the crack and eventually pull the slabby face to the anchors.
location: First sport route to the left of hidden corners.

description: Open project for anyone up to a challenge
location: 4 bolt sport route to the left of Monthly Training

description: Like most of the problems at SFSP the crux comes at the start. Lay back and pull hard to get to the crimpy side pull. Then use the side pulls to climb the face to the boulder top out.
location: Just to the right around corner of Fat Boy Strikes Back.
protection: Bring a static rope and the good cedar trees to tie off to on the top.

description: Pull on good holds through the short section of hanging block limestone. Work your way onto the face and use pockets and edges to make your way to the top
location: 5 feet to the right of Beguile

description: The low angle sport route on the left side of the gully. Climb the short face to gain a small ledge. Use great jugs as you lead up and into the upper face to eventually clip the anchor.
location: To the right of Onlooker

description: The crux is the start of the route then smear and stem your way to the top in the small dihedral.
location: One of the first routes you come to on the overlook wall. Kind of a mini dihedral.
protection: Highball boulder or set  a top rope off the trees up top.

description: Start on edges and use pockets to reach good jugs. From here pul up and stand on jugs. Follow the bolts to the top.
location: 30 feet to the right of the roof crack.

description: Starts with some balancy moves on small holds. Then climb the face to a strong move to top out on the over hang at the top.
location: Bad Mouth is the route to the furthest right on the Overlook Wall.
protection: There are good cedar trees to tie off to on top.

location: 30 feet to the right of Dihedral

description: Begin on the left inside corner, traverse up and right around the arete. Gain the face and proceed through thin holds till you gain back the arete up top.
location: the arete to the right of Dehedral

description: Crux start. ¬†Slight over hang on sketchy rock. Left facing side pull to decent pocket. High right hand throw to strong pull up. ¬†Low angle top out. Boulder finish to the top of the anchor shared with Guide Crack.
location: Far right corner of the Jam Wall. 10 feet to the right of Guide Crack.
protection: TR off the anchor shared with Guide Crack. Trad option. Totems .50 - 1.25.

description: Utilize edges and sidepulls to eventually access the better hold on top.
location: 15 feet to the right of punching in a dream

description: Climb the crack finding face holds along the way eventually reaching the anchors
location: inside left corner of gully

description: Climb through the wide section using good holds on the wall, eventually work into a layback. Protect the crack and climb to the apex of the crack. From here, climb the face and clip the anchor.
location: 30 Feet to the right of Punching in a Dream

description: Climb the crack using face holds when possible to eventually reach the anchor
location: five feet to the right of Hidden Corner on the right side the same gully
This route is the second route from the left, just to the right of Unknown at the farthest end of the bluff.
protection: 4 bolts plus shared anchor with Big River.

description: A fun little introduction to St. Francois climbing.  The crux is in the first ten feet of the route. Begin with some fun balancy moves, eventually gaining good holds.  Once you're past the third bolt, cruise to the anchor and you're home free!
location: This is one the left-most bolted lines, just right of Mista Girly Man on the bluff.
protection: There are five bolts (very well-protected), and anchors.

description: Begin on the same holds as Pump Me Up and climb up and left to a great vertical edge. From here stay left of the bolts and continue straight up.
location: Begin on Pump Me Up and angle up and left

description: Thin crimps on a steep vertical section of the east side or the boulder that faces the Slab Wall section of the Main Bluff. Top rope recommended!
location: Thin crimps on the east side or the boulder that faces the Slab Wall section of the Main Bluff.

description: start in a pocket side pull on arete, use slot features work around arete on sharp crimps, move left to shelf, and up and right to finish.
location: back side of boulder nestled in the rock.

description: The left arete of the steeper slab face on the Nubbin. Climb up from as low as you can on decent features just past the corner.
location: On the downhill side of the Nubbin.

description: start on sharp jugs head sharp right work into water runnel feature straight up to the mantely finish.
This line follows up through the scoop dished-out shape and starts from a standing start. A vine hangs nearby.
location: Front left side of boulder. Look for the scoop dished-out shape and start from a standing start.

description: traverse up and right or left of arch.
location: Refer to description

description: Standing start using the horizontal crack for your feet.
location: Just to the left of Crynomas on the back side of the boulder.

description: Where you see the obvious place to top out you can keep traversing off to the left. There is about 20 - 25 feet of traversing (with crux about 1/3 of the way in) before you come to the other arete which immediately followed by a dihedral. Did feel safe going further than that.
location: refer to description

description: To the right of chimney and sapling-climb arete
location: Refer to description

description: To the right of chimney and sapling-climb arete
This is a hard sit start with very little for the feet. ¬†If you'd like to take the edge off you can stand start which is V0. Maybe v3-4 for a shorter individual who can't reach the upper holds.
location: Bravo side of the Crying Shame boulder right of Low Down Dirty Shame.

description: This climb was hiding on the back side of the main boulder, between a few boulders. The difficulty of the climb varies from a standing or squatting position. Standing start with slopers is a V0 and a squatting position is around a V3-4. Crynomas is from a sitting position, from a bouldering pad, and is around a V6.
location: Behind the Crying Shame Boulder, along the Mooner's Hollow West Loop Trail.

description: sit start on jugs move up on big holds and cool lay back feature.
sit start matched on pocket side pull feature, small intermediate crimps or go big to the lip, use shallow holds over lip, and get up!
left hand big pocket, right hand small shallow slot, work over the bulge using hidden holds, gain the mediocre lip hold with a sweet spot, high feet, and rock over.
sit start on jugs move up and slightly right the crux is the top out.

route_name: My face is to pretty for slab
description: Easy standing start followed by a balancey middle to a satisfying top out
location: The problem is on the left face if The Nubbin closest to the Arete.
protection: Crash pad. Having a spotter might be a good idea might be a good idea due to the landing area.

description: Short but nice. Sit start matched on the corner, move up and left, and use some high feet to top out. With a few exceptions, the holds are unusually rounded for the area, and very solid.
location: Around on the right side of Crocodile Rock and a few feet up the hill.
protection: Pad. The landing is sloped, so careful how you place it.

description: Sit start with a funky pull on. Head up using the crack feature on the right. Gets a little burly at the top. The sit start is easy V3-ish, the stand start is something like V2 depending on wingspan. 2.5 stars if I could give it; it's a bit short for a full 3.
location: On the side of the Nubbin facing you on approach. Starts middle of the face.
protection: Pad, maybe a spotter for the top.

description: Captain Obvious is a standing start moves straight up and tops out tears the back of the boulder.
location: Far left of the left face of The Nubbin.

description: Sit start with matched hands on the nose crack. Top out using the pockets just to the left.
location: Crocodile Rock

description: Sit start far right in the crack in the nose traverse left top out using the finger crack in the middle of the boulder.
location: Located in crocodile rock.

description: Sit start low on the crocodile's mouth and traverse left tops our the same as Brain Drain.
location: Located on Crocodile rock

description: Standing start on good holds
location: Left most problem on Crocodile Rock.

description: Sit start with two good jug pockets on either side of the corner. Make a medium-big move for a left crimp, slap up to good holds right. Move right around the corner to another jug pocket or follow the corner left a little further for a slightly tougher top.
location: On the far right corner of the block at the left end of the area.

description: It's start is under the roof pulling on the two finger pockets. Then you throw to the ledge outside the roof. Heal hook and pull up to the mono. Then mantle of the shelf to get the higher hold
location: On the overhanging block at the left end of the area, starts on the lonely mono in the middle of the wall.

description: Sit start on matched crimps, reach up and back for a high right hand, get high feet then power through the mantle to finish
Climb the series of ledges working up and to the left. Crux is the mantle to top out then scramble down by the observation deck.
location: Stack of ledges just right of the observation deck.

description: Start matching on the really good sloper and dino to the top.
location: In the field of boulders there is one fairly big boulder. The problem faces the highway.

description: Chose your line up the face at the back of the shallow alcove. ¬†The crux is finding solid hands and feet while avoiding choss. ¬†There is good rock you just have to search for it a bit. ¬†When finished either downclimb or top out and scramble back down by the Observation Deck. This route should get much better with time.
location: Look for the alcove sitting by itself uphill and left of the Observation Deck.

description: Sit start, use crimps to ascend face left of the crack. Crack is off.
location: Face left of the COVID Crack problem.

description: Sit start, use small crimps to work up the middle of the face¬†and top out.
location: Right facing slab just right of¬†COVID crack

description: Water continually shifts the pebble bank and varies in level through the year. Summer seems to be the best time to send this problem. A standing start is an easier warm up option.
location: Lower Wall Boulder sits on the opposite side of the pool of water from the cliff face. Sit start below the steep side of the boulder that faces up stream towards the cliff.

description: Sit start, either layback or use small crimps on the adjacent faces to work your way up the crack and top out.
location: Obvious left facing dihedral crack in a small alcove to your right as you arrive at the lower wall from main trail

description: Scramble up and down the path of least resistance from the observation deck. ¬†Its a quicker way to walk off the routes on the Main Wall. Easy scrambling just watch out for all the loose rock.
location: Wide area of loose rock directly below the observation deck

description: Climb the left side of the low angle face on this freestanding block. This one is all about the friction, avoid the blasting grooves to the right side of the face.
location: Look for the free standing block on the right side of the trail as you head downhill on the west side of the quarry blocks

description: Sit start on good crimp, bump left hand up and traverse around the boulder, utilizing the arete feature. Then mantle. Solid couple feet of easy climbing.
location: Walk down the main trail on the West side of the quarry rocks, its on the left about 2/3 of the way down the hill.

description: Climb the face using broken flakes and other edges.
location: The middle feature of the face just left of Arch Support. Refer to page 22 of Rock Climbs Of Johnson Shut Ins State Park

description: This is the route that climbs the buttress just to the right of the observation deck. The 5.7 Dihedral is to the left. The crux is getting off the ground. Face and crack climb to the top. A fun climb for sure.
location: The buttress just to the right of the observation deck (if looking up from base). the 5.7 Dihedral is to the left.

description: Crack climb the Johnson Shut-Ins classic!
location: Center crack splitting the featured face

description: Climb the flake feature using both the crack and face
location: refer to guide

description: Climb the face using pocketed edges and continue to the crack. Climb the crack up and right to top out.
location: Left of Gong Show. Refer to page 28 of Rock Climbs Of Johnson Shut Ins

description: Use a combination of crack climbing and stemming to reach the top
location: refer to guide

description: Climb the amazing dihedral formation and build an anchor at the top.
location: refer to guidebook

description: Follow the aerie into the dihedral and continue up the arete.
location: Small dihedral feature to the right of Beginner Chimney. Refer to page 24 of Rock Climbs Of Johnson Shut Ins State Park
protection: Small gear, looks to be desperate. just top rope it.

description: Climb the crack and enter the chimney. Layback and stem you way up.
location: refer to guidebook

description: Use the face and small dihedral crack to reach the obvious horizontal crack. From there angle up and left to build an anchor
location: refer to guidebook

description: Small slabbish boulder covered in lichen. Sit start with wide hands, make your way up the face in a few moves and mantle to the top.
location: Midway down the Lower East Side section is an almost free-standing boulder with a medium sized tree on the right side. The face is on the southern side of that rock.

description: Low start on good holds, follow the stack of quarry rocks using the arete(s).
location: Walk around the back of Liking Lichen. Directly over a sizeable hole.
protection: pad over the hole, fall could still be sketchy

description: Jugs up from the sit start, use the 2 finger pocket to reach the lip over the bulge.
location: Two large sit start start pockets at the base. Head directly up.

description: Climb the edges of the face protecting when necessary. Build an anchor at the top.
location: Refer to page 132 in the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

route_name: Keep on the Sunny Side (aka No. 44)
description: Follow the wicked crack placing gear when necessary, build anchor at the top.
location: Refer to page 132 in the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Follow the hand traverse, cut straight up when you can. Protect when necessary.
location: Refer to page 131 in the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Use the two sit start pockets low at the center of the boulder and head to the right arete up to the huge bowl jug above the lip of the roof.
location: Low center sit start to right

description: Climb the easy crack and protect when necessary
location: Refer to page 134 in the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Climb the easy crack and protect when necessary
location: Refer to page 134 in the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Climb the easy crack and place gear when necessary
location: Refer to page 134 in the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri
Refer to page 134 in the book Granite Climbs Of Missouri

description: Sit start in the hip-height pockets down low. Work out to leftmost and pull up to the little roof and mantle using good holds beyond the lip and a high foot to top out.
location: Low center to left of the boulder

description: Super hard route through the left side of cave.
location: cave left

description: Fairly straightforward face climb, follow the bolts to the anchor. ¬†The crux is right before the third bolt. It's possible to traverse to the left before the crux but a fall would be bad. This route has a lot of potential but it needs significant cleaning first.
location: Second sport route from the left
protection: Three bolts to anchor. New leaders might want to stick clip the first bolt.

description: Starts low on the 2 yellow circles
location: Right of Jim Would Be Proud
protection: 2 pads. One unfolded with the other on top

description: First, admire the communal work of man and mother nature. Next, get psyched. Work up the man cut perfect finger flake from the ground to a chiseled ledge between the head wall and overhanging boulder. Traverse left to the roof boulder's crack using natural jibs or the drilled holes for feet. Work into the crack with a heel hook on the ledge. Power up, through, and over the crack's thin holds and jams for a high ball top out on questionable blocks. Sustained line with a broad mix of technique and gumption.
location: Right and down from the porch, you'll reach a ledge you can down climb into the little corner that this beaut resides in. It's a pretty noticeable feature.
protection: Def want a crash pad and spotter to move it and watch you. Could be better but landing is about as flat and solid as you could hope for with a roof route like this. Could be led with gear, maybe top-roped if you wanted to jimmy rig something up.
parent_sector: J: The Man and Mother Corner

description: Crouch start with hands on small crimps, top out center of the boulder
location: Deep in the forest, refer to map

description: Start low work your way up to the ledge. Match heel (red dot) to hand and reach up
It is a slab route with a very high left foot start. but the route can be modded with the tree next to it.
protection: Helmet and rope may help those afraid of taking a hard fall, I would recommend a crash pad and a buddy.

description: Crux is at the start and topping out.
location: Start with left and right on side pulls and work left (V4). Start with left hand on slope and right on crimp below "nose" (V4-5)
Katie trail, next to blumenhof
protection: Top belay attached to tree could help but I found it unnecessary

location: Near trail to blumenhof off Katie trail. Park in state park

description: Start sitting below Norton's cyn on under cling and crimp. Find usuable feet then travel either left as of the beta picture or finish on Nortons cyn grades are the same.
location: Facing the road

description: Middle Crux, nice top out. Starts with match on sloper
Make your way up the steps without using your hands. Try to make your way back down for an added "high five" bonus.
location: Right of the taste of sandstone

protection: 3 pads due to most route are traversed

description: Up the hill from the welcome boulder. Find the excellent crack around the left corner of the tall face
Avoid the arete. Careful.
Short problem. Start with feet underneath. Hold self up and pull feet to right. Heel hook and make your way up
Crux is around the middle. The back wall is within the falling zone so YOU MUST STACK TWO PADS AGAINST THE WALL. Please be careful.
location: Hip level there is a small crimp for your left hand, left foot on the mantle start of Decantur, right hand in is in small pocket about head level
protection: 2 pads against the wall, 2 pads for the ground, and a helmet would help

description: The crux is the flat top finish. Please clean the top and be careful.
location: Slab to the left of Devil's Den

description: To the right of Jim Would be Proud
location: Right Boulder farthest right wall facing trail

description: The right exit to ‚ÄúJim Would Be Proud‚Äù. Same start and first few moves, but topout to the right instead of to the left. Avoids the traverse.
First non slab route
location: Right Boulder facing trail

description: Tall top out. Careful when spotting
Super easy climb but the features are really neat. Sitstart on left facing jug. Head straight up toward sloppy rails and cool pinch feature.
location: To the right of the no feet problem next to the rocky downslope.
protection: Probably a pad and spotter since the slope is not very flat.

description: Straight up
Climb the pocketed face to a very dirty top out.
location: Just left of Corkscrew crack up and left from the Dutzow boulder
protection: TR from sturdy trees on top or highball boulder

description: Getting to the last big jug to top out
location: Right of Devil's Den Start

description: This is a high ball. Please approach with extreme caution. Please use at least 4 pads. Starts with hands matched sit start. The arete is off
location: Directly behind the welcome boulder

description: To the left of Oak Barrels
location: Sit start below main jug, move to jug then two finger Gaston.

description: Climb the twisting rightward trending crack protecting as you go. The top out is pretty dirty, make sure to protect it well.
location: Up the hill from Dutzow boulder. ¬†It‚Äôs the obvious crack right around the arete from tannin crack.
protection: Standard rack .5-3, trees on top for anchor

description: Start with right hand on large diagonal crimp as pictured with lower left hand to start. The loose rock is off.
location: between scotty and Ashley's beta
protection: 2 pads. One to cover the rock on the left

description: Start low on the jugs. The top is a large jug.
Poop  Chute has an interesting start at the lower roof and dihedral crack. use a hand jam with the right and palm press with the left. Safety bolts are in place. Belayers should wear a helmet.
location: 30 - 40 feet right of Chubb Trail Crack
protection: 4 bolts to bolt anchors. Stickclip recommended.

description: Two different starts affect the route's rating dramatically depending on starting directly below the first bolt or just down and right of the first bolt. This rating is based on the harder start just direct below the first bolt.
location: One for Dunning is one of the first routes you find on the right end of the Chubb Crack Wall.

description: One for Dunning is one of the first routes you find on the right end of the Chubb Crack Wall. Two different starts effect the route's rating dramatically depending on starting directly below the first bolt or just down and right of the first bolt. this rating is based on the easier start just right of the bolt. Climb up then step left to use a pocket to clip the first bolt. Continue to the next bolts and rap anchors at the top.
location: Route furthest right along the wall, close to the top of the right side approach trail.

description: This pocketed line is just right of Chubb Trail Crack. The easy start option involves using the beginning of the Chubb Trail Crack then heading right to the first bolt and up past many pockets and a hand full of bolts to a two bolt rap anchor. Harder start begins directly under the route and slightly right of the first bolt, pulling on pockets to manage your way over the low roof. Boulder problem crux feels like a 10+ move and is a bit reach dependent.
location: Geranium Mine is the obvious line of bolts just right of Chubb Trail Crack.
protection: 5 bolts to bolt anchors. Stickclip recommended.

location: 30 feet right of Chubb Trail Crack, just left of Poop Chute.
protection: 4 bolts, chains at anchor. Highly recommend bringing a stick clip.

description: Crux is the last 15 feet of the climb, between the last bolt and the two bolt anchor. Steep face with pockets transitions to a roof bulge with a reach. The route gets it's name from the fact that someone can move right and finish the climb on Chubb Trail Crack to avoid the crux.
location: Sport line just 10 ft left of Chubb Trail Crack.
protection: 4 bolts to bolt anchors. Stickclip on first bolt recommended.

description: This continuous crack sucks up pro so take a range of cams, nuts and what ever else you fancy. The crux is getting started and mellows after you are 10 feet off the ground. A slightly easier start involves several face moves just left of the base of the crack. This may feel more like a 5.7 crux for people who feel more comfortable with face climbing.
location: Chubb Trail Crack divides the cliff face and is situated in the middle of the crag.
protection: Take a standard rack of cams and stoppers. Use rap anchors to descend.

description: Traverse under the roof from One for Dunning to Poop Shoot. ¬†It is possible to continue bouldering all the way to the Chubb Trail Crack start. The problem is a bit harder and require a bit more repeated cleaning. This is a nice diversion on a rainy day or while waiting your turn to climb.
location: Obvious roof on right side of crag.

description: The first 30 foot vertical start requires stepping up onto the starting block then using small pockets and mid-finger depth side pulls to move through a well defined 9 sequence. Mantle up and to the right to top out the first section. Roughly 15 feet of 5.2 ascends a ramp band section of chert. A section of 5.5 moves to top out. Rap anchors provided a the top, just below the lip.
location: Farthest left (east) bolted route of the crag.

description: Find yourself with just enough room for the right hand finger tips in the first slot hold The sit start requires some strength and tricky feet to figure out which lead into a short finessed foot-puzzle before the top out. DONT BREAK THE FLAKE even it does feel satisfying to hold. Stand start with some slotted hold probably a V2.
location: To the right of The North Rememberers. You‚Äôll identify a slabby face and it‚Äôs bellybutton. That will be the right hand start hold. Left hand is pressing on the crescent. It‚Äôs in great chill spot off the trail protected by a shorter rock.
protection: 1 big pad. Maybe one on the adjacent rock.

description: Sit start on an overhang and jugs through fun, bouldery moves to a very blank slab. Absolutely exhilarating¬†feeling to stick that top hold. It‚Äôs a beautiful climb.
location: West of the main cluster of this area. Obvious to spot. Boulder sits on a large, flat slab.
parent_sector: F: The Herd and The Den

description: Sit start on a low jug, move up and right through cool holds and unusual moves. Topping out the boulder is possible but not entirely recommended; there's an obvious stopping point on a ledge, and while the climb the rest of the way to the top isn't hard the downclimb is pretty tenuous.
location: Near the center of the area, under a large overhanging prow. Near 18 on the map of the area.
parent_sector: F: The Herd and The Den

description: Begin on Fen and traverse left into Smoke
location: Begin on Fen

description: Start on the horizontal shelf, climb around the bulge and to the top
location: Directly right of Destined to forget

description: Sit start on a pair of crimps. Work up the face making interesting moves on sidepulls and gastons.
location: About 80 feet down the trail from Turtle Traverse. Flat, chalked, vertical, and facing the trail.

description: Start matched on the right-facing scoop jug and head up.
location: Near the left corner of the trail-facing side of the far clump of Front Range boulders.
After forking right on the trail, look out to the left for a large boulder that looks like a turtle.
protection: You don't really even need a crashpad, since it's like four feet off the ground.

description: Climb through the cool looking zig zag crack system
location: Crack to the left of Jump Start Thing

description: Climb the slab using the black crystal
location: To the right of Extra Cheese

description: Dyno to the lip followed by a mantle for the finish
location: The first boulder you reach at the Front Range
Front Range, in front of the Ananconda Boulder. If you are facing Vector Days the climb is behind you to the right.
protection: Low to the ground. Standard bouldering pad and a second to slide it along as you move up to the left.

description: Nice crack with a variety of jams available.
location: Trailside face of the second clump of Front Range boulders

description: Climb through the tall flaring crack to the left of the dihedral
location: To the right of The Lightning Cracks

description: Start on Bigfoot, traverse the crack left.
location: On the right trailside face of the Vector Days boulder.

description: Start on jugs in the horizontal crack. Go up the arete to the right.
location: Towards the back of the Vector Days boulder.

description: Climb subtle edges and crystals up the face.
location: Next line to the right of Knob Job.
protection: A pad or two and a spotter

description: Sit start and go up the arete and onto the slab to the right. Those without the length to reach the jug from a true sit may have to use some funky tactics to do the start (recommended even for those who do have the reach, it's fun!). Know your downclimb!
location: On the right (facing the Porch from below) end of the boulder to the right of the Porch's main outcrop.
protection: Pad(s), maybe spotters. Watch the boulder behind you; it can be useful for bailing, but a problem in a fall.

description: High start using gastons, head up and right using crimps to the rounded top out
location: To the right of Jamboree

description: The classic warm up at the porch. Layback the crack and use the finger buckets to mantle out
location: The leftmost problem at the porch

description: Dyno and hita crystal edge in the middle of the wall. Have fun with the hand foot match for the finish
location: Directly right of The Layback Crack
Directly right of Jumping Jim

description: Start on jugs and work up the aerie
location: Directly right of Smoke

description: Don't forget it
location: Directly right of Mission Control

description: Start with left pinch/crimp and right crimp and go straight up. A couple hard moves lead to an easy but lichen-y topout.
location: The middle of the face of the separate boulder to the right of the main Porch.
protection: A pad or two, maybe a spotter.

description: Grab a high right-facing jug flake and move upward on decent holds to a committed topout. There is a tough sit start.
location: On the boulder to the right of the main outcrop of The Porch. Look for the flake a little above head height.

description: Battle to get into the large offwidth crack then scrap your way up the highball boulder. (Know your down climb)
location: it is the wide crack on the left side of huge egg shaped boulder (looks like a butt crack). At the top of the park.
protection: Pads and spotters.  Have spotter throw pad on adjacent boulder for down climb.

description: One the backside of the obviously elephant shaped boulder- find a left hand sloper and right hand slopey crimp and low feet to start...traverse right & move upwards to the left hand side press and ride the rump to top out
location: North Mountain area on the elephant boulder

description: Crux is near the top. Head up the layback and crack, then left to jams. Continue up and left for the top out. Originally climbed with a top rope, then lead with pro before bouldering (solo).
location: Just west of the Bed of Moss Boulder, past the hallway between the rocks and look for the obvious crack heading up and left. Head down the backside or jump over to an easier walk down.
protection: Standard rack, sucks up pro if you are not the bouldering type.

description: See map and photos for details
location: Northern Exposure boulder feature

description: Start on high knob and move straight up.
location: When you get off the trail you come to a kind of hallway, it's the first boulder on the eastern side, climb in the middle of the face.

description: Climb a featureless slab using the thumb undercling
location: Slab to the right of The Finger Crack

description: The V-shaped dihedral. Do it with tennis shoes on!
location: just around the bend from The Scary One, closer to the parking.

description: SDS or not, SDS is a bit harder but fun. Move to a left crimp on the face and then top out left of the apex.
location: On the NW corner of the boulder just behind the two picnic table area.

description: Start in a big jug under a roof and traverse right.  Finish with a really cool mantel on a unique hold.  Fun, unique moves and good rock make this a great problem.
location: With the huge triangular overhang of Tablecloth at your back, Sterno is on the right side of the boulder you are looking at.

description: Two hand start. End on a chossy top out. Fun problem!
location: There is a tree on the lip of the face. It is a few feet to the left of that.

description: Great problem! Two hand start, finish with a match. A top out would be really awesome but would be incredibly dangerous and difficult.
location: underneath the biggest ledge. The area is to the left of the bluff.
protection: At least two pads. We did it with one spotter but another would have been nice. Watch out for the hill on as the name says, you might roll.

description: Start on the lookers left side of the bluff with both hands on a wide, obvious ledge. Traverse from the far right of the ledge to the far left. Once you are all the way to the left of the ledge, a large pocket on your left and jug to your right provide the first holds creating vertical progress. Bump the right hand to a crimp and then lock off the right arm for a chossy top out.
Climb up the less than vertical face with a right facing flake. Go all the way up, toping out as high as you can.
location: further left of Tennishoe and just right of Kaya.

description: Slab moves all the way up.
location: Just left of The Tennishoe Crack

description: Sit-start low and climb 3/4 of the way up to a crimp and top out on the arete.
location: NE corner of the same boulder as Tablecloth.

description: Left Facing offset crack. Climb up. A little sketchy.
location: Behind you when you face Rosin.

description: Sit-start with a positive left-facing hold and climb up the slopey seam.
location: Around the arete from Flame.

description: Start with a high edge for the left hand and jump to a good crimp. Move out to finish on Tablecloth.
location: On the face just left of Tablecloth.

description: Work your way up the crack
location: First crack to the left of Kaya

description: Climb the face
location: To the right of The Scary One
Shares some of its line with Tablecloth.

description: Start in the corner and go up to the left facing flake(dog ear shaped). Do the sketchy top out.
location: Just left of Spooky.

description: Climb huge jugs and have fun topping out. It gets interesting up there
location: a few feet to the right of the arete

description: Start on edge at head-level. Go to rounded top-out.
location: Large boulder close to parking lot and west of picnic table.

description: Start with a left facing hold and make a long move to a good hold.
location: left of Tablecloth, past a tree. start with a tree to your back.

description: Start to the right of the tree. Follow jugs to the top
location: On the Southeast side of the Tablecloth boulder

description: Sit-start with and undercling and a sidepull and continue up the arete.
location: just right of Heat. On the boulder west of the picnic table.

description: Climb the face using the obvious edges. Several variations exist
location: Just left of Slow Ride

description: It's the center offwidth in the middle of the three cracks.
protection: A crash pad is needed, Spotter or two is recommended.

description: Sit start on Fire and then do¬†a cool gaston sequence to transition into the start of Backdraft and then finish as per Backdraft. I thought "Firestarter" would've been a cool name for this, but for reasons unknown, "DITCOE" stuck...
location: Sit start on Fire, link into Backdraft. Simple.

description: SDS as per Rosin but traverse right on the slopey top and finish as per Sterno.
location: Around arete from Flame on the boulder west of the picnic table.

description: SDS as per Rosin but traverse low and right towards a right facing hold into Sterno. Then climb as per Sterno and continue right to end on Blazin.
location: Around arete from Flame. On the boulder west of the picnic table.

description: Climb the crack
location: First crack to the left of Paul Bunyan Crack

description: Climb up the right side of the arete
location: Right side of the arete to the left of Mono Arete

description: An easy crack with a good landing. It trends rightward, and runs hands low to a perfect fist jam up high. A good low-commitment beginner crack
location: On the 12ft high mezzanine rib-like wall running from the upper picnic area to the lower picnic area, find the fist crack directly in the middle between the two areas (see map photos).

description: With hands set left in crack and right in mono fire to the top
location: Start with left hand in the crack and right hand in mono
