location: start on rock pad on left before bouldering starts just below the right facing flake(sunshine route

description: This traverse is in the same area as the High Traverse and the Low Traverse. Start on Jugs on the right hand side of the Low Traverse and climb through slopers at about chest height. After about five feet, There are some jugs at chest height. Don't grab these, but use a crimper to the right of the jugs at about head height (about 6 feet up). The rest of the traverse uses the holds located where the rock changes from smooth to chirt right below the two jugs mentioned earlier. You will find a sloper/pinch, and some small crimps. One of the crimps has a piece of chirt right about it which scrapes against your finger nails. End the traverse on the smallest holds you can use. A slightly (but still V4) easier version uses the pork chop shaped hold. There should be some easier way to describe the elimination problems at Capen. This one is included because it is one of the best, but it is hard to describe. If you want a really good workout, do the traverse one way, then reverse it. It has been done.
location: bouldering cave

description: Crux is moving past the lower roof and mid section of the route. Again, the line tests you at the top with a lay back crack to finish. Start the route 15 to 20 feet right of the start for the Open Book.
Start similar to Missouri Breaks or Russian Vault. Finish up the overhang left side of the Vault overhang area.
Steep roof line following obvious holds left of Swing Time. Start at the right side of the small cave hole at the base of the cliff.
Main wall of Capen Park, inside the bouldering cave lies a well thought puzzle of a sit down problem. Starting moves are better if someone shows you & the crux involves a vertical yoga pose.
location: Bouldering Cave on the far right

description: Crux is in the sloping scoop feature which forces a long reach to gain the next good edge. Finish on the Green Slime finish.

One of the great climbs at CapenPark Direct from the old BooneCountyClimbs book: First ascent Stuart Schneider, July 1978. Starting at the extreme left end of the bluff, grasp a pocket with the left hand and pinch hold with the right. Pull up and heel hook on a ledge. Reach high for a good hold, pull up and mantle on the overhang. The eliminator version does a one-arm pull-up with no feet. If you come off, the name of the climb becomes a reality. (Ask Stuart!)
location: far left end of cliff

description: If you climb between the bouldering cave and the flake on ThreeHorns , you will do Bon Voyage. It is short, and is not climbed very often
location: between the bouldering cave and the flake

description: Ape Man is to the right of The Slot and to the left of a small right facing flake with a crack behind it, and goes through a small roof at the top. Start on a slab with pockets and climb to the "roof". Right over the "roof" is a crack. Grab that and mantle over the top. Another way to do this boulder problem is to climb the right facing flake just before the traverses to a jug just above the flake, traverse left to the topout on Ape Man
location: left end if cliff under small roof
protection: can be top roped, natural anchors. if done as boulder problem, use a spotter and crash pad. OR if you just wanna solo it you can. pretty tall highball though

description: One of the best hand cracks the area has to offer. Lieback in a perfect corner to a large edge right before topping out.
location: Located on the largest cliffs nearest to the highway, and directly behind the two prominent boulders furthest south. Scramble around the east side of the outcrop to set up an anchor if top roping.
protection: Protects well with a couple #1 Camalots or a few finger sized pieces. A top rope anchor can also be set up using multiple earth anchors and a #3 or #4 Camalot. Bring a couple long cordelettes or a static line to assist with properly equalizing everything.

description: Twin cracks at the start that will lead you to an offwidth. Large ledges and jugs will follow after the offwidth.
location: To the left of Right Crack
protection: Fence posts at the summit for TR anchors.

location: Sinkhole Area
protection: Bring pads, uneven surface, more pads the better, 4 or 5 would be optimal to even out the landing

route_name: Step or Stone, Breath or Bone
description: Fun techy face climbing! Start on a boulder with a couple large pockets, work your way up to a ledge at a band of choss, then get ready for the fight as you crimp your way up the balancy wall above. Note that between the first and second bolts you may want a #1 cam.
location: Bolt line just left of the crack of Blood, Sweat, and Beers.

description: Start at southwest face of boulder and use pockets and edge of boulder to top out. Good warmup for the rest of boulder.
location: Southwest edge of the boulder.

description: Start with hands on or near ledge about 6ft and feet on toe edges near the bottom. Push up to grab the slight overhang with an inverted pinch and hang on to pull up and top out. Feet can be a little loose.
location: Located on the east face of the boulder.

description: Start on the Northwest edge of the boulder with hands on small fingertip edges of visible scratches across the rock from low left up the the right towards the top. Use these edges to work up to the top.
Bold line that traverse to the right of Slabby Cat. Cool moves on some tricky sidepulls.
location: Right of Slabby Cat.

description: Great route! Delicate, tought provoking, balancy moves in the dihedral on super-friction rock, then a strenuous, tenuous, histoplasmosis undercling lieback section to pull through the roof - and it ain't over until you've worked your way back to the left to the safety of a crack above the cat.
location: Look for the bolted line with the thinnest of thin cracks in the corner of a dihedral, a bolted line goes up that with the cat-eared silhouette of the eponymous slabby cat visible, playing with the permadraw-chain/cat-toy.

description: Hand and fist crack with small roof in a dihedral.
Fist crack moves into an offwidth crack with a couple ledges.
location: The most direct line to the right of Gift of Life, wide crack up high should be visible.

description: A bit wandering, but the destination is clear: the arching fingertips crack in the alcove/roof area. Start up Off Width His Head (don't go up the steep fist crack though), moving left along ledges until you get to the base of that crack in the corner. Then enjoy the sharp, thin crack with smeary feet and a cool roof. Pull out onto the vertical and the climbing eases up a bit to the anchors.
location: Left of Off Width His Head. Look for the thin crack that arches up to the left.
protection: Lots of small cams! I think I used (camalot sizes) .1(2), .2, black totem, .3(2), .4(2), .5, green c3, #3 (maybe that big cam at the beginning).

description: Start with Off Width His Head, then step left at the large ledge (after the fist crack), following 4 bolts up. Tricky beta-intensive sequence gets you past overhanging bulge onto the slabby finish. Cool route!
protection: .5, 3 camalot size for start. Then 4 bolts. Two bolt anchor.

description: Up a dihedral on non-confidence inspiring rock up to the much better band of rock featuring a rightward trending crack.
location: Starts at dihedral to the right of Step or Stone, Breath or Bone.
20 feet right of Offwidth His Head.

description: This route lies directly beneth the barbed wire fence line that runs atop the butte. Starts slabby with thin hands, to a big ledge, then fingers and lieback up the crack to a stemmy finish. Two bolt anchor at top. Watch out for barbed wire when grabbing the top.
location: 10 feet right of Red Cloud Crack.

description: Balance will you get you to the top of this interesting line, A line with a great view
location: Secreat Area

description: Chimney climb with few solid foot holds. It's fairly difficult to smear so be prepared to use your upper body.
location: The route is just to the right of the Right Crack.
protection: The fence posts at the summit can be used as top rope anchors.

description: Twin cracks at the start. The crux is 3/4 of the way up.
protection: Fence posts are at the summit and they can be used as anchors.

description: Twin cracks at the start are available on this route for solid toe jams and fingers. There is a rose bush growing in a crack half way up the route. Be aware of this so you don't grab onto it and get a fistful of thorns. This route may have been the first toprope ever done in North Dakota back in 1994.
location: Left-hand side of the butte near the center.
protection: Fence posts at the summit for TR anchors.

description: Somewhat easy route route that moves right. Some loose rock up top. Rock is pretty soft and I suspect cams would likely rip out.
location: It is to the right of the obvious corner on the left side of the formation. Just look at the picture.
protection: Two fence posts on top for anchors

description: Sit start on left side of rock face and work your way up and right to top out. Great jugs are easy to find, but beware of chossy pieces that can make it more difficult.
location: Back side of the boulder if facing the road.

description: Start on the right side of the left (if facing road) part of Gronk and use the right arete for feet. Avoid using the north (right) part of Gronk to make the route more fun/ challenging.
location: Right side of left half (south side) of Gronk.

description: Start with your hands in almost a compression move with the right in the divot on its side and left along the edge of the south west face. Get your feet into the depression about a foot up and extend up to catch the sloping right side of the edge for the crux. Anyone under 5' 10" might have to dyno it. Get your feet and pull up from there for the topout.
location: Route runs up the south edge of the rock.

Park in the big gravel patch just north-west of the easternmost (smaller) radio tower. Squeeze through the very cool narrow slot chimney and downclimb a few 4th class moves to get to the base of the cliff (alternately, scramble down the scree a little further west), then follow the wall about 30 feet east.

description: Fun crack climb with sketchy placements.
location: The crack is located about 10 ft. left of Unknown 5.8.
protection: Standard traditional rock.  Top rope possible if you have trad gear to set up an anchor.  Weak rock that could easily result in gear pulling out during a fall.

description: Start standing, and dyno for a big jug. Pretty crumbly so be careful. Could be sat start, but would be hard due to bad rock.
location: Get to it by going to the second pile or rocks(the main pile), its right across from the big cave in the enclosure like area. It is kinda its own boulder. Top out and walk down backside.

description: Fun little overhanging v-shaped rock. Start sitting at the base with one hand out on the outside and one in the inside and work up to a big move to the lip.
location: Right off the road in the middle of the two main boulder piles.

description: Sandstone with rock that breaks off easily, top rope anchors should be inspected.
location: On the arete to the left of Hell's Heaven
protection: Top rope anchors over the top of the climb.  Check thoroughly before using

description: A tricky opening sequence leads to plenty of crimping fun. Easier toward top.
location: bolt line to the right of Hell's Heaven. This one has regular bolt hangers (or maybe it was glue-ins), Hell's Heaven has cold shuts as the hangers.

description: A sustained vertical finger crack with the occasional hand jam and face hold to shake out on. Fun and pumpy for the area.
location: On the south-facing side of the main (western) summit, near where the power lines run off the top and directly south of the first "main" building and propane tank you see upon arriving at the top of the Butte.
protection: Thin finger to hand-size cams and a few nuts. There is a pair of old quarter-inch buttonhead bolts at the top missing hangers, presumably installed by the first ascensionist(s).

description: Sandstone route.  Not the most exciting, but you're in ND.
location: To the right of the arete containing Unknown 5.8.
protection: 5 bolts and top anchors.  If leading, inspect the anchors thoroughly before use.

description: Chicken wing and smear your way up the fifteen foot vertical section before pulling the roof using jugs and stems. Cruise to the top.
location: On the south-facing side of the main (western) summit, near where the power lines run off the top and directly south of the first "main" building and propane tank you see upon arriving at the top of the Butte.

description: Fun route. Route stays a little left of the bolts. Good anchors up top
location: Bolts to the R of the Great Roof

description: Start with your feet on the ground and right jand hand jammed between the boulder and rock next to it. Use the jam to move up and try and keep in it for as long as you can.
location: On the north west side of the boulder. Starting in the rockpile.

description: Worm your way up.
Stand start matched on jugs below the right arete. Make a few moves up to the arete and then rock over onto the slab. V1 or V2 depending on how far up the arete you climb before exiting.
location: Park in the area labeled "alternate parking" and walk east to scramble off the top of the butte. Walk along the base of the butte with the wall on your right and this is the first problem you will see. On the arete to the right of Beat the Champ.

Park in the area labeled "alternate parking" and walk east to scramble off the top of the butte. Walk along the base of the butte with the wall on your right. Beat the Champ is just to the left of Grudge Match, climbing the center of tallest section of the block.

description: Right trending line on the Would You Rather Boulder
location: Would you Rather Boulder

description: Left trending route on the Would You Rather Boulder
Start as low as you dare on the overhanging face and make several very powerful moves on wide pinches into the start of Viagra.
location: The center of the obvious overhanging face on the boulder directly north (downhill) of the spire.

description: Start on the two best pinches you can find at the top of the overhanging section and throw to the ledge over the lip. Make a few easier moves through an incut sidepull and a flat jug to rock up onto the slab.
location: The center of the obvious overhanging face on the boulder directly north (downhill) of the spire.

description: Work your way up the left-ish side of the slab using interesting holds. A sit start adds a couple fun moves without changing the grade.
location: The west face of the tall boulder just to the west of the spire.

description: Start as low as you can in the crack to the left of Viagra and work your way up the detached block. This problem would probably warrant another star if it wasn't so low to the ground.
location: Just to the left of Viagra, deep in the crack.

description: Stick to the obvious crack system using hand and fist jams.
location: The obvious crack on the only face that looks worth climbing.
The prominent prow on the north side of the Moai boulder.
protection: A couple pads and a spotter to keep you from tumbling down the hill.

description: Climb up the face to the right of The Nose using a pinch, slopey edges and a shallow two finger pocket. Top out on slopers.
location: North-west face of the Moai boulder.
protection: A couple pads and a spotter.

description: SDS with your left hand on a good rail and your right on a blocky side-pull. Move up and right through the "turnbuckle" using a nice selection of crimps, pinches and slopers. Top out on jugs. Scrunchy feet make the first few moves (crux) a bit awkward.
location: Right side of the west face of the Turnbuckle boulder.

description: SDS with your left hand on a good rail and your right on a blocky side-pull. Move up through the left side of the sloping "turnbuckle", either making a big move up to the dunker hole or a slightly smaller move to a pretty good rounded ledge. Top out on jugs.
location: Middle/right side of the west face of the Turnbuckle boulder.
The obvious face on the A-Frame boulder.
protection: A pad or two and a spotter.

description: SDS with your left hand on a sloping ledge and your right on a good flat edge/pinch. Make a few moves directly up the face, avoiding the jugs to the left.
location: Left side of the west face of the Turnbuckle boulder.

description: Sit start on the left near the lower corner edge, come up to longer stretch, traverse to lever up and top out.
Bring your machete and get ready for some bush wackin'
location: Right of Paradox Left of Sketchy Toasty
protection: Enough room for a crash pad

description: Climb the face or use the tree for a nice chimney effect.
location: To the Right of Mary, directly behind a tree

description: Couldn't be any closer to the road, but its the second tallest route in the area.
location: To the right of Paradox and Left of Morning Butter

description: No good holds in the middle of the face
location: Tree route is to the left
protection: Enough room for a crash pad or two

description: Avoid the bush in the middle of the route and climb to the right of it.
location: to the right of Ribeye and left of Wacker

description: Nice and easy warm up
location: First route when coming from the parking area, to the right of Sketchy Toasty
protection: Enough room for a crash pad

description: Enough area for a good sized crash pad, definite high ball problem with a roof at the very top
location: Look for Mary Magdalene, First good route you see when you turn on South 245th off West Q Road
protection: Crash Pad, maybe set up a top rope on the trees?

description: A simple and enjoyable fun problem
location: Start on the stepping stool ledge in the middle of wall at the base, over and up to the left.

description: At the start, crimpy moves in the thin crack, side Layback, Pockety. The mantle move into the lower shelf, was difficult using left elbow/arm, search for Good right hand, not much available. Up to honeycomb section with lots of little finger grabs and balanced moves gains. Up to roof, traversing to the anchor. My first ascent, ode to daughter, first and only.
location: Giant Z formation. To the left of O wall. Facing same direction as Christ Died. Thin crack to right above what now looks like ‚ÄúBlue Grunks‚Äù spray paint.

description: Start with right hand on side pull crimp and left hand in a gaston palm to top out. Climbing shoes not necessary
location: At the top south side of Nippert Stadium off of CCM Blvd. There are two curved brick structures here. This route is on the eastern curve facing the stadium further away from "Climb Crimps, Man" if you're walking from there.

description: Start the same as Pip Squeak but top out early using the undercling rail on the slab just beneath the chip.
location: Same start as Pip Squeak.

description: Fun little powerful problem. Often referred to as "That undercling problem" because of the powerful first move to an undercling. Start with a bad right hand crimp on the arete, and a left hand side pull crimp way down low. Throw a series of powerful moves to the lip generally following the arete, and top out.
location: On the left arete of the Triangle Slab boulder, starting under the little overhang on it. The boulder rests just upstream of "Dr. Jones", but down stream from "Fortune and Glory".

description: Start on small crimp left of the main arete with good foot. Make hard reach to good rail, then hike your feet up and continue to the top.
location: On the Snake Eyes boulder, left of the main arete where "Snake Eyes" tops out.

description: Begin on the same hold as "Steel Head", and work right, beginning with a big move. Power through sloping ledges and some big moves to be rewarded with a juggy top out.
location: On the Spider Dojo boulder, which is slightly uphill from the trail, approx. 50 yards uphill of the river. Upstream from "The Pharaoh", downstream from the Snake Eyes boulder.

description: Start on the same hold as "Temple of Hank", the sloping jug on the far left side of the boulder. Power straight up through some committing moves on holds that take some skin, with a balancy move just before the lip.
location: On the Spider Dojo boulder, which is slightly uphill from the trail, approx. 50 yards uphill of the river. Upstream from "The Pharaoh", downstream from the Snake Eyes boulder.

description: Start way back in the little cave on the farthest jug on the left (often slimy). Work out a jug shelf to some tough compression moves getting over the bulge. Juggy top out.
location: On the Spider Dojo boulder, which is slightly uphill from the trail, approx. 50 yards uphill of the river. Upstream from "The Pharaoh", downstream from the Snake Eyes boulder.

description: Start on some gastons just right of the right side arete of the boulder. continue up the arete using sparse holds on the face to eventually reach the top of the triangle. Top out.
location: On the right arete of the triangle slab boulder. The boulder rests just upstream of "Dr. Jones", but down stream from "Fortune and Glory".

description: Start down and right on the lowest jug. Work up and left through a series of jug and sloper shelves to top out at the arete all the way on the left.
location: First boulder you come across on the walk in.

description: Direct start to Fortune and Glory. Start on two sidepulls below the cool ledge feature. The left hand is almost always wet and slimy. Work up to the ledge/ rail feature, then finish up Fortune and Glory.
location: On the hike to boulders farther downstream. Upstream from Triangle Slab boulder, but downstream from the Spider Dojo boulder.

description: A great problem, but very height dependent, and poor rock quality. Start at the base of the block, and use compression to get to the obvious jug shelf on the left. Bail onto that shelf if you don't want a high top out, or continue to the top for the full problem.
location: One of the most uphill problems, yet a very obvious block shaped boulder with graffiti letters spelling "SAMO" on it. Slightly downstream and uphill of the Spider Dojo boulder.

description: Start left on a sloping shelf, and work right through a cool ledge feature, topping out up a sequential shield, awesome movement!
location: On the hike to boulders farther downstream. Upstream from Triangle Slab boulder, but downstream from the Spider Dojo boulder.

description: Start matched on the far right small crimp rail. Work left past some sharp holds with bad feet and high tension heel hooks. Use the arete all the way on the left to top out.
location: One of the last boulders you come across. The problem faces the river and sits atop another boulder. Just upstream from "The Art of Zen", and just downstream from the triangle shaped slab boulder.
protection: Pads (maybe have someone there to watch that they don't slide into the river).

description: Start as far back as you can in the roof like overhang on a jug (your feet might be over the river). Work through great jug shelves to a reachy crux just below the lip. Easy top out.
location: The most downstream route you'll probably go to. A boulder or two downstream from Dr. Jones and the triangle slab boulder. Right on the river.
protection: Pads (watch that they don't slide into the river).

location: Main line on The Little Hard boulder

description: Hug the corner and use the square metal plates as feet. One move to the left and top out. Do not use the white bit on the bottom left (see image).
location: By the white door next to "Touchdown"

description: Start with wide legs¬†and climb up to the same topout as "Climb Crimps, Man". Do not use the south-facing wall/corner with feet or hands (see image).
location: Same as "Climb Crimps, Man", in the Northwest end of CCM circle by the wall that says "Robert J. Werner".

description: Mini slopers and side pulls to top out. Good texture. There is the eponymous rainbow orca on the opposite side of the wall that you top out on and a not-so-fun chossy chimney climb that's probably not worth it.
location: Bottom of the DAAP parking lot on the westernmost side. Walk or drive down Clifton Court, enter the garage, take the stairs all the way down, and walk left. Top of route is visible from the road. This route is about 1 minute walking due west from the UC Mountaineering Club store room.

description: Start with a right hand on the bomber corner and use either of the crimpy rails to shimmy feet up and top out. Quite fun for how short it is. Climbing shoes not necessary
location: In the courtyard just below New Chemistry in the Zimmer Roof Garden

description: Sit start underneath as low as possible on either side and traverse left or right to top out, be careful of the low risk but long fall on either side of the top out. The only boulder to use a metal structure on campus (the handrail for the top out), climbing shoes not necessary
location: By the triangular-prism skylight windows in the Zimmer Roof Garden, sort of nearby the front entrance of Baldwin and behind the Old Chemistry building

description: Dihedral turns into a narrow chimney climb and top out. Start with low feet for a couple starting slab moves or jump and slap your foot right up into the windowsill. Fun and consistent route with a little flaking towards the middle to watch out for.
location: Off the right side of Clifton Court on the Western face of the Geology-Physics building, right around the corner from "Clover"

description: Crimps and side pulls lead to a very fun, body tension-reliant deadpoint and topout. One of the most dynamic and satisfying boulders around campus
location: The northernmost line of the outside of Corry Garage on Dennis Street. Near the baseball field.

description: Sit start at the bottom of the stairs, climb underneath, traverse the bridge, find feet + a crimp on the wall, and dyno to top out. Use the fence for V1 (climbing shoes not necessary) or don't for V3
location: On the inside of the stairs next to the Southern entrance to CECH. Right off of McMicken Circle and Clifton Ave

description: This is a classic to campus. It's a super consistent and diverse line that takes a bit of solving. There is a chalk drawing of a clover on the route and "CLOVER" written so I guessed that was the name. If you FA'd this boulder or have climbed it please comment!
location: On the Westernmost part of the tunnel under the Geology-Physics building just off Clifton Court

description: Quarter pad crimps to top out
location: Near the big brown artificial tree trunk in the Northwest of CCM circle. There is a big wall ornament that says "Robert J Werner Recital Hall" that makes this route pretty easy to find (see image).

description: Go up the letters. Top out provides a nice view but can be quite wet if it has rained recently. Easily doable barefoot, street shoes will be a challenge, pad recommended
location: Right off MLK Dr., across from DAAP, just outside of Burnet Woods

description: Start with both hands under the pool window to a shouldery press, make your way under the overhang and come out the other side for a nice top out. One of my favorites for its minimal features and technique dependency. Can do without climbing shoes, but probably not with street shoes
location: Near CRC circle attached to the rec on Main Street

description: Start standing as low as you can and monkey up the proudest boulder-esque face on campus and top out. Climbing shoes not necessary, pad recommended
location: In the middle of Main Street on campus attached to the rec center. Just up the hill from "Campus Recreation"

description: Start and end in a sit start and move from the outside of the East side of the semicircle to the opposing side using any holds and feet (no walking up the pillars, obviously). Kind of a dumb traverse, but it's just something to do if you're over by this polylith for the other climbs.
location: Right off MLK Dr., across from DAAP, just outside of Burnet Woods

description: Very similar route to "Rainbow Orca" but more accessible from the road + slightly worse holds and a slightly more challenging topout. Don't use the garage lettering
location: On the right side of the front face of Clifton Court Garage

description: Refrigerator climb to the top, don't use the pillars to the left and right. Top out provides a nice view but can be quite wet if it's rained recently. There is a structure at the bottom of this one that's impossible to pad, so be cautious because a shallow fall could be dangerous.
location: Right off MLK Dr., across from DAAP, just outside of Burnet Woods

description: Chimney climb to a corner crimp and pull hard till your feet touch. Traverse slab right and climb over. Climbing shoes not necessary, barefoot falls can hurt
location: In the front of the College of Law right off of Clifton Ave. To the left of the stairway kind of hidden behind some shrubbery
protection: Probably don't need anything for this one but there is an opposing face you don't want to slam into if you slip on the slab part

route_name: Z's Go with the Flo Traverse

first_ascent: Unknown (assume its been climbed before; not on MP; Jim Arnold did it 7/3/2020)
location: Just inside the obvious gap/chimney about 40 meters south of the Padua crack. Start is at the base of the chimney, 2-3 feet in (just at the end of the roof to the south and with the roof to the north right behind you).
protection: TR; anchor to the solid tree above; pass your master point through the brush at the edge of the cliff to a small but identifiable indent 2-3 feet in from the point; mossy on top, use rope protector.

description: Coming up into the honey comb section, is a search to find your schmearin and holds
location: Red rocks start, cruise up to the anchor, right side of tree, slight reverse waterfall, starting about 2 feet out.

description: See New Wave Mang. Hang way left past the edge of Z and circle around the upper Wave to anchor. Winner
location: New Wave Mang start, wide left hook variation

first_ascent: Unknown (assume it's been climbed before; not on MP; Chris Reynolds did it 7/3/2020; if anyone has info on earlier ascents/names, please update!)
location: Between Slippery When Wet and Padua wall crack. Start ~8' to the south of the chimney, next to the log (see photo; unless attempting to boulder the cave/roof). Direct would be straight up from the north edge of the first ledge. Traverse starts 5-6' to the south onto the second ledge. Spoiler alert/beta tip on the traverse: scrunch down to get around the initial overhanging bit when moving left/north.
protection: TR; anchor to the solid tree at the top

description: Nice n‚Äô easy walk up the big blocks, gaining a couple easy finger jugs for lift to some balanced footwork. NBD
location: Following the easy access of the exposed corners bottom rocks, up to the bottom corner of the Z, staying about 12 inches to the left of anchor

description: Sit start matched on the undercling. Boulder up and as far left as possible without dragging on the detached boulder beneath. Heel hooking through the crux will gain you slopers and the first ledge. Step up onto the face and traverse left of the arete. Pump your way to the top.
location: Locate the large overhang to the left of Blue Grunks.
protection: Traditional anchor built on the tree for Blue Grunks

description: Smooth traverse along rail of pockets.  Keep from swinging and you are fine.
location: Middle of Right boulder.  SDS on low bulge, working to the left along obvious rail.  Staying to the right of large crack.

description: crux midway,bomber pockets,really clean thru the climb but dirty top out.in the picture it looks dirty but its clean and dry.
location: second set of boulders on the edge of the first.

description: Low start to an already established dyno, super burly and shouldery moves up to the ledge where the dyno leads to a relatively easy top out.
location: Just to the right of Pvt Benjamin
protection: At least one pad and a good spot, two or three pads if you're climbing solo

description: Starts on the dry corner most climbers prefer on this rock.  Lots of good holds and a fun climb.  Start in the same holds as Dirty Blond (1a) and finishes a little right of Dirty Blonde (1a).  Fun climb and another easy top off.
Follow the rightward leaning pillar until it ends and then send the face.
location: Far left side of the small bluff to the left of the Amphitheater Boulder.
protection: Standard traditional rack if you are feeling it, can also be top roped.

description: Begin on the ar√™te on friendly holds. Follow the ar√™te to about half way, then move out right about 1 foot and finish from there. Very nice pocket climbing, reminds me of Wild Iris
location: Right side, about 1 foot off the main ar√™te at the Ampitheater Boulder. Yellow route from beta photo
The crack that runs up the center of the Amphitheater Boulder. Look for the rusty piton.
protection: Standard traditional rack "not recommended to be lead"

description: Climb the shaded left side of the ar√™te. The route is loaded with amazing limestone holds, but still has a lot of black dirt on it. I cleaned it as best as I could..... Hence the name...
location: Shady side of the Ampitheater Boulder Ar√™te.

description: Overhung side of Frathouse Rock.  Big moves on great holds.  Fun short problem.  Very good chance it is wet.
location: Boulder is left of grass lot entrance.  Center of overhung face.  Eye level pockets just left of golf ball start you up direct line.

description: Easy climb with slight cheese grading possibility.  We've seen many douchbags climb this with tennis shoes.  Problem is located on the rear-right corner.  Easy start and easy climb.  The height is a little sketchy due to the angle of the rock face.

This is a good warm up located on Frathouse Rock.  It's on the dry corner most people like to climb.  Start with both hands on the undercling.  For the easier start, start above the undercling in the finger pockets on the right and side-pull on the left.  Work your way to the top.  This is an easy top off.
Techy short problem. Can be done several ways to make it easier or harder.
location: From grass entrance: Right boulder, west corner (white face of rock) SUS on crimps chest high.  Works right to easy top-out.

description: Overhung start to bulge crux.  Typical problem for Veteran's Park.
location: Right boulder, southeast corner. SDS on ledge far east side of overhang face.

description: Start as low as possible on the arete. Climb it till it ends and top out.
location: The Big Easy Boulder.

description: Start low on the arete and climb it till it runs out. Avoid stepping onto the slab when topping out. Tops out just to the right of Slam Dunk.
location: Sloping arete on The Anvil Boulder.

description: Same start as Unnamed #1 branch left on the sloping side pull with a heel hook. Latch a two finger crimp scoop with your left hand and get to the ledge directly above the left hand.
The route is on Yellow Wall in the center. Sit start on the ledge and go straight up a series of crimps. The problem ends right beneath the capped roof. It will almost always have chalk on it.

first_ascent: Unknown (assume it's been climbed before; not on MP; Chris Reynolds 8/9/2020)
description: Start is at the base of the honeycomb. Possibly two cruxes: first is the large hump in the middle of the route, second is the overhung finish. The hump *may* require a small dyno to pass the top off some small-ish crimps and a sidepull on the left. The overhang at the top has some semi-decent hands, though the slots are pitched slightly downward toward the front.
location: Face directly to the left of the dihedral; between the dihedral edge and the twin flakes.
protection: Large trees directly above for setting static line

first_ascent: Unknown (assume it's been climbed before; not on MP; Chris Reynolds and Jim Arnold climbed it 8/9/2020)
description: Start is from the left (south) side of the off-width crack. Good hands and feet through the traverse to the left (north) under the "wave" overhang. Crux is the finish, which is over the ceiling. Not sure the grade is right yet; please provide feedback!
location: Around the corner after passing the large, lichen-covered slab due south of Owl's Eyes/Shooting Star. There is "FISH" spray painted at the base right next to a large off-width crack
protection: There are several large trees at the top to set static lines

description: Been enjoying a mix of small finger pockets and pinches, with crimps. Vary em up.

Start about 3-4 feet to the right of the corner for a nice start with an easy jug. As you're moving up, start easing yourself towards the arete using sidepulls and crimps till you get to the crack near the top, where it's a smooth finish.
location: To the right and around the corner from the boulder problems on the Yellow Wall.
protection: Two small trees near the edge for an easy, but not as good, anchor setup, or a 2 foot diameter tree pretty far back from the edge for a bomber anchor.

description: Start on lowest holds on face. Climb obvious line of weakness through jugs and sidepulls, making a fun move to the large round hold before topping out.
location: On the face of The Anvil Boulder

description: Start low with a right hand on a small knob and a left on the slopey feature. Make a few smeary moves up the slab avoiding the holds on the surrounding aretes.
location: On the slab on the right side of The Anvil boulder.

description: Start under the roof with your left hand in the pocket and your right out on the arete. Either make a huge move out right to get higher on the arete, then shoot for the megapocket, or just go all out and chuck for the megapocket from the start. Try not to dab on the tree.
location: Under the roof on the left side of The Anvil boulder.

description: Start with feet low and hands matched on the jug circled. Good crimps and jugs take you up to a shelf, where you can mantle to a finish.
location: This boulder is between Beer Can Alley and Christ Died Area. It is just a few steps uphill from the lower trail.

description: Start with stemming feet and finding wider hand jams. Intermittent holds for hands and feet allow you to choose to jam or stay out on the face while you take your pick of textbook placements. Mantle onto the large ledge and then choose whether to continue up right or left to a large healthy tree for anchor building. Cord or long slings are useful here.
location: Hike South a short distance from Beer Can Alley and Cigarettes After Sex. Find PADUA chiseled in the face. This crack is located 20ft or so South of the PADUA tag.
protection: #2-#3 cams. Large healthy tree at the top.

location: Downhill side of the chez-toes bolder

description: ..It's v0. There isn't much of a crux. Pull up, cheating left or right is.. well, cheating.
location: First boulder after walking South from Beer Can Alley. There are some racial slurs spray painted on the rock .. cannot miss it.

description: Straight forward warm up lap option to start your climbing session. Top is approximately 18 feet off the deck. FA done without any protection (no crash pad). Horizontal shelf holds are numerous, positive, and provide several warm up options for practice. Top out mantle can get the heart pumping a bit for those not used to runout.
location: On the East Face of the Mini-Island (i.e. the uphill side, northeast of Many Faces). The route is the farthest to the climber's right.
protection: Pad recommended, but not necessary. Just be careful if free soloing it.

description: Start on 2 pinches underneath the overhang. Reach out and pull on to the face to start working your way left and as low as possible.. staying off the jug rails overhead. Cross, pinch, and crimp your way to the top of the ledge to finish.
location: Low right start of many faces

description: Start with jugs on the face. Climb diagonally up and left through a small split to reach the ledge finish.
location: Overhanging boulder start of Many Faces
protection: Multiple pads would be nice as the landing is rocky

description: Right of Dunes
location: Start 10‚Äô right of Dunes, just left of an obvious left facing corner. Angle up and left, staying right of the holds on Dunes.
protection: Top Rope, long slings needed. One of the longest setups at Whips Ledges, with the challenge of wrestling Greenbriar included.  If set correctly, Dunes can be climbed from this anchor.

location: Just Right of the Phantom Fifth.

description: Mind crux for the newb...
Start on pockets mostly to the right of the wall.  Ascend directly to the high ledge.  Traverse the full length to the left.
location: Right side of the sandbox.
protection: A spotter who will move your pad as your traverse would be nice.

description: Start on large sidepull in the middle of the wall.  Line is straight up to the right most portion of the mid-wall ledge system.  Traverse left along the ledge around the corner to descend.  Crux move is the last lunge to the jugs on the ledge off of two crimps with high feet.
location: West face of the island.

description: Straddle the arete all the way to the finish horn using pockets and edges.  Crux revolves around a small sidepull/pocket on the left side of the arete.  Descend off to the left.
location: Corner defining the left end of the sandbox.

description: Getting up onto and into the second slabby part, was a little rounded down, proved to be a little slippery and not easy at times to find a hand hold. ¬†In the flat face in the mid section, delicate mono finger pockets and balanced moves gains. Fun running the side crack to the roof. Finding a decent hooked traverse along the roof, down climbing into the short left crack, was an easy enough down. Run it back. Have fun!
location: Standing at main wall looking at island, follow right down corridor, to wall of island on your left/right of the island. Obvious roof above. Island needs solo from opposite side, with ability to rappel.

description: Start about 5‚Äô right of The Arete. Start on easier ground to a hard crux just left of the left most vertical crack on Sandy Ledges. Steeper rock takes you to the top.
location: Blank looking section (about 1/2 way up) between The Arete and the left most vertical crack on Sandy Ledges.
protection: TR. There are 3 newer looking bolts (use your own judgement) over the edge on top of the Island that can be used to set up this climb and Sandy Ledges.

location: Facing Sandy Ledges, walk to your right to the right corner of the Island. Turn 180 degrees and you will be facing The Orgator.
Located between the Arete and the Sandbox, closer to the Sandbox than The Arete.
protection: A cool head and someone with a cell phone if you spit off. I've rescued a few from this acent over the years.

description: Perfect hand jams take you up to a ledge. Traverse left and mantle over a block to finish.
location: Find "Runnin' Laps on the Island - Turn around 180* and take a few steps uphill.
protection: Standard Rack. Nothing established at the top.

description: A Hinckley Classic. Start on slab, move slightly right to a face, then slightly back left to an overhanging face. A horizontal leg jam gives you a rest before the difficult finishing moves.
location: Facing Sandy Ledges, walk to your right. Go around the corner of the Island. Dunes starts about 25‚Äô right of the corner.
protection: Top Rope, long slings needed. One of the longest setups at Whips Ledges, with the challenge of wrestling Greenbriar included. Worth the trouble. If set correctly, Scarpa can be climbed from this anchor.

description: Pull the bulge, walk it up, pull multiple roofs. :) Multiple variations.
location: Start twelve foot right of Ape Traverse.
protection: Top rope. Anchors consist of (2) 6 " wave bolts (installed in 2018) and (1) 8" twist bolt (installed in 2019) going through layered rock. Use your own judgement, you may want to back these up. The anchors are located on top of the island about 10' back from the edge. They can be difficult to see.

description: Climb The Arete until you are able to step out onto the overhanging face left. Pinch and pull on pockets up and right until you reach the split. Pump through the roof to finish at the anchor shown. 5 pull-ups on the final hold.
location: Start on The Arete. Be mindful of birds‚Äô nests throughout.
protection: Anchors at the top. Long webbing is useful here.

location: Find the side of the Island that faces the Main Wall. The Arete is on the left side of this wall.
protection: Top rope. There is a tree that sets back about 3‚Äô at the top of this route with a chain around it. Place the anchor over the edge in a spot that reduces the  possibility of hitting the large tree growing close to the route.

description: Climb up to a left facing corner, up to the roof. Traverse left, cutting your feet loose if you like, which is where the route get it‚Äôs name. Finish in the small slot at the top.
location: Start 10‚Äô right of Scarpa. Climb up to a left facing corner, up to the roof. Traverse left, cutting your feet loose if you like, which is where the route get it‚Äôs name. Finish in the small slot at the top.
protection: TR is hard to set up for this one. Most of the route can be climbed from the Double O anchors with the chance of a pretty good swing if you come off high. After the ape traverse, go back right and avoid the big swing.

first_ascent: Some old Ohio climber since reloc to Cali
description: Originally done in converse.
location: This starts on the left side of the sandbox, has the right / left hand flake, runs up and up to the top of the Island until it is possible to walk off  left.

description: Best done in the fall with low humidity, wind and lower temperatures. Good Luck!
location: Between Snoopy and Buzzard. Hard bouldery start takes you to 2 pockets that are close together. Then thin moves, to more thin moves...
protection: Top Rope, long slings needed. If set up correctly, one rope can cover Buzzard also.

description: Can be climbed on brittle pockets out right or more fun, but slightly more challenging face on the left.
location: To the right of Double Layback Crack

description: White slightly overhanging face.
location: Left side of the arete that has Keyhole Crack.

description: High traverse tending left of the crack.
location: Start on the left side of the crack staying high. The feet of "Tall Man" consist of the hands that are typical on "Smart Woman."
protection: Strategically placed climbing pad(s) would be a good idea.

description: There are three variations, all Hinkley classics. Each has its own personality. Up and Left is hard. Up and Right is harder. Up and Up (straight) is somewhere in-between.
location: Start about 15‚Äô right from And Now for Something Completely Different(all three Snoopy routes start in the same place). Go straight up through Snoopy‚Äôs ear, then go right through some very thin moves requiring precision footwork.One more set of moves takes you to a good ledge, where it is wise to traverse left back to your sling anchor.

description: A nice way to occupy your time while waiting for your friends to arrive.
location: Start on the right side of the cave and traverse right. Go as far as you want, then traverse back to the cave.
protection: This traverse stays close to the ground, no protection needed.

description: There are three variations, all Hinkley classics. Each has its own personality. Up and Left is hard. Up and Right is harder. Up and Up (straight) is somewhere in-between.
location: Start about 15‚Äô right from And Now for Something Completely Different(all three Snoopy routes start in the same place). Go straight up through Snoopy‚Äôs ear, then keep going straight up to the top; using holds from Snoopy right with your right hand and Snoopy with your left hand.

description: There are three variations, all Hinkley classics. Each has its own personality. Up and Left is hard. Up and Right is harder. Up and Up (straight) is somewhere in-between.
location: Start about 15‚Äô right from And Now for Something Completely Different (all three Snoopy routes start in the same place). Go straight up through Snoopy‚Äôs ear, then angle left to a three finger pocket. Straight up takes you to the top.

description: Solid V2. Low traverse trending left of the crack.
location: Start low on the left side of the crack and work your way left, avoiding the huge "jugs" above you.
protection: This traverse stays close to the ground, no protection needed.

description: Short.
location: To the right of the Keyhole Crack is a blank looking face with a few slot like holds on it.

description: Same start as SALLY + DON. Use the letters. Reach up high to finish. Being tall is an advantage.
location: About 6‚Äô right of Flakes, SALLY + DON is carved in the rock, about 10‚Äô off the ground.

description: Same start as Flakes. With hands on top of the flake start traversing right to a vertical 2‚Äô slot about 4‚Äô above and slightly left of the S in SALLY. Move across this slot and reach up right to finish.
location: About 6‚Äô right of Flakes, SALLY + DON is carved in the rock, about 10‚Äô off the ground.

description: A nice flowing route using the right side of the crack as an arete.
location: Use the right side of The Crack as an arete. As long as one hand stays on the arete, anything to the right is on. Do not use the left side of the crack.
protection: A TR can be set up utilizing the Maple tree above and to the right of The Crack. Several routes can be climbed from this tree.

description: Well named.
location: Between the carving ‚ÄúSALLY + DON‚Äù and Double Layback Crack. Towards the top, reach for the sky!

description: Fun climb.
location: To the right of You Break It, You Break It, ¬†furthest route on the same unified cliff.

description: No specific crux, fun climb regardless.
location: Route right of Hate Route.  Locate an 8‚Äù feature that looks like South America, about 10‚Äô off the ground. The climb wanders through here.

description: Some unusual moves using the left side of the crack as an arete.
location: Use the left side of The Crack as an arete. As long as one hand stays on the arete, anything to the left is on. Do not use the right side of the crack.

description: The whole of the Land Arete.
location: Left if cave at main wall

description: Behind the tree in this photo. Plainly obvious in person.
location: Main wall, right of The Crack, just North of and left of the cave and offwidth.

description: Climb only the face avoiding The Land Arete Left off.
location: Left of the large offwidth at the cave, right of Beyond Patagonia. ‚ÄúNext line‚Äù.

description: Mostly blank and slightly slabby face to the left of the crack
location: Start is the same as for Keyhole Crack. Traverse left at first ledge to blank and slightly slabby face to the left of the crack. Left arete and crack edge are off. Start ascent of face using low left undercling and shallow slot to the right (at about shoulder height). Lots of lichen=slippery! Better hands on the way up. Top out using ‚Äúslopers‚Äù on upper ledge and mantling.

description: Obvious crack the splits the upper part of the wall. Towards the top of the crack there is a keyhole looking feature.
location: Right around the corner from Tina Turner.

description: Short but spicy.
location: First route on Main Wall. Walk down the stairs until you see ‚ÄúJC Bidle‚Äù carved into the wall on your left, about eye level. Start just right of this. You should see the initials J.B.N. carved into the rock about  8‚Äô  above the ground. There is a large Maple tree that marks the top of the route.
protection: Top Rope from the large Maple tree at the top of the route.

description: Several climbers have said ‚ÄúI hate this route‚Äù. It may go well one day and be trouble the next, until dialed. Nice variation with unique moves.
location: Same start as Burnout. After the start, go straight up avoiding the Burnout holds.
protection: A TR can be set up utilizing the Maple tree above and to the right of The Crack. Several routes can be climbed from this tree.

description: Short, fun climb.
location: To the right of Slots is rock with many groove like features in it.

description: Fun short climb.
Making sure your gear stays in the crux if you lead it .. otherwise it is smooth sailing.
location: Obvious double crack to the right of Reach for the Sky.

description: Crux varies for everyone until you have it dialed. A Hinckley Classic.
location: If you're walking along the prominent cliff, this is the Hinckley Crack / Crack ... you cannot miss it.
protection: TR or Gear. A TR can be set up utilizing the Maple tree above and to the right of The Crack. Several routes can be climbed from this tree.

description: Sweet problem / TR. The erosion has taken the ground and lowered it ~one foot.. your mileage may vary on getting started. Originally done via a running jump to the suit case handle. May need cleaning before climbing.
location: To the right of Patagonia the wall has a large split. To the right of the split is a small ‚Äúcave". Start the climb under where the crack splits the top part of the wall. One start is to stand on the rock to the left of the two slots under the roof, reach up and start in the slot. It‚Äôs not over after the roof is pulled.
protection: Pads / Spotters or a Rope (Ideally a double rope system.)

description: A low crux takes you to the thin but classic moves of Buzzard.
location: Immediately left of the Crack. Crack is off. Avoid the obvious 5‚Äù hole in the wall. Climb between the 5‚Äù hole and the crack to start, then finish on Buzzard.

description: Another Hinckley classic.
location: Left of the Crack. Crack is off. Start by heading straight for obvious 5‚Äù hole in the wall. Use the hole and go slightly right, then straight up. Remember to stay out of the crack!

description: Well named. A Hinckley Classic.
location: About 15‚Äô right of The Crack is a horizontal slot, about 2‚Äô long, at chest level. Start here and angle left toward the crack. Pass the crux and continue climbing right of The Crack. Near the top traverse right and finish to the right side of the tree. There are also nice finishes straight to the tree and between the tree and The Crack.
protection: A TR can be set up utilizing the Maple tree above and to the right of The Crack. Several routes can be climbed from this tree.

location: Next line of climbing after Beyond Patagonia

description: Lower half is smoother, upper got¬†pockets.
location: Next Routes just beyond Patagonia.

description: Great climbing, however it is wet most of the year due to water seepage from a seam about 3/4 of the way up the route. If it‚Äôs dry, jump on it while you can. The name comes from a banana shaped feature about 1/2 way up the wall.
location: Starts about 7‚Äô right from J.B.N.  Head straight up for a few moves then angle right until you are above and slightly left of the banana shaped feature. Crux move takes you to the top.
protection: Top Rope, long slings needed. If set up correctly, one rope can cover the three Banana routes and And Now for Something Completely Different.

description: Great climbing, however it is wet most of the year due to water seepage from a seam about 3/4 of the way up the route. If it‚Äôs dry, jump on it while you can. The name comes from a banana shaped feature about 1/2 way up the wall.
location: Starts about 6‚Äô right of Banana Left. Go straight up and then slightly right from the banana shaped feature to harder moves.
protection: Top Rope, long slings needed. If set up correctly, one rope can cover the three Banana routes and And Now for Something Completely Different.

description: Great climbing, however it is wet most of the year due to water seepage from a seam about 3/4 of the way up the route. If it‚Äôs dry, jump on it while you can. The name comes from a banana shaped feature about 1/2 way up the wall.
location: Same start as Banana Center. At the Banana shaped feature traverse right several feet to a whale shaped feature. A final hard move takes you to the top.
protection: Top Rope, long slings needed. If set up correctly, one rope can cover the three Banana routes and And Now for Something Completely Different.

route_name: And Now For Something Completely Different
description: Bouldery start to thin moves.
location: Start about 8‚Äô from the Banana. A bouldery start takes you to thin moves to a whale shaped feature. Finish on Banana
protection: Top Rope, long slings needed. If set up correctly, one rope can cover this and the three Banana routes.

description: Looking for deets/ratings opinions
location: Easy, take it to the heels¬†of the Giant, moving gracefully onto his back, reaching for the crown. Anything is good
First route about a foot and a half in to the right of the Arete. ¬†In the Many Faces Area

description: Sit for a bouldery start below the overhang. Pull out and up onto the face - this is the crux. Continue up good pinches and crimps staying to the right of the diagonal "zag" until you top out though the obvious V at the top of the rock.
location: This face is viewed from the lowest access trail and North of The Island by couple hundred feet or so.
protection: Two mid-sized trees at the top can be used for anchor building. Static rope or long slings / cord is useful here.

description: Looking for description/ratings proper
location: Under the handsome neck, prominent jawline and chin of man, creep past his downturned lip, past the high cheekbone to the temple and behind his revered Frog Hat!

description: Looking for/ratings.
location: Obvious boulder start, cause a burger hits you like one, creeping the edge, all condiments are on, till you reach the height of the grilled stack yo!

description: Looking for description and proper rating
location: Start at the mans feet, walking back and forth up the midline to and over his square face to top

description: Sit start, with one hand on each side of the bottom fin. Pull up the middle of the face, shifting to the left arete for the last move and top out mantle.
location: West (downhill) Face of the Shifting Sands Boulder. ¬†15 feet from the Mini-Island Northwest Arete.
protection: FA done with no pad. A pad would be helpful.

route_name: Red Gully (A Homage to Crestone Peak)
description: Fun, easy route. Sit start at left flaring splitter. Angle right into the hueco field in the horizontal crimson ribbon. Solid feet on positive ledges and good pockets. Climb through the notch up top as the wall tilts slights past vertical. Mantle on the top out. Excellent warm up route.
location: On the Western Wall. On the Right Side. At the Overt Gully (Notch) Access Point
Starts at the base of the Mini-Island's Northwest Arete.

description: Move laterally across the east face of the Mini-Island, half way up the wall. Initially done climber's right-to-left. Down climb southeast corner arete.
location: East face of Mini-Island. Traverse line is the middle lateral line.
protection: Spotters would be helpful near the end of the route.

description: Western Wall. Start on the Northwest Arete. Then move climber's left to right along the entire Western Wall, and onto the South Face. Start on the crimson rock band - balance with poor hands but great feet on the ledge. At mid-wall-point, transition to good huecos, with feet on small ledges. Work over to the Southwest Arete on slopers and wrap onto the facade of the South Face ledge system. Then finish up to the top of the ledge on the mini-upward-right-flaring-dihedral.
location: Mini-Island > Western Wall > traverse entire wall from the Northwest Arete (on climber's left) to the Southwest Arete, onto the facade of the south wall ledge and finish up the mini-dihedral.

description: Sit start on left flaring splitter. Work up to a left handed 2 finger pocket, and throw to a right handed 2 finger lock. Gain one of the small ledges on the left. Finish with a right handed throw to the horn. High step and mantle finish. Red Gully holds are off.
location: Mini-Island > Western Wall > middle of wall > 2 feet to the left of Red Gully

description: Same start as Journey to the Sun, second move goes straight up instead of dyno right.
Start wherever (low) and slap high. Rock has the etching of "Swingles" on it at the base of Journey and Ultimate Journey.
The slab of Moonlight Buttress.
protection: A cool head if your a Bunky?

description: The wetness.
location: Large overhanging chalked up face.

description: Start under the middle of the roof of this beauty with 2 jugs and feet down low. Keep your back off the pads while you work out and up onto crimps and slopers to finish.
location: Follow a trail downhill from Fingertips. If it is grown over as it often is, backtrack the lower trail less than 50 feet to cut left and pick up another trail. Continue downhill and slightly right to find this gem.

description: Not hitting the rocks on the ground when the rock breaks on you.
location: Starts way to the left of the roof, working the overhanging roof towards Cigarettes After Sex. Finishes on the top, working towards the off width crack.

description: An easy slab problem that goes straight up the middle of the face. Name?
location: Boulder right behind Owl‚Äôs Eyes.

description: Variety of boulder problems on Sunshine‚Äôs backside.
location: Face the ‚ÄúCHRIST DIED‚Äù carving and turn 180 degrees. About 20‚Äô in front of you is the Sunshine Boulder. The Sunshine routes are on the slab on the far side of the boulder. The boulder problems facing you are considered Sunshine‚Äôs Backside.

description: Three common variations: Left Sunshine goes at about 5.9, Center variation 5.10b,  Right variation 5.6 or easier.
location: Face the ‚ÄúCHRIST DIED‚Äù carving and turn 180 degrees. About 20‚Äô in front of you is the Sunshine Boulder. The Sunshine routes are on the slab on the far side of the boulder. (The boulder problems facing you are considered Sunshine‚Äôs Backside.)

description: The moss.. clean the moss. Try and climb it. Come back when it is dry. Clean the moss.
location: Starts at the arete on slopers and traverse the slopers to the top!
protection: A brush, preferably not the steel variety.

description: Start the Old Man's Variation low and left by matching on a jug and planting a left toe. Stay low while traversing right until the right edge of the boulder is within reach. Reach for the large and obvious bucket to pull over the top.

This is the longest trad route we have found at Whipps.¬† Start on an overhanging, usually wet, crack on the main corner left of Christ Died.¬† Once through the overhang, delicately traverse about 10' to the right then up a fun 5.6/5.7 hand crack to top out.¬† This route is pretty fun, and when combined in a day with leading the Hinckley Crack and Christ Died Crack makes a good day of cragging for a trad leader.¬† Note: we haven't been able to dig up any FA info other than ours, please let us know if you have been leading this route for years!
location: See photos.¬† This is the main corner left of Christ Died when facing the main Christ Died Crack.¬† From Christ Died walk slightly down the hill past the downed tree to the corner where the entire wall turns direction.¬† You should see an overhanging 15-20' section of cracks then 10' right up higher another 15-20' of larger hand crack to the top.
protection: Full set of cams from 0.75 to 3.  Beware the first 20' as the crack is slippery when wet (usually wet) and may spit out cams!

description: Follow crack to top
location: Just right of Christ Died Arete.

description: Named because the series of pockets towards the top of the wall looked like a shooting star. Climb face to top.
location: Face just around the corner from Christ Died Wall.

description: Boulder problem that starts in the low pockets of "O" wall and traverses right to a large sloping pocket. Using an undercling pocket continue straight up through small crimps and pockets to the break.
location: Between "O" wall and the Nut Cracker.

description: Up top there are two pockets that if you use your imagination, looks like owls eyes. One move wonder.
location: 8‚Äô right of Shooting Star.

description: O for overhung, another Hinkley Classic. Three variations .. all have the same start. Once you move out of the pockets either go left (5.11b), straight up on finger locks and mono‚Äôs (5.12a) or right (5.11c).
location: Find the carving in the rock ‚ÄúCHRIST DIED‚Äù. Follow the wall left to an inside corner, then left several more feet to a large maple tree. About 8‚Äô left of the tree is the start for O Wall.
To the right of O Wall and 5‚Äô right of the maple tree.

route_name: He Had a Lot to Say
location: Locate the offwidth¬†perhaps 10 feet right of Christ Died Crack.
protection: Traditional anchors can be made at the top using surrounding trees. Long webbing or static line is useful here.

description: Start with a pinch down and left. Climb up and right as you navigate through pockets and pinches.¬†Slopes and jugs await as you top out.
location: Walk counter clockwise around the backside of Sunshine Boulder. Good Morning Sunshine is on the right side.
protection: Multiple pads and spotters will keep you off of a rocky landing

route_name: Christ! Meet in The Middle Way
description: Finger lay back with foot schmear, leads straight up the slab like midline to a nice ledge for traverse to anchors.
location: The middle crack between Christ Died Crack and He Had a Lot to Say
protection: Fixed anchors now in place. Please remember to bring your own gear!

description: Short crack to small overhang.
location: 3‚Äô left of carving ‚ÄúCHRIST DIED FOR OUR SINS‚Äù

description: Short but fun. Climb the face with right hand using arete.
location: Right of Christ Died. Locate large tulip tree. Climb arete.

description: Straight up face, crack is off.
location: Locate ‚ÄúCHRIST DIED FOR OUR SINS‚Äù carved in the rock.

description: Have no fear, the holds will appear, unless they don‚Äôt.
location: To the right of Short Crack. Climb the face between the maple tree and the corner.

description: This is the problem that starts in the small cave working out the roof.. up the face.
protection: Pads, Spotters, heel locks, toe locks, finger locks. Works out the roof and up the face to the top.

description: Start in the obvious crack just off the corner and work your way over simple roofs with good holds. Crux be at the top!
location: The first big cliff you come to after leaving Gumby Crack as you walk south crossing over the rock rubble area void of any significant rock features.
protection: Trees at top and long anchor material.

description: Traverse left from the crack keeping feet *above* the obvious line ~2-3 feet from the ground. ¬†Crux is about half way (10 feet) from start. No idea if this had been attempted before (though imagine it has). We (Johnny Arnold and I) decided to throw down a little challenge while climbing the Christ Died Crack by adding in a long traverse. If bouldering, Route would end at He Had a Lot to Say; if using as an add-on to Christ Died Crack (or HHALTS or C!MITMW) beware of the LONG pendulum from being roped into the crack anchors (including the potential for plowing into your belayer, the tree, decking on the boulder right below HHALTS, or if your lucky to peel off further along, the long swing (hopefully) between the tree and wall. Would give this a¬†‚ÄúPG13‚Äù add-on if using as an addition to the crack.
location: Start at the dihedral crack to the left of Christ Died.
protection: Pads if bouldering; TR to Christ Died Crack if adding as a start traverse

description: Moss. This crag has moss.
Opposite Angels Arete .. possibly have someone show you.
location: Underclings lead to tiny slopers..

description: Start on the slab to the right of a scooped arete. Climb the slab until it runs out of holds and forces you left around the arete and into the overhanging scoop. Climb left through the overhanging section on some good jug rails, into the chimney. Climb the chimney/arete for a few feet and then break out right back onto the face. Traverse the moss at the top to the anchors.
Can climb multiple combinations in tennis.
location: Left hand side of this hunka¬†chunk

description: Start on a rail and work along small crimps with balancy moves on one of the blankest of the wood sections.
location: Woods wall, starts directly below pillar 8, look at the photo to identify the rail start. 15 feet left of Woodland Walk. Traverse your way right until you get to the 4th fence section from the 7th pillar.
protection: a bouldering pad or two have someone move it if you want to do the whole problem.

description: Start standing up and work your way up the side of the boulder to a top out.
location: Once you arrive in the Sand Hill area the problem is on the backside of the big boulder on your right.

description: Fun warm up route. Start standing up and pull yourself and work your way up the crack to a top out.
location: As you are leaving the bouldering area on the Sand Hill Trail it is on your left. Directly across from large lone boulder on your right.

description: Start on the left side of the big boulder and traverse yourself across the face of the rock. This requires good footwork, finger jams, and presses. After traversing across, work yourself up the face of the wall to a top out. Patience is required to complete this route.
location: This will be the first big boulder you come to while following the Sand Hill Trail.

description: Easy and fun warm up traverse across the boulder to a top out.
location: Walk all the through the Sand Hill climbing area. The start this problem is the last boulder on your left.

description: Start standing up, work your way up the problem with small finger crimps to the top out.
location: When you arrive in Sand Hill Bouldering area the problem will be on the right side of the trail in the middle of the largest boulder in this area.

description: Stand up start, the crux is the next move which is holding onto the sloper and then grabbing a little knob. Then you will have to almost mantle yourself onto the big sloper and then it is an easy top out from there.
location: Once you arrive at Sand Hill climbing location you will come to a large stand alone boulder. The start to this problem is directly across from this large boulder.

description: Start standing up, move from right to left to a top out. The crux is within the first couple moves when you down climb across the face.
location: As soon as you arrive at the Sand Hill Bouldering area the problem is the first boulder on the left side of the trail.

description: Start standing with left hand on side pull and right hand in the little pocket. Work your way straight up the problem. Using little crimps and slopers. Footwork is super important for this slab problem.
location: When you arrive in Sand Hill bouldering area. Walk about 15 yards and the problem will be in the middle of the long boulder on your left.

description: Sit down start on the rock jutting up and match hands above you. Start pulling up to reach for the multiple roofs to touch the top. You're able to get on top, but there's no where to walk off. Downclimbing is only good way down, the deck is a bit sketchy.
location: NE corner of the Ignoreland area, where the trail on top of the ledges turns around to come through the main corridor. The bottom of the route has SAT spraypainted on the rock face, and there's two fallen decaying trees near the rock.
protection: Pads and spotters highly necessary. The deck has several large boulders with pointed edges that will hurt a lot if you fell.

description: Super height dependent. Face / Slab climb.
location: To the right of the arete that has Back Scratcher .. North of the Island.

description: Balance and techy¬†movements take you up the slightly less than vertical climbing. The crux is finding a trustworthy foot to gain the pods overhead. Pinch and step on more defined features towards the finish.
location: North of Back Scratcher - Ignoramus climbs up the right side of the slabby¬†face.
protection: Natural anchors at the top. Two trees simul with cords or long slings.

description: Crux is usually avoiding the rock behind you.. hence "Back scratcher."
location: Large chimney north of the Island. To the left of Look Ma No Hands.

description: Just after the Keyhole Crack the cliff breaks down, follows the trail down.. there is the face of Beer Can Alley. This is a small dyno and face.

location: Most Southwest of the actual cliffs on the opposite side of Beer Can Alley. Looking up at the top of the route is a rock outcropping, this route is to the right of that. Gumby's Crack is to the left of the outcropping. Easiest access point is coming from the Bottom O' Ledges parking area and hiking up the gravel trail, it'll be the first large rock face you see coming up the hill.
protection: Large diameter tree that sticks out at the top of the route for setting up a top rope anchor.

description: There are many classic problems on the Racoon Boulder ..
location: Just 50 feet down hill from 1.5oz and Beer Can Alley. Walk off the top ..

description: The full grunt.
location: Chalked up tiny boulder near the gulley of Beer Can Alley.

description: Mostly face climbing with some cracks for gear.  At the bottom it is easier to traverse left then right to get to the bottom of the crack about halfway up.  Some of the topout is a little mossy.
location: Face on the opposite side of Beer Can Alley.
protection: I climbed it with a set of nuts and hexes.  A toprope can be setup at the top by walking around the back and bouldering up to the top.

description: Realizing how high you've become and staying on the rock.
location: The Beer Can Alley traverse!

description: Rarely climbed anymore .. there is a large series of trees blocking the start.
protection: Pro? Avoid landing on the trees if you spit off.

description: Kinda tricky start to ¬†fun pockets and a little crack.
location: Left of Chin Chimney.

description: Carefully balance your way to huge ledge under roof, and find the awesome pockets to get to the finish. Lots of fun!
location: Right side of arete. Huge ledge halfway up route.

description: Start with left hand on an undercling beneath the overhang and right hand on one of the larger pockets on the face. You will have to get a good right foot heel hook to stay off of the ground.¬† Move your left hand out to the lip of the face and then slowly bump your hands up with the small holds on the face until you reach the jugs at the top of the face to get to the easy topout.
location: Left

description: Start as low as you can on the right arete and follow it to the top using good feet on the face.
location: The right most of the three routes on the face
protection: A few pads, and watch the tree

description: Cross start on pocket and crimp, work your way up the arete with an undercling and some fancy footwork.
location: Middle of Suburban Boulder.

description: Start on high crimps with good feet on the left hand side of the face, make a long move right to a good crimp before finishing with some delicate movements
location: Back side of the block, start on the far left doing your best to avoid a tree assist.

description: Start on the farthest right ledge and trend left to merge in to "Climbin in Sperrys"
location: The middle of the three on the easy face

description: Stand start at bottom of sloping arete, move through edge and pocket to middle of arete. Figure out your feet to gain jug ledge and top out.
location: Located on the back of Shipwreck Bloc to the right of Keel Hulled.

description: Start on the lowest ledge with your right foot in the pocket. Continue following the ledges to the lip. This was first done in Sperrys
location: The left most route on the easy face
Starts on pockets on right side of arete.
protection: Setup anchors for Stout and Round

description: Takes small nuts and cams. Look for the bomber V slot on the right bulge below the big ledge. Take advantage of the super deep pocket on the upper face.
location: Left side of arete. Look for narrow vertical crack down low that leads to bulge. Permanent anchors on top.

description: Good right hand and three finger pocket left hand start holds. End matched as shown in photo.
location: Right of pooh's corner routes. Left of dirty little boulder routes when looking at cliff line.

description: Bring some small cams and tricams for the mail slots and bigger gear to build an anchor in the upper fist crack. Double up for the slight runout.Traverse to fixed anchors if needed.
location: Far left route thru bomber horizontals.
protection: Mixed smaller cam, big hex and equivalents for anchor.

description: This route is a traverse Start is the same as Remy‚Äôs spuddies with low feet to the right then right hand goes up to a 2 finger pocket and left hand goes to the left onto a decent hold with a thumb catch re - position feet and stretch your left hand out pretty far into another 2 finger pocket bring left foot farther out onto what‚Äôs basically a smear and you will be in the splits cross right hand under left onto a crimp and use pockets all the way up to Where 1.5 kids finished
location: Past amusement wall on the right side of the trail

description: Sit start on the large flake and follow the arete to the top using the occasional foot and hand hold on the left face
location: farthest route on the right of the boulder
protection: a pad and a spotter to keep you from rolling down the hill

description: Start right crimp, left side pull. Long move up and finish on 1.5 Kids' topout.
location: Between Uptight Neighbors and 1.5 Kids on Suburban.

description: Start on opposing side pulls, crimp up and long reach to layback. Stay right of arete and don't use mossy steps on left for topout. Fun feet!
location: Left of 401k on Suburban.

description: Go straight up. You may take a swing if you falter. Thin low and big pockets at top.
location: Use the bolts for "'What Tiggers Do Best" but start left .

description: Start in depression area on bolt line, ascend up on fun moves, and figure out the middle crux before moving to finish.
location: Route is in between Left Eye and Jacob's Ladder.

description: Reachy start to great crack, steep bulge to big holds at top.
location: Steep crack left of Digitalis.

description: Tricky start with undercut feet. If you can make it to the first bolt, it should be smooth sailing to the end.
location: Right of Double Overhangs

First bolted route on the right-most wall in the Trash Shoot area. When taking the trail to the Trash Shoot Area, turn right at the first wall, and walk to the end. This is the route left of Bloodmutt.
protection: Two bolts to a two-bolt anchor

description: Layaway to the left with a high right foot and no LF to nail the far right of horizontal.. Don't follow the chalk on the right. The original start makes the route. Also don't cheap out and go right at the top. Otherwise consider it a 5.9.
location: Right of Hellstrong and left of Raining Buckeyes

description: Same start as Garburator but climbs right before the big ledge through jug gaston. Climb up and right through crimps to top out.
location: Located in a break in the cliff between Jacob's Ladder and Mad Corner.
