description: Fun beginner route with big pockets and ledges. Start just below or slightly left of bolts. Trend right as you move up on great holds past two bolts to the top. Possibly the easiest route currently bolted at the Mad. Would be great for a first-time leader.
location: In the central Trash Shoot area. To the right of Raining Buckeyes, and just left of the big hole in the wall.
protection: Two bolts to a two-bolt anchor

description: Start directly under overhang. Short powerful route with barn door finish. Watch the tree if you blow it at the anchors.
location: Right of Chin Chimney crack.

description: Sit start on jug outside of break in cliff. Climb right on jug blocks through the break making big move to ledge and topping out.
location: Located in a break in the cliff between Jacob's Ladder and Mad Corner.
This is the second bolted route on the right-most wall of the Trash Shoot Area. It is located directly to the right of Mad Corner and left of Bloodmutt.
protection: Two bolts to a two-bolt anchor

location: Far right line in Trash Shoot Area. Once the trail meets the walls of the Trash Shoot Area, turn right and walk to the end. Just to¬†the right of Bloodmutt
protection: Two bolts to a two-bolt anchor

description: Furthest east sport route on the cliff line. Direct start off the ground. Avoid the detached boulder on the right. Reach to mono is the crux. Two moves past the anchor gets the tick. Make sure to check bolts before climbing here as this area has not yet been rebolted.
location: Left of trash shoot.

description: Stay off the big stuff at the bottom and make sure you snag the very top ledge for the tick.
location: Starts in the middle of white semi-detached block right of Digitalis.

description: Classic climb (and is definitely hard for the grade in comparison to other 5.8s at the Mad). Moderate climbing on good edges and pockets. Start slightly left of bolts and continue on some thin moves at top for a more exciting 5.10a. variation. ¬†Original route is right of bolt line.
location: From the path up to Trash Shoot from the Taylor Property trail, head right. Chin Chimney will be the obvious arete on the right side of this portion of wall.

description: Classic climb (and is definitely hard for the grade in comparison to other 5.8s at the Mad). Climb fun and easy bulges after a challenging start.
location: West of trash shoot.

description: Starts low on a sharp crimpy match- toehook deep into the cave to get off the ground then the crux second move is one of the gnarliest lock offs out to the ledge of the small roof. Maintain body tension and get your other hand out to another tiny intermediate and then up to a jug and it should be pretty easy cruisin from there. Probably been climbed before but it's not on here so.
location: Hike in from the wingo picnic area, turn right at the main trail, then left at the first approach trail. This takes you to one of the toprope sites, which has a small trail winding through it. Follow this trail a little ways down and back up to this wonderful little spot that has way more potential for cool lines.
protection: A pad, maybe two if you're climbing solo

description: Starts in the cave on the left of the boulder on a small block. Use toe hooks to pull the lip and keep it together to get to the jugs and top out.
location: Continue down the trail with the river on your right past Hug Me boulder. In about 400m there will be a large boulder on the left, this is Pride Rock. The problem is on the left.

description: Climb from the right side of the vertical flake up then across to the left to top out.
location: Directly downhill from Yellow Middle near the trail

route_name: Over the River and Through the Woods
description: Starting from the left edge of the boulder at a hanging position then traverse across the flat face of the boulder to the section that juts out. Then climbing around, underneath the jut out. Move up the right side using the jugs climb left and top out where the top of the jut out meets the flat faced boulder.
location: Traveling on the lower gorge trail follow a very well-travel trail that point towards the gorge walls away from the river. There will be two large boulders visible the Maverick boulder (small overhang) is on the left. This is on the the other boulder (jut out) on the right
protection: Toss a mat under the crux on the jut out

description: A sit start to a clearly previously climbed line. The first three moves on small crimps are rather thuggy and the redpoint crux seems to be a foot sequence of some kind but after that the top outs rather easy if a little dirty at times.
location: Like 20 feet to the left of The proj
protection: Pad- maybe definitely a spotter, landings a little sketchy

description: Easy boulder up left side of vertical flake. Top out and climb down the other side.
location: Downhill from Yellow Middle near the trail.

This boulder is found approximately 60 yards downhill(south) of the "Red Top-rope" section of the climbing wall. See map on the John Bryan/Mountain project page to see where the "Red Top-Rope" area is located.

This boulder is found approximately 60 yards downhill(south) of the "Red Top-rope" section of the climbing wall.  See map on the John Bryan/Mountain project page to see where the "Red Top-Rope" area is located.
protection: One pad and maybe a spotter

route_name: Mavericks Boulder, Gleaming the Tube V3+
location: This boulder is found approximately 60 yards downhill(south) of the "Red Top-rope" section of the climbing wall. See map on the John Bryan/Mountain project page to see where the "Red Top-Rope" area is located.

description: Start with small crimps, move up using small crimps and mono pockets to small jugs. Small jugs and slopers to the top.
location: Same boulder as Midas

description: Start low on good slot to the left of the bulge. Make a big move right and follow jugs straight up to top out.
location: On the far right of the boulder to the right of the Maverick boulder.

description: Start on the same starting jug as the parrot, but move straight up the right face
location: Right of the beak feature

description: Start on jug, make large left hand move to decent hold. ¬†Move to the beak looking feature and then top out.
location: On the obvious feature of the Kraken Boulder.
On the abominable boulder, around the right side. Starts just to the left of the white streak.

description: Sit start on the jug rail and work your way left to the end of the boulder. A great way to play on the fun holds this face has to offer. Alternatively, one could split off onto Zach Galifianakis for a solid 25 feet of climbing.
This low ball is great! Sit start on the far right hand side on an incut crimp. Walk your heels and toes along the plank until you get to the end where a big move pulls you over the lip and on top!
location: The trailside portion of the boulder
protection: Multiple pads or someone to move them for you as you work around the boulder

description: Sit start on side pull and chickenhead, up and right on easy holds. Mind the moss.
location: Left side of Hippie boulder.

description: Sit start on good pockets. Bump left and match, swoop the corner and shuffle up and left on good feet.
location: Right side of Hippie boulder.

description: Offwidth/layback problem

This short powerful problem ascends the prominent overhanging arete on the left end of the boulder just off the trail. If not for the bad landing, it would be a good boulder problem. But since we don't climb for shoe deals, we put a one bolt anchor.
location: Abominable Boulder 50 feet right of Roadside Distraction

description: Super slimy if it's just rained, will need some cleanup. Start in the obvious jug at stomach/waist height and make the big move out left.
location: Right of Offwidth Problem on Abominable Boulder
protection: Thick pads. Fall will result in hitting the slope of the 4ft ditch you have to walk up to get to start.

description: Wide flaring crack. Takes pro easily.
location: Left of Smokey.
Right of Meltdown near overpass

description: Use small holds down low to gain good ledges for clipping stances. Work your way through the crux to the large ledge at the finish. Bolted in 2019.
location: Right of White Lightning and left of Drop Zone

description: Classic route. Ease up to a great ledge then muscle the roof using a phenominal crack. Trend right after the 3rd bolt to finish on big jugs and bomber top just right of anchors. Take a sit down and enjoy the view..
location: Right of You Sure? near overpass

description: West facing corner crack with huge roof before you get to Smokey.
location: In between two sport projects on right side of the Overpass Area

description: Grab the large horizontal and work yourself into the depression. Smear and crimp thru the crux to reach larger holds and move right to pull the roof.
location: Just left of the Roadside Distraction crack.

description: To the left of Drop Zone. Followed muddy streak. Bolts removed, but route listed here for historical purposes.
location: Left of Drop Zone
protection: Bolts removed in 2019. Kept for historical purposes.

location: Right of Tire Fire near overpass

description: Work straight up from the first bolt or use the right facing crack to gain easier ledges.
location: The face left of You Sure.

This boulder problem is located on the face between the cracks You Sure? and Roadside Distraction. ¬†The section of wall has a large overhang and Crimp Slap is located right in the middle where it climbs up to the corner of the roof to finish.
protection: One pad, super safe.  You can even get away with no pads.

description: Thin face moves then big ledges to the shared anchors of Roadside-Disrtraction.
location: The face just right of the corner crack of Roadside Distraction

description: Work your way up left or right of the bolt line to figure out the crux. Enjoyable top. Bolted in 2019.
location: Around corner to right of Smokey and left of Razor Ledge on wall that faces main path.

route_name: (Closed due to loose rock) Tire Fire
location: Far left of Overpass Area

description: grade should reflect difficulty once cleaned up. Start matched on jug. Traverse right to left along the rim. Start from the walk off area, around the beak feature to top out above the beak. Low boulder feature underneath beak,¬†as well as small out cropping on ledge around the beak are on (pictured). Once clean, removal of the Boulder feature underneath beak ¬†and the outcropping for the left foot on the ledge should make this climb significantly harder.
location: Kraken Boulder. Start is matched on jug near down climb area for other climbs in this boulder.
protection: Pad near middle of route (while dirty) or under beak should suffice.

description: Sit start beneath the little overhang. Start with your right hand on the good sidepull and sort out how to pull over the bulge.
location: Just behind the Black Pearl boulder
protection: One pad, watch out for the large dead limb

description: Classic route. Route begins under small roof with a few thin moves. Pull roof to easier climbing. Moving out right after roof makes it spicier and a shade harder.

This is the 2nd route on the buttress. Balance up thin seam, trending left after the 2nd bolt. Keep moving up and left to finish on anchors of Where the Green Fern Grows. Cleaning can be a bit of a challenge. Be careful unclipping first bolt.
location: Right of Where the Green Fern Grows on Fern Buttress
Down the trail from Pooh's corner, pretty hard to miss.

description: Classic route. Mad River Gorge's semi overhanging jug hall. Make big moves on positive holds.
Classic route. Climb "S" curved crack. Awkward placing gear but fun route and decent first lead. There is a top rope variation to the left of crack as well.
location: Right of Super Dads
protection: Trad gear and 2 anchors with SS chains and rappel rings

description: Using consecutive underclings and precise foot work, climb your way to a blind finish.
location: Right of Dear Jim

description: Start on pockets off cheater stone. Hanging start. Make use of good pockets and small edges to anchors up and right.
location: Just left of Recycler on main cliff face

description: Start off cheater stone on two shallow pockets. Campus up to two hand ledge and use pockets and small edges to gain the face. A strenuous clip leads to the crux and then easier climbing up top.
location: Right of Nuts and Honey

description: Great route! Sustained route to great finish.
location: Right of The Phat and the Dope on the main cliff face

description: Thin face moves to overhang crux. The 2nd bolt is too dicey to clip. I would haul up a stick clip until I come up with something better. The run to anchors from 2nd bolt is 5.5ish.
location: Start on sloper from ground right of the boulder.
protection: 2 bolts to anchors of Dear Jim.

description: Bouldery start to a insecure slabby finish.
location: Just right of Recyclable Stone below the large overhang.

description: Delicately balance and crimp your way up hidden holds to the roof and figure out how to clip anchors.
location: Left of Dear Jim on main cliff face

description: Moderate face leads to a thin crack below big ledges.
location: Between NWO and SWW. ¬†Start at the graffitti.

description: Undercling an arching crack to under roof. Traverse right to a bolt. Placing protection can be strenuous but crack eats up cams. Clip bolt and pull roof using crack. Mixed route.
location: Just right of 12 pack in the crack

description: Stick clip high first bolt. Figure out crux, Take a break at the ¬†2nd clip before the exciting finish.
location: Just right of Garbage Warrior.

description: Classic route. Begin on some moderate moves with some tricky feet. Continue through the crux as it becomes slightly overhung. Be sure to take advantage of the dyno up top, as this is what makes the route so good! This route stays fairly dry after a rain... except for one key spot (which explains the name).
location: Two routes to the left of the mixed crack climb called Diagonal To Nowhere. Look for a good sized shelf at the top of the climb.
protection: 5 bolts & SS chains with rappel rings

description: Great workout or warm-up when dry..
location: Horizontal seam starting at bottom of stairs and traversing left or start left below Diagonal to Nowhere and go right..
protection: Pad would be nice, but not essential.

route_name: She Keeps it on the Mantel
description: Don't be tempted by the tree or anything left of it. Strictly off route.
location: Face left of Springfield Arch

description: Great moderate route with a crux that makes you think about half way up. Since it is a brand new route, it is a little dirty towards the top, but that should cleanup with more climbers on the wall.
location: Located on Clear Creek Crag- two routes left of 12 pack (10c) and on wall right of arete with Excellent Ella (5.6)

description: Recycler to 3rd bolt, move right on side-pulls and knee bar to clip 4th. Gain blunt arete using fierce pockets. ¬†Clip 5th chest high then be rewarded with fantastic pockets at the roof.
location: Right variation of Recycler. The black slab.

description: Start below the bolts on "She Keeps It on the Mantel". Boulder up and into the crack. Follow the crack up and right using secure jams to gain the right facing flake. Continue up to the first roof moving out left to gain a large crack up to the second roof. Move left to clip the third bolt continuing to the anchors on "She Keeps It on the Mantel".
location: Clear Creek Crag (MRG). Between "She Keeps It on the Mantel" & "Springfield Arch"
protection: Standard rack & one bolt. A number 4 C4 is helpful in the roof.

description: The start is not really in line with the rest of the routes difficulty, but its a good one nonetheless. Utilize the crack, balance up and over a few ledges and clip anchors
location: Left of Devine Root

description: Rumored to be the first route bolted in Springfield in the early 90s. Look for 3 stacked roofs with several fixed draws.
location: Bolted route directly left of a large vertical crack. The crack begins as an offwidth.

description: Stick clip second bolt. Campus till you gain feet. Shake out at big ledge and fire through crux. Clipping anchors can be interesting if you choose wrong hold to clip from.
location: On main face of wall in between Man with a Beard and Trash.com

description: Probably want to stick clip 2nd bolt, or be REALLY strong. Originally intentioned to stay left thru micro edges as Man With a Beard.It can be done by trending right on bigger holds as The Pinch.
location: Start just right of Arch on large pinch.
protection: 3 bolts to anchors of Recyclable Stone.

description: Beginning on some small pockets, crimp your way up this the route on tiny holds with some very physical moves to some slightly overhanging chains.
location: Second bolted route to the right of the obvious crack that begins as an offwidth.

description: This route begins in the obvious off width and continues up to a flaring layback crack. Use anchors of Trash Talk
location: Offwidth between Recycler and Trash Talk on main cliff face
protection: Gear to Anchors for Trash Talk

description: One set of anchors with 3 different starts. .
location: As soon as you cross the stone bridge.

description: Begin on small crimps with technical moves. Climb through several bolts to reach much easier climbing towards the top of the wall.
location: First bolted route on a blank looking wall to the left of Slippery When Wet.

description: Chossy start to stopper crux at 2nd bolt. Traverse right to Recyclable Stone anchors.
location: Just left of Recyclable Stone (they share anchors)

description: Long moves lead to a good rest before run to the top.
location: Left variation of Recycler. Trend left after 2nd bolt of Recycler.

description: Nice pockets and features at the bottom lead to a blank middle section crux where tiny crimps and good balance are needed to get further up the wall.
location: Just left of 12 Pack (10c) on the Clearcreek Wall.

description: Thin face to a tricky bulge then traverse to SWW anchors.
location: The face right of SWW.

description: This is a great route! A sequential, powerful start leads to a surprise ending.
location: Right of The Underling and left of Root for Me

description: Begin climbing the crack for 20 feet on good holds and good feet. Beware of the loose blocks towards the middle of the crack while placing gear. Head right for the chains at the top of the crack.
location: Follow the approach trail into the gorge, turning right as you reach the bottom. Follow wall for 50 feet, looking for a crack with a bolt and anchor at the top.
protection: Standard rack w/ 1 bolt and 2 anchors

description: Starts under first bolt and traverse left briefly into Root for Me. Clip 2nd bolt and trend up right to anchors. It is believed this route was bolted by Mike Johnson in the late 80s.
location: Right of Root for Me

description: 1 bolt protects a hard to protect start and 1 bolt is up top to protect traverse to anchors. Climb crack in between. This route takes nuts and cams galore. It is a very good route for beginning tradsters comfortable at this grade.
location: Right of Steve-O and left of The Underling
protection: Two bolts, gear to two ring anchor. Mixed route

description: Start is crux although the top is a little in your face as well.
location: right of 12 pack

description: Classic route. Begin on jugs to a technical middle section. Watch out for the run-out between the first & second bolt as there is ground fall potential. If you can pull the bottom moves though, the middle should be no problem.
location: The first bolted route to the right of Dad's Wall.
Right of Excellent Ella on arete
protection: Gear and Chain anchors. Or lead Excellent Ella to setup top rope.

location: This climb is on the far left side of Dad's Wall. ¬†It is just left of Cracking Point and Chain Mail Hula Skirt but all three of the climbs share the same anchors.
protection: This climb protects extremely well. ¬†The traverse eats up gear from .5 to 4 and there are great stances to make placements.

description: Classic route. Climb arete using big pockets and cracks. Great first lead or warm up to the area.
location: Right of J-Ella on right face of arete
protection: Gear to 2 chain anchor or Lead Excellent Ella to setup anchors for top rope

description: Classic route. This route takes the line of bolts directly right of S Crack. Climb thin face moves to roof.
location: Right of S Crack
protection: 3 bolts to 2 bolt anchors with SS chains and rappel rings

description: Classic route. This route ascends face directly under chains. Highly featured with great pockets. Excellent first lead for a newer outdoor climber, or warm up route for the area.
protection: 3 bolts to 2 chain SS anchors with rappel rings

location: Cracking Point is located on the far left side of Dad's Wall in between Lost Soles and Chain Mail Hula Skirt.¬† All three routes share the same anchors.
protection: If you are decently tall you should be able to reach up to the horizontal crack to place a .75 before going through the crux of the route. ¬†You wont be able to see in the crack for the placement but the crack is perfect for gear and it is very possible to make safe placements without looking. ¬†If you can manage to get these placements in before pulling the moves that get you up to the crack and lip then the climb is safe but if you are shorter and have to get through the crux before placing any gear it can get pretty dicey.¬† Boulder pads may help you feel safer.

description: Fun route that takes big gear. Bring your wide toys, kids!
location: This route is the furthest left on Dad's Wall, and follows the large detached flake up and left (stepped edge). Layback and / or throw in jams deep behind the flake. At the top, shift right out onto flake and find the anchors. These will allow top-roping the route (use quickdraws).

description: Fun moves between good holds. Setup Top Rope after leading S-Crack. Stays dry in the rain.
location: Just Left of S-Crack. Starts on two two finger pockets, move up on edges to a right jug side-pull. Make a large crux move to a high jug. Finish on easy terrain to S-Crack chain anchors
protection: Use SS chain/ rap ring anchor for S Crack

location: This boulder is located between Pooh's Corner and Dirty Little Boulder. ¬†I currently have it listed as unsorted under Dirty Little Boulder because there isn't actually a location name for the area yet. ¬†If you are looking at Dirty Little Bolder, just walk 30-ish feet to the left and you should see this boulder suspended in the air on the same wall. ¬†If you make it to Pooh's Corner then you've gone too far.
protection: Two pads or one pad and a spotter will get the job done but the more pads you can get the better.¬† It's a high climb with a nice flat landing.

description: Super fun sit start to two great jugs. Large reach up to decent ledge. Traverse left and top out WITHOUT the tree.
protection: 1 pad and 1 spotter since you are on a hill

description: Start on obvious jug, move into two two-finger pockets. ¬†Make a reachy move into a slot, continue left into a super deep pocket, finish on obvious jug. Stay underneath the rail the entire time.
location: Directly next to Amusement Wall.

description: Traverse with nice ledges for feet throughout the first half that disappear into quite small footholds that require some precision. Start with feet on lowest ledge, left hand on good crimp right hand up and slightly over on other good crimp. Use low ledges to walk left until they run out while walking hands left using side pulls and a gaston. Hands continue up to a nice jug then left following the small overhang using a series of good holds to finish. Finish far left, matching on the undercling in top left corner of picture
location: The wall left of Amusement Wall bouldering cave when looking at the cave. Route follows along the slanted dirt hill that leads into a small crack/cave.
protection: Spotter and crash pad for slanted landing

description: Obvious overhanging fin feature detached from the wall. Start under the feature compressing on on a slopey edge for the left hand and and the juicy undercling for the right hand. Figure out the feet and fire to a pinch. Slap your way up the rest of the problem and end at a sloper jug on the left side of the fin and drop off. You could continue up to the top on 5.8 terrain but the rock quality is questionable and the walk off lengthy.
Start on jug sidepulls and climb the flake to the 'faux' top out.
location: Located on left side of the area where a large section of rock has broken away from the cliff.

description: Start on block to the right of prow, same as Intersectionality. Climb left under belly feature and straight up prow, Finish on block jugs at top of prow. Flake at base of cliff under the prow is off.
location: Starts just to the right of prow feature.

description: Start on block left of prow. Climb right through sidepulls and good feet. Finish standing on top of ledge.
location: Located on the left side of the slab as you approach from the trail.

description: Start on block jug, traverse left under belly feature. Continue through sidepulls on smeary feet. Finish standing on ledge. Flake at the base of the cliff under the prow is off.
location: Starts just to the right of prow feature visible from trail.

description: Crimp up to possible dyno out to horizontal flake (will test security on cleaning). Great feet to end
location: East of Project 1

description: Easy side pulls up to large edges, overcome the fear of the crap landing to pull through top.
location: Underneath west start of overhang

description: Sit start on the corner, feet on detached rock. Work right on good holds then straight up to slightly dusty finish.
location: Far left corner of cave that's to the left of Amusement Wall. Walk off towards the gully.

description: Start low and left of the bolt line in the depression for full effect. ¬†Traverse right down low then flow up using balance moves on bolt line. Crux movements just below bolt.
location: Aft of Ship Rock

description: Start in the alcove ( w/o the boulder) ¬†and use the crack to gain pockets and edges. A nice side-pull uptop eases you to the anchors. Check out the high right ledge above.
location: Far right of Mike's Wall.
parent_sector: Mike's Wall (Formerly Known as Midway Wall)

description: Technical start to a diamond finish.
location: Left of Dr Evil, very tuff for it's size.
parent_sector: Mike's Wall (Formerly Known as Midway Wall)

description: Basically a boulder problem off the large rock protected by one bolt. Easy ground to anchors.
location: Right of Scotty Boy on the arete.
parent_sector: Mike's Wall (Formerly Known as Midway Wall)

description: Far left route. .
location: Midway wall
parent_sector: Mike's Wall (Formerly Known as Midway Wall)

description: Not really any great holds until the anchors.
location: Obvious finger crack in middle of wall.
parent_sector: Mike's Wall (Formerly Known as Midway Wall)

location: At ship rock, look for low buldge under the left side of an obviously large ledge that could support a whale

route_name: She is very gorgeous to me
location: Left of all ship routes.
protection: Pad, landing is slanted with loose rock

description: Decide left or right sequence on big pockets to ledge. Make a couple easy moves to anchors.
location: Just right of Minute Man,

description: Technical face climbing.
location: The aft of Ship Rock. Start on log and straight up left side.

protection: 2 bolts, needs one more after the chain to make working the route easier. ¬†In the meantime, stick clip the anchors from the 2nd bolt to toprope the crux.

description: Look for good pockets down low and utilize side pulls and bomber ledges up high.
location: In between Beached Whale and Narwal. Avoid using big platform on Beached Whale (unless of course you want the super nice rest spot)

description: Start either in pockets under the ledge or out right following the thin crack (more difficult), climb up through pockets to surmount the ledge, elegantly or like a beached whale, then continue using a shared bolt and anchors finishing to right of anchors.
location: Under right side of big ledge on Ship Rock

description: Start low and left and traverse over to the arete. Then work your way up the arete and take advantage of the great holds when you can find them.
location: Arete on far right side of Ship Rock (next to gulley that separates Ship Rock from Mike's Wall)
Just left of Sparky, directly up the steep face.

description: Start on flakey jug near the ground, then work your way up on to the roof using more flakey jugs. At the end of the roof take a poor match to move a heel out to the right and pull on that to a good side pull and finish on the next large flake. The route is a bit dirty,¬†some shrubbery near the finish and top out.
location: The route is located past the second wall at "The Dark Side" crag at the Mad River Gorge. Follow trails from the parking lot and once at the second wall follow it closely till the sport routes end and the wall decreases in height. You'll notice a roof and a large buried rock the route starts just to the left, near the ground, of the specified rock. (Probably best to cover the rock with a pad because the roof will take you out over it a bit).
protection: One or two crash pads and spotters.

description: Sit start with your hands on the ledge. Moving straight up, squeeze some beta out of the teets, gain some pockets, and then pull on crimps till you reach the jug right of the small roof.  The finish jug is above and left of the finish for Pocket Rocket/Rocktober Festival.
location: Located between the main Amusement Wall bolted routes and the bouldering cave.  Left of Pocket Rocket/Rocktober Festival.

description: This is a new route that was added in May 2017.
location: Two routes left of Crazy Trailer Bitch

description: Climb the same line as "Anxious Arrival", but instead of topping out "Lunge or Plunge" continue on and finish the same as "Campus Ousside". Climbs like a route.
Nice crack route. Probably soloed along time ago..although topping out could be really sketchy. Can be led trad.
location: Pretty obvious.
protection: 2 bolts to anchors.needs SS. rings and quicklinks.

description: Sit start on the jugs and throw to a Gaston (V1). V0 stand start. My favorite warm up in the area.¬†My climbing partner and I have been warming up here for a long time. Top out doesn‚Äôt add anything and is muddy. Not sure if we did it first or others. Feel free to pm me if you were the FA and want a different name!
location: Just past the cave.

description: Pretty sustained 10ish.
location: Left of Slappy McCracken

description: Start on low edge match, follow the slots up and swing out for the sloper. Grab the left hand under cling and make your way to the jug
location: Left side of Amusement Wall in the cave area

description: Great pockets help you get onto the wall and crux is getting over the bulge just above the second bolt. Watch out for mud on top, but key hands will help you get to the top. Really enjoyable moderate for the area.
location: Route just right of Crazy Trailer Bitch. Climbs the far right side of the wall/ left side of the arete.

description: Slappey McCracken was developed in May 2017 and is located on Amusement Wall.
location: Route is three left of Crazy Trailer Bitch on Amusement Wall

description: Start on a flat hold to the right of "Dry Route". Make a big reach to a slot at the lip, then core up and make some dead points to get to the jug.
Knee-bar start.
location: Wide crack next to Scrappy.
protection: Use anchors on Scrappy. Bring protection.

description: Start as far back in cave as possible for full-effect. Some really nice moves on face, eases at top.
location: Right of Scooby Doo above cave.

description: Difficulty depends on where you start. Eases to big holds at top.
location: Left route above bouldering cave

description: Sit start below, and then climb to the start holds of Pocket Rocket. Find some long but static moves instead of jumping to the same ledge.
Start low on two slots, move straight up using mixture of slots and crimps. Big move to jug. Finish through "campus traverse V5"
location: Left side of Amusement Wall  in the boulder cave area. Just right of Lukewarm Sausage.

description: Start underneath roof on good holds. Eventually bump your left hand to a good pinch in roof. Set your feet and do a wild drive by to a jug. Drop off, or if you are tied in continue up the sport route that starts on the finishing jug
Start in the crack on the far right side of the boulder. Follow the crack up and left on good holds, then top out on dirty holds.
location: This boulder is in the ditch right in front of amusement wall.

description: A few long moves on big ledges to bomber hold above anchors.
location: Start on Pocket Rocket and continue.
Located between the main Amusement Wall bolted routes and the bouldering cave. Right of The Teets. ¬†This boulder climbs the start of the sport route Pocket Rocket Man 5.12a.

description: Start all the way under the roof on left facing jug. Pull through crimps to block, finish same as Lunge or Plunge.
location: Starts directly under Lunge or Plunge all the way at the back of the roof. Careful not to dab on the first couple moves.

description: Start on blocky undercling, paste feet, and do a long move to a finger bucket. Work your feet and swing out to a sloper. Traverse a few moves left and finish on slot machine. Fun, gymnastic problem.
location: Right most problem in the bouldering cave
protection: A couple pads for the first move

description: Start on good jug below yellowish spot. Cross into sidepull, finish up and left on crimps.
location: Left side of Amusement Wall right of the creek bed

description: Somewhat challenging start leads to fun climbing on the arete. Great warmup for other routes at Amusement Wall and generally fun climb.
location: Far right side of Amusement wall on right arete.

description: Stand start on low left hand side pull and right hand pocket pinch on opposite sides of the arete. Climb straight up the arete, finishing on the jug just below the roof.
location: Obvious arete to the right of Easily Amused

description: Start 15 feet right of "Pocket Rocket" matched on an obvious chalked up edge to the left of a crack. Traverse left, making some big, sequential moves on cool grips to the start of "Pocket Rocket". Dyno or crimp your way to the finishing jug and drop.

route_name: Hey look Ma I made it.
description: Eliminate boulder. Start on weird side pull and ok pocket at lip of the bottom roof then go up to the crack jug, then out to crimp and finish on the obvious ¬†big jug before the arete.
location: Start at the far right of the cave
Left side of Amusement Wall

protection: A couple of pads for the low traverse

location: Same as ‚Äúhey look ma I made it‚Äù¬†finished around the far left corner of the cave

description: Only wide crack on A.M wall. Yes... it was once filled with trash.
location: True squeeze chimney. Seldom dry. November is usually good.

description: Start all the way under the roof on left facing jug. Pull through crimps to block, finish same as Blindspot.
location: Starts directly under Lunge or Plunge all the way at the back of the roof. Careful not to dab on the first couple moves.

description: Sit start on two small pockets with heel above hands, cross to good slot and traverse left to jug at lip.
location: Starts to the left of Dingus Prince and follows holds left to same finish as Power Play.

description: Start matched under low roof with very strange feet-first bicycle on lip. Move out to little pinch at lip, bump and climb¬†straight up to stance on face.
location: Start under low roof to right of ‚ÄúFable‚Äù.

description: Historic route, and the only bolted line that existed on Amusement Wall before the Mad was opened. CTB has a colorful background story. Ask Jim if you see him out at the Gorge. ;)
Start on What Just Bit Me to roof then traverse left on flake. Awesome transition to left wall and easy pull up to top-out.
location: Cave left on Amusement Wall
Same start as ‚Äòwhat just bit me‚Äô

description: Start same as "Lunge or Plunge" but make a few powerful compression moves out right to finish on "Dry Route".
location: Same start as "Lunge or Plunge"

description: Route was developed right before the Mad River Gorge was officially opened in May 2017. You might need to start off a cheater stone straight into the bouldery start. After earning the grade before clipping the first bolt cruise up some fun movements until the last few moves test whether or not you brought enough gas for the whole trip.
location: Directly left of Crazy Trailer Bitch

description: Start with your hands in the crack in the middle of the roof. ¬†This is the same start as Dry Route. ¬†Climb left, following Dry Route, dropping down after the crux to link into Lunge or Plunge. ¬†The hardest section is linking the problems, but there still is a pump crux at the finish.

location: This climb is located out right past the Back Alley immediately after a break in the cliff face. ¬†It can be difficult to see from the path because it is hidden behind the Abominable Boulder and another mossy boulder without any climbs. To the left of this climb are a few concrete structures where the cliff line breaks.
protection: Two pads or one pad and someone to move it.  Very safe climb.

description: Start low on slab section, mantle up midway to long moves and lockoffs.
location: Right side of southern wall.

description: Mostly crimpy holds, but there's a nice large square brick shortly after the first clip and an odd I shaped brick right before the last move that are nice and juggy. The top cap of the wall has 2 great holds to finish on as you transition to a top out or the fence to set an anchor. Some of the lower holds are a bit polished, but after after the first few feet they're good and rough.
location: Located on the west wall shortly before woods wall. Walk east from the parking lot to where the grass field gives way to a less well grooomed field, and look about 10 feet up for the first bolt. It's slightly left of the fourth pillar, first fence section.
protection: 2 quickdraws, plus 2 slings and a biner for a top anchor. There's a bomber fence that's easy to anchor to at the top. Bring something to protect your slings as they'll rubbing on the edge.

description: Follow crimps and crimpy slopers up and right to the first bolt, continue past to the top past one more bolt on jugs to the lip of the bridge.
location: From the parking lot start walking along the wall towards the woods. You will find this route around the third pillar. Look for the first bolt by the metal cross-beam about 15 feet off the ground.
protection: 2 bolts, plus a fence to set up a top rope

description: Start on pockets right of Finger Twist and climb straight up on blank-ish face.
location: Right of crack for Finger Twist

description: This is a fun traverse problem about 50' long on the cliff side of the gorge.
location: The route starts at the entrance to the Gorge

description: Start low on two parallel crimps. Climb out through two sharp pockets to a huge move to the jugs. Finish at the lip and drop off.
Start on two mini- jugs, climb straight out the roof on crimps. Finish on jug at lip.
Start same as Mixtape, climb up and right through crimps to sloper. Finish on Busted.
location: Located on left side of roof.

description: Stand start matched on crimp/sloper, make big move to jug and follow holds to lip.
Start on sloper same as Busted. Traverse left and finish on same jug as Mixtape.
location: Left side of the roof between Mixtape and Busted.

description: Double hand undercling on the far right side low on the rock. Stay low, traverse through the depression and around the bulging corner. Don't go up until you pull the corner. Up easy pockets to the finish.
location: Route is located on side of the boulder. Start is on the lower right side, with a double hand undercling that is at about thigh to hip level. Down climb opposite face on easy pockets.

description: Low start on the corner with the two handed diagonal slot. Follow the diagonal crack up and right until it ends. Climb up using pockets and jugs to finish to the top.
location: Route is on the left side of the face by the bulge. Starting hands are hidden low on the bulge, but it is a great diagonal slot to hold onto.

description: Double hand start in slot with feet tucked under rock on small ledge. Move out from underneath rock to good hands halfway up. Balance over feet to move over bulge onto top. Watch out for loose rocks on top holds.
location: Back side of rock. Starts below bulge and goes up. Side platform (ledge) is out.

description: Start low in depression with your hand in lowest slot. Move up through the pockets, and then top out on some suspicious rock.
location: Look for depression area of main traverse directly behind large tree. Down climb off opposite side of boulder.

description: Stand start on sloper and traverse right. Pull two powerful moves to gain jug at lip.
Route follows vertical crack on main face of boulder. V3-4 if you use crack for hands and feet. If you use face of boulder for feet and only use crack for hands, it eases the grade to V1/2.
location: Follow obvious vertical crack on main face of boulder.

description: Start on pockets right of UP! and move up on the blank-ish face to the top.
location: Start on pockets on right side of large vertical crack, Up! and lower vertical crack
West Wall. Start in the woods to save strength.
protection: None needed. Pads for the cautious (you are only getting max of 10 feet off the ground)

description: Crack immediately when you turn the corner of the west-wall. Short bouldering problem with sadly boring moves. Lots of ways to cheat and not use the crack. Worth doing but nothing interesting here.
location: Far right of West-Wall.

description: Start low and left, move up on small ledges, traverse right up high to black hole.
location: Middle of the right part of the wall, near the end, left of the Cracken by about 20 feet.
Main face of Electric Avenue.

description: Low start on your choice of block jugs. Pull through roof and traverse feature on slots and pockets to jug at lip.
location: Located in the center of the cliff where the roof breaks.

description: Start on a jug at the back of the overhang, make a couple moves up on big holds to get past the overhang, then finish on big and dirty holds.
location: Middle of overhang

description: Sit start on pocket mini jugs. ¬†Move up and left to a long, incut jug and continue up to the highest point on the boulder.
protection: 1-2 crash pads, the landing is sloped.

description: Sit start on a low ledge right of the arete. ¬†This is the same starting hold as Borgin.¬† Move up to a pocket with your left, the right to flat, gaston. ¬†Follow the sidepulls past a hueco to the top. ¬†Aim for a notch.
protection: 1-2 crash pads, the landing is sloped.

description: Yellow is a V0+ with two good solid crimps and then big move into a crack (can‚Äôt really see it when on the wall) and then climb up and top out to the right. The blue holds make it a V2 variation with a quick move to the yellow right hand start and then follow the yellow route. The bottom blue circle is the foot.
location: The right side of Crinoid Cove. Around the corner of The Surfing Raptor.
protection: 1 or 2 pads and a spotter. We had 1 pad.

description: Left of shark week. The harder line up the middle. Pop to a good right hand¬†side pull halfway up.
Start at the far right with both hands in the two small pockets. Traverse to the left until you reach corner where most people will down climb to get off the boulder. Top out from there.
location: Start is on the side of the boulder facing the Giddy Up boulder.

description: Start on the same hands as Everything is Matter. Move up to a gaston with your left to a pinch on a tooth. Get a hand on a less-than-ideal crimp and finish with a topout.
location: Same start as Everything is Matter. Runs vertically between Turd Burglar and Chundercling.
Sit start on the lowest left shelf, same as Gaston Bone

description: Long but secure moves to the top, fun top out.
location: Left crimp and right slot just above and right of detached block.

description: Somewhat contrived. Stay in narrow lane, don't use holds out left on "Shark Week". Start on jug and climb straight up blank steepness through a couple small holds.
location: Start in middle of steepest part of the boulder, just right of shark week.

description: Start on obvious flat jug follow good holds straight up the face to top out.
location: Down the hill to the left of Ape Index.

description: Start with left hand on a geometric ledge and right on an incut within the seam above the rightmost death block on the left side of the boulder. Place a high foot and launch past Everything is Matter and Rest Day, Best Day's rail to dunk on the good spot on the lip. Mantle on secure holds and reflect on the vast oceans that once occupied the Ohio Valley.
location: The start holds are to the left of Turd Burglar and to the right of Gaston Bone and Crinoid Temptations
protection: Mega pads and spotters unless you can fly

description: I didn't see any chalk on this route, and the landing is really bad so I may have been the first to put this up, not sure though. Some techy moves up a block. Possibly some loose holds, be careful. Also, top out is scary.
location: Left side of the boulder, sit start on some light colored ledges.

description: This is a long extension into Feather Star. Start by using a left side pull and a flake, then traverse right into Feather Star.
location: It starts just to the left of Rest Day, Best Day, and finishes where Feather Star ends.

description: The easiest line to the top. Follow the flakes to the lip.
protection: Multiple pads. Its a bit tall.

description: This is an extension to Feather Star. Start using the same starting hold for Shark Week. Traverse to the right to link into Feather Star
location: Start at Shark Week and finish in Feather Star

description: Traverse left and dyno to topout.
location: Start left of Feather Star
Left side of the Crinoid cave.

description: Right of shark week. ¬†Right hand Undercling to left hand funk knob to jug¬†rail.

Start on The Surfing Raptor and continue around the arete, traversing low with your feet on the ramp. ¬†Once you encounter a good slot and left hand side pull pinch, cross up to a crimp, then move left to a ledge. ¬†Traverse left into Gaston Bone and top out on the arete.
location: The boulder starts on the lower left end of the Crinoid Cove boulder and traverses all the way to the right.
protection: 3-4 Crash pads.  The landing at the end of the boulder when you move to top out is covered in pointed rocks.  Spotters to move the pads as you traverse are helpful as well.

description: Same start as Riptide. Pull left to undercling, make big move to slopers and top out.
location: Just to the left of the prominent prow of the Crinoid boulder.

description: Sit start on a low ledge right of the arete. ¬†This is the same starting hold as Burkes. ¬†Move left on pockets and crimps, then right to a large gaston. ¬†Continue past a hueco to good ledges before topping out.
protection: 1-2 crash pads, the landing is sloped.

location: Right side of Giddy Up by arete.

description: Start on the right side of the face, and walk your hands up the arete as you climb to the top.
location: Right arete on Giddy Up
Left side of main face of Giddy Up
Right side of arete on Giddy Up

description: Start on two good pockets below the shelf, gain the face using your choice of holds. Move up and right to a nice top out.
location: Left side of the overhang facing the river.

description: Sit start at the obvious crack on the right side of the wall, follow the crack line to the top, two move traverse left to mantle top out.
location: Right side of the wall with the obvious deep crack.

description: Sit start using large right hand pocket and smaller left pocket. Move up to ledges below blank section, plan your feet, because they will disappear. Use high feet to get to crux, and work your way through to the top out.
location: Center of wall. Starts under the more blank area of the wall and works slightly right into the more pocketed portion of the wall.
This route is the right route on the blank face on Tinkerbell boulder. Visible from the main path.

description: Mantle start on the short rock in between the down paths, work your way clockwise around the entire boulder. End on the mantle you start on.
location: Tinkerbell boulder is the second boulder you see when walking down the path developed across the lowlands of the Taylor Property. Start of this route is on the backside of the boulder (opposite side of the path).

description: Sit start low using telephone-isa hold on left side of platform, climb straight up, using only holds on the left of the vertical crack. Top out.
location: From the Taylor Property path, locate the blank face of Tinkerbell boulder and walk right to the back right arete on the boulder.

description: Start in double handed shield plate down low and right. Traverse left while moving slightly up until you reach the blanker section of wall. Head up and top out.
location: You can see this route from the Taylor Property trail. It is located on the left side of the boulder. You will see a finger size vertical crack that goes up the boulder and a blanker section of white and gray rock. This section is before the heavily pocketed rock that makes up most of this face of the rock.

description: Climb the crack starting as low as possible. The lower you start, the harder it is. Top out through the depressed ledges.
location: Route on left crack on blank section of boulder. Visible from the Taylor Property path.

description: Sit start low on horizontal ledge. Climb up on right side of arete. Top out.
location: From the Taylor Property path, locate the blank face on Tinkerbell boulder and then walk around to the right back corner arete.

description: Double hand low start using horizontal slot. Climb straight up the arete and top out. Try to stay in between the two vertical cracks on the left and right side of the arete.
location: From the Taylor Property path, locate the blank face on Tinkerbell boulder and then walk around to the right back corner arete.

description: Start low on arete, climb the overhang and topout over the bulge

Start on far right side on low vertical ledge. Then move to the left on some nice pocket/jugs and pull the slab section from the protruding arete with the chicken head on top. Finish at the peak of the slab where it becomes a triangle.
location: Starts on far right side low on vertical ledge

description: This climb is okay. ¬†It makes a good warmup if you're going to try Boone Saloon. ¬†From the start holds, make a ¬†few moves to get a huge left hand jug-sidepull and then reach up with your right hand to a high jug rail. ¬†The rest is just an easy and sketchy top out. ¬†Same start holds as Boone Saloon.
location: Left side of Borsmith Block.¬† Can be seen from inside Crinoid Cove.
Right of Battlement Lefty. First column on East-wall.

description: Traverse Begins with hands on 2nd and 3rd blocks from turret. use blocks as the only handholds, either side pulling or just flat out gripping them. route ends with both feet on keystone. crux starts on the black rock, be careful coming off here and slipping your feet inside the arch
location: starts in the corner right by heaven is a second
protection: pad at the very end near keystone

location: This is the right dihedral formed between the main wall facing the road and the shorter, right white buttress (battlement).
east side of the wall, second column if your coming from the parking lot. Should be pretty obvious.
protection: pads or no pads, only gets sketchy towards the finish and its all into flat grass so not a big deal

location: Far right, at the second column on the East-Wall at the start of "Pocket 'n Lock it".
protection: 1-2 bouldering pads, probably a spotter too. Or a rope.

first_ascent: Madison Deckert FFA Jimmy Dirr FMA
description: 'Trad' may be pushing it here - but if you're looking for a place to practice placing 2 pieces of gear, 15 feet or less off the ground, this is the route for you!
location: Far right, at the second column on the East-Wall (Follows a similar line to "My Dirty Crack")

description: A classic to the area, this climb was attempted so many times that the flat, slopey feet on the arch are now extremely slick, making the climb basically a campus with annoyingly slippery feet. Personally, I have not found the climb to be much fun at all, especially since you are essentially down-climbing the second half of the climb (I should mention this is the harder half).
location: The largest arch, visible from the parking lot and road-way.
protection: Bouldering pads and someone to move them.

description: Stand up start, work your way up to the right using a sloper and a crimp. Then a big throw to a nice hold. Continue to work your way up the boulder to a top out.
location: This problem is on the backside of the pit climbing area. Walk through the pit and immediately to the left you will see a large boulder. The start to this problem is on backside of it.

description: Start from the undercling pocket and crimp and make some big moves up to the jug for a fun mantle finish.
location: Directly right of Kerchak

description: Start under the over hang and work yourself up. Once you get yourself up on the ledge work left and mantel to the top out.
location: Walk about 20 yards outside of the main Pit area. The start is on the backside of the large boulder on your left side.

description: Start on the right side of the face and traverse low cross the entire face. You can continue traversing around the entire boulder or you can climb up for a top out. Nice boulder to warm up on. Nice problem to work footwork.
location: Walk left out of the pit area and there will be a lone boulder about 20 yards on the left side of the trail.

description: Tricky start and first couple of moves. Traverse to the right and then up to an easier top out.
location: When you arrive in the main Pit bouldering, walk straight about 10 yards and the start is on the boulder on your right.

description: Stand up start then work your way up the route using a few crimps and mossy slopers to an easy top out.
location: Once arriving at The Pit bouldering area make a left and walk to the backside of the first boulder. The problem will be directly at that back of the rock.

description: Start standing up on the crimps. Then work your way up to the right. The crux is a big throw to a crimp.
location: The back side of the boulder on the left when entering The Pit.

description: Start low and work yourself up the right side of the wall to top out.
location: Located on the backside of the big boulder located in the center of the Pit area.

description: Start standing up and using the solid holds to work your way straight up the problem to a top out.
location: Once you arrive in the pit climbing area. There will be a big boulder immediately on your left. This is were the start to this problem is.

description: Stand up start, work your way straight up the boulder to a top out. Holds can be a little sharp and rough on the hands.
location: Walk directly into the pit climbing area and make a left for 10ft. The start to the problem will be directly on your right.

description: Start standing up directly behind the tree. Move up and then traverse left across the face to a top out.
location: The start is behind a large elm tree. The boulder is to the left of the trail leaving the pit area.

description: Start sitting down and work your way straight up the problem. Holds can be a little sandy and slippery.
location: When you arrive in The Pit make a left and the problem is on the back side of the boulder.

description: Start down low on the under hang. The crux is the big throw with the right, followed by another throw with your left.
location: Located on the backside of the pit climbing area. Once you leave the pit there will be a large boulder on your left side. The start is on the backside of it.

description: Sit down start, work your way up the boulder using pretty solid holds to a top out.
location: This problem is located as soon as you arrive into the Pit climbing area. It is the first boulder on your right.

description: Start standing up with a double under cling holds. Work your way right and then up to a top out.
location: Once you arrive in the pit via approach trail, the start is on the back side of the most centrally located boulder.

description: Start sitting down. The crux in this problem is the throw/dyno to the left handed sloper depending on how long you are. Once you get his move you will continue working your way up the boulder using some pretty decent holds.
location: The start to this problem is on the back side of the Pit climbing area to the left. Directly next to the Tecumseh problem.

description: Start in the pocket on the left face of the tiny battlement, move to crack on the rectangle parts of the battlement, then do fun move to the lip. Worth doing but not worth telling your friends about.
location: The teeny, tiny battlement on the East wall, facing the road.

description: Highly balance-dependent slab problem that benefits from soft shoes and a good friction day. Similar difficulty to Bauman's Problem, but located on the right face of "the Arete". Arete is in.

Left dihedral formed by the wall and the tallet battlemont. Lower holds are fairly polished. It's not a spectacular climb, but it is one of the better known routes in the area. Use the wall for most of your holds, occasionally using the battlemont for foot holds. Top out it possible, but more difficult due to the overhang.
location: Left of the first battlemont you pass walking from the parking lot
protection: Set up a top rope using the black fence at the top.

description: This problem is the left face of "The Arete", where you don't use the arete. Very balancey problem; it helps to attempt it when its cold, because it is very friction dependent.
location: Left face of "The Arete", the concrete face that is clearly visible from the parking lot.
The right face (only!) of the left-most battlement.
Along the front (roadside-facing) wall of the main Eden park climbing wall

description: Fun Climb along up the column using lots of side-pulls and deep cracks. Top out is possible. You will need to set up a top-rope on the fence at the top for this one to work.
location: East wall, first, biggest column on the left side.
protection: Rope! Be careful setting up the top rope on the fence at the top, check for rust and make sure its secure.

description: Start on the left face of the battlemount and traverse right. Two-move crux as you transition from the left to the front face with a difficult fall-in left hand to a crimp. Good holds at the start and finish.
location: Left-most, tallest battlemount on the East Wall.
protection: No bouldering pads if you want to risk a rolled ankle, but you probably would be fine.

location: You'll see it instantly when you park in the parking lot in front of the east wall. Check area photos for more location information.
protection: One bouldering pad (or none, its not that high)

location: East-Wall, first arch structure that you'll see. Directly right to "The Arete" and left of "Battlement Lefty"
protection: 1 Bouldering pad + someone to move it or 2 pads and nobody

location: The left face of the teeny battlement to the far right of the East wall, facing the road.

description: This boulder climbs really well. ¬†It is one of my favorites in the mad. ¬†It's high in the air but the landing is nice and flat. ¬†Be careful at the top, the climbing gets easy but ¬†the rock quality gets questionable. ¬†Same start as Social Distancing.
location: This boulder is on the left side of Borsmith Block (if facing the cliff line). ¬†It can almost be seen from inside of Crinoid Cove.
protection: A couple pads and maybe someone to help move them.

description: Mug Thug is the V3 maybe a 4 that starts on the central low arete with one hand on the good lip and the other on top as a pinch. Then move straight up to the flake above the start and work your way a little to the right to find the big pocket on the vertical face. It's a little throw to find the monster jug that you use to pull yourself up onto the slab section. Lastly navigate your way straight to the top right up the middle of the slab.
location: Stars on the central low arete with one hand on the good lop and the other on top as a pinch.

description: Start on flake, climb up and right to the easy topout
Sit start with feet to right, climb through pockets
Start low on arete staying off the rail, low traverse in pockets to far left, topout over the corner.
Start on flake, climb up and left to the easy topout.
Start on left corner, stay low, traverse right using pockets until around arete, topout on arete
location: Starts on left side of boulder and moves right to arete.
Right most route at yellow if looking at the cliff.
protection: Top rope from fixed anchor on top of cliff. Bring webbing or static rope for setup.

description: Is the easiest for climbing and the best for rappelling.  Organized groups may reserve this site by calling the park office in advance.
location: Rightmost of Black wall

description: This route follows the jam crack and uses pockets on the right side.
location: RIghtmost Pink Bolts. Left side crack.

description: Blue Right can be conquered 3 ways. The first being a level of 5.8 if you take the crack to the left is known as ¬ìBat Crack.¬î The second route- ¬†¬ìSnake Ledge-¬î the crack to the right is a 5.7. If you're looking for a harder challenge (5.9?), try tackling the bulge in the middle directly by starting on Snake Ledge and- instead of trending right- climb straight up the crack and throw almost blind for one of the myriad dirty pockets above you. Pull the few hard moves over the bulge and you'll be at the top in no time.
location: Rightmost Blue route

description: Orange Left, located at the orange site is given a rating of 5.10A.  This climb involves a boost or a jump for a tall person in order to get to the starting holds. Once the face is obtained, the route is face climbing and overhanging.
location: Leftmost of Orange wall

description: Climb the leftmost side of the rock face.
location: Left most Blue route.

description: Left side offers a bouldering start with some decent finger pockets to pull through the first ten feet. eases up for a juggy finish. Starting at the vertical crack directly below the right anchor, traverse slightly right to finish on right anchor, or traverse left to finish below left anchor.
location: park at Wingo Picnic Area. take path to cliff top. right at wooden overlook deck, and take trail 50-100 feet.  Anchors are 20 feet left off trail at top of cliff and easily identifiable.
protection: top rope only.  two bomber eye-bolt anchors.  given their distance apart and away from top lip, using both creates too much rope drag.

description: Green Right is a little easier with a rating of 5.8 if you take the crack to the left, and 5.7 if you do the lie back crack on the right.
location: Rightmost green route

description: Green Left includes a crux near the top at the overhang with a 5.9 level of difficulty if you take a direct line up. Varying from the direct line can increase the difficulty to 5.10.
location: Climbers far left in the Green area. Anchors closest to the wooden lookout platform

description: This one can be climbed a few different ways, and crack start was my favorite. If you follow the crack and keep going to the right, it will be a little easier to complete with large foot holds. If you stay left it is a little more challenging but it ends with some good shelves
location: Park at the Wingo lot and hike to the trail head and turn left. The Green route is the first one you will come to

description: Smooth start, decent reach to a solid ridge. Move off two horizontal pinch holds to some small pockets above. Slight mantle before roof finish.
location: Rightmost Pink Bolts, right side line

description: Short route directly under rightmost Pink bolts. Middle section has reachy crux with some unsure footing, then finishes with a large roof
location: Middle line under the rightmost Pink bolts.

description: Pink Middle is 5.5 to 5.6 with an awkward start that requires a left foot smear on the face, or wedging a foot in the large crack. If the right side of pink B is taken the rating goes down to 5.3 or 5.4. It is another large crack and those climbing for the first time on real rock will find the crack use very different from gym climbing.
location: Middle pink route

description: Pink Left is a high overhanging wall with a difficult start. It has been rated 11B to C.
location: Leftmost Pink bolts. Center route

description: This rappel site has a lovely 5.2 climb on the arete. If you equalize your anchors well and throw the rope down on the other side of the tree you can also climb further left of the arete. It's a lovely 5.2 climb until you hit a blank looking section just below the top. Pull a single balancy 5.4 move to reestablish on the good holds and you'll be at the top.
location: Left most of Black wall
protection: Top Rope.  Bring extra webbing for your anchor as the eye bolts sit about four feet back from the edge.

description: Is the large block behind which forms the cave is stemmed it the rating is 5.8, and if the face is used the difficulty is increased to 5.9.
location: Middle route on Yellow wall.

description: involves some under-cling to surmount the bulge and gain the face.
location: Yellow leftmost.
From the Wingo parking lot take a left at the observer deck and it is the last set of routes in this area.

description: Red Middle is a crack climb that uses lie-back, and under-cling. It might have some water on it, but goes at about 5.6. It will require more strength, but less finesse.
location: Middle of the red climbs.

description: Red Left is a face climb that requires balance and finger tip strength, and goes to the notch at the top with a difficulty of 5.7.
location: Left red route.

description: Using only a combination of side pulls on the arete and the crack, hug your way to the top. Feet are a mix of hooks, wedges and shelves on the natural features. Can get a bit more difficult near the top with the wide pulls.
location: The route is just to the right of the Crack formation.
The Tarantula boulder, on the same face.
protection: Pads. A spotter is nice for the last move

description: Traverse the jugs Splinter Cell style. Work your way up to and top out to the right of Jane Doe
location: Around the Left corner of Jane Doe

description: Pull past a hand ledge and navigate big pockets to an easy top out. Try not to disturb the bird nests!
location: Located on the right side of The Patio Boulders. Take the path down to the water and find the sunny boulder on the water with features similar to "The Hive".

description: Sit start and pull a high foot and continue straight up until the top out. Avoid the aretes.
location: To the right of Good Fortune.

description: Clean arete face with a beautiful background for that perfect photo opportunity. Sit start low on two pockets right side of arete. Utilize crimps and pockets to climb straight up the arete to an easy top out.
location: On the lake, to the right of Aztec Warrior

description: Climb up tallest part of boulder to top out for a beautiful view.
location: Within the patio boulders.

description: A few different routes on this one. Can climb up the side¬†‚Äãwhere there's a crack, or can start on the side and traverse left onto the ledge and top out.
location: Up the hill a little bit from the patio boulders. Should basically run into it from the Pinecrest loop trail (blue blazes)

description: Start the climb around the corner from Jane Doe, as far right as you can on the long, low, flat edge. One of the cruxes is not dabbing at the beginning. ¬†Traverse the face, and move around the arete and finally finish with John Doe. ¬†Super great/pumpy climb for the area.
location: Same boulder as John and Jane Doe.

description: Semi-reminiscent of Dial 911 at Rocktown, only easier. Start beneath the large overhanging boulder at the shore line on the lowest large pocket jugs. Pull on and climb up and left, surmounting the roof and climbing the steep face using "choose your hold" tactics.
location: On the patio Boulder

description: The slab on the right side of the Iron Resolve boulder. Use cool vertical iron features to climb the short slab.
location: Iron Resolve Boulder

description: With rock reminiscent of Coopers, this problem will be an Ohio classic once it is sent. Sit start on sculpted underclings, figure out how to get your butt off the ground, and follow sculpted crimps and slimpers to an easier topout. Grade is an estimate.
location: On the Iron Boulder, directly up hill from the Meteor Bloc.

description: Starts on a bean shaped iron feature on the right side of the clean white face. Climb sharp holds to an easy topout.
location: Iron Resolve Boulder

description: Same start as John Doe, but after establishing yourself beneath the roof, climb to the right and out the imposing bulge. Big holds and some air under your feet.
location: The lakeside face of the Patio Boulder
protection: A few crashpads and attentive spotters

description: Climb the tall boulder starting a little bit right-of-center and use the small ledges to top out. Lots of potential on this one & many different ways to climb it.
location: Upwards of the hive Boulder. If the hive is the first boulder you see on your right, this will be up on your left. To the right of Arrowhead arete.

description: If you understand the reference, this arete lives up to the name
location: Located around the left side of Jane Doe go pass the Tom Clancy Traverse to the next boulder.

description: Steep, solid rock that offers the best warm ups in the area. As its covered with all sorts of holds, it is hard to define individual problems, but I've had hours of fun with this one just making up eliminates and trying hard.
location: The steep, pocketed face of the Hive Boulder

description: Sit start left hand on small knob like feature, right hand on pocket. Straight up through crimps and over the ledge. Top out through the grass or traverse left and out once over the ledge.
location: Left most problem on the boulder. Left of Backbend
protection: Pads and spotter, top out is heady and grassy, but doable.

description: Starts sitting on huge jug beneath the crack splitting the tall face. Work up into the crack and make a few more moves to an easy heady topout
location: Behind the hive boulder. Route splitting the tall face

description: Trends left on the side of the Hive Boulder. Sit start on low jugs to the right, then follow good holds up and left to a top out at the apex of the boulder.
location: Lakeside face of the Hive Boulder

description: Start by climbing up the part protruding from underneath the boulder so you can reach good crimps. Slightly traverse right on decent feet and figure out how to use the diagonal rails to reach the huge jug slightly beneath the top. Be Careful topping out.
location: On the face that is facing directly towards the water on the same boulder as "Cloud Nine".
protection: 2 or 3 crash pads would be ideal.

description: The tall attractive lakeside arete. Start on underclings with a large ledge foot and figure out how to reach distant holds higher up on the arete.
location: The tall arete on the Meteor Bloc. See the topo for location.

description: A fun, but contrived power problem. Sit start on the short steep face on the backside of the Hive Boulder on two chalked sloping crimps. Avoiding the large holds out left, move up and right to a sloping pinch/crimp, the fire up and left for another slopey pinch. Definitely an eliminate, but still fun.
location: Backside of the Hive Boulder

description: The variety of holds and quality of movement make this one worth checking out. Start in the low dual pockets and work your way up a sloper and crimp rails to gain the slab face. Proceed straight up to the ledge under the wave face where you'll understand the problems name. Traverse left along the ledge to walk off.
location: On the wall behind the Hive boulder. The wide slabby face to the left of Have Horse, Will Travel.

description: Climb the rails and jugs on the slab to a nice top out and enjoy the view.
location: Located at The Patio Boulders around the corner of  The Roost. Walk past John Doe and go right. Find the boulder on the water on the edge.

description: Sit start on the under cling on the left and heel hook the right side of the arete. Find the slopers  and a super easy top out. Hardest part is the first two moves.
location: Left of Have Horse, Will Travel

description: Yeah it‚Äôs roadside, but the hike down 146¬†still kinda sucks. But this boulder problem doesn‚Äôt! Well it‚Äôs not the best, but you‚Äôre in Zanesville climbing so chill and have fun.

Reachy, powerful moves on a steep overhang with few usuable features. Powerful compression moves to start, entering the crux almost immediately once you pull on the start crimps. Tarantula is nestled into the hillside and has an interesting walkable/climbable cave system underneath. Very fun. Very unique!
location: Sit start with feet on small chips under a ledge, hands on semi high crimps (if you‚Äôre short). Power up to an open hand crimp on a small slopey ledge, compress, match, catch feet and head to the undercling. Collect yo‚Äôself and power¬†into small crimps leading to a large ledge at the top out.

description: Reach up to some incut holds facing the wrong way. Pull on and make big moves up the steep wall. Committing finish.
location: Starts to the right of "Tarantula" on some incut crimps surrounding the obvious rock scar (Previous starting hold)
protection: A few pads and a spotter would be nice for the last move

description: The name says it all. Slip-N-Slide. Small holds, balancey moves and so much moss.¬†Usually it‚Äôs green and actively growing moss. But once in a while, on a cool fall afternoon, after some careful brushing...it goes!
location: Stand start at the bottom of the slab, small crimps to start, use the mono and the arete to work upward.

description: Around the corner on the Tarantula Boulder. Start on the bottom left arete and move up and right to "The Rug". Just wipe your feet off or mom's gonna kill me!

Mammoth is a large boulder hosting multiple lines of varying difficulties. Not a fun hike, but a very easy hike. Head towards Zanesville (river on your right) until you see a large boulder over the guardrail on the right.
location: Start in the crack under the overhang at the base of the boulder. Continue to follow the crack until it ends and jugs appear.

description: In a hallway of doom and mosquitos a very unique problem lurks. The first visible boulders as you round the top of the hill from parking.
location: Sit start left, working the huecos out right through a horizontal series of heel and toe hooks. Land the big swing or beta ball your way through to the right side by the tree to top out.

description: Far right at the Lakeside set, in a hole, really close to the road. Also the¬†home of a frequented geo cache.
location: Sit start using crimps/slots and small rails for feet. Work up on the arete out left and the slopers straight above. Once you‚Äôre to the sloper mantle, pick feet wisely and reach to the crimps above. Standing up will let you walk it out to the top. Wave to passing traffic. It‚Äôs always fun the looks they give!

description: Creeky emerges from the creek below Taratula. Makes a great warm up and has a lot of variations. I like to start my day at the lakeside set at Creeky, followed up by Tarantula and work my way boulder to boulder back to the truck.
location: I‚Äôm the creek below Tarantula. Careful not to get too wet getting to the start. Pockets and heal hooks on the blade lead to small foot chips and great holds above. Tons of variations. Top out around the corner.

description: The crux is two thirds of the way up.  The main line runs up just to the left of the anchor.
location: On the middle column, just to the left of the low side of the arch when standing under it facing the middle column.
protection: Top rope from to anchor carabiners

description: Good mix of traversing and variety of holds. Can be completed by staying to the far left using the arete but uses more slopey shelves. Can get quite warm in the sun but a great climb none the less.
location: It is on the south face to the left of the crack. Directly in front of the information board.

description: One of the most difficult climbs at the wall when only using the natural formation. The crux is definitely between bolt 3 and 4. Without giving too much beta the main lines run up the bolts as well as a full arm length to the right of the bolts.
location: Main face opposite the water tower.
protection: 5 bolts with 2 opposite and opposing biners at the top.

description: A nice mix of shelves and lay backs. Not sure about the crux but a slightly awkward start when staying on the main line. A fun variation is to run the arete to the right of the main line, which has a good mix of side pulls and slopers.
location: Between first and third anchors to the right of the mini arch.

description: The crux is at about the center of the route if stay on the center line. Its a great climb because its overlapped by one of the easiest climbs using holds. As a result you can keep a rope up for your friend who is new to climbing while allowing you to climb the more difficult natural climb.
location: First climb just to the right of the bouldering arch.

description: Long pumpy route over the large arch of the wall. Its a good climb for endurance but not too heavy on the technical climbing aspect. Primary done with holds but always interested to see if someone can complete it with just features/natural (it would definitely increase the difficulty without holds).
location: Starts on the East side of the wall facing the main parking lot. Best to clean by top roping and belaying from the opposite side (Top Rope chains).
protection: 7 bolts, top chains with two carabiners to top rope

description: This interesting route because the climb from the roof down is 2 solid grades more difficult than above the roof. The crux is passing the roof. There are two easier methods for climbing the route which are by shifting either to the right or left of the main line.
location: On the east face between the two arches.
protection: Two carabiners at the top anchors
Protection is solid but a crash pad is nice for the arch and the high top out.

description: The crack climb at the wall. The two cracks are a little uncommon because they flare out on the inside allowing for fist stacking and even full arm jams. Proving to be for fun experimentation as well as technical crack climbs. The crux is actually at the top just past the last bolt making it difficult to clip the top anchors without using the holds.
