location: Just next to the main information board.
protection: 5 bolts with 2 carabiners as the top anchors.

description: This can be climbed on either top rope or auto belay. It is a great mix of mantel and stemming movements.
location: The main dihedral to the left of the Auto Belay device.
protection: Same two carabiners at the top.

description: Natural features only. For the 5.10b grade, the route must be climbed without using the ar√™te to the left or the crack to the right. Start on the face, left of the crack on the south end side of the wall. Work through the first couple of reachy holds to some thin leaning crimps. Pull through the crux about two thirds of the way up to a balanced finish at the anchors.
location: Left of the south end crack formation.
protection: 5 bolts with 2 opposite and opposing carabiners for anchors.

description: Start near the left side of the small arch on two pinches and make it back to the same start! This problem is easier to do when the auto-belays have been taken down. Take a no-hands rest near the easy auto-belay halfway through and get ready to get low and make it under the arch to the finish.
location: Look for a yellow hold that is circled in colorful chalk on the left side of the small arch, to the left of it are two large pinches.

description: All natural holds. ¬†If you can do with holds you can do all natural. ¬†Good mixture of side holds and some jugs. ¬†The crux is the last 6 ft of the route with¬†very crimpy small holds.
location: Auto belay on the southeast facing corner. ¬†Can be either TR or autobelay
See Picture.

description: Use "natural" features only. The crux is the last move before the top. Top out to finish. It's definitely more friendly to lengthier folk. If you don't use the slopey jug rail on the right a few feet above the start holds it's a bit harder.
location: It's on the lowest section that you climb up to set top ropes, on the side facing the parking lot.

description: Nice hand crack. There is a chalkstone about the size of a bread box about 8' up in the crack. Small hands to the bread box then opens up and closes again to a hand and fist crack.
location: About 150' down the cliff from Mickey Mantle (approx. 110 steps from garbage can)

description: Climb up the face a couple feet right of the Ban The Bomb crack to reach shallow, left-facing seam. Where the seam ends use small pockets, uderclings, side pulls, and a thin crimp to work your way up through the small roof.
location: Right of Ban the Bomb

description: Climb the face to a large gully then right of the gully up a small crack good top out
location: This rout is twenty feet left of Harmony Crack

description: Ascend thin, blocky holds up the ar√™te located to the left of Mail Slot
Start up a few face moves to gain a crack in a shallow, left-facing, corner that arches over slightly to the right and then goes straight up.
location: To the left and around the corner from Ban The Bomb and Shruti.

description: Surmount the bulge and mantle up into the dihedral to gain a finger crack. Continue up the dihedral using the crack and stemming to reach the top.
location: Harmony Wall at Paint Creek State Park OH.  Left of the Buckeye Buttress ar√™te is a dihedral.

description: Follow the seam in the middle of the face located between Red hawk Ar√™te and Bearcat Chimney. Variations exist on either side of the seam.

Start about 10 feet right of the slot under a left-facing, arching bulge. Climb the face to reach a crack just left of the bulge and continue up the crack to where it ends in a roof. Traverse left under the roof until you can surmount the roof up through the slot.
location: Harmony Wall Paint Creek State Park OH.  Look for a prominent slot above a small overhang about 50 feet left of the Mickey Mantle dihedral.

description: Start directly underneath the slot and climb up the light colored streak on the face through the overhang at the slot
location: Look for a prominent slot above a small overhang about 50 feet left of the Mickey Mantle dihedral.

description: The route climbs the nose of the ar√™te. Start directly in front of the ar√™te which is under cut and there is a small rock on the ground directly below. Boulder your way up using the cracks and face holds to gain the ar√™te. Follow the ar√™te to the top exit right or lower. The route has lots of lichen but all the holds needed have been cleaned and the climb is well worth doing. The start can be a bit challenging.
location: This is a large ar√™te about 10' left of "Who Forgot the Jam?¬î

description: Stem up the shallow, left-facing, dihedral and then use the hand crack and/or face holds to climb up into the gully above. Continue up the crack, left of the gully.
location: This route ascends the obvious dihedral and crack left and around a corner from Gumby's Gully.

description: Scramble up this easy short crack
location: Located half way between Peacenik and Harmony Crack.

description: Climb up through a large roof then pull your way through the green moss
location: Located ten feet left of Gumby's Gully

description: Straight forward, follows the arete up pockets and crimps.
location: Ascends the first ar√™te beyond where the trail to the base of the cliff splits off of the Harmony Trail.
protection: TR, very hard to protect with gear.  Could go on small pro maybe up to finger sized stuff in a few pods.

description: Work your way up the obvious chimney to offwidth and climb through the overhang using the hand crack in the dihedral above.  (Best if climbed in the fall or winter to avoid the spiders.)
location: Harmony Wall, located in the dihedral left of the Miami Wall face

description: Jam and crank up the obvious crack in the overhanging face left of Bearcat Chimney and Shruti.
location: On the face to the left of Bearcat Chimney

description: Good beginner route with easy anchor points. One slightly awkward move in the middle of the route which requires some balance.  Watch your footing while belaying and have something to keep the rope off the ground.
location: After following the path to the cliff edge, turn right and walk down the path past the blue routes.
protection: Bolts at the top for setting the rope. Recommend bringing extra webbing.

description: Just like swimming, this one is easier than it looks. ¬†Enjoy a nice flow of movement on good holds.
location: Runs up the middle of the steep face

description: A very fun climb that follows the obvious line up the middle of the crack/chimney.¬†Pull the initial reachy bulge to get started, enjoy easier ground through the middle, and then work through the last tricky bit of stemming before you clip the chains.
location: Starts in a wide crack with a faint "790" visible written on the rock in large lettering. ¬†About 10 ft right of a large tree growing leaning away from the cliff.

description: Right side of the wall immediately to the left of the very low angle slab routes. Techy vertical climbing on small but positive holds to a very balancy crux.

Climb up a crack to an ear feature and launch into the ever steepening wave where you make some desperate moves to a fantastic friendly jug. ¬†Shake out, because it is not over and slopers guard your run to the chains.
location: From the main trail cut left and walk up the wave wall. ¬†This is right of the 3 lines, equipped with glue ins.

description: Climb a steep opening with excellent movement to a series of small crimps. ¬† Then either get dynamic to get to the anchors or figure out how to crimp on a sloping rail. Often wet, but a great route if you can catch it dry.
location: From the main trail in, take the left fork.¬† This is the middle of 3 lines on the Wave Wall

description: Ends on Get Railed. Start on sloper rail, make a few moves up semi¬†bad holds straight up and end on good jug. Short and sweet
location: Left of Get Railed, last obvious holds before the moss takes over the rock.

description: Engaging climbing with some excellent sequences. ¬†Often wet in the spring, get on it in the fall
location: Walk left at the cut off from the main trail which will shortly take you to wave like wall. ¬†This is the furthest left on the wall.

description: Start on left hand edge and right hand undercling. Figure out impossible static beta, or set feet and fly out to flat shelf. Traverse left and up a few moves and drop. Someone who's inspired can clean the high slab topout.
location: Left side of the Wave Wall, just left of the three bolted routes.
Starts on the obvious rail on the far left side of the Wave Cave. See Get Railed for additional info.
protection: A pad. Two if you want (no more than two pads permitted on Benjamin Button's Badass Butthole Assassin).

description: Fun little route on the right side of Wave Wall. ¬†Start with a couple of big moves up to a techy finish in a dihedral with some finger jams.
location: Right side of Wave Wall. ¬†Straight ahead as you walk up to the cliff on the approach trail.
Left side of Tsunami wall. Obvious rail.

description: The furthest right boulder problem in the cave adjacent to the wave wall. Start sitting at a rail with a variety of crimps. Without using the massive pedestal foot to the right, make one reach dependent move to the higher rail, and traverse left to finish the same as Drip. At least as long as some of the sport routes in the area
location: Start sitting at the obvious rail, in the far right of the cave. The huge foot/feature to the right is off.

description: In the cave adjacent to the wave wall. Start sitting on a good edge and the handle bar hold. Tense, crimpy undercling moves lead slightly left to a reach dependent move to the jug rail. Traverse left to one more big move off of crimps to finish in high horizontal just above the apex of the cave. Drop off, though a top out would be reasonable with some cleaning
location: In the cave adjacent to the wave wall, starts sitting to the right of Hot Pants.
Far right side of Wave Wall. ¬†Straight ahead as you walk up to the cliff on the approach trail.

description: Start right of the obvious crack, next to a tree. ¬†Reachy start, move right, and then find the hidden hold... exactly where you want it to be!
Pretty similar to the ones next too it!
right of the crack
Bouldery start to pull the first bulge, and then a little second overhand with poor holds to contend with. ¬†Got a bit harder after a hold broke at the second lip!
location: First route you come to on the access trail after turning right at the fork. ¬†Far left end of the Warm-Up Wall.

description: Follow the crack between "Get Over It" and "Stand Up and Deliver." ¬†At the V, move right to finish on the "Deliver" chains. ¬†First trad route at Marne Wall (to my knowledge).¬† Bolts? ¬†Who needs bolts?!
protection: Single rack. A #5 handy for the top

description: Climb the face left of the crack, head toward the big slot, and then traverse left under the bulge.
Thought provoking moves through the roof.
location: Just left of the giant off-width/chimney. ¬†Look for the links of chain at the 2nd bolt.

description: Another fun one with juggy holds, until they're not.
follow up on the sandstone, 4 bolts to anchor
location: Left of obvious crack. See the topo photo on the main page.
About 50 yards to the right as you approach the cliff from the road.¬† Follows the buttress between two large crack systems (that are Silver Streaks and End of Poison Ivy).

description: Vertical climbing on good but small crimps to start, followed by some thought-provoking moves up top on slopers. ¬†Don't blow it trying to clip the chains. ¬†If getting on it early in the season, convince your buddy to climb it first and brush off the finish hold for you.
Follows an angling crack up a slab.
location: Obvious slab route with large holds.

description: Another easy line with big holds and fun movement. ¬†Start in the large crack, then follow the jugs through the steep stuff. ¬†Can finish straight up staying next to the big crack, or move left into the flake to go to the upper set of anchors. ¬†Great kids/beginners route.
location: Right of the two slab jugs line.

description: Climb the vertical face to a good-sized roof/bulge.

protection: Everything from stoppers to micro-cams to a #3.  Bolted anchors

description: Great off width! Very fun with great placements. Start in the OW with good pro or climb the 5.7 face to the right with no pro to the first ledge. After the small tree mid route squeeze your way and stem up the crack. To finish, top out with a well protected but thought provoking crux. Bolted anchors in place.
location: This route is the crack to the left of ¬†Silver Streak(5.9). It has a small tree growing out of it 20‚Äô up.
protection: Standard rack, but 5s and 6s would be great although it‚Äôs doable without them, set of nuts and some slings for natural pro if your into that sort of thing.

description: Start just right of a broad shield and work your way up a vertical face. ¬†Stand on a ledge, set up and pull through the cruxy bulge up top.
Climb through a series a bulges, some easy, some hard. ¬†The last one will likely give you pause and require a pretty good reach. Take it all the way to the top on some easy but insecure slab.
location: On a buttress/bulge between two very large crack systems. ¬†Between Silver Streaks and My First Time.

description: Start in a large water runnel under the crack, stemming and chimney up the crack using large face holds on both sides.
location: Right end of Katz Wall, in the large crack right of Katz Corner.
protection: Gear from #2 to #4 or 5. Bolted anchors.

location: Starts on the chest-high holds of "Give Thanks" and traverses right, ending on the far side of the next large crack system over.
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

location: Starts in a large textured pocket under a large bulge, just to the left of the second large crack system around the corner from the Genesis Wall.
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

location: Starts in a highly texted large slot, just left of a large mossy crack system, about 50 feet climber's right of Genesis Wall.
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

description: Closed project. Hard 12? Easier 13?
location: Starts on a large right-leaning rail at the top of the trail as you come up the hill to the Genesis Wall. Goes up just right of the large obvious black streak.
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

description: Desperate climbing up the steepest part of Genesis wall.
location: Starts on the right side of the ledge under the steepness.
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

description: Start low in a thin, sloping slot with a poor left foot. ¬†Climb up through textured sloping ledges to jugs at the top. ¬†Drop from an incut ledge just below the first bolt.
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

location: In the big dihedral.¬† Last route on the right side of the crag.
protection: 2 bolts, plus thin hand sizes to #5. ¬†Bolted anchors.
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

location: Same start as Give Thanks, around the corner from the Genesis Wall
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

location: Just around the corner from the Genesis Wall. Climbs the arete to the the right of the first obvious crack past Mungdungus Corner
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

description: best part of Marne Wall
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

description: Start low and make a few delicate moves to reach a stance under the 1st bolt. ¬†Begin in earnest with a powerful move to get going and cruise up to the ledge. ¬† Hit the timer and launch into the overhanging face above where it is a race against the pump clock. ¬†While no move is particularly hard, you also don‚Äôt get much of a rest until the anchors.
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

description: This is a route where you actually get to feel like you are really rock climbing. ¬† A retro-bolt and extension of an old unknown sport line. ¬†This one is super enjoyable with a few cruxes to make things interesting.
location: Starts on the far left side of the Genesis wall. ¬† Original start is the arete down and to the left which probably up the grade by a few letters.
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

first_ascent: Jordan Katz, Oct. '19  Equipped by Ian Kirk
description: Start on the large cheater block or jump start to a large slot in front of the tree. ¬†Traverse left through the roof and move onto the pockets above.
location: Starts just right of the tree
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

route_name: Between a Flood and a Lockdown
location: Around the corner from the Genesis Wall. ¬†Starts just left of the first obvious large vertical crack.
parent_sector: F. Genesis Wall and East Side Boulders

description: Improbable climbing for the grade takes you through a series of horizontal roofs where your playgrounds monkey bar skills may pay off. ¬†Unfortunately, just when you‚Äôre starting to enjoy the¬†climbing, you‚Äôre at the lip and the ride is over. ¬† Grade may be height dependent.
location: Starts about 15 ft to to the right of the Calf Ripper crack on a vert face.
Far right end of Poison Ivy Wall, just left of the route on the corner, Casual Business

description: Start up the right side of the low scoop. ¬†Pull the start and make some easy moves on jugs. ¬†Lock it down and finish it off.
location: Starts on the face just below the right side of the low scoop

description: Start just left of the off-width roof crack and work your way right of the crack and up the steepness that requires some core fitness to get you through the roof. ¬†The finish is no gimme to the anchors. ¬†Clip the old rusty bolt and hanger as a directional only.
location: Just left of crack in middle of the wall.

description: Easy intro climbing leads to a nice boulder problem which is harder (and more fun) if you avoid the crack. ¬†Finish up on jugs.
location: Steep cave route, just left of a crack. ¬†Often wet after heavy rains or in the early spring.

description: Climb on good rock and holds through an extremely steep face requiring some core strength and big moves. ¬† ¬†Very fun, and climbs longer than it looks due to the steepness.
location: Starts on the left side of the cave routes

description: Begins with a tricky boulder problem with a sidepull to a big reach and limited feet. ¬†Regain your composure under the big roof and then jug haul your way to the lip. As you go to pull onto the face above, you may find yourself looking left... or was it right... for some decent holds. You'll figure it out!
location: Right side of the Poison Ivy Wall. ¬†Starts on the blankish face under a large roof, about 6 feet right of the hand/finger crack and just under and right of the obvious chimney that is Calf Ripper.

route_name: Don't Break It if You Can't Buy It
description: Mantle up, milk the jug, and then figure out how to get the to lip. ¬†Once you pull that one, another one awaits with easier moves... if only you could see the holds!¬† Try not to break anything.
Start under the big roof with a finger crack, move onto pockets, then traverse right into the crack to pull the roof. ¬†Stem to the top.
location: Middle of the Poison Ivy Wall. ¬†Walk right upon entering until you reach the big wall with the cave at the bottom.

description: Fantastic movement packed into a short climb! Starts with a bouldery sequence off an undercling to a rail. Power through to the good holds, get to the large shelf hold, hit the pocket and crank up and throw for the lip. It's not over yet though... A last crux awaits you as you try to pull onto the face.
location: Starts left of the finger/hand crack that is the beginning of Calf Ripper.

description: Start in the cave with an exciting and steep start to get things going. ¬†Continue past the steep stuff to more moderate vert terrain. ¬† Pull a move to gain the slab face and continue to more vert terrain. ¬†High clip the last bolt if you can and launch into the crux that will test your reach or lock off strength. ¬† If you fall, join the list of people with broken dreams of sending. ¬†Grade probably height dependent.
location: Starts in steep section on far left side of the cave.
protection: 10 bolts + anchors. ¬†Stick clip the first and make sure your belayer is ready to pull in slack as you dyno near the start. ¬†If the belayer is much lighter, it might be a good idea to anchor them to the nearby tree if you are uncertain of your dynoing abilities.

route_name: Born on the Fourth of July
protection: Standard rack to #4 plus a #5 or #6 if you want to sew up the off-width (it's very easy climbing). Some long runners to manage drag. ¬†Bolted anchors up top.

description: Easy climbing on jugs to the last ledge where you might find yourself searching for the easy beta to get to the anchors.
location: Middle of cave routes.

description: Sit start on the low left side of the boulder. Using a right hand side pulling crimp, a left hand pocket jug and solid feet on the shelf below, stand up to a small incut slot with a slopper on the outside. Traverse left, crossing the bowling ball pinch. The crux begins when you‚Äôre set up directly under the steep sloper. Right hand on the arete, left on a side pulling sloper above a small knob. Set feet, Power the right hand into the sloper, bump the left hand up to a good open hand crimp, collect and throw further up left to the victory jug. Tops out with a small foot chip just under the jug a bit.
location: North side of the Amoeba boulder (mushroom bloc). Sit starts on low left, working up to the left.
Backside of Amoeba (mushroom bloc).

description: Start on the right far right of the boulder, traverse left and then up when you hit the big hueco, top out
location: Far right of the first boulder from the approach trail

description: Middle line up the Big Tex bloc. Have your wits together as you pull over the mantle and onto the ramp.
location: Start from Lil‚Äô Tex pockets, trend up and right trough the vast amount of jugs to great mantle (mantle is just right of center bloc/just left of the tree). Once on top of the mantle, trend back left up the ramp. Crimps. Slopers. Scaries.

description: Behind Big Tex is the coolest lowball of all lowball traverses. Low and short, crux is keeping your ass off¬†the ground.
location: Sit start low right. Hand foot matches along the ledge lead to a pocket out left. Once reaching the pocket (directly about the tree) mantle out to the other pocket. Keep the form pure and the try hard hard and it‚Äôll be a blast!

description: Sit start on two good angled slopers, with feet on the semi crumbly orange and black rail below. The entire jug rail is OFF. Crux- Power to a rail center face, establish feet. Stand up using two small holds in a seam just above. Tops out straight to a small rail and¬†slopers.
location: just right of the tree growing around the rock.

description: Really fun line up a long sloper rail. Condition dependent!
location: Sit start left/directly under the edge of the boulder with two great underclings. Use caution on the first couple chossy foot holds.

description: Start off on two large handholds that have a few okay ways to be held, feet start on a rail to the left and a dish to the right. Work your way to the right through a series of side pulls on the handlebars while walking your feet along below you. Reach for a solid undercling in the big pocket. Find an okay sloper for your left hand, pop up to the slot with your right and get good feet. Reach for the book-sized pinch and pull yourself up using the tension between your right foot and hand. Get a foot out to the right and pull yourself over to the ledge and walk-up the finish to the right.
location: This route is located to the left of Crimp City on the first boulder.

description: Sit start under large hueco, left hand pinch right hand flat ledge, pull up and through the hueco, bring a high left foot to mantle up and then walk the easy top out

The slab to the left of Big Tex. Stand start with your hands in the low pockets. Find your feet up the slab to mantle off the high knob. Proceed up the low angle slab to walk off the back of the boulder.
location: obvious slab to the left of big tex ¬†on the big tex¬†boulder
protection: Pads. Small tree to fall on if you lose your balance

description: Far left line on the Big Tex boulder.
location: Stand start, hands in the waist high small pocket. Power through a left sloper foot, up and left to the ‚Äúhorn‚Äù. Work the few holds up the rail to the right, topping out on the Big¬†Tex nose.

description: Behind the Crimp City boulder is a nice jug filled wall full of fun!! The most obvious line going up this wall has a large hueco that is kinda shaped like Texas. From this, we got Big Tex...from this, we got Lil‚Äô Tex. The much less obvious line using only small mono pockets, crimps, the smallest chips for feet and nothing else. Make it as complicated as possible. Have fun!
location: Small pockets just right on Big Tex‚Äôs jugs. Straight up. Small holds only.

description: Right most line on the Big Tex boulder.
location: Stand start far right. Left hand on the arete.

description: Right of the tree, small log landing. Fun line with a lot of variation.
location: Right hand on the arete, right foot on the arete. There‚Äôs some lefts too. Do the thang.

description: Right from White Noise, start in a small side pull. Work into a small iron slot with a right crimp, left working the arete. Top out is mildly heady with small holds to top out.
location: On the mushroom shaped block. In between Amoeba/White Noise.

description: At the top of the approach trail, left of the tree growing around the rock. Sit start under the colorful orange and black nose using pinches and horrid pockets for undercut feet. Work the low crux of crimps, pinches and awkward movement over the nose. Once mantling onto the nose step out high left on the steep ramp to¬†some dark jugs leading to the top and friendly crimps.
location: Sit start far left, pinches inside the hueco, feet out right to the orange and black pockets.

description: Sit start on the far right. Traverse the rail of jugs and slopers toward the tree growing around the rock. Find a few good holds through the large hueco, topping out on slopers just right of the tree.
location: On the first boulder you reach as you come up the trail, on the far right.

description: Sit start, big semi narrow left hand pinch¬†with a left heal hole slightly under it, right hand in an orange sopey slot. Power right hand to a good sloper, left to a wide pinch. Stand into the large hueco and top out on some fair slopers.
location: Just left of the tree molding it‚Äôs growth around the rock.

description: Behind the Crimp City boulder is this large jug filled wall of fun holding all kinds of interesting problems. The most obvious, Big Tex. A favorite of children and beginners, but not for the faint of heart. The airy top out brings little security at close to 20ft off the deck and I have personally watched ankles snap from this route. Pad that shit up and don‚Äôt forget the spotter if you‚Äôre unsure! No shame in keeping your ankles together.
location: Find the large Hueco shaped like Texas. Use the large jugs in whatever fashion you prefer, trending straight up to the obvious nose. Top out right around the nose.

description: Start on a head high hueco and traverse left into Voodoo. ¬†Move into the crack whenever possible and top out.
Underneath all the white noise is cosmic background radiation. Same start and finish as the burly V8, but stay low. Work through the side pulls and crimps to the powerful top out.
location: Mushroom shaped boulder, starts and ends on white noise. Staying low off the sloper

description: Mushroom shaped boulder with two gems! Don‚Äôt forget to set your feet up to make the long reach over the lip to a half pad crimp!
location: Sit start in the large low huecos. Use pinches and slopers to work to the fun stuff. Once hanging on the sloper lip, find your feet and commit to the long reach up to a small half pad¬†crimp.

description: Start low on crimps, climb straight up through slopers and top out.
location: Left face of the Armada boulder

description: Sit start on the dagger-like jug 5 feet right of Crown Jewel. Climb straight up on crimps.
location: On the same boulder as Crown Jewel, which lies directly uphill from the Diving Board.

description: This problem climbs up the arete, left of poo in the pool. Stand start, left hand on undercling jug, right hand on undercling ledge/pinch. Climbs straight up the arete topping out directly over the arete.
location: To find this boulder and this area in general follow these directions. Park at Morgan trail parking lot. Follow the blue trail which is Morgan trail, you will pass the trail entrance to Morgan loop trail, and a sign that is marked ‚ÄúV‚Äù keep going on the blue trail straight forward. You will then hit a map sign that is marked ‚ÄúW‚Äù here you will go left onto the bridle trail (this is the horse trail marked by white diamonds on the trees.) follow the bridle trail and it will bring you to the lake, keep following the trail with the lake on your left. You will pass boulders on your right side that will need cleaning but keep going and look down the hill on your left you will see the tall High Dive boulder first. To hit Pool Party keep on bridle trail and you will see the boulder¬†directly off the trail on your right.

description: Great traversing/switchbacking line with awesome features. Small feet on some questionable rock. Just remember to use those feet! A high foot with a low gastone right hand make for an exciting crux move!
location: Start on the low choosy ramp out right. Walking up the first couple moves left to an undercling, start looking left for small foot chips. Work the crimps left on those small feet. Find a right hand gastone on a horn, and a high left foot to push up to ‚ÄúThe Wave‚Äù. Lay back and ride the wave, trending back right toward the featureless face with few pockets. From the featureless face, use the few pockets to reach shelf and continue straight for the top out.

description: This route starts off with an overhang. You‚Äôll have to climb over the lip of the rock and go straight into a deadpoint. This route looks like it‚Äôs only 15 feet or so from the picture, but the top section slopes backwards for another 10 feet or so.
location: This is one of the furthest boulders back along the trail. As you go further back, the boulders will get progressively larger, and that‚Äôs a good indication that you‚Äôre close. Should be the 2nd ‚Äúlarge boulder.‚Äù

description: Very fun problem that took me quite a while to figure out. Start right off the ground with two nice handholds and decent footholds. You‚Äôll have to move in such a way to get your right foot into the pocket your left hand starts out in. Once there, you‚Äôll have two crimpy holds, and must traverse to the left then take the obvious route up. Crux is definitely the middle section of getting your right foot set into the pocket and traversing to the left.
location: Once on the path leading back into the woods, you‚Äôll have to go back in about 400 yards. This route is set on the far left side of a really large crag.

description: Really nice crack climb. The crux is the start as there‚Äôs only one good place for foot placement at the start. You can either do left hand in the crack and right hand on a small crimp to start or both hands in the crack. Either one makes for a fun and slightly difficult climb!
location: Should be about 50-100 yards further from ‚ÄúFly Away‚Äù. You‚Äôll find it right before a large wooden obstacle with yellow hanging rope ladders. If you look closely in the top left of the picture you can see part of the obstacle.

description: Pretty easy route. The crux is the getting to the top ledge. As the name might imply, a heel hook makes this route quite manageable.
location: This is one of the largest and most obvious boulders you‚Äôll find. It‚Äôs almost directly up to the right as you enter the woods.

description: Nice and easy problem. Makes for a fun route. Just make sure you have good handholds and avoid grabbing smaller ledges as the rock is brittle in some places.
location: Can be found further back the trail from ‚ÄúHeel Hook‚Äù around 50 yards or so. It‚Äôs still along the top of the hill¬†and should be noticeable as you come upon it.

description: Sit start, far left, on the large boulder. Start matched on a large shelf about thigh high. Right Heel hook with your matched hands, move hand left. Using a series of fair crimps, work your way to standing on the right foot on the large shelf. Work up the small holds and techy movement until you reach a big black bulb of rock. From there the climbing eases and it‚Äôs a walk to the top.
Left from Near Death Experience about 250yrds with a log stack landing.
location: Start on the step below the half arete in a dirty corner. Use crimps and small chips to balance your way¬†to the arete.

description: Left of Something Fuky about 250yrds. Starts off in a low crux, leading way to a nice rest before 3 more hard moves to the top! Watch for loose rock out above¬†the left arete(which is off).
location: Stand start left on decent crimps. Feet are optional. Traverse out right on small, sparse holds for the low crux. Once you reach a big rail/ledge, mantle up, step out right to a high foot and small undercling. Pulling through the high foot exposes a small sloper and crimp that line up directly under the top out. Watch for lose rock out left by the tree roots.

description: Big flake line on some ok stone. From the North parking area by the guardrail, hike south about 400 yards on the road. Upon reaching a yellow hydrant, hike up hill and slightly left. It‚Äôs the closest large boulder to the road.
location: Hike 60-80yrds east of the gps pin. First bloc you should see as its he lowest to the road. Follow the flake all the way up left to the ledges. Watch for choss up top!

description: From Near Death Experience (directly across from the yellow hydrant on 666 at the pin) hike uphill to the right about 150yds. First line on the left at the top of the ridge with a landing built on the left.
location: Start laying on your back from the crimps, with feet out right on the ‚Äúvolume‚Äù like holds. Work¬†left and mantle up to a small rail. Left Arete is off.

description: Hefty compression problem. Solid problem from beginning to end.
location: North ravine. Right of the big dihedral. Obvious log landing to protect pads from the mud. Sit start on a large jug, feet are small and hidden.

description: On the right side of the same small bluff the holds Lowball Rave and Crackbaby.
location: Step onto the small blade of rock coming from the base of the boulder. Find a small foot chip and a semi high right hand. Pull through and dunk to the lip

description: On the left face of the boulder. Stand start using a left hand undercling, right hand on a small crimp. Stand up into the first long reaching move into a right hand pocket, just right of a book size slot (slot is off unless absolutely need due to height). Left hand to a good slope pocket above. Establish high feet. Tops out directly above.

Use the obvious finger crack and few other small features. Try to stay in the crack as much as possible. Watch for bats about chest high. I skip the crack there and choose to crimp a bit higher to let the little creatures sleep in peace.
location: Middle crack on the Hennessy boulder.

description: Start low on the arete. Pull through the crux in the first few moves to a nice small rail on the corner of the arete. Continue up the arete and out to some jugs before pulling the last couple heady moves out under and over the nose to top out.
location: From the North parking lot, hike the logging road to a cairn. Follow the cairn trail down into the N ravine. Obvious arete with a log landing. Left of Inches and Fractions. Left of the gnarly dihedral. Yeah, right there.

description: Far right, through a ravine with a small waterfall, up a choss pile to a small landing. Only large enough for one pad (with another small pad folded under the back for support) and one spotter. Watch for choss¬†on the top out as the hill has a lot of runoff!
location: Once perching yourself on the small landing, step up left towards some vegetation until the start is reachable. Very obvious right trending crack/rail over some vertical before some nice slab.

description: Start at the edge of the roof about 10 feet to the right of the arete. Climb through the overhanging face with a smack down crux going to the anchors just waiting to deny your send.
location: Starts at the edge of the roof about 10 feet right of the arete.

description: Great dynamic and powerful problem! Sadly defaced by some punk kids, but simple to spot and quick to be named.¬†Fairly sustained. Hard moves from the beginning to the end!
location: Stand start from a large half moon hueco, trending left on sidepulls and a small sloper, Air Jordan stance ftw, push into a hard compression move. From there go straight up between some small ferns to a crimp. Two more moves to a ledge and we‚Äôve been calling that the top out.

description: The steepest route at Mollies and it packs a punch for the 40 feet of climbing. ¬†Enter in from the slab under the roof and reach out to some pockets at the lip. ¬†Grab the jug and cut feet to pull on to the face. ¬†Climb the steep face where a bouldery crux awaits. ¬†Originally sent directly through the bolt line, an easier version traverses just right of the line at the 3rd bolt skipping the hardest moves and goes at 12a. ¬†Finish up on jugs to the anchors.
location: Starts under the roof and trends up the steep face just right of the arete.

description: Big moves the whole way! Control the pump!
location: Start on the same low ramp as The Wave. When you reach the undercling and crimps, go straight up into a sandy shelf. Climb under the roof, moving out right to the nose. Use a series of pockets, crimps and heels to work up the steep undercut of the nose, trending slightly left to a large dark shelf for the top out.

description: Climb through some excellent movement on the slightly overhanging face to a good rest before the roof and catch your breath. ¬†When ready, launch into a full body length roof where good footwork will help. ¬†Finish with a burly mantle to a no hands stance at the anchors. ¬†Most decide its probably better not to clip them to save your rope, take the whip and then clean the lower draws on TR.
location: Starts on the face about 15 feet left of the Sycamore tree.

description: Start on Dynoman and after pulling the initial crux trend left to the line of bolts right of the arete. ¬†Climb to the ledge, clip high and then get ready to make a few sequential moves up and left to the anchors. ¬†Alternative start: Stick clip the second bolt and then start on 1886 arete. ¬† Put a directional on the first bolt of 1886 arete and pull it as you traverse to the right.
location: Start on Dynoman, just right of the Sycamore

description: This is easiest route at Mollies and probably the only one without too much of a low crux though it does require a bit of a reach or good footwork. ¬†Traverse the slab to the left to the first bolt. ¬†Continue up through a couple of tough moves to gain a stance. ¬†Finish up on easier terrain to the anchors.
location: Starts under the roof and traverse left to the route, passing Kill Shot.

description: Far left in the corner. Watch for broken glass and choss! Big ledge marked with X is off (the impaler ledge).
location: Sit start in some dirty crimps, with feet out left, flag under. Work up and cross the large crevasse, using the side pulls and rails to guide you.

description: ‚ÄúIf you can‚Äôt reach, just dyno man‚Äù By far the most climbed line at Mollies. Usually shaded and dry even in sub prime conditions. ¬†Grade is height dependent. ¬† Consider pulling through the first moves to use a a warm up or if it you are on the shorter side to enjoy the rest of the moderate route that is 5.9ish.
location: Start on the large side pulls behind the sycamore tree. Work up and right to a large shelf. Getting to the shelf is often the move people will dyno. Big reach moves lead from shelf to shelf trending with the line trending slightly right.
protection: 3 bolts plus anchors. ¬†This route can be set up on top rope from above.

description: Start on Dynoman and head straight up and slightly left after the opening boulder problem. ¬†The route finishes with crimping at a bit of spice to keep your attention.
location: Start on the obvious sidepulls of Dynoman just right of the Sycamore tree.

description: The left nose behind the large sycamore tree.
location: Start just right of the large sycamore, and move left through some small crimps working up under the small roof to a pocket. ¬†Work your way up through some great movement making use of a rail. ¬†Shake out at the ledge and finish up on steep pocket pulling to the anchors

description: On the second "tier" of sorts there are 3 or 4 in-place, attractive boulders that upon closer inspection lack any obvious lines. This problem is on the right side of the steep wall that lacks holds besides a few honkin' jugs. Anyway, this fun problem begins on low flat jugs, moves up and right to a circular pinch hold, then to a solid iron crimp rail and a fun mantle.
This easy highball follows the swath of pockets up the right side of the tall and attractive face that is central to the Diving Board Boulders.
location: The right most line on the largest, triangular boulder central to the Diving Board
protection: A few pads and attentive spotters

description: This problem sits atop the hill, and commands the area like the center jewel on the crown of a king. Sit start with a tooth-like pinch and work into a undercling dish. Another strenuous move to a crimp followed by a committing bump and core intensive footwork eventually leads to easier ground.
location: This boulder is atop the hill, directly uphill (roughly North East) of the Diving Board- it may take some poking around to find it the first time. It has a nose-like profile if you approach it from the shoreline.

description: Sit start on large holds left of the arete. Move up into underclings, and then a distant hold on the top of the arete.
location: Blunt arete on the rightside of the clean face, past the Armada boulder.

description: THE problem at Hozaks! Sit start beneath the awesome, rounded arete. Climb up to good holds, the figure out how to manipulate a slopey dish and  foot smears to reach the high sidepull and top out jug. An excellent boulder problem requiring some funky body tension.
location: The blunt arete on the Armada boulder
Far left of the boulder
Starts between Friends and Raid the Castle.
Middle of the overhung highball bouldering area, going exactly from one small tree next to the wall to the other.
protection: The crux is at the top and the landing is very uneven.  Pad 'er up!

description: Start on a slopey ledge and smear up the wall to sidepulls. ¬†Top out above the water grove.

Start low in a large two-hand slot and work through some crimpy pockets in a shallow crack up to where it widens into a pair of hand sized slots. Jam or lie back and reach high to finger lock in the parallel crack, and then go for the top out.
location: Middle of the vertical section of the bouldering area, a few feet right of a tree growing near the base of the face.
protection: Pads & spotters, preferably a few of each. The crux is towards the top...

description: Boulder up good edges and then use a large ear like hueco to get you to the top.
location: Right side bouldering area. ¬†Just right of the last steep roof.

description: Hop up to a high, good ledge. ¬†Mantle up, then climb to the lip using bad smears and sidepulls.

protection: Crash pads, lots as the crux is the top and topout.

description: Sit start on a long ledge close to the ground. ¬†This shares a start with Into the Sun. ¬†Flip to an undercling and make a big throw up to a wide, deep slot. ¬†Continue on slots to a long, sloping ledge just before the top out.
location: Located on the far left side of the Roof Boulder, at the end of the bouldering area.

description: Start on a large horn immediately to the right of a tree, just left of the start of Psych. ¬†Traverse right on holds about head-height, before angling up and to the right.¬† Finish on a large hold just below the blank headwall
Start on a slopey ledge and climb up into the layback crack.¬† Preform a tricky mantle to gain the top.

location: As for the baguette and contortionist

description: Starts left of mail slot on the two slots¬†then finish same as mail slot. Added this variation due to the undercling start hold being snapped off of mail slot.
location: Just left if mail slot

description: Sit start on a long ledge close to the ground. ¬†This shares a start with Mail Slot. ¬†Make a big move right to a small slot, then move up and right on more slots, before a big move to a slopey ledge just before the top. ¬†Top out.
location: Located on the far left side of the Roof Boulder, at the end of the bouldering area.

description: Start from a stand on deep incut slots. Make some big moves where cutting feet may be easier.
location: Far left side of the crag, middle of the roof boulder starting on an obvious incut slot about chest height.

description: Start on double underclings and make move to an angeled slot. ¬†Keep going up and right, on a bad slot and poor pinches to a gaston before the top.
protection: Crash pads.  The landing is flat, but the boulder is tall.

description: Start on a rough, protruding knob at head height. ¬†Climb up on deep, slightly slopey ledges to a tricky topout that lacks feet.

Start on sidepulls on either side of a protruding block. ¬†Climb up on slopey holds, then make a big sideways move right to a good crimp, and then top out on the slopey slab. ¬†Avoid taking a direct approach by grabbing the good holds along the lower lip next to the crack.
protection: Crash Pads.  The boulder has a high crux.

description: Starts on Contortionist, moves left and links up with Grunt and Go and ends with Into the Sun
location: Contortionist

description: Start in the big waist-high pocket on a sloping ledge and head up and left through another big pocket.
location: On the far left end of the Bouldering Wall. ¬†Starts on the right side of the last big overhanging bulge before the end of the wall.

protection: Rock ledge in the landing. Pad it up.
Pad er up.  Ledge in the landing.
Pads... Preferably a few! ¬†Try not to fall up top. Crux comes about halfway between the roof and the topout.

description: Start with your hands in a slot deep under the roof with your feet on a ramp. ¬†This is the same start as Contortionist. ¬†Climb towards a round pinch ledge in the middle of the roof, possibly using holds on Contortionist, then go big to the ledge. ¬†Perform a high heelhook to get to the lip and mantle over at the corner of the boulder.

The obvious splitter crack on the left side of the tunnel as you walk uphill. Begin with a couple of tense face moves to establish at the base of the seam. Secure laybacking and jamming, with tenuous smears take it to the top.

Start with a left hand on the arete and a right on a sloper. Poor/crumbly feet exist, but use caution. Smearing works well. Use the left arete and stay on the face of the boulder, working towards good ledges and slopers on top.
location: On the back side of the main boulder. Left side of the parking road.

description: Start in the middle of the Airplanes Boulder. ¬†Climb up the short ramp, past slopey ledges to a vertical seam. ¬†Continue to a tricky and committing mantle that guards the top.
protection: A spotter or many crash pads is recommended. The landing is uneven and the crux is the topout.

description: Top rope. A comination of sandy rails and ledges for good feet. Start on a boulder At the base and work your way straight up. Helmets are a must since there are loose rock patches and rocks hanging around on the small ledges. Trail at the top of the area provides healthy trees for top rope anchors. This wall can get very wet after a rain so it's best climbed after a big of dry weather.
protection: Top rope. Anchor built from trees up top.

description: Follow the obvious incut jugs moving from bottom right to the middle top. Good hands bad feet, pretty fun
location: Greenhouse boulder

description: Start low on left ar√™te sidepull, move right into crimps and up
location: Downstream from spray paint wall

description: Ledgy steps up to an overhang. Can easily be top roped using trees from above.
location: Around the corner from Unknown 5.8, look for the blocky steps. There is a small bent tree about 3/4 of the way up the route.
protection: Has been led on nuts and cams but can easily be TR'd using trees.

description: Start on waist high jug rail, move right into overhang, reach out of the roof into the crimps on the face and top it out. Watch out for loose sand and rocks
location: Downstream from Pocketsand, near the stairset toproping area

description: Start low on ledge and work your way up hanging and using feet for anchor.
This is a fun boulder problem with close resemblance to "Where the Sidewalk Ends".

location: Warhol is small bouldering area located on the west portion of Secret Sandbox Cave (left portion when looking at the Secret Sandbox).

description: This is a nice bouldering traverse for beginners or when your arms are tired from the other problems in Secret Sandbox.
Tougher traverse going over small cave.
Short traverse with lots of options.

location: This is the South Face of the rock (opposite to the "North Face").  In the corer of South Face is the "Krak"

description: Not sure.

Secret sandbox cave is one of the many bouldering spots in Gorge.  It has a lot of traverse bouldering options.  The length of the ledge is about 200 or 300 feet and about 20 to 30 feet high.  It is south facing and gets a lot of sun.  Most parts closer to the ground are dry and without moss.
location: This route is off the beaten path on the west end of Gorge Metro Park.

description: This is a boulder problem just adjacent to Batman.  Starts easy using feet, then a dyno brings you to the end.
Nice upward traverse.
Notebook is a traverse located just east of North Face.
This is a relatively long traverse with a lot of fun options to try.
None.
None.
None.
Krak is located in the middle of the South Face.  This is a nice warm spot to climb protected from wind if it is a cold day.

Gamma Ray is a 50 foot traverse in the center portion of the Secret Sandbox.  The crux is a move to transition from the middle portion pulling a crimp up high with a long reach with your feet to the end.
A short bolder problem looking slightly like the ninja turtle, Donatello.
Not completed yet.
Batman is a boulder problem just West of Zorton.  It is named after the small "bat cave" in the center.  Start low and then go high above the cave.
Sit low with hands on small rail, move high left to another small crack rail, establish good feet and move through the last few intermediate slab moves to the top
location: Greenhouse boulder

description: Start in the good jugs down low, working up into the seam of the dihedral. Layback and balance your way up small feet and progressively smaller holds to a good layback in the big runnel. A small right hand rail secured the top out moves for a heady finish.
location: On the Beer block (main big boulder to left when coming in the parking road) In the mellow dihedral closest to the road/ditch.
protection: A few pads and a spot

description: Proud line going up the steep face of the bobcat boulder. Start on good pockets down low and move up to a tough undercling move. Shift right to the arete and pull one more hard snatch move before the slopey topout.
location: Overhung face of bobcat boulder right by the road.
protection: Several pads and a spotter. Flat landing but pretty intense barndoor potential at the top that can send you flying.

description: Climb straight up through roof to the top.
location: atop the Horn.
protection: Sport climb with 4 bolts to anchors

description: This route climbs pass a large mail box "like" pocket to a few good holds and the a long reach / leap of faith to some good holds which lead to a hard roof move and mantle to the anchors
location: This route is about 20 feet to the left of Dog Job and five feet to the right of Mr. Green Jeans

description: Crawl down onto the tall rock under the left side of the roof, pull on the rail, and core up to get off the ground (barely). Out to the big sloper, then the far crimp on the corner. Powerful move up to the jug before the rest of the roof, then out to a couple of slimps (the right of the two is a good pinch), then pull up to the top.

On the right side of the cave, start on the rail and try to fit your feet on, then go back to the sloper. Throw out left to the other juggy sloper. Bump into the sidepull if needed for the reach, then bump up to the top.
Start with a tough undercling up to your preferred ledge before traversing to the original Coughing Fit to top out.
location: Starts to the right of Coughing Fit on Fault Line (by east entrance).
protection: Mostly clear for pads with a few ground rocks.

description: Nice warmup. Side pull standing start filling in crimps, side pulls and jugs to a decent top out. Trust a high foot for a low risk top out. After topping out, walk back toward the entrance for an easy down climb.
location: Located just off the trail from the East parking lot. Up the hill from Kid's cave and east of Front Wall and Squid Wall.

description: Even shorter than Marthas Bunion! Start on the edge and go straight up. Should be topped out, but might need cleaned a little.
location: Far climber's right on the front wall. Just past the overhanging horn. Across from the downclimb of the Broken Boulder.

description: Start on the ledge under the overhang. Come out through some crimping, then work up the right side of the seam. Finish is up right.
location: Seam up the center of the Front Wall.

description: Start on the undercling rail in the roof, then work up the juggy pockets. The last two holds are a little crimpy, and it's a bit dynamic to the finish hold.
location: Just to the left of the arete on the Front Wall.

description: Start on edge far out right (same as Vegan Stout) and traverse your way left into the roof. Top out left of the tip of the horn. Downclimb through the hole.
location: A giant horn jutting out of the Front Wall towards the right.
protection: 2-3 pads would be ideal, but can be done with 1.

description: Very positive holds up an interior corner (featuring a crack) and the narrow face to its right. The top is slightly overhanging. Try to only use the narrow face and avoid stepping into the dihedral, for some challenge.
location: A little right of the middle on the Squid Wall, there's a ledge that steps down from the top of the boulder. This problem approaches that ledge from the left.

description: Easy balancing up to a big undercling, then a slighlty slopey top-out.
location: A little right of the middle on the Squid Wall, there's a ledge that steps down from the top of the boulder. This problem approaches that ledge head-on.

description: Great highball(ish) easy climb.
location: The left, tall arete of the Squid Wall (and some of the left face of the boulder). Closer to Bears Den Rd/the stream.

description: Start out on small jug on far right side of traverse.
Short little warmup. Starts on left side of arete (sit on the slanted rock on the ground, hands on crimps, left foot on ledge & right foot smeared onto corner) and goes up.
location: Rightermost problem on the Squid Wall. On the arete that is closer to New Cross Dr.

description: Sit-start with outward pulls, moves on to a crimp and slightly tricky feet. Then, a throw to a finger jam in a partial pocket (like trying to hold the open part of a "C"). You could also try to crimp or undercling it, but it's a pretty solid lock that you can easily get out of if you need to. It's jugs from there.
location: On the Squid Wall; from the South and looking North, it starts on the first "lip" that sticks out of the wall, towards the bottom.

description: Climb the ramp through the shelves to an alcove.  Pull out of alcove and follow crack through overhang above.
location: At far right end of cliff there is a sloping ramp below two shelves and an inside corner.

description: This route climbs past a slightly overhanging large stacked blocks pass 3 bolts to a finish.
location: This route is located about 50 feet around the corner and to the right of Return to Sender or just about 5 feet to the right of the old trad route called Save the Wails.

description: Climb up blocks to a crack.  Pull the overhanging block to the top.
location: 15 feet left of a double trunked tree at left end of cliff.

description: Climb Dick Rock Route to a ledge.  Step around left to the main face.  Traverse left over precariously perched block and go to top.
location: Where large buttress on left side of cliff forms an inside corner with the main wall.

description: This is a fun little route with pockets reaches and even a mantel near the finished.
location: This route is located about five to the right of Dick Rock Route and about 10 feet to the left of Blast from the past.

description: Pull straight out of alcove to small flake to ledge.  Crank through roof to top.
location: On ledge inside alcove right of Dog Job

description: Climb up ramp to the left to a small corner below a roof.  Go out left side of roof to top.
location: Atop Dog Job ledge.

description: Climb the corner to the horn on the left.  Pull up to ledge.  Walk left until ledge ends.  Traverse to and finish on Dick Rock.
location: At obvious right facing corner right of Astroboy.

description: From ledge, traverse right onto the main wall.  Follow shallow crack system up and right to top.
location: Ledge part way up Dick Rock Route

description: Pull series of overhanging blocks to the top.
location: At double trunked tree at left end of cliff.

description: Dog Job and Dog Job Direct are now a mixed line that climbs the thin book like corner to a large ledge and then climbs the overhangs pass 4 bolts to ring anchors
location: from Dog Job ledge.
protection: Short crack, takes small nuts or C3 cams. 4 ¬†Bolts.

description: Climb the corner, pull the roof to ledge.  Finish on Direct or Indirect.  Named after a pulp porno novel found on ledge on FA.  Yes, it was about "doing" dogs.  Pretty funny stuff when you are 15.
location: At obvious inside corner with roof in center of cliff.

description: Climb up corner to ledge.  Move up and right to the top.
location: At corner formed by buttress and main wall at left end of cliff.

description: Climb overhanging crack through the broken center of the face to a ledge.  Finish to left or right.
location: At corner of buttress and main wall near left end of cliff.

description: Pull out of alcove to ledge on right.  Mantle up and traverse to end.  More of a boulder problem than a route.
location: From alcove right of Dog Job

description: This route climbs pass an old broken drill bit with long reaches pass 4 bolts to the anchors.
location: This route is located about 10 feet to the right of Return to Sender and 10 feet to the left of Astroboy

description: Climb to the obvious horizontal slot in the wall.  Step up to a flake and traverse to Dog Job ledge.  Finish to right or left.
location: Left of Dog Job at rounded wall.

description: Climb the akward corner to a ledge.  Follow the crack to the top.
location: 25 feet right of Dick Rock Route is a shallow right facing duhedral that starts about 5 feet above the ground.

description: Climb up blocks to the roof.  Pull it through the middle to the top.
location: Three feet left of the double trunked tree at left end of cliff.

description: Start with underclings on the roof under the bulge. Reach up then stand up on the bulge, go to the hueco, then work up to the corner for a mildly heady topout (not helped by the moss).
location: Left on the main face, before the arete.

description: Climb the wall with crescent shaped left facing holds and overhang above. A rockfall in early 1992 removed a ledge and helped to make this route.
location: Start just below the left end of the ledge from which BURSITIS starts.

protection: 5 bolts and shares anchors with Nightmare Right Side.

description: Start at the 5th drill mark (count the drill marks half way up the climb) from the left on The Left Main Wall. Climb along the drill mark using tenuous lay-backs to get to a ledge. Finish up on the top wall to get to the Terrace, 45 ft.
Climb to the right of Beam Me Up Scotty, using the bolts on Scotty.
protection: Same as Beam Me Up Scotty: 5 bolts + anchor

description: This route was established in the late 90's and climbs up drill lines to a good left crimp and a big reach to a small ledge and then joins Nichols is a weenie.
location: This climb is located in between Beam me up Scotty and Nichols is a Weenie. It is between the 3rd and 4th drill marks (count the drill marks half way up the climb) to the left of Open Book.

description: Start the same as FRODO LIVES. Climb FRODO through the first mantel, step right around the corner, climb to the next good stance, traverse left across the foot ledge under the mailbox slot high on FRODO and climb to the anchors, 45 ft. More like 11a than 10b.
This route was established in the late 90's and climbs a thin face/ar√™te to a small lip and then shares anchors with The Open Book.
location: This climb is located just about 5' feet to the right of The Open Book.
protection: 4 bolts + shuts (same shuts used for Open Book)

description: Start between the 2nd. and 3rd. drillmarks to the left of OPEN BOOK. Climb along the 3rd. drillmark past the 1st. bolt then climb along the drillmark above past the 2nd. and 3rd. bolts

Follow the bolt line using the arete to the right and drill mark to left as needed. Do not go around the arete. Start by climbing the face, making good use of a few small holds and a drill mark to gain the first bolt. From here, look for some holds to the left and work your way to a stance. Climb up, aiming for a nice horn like jug. Mantle up using the jug and a nice, but small ledge to gain a stance. Make one or two more moves over the blank face to reach the overhang at the top and shuts.
location: Start just to the left side of the arete that separates the Left Main Wall from the Right Main Wall.

description: Start at ground level just to the right of the large V-shaped chimney (chimney is about 1/2 way up the climb) on the left side of The Left Main Wall. Climb to a spacious ledge under the V-shaped chimney then climb the wall or corner to the right of the chimney. The first part of this climb was originally known as CAPTAIN KIRK

Start between the 2nd and 3rd drill marks (count the drill marks half way up the climb) from the left on The Left Main Wall. Climb the face along the first two bolts using the drill marks, then pull the mantel under the third bolt. Finish on the ledge.
This route is located on the far right side of the right wall and climbs passed 3 bolts on a short textured wall to Broadway Ledge and shares anchors with Spock Lives.
location: Last route on Right Main Wall.
protection: Three (3) ¬†well placed bolts to Fixed Rings

location: To the left of Nightmare's Right Side, just right of the center of the wall.
protection: 2 fixed rings (1999) shared with Nightmare's Right Side

description: Climb up the face, passing a few good shallow horizontal holds to reach a stance.  Make a few slabby moves to reach the 2nd bolt to the right of the small overhang.  Make some reachy moves using some slopping holds to gain a stance above the overhang.   Continue on easier terrain for a few moves to reach the anchors.
location: This is the bolted line slightly to the right of a small overhang in the middle of the face of the Right Main Wall.

description: Climb past the face to gain a blank section. Make a big move to an excellent hold. Make an interesting mantle and head to the large ledge at the top with anchors.
location: This is the second line of bolts from the left on the Right Main Wall.

description: This is another that you probably want to stick clip the first bolt.  Climb up to gain the first bolt.  From here, smear your way up until you can dyno for a great hold (crux).  From here, pass a nice mail slot hold and reach the final face.  2 crimpy holds on the final face allow you to make a reach to the big ledge at the top.  Brush this route if you want a sporting chance of getting it clean.
location: Blank looking face to the left of a small overhang in the middle of the Right Main Wall.

description: Right most sport climb on Right Main Wall. Start on the face just to the right of the 1st drillmark, 10 ft left of the left facing inside corner where Dreaming starts.

location: Where the The Right Main Wall makes a 90 degree turn.

description: Climb the arete and ascend the right side of the overhang, continue to the end of the good rock and then lower down from anchors on FOOTLOOSE AND FINGER FREE.
location: Start below the arete under the roof to the left of the 1st. drillmark from the right on the Right Main Wall.
protection: This is usually a TR off anchors of Footloose. It has also been led using the bolts and anchors on Footloose.

location: Start 6 feet to the right of the outside corner.
protection: 5 Bolts + anchors (same bolts and anchors as Coordinate Covalent Bonding)

first_ascent: Fabulous Furry Freak Brothers, FFA- unknown
description: This is one of the nicer climbs in the area. I'd recommend stick clipping the first bolt. Climb straight up the arete to gain the first bolt. Continue past 3 more bolts using the arete and face holds on the right of the arete to reach the shuts.
location: This is the left most route on the Right Main Wall.

protection: 2 fixed rings (1999) shared with Nightmare's Right Side.

description: The Overhang 5.7- Starts below a 2 foot block with a finger crack and then climbs up and left on good holds through a small overhang to a well placed bolt at the mantel crux from there climb up and slightly right to the anchors.
Start 10‚Äô to the left of the sport route OBSESSION where there is a finger pocket literally inside the drillmark. Climb using the finger pocket and to get to Broadway Ledge, 15 ft.
protection: Set up a Top Rope with gear above Broadway Ledge.

description: Start in the shallow left facing inside corner to the left of the Pit, climb the left facing inside corner.
location: Left of the pit but right of Always Saturday. Always Saturday is the last bolted line on the Front Wall.

description: 4 bolts to anchors
location: Located between Boulder Problem and Block Party

description: Easy Does It 5.5 - Is a great addition to Logtown Quarries and a good warm up. This route climbs a short easy slab section with big holds and great protection to a high step and mantel at the crux and finishes with easy climbing to the anchors.
location: This climb is just to the right of "Bugs Bunny" and just to the left of the "Ryser Route" located on the Front wall section of the "Big Cliff" area of Logtown Quarry

description: Start between the 1st and 2nd drillmarks to the right of the arete. Climb the right side of the arete and flake on the right, mantle up to Broadway Ledge.
protection: 2 bolts, side by side, and fixed anchor (shared with Nightmare wall climbs)

description: Start between the 4th and 5th drill marks near a nice little pocket climb straight up to ¬†ring anchors on right going over a slight roof, or go left and follow 3 bolts to another set of ring anchors climbing up a small arete. The anchors are about 6‚Äô left of last bolt. The roof and arete are both cruxes, the arete has small foot holds but a good ledge to hold on.

location: Second bolted line to left of pit.

description: Climbs up a few good holds to a long reach to a good crimp at the base of the drill line in a obvious corner / book, From this point pull you feet up high to a good ledge and find a few good crimps on both sides of the small corner / book. Many options from this point right a little, left a little or straight up all lead to a mantel with great protection and easy climbing to the anchors.
location: Located on the Front Wall of the big cliff just to the right of Beach Party and just to the left of Husker Do. First obvious drill mark above and right of Broadway Ledge and last bolted line on The Front Wall.

description: Climb over several overhanging blocks and the block filled top section. CAUTION: Loose rock high on the cliff here as well as a hornet's nest.
location: Just right of the sport route Easy Does It.
protection: TR, not recommended due to the loose rock at the top of the cliff

description: Start on the left side of the Southeast wall The Pit. Climb the bulging wall without using the corner crack.
Start in the altar-like area of the Southeast wall of The Pit. Climb straight up the wall.

Start 25 feet to the right of The Pit where the overhanging prow is next to the path which leads to the cliff top. Climb the prow shaped overhanging boulder at its widest point, 15 ft. Walk back down the path.
Start the same as CLASSIC CORNER CRACK. Climb the right facing inside corner to a pedestal then climb the smaller right facing inside corner and the overhang above.
Start in the East corner of The Pit. Traverse left a few feet and then climb straight up.
Climb the wall, do a hard mantel move then pull through the roof.
location: Start halfway between the start of BURSITIS and CLASSIC CORNER CRACK on the ledge 6 feet of the ground.
protection: This climb used to have 2 bolts on it until they were shot out by unknown persons back in 1995.

description: Start to the left of center on the fractured Southwest wall (road side) of The Pit. Climb the fractured wall.
Start in the East corner.

location: Start on the Northeast wall on the ledge 15 feet off the ground.

description: Climb the crack system, move right and climb the roof-crack in the overhang to finish up on the ledge above the overhang. Continue to anchors near top.
location: Start on the Northeast wall of The Pit on the ledge 15 feet off the ground. This is the same side of the Pit as The Front Wall.

description: Sidepull up some cracks and a pocket. Use the tree to top out.
location: Right under the tree in the middle of the wall.

description: Start on a sloper in the roof. Come out with some challenging moves, then get up on the ledge and enjoy a chill topout.
location: Coming out of the low roof and going left.

description: Up the left of the crack (right side is off). Starts matched on the pie that sits in the crack, moves out to a ledge, then a throw to the top of the middle segment of the boulder. Once standing on the ledge, the last move is pretty easy.
location: On the broken boulder, on its face toward New Cross Dr. The problem is up the left side of the crack.
On the broken boulder, on its face toward New Cross Dr. The problem is up the right side and the face to the right of the crack.

route_name: You don't deserve this big Toblerone
description: Slabby side of the Toblerone. Previously coated in moss, but has since been scrubbed clean. Crimpy-ish underclings and some 1/4 pad sharp pockets. Aretes are off.
Layback your way up the right arete and the slot on the right side of the slabby face. There's the little flake for your feet at the start, and some more foot options toward the top.
Begin up Triple Right and finish on Triple Left, avoiding the top crux of Triple Right.
location: See Photo, Climbers left of the tall 50' wall.

description: OS, FA, free solo with a bouldering pad.
location: This is the left side of the tall line right of the Triple wall.
protection: Top Rope, or LOTS of bouldering pads.

description: There isn't really a crux on this one, other than the top.
location: About 5 minutes up trail from the Gorge Parking Lot.

description: Traverse along the base of the roof, is it a hand-foot match? Stay low? Stay high? Enjoy figuring it out...
location: The route is the first roof boulder you will come to from the Gorge Parking area.

description: Only use the right crack, hard up top.
location: See photo, right line.

description: Good jamming, leads to a ledge, down-climb or drop from ledge. Surprisingly great rock quality.
location: The route is the left crack of the two cracks, see photo.

description: The crux is lower, pulling longer moves on sharp crimps, the climb eases as you continue higher, don't blow the moves up top. The rock quality is terrific on this one.
location: The route is 5 minutes from the gorge parking lot and has a notable K+W at the base (left).

description: Rock quality is good, delicate moves about the arete. Fun climbing all and all.
location: This found by the graffiti at the base of the route, look for the K-W at the base of the route (left side of the arete). Look for the obvious chock-stone as seen in the photo on the right side of the arete.

description: The crux is a small crimp rail at 3/4 height.If you fall here, you are falling to a ledge 10' down or the depths about a 25-30' fall.
location: The route is at the entrance of East Side Boulders.

description: The crux is a long move two moves in.
location: The route shares the boulder with Shard.

description: Good quality boulder problem, lie back or compression movement to the top.
location: The route is right of "Rivers Run." Walk off the top.
protection: Good landing zone, one pad would suffice.

description: Fun problem start on a ledge and make a large lock off move to a good crimp rail, match the rail and finish on the jugs up top.
location: The boulder is along the riverside, you access it off of a flat rock that protrudes into the river itself. Walk off top.
protection: One good spotter and a pad.

description: The route shares the same start with "Rivers Run" from here chug out right through a bad slope rail or a very large committing move to a crimp  follow this to the top right corner.
location: Same as "Rivers Run."
protection: A bouldering pad and spotter, once you near the top you may have a bad fall (into the river.)

description: Sit start with hand jams, then pull and stand up on the big foot ledge to reach some holds inside and along the edge of the crack. Get another good hold on the right edge, then reach the lip. Topout.
location: Backside of the Broken Boulder (opposite of Sustain and Refrain). Faces away from New Cross Dr.

description: Start on a ledge in the middle of the cave where the vertical wall meets the roof. Come straight out using the rail, jug flake, and pocket above the roof. Mantle/muscle-up topout.
location: Slightly right-of-middle of the cave/roof directly behind and under the cabin (near the chimney).

description: A compressy overhanging arete. Start hanging on the rail, pull to the ledge, then make use of some dimples on each side of the arete to work your way to the top. Topout's chill.

location: Overhang/roof immediately behind and below the cabin.

description: May be some loose rock, has an R rating.
location: 40‚Äô left of Back Wall/Left Main Wall corner, above Practice Route, starts off large ledge.
protection: Anchors: Cold Shuts which were not checked or replaced as of 2018.

description: Name says it all.
location: 40‚Äô left of Back Wall/Left Main Wall corner.

route_name: Just for the Fun of It
description: Fun route with a crux about 1/2 way and an easy finish if you use the correct hold.
location: 75‚Äô left of Back Wall/Left Main Wall corner.

description: The route, a crack route. Its right near the waterfall so its often wet. there is opportunity to extend the route to have an overhang involved in the start. It is sandstone so careful of the possibility of broken holds. The crux: prob the 1st and 2nd moves. Otherwise its a finger and hand crack
location: To the right of the main falls when facing the falls. flat rock near the base
protection: Trad definitely possible. Top rope might be better. Used a 3 inch tree for a anchor.

description: Start on upstream side of Racist Arete boulder and top out on jugs and edges.
location: Upstream side of Racist Arete boulder.

description: Two big jugs chest height to big move to top.
location: Just right of blood gnome.

description: Easy jug haul to the top of the boulder.  Most dangerous part is topping-out.
location: All the way downhill next to the creek.

description: Underclings lead to matching sloper to topout.
location: Left of Fight or Flight.

description: Start fart left on ledge go right to rails and jugs to topout where mantis does.
location: Backside of Solitary boulder by drop in trail.

description: Sit Start on rail to topout.
location: Mantis boulder, solitary boulder by drop in trail.
protection: Pads and spotters, high potential of falling down cliff without a "lineman" spotter.

description: Start in an undercling (the same one as "Left Handed S.O.B", but farther to the right), then move straight up on small crimps and smeary feet to a crimp rail right before the lip. Traverse out left to some really good hidden holds over the top lip of the boulder. Be sure to clean off the top really well as it gets dirty very easily.
location: On the same boulder as "Left Handed Whore", but more towards the right-hand side of the same face.

description: An eliminate on the "flight" boulder. The same undercling start, but go straight from the left hand pinch on up to the top jug, eliminating the middle right hand
location: Directly left of "fight or flight"
protection: A pad or two and a spotter

description: Start and move in pockets to topout.
location: Across the stream from Left Handed Whore.

description: Sit start with left hand on crimp and right in CD slot, move up using the little ar√™te and the big smile
location: Directly across the stream from the drop in, in between The Hangar and the creek

description: This route is directly above Key Hole Boulder. Start from the ground and use leg bracing to make your way up. You can top out on this route and walk back down to the start area. Moss can be slippery, be careful.
location: Use the hemlock loop trail until you get to the restricted area sign. Walk down the path towards the river. On your right side with be Fight Or Flight as you walk down the hill. At the bottom will be Pinch Arete. Walk left of Pinch Arete and you will see Prickly Pickle/Ninja Split Kick on your left right above Key Hole Boulder.

description: Avoid catching your ankle in the crack and missing / not committing to the move to the sloper.
location: Down the hill from Fight or Flight.

description: Sit start in the center of the boulder and reach up to very small holds to balance your way to the sloping edge.
location: Center of Lumberjack boulder
About fifty feet downstream from Fight or Flight. One of the first boulders over the fence from the parking lot. If you can't find it, just walk along the fence. Faces away from the road.

description: Traversing problem on a sloping edge to an easy topout.  Start on far right of boulder.
location: downstream from Fight or Flight
protection: at least a pad to cover one very scary rock

description: Start low on side pulls/pinches to top.
