location: Just downstream of pinch arete.

description: Up left arete to topout.
location: Left arete of block head boulder, most likely sporting a water landing.

description: Start in an undercling on the center of the boulder, then traverse through another unercling and small to almost non-existant sloping crimps out to the arete where you finish off by linking with "Left Handed Whore"
location: An extension on the "Left Handed Whore". Drop down by "Fight or Flight", head down the partial staircase toward the "Pinch Arete" boulder, then continue straight forward. Drop down near the boulder using some sturdy logs and rock hops.

description: dont forget to toe cling the arete
Start low and to the far right of the boulder using the rail to traverse towards the arete. Move up the arete to top out.
Finding it, since in all likely scenarios, the base of this is washed out for a while ..
Last move
Hitting the sloper on a low gravity day and a lower humidity day.
location: Over the fence, over the hill, Fight or Flight will be there.

description: Climb the little slab on the back of the Bonsai boulder. Easy but would be crimpy and technical for a newbie.
location: On the back of Bonsai.

description: Start on flat ledges of the lower rail down to the right, and work your way up the arete using an undercling/ sidepull on the roof side to get to the top.
location: Upstream from Cess Pool, and The Gem on the same side. Maybe 200 yards downstream of the bridge.

description: Sit start on arete and right crimp and on up.
location: Solitary boulder west of Boo Ya Arete.

description: Desperate times. Same start as Racist, but trends right climbing the face only (left arete off) and exits with a punch out right to a large horn. There's room for another compression variant to the right for those with albatross wingspans.
location: Racist Block

description: SDS on sloper, through up to slopey lip and climb the slopey arete up and right 8ft then top out
location: right behind the GEM

description: Start on low jug, up arete.
location: Just downstream of Racist arete on birth of a nation wall.

description: Start on undercling or crimps to up.
location: Same as blood gnome sit start.

description: Sit Start to crimps up.
location: Just right of Boo Ya Arete

description: This is the furthest upstream route on the Bill Wall. ¬†Although it looks pretty easy from the ground, don't let the features fool you. ¬†There are a lot of seemingly good hand holds that are tough to get a grip on. ¬†Be careful of lose rocks. ¬†Soft/wet sandstone holds can be precarious.
protection: Bolt-in chains are located at the top of the climb, but you'll need some longer runners if you are going to dangle your anchor so that it wont have any drag.

location: Parking in the Berea Falls parking lot, find a way down to the river. The rock will be just below some of the cliffs about 100 feet downriver of the wooden overlook.

description: Right hand makes 3 jumps up
location: way left from the parking lot, at the farthest most ridge line.

This is the furthest downstream route on the Bill Wall. ¬†You can access the base of the climb by walking left of the wooden lookout, then crossing under it. ¬†You can anchor either to the slanted tree at the top of the route, or into the fixed chains set about 4 feet back from the ledge. ¬†Either work.¬† The walk down to the base is a bit slippery when wet so be careful when walking down after setting the anchor.
protection: There is a tree at the top of this climb that can be used for an anchor for this route. ¬†There are also fixed chains bolted to a rock set about 4 feet back from that tree. ¬†If you feel the need to "top out," you'll need to use the chains.¬† You'll also need some webbing if using the chains unless you are okay with your rope dragging over the edge.

description: The crux may be getting into the crack. The crack needs cleaned up before the send.
location: The route is to climbers right of the "sport" route. This is the furthest obvious crack of the three on the roof feature.
protection: Passive nuts work well, some finger/hand cams will work also. Top out & rappel from tree.

description: Crux is finding good feet
location: Far right of the warm up boulder in the dihedral.

description: Finding it .. The rock is good, though it probably could use a cleaning.
location: On the entrance boulder, goes up right.

first_ascent: Probably some long haired smelly hippy in the late sixties.
description: It is only ~9ft high .. just don't fall wildly as some people have tweaked their ankles in this fashion.
location: First problem one sees after crossing the creek.

description: A fun very easy diagonal lay back all the way up to the top. ¬†once you reach the top top out and climb over the edge and use the holes on the backside to get back down.
location: very apparent right off the trail on the left side going towards the falls.

description: SDS left, climb sloper lip and holds up and right, feet are sparse, so hold on tight!
location: this boulder is in the middle creek area of the park

description: A fun crack to the left of the Cascade crack just inside the dihedral. ¬†Not the cleanest rock ever but fun hand and arm jams up the crack to top out.
really great problem with a lot of possibilities for moves. ¬†Depending on how you move you can make this boulder relatively easy or as hard as you want.
location: this boulder is on top of the first hill to your right as you start on the trail going towards cascade falls from the parking lot.

description: A real fun flake going straight up the cliff, the moves are really reachy and fun with alot of side pulls. ¬†You can set up toprope off the tree directly above the route(be careful walking above the cliff the dirt is slanted and loose, also be cognizant of not walking up to high above the cliff into people's backyards) or place some protection in the cracks. ¬†The crux is towards the top of the flake where there is a very long reach to the next possible hand hold. ¬†A bit chossy in some areas but overall a pretty fun route
location: walk down directly behind elyria baptist church and take a right turn at the river.¬† Its about a 10 minute walk and the cliffs will be to your right
protection: Be careful of rock integrity, if attempting to place protection on this route.

description: a fun short off width crack. ¬†Just a body jam and muscle your way up. once you get the top you get to another flat platform of ground with a very obvious second crack directly in front of you. climb the second crack and top out and walk back down around back.
location: from the parking lot facing th water walk on the trail toward the right that goes to the falls you will eventually come across 2 obvious flat walls one above the other.
protection: bouldering mat recommended.  difficult to get up to second crack.

route_name: Baptism of desire AKA Parish Swagger
description: As it is a crack it is entirely finger size dependent.
location: The route is located behind the "Baptism by fire" project. Their is some graffiti spelling Swagger crossing over the crack.

description: The crux is most likely the top out...
location: The route is the first route you will encounter when coming down from the entrance. The route starts in the back of a small roof on a jug and tops out near the small tree.

description: Easier version of Feets of Contortion
location: Right streamside of Harley boulder.  Right of Feets of Contortion.

description: Start low on underclings to lockoffs to topout.
location: Northside of Harley Boulder

description: Overhanging, some nice large huecos lower on the route, but everything is covered in moss, mud, and is constantly wet. Some nice pro placement locations to cut swing as route wanders to hit good holds from the TR point. TR tree is 25' from edge. Nice dyno mid route but have to nail it as approach other ways is difficult. Needs some major cleaning and it might be a cool Route. Just mucky right now.
Start on obvious right hand undercling-sidepull, and left hand on bad crimp. Bump left up to a good hold, proceed to the lip.
location: Pretty much in the river, downstream 20 yards of Perfect Sunday.

description: Start the same as Los nuggets, but finish by moving out right instead of going straight up.
location: On the way to monkey swing, there should be a huge tree on your left before the drop in to bonsai, drop in to your right hand side and the boulder should be right there.
protection: Can be covered with a pad or two

description: Good size hand crack that slants slightly to the left half way up the route before finishing at the top. Crux is the top just because of the balancy mantle move the gain the top of the wall. Crack takes gear well but can be a little dirty sometimes.
location: From the parking lot, follow the gravel hiking trail past the shelter. Once you cross a little ditch, the trail will shortly split in three different directions, continue straight on the middle trail that takes you directly up the hillside. Once you reach the top of the hill there will be a bench on your left. From here you'll make a right and follow the trail for 200 yards until the trail starts to turn back left around a large rock face. The climb will be the hand crack on your left
protection: Camalots #1 and #2 (doubles). Rap from tree at top.

description: Very easy edge traverse route. Only about 10ft long. Top out.
protection: Bouldering. Crashpad probably not neccessary. Spotting encouraged for less experienced climbers.

description: Start at arete with right hand on the right arete, and left hand on left facing sidepull. Get a heel hook on the right, and cross to the lip. Ride the lip left to "Rollout" on the slopey section of it.
location: On the Rollout Boulder on the park side of the river, downstream from the God Boulder, if you stand and touch a boulder with "HC" graffitied on it, the Rollout Boulder will be behind you.

description: Start at the left most crimps under the Rollout roof, with a far far left high foot. Traverse right keeping your feet in front of you. Just before rounding the arete, grab the lip and top out.
location: On the Rollout boulder. Downstream from the God Boulder, and directly behind the boulder with "HC" graffitied on it if you're standing by it.

description: Start on obvious big rail and move up to topout.
location: Right side of Sauna boulder.

description: Start low in deep pocket, move through intermediates to the crimp crack and high left crimp, deadpoint to lip. Topout is kinda spooky
location: 50 meters downstream from monkey swing on the cliff line
next face to the right of monkey swing roof

description: A very fun eliminate on the Poo Arete. Start the same as the V2, and avoid the Jug you usually dyno to, and instead go left on crimps and sloping ledges.
location: On the Poo Arete in the Monkey Swing area.

description: Start on campusing crimps to high top out.
location: Upstream on the 8th of crack cliff band.

description: Start on the obvious chalked jug, continue up and left through a pocket in a thin seam to the lip. CAREFULLY rock over the lip. Hike all the way up the slab to the top, and down climb off the back.
location: Just upstream of the Star arete, and downhill and slightly downstream of the Monkey Swing area. It's the biggest boulder you see.

description: start down and right on face, move left through slopers, and very crappy feet, right hand to good roof rail, match and go right to sloper lip, continue one move right and mantle up
location: Monkey Swing Roof Lat/Long: 41.322172, -81.615745
West of Los Nuggets; prominent boulder just south of the main trail.
protection: 1-2 pads, spotter strongly suggested as there is a large boulder in the fall zone.

description: Sit start on 2 crimpy edges, go straight up.
location: Chalked up boulder south of 8th of crack.

description: Start on the left side slopey crimps, traverse right to the prow and top out.
location: About 5 feet downhill from the Bonsai Boulder, uphill from the Arrow Boulder.

description: Start left side of boulder on crimps make way to topout.
location: Left side of Sauna boulder.

description: Climb right ar√™te
location: Right next to the arrow

description: Start the same as "A Summertime Christmas", but traverse out left on sloping ledges. Continue up to the top on more slopers. Could use traffic, but it will clean up nicely.
location: On the back side of the warm up boulder in the Monkey Swing Area.

description: Start on the first right hand of Los Nuggets. Traverse right to a small ledge, bring the left hand into a pinch, then throw to the arete. Follow the arete to a top out.
location: Same boulder as Los Nuggets.

description: Start on the two holds down in the crack and work your way up To the mail slot. Then stand and smear to the top.
location: The problem is right next to star across the river.

description: Start at the obvious jug down in the little cave. Climb up and out to a moderately tall but easy top out.
location: Right of the Poo Arete on the same cliff line, in a little cave. In the Monkey Swing Area.

description: Start low on jugs on far left side of boulder and move up to a slabby topout.
location: Streamside of harley boulder.

description: SDS left hand on thin undercling, right hand on arete. bump right hand up arete and hope you have good foot work and core strength to keep yo feet on, left hand throws out to the flat corner of boulder, keep compression and launch for the lip with your left hand. top out
location: Across from the Arrow head boulder

description: Start on left hand undercling then move up sparse crimps to large lock off move to the top crimp
location: monkey swing area

description: Same start as "hallucinogens", but move out right to the lip, then work your way up the slab.
location: across the stream from star arete and perfect sunday. It's the large slab face with the mail slot in the center.
protection: A pad or two, and a spotter

description: Start with right hand on corner of the arete where there should be a crimp, and the left hand on the obvious pinch in the center. Work you way through both aretes to a juggy topout. The starting foot may have to be dug out, as it can get washed over with sand.
location: About 100 yards upstream of the egg.
protection: A couple pads and a spotter.

description: Start low on crimps to throw out to jug on arete to topout.
location: Boulder across from Harley boulder.

description: Starts the same as "The Arrow of Light", but eventually bumps out to the indent feature of the left side. Finish by riding both aretes in a compression to the top. May be harder for people under 5ft. 7.
location: On the Arrow boulder, across the river from the egg, almost directly West of Plans to Commit Arson, and near Thugged out since Cub Scouts. The obvious arrow shaped boulder near facing the creek.
protection: Pads, maybe a spotter to feel extra safe.

description: Work your way up the left side arete of the boulder using the obvious incut feature in the middle to start on.
location: Across the creek from the Egg, or follow the trail from Bonsi down to the creek. Obvious arrow shaped boulder facing the creek.

description: Split start with right hand just below crescent shaped indent on the right arete, and left hand on a poor slopey ledge low on the face. Work up the right arete using the obivous slopy crimp in the center of the boulder near the top.
location: On the Arrow boulder, across the river from the egg, almost directly West of Plans to Commit Arson, and near Thugged out since Cub Scouts. The obvious arrow shaped boulder near facing the creek.
protection: Pads, and maybe a spotter to make sure the climber stays on the landing zone.

description: Sit Start with hands jammed in vertical crack big move out to overhanging crack to top out.
Start on the lowest flat sloped ledge. Continue up  blocky slopers to top out. A bit dirty, and could use some traffic, but fun movement!
location: On the backside of the warmup boulder in the Monkey Swing Area.

description: Start under roof on obvious jug, pull up to slopey feature, try to climb feature to thin crimps to a jug top out
location: next problem to the right of Hang line

There's an undercling for illusions of grandeur that can be held as you smear feet, making your way as far right as possible, which leads to a couple fun pauses in footwork. Then looking up and left there are small fingers and tips for matching, traversing back.

description: Scramble up easy moves to the obvious roof crack, climb crack out roof 12ft to big move at the lip and few easy moves on the head wall to easy top out
location: The Hanger

description: From left to Right, has an incredible edge for flat finger crimps, schmeary feet, some good blade and features to get toes onto. You can make some nice movements.
location: Just beyond and still considered The Hanger area to the left, there is a wall of flat rock about face height that has a few artificially drilled marks in it.

description: Start with left on crimp and right hand/heel hook match. The crux is making the first two moves. Good crimps, just maybe too small for a newbie. After the crimps, reach for the huge jugs and make an easy top-out.
location: Relatively in the center of the area. Can be identified by the small roof on the side away from you as you approach.

description: sloping wall with small rails to dig your fingertips into.  Crux is between second and third bolt.
location: From the south side of the wall, walk approx. 1/4 to 3/8 of a mile down the face of the wall
protection: four bolts with two anchors at the top

description: A little high.
location: Towards the far end of the area.

description: There is a tree in the top for an anchor, great rock for beginners
Farthest crack to the right on this rock, next to the trail going to the top. ¬†one well protected 5.8ish roof to a fun top out.
This is the second crack you see after you reach the main wall. ¬†Climb to the slabby face and sling the sketchy bolt with a nut. ¬†Sack up and top it out.
Chimney sized crack with lots of face climbing on edges. ¬†Walk past bluff around first arete. ¬†Crack will be obvious.
Left of the two sport lines, shares anchors with Blueberry Funk. ¬†4 bolts 2 bolt anchor.

The southern most full-length route in the area starts below the vertical crack.  The easier face moves bring you to a small roof that requires fist and hand jams to bypass (this is the crux).  From here it is face climbing again.  Watch out for bats that like to catch rays on this rock face.  Also be careful tossing your rope down or dropping any gear, this route goes right over the main trail and is very close to the water.
location: Walking along the Lake Shore trail from the dam look for the obvious crack that runs up the middle of this south facing wall.  It is where the space between rock face and lake is most narrow.
protection: I used a #2 hex, blue tricam, and some nuts in the 10 to 13 range. Top roping would require at least 50 feet of rope/webbing because the trees are set back.

description: The right of the two bolted lines that share anchors. ¬†4 bolts 2 bolt anchor.
The obvious arete route left of Blueberry Funk and Gingergay. ¬†2 Bolts, 2 Bolt Anchor.
Crux could be getting off the ground. Friction climbing at it's best! Finding the route might be your biggest challenge.
location: A few feet to the left of the tree. The line, and start are not that obvious. Peach colored line in the beta photo.

description: Crux is down low. A few tenuous foot placements make things interesting.
location: Just to the right of the tree.

description: Work your way around to the right side of the slab. Utilizing feet on the back part of the slab.
location: Starts on far right of slab. Work your way around the arete for some steeper climbing. Yellow route in beta photo.

description: Crux is getting off the ground and around the arete. Could be a big move to the top.
location: Left side of slab. This route has a sit start around the left side of the slab. Work your way to the front of the slab for easy climbing above.

description: Crux is trusting your feet.
location: Just to the right of the tree. Climbs just right of Slab Yellow, same start.

description: Just easy climbing to the top.
location: Right side of slab.

description: Amazing climb up the tallest section of the slab! Skate your way to the top, aiming for the two finger pocket as you go up.
location: Start on some blackish textured rock and head up! Start should be about in line with the small pockets near the top. Red route on the beta photo.
protection: Multiple pads and a spotter would probably be best.

description: Sit start low, left hand two finger pocket, right hand two finger divet. Move slightly left then up to a great shouldery undercling move and top out
location: Right of Easter island arete

description: Easy problem. Good for beginners.
location: Back left corner of boulder.

description: Sit start both hands on a ledge and small pocket on the narrow face of the boulder, climbing up the back face of the boulder through pinches, pockets and crimps. Make a committing move to the top. Stay off the front of the boulder until it‚Äôs time to top out.
location: Uphill from the Easter Island Boulder, backside of the slab climbs

description: Could be tough for shorter climbers.
Interesting movement.
Sit start left hand in two finger pocket, right hand in good pocket bear hugging the arete and climb straight up.
location: Obvious bulging arete on the Easter Island boulder

description: Crux could be the top out. Don't fall.
location: This problem is on the rock that the slab leans against.

description: Up! Top out could be crux.
location: This problem is on the rock that the slab leans against.

description: Stand start on the good circular (pancake looking) hold, make a big move left to some sharp jugs and straight up
location: To the right of Get Your Rocks Off

description: This is still up for grabs. Just work your way up the right side of the boulder, in front of the tree.
Move left from a stand up start towards the arete. Then move to the slab just left of the arete and to the top.
Move straight up the problem from a stand up start. First hold is usually chalked up and easy to spot.
location: First problem you encounter after you turn down the hill from the blue barrel.

description: Dominant line on the Pac-Man boulder. Compression style climbing with some techs moves on thin feet. ¬†Sit start left hand on obvious side pull edge and right hand arete. Climb straight up the blank arete and top out
location: Straight up the blank face of Pac-Man boulder

description: Fun traverse, a little pump.
location: This is a traverse, starts left, low to the ground.

description: Easy gently sloped.
location: Located on instant winner, starts just to the left of the tree.

description: Starts with an under cling sort of pinch. A few moves to the left, then over a steep lip to finish.
Sit start low right side of the boulder both hands on a good undercling. Move out left through ledges and pinches. Get over the lip in the center of the boulder and mantle up!
location: Low, right side of the Instant Winner boulder

description: Sit start very low two hands on a good ledge, bunched up, between some rocks on the ground (try not to dab the rocks!) head up the face through some pockets, heel hooks, and eventually jugs with an easy top out.
location: Obvious overhung arete boulder, if you‚Äôre looking at Acme it‚Äôs the boulder to the right of the anvil boulder.

description: Still up for grabs. Big moves to the top.
A little reachy for shorter folk.
Fun traverse starting at the left of the rock. Follow the ledge with under clings to its end. Then a 5 foot dyno to the left. Fantastic!
Little Bit of Lie Backing up a short crack.
Climb through the flake to the good ledge, mantle over on to the blank slab and delicately climb through
location: Towards the far end of the bouldering area.

description: Start on a corner ledge, move straight up and behind you to get the demanding top out
location: The last boulder at the end of the Little Rock wall. To the¬†right of The Long Haul

description: Easy climb up to a high traverse to the right.
location: A slightly reachy start.

description: An easy slab climb. Nice warm up rock close to the entrance of the bouldering area.
Stand start on two pockets bout chest high and climb up and right through pockets, topping out above the hand size crack. Fun problem
location: Backside of the anvil boulder

description: First route on the wall. South to north. Easy top rope
location: First route headed north on wall

description: offwidth
location: south wall area

description: up the center of the huge flak
location: right of rainy day

description: up the face on the right of tree
location: just right of unnamed .100 yards north on wall

description: get creative placing gear a little run out
location: south wall area

description: Nice liebacking up the first half of the route, where you meet the crux of the climb transitioning into a wider crack
location: The route is on the far north side of the wall.  It is best to drive north on route 7 past the Kiedaisch foot trail to the second high school spirit rock.  There is a foot path marked with blue dashes on the trees that will lead you to the climbing site.
protection: Crack requires midrange cams and a few small nuts

description: start on the small huecos up to flake on left then right and up to ledge then straight up
location: 75 feet north of tanasity

description: dirty flak arching to the right
location: 50 feet down to the right of ohanna

description: Very steep off with
location: South wall area

description: Start on flaks on right. Up to blocks in corner then up corner to shuts
location: south wall area

description: just to the right of milk money
location: just to the right of milk money

description: left facing dihedral offwith to the shuts
location: around corner and up the hill from battle of the bulge

description: fallow the bolt line
location: joes project area

description: Climb follows the first large crack on the south side of the wall.  Crux is about half way up route
location: Second route coming from the south side of the wall.
protection: Set of anchors at top.  Mostly cams needed to lead route.

description: up the chimey
location: south wall area

description: climb begins on portion of rock facing the river.  Reach around left side to clip draws in.  Crux is approx. 3/4 of the way up the route where you work yourself out onto the wall containing the bolts.
location: Approach to the route is from the south side of the Keidash trail.  Hike along the wall for approx. 1/4 mile.

description: Follow the bolts to two big flakes and then the crux is working yourself over a small bulge and to the right towards the anchors.
location: Begins at the top of a steep hill on the trail, about six feet to the right a small chimney with a low roof. Down the hill the cluster of Rainy Day, an unnamed route and Tannasity.

description: First half of poison ivy up the flaks. Then the second half of poison oak the off with.
location: south wall area
protection: nuts and cams shuts at top

description: Dihedral corner
location: joes project area

description: Work the corner on the lift of the bulge until it ends then traverce right then up to the shuts
location: just to the right of hannable lecter

description: Situated between Lichen and Leave it and Zumunda on the ar√™te. ¬†Make your way up the route in small incremental steps on thin rails. ¬† Crux is between 3rd and 4th bolt.
protection: sport bolts in rock lead to two shuts at top.

description: small sloppy rails
location: joes project area
Same boulder as Beneath the Bow. Just climb the relatively blank vertical face left of the arete.

description: Start on two small knobs and make a big move to the eye socket, match, turn it unto a undercling and figure out how to go underneath the small roof with some tricky toe/heel hook beta ¬†and then up the vertical face on the other side using the arete and good crimps.
location: Relatively easy to find. There is only a handful of boulders in the section of the woods.

description: Start low with a left hand on the lowest crimp and a right on a diagonal crimp. Use slopers and underclings to reach a shallow pocket. Figure out beta to get a nearly chest height foot and stand off that one leg(crux) to then finish by climbing the slab.
location: On the face of the first boulder that is facing you as you approach the area.

description: This is a super fun route directly to the left of the main rock outcropping seen across the lake. Its a rather lengthy route (really impressive for Ohio) that has a great combo of pushes and rests. The rock is super clean, but does have some lichen towards the left of the main route. The start is rather like a boulder problem, pulling hard and engaging the core to bring the feet up. Very cool to be climbing and look over your shoulder to see fellow hikers taking in the scenery on the adjacent rock. Awesome views from the top of the lake.
location: Hike 5-10 min counterclockwise on the "Lakeshore Trail" until you pass the giant rock outcropping. The route will be the closest on the left of the outcropping.

description: Start low on good pockets. Find the right pockets as you move up just left of the arete to the jug finish.
location: On the right wall of the overhang area at Workout Wall.
In the overhang area at Workout Wall.

description: Start on a good side pull and crimp on the lower left part of the boulder. Follow the obvious crack/seam across the face using some delicate foot work before making some tough moves to top out.
location: Just past the Fin Boulder on the left hand side of the trail
On the same arete as Sunshine Arete but start sitting at the very bottom of the boulder.
you can see the boulder from the picnic area parking lot. 2 min hike. There is currently a 'Brenda' graffitti to the right of the line.

description: Sit start low on the obvious rail. Mantle up, working left and up the quickly thinning seam. Establish feet high atop the seam on small edges. Top out on a good ledge above.
location: Right of the gearshift area, near the top of Sunshine Valley.
Located farther down the creek bed to the left of the large boulder in the middle of the valley. On the right wall of a little cave area.
Follow the trail past the creek bed the Fin is located on the first two boulders on your right.

description: A one move wonder. Start on the low ledge/rail and make the bigish throw to the lip and mantle over, you can also move to an intermediate hold to the right and the grade feels about the same
location: Along the cliff side, the left portion of the cluster
Located on the opposite side of the Sunshine boulder as you approach it.

When you arrive in the Workout Wall area follow the trail directly left of the first boulder that you come to (Block Arete 1). On this trail about 30 yards away you will find a long wall and this problem will be on the far right of this wall closest to the trail.

description: Start sitting down holding both jugs. Work your way up the problem with a few crimps and one finger pocket to a top out.
location: Follow the established trail to the Workout Wall area. Once arriving in there the problem is on the far right of the wall right next to the trail that takes you to Cascada Boulders. The problem is approximately 12ftt directly right of the Lean Crack problem and within 8ft to the left of the trail.

description: Start high on underclings and traverse right to the same finish as the pocket problem.
location: Just left of the pocket problem in the overhang area.

description: Follow Crack until first mantle. On the far right of the Workout Wall.
location: Far Right of Workout Wall

description: Same start as Book, Chapter and Traverse but stay on the low edge the whole time.
location: Same as Book, Chapter and Traverse.

description: Start in the big crack left of center in the over hang area. Traverse left along the shelf and top out around the corner.
location: In the overhang area to the left of the block boulder.
On the right side of the block boulder.
The block boulder is the first large boulder you see when you come to the workout wall area. Sit just in front of the over hang on the cliff face.

description: Starts on good holds at the bottom of the slab. Climbs through small knobs and crimps in the middle and good holds at the end again. Could be bouldered/ free soloed.
location: Located just up the hill from Shipwreck boulder. Big green slab with obvious line.

description: Start in the back of the cave on a good side pull with feet on the left wall, work through the roof crack using flaring hand jams and strenuous side pulls before making the big move to the slot at the lip and mantling over
location: Starts in the back of the cave right across from the currently unnamed dihedral problem, on the backside of rectangle rock in the jumble of boulders

description: Start on large ledge and move up into the dihedral on crimps and pockets to a narrow top out climbers left.
location: Follow the narrow corridor between Rectangle rock and the main wall. Boulder is located behind Rectangle rock
On the evolution boulder.
On the Evolution Boulder. Walk off the back of boulder.

description: Start on the jugs on right of the boulder and climb straight up and top out.
location: Same start as Evolution Center.
Boulder is to the left of gearshift when facing away from the cliff line. Get down by down climbing or jumping from the top out.

description: Starts on low ledge to the left of Constant Gardener and move up and to the right following a series on big ledge on the steep slab.  Joins the top of Control Joint and tops out, watch out for the fern.
location: On the left side of the Garden Wall boulder to the right of Constant Gardener.

description: Start on a good good edge and make a big move to a nice side pull.  Continue to top on crimps. (Only a select few know what the true meaning of the cryptic initials is).
location: On the far right end of the Garden Wall boulder, starts where the initials M.C.T.S are carved into the face.

description: Tallest problem on the Garden Wall boulder, follow the arete on the far left end and transitions onto the slab face near the top before topping out.
location: Far left side of the Garden Wall Boulder.
On the Garden Wall boulder to the right of The Gate.
Right side of the Garden Wall boulder to the right of Control Joint.

description: Climb the fist and off hand crack in the middle of the Garden Wall boulder, follows crack to the top.
location: Middle of the Garden Wall boulder.

description: Tall slab problem on the left side of the Garden Wall boulder.  Starts on underclings and moves straight up the face on small crimps to the top out.
location: Left end of the Garden Wall boulder on the tall slab to the right of Lake View arete.

description: Traverse across the pockety face starting on the far left and finish by topping out Triangle Arete 1.
location: Located on triangle rock.
Follows the arete on the up-hill side of triangle rock.
Located on the triangle boulder at the base of rectangle rock. Starts low on good edge on arete facing away from rectangle rock. Can down climb back of boulder.

description: The first 12-15ft of this route is the hardest part, once you get past this is becomes quite easy to top out. You can set a top rope but soloing it is pretty easy.
location: Walk on the left side of Rectangle Rock. Walk towards the corridor and this route is on the left before you enter the corridor.

description: Start in the middle of Rectangle Rock and work your way left across the rock and then up to a top out.
location: Directly in the middle of Rectangle Rock

description: Stand start with left and right hands on opposing sidepulls, move to sloping dish, and then up and left to a good (but hard to see) crimp. Then straight up (without use of the right arete).
location: Back of boulder on left side.

description: The first couple moves are the most difficult part, which are made up of mostly crimps. Once you get past these moves that holds are significantly easy. Climb about 10ft up to sloped/mossy finish.
location: On the left face side of the Rectangle Rock.

description: Follow the easy seam making liberal use of face holds
location: In the narrow corridor on the left hand side of rectangle rock

description: Climb up right slab of Rectangle Rock, once you reach the ledge the climbing becomes more difficult.
location: Right side on the face of Rectangle Rock.

description: Start with easy climbing on the obvious flake. Crux is after you reach the ledge.
location: The start is in the middle of rectangle rock on the obvious flake.
protection: Anchors on trees at the top. Bring plenty of webbing and static rope.

location: Starts in the middle of triangle rock on the same side as triangle arete 1.
Right at the front of Rectangle Rock. Easily visible as you walk up the path.

description: Start on the low incut crimps. Climb the arete to the top.
location: On the backside of Rectangle rock on the obvious fin/flake feature.
On the left side of the Shipwreck boulder.

description: Starts on right of boulder with right hand on arete and left on 'scar' side pull. Stand up and traverse through some slopers at the lip then press mantle to top out. Very balance oriented problem.
location: Up the hill and a little left from shipwreck rock at the end of a small corridor between a large boulder and the cliff line.
Located on the Shipwreck boulder. First boulder you come to in the area.

description: Start at the start for Mean Gene and friction traverse left into Hate Crime. ¬†Smear your feet high and mantle onto the sloping ledge, press up into a hand foot match and reach up into good pockets above. Tops out at the top of Hate Crime.
location: North face of the boulder
protection: Multiple Pads and a spotter, bad landing.

description: Start low on pockets in the center of the southeast face of the boulder.  Pick your way up heavily pocketed steep face and top out.
location: Center of the southeast face just to the left of Guantanamo Bay.

description: Work your way straight up the steep slab making use of good friction, shallow ripples and a few sloper pockets to a high chicken head and deep pockets at the top.  Top out in the grove.
location: West side of the Detention Block about 7 feet to the right of Hate Crime.

description: Start at the base of the arete on the left. ¬†Smear your right foot and mantle up into a hand foot match on the lower ledge. ¬†Climb the arete to a sloping ledge, ¬†mantel up and get a high foot and step up to deep pockets on the upper left corner of the west face and top out.
location: Ar√©te on the far left end of the west face of the boulder.
protection: Multiple pads and spotters, bad landing.

description: Good foot holds, good hand holds, but has some variety including vertical pinches for the beginning climber or a warm up for others. It's a little mossy on top.
location: It is the main vertical line of holes near the skinny tree

description: Start low on the pocketed face in the center of the southeast side of the boulder.  Move left onto a rail and continue up the steep face on small crimps to larger ledges near the top.  Pull through the ledges and negotiate the tricky top out.
location: Starts near the center of southeast face directly left of pickpocket.

description: Start on pockets on the right side of the southeast face. Continue up the steep face on shallow pockets, thin rails and slopey edges.
location: Locate near the right side of the southeast face to the right of Guantanamo Bay.

description: Sit start on the left side with having your hands matched on a distinguished sloper your toes in two small pockets right off the ground. Work your way up to the right using some small crimp ledges. Reach high for the horn up top and that is the crux. Continue up a little more to the right and get both hands into the pockets and that is the top out to Spider monkey.
location: At the base of the first wall as you walk up to the crag. It is a slight overhanging boulder.

description: Sit start a few feet right of Birds Nest. Work up a few feet then dyno/stretch out left to a far away pocket. ¬†Side pull on the crack near the top and use friction to finish.
Stand up start and work your way straight up the problem, the holds are good and fairly easy but the top out can be quite tricky.
location: The middle of the Cabin Boulder

description: Start standing up, work your way up the crack to a top out
location: On the left side of the face of the Cabin Boulder

description: A decent Offwidth start leads into a grunter of a chimney. Chicken wing and arm bar your way up 40ft of chossy goodness, Than emerge from the earth like a new born climber! Solid trees to build anchors at top. (Route was leadable at one point by slinging chok stones inside the chimney, but they have since fallen out)
location: To the right¬†of "J Tree" Walk a few hundred feet and find this obvious crack along the wall.

description: A short and dirty route that would be even easier if you didn't have to clear out mud and leaves from the cracks during the climb. Lots of very rounded edges also make this slightly difficult. The cracks are big and deep enough to fit your entire hand in.
location: East side of the climbing area by the only decent tree that is within 10 feet of the cliff.
protection: Many trees are available at the top to create a safe TR.

description: Start compressing on to bad slopers with right heel and slap your way up the arete.
location: Located two boulders left of the cascada boulder. Short arete between two other small boulders.
On the cascada boulder around the corner to the left of La Cascada.
The Cascada boulder. A large, short boulder right at the bottom of the waterfall. Route is on the side facing the cliff.
Starts in the middle of the cascada boulder on the low over hang part right between La Cascada and Cascada Traverse.
Located on tall blank boulder behind the cascada boulder and Versicolor. Starts high on only hold on the face.

description: Start five feet to the right of the original Cascada Traverse, just below lip on right facing seam/edge. Make a couple moves on slopers to start of Cascada Traverse and follow lip to arete and top out.
location: Located on far right of the Cascada boulder a few feet right of Cascada Traverse. Adds a couple delicate sloper moves to the original traverse to complete the full line.
Same side of boulder as La Cascada.
Large boulder to the right of the cascada boulder. Line starts on the features on the right of the boulder.
See area map.

description: Stand up start, climb straight up the side of the boulder to a easy top out.
location: On the right side of the Cabin boulder.

description: Start on the hand rail in the middle of Birds Nest and traverse right all the way to Peeler and top out... ¬†Good hands, little feet.
This is the far right crack on the boulder... follow it to the top.
From the back side of the boulder (short side) this is the farthest left problem... The easiest way to the top. ¬†Hop down from the boulder at this point, standard decent.
Start low on the left side of the boulder with low feet and off two pockets. ¬†Pinch the pockets and make a big move up to a good ledge. ¬†Pull the roof to slopers then to jugs at the top.

Traverse that works head height right to left utilizing pockets and knobs (which are my favorite). Start right in these two pockets and work your way left across the crack and into the pockets on the other wall. reach the far left jug pocket and that is the top out.
location: At the base and in the middle of the wall

description: Climb up the first and most distinguished crack of the wall.
location: In between Spider Monkey and Spider Man

description: Follows a crack up a series of short triangular roofs
location: Route is located on the far left of the Dam climbing area at the base of a set of twin cracks.  Shares a start with Shakey Dog, Triangles follows the left hand crack.
protection: Bolts. It is easy to lead this route using gear as protection in the crack. Route can easily be toproped.

description: easy ledges up to the leftmost drill line, blanker face and smaller moves from there to the top
location: leftmost drill line
protection: fixed bolts at the top of the cliff

description: Follows a crack up to a small roof then out right onto a left facing sloppy flake.
location: Shares a start with Triangle on the far left end of the Dam climbing area.  Follows the right of the two cracks.

description: climb up to and along the right drill line
location: right drill line near the center of the South Wall, left of Danger zone
protection: bolts at top of cliff to set TR

description: rightmost side of the south cliff, lots of ledges
location: rightmost climb on the wall
protection: fixed bolts at the top of the cliff

description: move right of the stump halfway up the wall
location: right of full stump and right of the stump on the ledge halfway up the wall
protection: bolts at the top of the cliff

description: go up the left side and around the left of the big stump on the ledge. Stump is solid right now but may loosen up over time
location: left of the stump, left of south side stump
protection: bolts farther back on top of cliff

description: follow easy ledges up to the bulge on the right of the south wall to a slightly overhanging finish. lots of loose rocks and dirt, should clean up with more traffic and rain
location: bulge directly right of the large dirty crevasse on the south wall.
protection: anchors on top of cliff face, TR

description: Route wanders to climbers right, climbing around a small beech tree, then up to top out or lower off top rope anchor.
location: Route starts approximately 15' to the right of right field.
protection: approximately 50' of rope for top rope anchor from medium size beech tree about 15' back from the edge of the rock.

description: Start from a ledge and follow a thin finger crack up to a left leaning hand crack.
location: The right of the two routes with a roof near the start.  15 feet right of Center Field.
protection: .4 to #1 Camelot and small to medium stoppers

description: Starting can be a bit tricky, but once on the shelf, it is pretty smooth going up. The route is covered in Lichen currently, so it does need to be cleaned. And this makes for a fun laid back top rope route. I would like to see bolts in the future as this would be a good "first Lead" route.
location: On the "field side" of the Green Monster. There is a thorn bush at the bottom of the route.
protection: No bolts yet, only natural top rope anchor.

description: Climb the wide crack with the large tree growing in the middle to a chossy thinner crack and top out.
location: Prominent crack in the cliff line in the rear of left field.

description: The small pocketed face that looks like a honeycomb on the far left side of the baseball field.
location: Heavily pocketed face right of Left Field
protection: X rated trad line, easily top roped

description: Climbs the wall close to the arete.  Route goes straight up the wall on crimps and curves to climbers left to anchors.
location: Walk to the cliff at the rear of the baseball field.  Follow the cliff to the left and around the corner. Route is the right bolted line of the three sport route, shares anchor with Cracker Jack.

description: On the Catacomb Wall, to the right of Willy Tea. Start at the crack and move to the right of the ‚Äúcatacomb area‚Äù. The object is to stay out of the ‚Äúcatacomb area‚Äù in the middle of the crag. Due to the direction you have to climb and where the Top Rope Anchor is, you will swing quite a bit if you fall.
location: Start at the center crack, where you start Willy Tea. Move to the right of the ‚Äúcatacomb area‚Äù. The object is to stay out of the ‚Äúcatacomb area‚Äù in the middle of the crag.

description: Follow crimps and sloping pockets straight up the sandstone face.  Shares bolted anchor with Green Monster.
location: Walk to the cliff at the back of the baseball field and follow the cliff to the left around an arete.  The route is the middle bolted route of the three.

description: The left of the two cracks with a roof to pull near the start
location: Walk to cliff at the rear of the baseball field, look for thin crack starting at a ledge under a small roof. Center of cliff line right of Honeycomb.
protection: .5 to #3 Camelot and medium to large stoppers

description: This is an excellent wall with lots of foot and handholds galore!  The wall is flat until you get to the brain (approx 30' up) then it gradually pitches out.
protection: No bolts yet.  Planning to add them soon.  Large tree at the top and a large boulder in front of it with a natural channel that's weathered out over the top of it to feed an anchor through (We made a tensionless anchor out of static rope).

description: Short, crimpy and slightly overhanging. Small roof crux right before anchor chains. Route arc's slightly to the climbers left.
location: At the cliff line in the rear of the baseball field walk to the left around a corner into the woods and see a wall with three bolted lines. Farthest left of the three sport routes on this wall.

description: Start in the crack and follow it up the face.  Main crack tapers out near the top, traverse left to another finger crack and top out.
location: Located on the face to the left of Hot Monkey Love.  Look for the S shaped crack in the middle of the face between Gargamel and Doing Time.
protection: Small to medium stoppers and cams from fingers to hands (.5 to 2).  Use trees at the top of the cliff for anchors.

description: Climb the cracks up the dihedral.
location: Located in the dihedral to the left of Hot Monkey Love.
protection: Medium to larger gear, best to top rope this route.  Anchor from trees at the top of the cliff.

description: Vertical face climbing up small edges and pockets.
location: Located 10 feet to the right of Shakey Dog

description: This climb is slightly overhung and will dish out sloppers, monos, painful underclings and the like. Use the chicken head cautiously and enjoy the finishing crux. easy toprope access
location: In the Dam area, found on the wall to the right of the S crack.
protection: 4 bolts and cold shuts for anchors

description: Balancy bouldery start that leads to easy slab climbing.
location: Located on the right side of the prominent arete to the right of Mono e Mono

description: A slightly overhanging start on big holds to a stance, followed by a slightly thinner move to more jugs and a dirt top out. Extremely dirty, like most Vesuvius climbs, but the holds are there and the moves are fun Red River-type hauls. Enjoyable, if brief.
location: Hike down the main trail from the dam about 100 yards until the trail crosses a dinner table sized flat rock, then turn right. There are 3 house-sized detached boulders here; walk straight up to the main wall, keeping the boulders on your right. The climb is on the obvious pocketed arete.
protection: The FA was done as a rope solo using the big tree 5 ft to the left of the arete for an anchor. Could be led with some small gear (around Camalot .4) in horizontals at about 15 and 20 ft, if one were so inclined.

description: Bouldery start up to roof, pull through the roof and continue up the easier slabby face.
location: Located on the face to the left of Hot Monkey Love between S Crack an Oh So Slippery.  Starts under the prominent roof.

description: SDS right of tree and cling to the lip as you move right.
SDS on jug under roof and move up through the skull that is chiseled into the rock.
SUS on sloper rails and move up the face directly across from 'Crack Face'.

The rock is sandstone and pretty dirty so holds can be flakey, I ripped off a couple holds projecting. Start on the left side of the wall with left hand at the bottom of the huge divot. Right hand to a side pull about waist height. Work straight up to a crimp above head to the right, continue working right to big ledge. There is a good hold above and right of the ledge, mantle on ledge to top out.
location: Walk up the bong hill trail, about half way up there is a trail that breaks off right towards the cliff face. The fence will be obviously bent over and a you will see a trail going away from the fence. Follow the trail all the way down to the far end of the cliff face. Just before the cliff face ends you will see a rock wall about 10 feet tall.

description: Find the low side pull then move through the middle using crimps. Then enjoy the juggy top out right of the tree.
location: Right of Drop, Lock, and Pocket

route_name: With a Brush and a Vengeance
description: Start below the hueco on jug underclings, head up and left into the hueco.  Reach up and left for a sidepull pocket before heading up onto the edge and up and right onto jug holds to top out.
location: Just left off of the trail on your way to the Commitment Boulders.  Just to the right of the roof and left of the cave.

description: Start on the finger size seams and move up and left following the crack and eventually top out on the ledge up and as far left as possible.  Watch out for the fecal matter on certain portions of the ledge.
location: Around the corner and left of With a Brush and a Vengeance.

description: Begin with a sit start under the rock on the left side of the boulder. Find the good holds to pullup and out from under the rock. Then finish with a slabby jug hull to the top.
Start with a double pocket start with high feet. Finish with a top out left of the tree.
location: Right of Flakey

description: Start at the bottom of the Arete and follow the good holds to the top.
location: Behind the big double boulder.

description: Use the ledge to start and follow the crimps to move towards the arete. Then use the jugs and finish on top of the arete.
location: On a "ball" like boulder on the uphill side of the RockHouse trail. This problem is on the other face next to Three Star Face and right of Food Evolution.

description: Use the two pockets at the start to move to a pocket on the left. Then bust a move to the jugs for a top out right of the tree.
location: Right of You Got Me Sweaty

description: Face climb with an arete
Start with a match on the lower flake then move through the slightly overhanging face with jugs for the top out.
location: Uphill side of the RockHouse trail on the back inner wall of the "ball" like boulder.

description: Sit start with good jugs on the bottom of the arete. Then move under the mini roof to the slopy top out.
location: This is a small boulder on the down hillside from the "ball" like boulder. It is a small boulder on the right side of the Rockhouse trail coming form Sells parking lot.

description: Start between the two cracks and follow the crimps to a top out on the right.
location: Right of mini dihedral

description: Sit start under the low shelf. Then move high and follow the traverse to a good ledge for the finish.
location: This is the middle boulder on the uphill side of the Rockhouse Trail. Its most notable mark is the sloped roof, and the boulder sits on a 2-foot ledge.

description: Climb the good holds to the slopey top out.
Find the good feet to start. Then move to the pocket for a finish with nice jugs moving left of the tree.
location: Right of Hot Pocket

description: Begin with good crimps and follow them to the jug line. Follow jugs to top out left of the tree
location: Right of Fake Flake

description: Start in between the two rock faces that are divided by a small crack. Then enjoy the smallish holds and steeming moves to the top out towards the right.
location: Righ of Dextrose

description: Start underneath the roof on the smallest block feature. Move underneath the roof and out on to the ledge of the roof. Then find the good hold in the crack to top out.
location: This is the upper boulder on the uphill side of the trail. The boulder has a small roof and a slopy top. The problem starts under the roof on the smallest block-like feature.

description: Same start as Slope Star, finish with a top out using the upper crack.
location: This is the upper boulder with a large roof on the uphill side of the trail.

description: Use the crips to the horizontal flake then go for the jugs for a top out left of the tree.
location: Right of Much

description: Begin with a sit start and move up and over the bulge to a sloper section. Then use the good handholds and fun slaby footholds to top out.
location: This route is on the uphill side of the Rockhouse trial pass PawPaw Connector trail. It is on the boulder that is home to Whale Belly, located on the opposite side just left of the arete.

description: A fun matching start in a medium-size pocket. Then finishing on a jug and sloper to top out.
location: On the "ball" like boulder on the uphill side of the trial. Right of Cutleaf Toothwort.

description: Start with a match on a low ledge. Move through the crimps and towards the pocket. Then use the good jugs to top out.
location: The uphill side of the RockHouse trail on the right face of Broken Glass.

description: Start with a two-pocket start and use good crimps to the top out.
location: Right of Bobcat Crack

description: Follow the jugs to the mantle top out.
Follow the flake to a top out left of the tree.
location: Right of Up and Up

description: Start with the crimps at the bottom and move to the left side of the pocket. The find the good jugs to top out right of the tree.
location: Right of Pocket Putty

description: Start left of the mini dihedral and follow the slab-like rock to finish on the left.
location: This is the farthest route on the left side of the wall.

description: Begin with a sit start using high handholds on the arete. Then use a mix of good holds and good crimps to top out on the taller side of the boulder.
location: On the "ball" like boulder on the uphill side of the trial. This problem is on the opposite side of the boulder of where Three Star Face and Broken Glass are.

description: Begin with a match in a hand size pocket. Move up and left for good holds and top out at the peak of the boulder.
location: This is the wedge-like boulder on the uphill side of the RockHouse trail after PawPaw Connector. The climb is on the far right side on the vertical face portion of this boulder.

description: A fun and finger focused route also great options for feet.
location: The ridge at the top of the hill which is home to most of the problems at COAD.

description: Follow the good jugs across the rock face. Great climb to do while waiting for a problem to open up. Also, it is good to work the feet and improve endurance.
location: This is the ridge on top of the hill that is home to the majority of the problems at COAD.

description: Start at the indent of the arete and find the good feet. Then follow the arete to the top out.
location: This is the wedge-like a boulder on the uphill side of the Rockhouse Trail after PawPaw Connector. This climb shares the same arete with Free From.

description: Sit start, then use the arete and good crimps on the right to finish on a slab-like top out.
location: Uphill side of the RockHouse trail on the back inner wall of the "ball" like boulder. Right of Little.

description: Start below the crack and move into the good holds in the crack. Then follow the holds to the top out.
location: Right of spoons not forks

description: Use jugs and underclings with a crag near the top
location: Downhill and S of Fire in the Hole

description: Start with a crimp and a sloper pinch. Move to the good crimp and flow through the slopey top out.
location: This climb is on the far end (opposite of the crack) on top of the hill on the ridge that hosts most of the climbs.

description: SUS in right pocket and left rail. Make an awkward move to reach the slimpers.

Located on the right side of the cave behind the small boulder that sits in the fall zone for this problem. SUS at a jug at head height, make moves out to the roof above the boulder. This one can be dirty quite often, so brush the top out if it has rained at all recently.
Low start on a bad left hand and right 2/3 finger pocket. Make a couple of desperate moves to easier climbing.

Start under the roof right of the prow on the large jug shelf. Work left off the rail to prow, then up through the pockets for the best possible path that will lead to a send. This line is very tall, with a slightly sloping land, so bring several pads and a good spotter.
SUS to ledge just below the boulder that perches on the edge. Make a dyno or figure out how to avoid it. Tops out on the perched boulder.
SUS and climb the finger crack. One of the best problems in the witches.
SDS on gritty rail and move straight up to a six foot top out.
SDS on jugs near choss.
SUS on sloper. Head straight up.
Start on the same jug rail as 'Light Show' and work right up through the weakness. Heading right then back left will probably yield the best results.
Possible roof crack problem, it has been aided.
Climb the arete feature that starts above the ramp. This line will need heavy cleaning.
SUS and climb the less than vertical face through less than quality rock.
SDS on sideways jugs under arete.
SUS and climb the face via crmps and edges, goes up and through the small bulge/arete.
SDS in large pocket and move straight up into trough like top out. Used to be easier, but broken jugs are challenging.
SDS on ¬ìWitches Backside¬î and move right after second hold, move across slimpers and other trash to reach a weakness in the topout.
Work from start up ride side of the arete to awkward undercling (Thumb-dercling) then to slopey mantel.
SUS. Climb the easy crack system.
Climb the wide crack and its sides to the top.
Climb the slab with feet, no hands or knees. Anything else is cheating!
SUS on the right and traverse to the other side.
SUS and climb through slopers to the lip.
SDS on jug and travel left around the prow. Utilizes same boulder as Route 12.
SDS and work into a shouldery move. Then reach for the top.
Mantel on the flat feature to an easy top out.
SDS on right side of arete. Make use of limited feet; if you get off the ground you've down more than most.
Easy mantel practice.
Climb the broken crack system to better holds.
Climb the arete to the top.
Same start as Lip Traverse. Instead, travel up and over to the top. Awkward moves followed by slabby top out.
Climb the angled arete on this free standing boulder to a slabby top out.
SUS Climb to the right of the crack and left of arete up the slabby dihedreal.
SUS Crimps lead to large move to good edge followed by another to the amazing topout.
A direct start leads to a great climb that presents with a splendid view.  Remain on the face about 5ft left of the bulge and the Spare Tire Route.
Climb the overhanging off-width chimney like crack in left corner of the recess.  Quite interesting
The Face to the Right of Easy A, left of the Pig Snout
A mossy slab start and plenty of holds.
location: First short face before the corner. Located on the left on the trail to the Big Wall base.

description: Ledgy starts on the outer right face of the recess and ends to the left of two chopped off tree stumps. There are numerous ledges. Stay to the right of the corner.

Direct boulder start is a 5.12a. Standing start. Directly over the bulge and then up to the finish. Pulling the upmost roof is doable with some cleaning. Dry in Rain. The bulge will definitely take some energy and you will have to be crafty because although it is a dry area, the rock is quite sandy.
Stays to the right of the stumps and to the left of the Nipple Route. Directly over the bulges. End at the top ledge.
Climb the right crack in the wall's recess. A bit off-width and slight overhang. End to the right of the two large vertical cracks at the top.
protection: Top Rope, trees and a passive pro placement at the ledge

description: Located in the crag's indent. Start at the center between the two large vertical cracks with lots of ledges for a short route. Left of the Hornet nest.

The left most of the two bolted routes in this area. I do not know who bolted this or when, looks to be put up within the last year. I'm adding it since the area is not showing any sport routes. Feel free to change if you are the bolter. The route felt like a 5.10 but feel free to adjust if you feel otherwise. This route was very sandy and did not feel comfortable trusting hands or feet. Bolts are solid regardless of how sandy the rock feels.
location: First bolted route on the wall. left most bolted route when facing the wall.

description: Thirty five feet of twists and turns will challenge you and have you wondering if you should have made a different start.  Overhanging Arete, right of Easy A, Starts at the left of the big crack . Lower horn looks like the profile of a pig's front quarter.

Start to the left of the roof section on the right end of the South face of the Big Wall. Direct start. Stay left of the major crack and climb straight up the thin face. Ends at the major horizontal shelf prior to the top.  You may be tempted to use the crack but climbers say that it proves quite useless.
Right side of the recess crack, ledgy start and some overhang. Had a hornets nest at the top left overhanging ledge.
protection: Top Rope, trees + passive pro placed at

description: Direct start, horns and slopers. No use of Easy A crack to the right. You may want to rappel and sweep it first.

Start to the left of the Firepit and the crack. A sloped foot start to directly up. Had pink chalk on parts of it. Follow the major zig zagging cracks to the top. Route ends at the upper most ledge prior to top out. Plenty of alternate paths.

Start on the roof and then straight up the crack. It is called the firepit because people insist on building illegal fires.  Do your part and refrain from any type of campfire while you are visiting Beach City.

Not sure who bolted this route but adding it since it isn‚Äôt listed on Mountain project. This is the second of the two bolted routes on this wall. This is the right-hand route while facing the wall. This route has fairly solid holds and is bolted about every 5 feet. it has 6 bolts and triple bolted anchor. The hardest move is the ledge to the roof. Not positive of the rating but it feels 5.10 ish, please adjust as you see fit.
location: This is the right hand bolted route while facing the wall.

description: Climb the flake's crack to the top. A slight overhang makes it fun.
protection: This can be top roped, but I've only climbed it on lead.¬† The crack goes all the way to the top.¬† This should definitely be listed as trad and top rope.

description: Above the Firepit roof follow the black streak straight up, to the right of the Firepit route. Dyno start, boulder start may be an option.
First slab section of the Big Wall, with a black color to it. Pulling the two roofs is a possible harder ending variation.
Follow the thin, horizontal finger crack to the top out finish
Direct start, approximately 5 ft left of the flake face. Straight up and over the two 'pockets.'
Follow the three obvious two handed pockets to the top of the ledge and top out.
Start on two small pockets and make one move to a matched hand finish.
location: Closest route to the right-most bouldering sign.

description: Follow the arete¬† on large holds to the top of the ledge
Start in the slopey pockets to the right of the colonnade.  Move up on bad feet to top out over the lip above.
location: Right of Long Duck Dong and Bird's Nest

description: Start on the colonnade, same as bird's nest, then move right using the sidepull to stand up on right side of the colonnade then top out the same as for Bird's Nest
location: Same start as Bird's Nest

description: Climb up the colonnade that Bird's Nest starts on then move out left to the obvious jug.  Top out directly over the jug without moving back right towards Bird's Nest.
location: Same start as Bird's Nest, topping out right of Bird's Nest.

description: Start on a pockety ledge and then move up to a frictiony and balancy top out above.
location: To the right of Tarzan on the opposing face.

description: SDS on colonnade and work up the slopers on the left side to a throw for a few slopey holds and the top out.
location: Starting from the colonnade and going straight up the most obvious line.

description: Start on the colonnade and then move left to the jug and traverse left, topping out left of Dope Nose/Three Times a Lady.
location: Starts on colonnade moving left to top out.

route_name: One Flew Over the Cukoos Nest
description: Southside of dome is an obvious vertical crack. That goes through the overhang
location: southside of dome.

route_name: If I Only Had A Brain
first_ascent: Equipped by Nate Renner and Greg Parker  First Ascent by Greg Parker

description: Right side of face. Much easier than the other routes on this face.

Fun lead/climb that starts left of Mesiah. Crack looks like a lightning bolt that goes up and left above a slab that is off limits.  Anticlimatic end inside a chimney with a large, blocky chockstone in it. A more exciting finish is to protect in the chimney and head right for a no-pro to the top. (The old original book says this route follows the crack for a bit then goes straight up. I dont remember it there is any protection for this version...)
location: left of Mesiah set several feet above a left running slab
protection: passive pro! A set of nuts and maybe a hex or two if youre leading and chord for the top anchors of trees

description: Wigwam only has one piton half way up.  Lots of fun with a bar stool sized summit.
location: Across the highway from Totem pole.  Climb the south side.
protection: One piton with a Needles rappel

description: Overhanging face to the right of medusa
protection: Could be led with nuts and small cams.

description: Stay between and use two small broken cracks on an obvious face. The crux is about halfway up the route. You will gain a ledge to your left on what looks like a square bulge. Hit this with your hands but don't be tricked...you want to head right for some good hands, then straight up.
location: Look to climbers left of the obvious arete (Medusa - 5.10).  Climb obvious face.
protection: Lots of trees at the top to set a solid anchor. Possible to trad lead.

description: Start on arete corner with decent sidepulls on right, pull the roof and continue up easier terrian on the face.
location: just right of mesiah and left of a vegetated dihedral

description: Dihedral and off width crack.  Bad rock near top grinds when stood on, but is stable.  Requires a variety of techniques, good route for noobs to learn on.  Reaches are long for small children, though.
protection: 0.5 cam or large nut and one loop in rock tunnel.  Bomber tree and rock at top for top belay.  Will get 8 feet above pro at one point.

description: Climb the dihedral just a few feet right of Thor.
Left side of wall, crux is down low. Hard 5.9
Start below large crack and climb directly upward. Center of face. Tricky climbing will foil some 5.9 climbers.

This route is the second route from the left. It starts with 3 bolts of 5.10 climbing followed by a wicked crux section on tiny crimps and pockets with no footholds. The fourth bolt is difficult to clip. It's actually easier to bypass it and clip it after you've done the crux and it's at your knees and the last bolt you've clipped is three feet below your feet. Fairly creepy. Luckily, it's probably only 5.11a after the crux. While attempting the first ascent I broke a hold and fell on the 5.11a section after fighting through the crux, which forced me to do the scary crux again. This is probably not the easiest 13a to go out and project.

first_ascent: Equipped by Nate Renner; First Ascent by Greg Parker
description: This route is awesome. In my opinion, if this route was at a bigger area, it would be one of the more sought after 12c's in the canyon. This route is the second route from the right. It's very powerful with many one-handed pulls with little or no intermediates. After the fourth bolt the route traverses up and right for one more bolt to reach Cowardly Lion's anchors. Superb.
protection: 5 bolts, funky anchor consisting of two locking carabiners.

first_ascent: Equipped by Nate Renner; First Ascent by Greg Parker
description: This is the far right route and climbs through the steepest section of the wall. Please stick-clip the first bolt to avoid any possible diggers off the ledge. This route begins with easy climbing that quickly gives way to a thin pocket crux complete with a half-pad crimp mono! A long reach to and off of a decent mono marks the crux, but the steep black bulge above should not be taken lightly. This route has great sequential climbing on great stone. The top can get a little dirty from run-off early in the season.
protection: 5 bolts, funky anchor consisting of two locking carabiners.

first_ascent: Howard Doyle, Phil Sena, and Paul Muehl 1984
description: start at the bottom of the small ledge next to a dirt mound, climb up with little protection to a nice pod about 35 feet up. Place good gear then climb the small overhanging finger crack.(crux)Then its about 20 feet of easy climbing to the top with an optional gear placement. Descent: you can either walk of or sling a big horn with your rope and rappel.
location: walk about 25 yards past End Pin. If you turn around and face End Pin it will be on the left side. It is to the right of Bushwhacker. look for and overhang with a small pod below it.

protection: Medium to large cams for the beginning and smaller pieces for the traverse.  There is a bolt anchor at the top.

first_ascent: Fritz Wiessner, Lawrence Coveney, Percy Olton, and Marguerite Schnellbacher (1936)
location: Route begins immediately above guardrail.
protection: Standard rack. Large cam for second chimney. Anchors.

route_name: "Pins and Needles" (assumed name, please correct it)
location: This route ascends from the lowest point of rock on the left side of the Tent Peg as seen from the downhill side.
protection: Not much- a few nuts and aliens or TCU's or better yet, TR from the anchors at the top.

location: This cliff is located on the south side of highway 385, just inside the park boundary. It is just to the east of Earl's Gas station. Looking south from highway 385, this cliff is on the left (east) side of a drainage to the south of the road.
Barber/Cleveland routes share a start at the notch with TENT PEG.
protection: No pro. Basically a free solo. No anchors.  Needles Style Rap

first_ascent: Henry Barber, Dennis Horning, Chip Lee, 1977

description: This route is just to the left of the Tricouni/Cerberus route. The first bolt is an obvious modern bolt, followed by two solid pitons, a super sketchy button head, then a large runnout (R) to a bolt near the top. The anchor is then built on the leftmost pinnacle.

protection: One bolt was placed on lead. Crack takes friends and small nuts and RP's at the top.
Quickdraws for bolts and pins, long runner for a flake, medium stoppers.

first_ascent: Todd Swain, Mitchell Frey & Matt Safford 05-08-1983
Josh Mudge and Tim Robinson Aug 25, 2018
description: Start climbing up through the low agle rock to the dish where you can clip the first bolt. Pass one more bolt to gain a small ledge. At this point you can place an optional #1 BD. Continue up angling right on easier terrain, then move up and left to a small "pedestal". Getting your feet on this is slightly cruxy (there is a crappy small cam placement to help get the next bolt clipped from the pedestal). From this point the climbing gets harder and somewhat sequential but if you have clipped the bolt from the pedastal it is very well protected. Climb past the well protected crux to the anchors. This route can also be toproped. Access by going around the mass to the left. A couple approx. 5.6 moves gain you access to the anchors. Bolted ground up with hand drills using hooks and cams as needed.
location: Hike up past the Pawn to the left, ¬†angling up the hill and to the left. Once you reach the top of the hill the climb is the obvious steep face with Super Pickle green lichen.
protection: Bolts, chain anchors. Optional #1 bd and a small cam (about the size of a green C3 I believe- offset X4 may work well but this placement is definitely not needed)

description: Start with left hand on low undercling on orange-ish face and right hand sidepull on other side of boulder‚Äôs road facing ar√™te. Many decent holds to choose from lead you to a large shelf on the ar√™te from which you can top out.
location: Problem climbs the orange face and road-facing ar√™te of the thumb shaped block 1.2 miles down the road from the Rankin Ridge Fire Tower. Boulder will be on the right side if you are driving from the tower.

description: To the left of Super Pickle. Go up the the groove, I remember placing some very marginal gear. ¬†Once on top of the groove move up and slightly right aiming for the first flaring crack where you get your first decent gear. Continue up to the obvious bigger crack placing good gear. The first ascent continued left of the block head summit after some bear hugging.
location: To the left of Super Pickle
protection: Single rack. Need to build an anchor up top.

description: Climb the SW arete of split pin
location: SW arete

first_ascent: Pete Delannoy, Paul Muehl, Brian Sarni, Jeff Wilber, Tim Loften, May 31, 1982.
description: Begin on the north face of split pin, climb to a (very) old bolt. Then follow pitons up and left until the crack peters out then place a small piece and run it to the top.
location: N face of split pin

description: Climb onto the northwest arch of the bridge (crux), then follow the arch out to its high point. One aid move will bring you onto the railing and the top (100 feet; 5.6 A1).
location: Beaver Creek Bridge on highway 87.
protection: Bring many huge slings for the pillars and to lasso the railing to aid up onto the roadway.

first_ascent: Paul Muehl, Pete DeLannoy, and Renn Fenton (7/8/85)
description: The lower crack is fairly easy climbing with great placement options.  After climbing for about 25 feet you traverse to the left over a bulge and do a short traverse.  This is a bit scary as there aren't too many gear options.  Head up again after about 10 feet with good gear placements behind a flake.  The crux for me was the face climbing which starts at about half way up the climb on top of the flakes.
location: The route is located on the northeast corner of the formation in an obvious dihedral.  You can climb this or the nice crack on the face.  Two ropes will be needed to get down to your starting point.  You may want to bring webbing to replace the anchor.  It was ok as of 11/07/07, but usually gets brittle quickly.
protection: The bottom half takes bomber nuts, cams, and I placed a hex as well.  The top half is bolted.  Bring a lot of slings with biners for the bottom and at least 8 draws for the top bolted section.

description: Climb the Arete on the uphill side.
location: From the Spires parking lot, it's, uh, well right there.
protection: Few small pieces and a fixed peg.

first_ascent: Royal and Liz Robbins, Aug 1964. Direct Var. John Biddick
description: Start on the southeast end of the spire (downhill, near the road).  An unnecessary first bolt protects a direct start, or one can traverse in from 5 feet up on the left.
