location: Locate the Spire Eight mass. Approach from the S. Scramble up rock gully and take first left into another gully, belay here. Start up slab to a flake, first bolt is above this flake.

Read the general description page to find the route.   Back up slings on summit as needed and double rope rappel off the west side.  Be careful when pulling your rope as there are many potential horns to get your rope stuck on.
protection: standard rack.  Used a couple of hexes in some bomber slots.

location: This is the continuous looking crack system on the N corner when viewed from the Picket Fence perspective. Rap from two new bolts with webbing and rap ring. 70m would barely make it. Another set of anchors will take you from the 3/4 gully back down to the packs.
From the International Chimney continue up and left through the tight corridor up and towards the 3 prominent cracks.
protection: Standard Rack, long runners, #4 is nice

location: Located on the south east face of the Moving Finger formation.
protection: 4 old button head bolts and a few small cams.

description: Climb a wide chimney under a large chock stone.  Move up and to the right to a belay ledge with slings.  The summit block is cracked so be careful if you decide to climb up it.  It must be down climbed back to the belay ledge.
location: The route is in the gully between Rubaiyat Spire and Tower of Darkness/Shaft of Light/Moving Finger.  Look for a wide crack with a large chock stone on your left as you hike up the gully.
protection: Standard rack.  Webbing to rap off of.  Replace as needed.

first_ascent: Bob Kamps, Mark and Beverly Powell, August 1966
description: This is a well protected but still somewhat spicy lead up the north face of the spire.  Follow discontinuous cracks up the vertical face until a large ledge when it is possible and logical to traverse left into an rightward arching chimney.  Make your way up this chimney and consider belaying your second from the top of the flake to lessen rope drag.  The second pitch (if you choose to make it a second pitch) then clips a bolt across the chasm made by the flake, and moves up and right into a flared crack and tops out.
location: Start on a block (see photos) on the north/uphill face of Rubaiyat spire.  Follow cracks as above.

description: Excellent face climbing up low angle rock with horizontal cracks. Supplement bolts with gear.
location: Begin on the east face, approach via the 2/3 gully.
Southwest side of the formation.
protection: Singles .3-.75, doubles 1-3, a set of stoppers, bring some long runners to extend pieces. There are also a few old pitons to clip.

location: Approach via the Spire 1/2 Gully.  Either bushwhack your way UP thru acres of beetle kill, or hike DOWN from the Spire 1/2 notch.  The beginning of the route is visible from "God's Own Drunk" on Khayyam Spire.
protection: C4's #.3 thru #2.  BD Stoppers #3 thru #9.  8 or 10 24" runners.  Take spare webbing and inspect anchors before you rap.

description: Beyond all the heavily trafficked routes lies this classic. Climbs a nice hand crack on the S side of the spire with a cruxy exit out right. Then follows a line of huge crystals, which is tricky to protect. Don't follow arete all the way to the top. Trend left easily into trough to find belay/rap.
location: Find obvious hand crack on S side. Rappel down opposite side. 60m rope.

description: Obvious plumb line with a short tricky crux following a thin seam. Protects very well and bolts are where you need them. One upward driven piton is questionable.
location: Easy to find crack in the center of the W Face. First bolt is at 15' right before seam.

first_ascent: Pete DeLannoy, Paul Muehl, and Cindy Tolle
description: The first pitch is 5.10 or so and a little runout in places offering both natural gear and 1/4" bolts to clip. The second pitch is the crux and absolutely never runout once you reach the first bolt(which is not hard to get to). Bring some small crack gear for the last bit of the crux pitch and to add to the two 1/4" bolts at the anchor. The last pitch is protected by very good natural gear and one bolt and is 5.10 as well. The route is very sustained and exposed and absolutely stellar climbing.
protection: Standard rack ranging from a few rp's to hand sized, and plenty of quickdraws for the second pitch (11 I think).

description: A great summit route with the crux at the top. Gain chimney from the N. Then chimney/stem your way up and forward placing gear where ever you can find it. Work on to S shoulder and pull the face bulge, protected by a bolt.
location: Scramble into chimney separating Spire One and Javelin. Belay from talus filled perch. One 70m rap will take you back to belay.

description: Very pleased with how this route turned out! Wander up NE face finding good gear and pulling well protected cruxes on excellent rock. Start the same as Gill Route from the talus perch. Place a piece right away then move out on to the face. Find your way to horizontal and prepare for the crux. Another smaller crux is near the top.
location: NE aspect of spire. 70m or double rope rap.
On the East face of the Grace Note Spire- this is the obvious route that starts wide and goes to hands-size.
protection: A standard rack to 3.5" with some long slings for the pro at the back of the chimney.

description: Route starts up chimney on northeast side of Grace Note Spire.  When you reach the saddle between Grace Note and Sharp move to the west side of the formation climbing the face with a nice crack with good pro.  trend right ending with a nice airy step across from a lower blade to the main  summit.
Crux is about 20-25 feet off the deck with a slight bulge crack.  I won't give the move away, but the seemingly obvious move is most likely not the easiest.
location: Start in the chimney on the east side coming to a ledge leading to a dirty bulgy hand crack.  At this point move up and left, around the corner to a ramp with nice protection on the right side (3-4" camalots).  The route ends with the Conn Finish which is a step across from the small blade on the left to the main summit.  This is a great airy move with good hands and feet.

description: This climbs the sunrise colored, left facing crack. A single bolt marks the crux start. Pumpy liebacking leads to another little crux...that damn bush! After the bush, take the left crack that ends at the anchors for Meltdown. An OK warm-up for the other routes.
location: Middle route marked by only one bolt. Trend right from bolt into orange/yellow lieback.

description: Route begins on the west wall somewhere in the south west corner. Start in a thin crack that widens up into a chimney and be sure to get scared as heck by a bunch of chockstones that you will set a belay up on. Enjoy the heck out of some more chimney climbing that can get steep and meaningful. At some point, there will be crystal jugs and wide open space on the second pitch. This route has traditionally been done in about three pitches with the final one being the money pitch. For the final pitch traverse left around the spire for one heck of a face finish. ¬†Expect great exposure and a summit that will not disappoint.
location: West side of the formation and just a bit south of the summit of Spire One.
protection: Standard Rack. You get one bolt on the last pitch.

first_ascent: Lee Terveen and Joel McKillop (Ground Up)
location: East face of the formation in the gully between Spire 1 and Spire 2. If you find yourself at the base of the Reppy Variation of Spire 1 just walk into the corridor and down the hill a bit. If you find yourself near God's Own Drunk on Khayyam Spire walk west towards Tuning Fork and head uphill high into the gully where the terrain almost becomes flat again. Route is located on a rounded buttress.
protection: Finger sized gear, medium sized gear and about a half dozen quickdraws.

location: Located several seams right of 'Gods Own Drunk'. Look for the bolts in the start. Double rope rappel.

protection: TR from 2 bolts or use a rack of gear from tiny to 3.5" with significant runouts

location: An option off belay ledge after first pitch

description: This is a tough route even as a TR and the effort and energy to get the marginal and meager protection afforded would not make the route any easier... I am not guessing at its grade on lead.  Start up the face on odd holds and with poor gear (5.9) to reach the bottom of a left-leaning crack (10a) where you can place a piece or two of small, so-so gear (pink tricam or an alien) and then up and right to a more vertical crack and some more so-so pro (stopper) then launch up the crack getting small gear when it is offered in coincidence of having a decent enough stance to place it.  If leading, some of the crux moves will be well above questionable gear. Although a long fall would be clean, there is the ground to worry about.  Finish up a vertical crack and seam with many face holds left of the crack, past and just left of a black streak in the wall.
location: Just to the right of God's Own Drunk, there is a yellow and grey wall articulated by some crack systems and a black vertical stripe. This climb follows the cracks and some face holds up the blank face to intersect a slightly left-leaning crack, then up past a few tiny plants to a better crack, then up to the bottom of a black streak, From there, continue up a crack and seam with face holds to the left up the wall to just left of a 2-bolt anchor on a ledge.  There is a second system just right of this with a 3' roof at mid-height.
protection: A few nuts and cams from tiny to 2.5"  Falling would be generally a bad idea. I imagine someone has lead this, but not me. Good TR, but use your own software and pay attention to the mini-links between the bolts and the fixed slings.  Accessible after climbing God's Own Drunk (8+) P1 and traverse over, or on rap from the top.

location: Start at the entrance of the chimney that is to the left of God's Own Drunk.

description: You'll need some bourbon to ease your butterflies on this full 40m of intensity! Ranks high as one of the boldest and best routes in the Park. Start up the right leaning trough/ramp and head straight  up at the first probable looking seam. This is the 'R' rated section since the first placement is at about 20'. After that, the rest is consistent PG13. Surprisingly, there is a lot of gear. But don't pass up a placement, be ready to sniff them out and get creative. Merge into the very end of Silk and Sangria for an exciting finish! Fight the urge to clip Silk's 2nd to last bolt.
location: The right most route on the Ethyl Wall. Start on right trending ramp. Single 80m barely makes it down.

first_ascent: Mark and Beverly Powell, and Bob Kamps, Aug. 1965
location: Route is located on the south side of the formation. The obvious wide chimney.

description: Beautiful line that ascends SW ridge. Get past three pins to a fun overhanging hand crack. Move left over bulge and clip a new bolt. Run it to the top!
location: Walk through passage W of Freak's Foot and you'll be looking right at the route, going up the SW ar√™te.

first_ascent: Bolted ground up by Lee Terveen and Joel McKillop. FFA:  Cali Terveen
description: A long line of nearly perfect crystal pinching and bolt clipping. High step and reach for super good holds. Stalk down and crush tiny crystals before gaining some good rests. Climbers may have to follow paths of good holds to the left and right of the bolt line but the overall climbing does not wander too much. Probably one of the most perfect face climbs in the entire park. Get on it and let us hear you roar!
location: Look for a line of bolts to the left of Lion's Share. Belay from the boulders below the climb.

description: This route tackles the overhanging northwest face of Eyetooth. The route is varied throughout and includes thoughtful gear placements, classic needles cracks, overhanging "sport" climbing and even an exciting step across! Originally put up with no bolts, though it detoured right after pulling the crux. Cheyenne and I returned to put in the direct finish, this time with a bolt kit! Like all CSP routes this was put in ground-up, both times. It can be started from both sides of the ridge line. The spires trail side variation should be broken into two pitch, while the standard 4/5 gully can be done in one mondo pitch with strategic gear placements to prevent drag.
location: If starting from the standard eyetooth start, go up the notch on the northish side between Eyetooth and a sub-formation until you have to start climbing. Follow cracks to a chimney feature that positions you on top of a large feature, commit to the step across and gain the obvious seam to the overhanging face, grab the top, build an anchor with the rope and dangle over the top! If starting from the spires trail side, look for a short, steep, striking hand crack take this to a fist crack to a large ledge below a steep finger crack. Build an anchor here. Take the finger crack to the chimney feature. Standard Eyetooth Rappel.

first_ascent: Bob Kamps, Mark and Beverly Powell
description: Walk around the front of Eyetooth to enter the Chimney on the Southeast side (separating the main mass from the large outer "flake").  Climb easily up to the top of the chimney and belay on the South West Shoulder at the crack leading up and left.Follow the Obvious Crack up and left on to the South West side of the spire.  There is a fixed pin in the crack up high if I remember correctly.  Move up out of the crack and right onto the south face to clip a big new bolt (better than the scary old nail that used to stick out of the face).  The angle eases off on the face and the climbing changes completely.  The face is very small crystals which you friction and smear on adn palm a few holds (really cool).  Climb up to the beefy 2 bolt anchor and belay. A double rope rappel brings you to the base of the route. Classic Needles must do with good gear, fun climbing and good exposure on one of the coolest spires in the Needles.

Proud line put up by Tony just before getting hitched and moving to Arizona. Nearly 60m long with only two bolts and lots of thin protectable face. In order to maintain the mystery and adventure of East Gruesome I must be vague. Begin off a large boulder with your first protection piece in a hueco. Join the original route for the last 30'. This is an intense lead, be ready.

first_ascent: October 1979, Paul Muehl, David Emery, Dick Laptad, Julie McFarland
location: The route is located 10 ft to the left of Route 1, which starts in the southeast corner of the spire four five gulley.
protection: Standard trad rack for climbing in the spires. Bring extra slings as always!

first_ascent: Joel McKillop and Mark Ellefson (Ground Up)
description: Classic five nine climbing that starts on a low angle slab and protects with some smaller gear up to a small roof that forces the climber right into a wide angle, chicken winging crack that soon gives up some of the best face climbing around. Place small gear and clip bolts on a gorgeous face of crystals to a picturesque summit. Feel the burn deep inside your red ruby slippers! This one will not die easily.
location: Almost directly behind Lions share and downhill on the West face.
protection: Standard Rack. Emphasis on smaller finger sized off set nuts and small cams. C3's to #3 C4 camalots. Long slings are a must. Those with 60 or 70 meter ropes will want to bring two of them. 80 meter to 100 meter ropes will get you off the summit with just one rope.

description: The Conns' finest acheivement! Done, of course, with only tight sneakers, 80' rope, pins, and down climbing the route. This has always been a mind blowing accomplishment. Now, all you need to know is...is that you should climb this route! But bear in mind that this is the Conns' hardest route, and their proposed 5.8 is not a modern 5.8. Please be confident in your ability and route finding skills. Leaving no description of the line is part of a traditional tribute to Herb and Jan. So please, no beta spraying here.

first_ascent: Chris Hirsch, Shankar Zamora, Matt Scherer; ground-up June 2020
description: This all-gear route climbs the steep North side of Eyetooth. For the approach pitch, beginning from the North, climb up a short hand crack located in between Tusk and Eyetooth. Then follow ledges up left into a gully/chimney filled with precarious boulders. Belay at a decent perch below the route. For the real climbing; take easy climbing up wide cracks and chimney to the right of the route's runnel feature above. Sling and mantel large horn then carefully lean over to place gear and get established in the steep crack. Follow crack all the way to the top through slopey liebacking, off balance crystal pinching, hard to place gear, a small runout, and a wicked pump. Mantel over the lip and you're at the bolted anchor of the original route.
location: Climbs the obvious fat wrinkle on the NNE aspect of the formation. 40m rappel down the South side.

description: There are still some secret gems in the Needles. I'm surprised I hadn't heard about this line earlier. If you like a typical needles crack, slightly flaring with solid fingers, hands, fists, some awkwardness, and if you can overlook a tiny section of choss and lichen, then go do this! This climb stays very consistent for the full length with the crux being the roof pull.
location: This is part of the 'Land of OZ', which is a small gully just behind the Bartizan Wall, to the W. Best to approach from the S, passing on the left side of the Naked Rib. Crack is on E face of the Lions spire with a triangular roof up high. Single 80m makes the rappel, 70m might be really close.

first_ascent: Joel McKillop and Mark Ellefson (Ground Up)
description: Follow a series of cracks to the top. A good ole' time will be had once you enter a long, yellow brick road of wicked chimney moves that will have you placing your flying monkey hands and feet on three separate spires all at once. Get ready to realize that you are not in Kansas anymore.
location: Starts in a gully to the right of "I'm Melting". Witch's Hat is the most obvious weakness on the Witch's Hat Spire which sits uphill from yellow jacket.
protection: No Bolts. Use a standard rack and bring long slings. Most people will rappel from the chains located on the top of the I'm Melting Spire which is just to the left of Witch's Hat. Climbers with 80 meter or 100 meter ropes will be able to rap down with just one rope. Climbers with 60 meter or 70 meter ropes will want to use two ropes to rap.

first_ascent: Equip  Larry Shaffer. FA  Chris Hirsch & Tony Schwartz, 2014. FFA  Chris Hirsch, belayed by Taylor Lais, 9/2015
description: A wildly exposed arete that Shaffer regrets not finishing. He had 95% of the route complete. Tony and I were able to finish the route without adding any bolts. This line is hard right off the belay, especially gaining the fourth bolt (bad fall potential). After the fifth, go left around corner into crack. Place some gear then three bolts lead to the redpoint crux. Find a small RP placement and exit right to the anchors.
location: W side of spire. Climbs the arete/dyke. To get to belay, climb Devious Nature first then scramble over. Rap down chimney to the SW, 70m rope. Scramble back to Devious Nature's rap.

protection: A set of nuts small Aliens and TCU's a 2-2.5" cam and some long runners. Use two ropes.

description: Fun route that meanders up the face on mostly good hold with some big moves.  From the 7th bolt to the top is runout but easy 5.6ish climbing up the shoulder.
location: In between the 3-4 and 4-5 gulleys is this formation.  Walk north into the hollow past a pine tree and small boulder.  This route is on the west/left face in the hollow between 2 faces.  See photos.
protection: 7 bolts.  2-bolt anchor with one biner and one quicklink on top.

description: A must do if you find yourself in the 4/5 gully. Very long and pleasing with a crux up high, protected by a bolt. Then either rap or try out the precarious summit! Be cautious around hollow flakes.
location: On the W face of Blockhead is a series of cracks and flakes that run together leading right below the summit block. Double rope rap.

first_ascent: Matt Scherer, Aly Bailey, Bryan Hamlin 7/9/2018 Ground up
description: Start in the crack with huge jugs surrounding it, follow this to the top and then take the sweet left angling crack to the top and build anchor in crack. rap off slung horn
location: located on the northwest side of balcony point in 1/2 gully
protection: finger to hand sized gear, RP's, C3's

first_ascent: Mark Rafferty, Rich Ellison, & Ryan Hoben, July 2018,Ground up
location: Located on the Southwest side of the formation. To the left of the large major dihedral on the south side.

first_ascent: Barry Corbet, Jake Breitenbach, Charles Plummer '56
description: This is a great climb.  Start by climbing the first 2 pitches of the east face route on Spire Two.  Then, when at the saddle between Spire Two and Balcony Point, climb up to the obvious beautiful splitter crack that goes almost to the summit of Balcony Point.  Climb this, the hardest move being pulling through a bulgy crack to the top of the pillar.
protection: Standard Rack.  The 3rd pitch is a perfect crack that eats up gear.

first_ascent: Tony Schwartz, Chris Hirsch, Kyle Rott (Ground-up) 10/14
location: This is the next rib formation to the right of the Naked Rib. Hike a short distance off the main trail to reach the start at the bottom of the gully that takes you to Crack of Earthly and Window on the West. Double rope rap.

Left/West side of Bartizan Wall. This is the prominent S facing rib just on the right side of a large grassy gully. Rap down the backside (NSR) and into the grassy gully to the W. Single 80m will get you down, otherwise double ropes needed.
Start between prominent buttress (on left) and very large boulder. Finish on obvious high point on E face. Navigate your way back towards visible hiker's trail to the W.
Next crack system to the right of Kevizan.

first_ascent: Jim Black, Pete Delannoy, John Matteson 7-3-80
description: Excellent corner pitch followed by a very exposed summit finish. Absolute must do! Pitch 1 (5.9 135') Climb up the steep right facing corner pulling a few strenuous laybacks early on, then fun cruiser stemming on big feet and plenty of patina jugs. Once the corner fades, traverse out left across flakes up into the saddle to find the anchors above on a separate formation. Pitch 2 (5.8R 75') Head directly up rib past one old bolt to the top. Bring small (Rp's) gear to supplement. 2nd pitch anchor needs to be replaced (as of 8-24-13). I would recommend a needles style rap.
location: On the left side of Bartizan Wall find the huge chimney, 'Terror-Cracktyl', Earthly Delights is the obvious right facing/leaning corner 20' left of that. Best to gain belay ledge by scrambling, 4th/5th class, from the SW gully. Either rap from 1st pitch anchors (double rope rap) or walk off the back.
Right side of the four-five gully just slightly down the hill from Eyetooth.
protection: Standard Rack. Bring lots of nuts and longer slings. Double up on Camalots 0.5 - 4 if you really want to sew it up. Shares same anchors as Copasetic and raps to its base.

description: Another excellent line to add to the 4/5 gully ticklist. Start in left crack and make the balancy transition into the lieback crack to the right. Gear is hard to place in the beginning. Keep it together for the crux at the end. Stay left, aiming for the webbing belay/rap anchor.
location: This crack is on the small wall down and right of Broken Point. 60m rope.

description: This route is actually no longer here; this route was only submitted for historical purpose.  The big block that created the top fingers crack fell off during the freeze/thaw of 2008/2009.
location: Route #2 on the photo
protection: Webbing anchored to solid trees at the top.

description: Sit start. First 2 moves are crux.
location: Just to the right of Wolf's Face. Sit start. Pull up on crimpers with both hands and small foot smears.

description: SDS in thin crack. Tricky moves lead up the face to the left.
location: To the right of Celestine, on the same boulder. ~5 min along the Scenic Overlook Trail.

description: Another great spot where you can climb down and explore different ways back up. At least 4 route possibilities either climbing down from edge or back up from water level.
To the left of the point you traverse to get over water and can climb up face, stem up the corner or climb the sunny side.
location: There is a outcrop where this photo was taken. Walk down to water level at the tip of the point and you can explore up the side and into the corner on either end.

description: Start compressing the aretes and climb the pretty slab.
location: ~5 mins along the scenic overlook trail, this boulder will be seen on the right

description: SDS under the bulge with right hand on a faint edge and left hand on a scoop dish. Powerful and tricky moves lead up the bulge. Last move is a heartbreaker!
location: Scenic Overlook Trail cliff band.

description: SDS on large jug. A few moves lead up the arete.
location: The left arete of the Celestine boulder. Just off the scenic overlook trail.

description: Sit start
location: On the back side of the boulder, not facing the road. Sit start to small ledge at bottom. Continue up on small crimpers.

description: A very easy route, but still fun.
location: Just to the left of Slap Happy. Start using a few crimpers. End by using the flake on the left to ascend to the top.

description: Sit start on the left. Start slapping your way into the overhang. Continue slapping to top out.
A great traverse
location: At the back side of the boulder (not facing the road). Start on the far left side. Traversing on small 1-2 finger crimpers until you reach Wolf's Face. Continue up on Wolf's Face holds to top.
This is route number 1 on the picture.

description: Little bit of a roof to climb above. Some "technical" foot work with some bomber holds.
location: South west corner of jumping hole
protection: make sure you are comfortable with depth of water

description: Crux is at the top as you get some silly high feet and pull yourself over the lip.
location: under north jumping platform right of splash zone
protection: water is protection so make sure you are comfortable with the depth. DO NOT ATTEMPT when people are jumping above you.

description: Campus start on east facing surface then stem up east and north faces to top out.
location: first major in-cut north of Atlantis rock.
protection: Water is pretty shallow (land on back). Climb with discretion. have a spotter or anchor an air matress below you.

description: Climb just left of the main jumping platform
location: north rim of jumping hole
protection: Ensure that water is deep enough for your comfort.

description: Climb North west corner of Jumping Hole. Difficulty varies depending on how wet the holds are.
location: Northwest corner of Jumping Hole
protection: Make sure water level is high enough for your comfort.

description: Start in the water and work your way up lake side of the alternative jumping location.
location: South rim of jumping hole.
protection: None... sure you are comfortable with the water depth.

description: Explore the overhang at the point across form where everyone is jumping
location: Steepest way up and then pull around to adjacent area to top out

description: immediate east facing surface around south corner of jumping hole
location: immediate east facing surface around south corner of jumping hole
protection: make sure you are comfortable with water depth

description: Hoist yourself up into the little cave like structure then scale the south most aspect of Jumping Hole Adjacent
location: South most, safe and vertical climb of Jumping hole adjacent
protection: Make sure you are comfortable with water depth

location: This climb traverses over the cave immediately south of the jumping hole.
protection: check water levels before climbing as the lake level rises and falls over the years.

description: Start on two edges. Climb left through awesome sloper rail features to an easing top. The detached ramp is off.
location: From the pullout, follow the cliff band to the right (SE) for about 5 mins. This boulder is past the Daylily boulder.
protection: 2-3 Pads. The landing is better than it first appears.

description: easy and fun warm-up with a cool jug at the top.
location: Just to the left of graceland. Start with one hand in a pocket and work your way up to the great left hand jug, top out

description: Sit start below the short but aesthetic arete, with a slot for the left on the arete and and edge on the arete just above. ¬†With some difficulty establish on the wall and gain the sweet sloper above and mantle. ¬†A sit start to Sawyer Jumps!
location: On Sawyer‚Äôs Boulder. ¬†It‚Äôs a free standing boulder in front of the main formation when walking in. ¬†You can see it, just look to the right when you get to the formation.

description: A new classic at Rattlesnake. Starts with an easy bouldering crack and leads  to small, widely spaced holds. Finishes with shoe smears and a small right hand finger crack.
location: This is the nose to the left of Timber Rattler on the Upper Tier. See photos for details.
protection: Top rope or a 30 foot boulder problem!

description: On the right side of the Chaos wall, start standing left hand in a gaston pocket, and right hand on a good part of the arete out right.  Do a couple powerful bumps and a fun jump to the top.
protection: A couple pads, kind of a rock behind you, probably won't hit it though.

description: From east side of bluff walk south past project wall.  Head up to the rim of bluff and look for boulders laying on top of each other.  Climb out from the cave here is the project.  Pads and spotters needed for sure.
location: Walk through saddle, and head right (south).  Pass project wall and keep moving up bluff line.  You will see boulders laying on one another.  This is the cave.

description: Sit start on obvious edges and climb straight up the gently overhanging face.
location: Just right of "Jump for Joy."

description: Starts with left hand on the good sloped ledge and right hand in good slot/crimp.  Goes left hand to a decieving slopey sidepull. Then throw to a bomber slot/jug. Keep it together for the topout.
location: Southeast of saddle. Just below cave, past Chaos on the right.

description: Starts on descent holds and moves up into no-mans land with horrible feet.
location: Head past the saddle and turn right.  Problem is on steep face with a boulder right in front of it.  Chaos is to the left of this.

description: Just left of the Project.  Climb corner with fun features and good top-out.
location: Project wall, just left of the Project.

description: Start on two pockets on the right side of the face. Make a long throw up left to a good sidepull.  Traverse right to corner and topout straight up.
location: First boulder south of the project wall.

description: Start down and left on pockets.  Move up and right to the ledge, traverse right to corner and topout straight up.
location: First boulder south of the project wall.
Left corner from Cottonmouth; main cliff east. Approach up hill through boulders between Kutcher Bluff and Main bluff. See pictures.
protection: Mixed rack of hexes, wired nuts, and cams; top rope is an easy set-up.

location: Northeast side of main bluff; meander up the hill through the boulders and you meet the climb head-on.
protection: Top rope or go with mixed cams and smaller nuts at the top.

description: Problem starts with a bomber ledge for feet off to the right of start hands. Thrutch out left to increasingly good crimps. From there head up to increasingly better holds to top out.
location: thru saddle. take a right and it is not far down on the right. It is apparently on the same wall and to the left of the 'project' i think.  It is also just before the 'dicey' problems and also 'jump for joy'
protection: pad on ground and one on rock directly behind you.

first_ascent: T. Melin w/ old sausage fingers Forge.
description: Just up hill from Project.  Scramble up to large ledge, problem is tall featured face to the right.  Another really fun but tricky problem.  Holds have changed over the years, so I'm not sure on current conditions.
location: Backside of southern bluff, just up hill from project wall.

description: Excellent dihedral climbing with a finger crack.
location: Obvious 20ft dihedral on the upper tier of the main bluff. Directly above Fists and Fury.

description: Excellent short route accented with a mix of short pulls,lay backs, balancing, and cracks.  Would be a great second pitch to Solo, Anniversary, Black Hornet, or Slab Cracks. Named for the timber rattlesnake found in the area and the dead pine felled off route face. TIMMMMMBERRRR!
location: Located above Solo Crack on upper tier.  Left towering buttress.
protection: Easy top rope access/set-up. Bring a set of wired nuts, small/med cams. First pro placement is at about 20 ft.

description: Starts with good holds and move up to a large blank section. The right arete will help here. Strong and burely. Holds can be seen, but havent figured out how to get them or use them.
location: arete right of Criminal Mastermind

description: Start as for Speechless, on the left side of the arete, with an undercling for the left hand and the arete for the right. ¬†Climb the left side of the arete. ¬†For the record, Speechless moves right around the arete about half way up.
location: On the main formation just right of the saddle you reach between the hills when walking from the car.
protection: Pads.  Flat landing though it is possible the wall behind could come into play..

description: Nice crack line with many stances and pro.
location: West side of main bluff, first good crack pm the left. There's a small stump at about 5ft.

description: Overhanging finger crack leading to a loose chock stone, finishing on nice holds, leading to the bus stop on top. I used the left corner arete to aid in the climb. Turkey vultures like to perch on top in the warm fall sun.
location: Around right corner from Timber Rattler on upper tier, left buttress.
protection: Top rope is an easy set-up. Crack will take mixed sizes of wired nuts and small cams.  Once at the loose chock stone the route can be run out.  Bottom 15 feet is the climb.

description: Route starts by mounting the overhang and clambering to the ledge as in Massasauga.  Step to the right above the long overhang and mount the exposed wall and climb nose to the top.
location: Located to right of Massasauga on Upper Tier at top of gully wash entrance.....South end of main cliff and up top.
protection: Recommend top rope......bottom crack/overhang is too big for gear and top is small ledge holds.....or a stunt man air bag and a long boulder problem.

description: Short crack to the right and in the corner from Snakes on a Plain. Short jam crack with some overhang angle in the middle.
location: Upper tier on the left buttress around the right corner from Timber Rattler and in the corner right of Snakes on a Plain.  See photos for route.
protection: Mixed cams, med/large hexes, top rope.

description: Nice balance climb on thin holds leading to lay-backs on big sloper jugs; up the left arete face and stepping across to finish the blocky top face.
location: Left of Upper Tier Dihedral on left side of face.  Starts on the diagonal crack. See photo outlying the route.
protection: Top rope set up is easy; not sure with trad other than really thin gear.

description: Excellent hand jams lead to a sloping top-out on jugs.
location: Crack left of Fists and Fury that ends on slab directly left of big boulder sitting on top.

description: Upper tier chimney climb with three inner cracks. Great beginner lead climb.
location: Located in the upper tier to the left of Massasuaga; where the gully wash access tops out.
protection: Bring all you got.....For beginners, you will be able to use cams, hexes, nuts, and can gain experience in stemming, jams, and chimney techniques. Short and sweet.

description: Tricky, sandy, sloper climbing. Tricky at the top.
location: West side of main bluff, just right of Chossholic.
protection: TR, no gear on route. There is a nice tree for an anchor at the top.

description: Great crack climbing with an exposed top section.  Climb starts with an off-width crack leading to a shelf.  Step across to the mid-section on smaller finger cracks and limited foot holds. Make the reach to the bucket hold and finish on the top latticed face. Step up onto the final boulder and shout "MASSASAUGA"!
location: Located on upper tier, at the top and right of the gully-wash access.
protection: Great trad climb with med/large cams, larger hexes, and nuts on top section. Can be top-roped also.

location: Walk up the trail from the parking. ¬†At the obvious saddle between the hills this is on the formation to the right just uphill. ¬†The chaos/ hocus pocus wall is just 50 feet away on the backside of the main formation. ¬†Speechless finishes on this climb, though starts on the other side of the arete.
protection: Pads and spot.  4 pads probably, there is a slight downward slant in the landing that should be leveled.

description: Old school cool fist crack. Solo up easy terrain then plug bomber cams in a hand crack. The crack gets wider and harder as you go up. Fists to arm-bar.
location: West side of the main bluff. It sits directly underneath a large boulder on the top.
protection: #4 C4 for the crux, maybe a #5.

description: Between two bluffs in saddle look for vertical boulder with easy climbing.  Good warm up.
location: Between two bluffs in the saddle.  Look south when crossing saddle and you will see the arete.

description: Interesting tight dihedral climbing.
location: On the north side of the main bluff. Dihedral between Criminal Mastermind and Speechless.

description: Sit start on large holds. Move up to thin sidepull, get your feet up and huck for another large hold, move up and grab arete on right, gain crimp or sidepull and make large move to top.
location: about 30 feet above Easy Arete.
protection: pads and spotters. The landing is ok until you get up about halfway. If you dryfired from there, you'd probably miss the pads and fly down the talus.

description: Chossy crack climb. I went to OS this one day but bailed when the choss started to consume me.
location: Crack system right of Fists and Fury.
protection: TR or deep gear in shitty rock.

description: This route coined the name from a hornets nest that had to be removed half way up (half way down on rappel), and from the remains of the black charred tree trunk at the start of the climb. This is a fun zig-zag crack with lay-backs and jamming. The last ten feet are slightly overhung and finishes on good hand holds.
location: Route is directly between Anniversary and Slab Crack.
protection: Route will take everything from cams, hexes, nuts and of course a top rope set-up.

description: Half crack leading to a challenging crux move to gain the horizontal ledge for foot placement. Continue up and left on sloped friction ledges to gain final finish straight up nice spaced hand and foot placements.  I solo'ed this on a petzl shunt and top roped it five days later with a friend.  The name derives from my ascent on my parents 58th wedding anniversary on August 24th.
location: Route is next half-crack to the right of Solo Crack (5.4). See photo for route. Area between red marks is the crux. Route finishes where boulder is resting on top.
protection: On top rope I used a #2 and #3 Camelot on the large boulder on top and a long webbing to a small but secure pine tree. Route will take pro but remember this is soft/chossy sandstone.

description: Nice boulder problem with true mantle.
location: Located on Sawyer's Boulder on the west side of the main cliff.

description: Tough sit start to an easy top-out.
location: Right side of Sawyer's Boulder. Match on left arete with high feet to start.

description: Plant your foot and jump for the nice sloper above, smear and layback to the top.
location: Located on Sawyer's Boulder on the west side of the main bluff.

description: Start from a sit matched on an obvious low rail. ¬†Climb left up the arete through thin holds and tricky moves then mantle at the apex. ¬†The seam behind the arete doesn‚Äôt come into play until¬†the end.
location: Facing the road, in front of the main formation on Sawyer‚Äôs Boulder.

description: Stand or jump to two decent slopers and hold on, continue up and either traverse out right or drop down. A full topout is doable but hornets and suspect rock make it very unappealing.
location: This route is on the slightly slabby face to the left of trust the sand.
protection: two or three pads. And a giant pair if one were to take it all the way up.

description: Start with both hands near last good hold near center and campus up to heal hook and move right on lip to end of lip and then up and over.
location: around and left of saddle, on back side of ridge

description: Start on best hold in center and move left with worsening right heels.
location: around left side of saddle on back side.

description: This is a super fun problem. Start on good left hand slot and right under cling and move up to two left pockets and slam dunk the good upper ledge and move up to sloper top out.
location: around left side of saddle on back side down from star destroyer.

description: Start on same left slot as Graceland and move right on up buldge
location: around left side of saddle on back side down from star destroyer.

description: Start on side pulls and climb the vertical features.
location: From the roadside pullout, hike ~2-5 mins left (NW). This boulder is just to the left of the Prototaxites project.

description: Start on the large ledge. A delicate mantle leads to the lower angle slab, where cool holds and desperate moves await.
location: To the right of Prototaxites, on the same boulder. Follow the cliffband NW from the pullout for ~1-2 min and you will see these looming slabs from below.

description: Sit start with right hand edge and left hand side pull. Climb tricky moves up the slab.
location: ~1 min past Wood Violet

description: Stand start on side pulls. Climb the short bulge.
location: Uphill and around the corner of Lion's Mane, along the social trail.

description: Climb the cool compression feature to a tricky topout (for the grade). A classic warmup!
location: From the roadside pullout, hike 5-10 mins left (NW). This boulder is just past chanterelle (on the same outcrop) and just before Garden Variety.
Just left of the slab climb Daylily. Walk right along the cliffband towards Wood Violet

description: SDS on left hand side pull and right hand crimp. Climb through the thin seam to a sweet sloper pinch and a huge dyno.
location: About 10 steps from the car on the first gently overhanging face by the roadside pullout.

description: Stand start on sloper jug. Climb sidepulls up gently overhanging wall. Detached blocks and wall to the right are not used.
location: To the right of Shiitake, on the same wall. Easily seen from the roadside pullout.

description: Sit start with left hand on rounded arete and right hand sloper. Several slaps lead over the bulge. Pretty fun, for a dumpy boulder.
location: Uphill and around the corner of Lion's Mane, along the social trail

description: Start the same as Garden Variety (matched in the thin crack) and do the first move, but instead of jumping to the lip, continue following the crack left.
location: From the parking head left and work your way down the cliff band for a few minutes. ¬†This climb is just past the boulders Chanterelle and Spore, on a short, steep wall with an obvious thin crack.

description: Start in the break, with good feet. Climb directly up the blank slab to the right of the crack seam.
location: From the roadside pullout, follow the cliff band left (NW) for 2-5 mins. This looming slab will be visible from below.

description: Stand start with left hand on arete and right hand with good edge on the face. Climb tenuous moves up the sloper arete and rail systems. Detached blocks are not used.
location: Follow the cliffband about 2-5 mins left (NW) of the roadside pullout. This climb is just past the Prototaxites Project.

description: Sit start matched on good edge. Climb cool features up the slab.
location: Left side of the roadside pullout cliff band. Just before Lion's Mane.

description: SDS on arete with left hand edge and right hand gaston. Climb the arete up and left, eventually topping out as for Deathcap.
location: To the right of Deathcap, on the same boulder.

description: Start on good edges. Long moves lead up the slab.
location: On the left side of the Roadside pullout cliff band. Just to the left of Mycelium

description: Stand start on large sidepull jug. Climb cool rounded granite rails up the slab.
location: To the right of daylily, on the same boulder.

description: SDS on sidepull rail. Climb straight up through crack systems to a tricky top.
location: Just above and slightly left of Nystatin.

description: Start matched in the thin crack. Bust a big move left and proceed to negotiate the tricky lip mantle.
location: From the roadside pullout, hike 5-10 mins left (NW). This boulder is just before the Deathcap/Morel Compass boulder and is hard to miss.

description: Climb obvious features to top.
location: Immediately right of Lion's Mane.

description: Start on the jug at chest height. Climb straight up through good holds and interesting moves.
location: From the roadside pullout, follow the cliff band to the left (NW) for about 5-10 mins. It's a little further down than you might expect.

description: Start on left hand side pull and right hand flat edge. Climb the tall slab. Stays on you the whole time.
location: From the roadside pullout, follow the cliff band to the right (SE) for 2-5 mins. This slab is pretty easily spotted.

description: Sit start on jug break. Climb the striking arete.
location: From the roadside pullout, hike 5-10 mins left (NW). This boulder pops into view after a short break in the cliff band.

description: Sit start in the dihedral left of Death Cap with a jug left hand undercling and right hand on a small dihedral edge above the jug. Climb up the dihedral with tricky feet
location: Left of Death Crap

description: Starts as for Wood Violet, but climbs straight up using crack and cool holds. The¬†detached ramp is off.
location: To the right of Wood Violet

description: Squeeze the mushroomy prow. Sit start with right hand incut slopey hold and left hand perfect half pad crimp. Thruch out left and start compressing.
location: 50 feet to the right of Chanterelle.

description: Starts on obvious lower right jug with a high left foot and climbs through the diagonal seam up and left to top out.
location: 70ish yards down and right of Chanterelle. Closest boulder to the road as the escarpment takes a sharp bend.

description: Stand start matched on a sloper. Follow sloper rail to the right, eventually reaching a tricky topout mantle.
location: To the right of Nystatin, which is just past the large Prototaxites slab.
protection: Pads. The landing is tiered, which makes it hard to protect

description: Climb up backside of Main bouder.  Easy warm-up.
location: Backside of Main boulder.

description: Start at Direct line jug and traverse left across boulder into Side-Pull.  Pumpy!
location: Bottom of steep face of main boulder.

description: Left side of steep face of main boulder.  Stand start of good holds and keep bumping hands up side pulls and cracks in rock.  Another super fun problem.  SDS makes it V5+.
location: Left side of steep face on main boulder.

description: Just left of Corner bulge.  Start low and get up into dirty crack and top out.
location: Steep face between Direct Line and Corner Bulge.

description: A Classic!  Middle of steep face, start on jug and get high up to small crimp, establish and gun for the lip.  Super fun problem with stretchy moves.  Seen few accents.
location: Middle line of main boulder.

description: Climb corner bulge of Main boulder.  Very much like HP 40.
location: Corner of Main boulder.

description: Climb up steep part of corner on Main boulder.  Left of the Main face.
location: Around left corner of steep face on Main boulder.

description: Starting on the face head to the overhang and around to corner to top off
protection: carefull not to roll off. that would suck

description: Climb up short overhang on left side of wall.  Once on ledge climb blank face straight up.
location: Left side of the Dark-side wall

description: Start standing on ledge and move to horizontal ledges, then up thin face to lay-back jugs.  Move from jugs to thin vertical crack.
location: Left-center of Dark-side wall

description: Nice outer corner route using holds on both sides. Would recommend top rope since this is an area starting to show chossy areas.  The route is solid and complete; typical chossy top.
location: Route is to the right of Kutcher Krack on outer corner. See picture showing route.
protection: Small pro for lead; would recommend the top rope; easy access and easy set-up.

description: Start on lower left and traverse up and right on good holds.
location: Directly right of the house boulder.  Same boulder as Beached Whale.

description: Start on good holds in the horizontal breaks and climb through more of the same.
location: Above and to the right of Lost in a Dream.

description: Start at the base and climb the other side of the arete/face of the Lost in a Dream boulder
location: Same as Lost in a Dream

description: pull up and over the roof. Pull through or around the tree.
location: Directly right of naptime

description: Start on the jug and climb up through the mini-dihedral.
location: Above and slightly to the right of Lost in a Dream.

description: Start at the base and climb the massive compression feature. An exceptional problem.
location: The first large outcropping seen from Lakeshore Lane. Hard to miss.

description: On wall just right of Lost in a Dream.. Not great but a warm up and kinda funky. ¬†Start sitting with a hollow flake, bust big left to the slanting ledge and continue on through slopes and better holds. ¬†Might be more fun to just start on the slanting ledge. ¬†And that hollow start hold might just break.
location: Just right of Lost in a Dream

description: Start on a horizontal edge beneath the dihedral. Climb through the dihedral, trending left to the face and top out using an awesome bread loaf jug.
location: To the right of Lost in a Dream.

description: Start on warm up 2 and pull around the arete to gain the slabby crack.
location: Around arete of Warm up 2
protection: After you pull around the corner, just dont fall.  You'll end up between the two house boulders.

location: Center of the house boulder.

description: On west face of House boulder, climb right side with fun features.  Great warm up.
location: West face of House boulder.

description: On the west face of the House boulder.  Climb up left side.  Pretty easy and a good warm up.
location: Left of west face on House boulder.

description: climb Crack with left hand and right hand on arete and face.
location: East to see boulder half way up hillside right of house boulders.

description: Climb short, north-west corner of House boulder.  Trickier than you would think.
location: NW corner of House Boulder.

description: A really fun 15 foot tall near vert slab (like as close to vert as you can get). About 25 yards North of the house boulder with a slightly angled landing, you can't miss it. More technical than powerful so it is hard to rate, but the crimps are pretty small. Start in the middle of the wall pretty much right under the overhanging tree. Find a small two finger crimp/pocket and start with right hand in or around there, and left hand on a crimp about a foot or so to the left. Stand up. Get foot/feet higher and reach for sharp crimps up and to the right. Reposition feet, stand up and reach for a good crimp up and to the right, or a crimpy v thingamabob just to the left of that (be careful because that v thing wants to be broken). Reposition feet and go for the top. Be careful because some of the top out holds are thin and might break easily. This problem is great because from the start, you slowly work your way right and towards the jugs on the arete, but you don't end up using them until the top out when they make for good feet. Also, there could be a good line that starts on the left side of the slab.
location: About 25 yards North of the House Boulder. It has a sloped landing and there is a cool thin sculpture like thing that has been eroded out of the wall on the arete to the right. .

description: Up hill from house boulder on rim of bluff, the mushroom is a cool boulder that is steep with good holds.
location: Up hill from House boulder on top rim.

description: Try and climb center line on small hands and feet.
location: Shark tooth boulder up left on hill from house boulder

description: You can stand start on good right hand side pull and left hand on arete and move up left side to top. For full value sit start on two lowest right side pulls and move up to right side pull from stand start.
location: Left side of sharks tooth boulder. Mid way up hill left side of house boulder

description: Sit start with left hand gaston on large rail, right hand on good crimp.  Stand up with feet out right and then kick in a good right heel hook.  Continue straight up with a series of difficult bumps on small hands.
location: Central right side of House Boulder.  Starts immediately right of the V4 warmup.

description: Start with booth hands on sloper ledge and heel hook up to mantle and top out straight over middle of pinch side pulls
location: left of house boulder at bottom of hill

description: Climb short slopey bulge on boulder just right of House boulder.  Really fun and the top-out is the crux.
location: Just right of House boulder.

description: Climb crack to top
location: Directly on the backside of Kutcher Crack. To the right of sidewinder.
protection: Large Nuts and medium to Large Cams. Tree for TR

description: Pretty good off-finger crack. Originally done as a boulder problem but I led it on gear.
location: Behind the house boulder to the right.
protection: Good gear all the way, wide fingers.

description: Interesting arete, holds are suspect.
location: Arete right of Kutcher Krack on the formation behind and right of the house boulder.

route_name: The Gentle Art of Making Enemies
description: Fun face climb with one crappy hold :(
location: Face right of Kutcher Crack on formation behind the House Boulder to the right.
